<SLUG> BC-CALDERA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMY SECRETARY HAILS SPIELBERG FILM AS LESSON FOR YOUTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY DAVID R. BAKER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On the eve of Veterans Day, Secretary of the Army
Louis Caldera said that he hoped the film ``Saving Private Ryan''
would help young Americans who have never known war understand the
meaning of military service.
</P>
<P>
   The graphic and gripping World War II movie has rekindled
interest in the conflict even as the generation that fought it
fades from public life, Caldera said Tuesday at a meeting with
Daily News reporters and editors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people have started thinking, Hey, maybe that elderly
guy in front of me was in World War II,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Caldera, the issue touches on more than pride in his
organization. For years, America's civilian army has faced
declining interest among the young people it needs for recruits, he
said. Many have no memory of war, with the exception of the brief
Persian Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say the words and you can see the comprehension in the
person's eyes, but they still won't understand the emotional
content of what you're saying,'' said Forrest Frields, a Thousand
Oaks planning commissioner and Vietnam veteran. ``To even have a
glimmer of what's being said, you have to experience it
firsthand.''
</P>
<P>
   Caldera said he did not know whether the film had yet spurred an
increase in recruitment. It has, however, drawn more visitors to
the French cemeteries shown in the movie's opening and closing
scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Caldera is spending most of the week in Los Angeles after a
one-day trip last weekend to Central American countries ravaged by
Hurricane Mitch. Nearly 1,000 U.S. Army soldiers are working to
help deliver food and rebuild bridges in the battered region, and
more are on the way, Caldera said.
</P>
<P>
   The former Whittier resident and state assemblyman said the
devastation he witnessed dwarfs anything wrought by Southern
California's winter mudslides.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some places, people have to tell you that there used to be
a town there, because it's now just brown mud,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 bridges in the region will have to be rebuilt.
Caldera noted that after the 1994 Northridge Earthquake,
reconstruction of a single span of the Golden State Freeway took
months, despite all the resources available.
</P>
<P>
   ``These countries have hundreds of situations like that and a
fraction of the resources,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
