<HEADLINE>
FORMER STUDENT CONVICTED OF KILLING SON OF TIME WARNER CHAIRMAN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: The following story is an added starter on The New York
Times front page.)   (sw) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 19-year-old former student of Jonathan Levin was
convicted on Tuesday of second-degree murder in the May 1997
slaying of Levin, a Bronx public high school teacher, in his
Manhattan apartment.
</P>
<P>
   But in a setback for prosecutors, the jury acquitted the
defendant, Corey Arthur, of first-degree murder, apparently
unconvinced that Arthur fired the shot that killed Levin, the son
of Gerald Levin, chairman of Time Warner Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur faces 25 years to life in prison. If he had been
convicted of first-degree murder, he would have been sentenced to
life in prison without parole.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors left the courthouse on Tuesday night without commenting
on their eleven hours of deliberations, but it appeared that they
rejected the testimony of the prosecution's lead witness, Carlethia
Weeks. Ms. Weeks, Arthur's former girlfriend, had testified that he
confessed the killing to her.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Weeks admitted under cross-examination that she had heard
voices in her head since she was a child and had seen a
psychiatrist about the problem. Prosecutors have not commented on
whether they knew of Ms. Weeks' psychiatric problems when they
placed her on the stand.
</P>
<P>
   Levin's mother, Carol Levin, expressed disappointment with the
verdict on Tuesday night in an emotional statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not happy about this,'' Ms. Levin said. ``There is no
happiness in this.'' She added, ``John wouldn't have been happy
with this verdict.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury's ruling essentially meant that prosecutors proved only
that Arthur and his 26-year-old codefendant, Montoun Hart, tortured
his former teacher until he gave them the code to his bank card and
robbed him of $800, not that Arthur personally killed Levin. Hart
will be tried separately on second-degree murder charges in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur shook his head and muttered to himself when the guilty
verdicts were announced. His mother, Penny Bostick, sat motionless
and Arthur's current girlfriend began weeping.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Levin, who spoke for the first time publicly about the
murder, praised her son's life and criticized defense lawyers for
raising drugs in the trial. Defense lawyers suggested that drugs
may have been a reason Arthur was in Levin's apartment that night.
But an autopsy found no drugs in Levin's body.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurt those who loved John very much to hear the defense
spin fictions about his life,'' she said. ``John lived a noble
life. He was a very honorable man.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Levin said that her son lived for his students and would not
have been able to achieve what he did in life if he had used drugs.
She said he gave selflessly to his students and that he responded
to Arthur's phone call the day of the killing because that was his
nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would probably be very disappointed in Corey Arthur,'' Ms.
Levin said on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The killing of Levin led some public-school teachers to question
how accessible they should be to their students outside of school,
and turned Levin into a symbol of public service.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur was a student in Levin's English class at Taft High
School in the Bronx during the 1993-1994 school year, and the young
teacher apparently took the troubled youth under his wing. At the
time, at least, the two were close.
</P>
<P>
   In a two-page, handwritten thank-you note that Arthur wrote to
Levin in 1993, he called the teacher his ``true and only friend in
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have shown me that it is alright to step in and help
someone,'' he said in the letter. ``You have shown me not all
people want to use and exploit me.''
</P>
<P>
   The note concluded: ``Wherever I get in life, I owe it to you
and for that I am entirely grateful. I am also lucky and most happy
to call Jake or John Levin my friend. Thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Levin wrote in a paper for a graduate school class he was taking
at the time that Arthur showed promise and that reading the note
from Arthur nearly brought him to tears.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and defense lawyers painted starkly different
portraits of what happened in their relationship. Defense lawyers
said the two remained close and argued in the closing statements on
Monday that Arthur would never have killed his former teacher. They
argued that cuts Arthur suffered on his hand at the time of the
murder occurred when he tried to stop one of his accomplices from
stabbing Levin.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way on God's earth that he would kill him,''
George Goltzer, one of Arthur's defense lawyers, said in his
closing statement. ``There is no way on God's earth he would harm
him.''
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors said that Arthur and Levin had grown apart by
May 30, 1997. The former student took advantage of his previous
relationship with his former teacher to gain entrance to his
apartment. Twice during the trial, prosecutors played a tape from
Levin's telephone answering machine that recorded Arthur calling
him at 4:55 p.m. on the day of the murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Levin, this is Corey,'' the voice on the tape says. ``Pick
up if you're there. It's important.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur and Hart did go to visit Levin, and prosecutors said they
attacked him and tied him up with duct tape. The teacher was
tortured with a knife, including three cuts made across his throat,
until he gave up the code to his bank card. At 5:15 p.m, a man
identified by a witness as Hart withdrew $800 from Levin's bank
account.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors portrayed Arthur as the leader of the two. His
fingerprints were found on the roll of duct tape and his DNA was
found on the knife used to torture Levin. Blood from Levin was
found on Arthur's clothes. While the gun that killed Levin was
never recovered, prosecutors argued that Arthur was the only one
with a motive to kill his former teacher because he could later
identify Arthur to the police.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
