<SLUG> BC-BOEING-TOOL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER TOOL LEFT INSIDE BOEING PLANE DURING ASSEMBLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Another tool has been found in the rudder of a Boeing
airplane, this time on a new 777 operated by EgyptAir.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, which can seat more than 300 passengers, had been
flying with a hammer in a ``critical'' part of the rudder since the
new 777 was delivered to EgyptAir last year, according to an
internal Boeing document obtained by the Seattle
Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-ounce hammer, left in the rudder during assembly of the
777 in Everett, Wash., in 1997, was found by EgyptAir mechanics
during an inspection late last month. By the time it was
discovered, it had already caused two small cracks inside the
rudder, apparently from bouncing around during flight.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Post-Intelligencer reported that a 5-pound
bucking bar, a tool use by riveters, was found inside the rudder of
a United Parcel Service 767. It punched small holes and dents
inside the rudder. As in the case of the EgyptAir 777, the bucking
bar was left in the rudder during assembly of the 767 in Everett.
</P>
<P>
   And in yet another recent incident involving what's known as
FOD, or foreign object debris, being left in new Boeing airplanes,
a 777 was grounded after the batteries of a flashlight left in a
wing during assembly corroded and shorted out a landing light.
Boeing would not identify the airline.
</P>
<P>
   The FOD problem is considered so serious that Boeing's Everett
factory is in the process of implementing a new policy that will
require workers to check out their tools at the start of each
shift, and check them back in.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing builds its widebody jets _ the 747, 777 and 767 _ in
Everett.
</P>
<P>
   A mechanic at the B.F. Goodrich airplane maintenance facility in
Everett, where the bucking bar was discovered in the 767's rudder,
said it is not uncommon there to find all kinds of tools that were
left in Boeing planes during production.
</P>
<P>
   Everything from flashlights to wrenches and pliers have been
found in the wings and flaps of new Boeing planes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, the tools are found during what is known as a ``C
check,'' which is the first major overhaul a new airplane undergoes
after it is delivered to a customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever we get a new Boeing plane in for a C check, the
standing joke is, `I wonder what tools Boeing has left for us
today,''' said the mechanic, who worked on the UPS 767 when it was
recently overhauled. He asked that his name not be used.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing confirmed Tuesday that a flashlight was recently found in
the wing of a 777. The problem was uncovered by airline mechanics
only after the flashlight batteries corroded and shorted out a
landing light.
</P>
<P>
   A Boeing spokeswoman declined to identify the airline.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unacceptable,'' Tim Copes, Boeing's quality assurance
manager for the 777 program, said Tuesday in an interview about the
EgyptAir incident. ``It's a breakdown of the system and something
we take very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Copes said he may be asked by Boeing management to fly to Egypt
to personally offer the company's apology over the hammer incident.
</P>
<P>
   These incidents in which tools have been left in Boeing planes
during production come at time when the company is struggling to
produce a record number of airplanes. The quality of those planes
has raised concerns by longtime customers. UPS and United, for
example, recently complained to Boeing executives about customer
service problems, including quality control issues.
</P>
<P>
   Both United and UPS opted to buy new planes from Boeing's rival
Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   EgyptAir is the national carrier of Eqypt and a longtime Boeing
customer. The airline ordered its first airplane from Boeing, a
707, in 1966. The 777 in question was the second of three of the
widebody jets delivered to EqyptAir by Boeing last year.
</P>
<P>
   Airline representatives at Egypt-Air's office in New York were
not familiar with the hammer incident when contacted Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the incident is detailed in an internal Boeing document
known as an ``ACT (airline concerns team) investigation activity
report.''
</P>
<P>
   The hammer was discovered when the rudder panels of the 777 were
removed by EqyptAir mechanics in October, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   The rudder is a critical flight control surface in the the tail
of an airplane.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presence of the hammer has caused two cracks at the rudder
hinge ... '' the report said. One crack measured 1.5 inches and the
other measured 1.75 inches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This area is deemed to be a critical area in the 777 ...'' the
report stated, and added:
</P>
<P>
   ``Please be advised that EgyptAir is upset with finding this
hammer.''
</P>
<P>
   Copes said the 16-ounce hammers are used throughout the Everett
factory and are painted bright orange so they can be easily spotted
and not left in an airplane.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the color of a hunter's jacket,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The hammer was apparently used by a worker during assembly to
help drive in the pins that hold the rudder to the 777's tail,
Copes said.
</P>
<P>
   The hammer was found in a rudder compartment that could be
accessed by hand but was too small for workers to stick their heads
in and check to see if any tools were left behind before the rudder
panels were closed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of Boeing's quality control program, after workers have
attached the rudder to the tail, another person is supposed to
inspect the rudder before it is closed to make sure no tools have
been left inside. This person then signs an ``OK to close''
inspection record.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the rudder compartment where the hammer was found
was too small for peek inside, a mirror should have been used to
aid in the check for such debris, Copes said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the EgyptAir incident is similar to the one involving
the UPS 767.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, he said, the tools left behind in the rudders
were used by workers to help tap in the pins that hold the rudder
to the tail.
</P>
<P>
   The 767 was delivered to UPS in September 1996 and the bucking
bar was not found until this past September.
</P>
<P>
   The mechanic who worked on the 767 at the B.F. Goodrich facility
in Everett said the bucking bar, which has sharp edges, punched a
small hole in a plate that covers a much more critical compartment
directly below that has the rudder control motors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might have taken a while, but the bucking bar could have
eventually ended up in that more critical compartment,'' the
mechanic said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing gave UPS a new rudder because of the damage caused by the
bucking bar.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Mark Sanders, Boeing's top quality
assurance manager for Everett's 747, 767 and 777 production, said
the company has made significant progress in educating workers
about the dangers of foreign object debris in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing offers non-cash prizes to workers who find the most
foreign object debris.
</P>
<P>
   Copes said Boeing workers on the Everett flight line, where new
planes are tested before being turned over to the customer, must
now check their tools in and out. Eventually, that practice will be
adopted throughout the factory, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to minimize (foreign objects) is to have a good
tool control program,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration has said that while it has
inspectors in Boeing assembly plants and reviews the company's
procedures, it's mainly up to Boeing to control foreign object
debris.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
