<HEADLINE>
STORR ASSIGNED TO ICE DOGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ Goalie Jamie Storr, who hasn't played since
suffering a strained groin in a tie with Colorado on Oct. 18, will
begin his comeback Thursday night, but not with the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year-old Storr has been assigned to the IHL's Ice Dogs
and is scheduled to play Thursday night when they play host to the
Utah Grizzlies at the Long Beach Arena and Saturday night at home
against Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited because it's something I asked for,'' said Storr,
who practiced with the Ice Dogs on Tuesday. ``I wanted to make sure
that when I do get back, I will be ready.... It's the perfect
situation for me, to get back to work right down the road. We're
lucky to have the minor-league team so close where it's easy to go
and play for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Storr played 11 games with the Ice Dogs a year ago after
suffering a groin injury in the exhibition season. Kings coach
Larry Robinson said he does not expect Storr to spend as much time
in Long Beach as he did a year ago but added that nothing is
guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he stinks out the joint in both of those games, we may keep
him down there,'' Robinson said. ``He's got to perform. Our
goaltenders aren't hurting us here. It's not a divine right that he
comes right back to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings have gotten strong play from Manny Legace since the
injuries to Storr and No.1 goalie Stephane Fiset in the Colorado
game. Robinson said he wants Storr to play his way back into shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really only played one game,'' Robinson said. ``He missed
much of training camp with the contract (dispute). Right now, he
needs to face some pucks. I think he wanted to come on this trip.
But he had a full practice (Tuesday with the Ice Dogs), whereas he
wouldn't have had one with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Loose pucks: Winger Steve McKenna's abdominal strain, suffered
six days ago, might sideline him for up to two months.... According
to a survey in The Hockey News, Robinson is tied for eighth on the
salary list of NHL coaches with Dallas' Ken Hitchcock, Mike Milbury
of the New York Islanders and Joel Quenneville of the St. Louis
Blues. All make $700,000. The highest-paid coach, at $1.1 million,
is Toronto's Pat Quinn. The lowest-paid coach is Calgary's Brian
Sutter at $278,885.... Kings prospect Matt Zultek, selected in the
first round of the 1997 draft, was named the Ontario Hockey
League's player of the week. Zultek, 19, recorded three goals and
nine points in three games for his junior team, the Ottawa 67's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
