<SLUG> BC-BKC-URI-VANDERBILT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ODOM RESCUES RHODE ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE _ Lamar Odom went to the bench with 16:09 remaining
in Tuesday night's Rhode Island-Vanderbilt game after picking up
his fourth foul. Any question about how important the sophomore
sensation is to URI was answered in the next 3:49.
</P>
<P>
   URI suddenly went from a team worthy of its No. 23 ranking to a
sad shell of itself, a team devoid of rhythm and continuity,
scoring just once in five possessions. It was only a matter of time
before coach Jim Harrick would decide he had seen enough.
</P>
<P>
   Odom reentered and scored 11 of his team-high 20 points to help
URI pull away and register an 82-69 victory in the CoSIDA Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started making eye contact with each other on the bench,''
said Odom. ``They went on a run, he looked over at me, and I knew
it was time to go back in.''
</P>
<P>
   Odom, who went to the bench with his team leading by 1,
reentered with the Rams trailing by 1. It was then that the
sophomore from Queens, N.Y., showed another aspect of his brilliant
all-around game _ the ability to play effectively while in foul
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams are 2-0 for the first time in three seasons, while
Vanderbilt, which kept the game close by sinking 14 of 33 3-point
attempts, fell to 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   In the evening's first game, Texas Christian edged Providence,
79-77, on a bucket by Scott Gradney with 28.6 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   This has been quite a week for Odom. He played in his first two
collegiate games. He scored his first winning basket, in Monday's
victory over TCU. He suffered his first injury, when he left
Tuesday's game in the first half after he drove into a crowded
paint area, took a hard fall, and came up with a bloody nose.
</P>
<P>
   And he had his first long stint on the bench because of foul
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I have ever played that long with four fouls
without fouling out,'' said Odom. ``Coach had his confidence in me
to go back in there and play well with four fouls.''
</P>
<P>
   What Odom has not experienced yet is his first collegiate
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to action with the Rams trailing, 51-50. URI then
outscored Vanderbilt, 7-1, to take a 57-52 lead, with Odom sinking
a 3-pointer. Vandy got within 61-58, but URI never relinquished
control. A pull-up by Antonio Reynolds-Dean with 3:59 left gave the
Rams a 73-63 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, Lamar controls the game, kind of like a more
athletic version of Magic Johnson,'' said Vanderbilt coach Jan van
Breda Kolff. ``He's a big guard who can see over the top of people
just like Magic did. His vision of the court is great and he has a
smaller defender on him, so he's able to find people.''
</P>
<P>
   Providence, meanwhile, is only two games into its season but it
developing a dangerous habit of blowing double-digit leads.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, the Friars squandered a 15-point first-half
advantage and lost to Vanderbilt by 6. On Tuesday, they jumped out
to a 12-point first-half lead.
</P>
<P>
   The second half was nip and tuck, and with the game tied at 77,
Gradney took a feed on the right wing and scored on a baseline bank
shot. PC blew a chance to tie or win when forward Jamel Thomas
misfired just before time expired.
</P>
<P>
   URI and PC face each other Saturday at the Civic Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
