<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-PENGUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENGUINS DEFEAT ISLANDERS, 3-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ After loafing through the first two periods on
Tuesday night, the New York Islanders turned up the pressure on the
Pittsburgh Penguins, outshooting their hosts by 14-4 through the
final 20 minutes. The scoring chances were plentiful, but the
Islanders lacked polish around the net.
</P>
<P>
   For too much of their dreary 3-2 loss to the Penguins, the
Islanders were sleepwalking, having played for a second straight
night. The fervor they displayed in Monday's 3-1 victory at Toronto
was missing early, and there was little doubt that weary legs had
something to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were probably five or six minutes we could have played
better,'' said Bryan Smolinski, who scored his fifth goal. ``That
cost us.''
</P>
<P>
   Down by 3-1, the Islanders (7-8) awakened when Trevor Linden
scored from the middle of the right circle at 1 minute 54 seconds
of the third period. After Linden cut the Penguins' lead to 3-2,
the Islanders had several chances to tie the score, but were
thwarted by Pittsburgh's backup goalie Jean-Sebastien Aubin, who
made 29 saves. Claude Lapointe hit the goal post with about six
minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Salo, the Islanders' goalie, played well for the second
night in row, but he was let down by his defense. Salo made 17
saves, five against Jaromir Jagr, the league's top scorer.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Islanders refused to cite exhaustion as an excuse,
but the veteran defenseman Rich Pilon had seen this sort of effort
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have our legs tonight,'' he said. ``We were just too
tired. I hate to use that as an excuse, but that's how a lot of us
felt.''
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders fell behind by 1-0 less than two minutes into the
game on a perfectly placed wrist shot by Aleksei Morozov.
</P>
<P>
   Playing in front of his parents, who traveled from his hometown
of Toledo, Ohio, Smolinski scored at 6:27 to tie the score at 1-1.
The Islanders were on the power play when Smolinski, standing in
front of the Penguins' net, knocked down a shot from Robert Reichel
and tapped in the puck.
</P>
<P>
   The loafing Islanders were sloppy in the second period as the
Penguins (6-3-4) extended their lead to 3-1. Both of their goals
came on busted plays by the Islanders' defense. The Penguins, who
had six attackers on the ice because of a delayed penalty, took a
2-1 lead 54 seconds into the period on a one-timer by Robert Lang,
who was left alone in front of the Islanders' goal.
</P>
<P>
   A second miscue by an Islanders defender helped the Penguins to
their third goal, at 11:29. Defenseman Barry Richter slid into Salo
as the goalie was making a save on Martin Straka, knocking the puck
in with his skate. Had Richter not lost his balance, Salo would
probably have held onto the puck.
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of game for the Islanders, who should get a
full night's rest now that they are stuck in Pittsburgh. The team's
chartered flight was canceled because of high winds. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
