<SLUG> BC-MEHTA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONDUCTOR TESTIFIED AGAINST SUSAN MCDOUGAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY PETER HARTLAUB 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA, Calif. _ Tired after traveling halfway around the
world to testify against Susan McDougal in her embezzlement trial,
conductor Zubin Mehta angrily protested a question about how he and
his wife spent their money.
</P>
<P>
   When McDougal's defense attorney confronted him with receipts
that contradicted the conductor's testimony, Mehta responded:
``That doesn't mean she can steal from us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting upset now,'' Mehta blurted out at one point,
cutting off Superior Court Judge Leslie Light.
</P>
<P>
   Light ordered Mehta to take a few breaths and compose himself.
</P>
<P>
   Mehta, the final witness of the trial, did little more in his
short stint on the stand Tuesday than confirm his wife's previous
testimony: When it comes to finances, she calls all the shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The check comes home. Then she puts it in the bank (and) we
both spend it,'' Mehta said.
</P>
<P>
   McDougal is charged with stealing $150,000 from the Mehtas while
she was working as a bookkeeper for them from 1989 to 1992.
</P>
<P>
   McDougal, who testified last week, and was in the courtroom
Tuesday, claims she had permission to spend the money and paid a
lot of it back. The Mehtas claim she took out a credit card in
their name and forged signatures without permission.
</P>
<P>
   The charges have nothing to do with the Whitewater land-deal
investigation that made McDougal's name known in households across
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Zubin Mehta, who was directing the New York Philharmonic when
McDougal worked for him, drew a crowd of reporters and others to
the small Santa Monica courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   He spent little more than an hour on the witness stand _ a mere
cameo in a trial that has lasted for more than a month. McDougal
testified for more than six days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sleepy,'' Mehta admitted when he took the witness stand
after a 13-hour flight from Germany. He is headed back to Munich
today for a concert.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of his time on the witness stand, the 62-year-old
conductor seemed to get a little testy, with the one notable
outburst during McDougal attorney Mark Garegos' cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
   Garegos confronted Mehta with receipts contradicting the
conductor's previous testimony that he didn't pay for his plumber's
plane ticket to Italy.
</P>
<P>
   During his testimony, Mehta said he was gone most of the time
McDougal was working for him and heard positive reports from his
wife, who kept track of their finances at his Los Angeles home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no complaints,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After the allegedly unauthorized credit card charges were
discovered, Mehta said he calmly told his wife to get their lawyer
and confront McDougal, but only after taking her to a movie.
</P>
<P>
   While Mehta's temper flared on the stand, most of the time he
and Judge Light acted as if they were trying to perfect a comedy
routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``All rise,'' Mehta joked at one point during his testimony,
ordering the packed courtroom to stand when Light entered the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate your gesture,'' Light said, but pointed out that
the tradition went out with long white wigs.
</P>
<P>
   Closing arguments are scheduled to start Thursday afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 0055EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
