<HEADLINE>
EARLY LESSONS FOR GEORGETOWN AND ILLINOIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They played basketball on Tuesday night at Madison
Square Garden. How's that for a novelty?
</P>
<P>
   For anyone in attendance who was feeling deprived in light of
the National Basketball Association's labor dispute, the Coaches
vs. Cancer Ikon Classic provided a brief lift. For Illinois and
Wake Forest, who played in the first game, the tournament provided
early indicators of what type of season they might have.
</P>
<P>
   The Demon Deacons are young, but they are experienced, returning
four sophomore starters. The Illini are young and inexperienced,
with no starters returning. The more seasoned Demon Deacons, led by
24 points from the sophomore guard Robert O'Kelley, won in
overtime, 75-73.
</P>
<P>
   In the second game, Temple, ranked No. 7 by The Associated
Press, defeated Georgetown, 65-49. Temple will meet Wake Forest in
the final on Wednesday night at 9.
</P>
<P>
   The Illini (0-1), the defending Big Ten champions, have enough
variables to keep a coach up at night, even in November. Despite
the loss, Coach Lon Kruger was relieved to see that his team was
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of learning opportunities in that ball game,''
he said. ``They would slide and then fight back. We're going to
have to learn a lot. We have a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Illini led by 73-72 with 25 seconds left in overtime after
Cory Bradford (20 points) drove past O'Kelley for a layup. O'Kelley
then exploded by Illinois' Sergio McClain at the other end and drew
the foul. He made both free throws to push Wake Forest ahead by
74-73 with 19 seconds remaining. Bradford tried to dribble past
O'Kelley on Illinois's next possession but was called for charging.
</P>
<P>
   O'Kelley made one free throw at the other end to increase Wake's
lead to 2. Bradford had one more opportunity, but threw up an air
ball as the buzzer sounded.
</P>
<P>
   In regulation, Wake's Craig Dawson scored all 8 of his points _
two 3-pointers and a pair of free throws _ in a one-minute span to
give the Demon Deacons a 64-61 lead with 1 minute 12 seconds left.
Rich Beyers sailed in a 3-pointer for Illinois to tie the game.
After a missed jump shot by O'Kelley, Beyers let fly the potential
game-winner with a few seconds remaining, but it was blocked by
Wake's Darius Songaila. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `'I don't really like my team, I love them,'' Wake Coach Dave
Odom said. ``That's kind of uncomfortable for me because I usually
kind of grow into loving my team.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams were sloppy. Illinois committed 26 turnovers, and
Wake had 21. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wake, the ACC's worst-shooting team last season at 40 percent,
shot 40 percent (26 of 65) on Tuesday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 0058EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4433 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-11 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
BCS can't deliver true champion
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN P. LOPEZ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   The championship part of college football's Bowl Championship
Series has become a sham, as suspected all along, so it might be
time to come up with a more appropriate abbreviation than the BCS.
</P>
<P>
   May we suggest eliminating the ``C.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, what is another championship system without a true
champion but just another pile in the pasture? What is it, but just
another example of why as long as there is not a national playoff,
there will be no true national champion. Period.
</P>
<P>
   We have been down this road before. We have seen such
nonsensical alternatives _ from under-the-table bowl agreements, to
the bowl coalition, to the bowl alliance, to the
super-duper-we-really-mean-it-this-time bowl alliance.
</P>
<P>
   But by any name, it is a sham.
</P>
<P>
   It hurts and diminishes the peripheral bowls that administrators
say they are trying to save. It cheats the fans to whom
administrators say they are faithful and whose fannies fill
stadiums and dollars build science labs.
</P>
<P>
   It penalizes some teams and conferences while rewarding others.
It is riddled with gaping holes and personal biases, no matter how
many computers, formulas and adjusted deviations are used.
</P>
<P>
   It is just another pile in the pasture. And the game's athletic
directors and university presidents have us stepping in it again.
</P>
<P>
   Let's look closely at the BCS as it stands. What has it offered
us with just three full weekends of football remaining?
</P>
<P>
   A true No. 1? No. Not now and probably not after the bowls.
</P>
<P>
   If the Fiesta Bowl were to hold its national-championship game
today, the teams involved would be UCLA and Tennessee, based on the
current rankings. Kansas State, probably the most consistent team
in the land, would be left out.
</P>
<P>
   And suppose Kansas State and Tennessee lose. Based on the
direction the rankings are headed, the winner of the
Florida-Florida State game Nov. 21 would earn the BCS bid to the
Fiesta instead of an undefeated Arkansas or Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us might be huge Florida and Florida State fans, but
such a development would be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The likes of Arkansas and Wisconsin deserve the chance to fail
on the field. In a playoff. If a 10-1 Florida _ after not playing
in its conference championship game because it lost to Tennessee _
believes it should have a shot, it should earn it on the field. In
a playoff. If a team goes undefeated, it should not be shut out
simply because of a conference affiliation, as Tulane might be.
</P>
<P>
   What about an unbiased ranking? Has this BCS come through? No.
Not now and probably not going into the bowls.
</P>
<P>
   The latest BCS rankings have UCLA No. 2 despite the hand of God
apparently helping the Bruins to close wins over Stanford and
Oregon State, which are a combined 1-12 in the Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins justifiably lost ground in the opinion polls, but
remarkably remained strong enough in the three computer polls to
stay in the hunt.
</P>
<P>
   The use of computer polls by the Seattle Times, the New York
Times and Jeff Sagarin was supposed to eliminate biases and create
a rock-solid formula for determining the best teams. The computer
polls also were supposed to eliminate the temptation for coaches to
run up victory margins in hopes of earning points.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong again.
</P>
<P>
   One computer poll (Seattle Times) does not consider victory
margin, another (New York Times) gives added weight to victory
margin, and the third (Sagarin) collapses the margin after 28
points. This was clearing things up?
</P>
<P>
   In other words, fans only thought Kansas State's 49-6 win over
Baylor last week was indeed 49-6. In Seattle, it was just a win _
7-6 or 49-6, it didn't matter to the computer. In New York, it was
a 60-6 win, and according to Sagarin it was 34-6. You figure it
out.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, today UCLA is No. 1 in Seattle; Sagarin has Kansas State
No. 1 and somehow the New York Times spit out Florida State, of all
teams, as No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   That's how Kansas State, despite being ranked higher than UCLA
in four of the five polls, is behind UCLA in the BCS ratings.
</P>
<P>
   As for the human factor, nothing illustrated the flaws more than
an Associated Press voter saying recently that he believed
Tennessee was the best team in the country, but he would vote
Tennessee No. 3, Florida State No. 2 and Kansas State No. 1, just
so UCLA could lose some points in the BCS formula.
</P>
<P>
   It has come to this: Pollsters no longer are voting on what they
see on the field, but on what they want to see in the BCS rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly drastic jumps in the opinion polls might occur after
this weekend if Arkansas upsets Tennessee in Knoxville. Pollsters
might suddenly vault Arkansas, currently No. 10 and No. 9 in the
opinion polls, above UCLA or Kansas State, just so they can
manipulate the computer.
</P>
<P>
   It's all just another sham. The more we want things decided on
the field, the more we find ourselves knee-deep in the pasture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
