<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
McNair relentless in pursuit of team
<TEXT>
<P>
   By FRAN BLINEBURY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   The sun is going down, and the shadows are lengthening. It's
getting late in the game and the clock seems to be running faster
and faster.
</P>
<P>
   This is Bob McNair's huddle, and there is no lack of confidence
from the man running it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crunch time,'' he said. ``We have the ball in the red
zone, and now the job is to punch it into the end zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Sis-boom-bah!
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't have official title of an NFL team for the city of
Houston, but McNair has the lingo.
</P>
<P>
   If we were looking for a reincarnation of Knute Rockne to carry
us back into the ranks of the NFL, McNair is our man, complete with
all the fiery words. Listen to him talk for just a few minutes, and
you'll believe he's willing to get down in the trenches and play
without a facemask if that's what it will take to bring pro
football back to town.
</P>
<P>
   He is like a linebacker in search of a set of exposed ribs in
which to jam his helmet, a running back with all the right moves
who is just itching to get his hands on the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Twiddle his thumbs? No way
</P>
<P>
   It has been two weeks since McNair, the well-respected
businessman, led a group that included Mayor Lee Brown, County
Judge Robert Eckels and Jack Rains, head of the sports authority,
to Kansas City, where they laid out a drop-dead proposal for a
state-of-the-art football stadium in our town.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston group fulfilled all of the prerequisites of the NFL,
cleared all of the hurdles, and easily outdistanced any Hollywood
glitz promises and dreams that were made by two groups from Los
Angeles. The NFL owners said, in essence, we'll get back to you on
that, maybe at our next scheduled meeting Feb. 16. Which left two
choices:
</P>
<P>
   Sit back and spend the next 3{ months trying to set a world
record for twiddling thumbs.
</P>
<P>
   Or put your head down, start your legs churning like you're
hitting a blocking sled, and try to grind out that one more yard
that might make the difference.
</P>
<P>
   McNair chose the latter. Soon after returning from Kansas City,
he reached an agreement to sell his highly successful gas business,
Cogen Technologies. Tuesday afternoon he met with a group of 82
local businessmen who are prospective limited partners in a Houston
football team. And as soon as commissioner Paul Tagliabue names the
expansion committee that will focus on determining the 32nd
franchise for the NFL _ which should happen soon after Thanksgiving
_ McNair will begin making rounds to do more campaigning and
convincing.
</P>
<P>
   Betting on himself
</P>
<P>
   This is a man who made the decision to sell off his business, in
part because it was a good deal, but also to serve notice he plans
for the NFL to become his prime focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I do feel confident,'' McNair said. ``It's simple,
really. We met the NFL requirements, and Los Angeles can't. Not
without a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he didn't come back from KC with a team, raising suspicions
about whether Houston is being used as a pawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it so much as them keeping the door open for LA,''
McNair said. ``They just like competition. It keeps the price up.
If they had agreed that Houston is ready to go and said yes back
then, there wouldn't be nearly the hype to keep the price high.
What you've got, I believe, is a managed auction. They are trying
to keep us all in the game to bid against each other.''
</P>
<P>
   But a price in excess of the $530 million paid for the Cleveland
expansion team is too high, according to McNair.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL did all the work, sold PSLs, got the stadium deal
worked out in Cleveland,'' he said. ``So I see that price as for
both a team and a stadium. I don't think it should be that much for
just a franchise in Houston, since we have done all the work to
deliver a world-class stadium. Of course, that's all negotiable.''
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of the NBA and in the aftermath of the baseball
season, these are the games we play. The money games. Moises Alou
squeezes an extra $3 million out of the Astros. Randy Johnson holds
himself out to the highest bidder. The NFL raises the cash bar
higher, and McNair vows to show us his vertical leap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm intent on getting a team for Houston,'' he said. ``I
consider Tagliabue to be a personal friend. He advised me what was
needed, and we've delivered. Now I've got to meet with the members
of the expansion committee when it is in place. I've got to keep
pushing at them, make them understand.''
</P>
<P>
   This could be a tense time, a nervous time, if you really
believe you've done all you can.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a working time,'' McNair said. ``I don't get nervous. I
get my juices flowing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
