<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4436 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-cami-HNS &LR;      11-11 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-cami-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Caminiti turns down Tigers' offer
<TEXT>
<P>
   Return to Astros likely if deal sweetened
</P>
<P>
   By CARLTON THOMPSON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   How badly does Ken Caminiti want to play for the Astros?
</P>
<P>
   All you need to know is what happened late Tuesday night. Faced
with a deadline to make a decision, Caminiti walked away from the
Detroit Tigers' generous three-year, $21.5 million offer in hopes
of striking a deal with the Astros, who have weighed in with an
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball sources said the Astros' proposal could net Caminiti
about $10.5 million over the next three years, assuming he reached
certain incentives. The first two years of the Astros' offer are
believed to be guaranteed, with the club holding an option for the
third year.
</P>
<P>
   That's a far cry from the Tigers' offer, but if the Astros would
be willing to improve it _ and there are indications it won't take
much more _ the two sides likely would reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti, who lives in Richmond, will resume negotiations with
the Astros today, and there is a distinct possibility the sides
could reach a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Astros) know what it's going to take, and I know what
it's going to take,'' said Caminiti, who declined to discuss
details of the Astros' offer or what it might take to sign him.
``Their offer was not bad, but it was not great, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm leaving a whole bunch of money out there (in Detroit). I
want to play (in Houston), but I'm not going to be penalized for
playing here. They need to try and treat me fairly. I guess I've
been on both sides of it; they were overfair in Detroit.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker, who is attending the
general manager's meetings in Naples, Fla., was unavailable for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers submitted identical offers last week to Caminiti and
Dean Palmer, with the condition the deal would be pulled off the
table after one of the free-agent third basemen decided to accept
it. That presumably is the reason they asked Caminiti to make a
decision Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed an answer from Caminiti because we're giving Palmer
our best offer, and you can't have two offers hanging out there,''
Tigers assistant general manager Steve Lubratich said. ``We needed
an answer; Palmer has teams on his heels, and we couldn't wait for
Caminiti to make a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti said: ``I just had no more time left. I had to make a
decision. If (the Tigers' offer) is still there (today), maybe
we'll see. Right now, I just need to slow the process a little
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Many observers will wonder how Caminiti could have turned down
such a lucrative deal from the Tigers to focus on the Astros'
offer, which is worth significantly less. It wasn't easy, but the
35-year-old third baseman wants to finish his career in Houston,
which would allow him to spend more time with his wife, Nancy, and
their three daughters _ Kendall, 7, Lindsey, 5, and Nicole (10
months).
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball has been good to me,'' Caminiti said. ``I'm fortunate
not to have to play for money. I've never been the kind of player
who plays for money. I play for happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   And happiness would be finishing his major-league career with
the same team for which it began.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Caminiti is that home is very important to
him,'' Tigers general manager Randy Smith said. ``It says a lot
about him that money isn't his No. 1 issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti was the Astros' third-round pick in the 1984 draft and
made his major-league debut with the club three years later. He
played in Houston through the 1994 season before being traded to
San Diego in a blockbuster deal.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti blossomed into a star player with the Padres, winning
three Gold Glove awards and claiming the National League's Most
Valuable Player Award in 1996 when he hit .326 with 40 homers and
130 RBIs. The RBI total tied Mickey Mantle's 1956 output, the most
ever by a switch-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, Dodgers and White Sox also have expressed interest in
Caminiti, but returning to the Padres doesn't seem an option.
</P>
<P>
   On the Randy Johnson front, the same day he toured the Arizona
Diamondbacks' complex, he accepted a long-distance call from New
York Yankees owner George Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   The Boss reached out and touched Johnson, although those were
the only numbers exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   ``George spoke with Randy today and everything went great. Randy
was very impressed,'' Johnson's agent, Alan Nero, said. ``Now it's
just a matter of us going through this process.''
</P>
<P>
   But to that end, the initial contract offer Nero was expecting
from the Yanks did not come when he spoke with GM Brian Cashman. At
least one GM monitoring the bidding surrounding the 6-10 lefty
dominator said he ``would be absolutely astounded if (Johnson)
wound up with the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got off the phone with (Cashman) and I'm still waiting
for an offer,'' Nero said. ``But our discussion went very well and
was very positive. They said they're going to make an offer; it's
just going to take a little time. I'm still hoping it's some time
(Tuesday night or today).''
</P>
<P>
   As for Arizona, general manager Joe Garagiola Jr., also at the
annual GM's meetings, said of Johnson: ``From our sense, Randy is
still kind of sorting things out and maybe wants to visit a couple
more places. Then I think the discussion will start to focus on the
dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas is also among the clubs interested in Johnson, who lives
in suburban Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle news services contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
