<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-LIGHTNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS CRUSH LIGHTNING, 10-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By TOM HARDESTY   
 c.1998 New York Times Regional Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ A week ago, six goals in one game seemed
impossible for the New York Rangers. On Tuesday night, they hit
double figures.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who entered the game as the lowest-scoring team in
the National Hockey League (24), scored at will and blasted the
Tampa Bay Lightning, 10-2, before 11,604 at the Ice Palace.
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive game, the Rangers' offense was on
fire. Kevin Stevens had three goals and two assists, while and Ulf
Samuelsson, who has been bothered by a swollen knee, scored two
goals. Brian Leetch and Todd Harvey registered three assists each.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin's been playing very well,'' Rangers Coach John Muckler
said. ``Five points? That's a pretty good night.''
</P>
<P>
   For Stevens, it was his first hat trick since Jan. 11, 1994, and
the first time he had 5 points in a game since Oct. 17, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who last scored 10 goals on Dec. 13, 1992, in a
10-5 victory over Montreal, won their first game on the road this
season and snapped a seven-game slump here (0-6-1).
</P>
<P>
   ``All phases of our game were on tonight,'' Muckler said. ``We
had better puck movement in the neutral zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, who has had two 6-point games in his career, said:
``It's nice to get one like this. It seems like all our games this
year have been nip and tuck. It was a great team effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gretzky, who had two assists in the final period,
complimented his teammates. ``It's great to see those guys pile up
numbers,'' he said of Stevens, Harvey and Leetch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody gets their butt kicked every once in a while,''
Lightning Coach Jacques Demers said. ``They played very well. We
just got beat in every department.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers didn't take long to assume control of the game.
Michael Knuble skated past the Lightning blue line and passed to a
wide-open Samuelsson, who teed it up and drilled a shot past Tampa
Bay goalie Bill Ranford on the glove side for a 1-0 lead and his
first goal of the season. The goal by Samuelsson came just 2
minutes 5 seconds into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay evened the score at 11:18 when, on a power play,
Daymond Langkow jammed in a rebound of a Benoit Hogue shot past
goalie Dan Cloutier.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers stunned the crowd with two goals in 16 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The first came on the power play. Jan Mertzig took a shot from
the right face-off circle, but Stevens redirected it with his stick
past Ranford at the 13:35 mark.
</P>
<P>
   The second was set up when Tampa Bay turned the puck over deep
in its own territory. Stevens grabbed the puck and passed to Manny
Malhotra, who was right in front of the net for the goal to make it
3-1 Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers got their fourth goal of the period when Mathieu
Schneider made a perfect pass to John MacLean, who despite being
nearly even with the Tampa Bay goal, got the puck past Ranford for
his fourth goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers scored just 25 seconds into the second period. Marc
Savard passed from the left side to Stevens, who one-timed it past
Ranford for a 5-1 advantage. It was Savard's fifth assist in two
games.
</P>
<P>
   Another defensive miscue by Tampa Bay boosted the New York lead
to 6-1. Deep in the Lightning zone, Steve Kelly couldn't clear the
puck and Harvey grabbed it and pulled the trigger. Ranford stopped
the shot but fell down, and Samuelsson lifted the rebound over
Ranford with 3:29 gone.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay finally broke the string of Ranger goals when Mikael
Andersson skated through center ice and passed to a streaking
Enrico Ciccone, who blasted a shot at Cloutier that trickled
between the goalie's legs and into the net. Ciccone's first goal of
the season came at the 6:17 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Ranger goal No. 7 came on the power play. Harvey, from the left
side, made a pinpoint pass to Savard on the right. Savard went high
and over a sliding Ranford for his first goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers got goals from Niklas Sundstrom, Stevens and Harvey
in the third period to close out the scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Distributed by The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
