<HEADER>
A4439 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     11-11 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORT WORTH-DALLAS AREA IS BASEBALL RICH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The best high school baseball in the country is right here in
the Fort Worth-Dallas area.
</P>
<P>
   But we didn't need two rookie-of-the-year awards to tell us
that.
</P>
<P>
   We knew it from the youth-league games that we saw every year at
places like Richfield Park. We saw it in the summer select leagues.
And we saw it every time a local high school player signed a
Division I scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Brown knows.
</P>
<P>
   The TCU baseball coach once had grant-in-aid commitments from _
are you sitting down for this? _ both Ben Grieve, who yesterday was
named the American League rookie of the year, and Kerry Wood, who
on Monday was named National League rookie of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Brown said yesterday, sighing deeply, ``if we had
gotten both of those, we might have been in good shape for a run at
the College World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown used to coach high school ball in this area, so he knows.
As good as it was in the '80s, it has been even better in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   High school kids now play baseball year-round. After the prep
season concludes, they head off to the Pony Colt leagues or Connie
Mack ball. Come September, it's fall-ball time.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, a lot of time when people would talk about the
difference between the baseball in California, Florida and Texas,''
TCU's Brown said, ``it was because the California players played 12
months of the year. But California isn't the only one who has fall
leagues anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids here are playing year-round, too. We picked up on it
sort of late here, but since then the amount of talent that comes
through this area has really blossomed.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood and Grieve are products of those summer-select and fall
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the summer team that Ben played on after his junior
year,'' said Tom Grieve, Ben's dad and the former Rangers general
manager. ``That team had Kip Harkrider, who went on and played at
Texas and made the Olympic team. It had Eddie Furniss, who went to
LSU and became college player of the year. It had Adam Leggett, who
is in the Angels organization and made All-SEC. It had Chad Allen,
who went to A&AMP;M and was on the Olympic team. And it had Matt Blank,
the Expos organization's minor-league pitcher of the year this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every kid on that Dallas Mustangs team that summer
ended up playing at a major Division I school or playing pro
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Coached by Sam Carpenter, that Mustangs team finished second to
a team from Cincinnati, Ohio, at the national Connie Mack League
tournament. But Carpenter has won it in other years.
</P>
<P>
   The two rookie-of-the-year awards this week represent an
affirmation, of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says something about baseball in the Tarrant County and
Dallas-Fort Worth area,'' Ben Grieve said yesterday, ``to have two
guys come through and be successful like this. I think there's a
lot of talent in the area and it's great to get some recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben himself was a part of a talented group at Martin High School
coached by Terry King.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played on a state championship team in Massachusetts when I
was growing up,'' Tom Grieve said, ``and I think only two kids on
our high school team could have even made the team that Ben played
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have people in California and Florida argue. But
there's not a place in the country where the caliber of baseball is
any better than the Metroplex.''
</P>
<P>
   For the eldest Grieve, the announcement yesterday was mixed with
as much relief as celebration. He knew that Ben was facing enough
pressure this past season, just proving that he was ready to stick
in the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made the comment yesterday that on the first day of spring
training, the first question asked to him was whether he thought he
was going to be the American League rookie of the year this year,''
Tom said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when it was all over and done, he did live up to the
expectations. And I was real proud and happy that he was able to
perform under those circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who know Ben, even the day of his biggest major-league
honor was typically Ben Grieve. The family was up at 6:30 a.m.,
having breakfast, and had been pre-alerted by Oakland officials to
expect a phone call.
</P>
<P>
   If the call from the Baseball Writers Association of America
representative arrived, Ben was scheduled to dash out the door to
catch the next flight to Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   If it didn't, Ben was going back to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   There is something refreshing, it says here, about a rising star
athlete who still sleeps in the same bed where he grew up. In the
off-season, the American League rookie of the year doesn't move to
a condo in Southern California. He comes home to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love it,'' Tom Grieve said. ``I'm sure he'll get married
someday, and when he does he'll leave. But for the time being, we
think it's great that he likes coming back here and living with us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't even complain about the mess.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
