<HEADLINE>
UCLA WINS EXHIBITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If one sloppy, endless exhibition is any
indication of the season to come, the new-era UCLA Bruins will play
hard, they will pass and they will play fast.
</P>
<P>
   With point guard Earl Watson directing the attack, UCLA sprinted
to a 27-point first-half lead and outlasted the California West
All-Stars 95-89 Tuesday night before 6,094 at Pauley Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've played 10 straight nights, so we can't get too
excited,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin said. ``But I saw some real
positive things. We shared the ball and played aggressively.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson is UCLA's most-improved player and its floor leader, at
least until injured guard Baron Davis returns. Tuesday, he was
everywhere, throwing alley-oops and 50-foot bounce passes and
finishing with 15 points, 13 assists and 10 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Heralded freshman forward JaRon Rush led UCLA with 17 points and
dived for more loose balls in one game than J.R. Henderson did in
four years.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Freshman center Dan Gadzuric (knee tendinitis) and
sophomore guard/forward Rico Hines (sprained knee) did not play.
Both are expected to play in the season opener Nov. 19 against
Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   Recruit Kareem Rush (JaRon's brother) gave UCLA an oral
commitment several weeks ago and might sign a letter of intent
during the early-signing period, which begins today. Or he might
wait until the spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
