   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EMAIL-EVIDENCE (Undated) _ Never mind monopoly power in the
marketplace; in the Microsoft antitrust trial e-mail has emerged as
the star witness _ a fact that appears to be giving pause to
corporate executives accustomed to clicking ``send'' without a
second thought. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIANS-MAILSCAM (New York) _ There was the doctor from West
Virginia who received a letter from the Nigerian government
offering a business opportunity; he wrote several checks totaling
$225,000. There were the three Amish farmers who heard about an
offer for an oil pipeline contract. They, too, wrote several
checks. They were among the millions of Americans who have received
letters from Nigeria claiming to be from governmental bodies
offering plans to strike it rich. The letters are part of what
federal investigators say may be the oldest mail fraud scheme. By
David W. Chen.
</P>
<P>
   ORGAN-BANK (Boston) _ Just as scientists announced that someday
they may be able to grow livers and hearts outside the body,
recipients and donors from around the world gather for the 30th
anniversary of the country's oldest organ bank. They talk about how
the fight over who gets organs is tearing apart organizations and
recipients. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS-TRAIL-TOWN (St. Marys, Kan.) _ St. Marys, once the last
``civilized'' stop on the Oregon trail, is now a crossroads of a
different sort, where passionately held and often contradictory
visions of American life at the end of the 20th century are being
lived out at close quarters. By Jo Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS (undated) _ The Texas Baptist convention, the biggest
Baptist group in the U.S., may be splitting, with conservatives
fleeing an organization that is dominated by moderates. Meanwhile,
the national Baptists are dominated by conservatives. By Gustav
Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   PAIN-RELIEF (San Diego) _ A new class of drugs seems to be
living up to its promise of relieving pain and inflammation for
millions of arthritis sufferers but without the gastrointestinal
side effects of current drugs, according to new data presented at
the annual meeting of the American College of Rheumatalogy in San
Diego. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   ALTERNATIVE-MEDICINE (Washington) _ The influential Journal of
the American Medical Association publishes an issue focusing on
various alternative medicine treatments. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   MIR-STATION (Washington) _ The Russian space agency proposes
changing the orbit of the future international space station to
match the orbit of Mir. The stated reason is to transfer elements
from Mir to the station, but some Russian nationalist leaders are
also arguing that Mir should be kept alive as Russia's own symbol
in space. By Warren Leary.
</P>
<P>
   EDUC-ACCREDITATION (Undated) _ A growing chorus says the
accreditation process has gone out of control, tying up college
administrators for weeks on end, answering the hundreds of
questions posed by visiting inspection teams. These critics also
raise the concern that many accrediting agencies have become
lobbyists for the academic disciplines they are supposed to
regulate. By William H. Honan.
</P>
<P>
   EDUC-PHD'S (Undated) _ Responding to charges that universities
are producing too many Ph.D.'s who are unable to find jobs, a
committee of the Association of American Universities, a group of
elite research universities, Tuesday defended their production of
Ph.D.'s as being useful for society, but called on its members to
make sure their programs were meeting student needs and preparing
them for careers. By Karen Arenson.
</P>
