<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS FLOP AT FINISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ When Jozef Stumpel recorded an assist 17
seconds into his return from injury, it seemed there was no way the
Kings could lose Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto when Olli Jokinen scored his first NHL goal. And when Luc
Robitaille scored for the fourth straight game. And when Glen
Murray's goal provided a two-goal lead nearly halfway through the
third period.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what? The Kings lost.
</P>
<P>
   And their 5-4 overtime loss to the Calgary Flames (6-6-2) before
a Saddledome crowd of 15,247 left coach Larry Robinson fuming. It
took all the sparkle off a victory by the Kings (5-7-3) in
Vancouver one day earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Bach, making his first NHL start and playing before friends
and family visiting from suburban Edmonton, allowed two late goals
in regulation, then had no chance when Andrew Cassels danced around
Steve Duchesne and scored the winner on a breakaway 1:12 into
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get these points back, you know,'' said Robinson,
adding that he is considering lineup changes for Thursday night's
home game against the expansion Nashville Predators. ``At this
point, it would have been great for us to come in here and go back
home with two wins under our belt. The thing that worries me most
about this is it's a devastating blow to our confidence level. I
don't know who the hell we think we are, that we can sit on a
two-goal lead, or a three-goal lead _ any lead. It's just
frustrating as hell. You get tired of screaming and yelling.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he sometimes feels as if he's talking to a brick wall,
Robinson replied, ``Sometimes there are brick walls, yes _ and
brick walls between their shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   To think the night had begun with such promise for the Kings.
Stumpel, back after missing 10 games with a strained left hip
flexor, assisted on a goal by Vladimir Tsyplakov at 1:52 of the
first period. Jokinen made it 2-0 nine minutes later off a pass
from Craig Johnson. And Robitaille made it 3-0 early in the second
period.
</P>
<P>
   But then the Kings let the Flames back in the game, allowing
goals to Theo Fluery and Valeri Bure before the end of the second
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're up, 3-0, we talk about keeping our shifts short in this
building because the air is thin, and Robitaille, Olli and Murray
got caught out twice, over a minute shift, two goals, they're back
in the game,'' Robinson said. ``Simple as that.... You (bleeping)
wonder why we scream and yell.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the lengthy shifts, Robitaille said, ``Sometimes that
happens. You want to come and change, but we got caught on a couple
of long shifts and got scored on.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Murray made it 4-2 at 8:42 of the third and the Kings
seemed secure. But Cory Stillman beat Bach with a shot from the
right faceoff circle less than two minutes later, and with 2:28
left, Derek Morris scored after Jeff Shantz beat Ian Laperriere on
a faceoff to Bach's left.
</P>
<P>
   In overtime, Cassels was one on one with Duchesne and
stickhandled past him. When he backhanded the puck past Bach, a
prone Duchesne buried his face in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fell down,'' Duchesne said. ``I worked hard. You make
mistakes. I feel really bad about losing the game like that, but it
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Bach said, ``It all happened pretty quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson had decided Monday to play Bach against Calgary and
give a rest to Manny Legace, who had appeared in 10 consecutive
games.
</P>
<P>
   Of Bach's play, Robinson said, ``He struggled a little bit, but
that's not the reason that we lost. Three of the goals were
questionable goals. But, still, knowing that this is a young kid
that's coming in here, you as a player, you don't have to be a
college graduate to know that you have to play strong
defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's solution to Tuesday's defensive woes might be lineup
changes. He said he will study videotape of the loss, then decide
whether to make one or more alterations. He added that healthy
scratches Dan Bylsma, Nathan LaFayette and Ray Ferraro might play
Thursday. He did not say who might be benched.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's immune,'' Robinson said. ``It's a team. A team is not
made up of superstars. A team is made up of hockey players. You've
got to be able to get the message across somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   If benchings don't work, Robinson said he has one more idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll pass out some resumes around here because obviously
there's a number of guys in there that think that their way is
better than my way, so if they want to coach themselves, then they
might as well fill out a resume,'' Robinson said. ``But they won't
last very long because their way has not been working.''
</P>
</TEXT>
