r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-REED-LADN     11-11 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-REED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM DESERT STORM TO BIG SKY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHRIDGE, Calif. _ Quinton Reed was asked if he felt like a
veteran. He paused, pondering the question for a few moments.
</P>
<P>
   Two years of playing linebacker at Mt. San Jacinto College
counted for something. Another nine games at Cal State Northridge
added to it.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, he had experience, but a veteran? No, not so early in his
Division I-AA career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that kind of a veteran,'' a voice shouted from the side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' Reed responded. ``You want to talk about the Army
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes. The Army stuff. The Desert Shield and Desert Storm stuff.
The Gulf War. That kind of veteran. A battlefield veteran, not a
gridiron one.
</P>
<P>
   After all, today is Veteran's Day. But Reed, as attested to by
the aforementioned exchange, is anything but your prototypical
veteran.
</P>
<P>
   He's a football player, a college student. Reed, 33, a
linebacker-turned-defensive lineman, wears an Army beret once in a
while, but it's the only thing that bears any military resemblance.
It certainly doesn't suggest eight years spent in the Army, which
included service in the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to think of it that often,'' Reed said. ``But it's a
great thing, Veteran's Day and Washington, D.C., with the wall.
It's a great way to remember the veterans because there was once a
day when they were cast away.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed was with the 1/39th FAR, an artillery division in the Army.
He went from Saudi Arabia to Kuwait and Iraq. Was on the battle
lines, always knowing death was possible.
</P>
<P>
   No big deal, he insists. The experience wasn't terrifying, only
his duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really wasn't anything that bad,'' Reed said. ``There were
times when you were walking around and you thought about it, but it
wasn't that big of a deal. It's not what you would think.''
</P>
<P>
   While in the Army, Reed would play football. Flag football,
mostly. Sometimes touch, but never tackle. He's 6-foot-2, 270
pounds, so why would one play tackle with Reed? Not in the Army,
anyhow.
</P>
<P>
   Junior college, though, was different. Reed wanted to play, but
didn't know where to go so he enrolled at Mt. San Jacinto.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Ron Ponciano scouted Reed. The coach's immediate
conviction was Reed would be playing high Division I-A football if
not for the age factor.
</P>
<P>
   Upon being named coach at CSUN, Ponciano contacted Reed and sold
the Matadors on him. Reed, not having many options, accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's exactly what we hoped he'd be when we decided to bring
him here,'' Ponciano said. ``He's mature. He's not a kid. It's
college, but everything's not an adventure to him. That's why you
can get on him and he'll look at you and say, `Check.'
</P>
<P>
   ```Check.' It means he's got it. A lot of kids give me excuses.
He gives you a check. That's why he gets better.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed's 10 tackles don't explain his value. Neither does his
willingness to move from linebacker to nose guard because the
Matadors were ravaged with injuries on the defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Reed at practice gives no indication of his age. He
hits the sleds as hard as the other Matadors, the ones who were
barely out of diapers when Reed went to Fort Bragg, N.C., for
bootcamp.
</P>
<P>
   Reed brings maturity to the rest of his teammates. During games,
it's the same thing. Reed offers no mannerisms to suggest he's
different, which he's not. Unless you look at his locker. His neat,
tidy locker that is so out of place in the Matadors locker room it
screams at you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's locked up in his locker, nothing is hanging
out,'' CSUN linebacker Kenny Knoop said. ``It's cleaned up, folded
up. He laughs at everyone and sleeps when he can. He's used to it.
And he gets a lot of guys around him to clean it up, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Ponciano wasn't happy with the effort during conditioning
drills at the end of practice and threw the offensive and defensive
lines off the field. He also made the players run ten 100-yard
sprints before the players, tongues in tow, went to the locker
room.... Wide receiver Mike Ogas hyperextended his left elbow in
practice and cornerback Donnell Day injured his left hand and is
expected to have X-rays taken today. Both players said they would
be back at practice today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
