</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SLUG-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HITCHCOCK LAYS DOWN LAW TO OUTSPOKEN HULL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Ken Hitchcock said Tuesday that Brett Hull's
comment about a lack of ice time in Saturday's game was ``just
talk.'' But the Stars coach said making public any displeasure is
something ``you just don't do'' in the Stars organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, this is a really good lesson for Brett Hull,''
Hitchcock said. ``He allowed himself to get going there, and you
can't do that. I don't know what he did before, but you don't do
that here. It doesn't matter if it's Hull, we just don't do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the general manager to the coach, we don't do it. We're a
family. If we have a family squabble, it's behind closed doors. We
don't air our laundry in public, period.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said that Hull's comment was blown out of proportion,
but that the incident allowed him and Hull to have a conversation
about what is expected from a Stars player in dealing with the news
media. The coach added that he ``would not let this fester'' before
the Stars play the Phoenix Coyotes at 7:30 p.m. Wednesday _ a
showdown between teams with the top winning percentages in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Hull, one of the NHL's most outspoken players in 10 seasons with
the St. Louis Blues, declined to comment yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   In a 10-minute news conference Monday, Hull answered several
questions, including one about him playing 11 minutes, 55 seconds
in a 4-3 victory against the Los Angeles Kings on Saturday _ about
five minutes less than his average ice time with the Stars and
eight minutes short of what he averaged with the St. Louis Blues
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no possible way Brett Hull can do anything in 11
minutes. There's no flow, there's no feel,'' he said. ``You're used
to playing so much more that it's a completely different mind-set.
... I could have had four goals, but my timing was all \Rmessed\S
up and my legs were asleep.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the issues raised in July when the Stars signed Hull to a
three-year, $17 million free-agent contract was whether the
free-wheeling Hull would fit into a Stars locker room filled with
``company men.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two focuses,'' Hitchcock said. ``No. 1 is: How is he
fitting in? And quite frankly, and I need this written properly,
he's fitting in great. No. 2 is: We have a different set of rules
here, and the rules are we don't do that on our team, period. My
door is open, and march in if you've got a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said the 11:55 in ice time for Hull was an anomaly
caused by a penalty-filled game. Hull averages almost 17 minutes a
game with the Stars, and Hitchcock said he expects Hull will get
his fair share of ice time.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to play well, Brett should be in the top three
\Rforwards\S in minutes, as long as those are productive minutes,''
Hitchcock said. ``When he's playing well, and he's been pretty damn
good, he needs to be playing 17 to 20 minutes a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars general manager Bob Gainey said the Stars' system is built
on inner conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply put, there is a place where a player who feels he
didn't receive what he should have received can make comments and
get results,'' Gainey said. ``And there are places you can make
comments and not get the answers to your questions. And every
player has to be able to understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Although that might seem overcontrolling, Stars defenseman Craig
Ludwig said players have always been able to talk with Stars
coaches when a problem arises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their doors are always open,'' Ludwig said. ``We've built a
strong locker room, and that's a big part of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
