<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4475 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-DEFENSE     11-11 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-DEFENSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M'S DEFENSE RELYING ON FRESH, YOUNG LINEMEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ In retrospect, Texas A&AMP;M defensive line
coach Bill Johnson can confess to fears he once covered with
bluster and bravado.
</P>
<P>
   In his seventh season at the school, Johnson is the
longest-tenured assistant on the staff of football coach R.C.
Slocum. He has seen the team's ``Wrecking Crew'' defense evolve
from dominant to docile and back to dominant during his stay in
College Station.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we had problems with our defense, it was when we were
short of experienced people in the line,'' Johnson said. ``And, to
be honest, I thought this would be the toughest year for us to get
through because of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson based those concerns on a defensive line that headed
into an Aug. 31 season opener against then-No.2 Florida State with
four sophomores, three freshmen, one junior and no returning
starters among its list of potential participants.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M still uses all eight players in games, with each handling
between 15 and 40 snaps. But Johnson's unit no longer needs pregame
pep talks about reaching untapped potential. It no longer needs him
to tell the world how good they might be ... someday.
</P>
<P>
   Someday is today. As No. 6 Texas A&AMP;M prepares for Saturday's
game against No. 13 Missouri, Slocum points to the evolution of the
defensive line as a major reason why the Aggies rank third
nationally in total defense, allowing 246.7 yards and 11.7 points
per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``At no time has that position been a weakness for us,'' said
Slocum, who has seen his linemen combine for 198 tackles (18 for
losses) and six sacks. ``Even against Florida State, with nothing
but new guys, they held their own. And they've gotten better every
week. In reality, we're further along than I expected to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Rival coaches have noticed the transformation. Missouri's Larry
Smith said A&AMP;M's progress up front has been ``striking.'' Texas
Tech coach Spike Dykes, who watched the Aggies make eight tackles
for losses in a 17-10 victory against the Red Raiders, praised the
Aggies' precision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their technique up front is tremendous. They do a great job of
occupying blockers and holding their ground so their linebackers
can go make tackles,'' Dykes said. ``In a 3-4 defense, that's
exactly what you're looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   That, plus a few big plays. Those have been coming in greater
numbers in recent weeks, with defensive end Rocky Bernard (47
tackles, six for losses) and nose guard Ron Edwards (39 tackles, 4
sacks) leading the charge.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards ranks fourth among A&AMP;M players in tackles for losses
with eight. He had a season-high seven stops in last week's 29-0
rout of Oklahoma, when the Aggies allowed just five first downs and
124 yards. His sack of Nebraska quarterback Bobby Newcombe on Oct.
10 resulted in a fumble that linebacker Warrick Holdman recovered
for a touchdown in a 28-21 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard's best game was against Kansas, when he had two tackles
for losses and a sack. Like Edwards, he also made a season-high
seven tackles against the Sooners.
</P>
<P>
   The secret of the line's success, said defensive coordinator
Mike Hankwitz, rests with Johnson's rotation system. No one gets
more than 40 plays. Against Nebraska, three fresh faces took the
field with each new series.
</P>
<P>
   Hankwitz, who is working for his eighth Division I-A school
since 1970, said he has never been around a defensive line with
more quality depth. And his list of past employers includes
Michigan, Colorado, Arizona, Kansas and Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can sell them on the idea that they have to play hard on
every snap because we're not asking them to do it 70 plays in a
row,'' Hankwitz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's strength in numbers,'' Johnson said. ``If we had only
three who could play, we wouldn't be as good. As young as we are, I
don't think anybody is mature enough to handle an every down
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   But no one is asked to do so. As a result, the Aggies have fresh
legs in the fourth quarter. The last team to score against A&AMP;M in
the final period was Baylor on Oct. 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the season first started, we hoped we could be part of
this team's success,'' Bernard said. ``Now that we've made some
contributions, it's exciting. I think the rotation system helps
with that. They keep us rolling to the point we really can't get
tired. And the stronger you feel, the better your chances to make
plays.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
