r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-LYONS-COLUMN-TEX     11-11 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LYONS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS-CARDINALS GAME OFFERS MATCHUP OF RARE SIGNIFICANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since they moved to Arizona in 1988, the Cardinals (5-4) have
had a winning record nine games into the season once. Thus,
November and December matchups featuring the Cowboys and Cardinals
have usually produced the pregame hoopla afforded a potato sack
race.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, you have to go back to Week 11 of the 1984 season _
when the Cardinals were in St. Louis _ to find a midseason
Cowboys-Cardinals game that merited big-game hype.
</P>
<P>
   That season, with each team sporting a 6-4 record, the Cowboys
and Cardinals were part of a four-way tie atop the NFC East when
the clubs met at Busch Stadium on Nov. 11, 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The week before the game, the Fort Worth-Dallas news media
provided big feature coverage of how many Cowboys fans were
traveling to St. Louis, and how the Cowboys hoped to stop speedy
Cardinals receiver Roy Green. The media followed news of Tom Landry
naming Gary Hogeboom the starting quarterback over Danny White, and
of Tony Dorsett missing much of practice to be with his ill father,
who died a few days before the game.
</P>
<P>
   There was even a story on how the Cowboys would not have to wear
their ``unlucky'' blue road jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   Although Rafael Septien missed three field goals, the Cowboys
defeated the Cardinals, 24-17. Afterward, the Cowboys talked about
how their season was saved. And the Cardinals talked about how they
would bounce back.
</P>
<P>
   But the talk proved hollow. Each club finished 9-7 and missed
the playoffs, the Cowboys for the first time in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   So here we are again. First place in the NFC East is on the
line, with enough storylines to fill area news pages and newscasts
for the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am,'' Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said, ``getting every bit as
many phone calls now \Rfrom national media\S about our team as I
was before we won our first Super Bowl in 1992, and that's fitting,
because then, and now, no one expected us to do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet with both clubs missing the playoffs last season, the hype
for this game won't match the hype of big games in the past. At
least that is the thinking of wide receiver Michael Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss those games that took up the whole week of coverage,
like the Green Bay and San Francisco games,'' Irvin said.
``Everybody looked forward to those games. I look forward to one
day having those matchups again.''
Dorsett miffed
</P>
<P>
   Tony Dorsett has said he is miffed that the club did not invite
him to Texas Stadium to watch Emmitt Smith break his career club
rushing record Sunday. Team owner Jerry Jones said yesterday that
if he had it to do again, he would have called Dorsett to join the
club on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Two things stopped Jones from making the call.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was not certain that Smith would get the 95 yards needed
to break the record. Smith had been limited to less than 91 yards
in each of the previous five games against the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   He also did not realize that Smith's accomplishment would
generate the publicity it did.
</P>
<P>
   Jones did not invite Roger Staubach and Drew Pearson to the
sidelines when Troy Aikman and Michael Irvin broke their records,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hadn't had a precedent for ceremonial-type approaches in
the past,'' Jones said. ``Had I known that Emmitt would have the
game he had, and that all of the positive things it would generate,
on hindsight, I would have invited Tony. And I didn't know that
Tony would not already be at the game because a lot of our former
players are already there.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was not meant as a slight in our recognition of what Tony
Dorsett has meant to this franchise,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Dorsett was unavailable to comment.
Inside the locker room
</P>
<P>
   When the Cowboys play in Arizona, much of the sellout crowd is
usually pro-Dallas. But because the Cardinals are in playoff
contention, Cowboys coach Chan Gailey expects the crowd to be
cheering mostly for the home team. ``In years past, we probably
would not practice with \Rcanned\S crowd noise,'' Gailey said.
``But we will this week.'' ... Deion Sanders, Michael Irvin, Fox
commentator Pat Summerall, former Notre Dame football coach Lou
Holtz and former Texas Gov. Ann Richards are expected to be in
attendance at 6:30 p.m. tomorrow to roast Jerry Jones at the 11th
annual Celebrity Roast and Auction benefiting St. Philip's School
and Community Center. The event will be at Dallas International
Apparel Mart. For information, call (214) 421-5221.
YARD MARKERS: How far do the Cowboys have to go? First-and-10
</P>
<P>
   Tony Dorsett and Emmitt Smith are not the only past and present
Cowboys who rank among the NFL's career league leaders. Troy
Aikman, Roger Staubach and Danny White rank among the top 20 in
passer ratings. Everson Walls and Mel Renfro rank among the top 20
interceptors. Dorsett, Smith and Herschel Walker rank among the top
20 in combined yards gained.
What's the call
</P>
<P>
   Giants coach Jim Fassel tried a pass near the goal line last
week that resulted in a sack. Chan Gailey tried a pass near the
goal line that resulted in a touchdown. Fassel made a dumb call
because it didn't work. Gailey made a smart call because it did
work. See, the science of detailing what makes a good coach isn't
so hard, is it?
Play action
</P>
<P>
   Most practice-squad players make minimal money and spend the
week working on the scout team, emulating the opponent's best
players. Speedy Zebbie Lethridge has played Denver's Rod Smith,
Oakland's James Jett and Carolina's Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail. But
Lethridge would play Arizona's Scott Player if he had to: ``Hey, if
they want me to hold for field goals, I'd do it and be happy doing
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
