<HEADER>
A4552 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PACKARD-POPULATION-SF     11-11 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACKARD-POPULATION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACKARD FOUNDATION GIVES $375 MILLION FOR POPULATION CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL MCCABE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With the world's population expected to top 6
billion sometime next year, the Packard Foundation will announce
details this week of its plan to dispense $375 million over the
next five years for programs intended to slow population growth.
</P>
<P>
   The grants by the David and Lucile Packard Foundation of Los
Altos, Calif., are believed to be the largest donations ever made
by a private donor for population programs.
</P>
<P>
   The grants, totaling $75 million a year starting next year, will
go mostly to nonprofit organizations around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Cole Wilbur, the foundation's executive director, declined
Tuesday to discuss how the money will be allocated. He said details
will be provided during a news conference Wednesday at the
Commonwealth Club in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be aimed mainly at developing countries, but we also
will continue funding programs in this country as well,'' Wilbur
said. ``If you were born in 1960, the world's population was about
3 billion. Every 12 to 15 years, the world gains another billion
people, and the fact that it will surpass 6 billion next year gives
you an idea of the enormity of the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The population grants are a small piece of the $8.6 billion the
Packard Foundation is gradually giving away.
</P>
<P>
   Created in 1964 by David Packard, co-founder of Hewlett Packard
Co., and his wife, Lucile, the private family organization divides
its grants among nonprofit organizations in eight categories,
including science, children, population, conservation, arts and
community. The grants for 1999 will total $400 million, double the
1997 level.
</P>
<P>
   Experts on population growth said the grants are particularly
timely in view of decreasing government spending to slow growth of
the world's population.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has cut its spending by 70 percent over
the past decade, said Peter Kostmayer, executive director of Zero
Population Growth in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's primarily politics, and the growing strength of the
religious right in Congress,'' said Kostmayer, whose organization
trains teachers around the world to teach children about the
population explosion's effect on the environment. ``Family-planning
programs reduce abortions because they don't get pregnant, but this
is lost on the religious right.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 80 percent of the world's population earn under $1,100 a
year, Kostmayer said, and that population is expected to double
within the next 39 years.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Ehrlich of Stanford University said Tuesday that he was
delighted to hear about the grants, although he still is awaiting
details.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exactly the time when something like this is needed,''
said Ehrlich, Bing Professor of Population Studies as well as a
professor of biological sciences at Stanford. ``Since I got into
this game 40 years ago, we have learned more than enough how to do
humane and healthy things to get birthrates down around the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlich's 1968 book, ``The Population Bomb,'' has been called a
``wake-up call'' for an entire generation and played a significant
role in popularizing smaller families in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlich said the disaster and human suffering in Central America
brought on by Hurricane Mitch ``has a huge population component to
it _ people are forced to live in marginal areas far more
susceptible to natural disasters.''
</P>
<P>
   When David Packard died in 1996, most of his money went to the
foundation. Since then, grants have soared, and the foundation is
now the third largest in the country.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, groups working to slow population growth received $14.8
million in Packard grants. By this September 15, the foundation had
given $35.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the funds have gone to a variety of organizations,
from a group that markets and distributes manual vacuum aspiration
equipment for abortions, to documentary filmmakers preparing a
feature on a health organization in Bangladesh, Wilbur said.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the Packard Foundation revealed a five-year, $175
million program focused on land conservation in California,
particularly in the Central Valley, the Central Coast and the
Sierra Nevada. To date, working with groups such as the Nature
Conservancy and Trust for Public Land, the program has helped
protect more than 135,000 acres.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 0340EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 03:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4554 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONDURAS-REBUILDING-S     11-11 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONDURAS-REBUILDING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR HONDURAS' HOMELESS, GOVERNMENT HAS NO READY SOLUTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT COLLIER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras _ To Gloria Reyes, the tiny shack on a
steep hillside overlooking downtown Tegucigalpa was home. To
government planners, eager to turn disaster into a
once-in-a-lifetime chance to redesign Honduras' capital, it was a
public menace.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Either way, the house where Gloria and Hector Reyes and 10
members of their extended family lived no longer exists. It was
smashed and buried by a mudslide during Hurricane Mitch a week and
a half ago.
</P>
<P>
   The family members huddle today in a corner of a tent in an
emergency shelter. For the moment, they are surviving on rations
provided by the government and foreign aid groups.
</P>
<P>
   But where they and the nearly 2 million other Hondurans,
Nicaraguans, Salvadorans and Guatemalans made homeless by the
hurricane will go next is unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Mitch's devastation dramatized what nearly every visitor flying
into Central America notices: Huge numbers of the urban poor live
in shantytowns perched on steep hillsides and narrow riverbanks
where Mother Nature never intended humans to live.
</P>
<P>
   In rural areas, the situation is similar: The poor are squeezed
onto marginal areas that are subject to periodic flooding,
landslides, droughts and other natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of the people killed and displaced by the hurricane
lived in areas that would be considered uninhabitable in the United
States and other wealthy nations.
</P>
<P>
   With the status quo finally demonstrated as untenable, the
question is: What next?
</P>
<P>
   ``After Hurricane Fifi (which killed 6,000 people in 1974), we
came up with an excellent plan for the nation's cities,'' said
Mario Martin, a top Tegucigalpa urban planning official who was
educated at Yale University and the University of California at
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the plan _ which advocated creating green spaces
and settling the urban poor in safer areas on the outskirts of
urban areas _ was stymied by official corruption and the
unwillingness of powerful real estate interests to sacrifice for
the greater good.
</P>
<P>
   ``And after Hurricane Gilbert (in 1988) caused mudslides and
made many people homeless, we had another opportunity,'' Martin
added. ``Other floods and disasters have done the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've never been able to take the destiny of our nation in
our own hands. Poverty, apathy and vested interests keep taking it
away from us.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the region's population explosion and the increasing
gap in incomes between rich and poor, workable solutions are few
indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Honduras is a mountainous nation, and nearly all flatland that
would be suitable for new towns and neighborhoods is already used
for farming. If much of this land is converted to urban uses, the
nation's inability to feed itself will be exacerbated. Like many
other Latin American countries, Honduras imports much of its food.
</P>
<P>
   Martin and other Honduran government officials have proposed a
new master plan for the nation, with Tegucigalpa as the test case.
The neighborhoods where the city's 20,000 newly homeless lived
would be declared parkland, and new industrial suburbs would be
created outside the city to house them.
</P>
<P>
   Other aspects of the plan include:
</P>
<P>
   -- Staggered work hours, with the start of the workday ranging
from 7 a.m. to 10 a.m., to reduce rush-hour traffic jams across the
few bridges that remain after Mitch's catastrophic floods.
</P>
<P>
   -- The creation of downtown pedestrian malls _ ``just like San
Diego and other U.S. cities,'' said Martin _ to reduce traffic.
</P>
<P>
   -- Emergency repair of main city bridges while relocating other
destroyed bridges to better locations.
</P>
<P>
   -- A nationwide property-title census, to sort out the tangled
web of conflicting property claims that prevents huge numbers of
city residents from getting bank loans, obtaining city services and
leaving the black-market underground economy.
</P>
<P>
   Martin and his colleagues presented their proposal Tuesday to
Tegucigalpa's mayor and city council. A decision on whether to
adopt it as a blueprint for change is expected within a week.
</P>
<P>
   Where the money will come from, however, is unclear, because
Mitch has delivered a staggering blow to Honduras' economy.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Minister Gabriela Nunez has no illusions about the
challenge ahead: ``We will have to make a number of difficult
social and political decisions in the coming months about how to
rebuild our country.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the type of decisions we can make, and whether they are
successful, will depend on the level of external support _ both in
aid and in forgiving our (foreign) debt.''
</P>
<P>
   Nunez said that in addition to large amounts of disaster relief
aid, Honduras and its neighbors will need long-term program support
costing billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   As in previous years when natural disasters struck, the huge
price tag of a safer future may prove to be prohibitive in
comparison to maintaining the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   In Tegucigalpa and most other Latin America cities, urban
shantytowns have been built through a complex, decades-long process
of demographic push and pull.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes' neighborhood, Colonia Soto, was founded about 20 years
ago by migrants from the countryside. They banded together,
squatted on unoccupied land and fought long political battles with
the city government.
</P>
<P>
   From the 1960s to the 1980s, when Honduras was viewed as a
bulwark against the spread of Marxism, U.S. and other foreign aid
agencies gave money to Colonia Soto and other poor neighborhoods to
build infrastructure and houses.
</P>
<P>
   Martin and his colleagues say the recent disaster proves that
the old model was a mere political stopgap.
</P>
<P>
   Such neighborhoods, although they possessed electricity and
water, were flimsily constructed _ and no match for Mitch. In
Tegucigalpa alone, 180 people were killed by the hurricane, 860
disappeared and 3,342 houses were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Similar devastation occurred across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   While Honduran and foreign officials wrestle with the dilemma of
how to improve urban development without destroying crucial
farmland, everyday citizens can see no further than tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   In El Porvenir, a squatter neighborhood next to Colonia Soto
that was spared its neighbor's muddy fate, residents say that they
fear the grand dreams of city officials like Mario Martin more than
they do Mother Nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place is unsafe and it fills me with fear, but it's all
we have,'' said Maria Ines Molina, leader of the neighborhood
patronato, or association. ``Where are we going to go?''
</P>
<P>
   Molina's home, perched on a 30-degree hillside, was shaken but
not stirred by the landslides during the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want us to move, that's fine,'' she said. ``But
they'll have to buy us a new place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We paid through the nose for our lot. We fought for it for
many years. And if anyone wants to take it away from us this time,
we'll fight again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 0346EST &QL; 
