<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4724 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOHLS-COLUMN12-COX     11-11 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOHLS-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Where have you gone Refrigerator Perry?
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ ``Me and a buddy were talking the other day, and
he bet me that in 10 years, there will be a whole bunch of
400-pounders in the NFL,'' Jay Humphrey said. ``I disagreed, but if
you look at (the University of Wisconsin's) Aaron Gibson and (the
University of Texas') Leonard Davis, it's going to be scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially scary if you're a 170-pound cornerback who is
politely asked to get in their way from time to time. That guy
should be a lot more concerned about this widening trend than the
310-pound Texas offensive tackle, who doesn't miss a trip to the
dining room any more than he does the weight room.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, Humphrey didn't bet his dad's hunting preserve
outside Denison with his friend. The NFL currently boasts 362
linemen who weigh at least 300 pounds. Only 27 such behemoths
suited up in 1987. A report in The Quincy Patriot-Ledger attributed
the increase in widebodies to a loosening of pass-blocking rules
allowing linemen to extend their hands and a corresponding move to
more zone blocking, as opposed to outside plays, where more agile
linemen pull and lead student-body sweeps.
</P>
<P>
   Teams have been copying Washington's Hogs since Super Bowl XVII,
but last year's champs, the Denver Broncos, offered rebuttal with
the smallest line in the league.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't noticed _ and those solar eclipses are a good
sign _ the pattern of supersized football players has filtered down
to the college level. In the Big 12 alone, team rosters include 118
players who weigh at least 300 pounds, 15 of them true freshmen.
That doesn't include 51 aspiring hefties who are 290 or heavier,
just a double-cheeseburger away from that austere list. That trend
will never be more obvious than this week, when you watch Texas try
not to get squashed by Texas Tech's mammoth offensive line, which
just happens to be the heaviest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Thank God for wide-angle lenses. These two teams have 27
300-pounders between them, including Texas' 350-pound Davis. But
don't start a food drive for Texas A&AMP;M. The Aggies think Slim Fast
is the star of a Cambodian Western flick. They weigh 299 pounds a
man in the line, and their backups weigh a svelte 298 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Hampton, the Longhorns' 6-foot, 300-pound defensive
tackle, could get a stiff neck from gawking up at a Red Raiders
group that averages 6 feet 4 inches and 323 pounds, 13 pounds more
than the Texas offensive line. Jonathan ``The House'' Gray has done
his part to keep that norm up, thanks to the Monday all-you-can-eat
buffets the Tech tackle frequents. He's a healthy 6-5, 357, give or
take second helpings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pounding on those little defensive tackles _ I say little,
some are about 300 pounds _ sets the stage,'' Gray says. ``It's
like pushing a car up a hill. They can do it one-quarter of the way
up the hill, but then it wears you out.''
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that Gray is not the biggest player in college
football. Hardly. That double-meat, double-cheese honor goes to
Wisconsin's Gibson, who at 6-7, 380, is big enough to consider
applying for statehood. Tom Humphrey _ Jay's father _ isn't all
that impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see a whole lot of football player there,'' he said,
figuratively speaking. ``Real fast defensive ends are going to wear
him out.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows a little about football. The elder Humphrey played six
years of pro football as a left tackle and, including three seasons
in the Canadian Football League when he was ``a rangy 252 pounds,''
never weighed more than 265. In fact, that's all he was allowed to
weigh. He even had to work at staying under that weight or risk
being fined $25 per pound for exceeding that mandatory limit. Once,
he spent most of a day in a sauna, melting off nine excess pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Humphrey was a naturally strong athlete playing at
Comanche, Texas, where he was agile enough to play two years for
Abilene Christian on a basketball scholarship before switching to
football for his final two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might have been in the Hall of Fame if I had lifted
weights,'' he said. ``Back then, you heard all (negative rumors)
about that muscle-bound stuff. You could have put the whole Denver
Broncos weight room in my bedroom. And (Lyle) Alzado was the only
one who ever used it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Alzado had other assistance _ he admitted to steroid
use before his tragic, premature death. Humphrey said he believes
the amount of steroid usage is vastly overestimated, adding on a
personal note that ``Jay would rather step in front of a truck than
take drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Humphrey, like other Longhorns, dabbled with the creatine
protein supplement that can be bought over the counter, and Texas
strength coach Jeff Madden has no problem with encouraging its use
so long as dehydration is carefully avoided. Gray says creatine
just added water weight on him and his teammates and that
linebackers are more prone to use the substance.
</P>
<P>
   Of greater health risk is the amount of overload stress on a
player's joints in his knees and ankles. That risk graduates for
the oversized athlete after his career ends, but UT Coach Mack
Brown said the key is continued exercise to lose weight at that
point. He points to former Detroit Lion lineman and Longhorn great
Doug English. ``Doug's skinny now,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, football players work out year-round, while Tom Humphrey
used to prepare for each season about six weeks out. Jay can
bench-press 430 pounds, probably 130 more than his dad ever thought
about putting on a bar. ``They're like Olympic athletes now,'' he
said. Gray said three Red Raiders can bench 400 pounds or more.
</P>
<P>
   These big linemen practice specialized weightlifting techniques
year-round, observe high-protein and low-carbohydrate diets and
follow strict nutritional guidelines. When Mack Brown was a running
back at Florida State, he and his teammates were given salt tablets
before games to avoid cramping. Then, the coaches dispensed Hershey
candy bars at halftime for a quick energy boost.
</P>
<P>
   Under Madden's guidance, no aspect of the Longhorns' diet is
overlooked. For instance, caffeine is off-limits, so no coffee, no
soft drinks, no Hershey bars all season long. Juice and water are
the way to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anything wrong with being big,'' Hampton
says. ``The student-athlete, period, is getting bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   He has a point. Ryan Leaf, the San Diego Chargers' rookie
quarterback, weighed 261 at a workout last spring. Two Longhorn
freshmen, Mike Williams and Antwan Kirk-Hughes, average 330 pounds.
The sky apparently is the limit, assuming you'll still be able to
see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad weighed 265 in the NFL, and I'm around 310 now,'' Jay
says. ``You can probably add another 50 pounds for my kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Bohls writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 1015EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4725 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EZZARD-COLUMN12-COX     11-11 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Steering voters not church's role
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Democratic candidates such as Georgia Gov.-elect Roy
Barnes showed up at black churches the Sunday before the election,
and Christian Coalition members distributed voter guides that
allocate points to mostly Republican candidates on a narrow set of
moral issues. The Christian Right is sometimes slammed for using
houses of worship for partisan campaigning, while little is said
about traditional Democratic treks to black churches, especially in
the South.
</P>
<P>
   African-American voter turnout in Georgia in this election was
nearly double the turnout four years ago, and it was key to
statewide Democratic victories. The successful get-out-the vote
effort in black communities can largely be attributed to the
church. But, is there a difference between the Christian
Coalition's political approach and that of black churches, newly
energized by the issues of this election?
</P>
<P>
   The answer isn't as simple as chastising either or both for
seeming partisanship. Religious leaders say churches have a
legitimate role in defining moral issues _ from views on abortion
to non-discrimination policies. But it's wrong for church leaders
to pick candidates for their congregations or for church folks to
work to suppress voter turnout.
</P>
<P>
   For guidance on the distinctions in the conservative Christian
vs. black church approaches, I checked with three prominent
theologians: Steve Tipton, an Emory professor of Religion and
Culture ; Robert Franklin, president of the Interdenominational
Theologian Center, and Alton Pollard, director of Black Church
Studies at the Candler School of Theology.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin said he hoped the black church would take a more
``prophetic,'' less political role in the future and pointed to the
restraint exercised by the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. in resisting
partisan endorsements from the pulpit. ``King never made the
political moves of (the religious right's)Jerry Falwell,'' he
noted, ``but I admit I'm frankly disappointed in the some of the
political operations in black churches.'' Franklin said blacks
shouldn't be dependent on one political party or seek to
spiritualize elections. ``That's not noble, and I hope it's not a
precedent.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pollard was harsher in his assessment of Christian Coalition
differences in approach. A key distinction is that the black church
is still serving large numbers of folks ``struggling to survive, ``
he said. In the rural South, for example, blacks still have little
access to political power. Many feel they are ``on the precipice of
danger, `` (of more discrimination) when they see invidious
political ads tinged with racism.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lieutenant governor candidate Mitch Skandalakis'
notorious ads bashing Atlanta's ``black mayor,'' then associating
him with opponent Mark Taylor, supposedly had the blessing of
former Christian Coalition director Ralph Reed, a Skandalakis
campaign adviser In the final analysis, Pollard said, ``There's
only one real difference, but it's critical: Is a political
activity based on the demeaning of others? Because if it is, it's
anti-democratic in spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Tipton, too, acknowledged the legitimate role of all churches in
identifying moral issues. But people of faith, he believes, must
search for facts and context rather then give out directives for
the voting booth _ they must look to teaching by example.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the black church can't and shouldn't be separated
from the black community, U.S. Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.), best known
for his courage during the civil rights struggle, drew the clearest
distinction between the political activities of the Christian Right
and those of the black church: ``We don't tell folks to punish
people because of a particular piece of legislation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Ezzard is a columnist for The Atlanta
Journal-Consitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mezzard(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
