<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4726 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-GATECH-BURNS     11-11 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-BURNS </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Way to go, Joe
</P>
<P>
   Hurdling obstacles is Burns' specialty
</P>
<P>
   By Carroll Rogers
</P>
<P>
   STAFF WRITER
</P>
<P>
   As a 10-year-old in Little League baseball, with his team
trailing by one run and nobody except maybe his father in the
stands expecting it, Joe Burns took off from third base and stole
home.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't supposed to make it, but he did. His team won, and
soon, after all the other Little-Leaguers were trying it.
</P>
<P>
   Stealing away from home nine years later proved much harder for
Burns, although it was that same instinctive aggressiveness, his
drive to excel and perhaps to shock _ his athletic ability
magnified by his will _ that has Burns sliding safely into his new
home as Georgia Tech tailback.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the recruiting process, Burns was stamped as an
academic casualty. Poor grades and a low SAT score his junior year
made him a significant risk. When he committed to Tech a year ago,
before he had qualified, doubts didn't just circulate in Atlanta,
they were right there in his hometown of Thomasville.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people said `He ain't going nowhere,''' Burns said.
``I used that as a motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   Summer school, a Princeton Review course, two more stabs at the
SAT, a heavy academic load his senior year, and Burns is right
where he said he'd be: taking on calculus and college tacklers. And
after a slow start this season, Burns has emerged as a breakaway
threat in the Yellow Jackets' backfield, a runner capable of making
the big play.
</P>
<P>
   Burns scored his first touchdown against New Mexico State in the
second game and added a team-high 43 yards against Florida State.
He earned his first start of the season against Maryland on
Halloween and responded in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   He rushed for a career-high 179 yards, including a 44-yard
touchdown run, to become the first Jackets back this season to gain
100 yards in a game. The performance earned him ACC rookie of the
week honors and helped strengthen a backfield weakened by the loss
of senior Charles Wiley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought he was going to be something special,'' coach
George O'Leary said. ``I'm amazed how much he's picked up our
offense as a true freshman. Our offense isn't the easiest to pick
things up with. He does a good job of that and protection and
things most young players have trouble with.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns' success hasn't come without a price. Although he was a
high school standout at Thomas County Central, many of the same
folks who cheered him, and perhaps some who recruited him, didn't
expect Burns to make it in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``Central has a reputation of having great athletes who can play
in Division I, but grades hinder them from going,'' Joe Burns Sr.
said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Georgia Tech, Burns also was getting recruited by
Florida State, Florida, Central Florida and South Carolina, but his
father was skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them didn't really think he'd get his grades up,'' Joe
Burns Sr. said. ``I don't think they were really serious about
recruiting him, even Florida State.''
</P>
<P>
   It was OK with Burns, who said early in his senior year that he
was going to stay in state and play for Georgia Tech. He'd realized
only a year earlier that he wanted to go to college at all.
</P>
<P>
   Burns has been a running back since he was 5. In middle school,
the Burns family lived in Riverdale, just south of Atlanta, for a
few years, but Joe was sent back to Thomasville to live with his
grandparents and play sixth- and seventh-grade football.
</P>
<P>
   Yet never in all those years did Burns figure his football
career would go beyond high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought about going to college,'' Burns said. ``I
thought I'd graduate from high school and get a job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been telling him he needed to prepare himself,'' Joe
Burns Sr. said. ``It never dawned on him what I was saying. He was
satisfied playing in high school. He never thought (his ability)
could take him where he is now.''
</P>
<P>
   His father's words didn't get to Burns in middle school, but
those of Thomas County Central coach Ed Pilcher did.
</P>
<P>
   ``He became like a father to me,'' Burns said. ``He kept me on
top of things. He pulled me in his office. We had deep talks. He's
one of the things that got me here. He helped me get my priorities
in order. I hadn't matured a lot. I had to stop doing some things I
was doing. I had to stop going places with my friends and
concentrate on my books.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit me I have a chance to play college football. That
motivated me.''
</P>
<P>
   team-high 43 yards
</P>
<P>
   (salinity)Please seeBURNS, D5
</P>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE B. TEAGLE / Staff
</P>
<P>
   On the ball: After gaining 179 rushing yards in his first start
for Georgia Tech, the view is definitely looking up for freshman
Joe Burns, the state's Class AAA Player of the Year in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   JOE BURNS FILE
</P>
<P>
   -- Birthdate: Sept. 15, 1979.
</P>
<P>
   -- Hometown: Thomasville.
</P>
<P>
   -- Position: Running back.
</P>
<P>
   -- Height, weight: 5 feet 10, 199 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   -- Accomplishments: Led Thomas County Central to two Class AAA
state titles; selected Georgia AAA Player of the Year in 1997 after
rushing for 1,941 yards and 24 touchdowns; finished his high school
career with 5,004 yards rushing and 50 touchdowns; rushed for 179
yards in his first start for Georgia Tech, a 31-14 victory over
Maryland, and earned ACC rookie of the week honors.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
