<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-CLEMSON </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   secrest
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lee (404) 799-1513
</P>
<P>
   Zachery gives positive charge
</P>
<P>
   Future bright at Clemson
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Lee
</P>
<P>
   STAFF WRITER
</P>
<P>
   The best part about being a member of the Clemson Tigers, says
Travis Zachery, is the 25-second pregame ritual of running down the
hill at Memorial Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The worst part of his two seasons in Death Valley has been the
downhill run of the Clemson football program; from the 7-5 team he
watched because of a broken ankle last season to the dreary 2-7
squad that he contributes to each week now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not used to having a season like this,'' said Zachery, a
redshirt freshman from Marietta. ``Little things keep us from
achieving our goals _ turnovers, missed assignments. I just try to
look at the positives.''
</P>
<P>
   There haven't been many. Clemson is headed to its worst finish
in more than 20 years, and his coach, Tommy West, could be removed
at season's end.
</P>
<P>
   But there have been some positives for Zachery. Like darting to
the field of 80,000 orange crazies for the first time and rushing
15 times for 73 yards in a 33-0 season-opening win against Furman.
He also had a 93-yard performance against Maryland, but his total
in nine games this year is just 488 yards and three touchdowns on
119 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   As the Tigers prepare for 22nd-ranked Georgia Tech on Thursday
night, the 6-foot-1, 191-pound tailback wants a prime performance
against his hometown team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be real pumped and ready to compete against my
fellow Georgians,'' said Zachery, who also returns punts and is
Clemson's all-purpose leader with 755 yards. ``I want to do better.
I want to do everything I can to make us win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think one person makes us win, but I take it a lot
upon myself to make big plays. That's the type of person I am.''
</P>
<P>
   At Marietta High, Zachery was a big-play machine who accumulated
7,528 all-purpose yards, including six kick returns for touchdowns.
Zachery rushed for 1,931 yards and 22 touchdowns his senior season.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I saw of him at Marietta, I knew he'd be the
featured back for us,'' West said. ``He's starting to give us that
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Zachery, ready to burst loose, has to be patient for a year. On
his second day of practice in 1997, and only his third day at
Clemson, Zachery ran an out pattern and felt a pop in his foot.
Zachery didn't know the seriousness of the injury until he saw the
X-ray, which showed a broken metatarsal bone.
</P>
<P>
   He promptly was redshirted, and the player who once said that he
and weights were ``like oil and water,'' spent most of his time in
the weight room, adding 20 pounds. With the Tigers' career rushing
leader, Raymond Priester, drafted in the fifth round of the NFL
draft by St. Louis, the job of first-team tailback was handed to
Zachery.
</P>
<P>
   Much of his support has come from his mother, Katie, who attends
every Clemson home game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to keep his spirits up,'' she said. ``He's not used to
playing on a losing team, but I don't think they'll be on the
losing end all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   And for himself, Zachery sees an upward turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sooner or later, I'm going to have a breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   Travis Zachery of Marietta is ``pumped and ready'' for Yellow
Jackets.
</P>
<P>
   DTuesday, Nov. 10, 1998 HHHHH The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
