<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4728 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS12-COX-     11-11 1529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS12-COX-TAKE1 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: John Glenn's space flight has rekindled my interest in the
space program. Where can I get information on future flights, so I
can go to Florida to watch a launch?
</P>
<P>
   A: For recorded information, call 407-867-4636. Current plans
call for the launch of an unmanned communications satelite between
6:47 p.m. and 7:17 p.m. Nov. 19, followed on Dec. 10 by the
unmanned Mars climate orbiter. The space shuttle Endeavour is
scheduled for launch at 4:45 a.m. Dec. 3. It will be the last
shuttle flight for 1998 and the first flight for construction of
the international space station. It will be followed May 13 by
Atlantis; June 17, Discovery; Aug. 5, Endeavour; and Sept. 16,
Atlantis. All launch dates and times are subject to change, so call
in advance before heading to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What happens to campaign money left over after an election,
or at the end of a politician's career, such as in the case of
resigning House Speaker Newt Gingrich?
</P>
<P>
   A: The only prohibition is that the money can't be converted to
private, personal use. ``They can't just keep the money and run,''
said Ian Stirton of the Federal Election Commission in Washington.
But other than that, politicians can do any number of things with
it, he added, such as contributing it without limit to a party
committee, setting up a political action committee, donating it to
charity, setting up chairs at a university, or even setting it
aside for future use if they choose to run again, such as for state
office.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has there been any more news about the sailing yacht Fantome,
reported missing off Honduras during Hurricane Mitch? Was it ever
found?
</P>
<P>
   A: Officials of Windjammer Barefoot Cruises Ltd. of Miami have
concluded that all 31 members of the crew went down with the
282-foot, four-masted schooner. The Coast Guard gave up its
weeklong search for the vessel on Nov. 5. The $15 million,
steel-hull Fantome, threatened by Hurricane Mitch while on a
one-week cruise, had let off passengers and ``nonessential'' crew
in Belize City before setting back to sea to look for safe haven.
The monster storm apparently followed the Fantome and sunk it with
115-mph winds and towering waves. A helicopter from the British
frigate Sheffield reported spotting eight life vests and two life
rafts with SV/Fantome stenciled on them near eastern Guanaja off
Honduras. But no other trace was found. The water in the area is
1,100 to 1,400 feet deep.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If the Bush brothers, George W. and Jeb, will be only the
second pair of brothers in U.S. history to be state governors at
the same time, who were the first?
</P>
<P>
   A: Nelson Rockefeller, governor of New York 1959-73; and
Winthrop Rockefeller, governor of Arkansas 1967-71.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did Q&AMP;A leave William Henry Harrison out of the list of
presidents assassinated while in office?
</P>
<P>
   A: Harrison was the first president to die in office, but he
wasn't assassinated. He rode coatless and hatless on a white horse
to the Capitol on March 4, 1841, to deliver his inaugural address,
getting soaked in a driving rainstorm. The cold rain continued
throughout his one-hour, 45-minute address, and after the ceremony
he led the inaugural parade to the White House. That evening, he
attended three inaugural balls. He caught cold at the ceremonies,
and was prostrated by a chill on March 27. He died of pneumonia on
April 4.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do the experts have any tips for preparing a car before
taking it for an emissions test?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are some things a motorist can do: have the engine
tuned (which should include a new air filter); change the oil and
oil filter; make sure the gas cap isn't clogged; and drive the car
for at least 15 minutes before the inspection test. The primary
reason that even well-maintained vehicles require longer test
times, or fail emission tests, is because they're not completely
warmed up at the time of testing. If the little needle on the
temperature gauge is in the middle position, it should be warm
enough. Just before your turn to be tested, rev the engine up a
little, about 2,500 rpm, for a minute. It will help the system
clear out and wake up from the idle time. (Some BMWs, Volvos and
Peugeots should not be revved up, however, because that can cause
transmission damage).
</P>
<P>
   Q: How is wind chill determined? What would it be outside an
airplane going 500 mph if the temperature is 50 degrees below zero
Fahrenheit?
</P>
<P>
   A: Wind chill factors are calculated using actual temperatures
in degrees (or negative degrees) Fahrenheit and wind velocity
measured in miles per hour. But there's no simple mathematical
formula. The National Weather Almanac's wind chill equivalent
temperature table shows 125 below zero as the most extreme, derived
from an actual temperature of 45 degrees below zero and a wind
velocity of 45 mph. As a practical matter, winds in excess of 40
mph produce little additional chilling effect. And it goes without
saying that wind chill is something that an airplane doesn't
experience, since it's a measurement of how the combined chilling
effect of low temperatures and wind feels to exposed flesh.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understant that melatonin is used by some older people to
aid in sleeping. But I heard that during his space flight, John
Glenn wouldn't be taking it. Why?
</P>
<P>
   A: Previously published reports said only that Glenn ``failed to
meet the criteria'' established by Dr. Charles Czeisler, the
principal researcher on the sleep experiments being conducted on
the Discovery mission. Glenn was disqualified from the portion of
the experiment that would have required him to take small doses of
melatonin, a hormone produced in the brain that some researchers
believe enhances sleep and could serve as a countermeasure for
weariness among astronauts. The use of melatonin constituted about
one-third of the Discovery sleep experiment. Czeisler said federal
medical privacy requirements and his institution's own medical
ethics prevented him from disclosing the reasons for Glenn's
disqualification.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My wife says she saw a UFO. She says it was gray, like
stainless steel, and at first was shaped like an isosceles
triangle. Then it moved very quickly to the north and changed shape
to a disc before vanishing. Is there some organization I can report
it to?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Federal Aviation Administration refers people who believe
they have spotted UFOs to the National UFO Reporting Center in
Seattle, 206-722-3000, said FAA spokeswoman Kathleen Bergen.
Recorded information at that number advises callers to leave
contact information and a brief description of the sighting so a
staff member can return the call. It also lists a Web site _
http://www.ufocenter.com _ for more information and on-line
reporting of sightings. Or you can write: National UFO Reporting
Center, P.O. Box 45623, University Station, Seattle, WA 98145. The
Mutual UFO Network is another possibility. You can call its
hotline, 1-800-836-2166, and you can get information at its Web
site _ http://www.mufon.org _ including a sighting questionnaire.
Or write: Mutual UFO Network Inc., 103 Oldtowne Road, Seguin, TX
78155-4099.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The latest space shuttle flight brought back memories of
Christa McAuliffe, who died in the Challenger explosion. What is
the status of her husband and children?
</P>
<P>
   A: Steve McAuliffe continues to adhere to the policy of not
speaking about his late wife that he set at the time of the
accident Jan. 28, 1986. McAuliffe has remarried, and in 1996 was
named a federal judge. He declines to talk to reporters about
Christa, and zealously guards the privacy of their children, Scott,
and Caroline. He even quashed a move to rename Concord High School
in Concord, N.H., after his wife, who taught there. Friends say he
keeps the Challenger explosion in quiet perspective. He just
doesn't talk in public about it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The launch of the Discovery mission, with John Glenn aboard
and millions watching, was delayed by an airplane that flew too
close to the launch area. What was the upshot of that?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Oct. 30 launch actually was threatened by five private
planes, not just one. ``It was an all-time high,'' said Federal
Aviation Agency spokeswoman Kathleen Bergen, who added that at
every previous shuttle launch, there has been at least one
intruder. Published reports said all five offending aircraft had
been identified by the FAA. The FAA restricts air space at the
shuttle launch site at NASA's request to maintain the integrity of
the airspace and to ensure the safety of the shuttle and the pilots
who might fly too close, Bergen said. In the latest instance,
Discovery's launch was delayed for less than 10 minutes while
patrolling security planes chased the five offenders from the
restricted airspace.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
