little, about 2,500 rpm, for a minute. It will help the system
clear out and wake up from the idle time. (Some BMWs, Volvos and
Peugeots should not be revved up, however, because that can cause
transmission damage).
</P>
<P>
   Q: How is wind chill determined? What would it be outside an
airplane going 500 mph if the temperature is 50 degrees below zero
Fahrenheit?
</P>
<P>
   A: Wind chill factors are calculated using actual temperatures
in degrees (or negative degrees) Fahrenheit and wind velocity
measured in miles per hour. But there's no simple mathematical
formula. The National Weather Almanac's wind chill equivalent
temperature table shows 125 below zero as the most extreme, derived
from an actual temperature of 45 degrees below zero and a wind
velocity of 45 mph. As a practical matter, winds in excess of 40
mph produce little additional chilling effect. And it goes without
saying that wind chill is something that an airplane doesn't
experience, since it's a measurement of how the combined chilling
effect of low temperatures and wind feels to exposed flesh.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understant that melatonin is used by some older people to
aid in sleeping. But I heard that during his space flight, John
Glenn wouldn't be taking it. Why?
</P>
<P>
   A: Previously published reports said only that Glenn ``failed to
meet the criteria'' established by Dr. Charles Czeisler, the
principal researcher on the sleep experiments being conducted on
the Discovery mission. Glenn was disqualified from the portion of
the experiment that would have required him to take small doses of
melatonin, a hormone produced in the brain that some researchers
believe enhances sleep and could serve as a countermeasure for
weariness among astronauts. The use of melatonin constituted about
one-third of the Discovery sleep experiment. Czeisler said federal
medical privacy requirements and his institution's own medical
ethics prevented him from disclosing the reasons for Glenn's
disqualification.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My wife says she saw a UFO. She says it was gray, like
stainless steel, and at first was shaped like an isosceles
triangle. Then it moved very quickly to the north and changed shape
to a disc before vanishing. Is there some organization I can report
it to?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Federal Aviation Administration refers people who believe
they have spotted UFOs to the National UFO Reporting Center in
Seattle, 206-722-3000, said FAA spokeswoman Kathleen Bergen.
Recorded information at that number advises callers to leave
contact information and a brief description of the sighting so a
staff member can return the call. It also lists a Web site _
http://www.ufocenter.com _ for more information and on-line
reporting of sightings. Or you can write: National UFO Reporting
Center, P.O. Box 45623, University Station, Seattle, WA 98145. The
Mutual UFO Network is another possibility. You can call its
hotline, 1-800-836-2166, and you can get information at its Web
site _ http://www.mufon.org _ including a sighting questionnaire.
Or write: Mutual UFO Network Inc., 103 Oldtowne Road, Seguin, TX
78155-4099.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The latest space shuttle flight brought back memories of
Christa McAuliffe, who died in the Challenger explosion. What is
the status of her husband and children?
</P>
<P>
   A: Steve McAuliffe continues to adhere to the policy of not
speaking about his late wife that he set at the time of the
accident Jan. 28, 1986. McAuliffe has remarried, and in 1996 was
named a federal judge. He declines to talk to reporters about
Christa, and zealously guards the privacy of their children, Scott,
and Caroline. He even quashed a move to rename Concord High School
in Concord, N.H., after his wife, who taught there. Friends say he
keeps the Challenger explosion in quiet perspective. He just
doesn't talk in public about it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The launch of the Discovery mission, with John Glenn aboard
and millions watching, was delayed by an airplane that flew too
close to the launch area. What was the upshot of that?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Oct. 30 launch actually was threatened by five private
planes, not just one. ``It was an all-time high,'' said Federal
Aviation Agency spokeswoman Kathleen Bergen, who added that at
every previous shuttle launch, there has been at least one
intruder. Published reports said all five offending aircraft had
been identified by the FAA. The FAA restricts air space at the
shuttle launch site at NASA's request to maintain the integrity of
the airspace and to ensure the safety of the shuttle and the pilots
who might fly too close, Bergen said. In the latest instance,
Discovery's launch was delayed for less than 10 minutes while
patrolling security planes chased the five offenders from the
restricted airspace.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
