<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4731 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS12-COX-     11-11 1393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS12-COX-TAKE2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: restricted airspace.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I watched the recent TV miniseries about the singing group
Temptations, and it made me wonder: Who are the people billed as
the Temptations who perform around the country now? What
relationship do they have, if any, to the original group?
</P>
<P>
   A: The original Temptations, in the early '60s, were Eddie
Kendricks, Paul Williams, Melvin Franklin, Eldridge Bryant and Otis
Williams. Over the years, the makeup of the act has been
ever-changing. Bryant left the group shortly after its first single
on the Motown label, ``Oh Mother of Mine,'' flopped. He was
replaced by David Ruffin, who himself was replaced by Dennis
Edwards when Ruffin decided to pursue a solo career in 1968. And so
on. Members who have died include Paul Williams (1973); Ruffin
(1991); Kendricks (1992); and Franklin (1995).
</P>
<P>
   As of this past summer, it was composed of Otis Williams (the
only original), Terry Weeks, Ron Tyson, Theo Peoples and Harry
McGilberry.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Hurricane Mitch left Central America devastated. How can we
send help to the people there?
</P>
<P>
   A: A number of relief operations are under way. These are among
them:
</P>
<P>
   CARE is concentrating its relief programs in the Atlantida and
Colon regions of Honduras, as well as the capital, Tegucigalpa.
Information: 1-800-521-2273; and at http://www.care.org on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   AmeriCares is organizing relief efforts in Honduras, Guatemala
and Nicaragua. Monetary contributions for the purchase of disaster
supplies can be sent to AmeriCares, 161 Cherry St., New Canaan, CT
06840. Information: 1-800-486-4357.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Committee for UNICEF requests funds for essential drugs
and medicines, clean water and blankets. Send donations to: U.S.
Committee for UNICEF, 333 E. 38th St., New York, NY 10016.
Information: 1-800-367-5437 or http://www.unicefusa.org on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors Without Borders has programs in Nicaragua, Honduras and
Guatemala, and is monitoring the situation in Costa Rica, El
Salvador, Belize and Mexico. Donations to the Hurricane Mitch
Relief Effort can be made to: Doctors Without Borders, 6 E. 39th
St., 8th Floor, New York, NY 10016. Information: 1-888-392-0392.
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross also is supporting Central American
relief efforts. Checks or money orders can be sent to: American Red
Cross International Response Fund, P.O. Box 37243, Washington, DC
20013. For a credit card donation, call 1-800-435-7669 or
1-800-257-7575 (Spanish). Internet users can make an online credit
card donation at http://www.redcross.org and choosing International
Relief Fund as their option of giving.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I remember that back in the '80s, Roanoke, Va., had a female
symphony conductor who was up-and-coming and making a reputation
for herself. I forgot her name. Who was she, and what became of
her?
</P>
<P>
   A: She's Victoria Bond, the first woman to earn a doctoral
degree in conducting from The Juilliard School in New York, and
music director and conductor of the Roanoke Symphony Orchestra from
1986 to 1995. She also served as artistic director of Opera Roanoke
from 1989 to 1995. In her multifaceted career, Bond, a Los Angeles
native, has composed symphonic and operatic works, chamber music,
ballet scores and pieces designed for young audiences. Her works
have been widely performed in the United States, Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   She currently is music adviser to the Wuhan (China) Symphony,
but returns to the United States often. In September, Bond
conducted the Greenville, S.C., Symphony in the opening of the $36
million Bi-Lo Center; in October, she presided over the
season-opening performance of the Harrisburg, Pa., Opera. In
December, she'll return to China to conduct a Christmas program in
Wuhan, a city of 12 million people, which will include the premiere
of a commisioned work by her based on traditional Chinese songs. In
January, Bond will present her opera ``Travels'' in New York, and
in March she'll conduct Opera Carolina's production of ``Madame
Butterfly'' in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How many U.S. presidents have been assassinated while in
office?
</P>
<P>
   A: Four: Abraham Lincoln, James Garfield, William McKinley and
John Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How long after liftoff does an astronaut start feeling the
weightlessness?
</P>
<P>
   A: It depends on the mission, because it's a combination of the
time it takes for both the solid rocket booster and the main engine
to fire, and that can vary. In the case of the current Discovery
mission, it was about 8 1/2 minutes, said John Petty of the Johnson
Space Center in Houston. The solid rocket booster burned for about
2 minutes; the main engine continued for another 6 1/2 minutes.
``When the main engine stops, that's basically when zero G, or
weightlessness, begins,'' Petty said. ``Just at the point the
external tank is jettisoned.'' The zero-gravity state lasts until
the astronauts turn the orbiter backward and ignite the orbital
maneuvering system engine to slow down and come out of orbit, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where do astronauts sleep when they're in space? Are they in
a hammock or bed of some type?
</P>
<P>
   A: On the current space shuttle Discovery mission, John Glenn
and the other astronauts sleep in small, rectangular containers,
said John Petty at the Johnson Space Center in Houston. He likened
them to the compartments common at railroad stations and in
minimalist hotels in Japan, with little more than a small bed
enclosed in a space which has room enough only for one person. In
other missions, astronauts use sleeping bags that can be attached
to the walls, Petty said. The astronauts can't simply float around,
because they would bump into things and wake up.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported that Bill Clinton was the first president
since Richard Nixon to watch a launch from Cape Canaveral. I seem
to remember pictures of Ronald Reagan at the Challenger launch when
it blew up. Is my memory faulty?
</P>
<P>
   A: Reagan was at the White House on Jan. 28, 1986, working on
the State of the Union address he was planning to deliver to the
nation that evening. When the Challenger exploded at 11:39 that
morning, just 74 seconds after liftoff, killing all seven crew
members, Reagan decided to postpone his State of the Union message.
He then made a nationally broadcast statement from the Oval Office,
saying, in part: ``Today is a day for mourning and remembering.
Nancy and I are pained to the core by the tragedy of the shuttle
Challenger. We know we share this pain with all of the people of
our country. This is truly a national loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that Democratic Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee of Texas
attended the Discovery launch. Wasn't she the congresswoman who
once was in the news for asking if the cameras used in the Mars
probe could pick out the U.S. flag left there by American
astronauts?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. The planetary gaffe occurred in September 1997 when Lee,
a member of the House Aeronautics and Space Committee whose Houston
district neighbors the Johnson Space Center, was talking to an
official at the Mars Pathfinder Mission Control Center in Pasadena,
Calif. She asked if the Pathfinder mission succeeded in taking
pictures of the American flag planted by astronaut Neil Armstrong
in 1969, which of course was on the moon, not Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow committee member Rep. Vern Ehlers (R-Mich.) didn't
consider the question out of the ordinary. ``If you ask the
American people how long it takes Earth to orbit the sun, 50
percent can't tell you,'' he said. ``We just don't teach enough
science.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: When I was stationed in the Rio Grand Valley in World War II,
we were told that the King Ranch in South Texas was one of the
biggest in the country. I've always wondered: Exactly how big is
it?
</P>
<P>
   A: The ranch certainly is kingdom-size: 825,000 acres (or more
than 1,300 square miles), making it larger than Rhode Island. It
was established in the mid-1850s by Richard King, a riverboat
captain. It's home to more than 60,000 head of cattle and more than
1,000 horses. In comparison, Ted Turner's Vermejo ranch in New
Mexico covers 578,000 acres. For another comparison, the Great
Smoky Mountains National Park covers 520,269 acres.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
