<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4733 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EIGHTIES-NOSTALGIA12-     11-11 0324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EIGHTIES-NOSTALGIA12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The '80s: Are you in tune with era?
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Lee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a big country, dreams stay with you.
</P>
<P>
   So do song lyrics, especially when there is always something
there to remind you.
</P>
<P>
   And with the '80s, there is. From the soundtracks of ``The
Wedding Singer'' and ``Romy and Michele's High School Reunion'' to
radio revival shows and pop culture shrines on the Internet, the
Reagan years have got the beat. Loverboy and Rick Springfield are
on tour, and Culture Club and the Human League sold out their
Atlanta concert this summer.
</P>
<P>
   In my mind and in my car, we can't rewind we've gone too far.
</P>
<P>
   Well, actually we haven't. Quizzes on '80s lyrics and copies of
the essay ``I Am a Child of the Eighties'' have become staples of
Gen-X e-mail and newsgroups, so there's plenty of opportunity to
rewind.
</P>
<P>
   The latest entry in the nostalgia fest is ``Who Can It Be Now?''
(Fireside, $9.95), a collection of trivia and 500 one-liner song
lyrics. Authors Peter T. Fornatale and Frank R. Scatoni, editors at
Simon &AMP; Schuster, put the book together after getting hooked on a
bar guessing game on '80s song lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are tired of listening to ABBA, so the '80s is the next
logical step,'' says Scatoni, 27, an MTV disciple whose first album
purchase was by the video-powered Men at Work.
</P>
<P>
   A little looking back goes a long way, though, even if mining
hundreds of songs for lyrics did rekindle Fornatale's respect for
Hall &AMP; Oates. After all, he and Scatoni had to listen to a lot of
Air Supply and Bonnie Tyler, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of fun reliving it,'' says Scatoni. ``But at the
end of writing the book, after listening to the songs over and over
again, we had had enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Lee writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 1018EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
