</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that Democratic Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee of Texas
attended the Discovery launch. Wasn't she the congresswoman who
once was in the news for asking if the cameras used in the Mars
probe could pick out the U.S. flag left there by American
astronauts?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. The planetary gaffe occurred in September 1997 when Lee,
a member of the House Aeronautics and Space Committee whose Houston
district neighbors the Johnson Space Center, was talking to an
official at the Mars Pathfinder Mission Control Center in Pasadena,
Calif. She asked if the Pathfinder mission succeeded in taking
pictures of the American flag planted by astronaut Neil Armstrong
in 1969, which of course was on the moon, not Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow committee member Rep. Vern Ehlers (R-Mich.) didn't
consider the question out of the ordinary. ``If you ask the
American people how long it takes Earth to orbit the sun, 50
percent can't tell you,'' he said. ``We just don't teach enough
science.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: When I was stationed in the Rio Grand Valley in World War II,
we were told that the King Ranch in South Texas was one of the
biggest in the country. I've always wondered: Exactly how big is
it?
</P>
<P>
   A: The ranch certainly is kingdom-size: 825,000 acres (or more
than 1,300 square miles), making it larger than Rhode Island. It
was established in the mid-1850s by Richard King, a riverboat
captain. It's home to more than 60,000 head of cattle and more than
1,000 horses. In comparison, Ted Turner's Vermejo ranch in New
Mexico covers 578,000 acres. For another comparison, the Great
Smoky Mountains National Park covers 520,269 acres.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
