</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4739 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-HUNTINGSEASON12-C     11-11 2175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-HUNTINGSEASON12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The culture of hunting: Texas deer season begins
 &HT;    (EDS: With photos.)
 &HT;    By Mike Leggett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPICEWOOD, Texas _ Griff Andrews is building the mother of all
campfires _ a hair-singeing, boot-melting eternal flame _ to ward
off the nasty wet chill that has settled on Red Bluff Ranch. It's
working, too, because anyone within 15 feet can feel the blast of
heat.
</P>
<P>
   Around the rest of the compound, the business of deer camp
begins. Jim Houser stands watch over a barbecue pit. Lynn Segall,
whose family owns the ranch, greets visitors. John Bloomquist, the
quiet one, disappears again after saying hello.
</P>
<P>
   The four hunters have been a single unit for 30 years or so, at
least since high school, and have been hunting from this spot for
the past 14 seasons. The group works as one in the fading light of
last Friday afternoon, getting everything ready for the next
morning, the opening day of deer season. They have spent weekends
leading up to this day, cutting brush, clearing camp and stacking
wood. The anticipation is thick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already drawn for stands,'' Andrews says. ``We've been
doing this for years. If you're No. 1 this year, you get to pick
first. Then your name moves down the list.'' Houser will get
hunting stand No. 1, the prize spot on the 500-plus acres.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a deer like old Big Boy will come along again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody ever killed him, but we saw him several times over
three years. Big Boy, he was something,'' Segall says. Everybody
stares reverently into the fire. The scene is repeated around
countless fires all over Texas on this night.
</P>
<P>
   The participants in this annual ritual spread across the state
this past weekend, from the midsize ranches like Red Bluff to
million-dollar deer-hunting temples along the Rio Grande border.
Deer hunting in Texas is big sport and big business. While some may
balk at the outcome, there is no arguing with the popularity of
this annual even-- that begins the first Saturday in Novem-- er and
continues into January.
</P>
<P>
   With this weekend's kickoff of the season, an estimated 600,000
hunters will kill somewhere between 400,000 and 500,000 deer. Those
numbers do not dent Texas' healthy deer population, estimated at
about 4 million.
</P>
<P>
   The hunters will spend nearly $1 billion on shells and beer, gas
and food. The ranch owners spend millions more to feed, fence and
manage their herds.
</P>
<P>
   Deer camps and deer hunting are the new business of ranching in
Texas, actually replacing livestock on hundreds of ranches that
once were reserved for cattle or sheep and goats.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are almost zero ranch sales for livestock anymore,''
said Darwin Avant, co-founder and operator of the private Los
Cazadores deer-hunting contest in Cotulla, former La Salle County
sheriff and now a ranch and lease broker in South Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the ranches up to 5,000 to 7,000 and even up to 10,000
acres are strictly for deer hunting. A few very large places are
sold for livestock and hunting,'' Avant said. ``Deer hunting has
added $100 to $200 per acre to the price of land, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Ranches in South Texas have sold for prices once reserved for
prime waterfront property along Hill Country streams, and Avant
credits the emergence of the white-tailed deer.
</P>
<P>
   Times change; deer stay
</P>
<P>
   Old Big Boy aside, trophy bucks are hard to come by on Red Bluff
Ranch, where the emphasis is as much on fun and friendship as it is
on huge antler racks. Tradition and ritual are passed on to the
next generation. The hunter who fails to obey them hears about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned real quick what to do,'' Andrews says over barbecue
and beer at the pre-opening dinner. ``Like you never go (relieve
yourself) inside the fence.'' He points at the ragged barbed-wire
fence that circles the small camping area. ``I stumbled out here in
the middle of the night one time and thought nobody would know if I
just went to the fence. . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Segall picks up the story: ``People were yelling at him from the
trailer, `Outside the fence.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned my lesson,'' Andrews says.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the camps are meant to be, places where lessons are
learned and traditions are shared among family and friends. That's
why B. Segall, Lynn's 79-year-old father and the camp patriarch,
started bringing the group when they were youngsters and why he
still comes _ just for the campfire life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We moved to Austin in the early 1950s,'' B. Segall says, as he
stands next to the campfire. ``I started Lynn hunting and then the
others came with us. I don't hunt anymore, but I still do my share
of work up here.''
</P>
<P>
   B. Segall started an engineering and consulting firm in Austin,
when the city was still just a town. He says he designed the
electrical and mechanical parts of the first air-conditioned
building in Mexico City and some of the first ones in Travis
County.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Spicewood was rural to the core, not a burgeoning
community between Austin and Marble Falls. ``I've seen this country
change,'' the elder Segall says. ``Some of the creeks have stopped
running as people have drilled wells and the cedar has spread. But
the deer have always been here.''
</P>
<P>
   Annual parade of hunters
</P>
<P>
   The deer have always been in the Hill Country, maybe nowhere
more than in Llano County, the designated Deer Hunting Capital of
Texas, which is to say the world. Even before deer hunting was big
business, the business of deer hunting was big in the tiny little
town on the banks of the Llano River.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first weekend of deer season is a major weekend for
sure,'' said Mary Rhodes, executive director of the Llano Chamber
of Commerce. ``Forty-six percent of all the contacts at the chamber
are related to wildlife recreation. We have people from Florida,
California, North and South Carolina, Missouri, you name it.''
</P>
<P>
   For Llano, famous barbecue is the foundation and deer hunting is
the superstructure of the area economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it weren't for deer season, we wouldn't be in business,''
said Bryan Miiller, owner of Miiller's Meats. ``We've been here for
13 years and deer hunters have kept us going. Half our annual
income comes during deer season.''
</P>
<P>
   Miiller said 10 percent of his business is done with hunters
from Florida, but he also has regular customers from Maryland, New
York, Pennsylvania, even England. ``One man has been coming here
for 37 years from Florida, and he brings 15, 20 people with him
every year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The same scene is played out throughout the Hill Country every
deer season, especially on the first weekend. By Wednesday of the
week leading up to opening day, streams of vehicles pulling
four-wheelers and deer stands are moving through every little town
west of Interstate 35.
</P>
<P>
   The hunters buy gas, food, deer corn, beer and soft drinks, as
well as book up the hotels and motels and fill up the restaurants.
Good times for the hunters, good times for the business people.
</P>
<P>
   Deer diary. . .
</P>
<P>
   Having wrapped themselves around a bunch of barbecued sausage,
backstrap and wild hog, and just a few beers, the crew at Red Bluff
Ranch is settling in around the fire to tell stories about hunts
gone by. Most of them are about shots that missed and jokes that
worked.
</P>
<P>
   The scene is less atavistic than anti-hunters would believe,
more Hemingwayesque and quiet _ people bonded by experience and
beliefs. Stories don't even have to be finished to be real. Just a
word or two, and everybody can live the event one more time.
</P>
<P>
   Houser pulls out the camp log book, a record going back to the
group's first year at Red Bluff Ranch, in 1984. Every deer killed
and its weight and age are recorded, along with personal notes
about good hunts and special bucks. Many of them have names.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's Big Boy, of course,'' Houser says. ``Stumpy.'' He only
had three good legs. ``White Head.'' Obviously. ``Limpy and Limpy
II.'' Don't ask. ``The Bobbsey Twins, Old Gray, Gotcha.''
</P>
<P>
   The list goes on, like the fire, but the night is winding down.
Time to crawl into bed for the short night and long wait for
opening morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to get to sleep before the snoring starts,''
Andrews says.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody is a little bit worried about the weather, which is
wet, cold and tending toward fog and mist. Not the best weather for
deer hunting, ``-- ut better than last year, when it was 90
degrees,'' Segall declares.
</P>
<P>
   One last question before bed: Which hunter is the most likely to
fire a shot at first light? All hands point to Andrews. ``That
would be me,'' he says. ``I've been pretty consistent killing a
deer on opening day.''
</P>
<P>
   There's none of this waiting for a giant to come along for
Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, if I see something I want to shoot, I shoot it,'' he
says. ``I like to get something on the ground and then look for a
bigger one.''
</P>
<P>
   Big bucks mean big bucks
</P>
<P>
   Hunters all over Texas are looking for a bigger one, it seems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 1996 National Survey of Fishing and Hunting and Wildlife
Associated Recreation showed that in-state expenditures for hunting
were $1.4 billion,'' said Jerry Cooke, director of upland and big
game ecology for Texas Parks and Wildlife. Deer hunting represents
about 65 percent of that.
</P>
<P>
   That $1.4 billion was direct spending for trips, food and
equipment and does not include the cost of ranches, high fences,
protein feed and hunting vehicles. Some deer hunts now sell for
more than $10,000, and the price of leasing land is creeping toward
a state standard of $10 per acre annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``White-tailed deer are the No. 1 game animal,'' Cooke said.
``The change has come about not so much in growth in demand as in a
more reliable supply. People are managing their land and their deer
herds, and that means better hunting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that anybody in my family has ever paid to hunt,
but we're all still closely tied to the land,'' he said. ``When a
substantial portion of the population lived on the land, the
thought of paying to hunt was unheard of. Now, most people live in
cities, and paying to hunt is the only way they can go.''
</P>
<P>
   Fire at will
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no money that changes hands here,'' Lynn Segall says
as he waits for the hunters' return on the first morning of the
season. ``We all just know there's work that has to be done and we
come up on the weekends all year to do it. We start working on next
season as soon as this season closes.''
</P>
<P>
   He glances up over the mountain that marks the edge of Red Bluff
Creek, for which the ranch is named. The top is shrouded in mist
and rain, pretty poor conditions for hunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard only one shot,'' Segall says. ``I think it was
Griff. He said he might kill a doe early.''
</P>
<P>
   As if on cue, Andrews' truck comes sliding up the wet caliche
road and circles camp to back in toward the hanging pole, where the
carcasses are displayed. Outside the fence. ``He's pulling around.
He's got one,'' Segall says.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews, stripped down to an orange University of Texas jersey
and a pair of olive-drab pants, pops out of the cab with a smile on
his face, which is painted with stripes of blood. ``I did it
myself,'' he says. ``It's one of the traditions here.''
</P>
<P>
   The doe he has killed turns out to be 3 years old and weighs 90
pounds, a very good weight for a doe in the Hill Country. He hasn't
hung the carcass yet when Houser makes it back to camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a good one and I was going to shoot it, too, but my
scope fogged up,'' he says. ``I tried wiping it off, but he saw me
and spooked. He never came back.''
</P>
<P>
   The whole camp moves to gather around Andrews' doe. The talk --
s of other deer that were seen but not shot. Of deer that never
showed up. Of the afternoon hunt.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, they have something new to talk about when
Bloomquist kills the largest buck in the 14-year history of the
camp. ``It was a big eight-pointer that weighed 140 pounds,''
Segall says. ``That's a big deer for this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrews keeps up a steady narrative, which everybody expects.
Bloomquist still hasn't said three words, but nobody expects him to
say anything. Houser keeps the log.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's part of this,'' Segall says. ``This opening weekend is
a ritual for us, and it would take a major emergency for any of us
to miss it. I've never had a better partnership than with these
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the men are starting to bring spouses and children with them
to share in the ritual _ the food, the talk and the hunting _ that
began when they were children themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life has gotten more complicated for all of us, but this is a
combination of values and tradition that are so easily lost
today,'' Segall says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad taught us to hunt and taught the value of ethics, and
we're feeling the same thing. We try to manage the game as much as
we can to to teach the kids the values of all this. It's almost
sacred to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Leggett writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
