u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEIGHTS12-COX     11-11 0405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEIGHTS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Byrd Goad powers to World Weightlifting bronze
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Robin Byrd Goad, who won three medals Tuesday in the
World Weightlifting Championships, says it's pure coincidence that
her daughter has the same name as the city hosting the first
Olympics with that sport for women.
</P>
<P>
   ``We chose her name the week before they announced we were going
to be in Sydney, Australia,'' said Byrd Goad, 28, who won three
bronze medals Tuesday in the 53 kg (116 pound) weight class at the
World Weightlifting Championships in Lahti, Finland. ``It wasn't
chosen for that, but maybe we instinctively knew.''
</P>
<P>
   Sydney is 2 1/2. Both of her parents, Byrd Goad and husband
Dean, have been training with the 2000 Games as their goal.
</P>
<P>
   In Finland, Byrd Goad lifted a total of 182.5 kg (401 1/2
pounds) for the overall bronze medal, including 82.5 kg (181 1/2
pounds) in snatch and 100 kg (220 pounds) in clean and jerk. She
finished behind China's Wang Xiufen and Bulgaria's Izabela Dragneva
in all three categories
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised because I didn't expect to be in medal
contention here,'' Byrd Goad said Tuesday. ``Women's weightlifting
. . . being an Olympic sport in 2000, is going to bring a lot more
attention and a lot more good athletes to the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1994 world champion, Byrd Goad has won 20 international
medals _ two golds, 12 silvers and six bronzes. For years, she
lobbied to get women's weightlifting into the Olympics and was
bitterly disappointed when the Atlanta Games didn't include it.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when Byrd Goad was four months pregnant and living near
Seattle, she received a pre-dawn call from her coach, John Coffee
with the good news about the Sydney Olympics. Even while taking
time off to have Sydney, Byrd Goad knew she wasn't finished with
weightlifting. And now, she says, ``I'd be crazy (to retire). It's
like being 16 and starting all over again. It's something I've
waited all these years for; training has a whole new meaning now.
Not to downplay anything I've accomplished before, but now
everything's new and fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   The Goads have turned their garage into a gym, and training is a
family affair; Dean Goad will lift in the American Open in
December.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Rosen writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
