<P>
   &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By GENE AND ADELE MALOTT &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   While the cost of flying continues to creep up, a few airlines
are trying to lure fliers ages 62 and older to their camps by
making changes to, and improving on, their discount programs.
</P>
<P>
   Fares are available to seniors in some selected markets at half
the cost of tickets bought with the popular senior-discount
coupons. For example, mature travelers could have flown round-trip
between New York and Chicago for as little as $138 under one new
club program, compared with $270 to $298 using senior-discount
coupons.
</P>
<P>
   Senior fliers will save some nice money with these recent
changes:
</P>
<P>
   _ Continental becomes the third major airline to set up a
senior-fare discount club.
</P>
<P>
   _ America West has expanded its newly restored ``Senior Saver
Pak'' coupon program to include more destinations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONTINENTAL'S CLUB &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the savings from other senior-discount clubs are based on
zone fares, Continental's new ``Freedom Flight Club'' offers fliers
ages 62 and older a savings of 15 percent to 20 percent off the
lowest published fares _ domestic or international.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Continental claims that unlike other airlines, its new
program has no capacity controls and requires no specified days or
times of travel. If any coach seat is available on the flight you
select, you get it.
</P>
<P>
   Club members get 20 percent discounts on weekdays, 15 percent on
weekends, on flights between Continental cities throughout the
United States, Europe, Canada, Mexico, Central and South America
and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Continental recently posted a limited-time,
promotional round-trip airfare between New York and Chicago of
$242. With 20 percent off, ``Freedom Flight Club'' members could
get those tickets at $196. In contrast, tickets purchased with
Continental's ``Freedom Trips'' senior-discount coupons would have
cost $270.
</P>
<P>
   A yearly Freedom Flight Club membership costs $75 for domestic
travel, an extra $50 for international travel. So far there is no
enrollment deadline. For more information, call (800) 248-8996.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER SENIOR CLUBS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where you live and where you fly most frequently should play a
part in your decision to join a particular senior-discount club.
</P>
<P>
   If you do not live in any cities served by American Airlines,
there would be no savings for you in its ``AActive American Travel
Club.''
</P>
<P>
   That club, like Delta's SkyWise club program, is based on a
complicated series of zone fares that, at worst, offer the same
fares as those available to senior-discount coupon holders and, at
best, offer spectacular savings.
</P>
<P>
   Round-trip flights between New York and Los Angeles cost $298
for both AActive American members and holders of American's
``Senior TrAAveler'' coupons. But a New York-Chicago round trip,
which also costs coupon holders $298, costs AActive American
members only $138 _ more than half off an already discounted
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Both Delta and American clubs require 14-day advance purchase
and overnight stays on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   There are also many blackout dates when you may not use club
discounts, and the AActive American club has additional blackouts
for some international zones. Delta's club program is not available
on international flights.
</P>
<P>
   AActive American membership costs $40 a year, and a senior
companion can enroll for an extra $30. Delta's SkyWise club
memberships also cost senior travelers $40 a year, with additional
memberships for companions of any age costing an extra $25.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to their clubs, all three airlines _ Continental,
American and Delta _ still tout senior-discount programs they
offered earlier: flat-rate coupons and 10 percent discounts for all
travelers ages 62 and older. Club discounts don't apply to any
other discount plan.
</P>
<P>
   For information on AActive American Travelers Club, call
(800)421-5600; for Delta SkyWise, call (800) 325-3750. (The SkyWise
enrollment period, which was originally scheduled to close Sept.
15, has been extended.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AW EXPANDS PROGRAM &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   America West Express passengers ages 62 and older and their
accompanying grandchildren may now use America West's newly
re-instated ``Senior Savers Pak'' discount coupons.
</P>
<P>
   The move opens the program to residents of 18 smaller cities in
the West. America West only recently restored the Senior Savers Pak
discount coupons after closing the program for a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Coupons cost $548 for a book of four. America West Express
passengers pay an extra $5 per flight. Coupons can also be used by
grandchildren ages 2 to 11 who are flying with a coupon-holder age
62 and older.
</P>
<P>
   Buy coupons from your travel agent or America West, (800)
235-9292.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 49 AND HOLDING &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Through Dec. 20, the Holiday Inn Hotel &AMP; Suites Main Gate East
in Orlando, Fla., is offering travelers ages 50 and older a ``49
and Holding'' package for $49/night. You get: free continental
breakfasts, free children's activities for the grandkids in the
Camp Holiday program, a coffee mug, and a collector's Mason jar
touting the hotel's 25th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   If you are traveling with grandkids between the ages of 3 and
12, they stay and eat free, and Holiday Inn will outfit you with a
free pager when you go off the premises. For more information, call
(800) 366-5437.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WARBIRDS ON DISPLAY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Warbirds at Tom Reilly's Flying Tigers Warbird Restoration
Museum'' (what a name!) at 231 N. Hoagland Blvd., in Kissimmee,
Fla., features a cross-section of this century's aviation history:
B-25s, Corsairs and F104 Starfighters.
</P>
<P>
   Museum guests are encouraged to look, see and touch these
aircraft, and once a month a ride is given in the B-25 Mitchell
bomber to a lucky museum visitor. Special events are matched with
dates like Pearl Harbor and Veterans' days.
</P>
<P>
   Mature travelers pay $6 admission, $2 off the regular rate.
Warbird rides are extra and start at about $140. For more
information, call (407) 933-1942.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENGLAND'S WAR MUSEUM &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you're heading to England, go to Duxford to see the Imperial
War Museum. Admission for mature travelers is a little over 4
pounds compared to 7 pounds for other adults. The museum has
regular air shows, so call 01223-835000 to see what's scheduled.
 &UR; ----- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions and comments to Gene and
Adele Malott, c/o The New York Times Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St.,
14th Floor, New York, N.Y. 10168. Send the Malotts a postcard from
your trip with ideas, questions and information on the bargains you
find for seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Questions may also be sent to the Malotts by electronic mail.
The address is MatureTrav(at)aol.com. (For (AT) use the symbol on
your keyboard.)
</P>
<P>
   The Malotts are the publishers of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.
