<SLUG> BC-MCCOY-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Mary McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Ten thousand dead. Ten thousand dead.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Mitch's toll in Central America is so mind-numbing you
shut it out as instinctively as you shield yourself from the midday
glare. How do you put your arms around a number like that? Do you
picture one out of 10 people walking around Dayton? The student
body of your college? The audience at your last Nutter concert?
</P>
<P>
   We find it easier to grasp a much smaller number:
</P>
<P>
   One.
</P>
<P>
   It was the story of Isabel Arriola de Guity that finally forced
me to look at the tragedy. The 36-year-old Honduran schoolteacher
survived for six days in the Caribbean Sea, clinging to floating
palm branches for the first four hours before fashioning a raft
from debris.
</P>
<P>
   Arriola's 4-year-old son was ripped from her arms as the water
carried her toward the sea. Before her eyes, the river swept away
her husband and two other children, ages 8 and 10.
</P>
<P>
   She had lost everything _ no, far worse, she had lost everyone.
Yet she clung to life, ferociously, her will to live as much a
miracle as her survival. On the sixth day, she pleaded with a duck
near her raft: ``Little duck, send a message that I'm alive. Take
me to my people. Take me to the shore.''
</P>
<P>
   Take Arriola's tragedy _ a family of five destroyed _ and
multiply it by 2,000.
</P>
<P>
   We can't imagine it. We don't want to imagine it.
</P>
<P>
   Yet thousands in the Miami Valley are forcing themselves to
imagine it, to put themselves in the place of the millions more
displaced by the hurricane, the thousands still fighting for their
lives. At the Dayton area chapter of the American Red Cross, ``the
phone has been ringing off the hook since Monday,'' said chief
development officer Kent Anderson. Because of the massive damage,
the Dayton chapter has raised its goal from $25,000 to $75,000 _
part of the $6 million the American Red Cross hopes to raise as
part of an international relief effort.
</P>
<P>
   At West Carrollton High School this week, Kathryn Juenger's
Spanish students are competing to see which class can raise the
most money. The students came up with the idea after discussing the
disaster in class Friday. ``If you guys want to do it, do it,''
Juenger told them. ``I'm just the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   The first day alone, they raised $417. At the end of each class
period this week, if they've finished their homework, they're
permitted to leave the classroom to solicit donations from
classmates.
</P>
<P>
   One student donated his lunch money for the week. Another turned
over his paycheck. Another is bringing her donation cup to her job
after school.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, these students woke up worrying about whether their
clothes looked right; now, they are seeing the contrast with
``these children who are waking up orphaned,'' Juenger said.
</P>
<P>
   Explained freshman Eric Jaynes, ``Some of the students are
starting to realize what it would feel like if we lived down there
and it happened to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten thousand dead. Ten thousand dead.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to follow the lead of the students, send a check
payable to the American Red Cross, P.O. Box 517, Dayton 45401-0517.
Specify Central American relief on the check.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Isabel Arriola, and what she faces in the days and
years after her dramatic rescue. Her will to live triumphed against
tremendous odds; now she must wonder why. ``I have nothing,'' she
said. ``I lost it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Officers on the HMS Sheffield, the British warship that rescued
Arriola, described her as ``an incredibly resilient lady with a
strong desire to live.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd say that's an understatement.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
