<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUHN-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dayton footballers currently living in their own interesting
times
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The seasons used to be mostly like gym class. For
the University of Dayton football team, just to show up breathing
was enough.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, for example, after nine games, the Flyers were 9-0 with
the scoring at 305-40; in 1984, it was 9-0 and 294-75; 1991, it was
9-0 and 278-66; two years ago, it was 9-0 and 333-138.
</P>
<P>
   This year the Flyers are 5-4 and the point differential is
244-235.
</P>
<P>
   To the philospher who said, ``May you live in interesting
times,'' UD coach Mike Kelly says, ``It's killing me.''
</P>
<P>
   He has lost 18 pounds this season as week after week, games are
decided on the final snap.
</P>
<P>
   Eight of UD's nine games have been decided in the fourth
quarter; six of them still at risk to the last tick. Said Kelly,
``We're three plays from 8-1 or three plays from 1-8.''
</P>
<P>
   They lost a game on a fumble at the goal line; lost another when
a shoe came off, followed by a fumble inside the opponent's 10;
lost another on an interception on the last play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you wake up screaming in the middle of the night?'' I
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't,'' he said, ``because I never go to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have pain in your stomach?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said. ``My stomach is so calloused, I feel
no pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's 43-42 victory over Towson was the capper, a
time-vault game. Up 27-0 at halftime, Kelly saw his team laughing
and joking on the way to the locker room. ``I threw a tantrum,'' he
said. ``I went nuts. I told them, 'You guys have no clue.' ``
</P>
<P>
   They didn't believe him. In the second half, the Flyers started
dropping the ball and falling down, and suddenly they were behind
42-34 with a minute-28 left.
</P>
<P>
   When UD scored a TD but didn't make the deuce with 0:28 left,
Kelly stood immobile on the sideline, contemplating, ``the darkest
day of my career,'' and trying to figure out what he was going to
say to his team afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't recovered an on-side kick in the 20 years I've been
here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   They got one Saturday. Magically, mystically, in a season where
so many things have gone wrong at games' ends, suddenly, a gift.
They moved to the Towson 24 and lined up for a 41-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago in practice, kicker Mike Pulsfort had been so
bad that after practice Kelly gathered the entire team at midfield
and told Pulsfort nobody was leaving until he kicked five in a row
from 35 yards. ``I would have kept them there till midnight,''
Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   But after Pulsfort missed the first one, he drilled five in a
row. ``I think that's the day he got his confidence back,'' the
coach said.
</P>
<P>
   So there he was Saturday, lining up a 41-yarder, and Kelly
caught Pulsfort's eye during the obligatory Towson ``ice him''
timeout. ``I shouted to him, 'Keep your head down and swing
through,' and tried to smile,'' Kelly said. ``He smiled back at me
and winked, and I thought, 'Oh, Lord, he's totally lost it.' ``
</P>
<P>
   He lost it through the uprights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Woulda gone 50,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you glad you've had the chance to experience this after
all those years of walkovers?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glad? Heck, no,'' Kelly said. ``But the fans have to be
enjoying it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the excitement, the challenge, the coaching-on-the-brink?
Isn't that better than the 50-0?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd prefer someplace in between,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And 10 years from now, or whenever you retire, which will you
remember best?''
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, no question,'' the coach said.
</P>
<P>
   Because for UD football, these are definitely interesting times.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nuhn writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
