A4771 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMALL-BIZ-COLUMN12-CO     11-11 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALL-BIZ-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Small businesses bank on the Internet
 &HT;    By Kim Tyson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Heroes and Legacies hopes that Internet commerce
is more than just blowing smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Like many small businesses, the Austin-based cigar seller has
launched a World Wide Web site in hopes of generating sales over
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which markets several hundred cigars and tobacco
products from 11 countries, has been generating only about a
half-dozen orders a week from the Web site. But manager Juan
Barajas is enthused about its chances for much higher sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to make money, but we're not there yet,''
Barajas says.
</P>
<P>
   Heroes and Legacies is interested in tapping the 67 million
potential customers using the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   According to Tom Fornoff, vice president of corporate marketing
of IntelliQuest Inc., an Austin-based computer industry marketing
research company, the number of people on the Web is expected to
continue to grow, reaching 110 million users in another two years.
</P>
<P>
   Fornoff says while there are lots of folks on the Internet,
there are far fewer buying products online _ only 13 million, or 20
percent. Those buying are now spending an average of $100 a month,
but that will more than double in three years, predicts Fornoff,
the keynote speaker at the first Electronic Commerce Seminar.
</P>
<P>
   One of the big attractions of the Net is the quick exposure to
millions of potential customers.
</P>
<P>
   A small company with limited capital can reach out to a much
broader audience than it usually could afford.
</P>
<P>
   A Web site not only offers the opportunity to attract new
customers, but it also provides a way for established businesses to
protect their established customer base, Fornoff says. He says
small-business owners also must consider what will happen if their
customers become comfortable buying online and their company
doesn't have a site.
</P>
<P>
   Much like when an interstate goes into a small town and traffic
changes, he says, businesses must weigh what happens if their
customers start going to another company that's online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will you open up a new 'store' and protect your business?'' he
says. ``Whether you open a store or not, a competitor will open one
on the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Fornoff says small companies considering the expense of building
and maintaining a Web site need to give the same commitment to it
as they would if they were building another store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the cost may be dramatically less than opening a
bricks and mortar store. But the same commitment has to be there or
greater,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Jo Betsy Vaught, executive producer of interactive services with
SicolaMartin Inc., an Austin marketing and advertising company,
says a company must give their Web site visibility by putting it in
their other advertising and on all company materials _ on voice
mail, business cards, direct mail flyers and sales receipts.
</P>
<P>
   She says it is also important that the company update the Web
site and keep it stocked with useful information so Net surfers
will continue to come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get a business card or flyer from somebody that says
visit our Web site, and I go there and there is nothing of any
value, you have wasted my time,'' she says. Put some more
information about your company, industry news or tips that can be
helpful to a customer, Vaught suggests.
</P>
<P>
   And if it's being used for direct sales, make sure every Web
page has a chance to order.
</P>
<P>
   There are lots of pitfalls to electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   One of the keys is that whatever service or product a company is
offering must match the profile of the current Web customer _
someone with higher disposable income that owns a computer with Web
access, Vaught says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like any other medium in that regard. You need to target
the message and target the medium. If you're selling products that
have a lower-income appeal or need, it may not be a good match
because the world is not wired.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web sites drawing the most traffic and sales are offering
products that are easily understood and don't require ``user
experience,'' such as books and CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Vaught says that Heroes and Legacies offers products that match
the demographic mix of current buyers _ young, upper income and
mostly male.
</P>
<P>
   Heroes and Legacies initially spent $10,000 to create the site
(http://heroesandlegacies.com/) and is now ready to invest another
$60,000 to improve its visibility.
</P>
<P>
   Barajas says his marketing plan includes buying more access
points on the major cigar Web sites that cater to cigar and tobacco
fans.
</P>
<P>
   A listing on one of the major cigar Web pages costs $1,200 a
year for a one-line home-page listing, plus $95 for each additional
category. He also plans to buy flashing banner ads to advertise
cigar specials.
</P>
<P>
   Heroes and Legacies, which has a retail store at the Arboretum
shopping center in Northwest Austin, primarily sells cigars
wholesale to liquor stores, bars and restaurants in a dozen states.
But Barajas says the Net offers the company a chance to expand
direct sales to customers far beyond what its local retail store.
</P>
<P>
   In the store, he says the average customer will spend $10 to $20
a visit, while the average Net sale is typically twice that high
because online customers are more often buying in bulk.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we put $60,000 into Austin alone (to advertise and generate
sales from the one local store) you get Austin customers alone,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put $60,000 into the Internet, you pretty much get the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Tyson writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
