<SLUG> BC-FBC-GEORGE-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This calculus series as good a way as any
 &HT;    By Dave George
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a small problem with the newly minted Bowl Championship
Series. Perhaps you've noticed it.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the plan is not perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, neither would a playoff system, everybody's panacea,
be perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Stock an imaginary post-season tournament at this moment, for
instance, with eight teams and there's a choice between leaving out
unbeaten Wisconsin or once-beaten Ohio State. The Buckeyes had been
No. 1 in the AP poll since August, remember, and likely would be
favored to handle the Badgers pretty easily if they played each
other.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, but wait, you say. All that stuff would work itself out by
the end of the season. Probably so, but why then is everybody so
eager to assume that the same thing won't happen with the BCS
formula? A month of games remain to be played, so much new
information that all this preliminary computer data may be headed
for the shredder.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee, top seed in the BCS, may have to stop unbeaten
Arkansas twice, including the SEC title game. Kansas State has got
Nebraska and Missouri yet to tackle and probably a Big 12 title
game against Texas A&AMP;M, No. 6 on the reconfigured BCS board. And
then there's UCLA, which looks to be running about a quartile low
after consecutive cliffhangers.
</P>
<P>
   What's really rich about all this sniping over the BCS program
is that it proves what can happen when you try to give people what
they want.
</P>
<P>
   Tired of seeing teams with weak nonconference schedules
rewarded? There's a strength-of-schedule component in there now,
hopefully encouraging athletic directors to tear up a few of those
contracts with Northwest Rose Petal State.
</P>
<P>
   Ever wish there were a way to reconcile the differences between
the media poll and the coaches' rankings? That's covered in the
BCS, too, with a simple process of averaging each contender's
standing in the two of them.
</P>
<P>
   What about the classic argument that nothing should matter
except a team's final record, regardless of where or when a loss
should come? The BCS boys are all over that one, too, slapping on a
quick and dirty penalty point for each and every defeat with no
questions asked.
</P>
<P>
   Fed up with teams running up the score in order to impress
pollsters? Sorry, that's the only thing the BCS doesn't endeavor to
fix, but from my viewpoint it's not a big deal. If a game is 60
minutes long, there's nothing wrong with letting them play it for
the full 60 minutes. There aren't any other major sports that
wrestle with this moral dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   To sum up all we've covered so far, the old system of polls and
backroom politics stunk, the elongated playoff system all you
dreamers crave will never be accepted by university presidents, and
the BCS is the best thing anyone's ever come up with to bring
precise shadings to the kaleidoscope of college football. All this
quibbling over the mysterious origin of a few lousy decimal points
seems kind of silly as long as the Big Ten is okay to operate with
11 teams.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, nobody understands the mathematical processes behind
the RPI rating system used in the selection and the seeding of the
NCAA basketball tournament but we have come to accept its findings
without rancor. The BCS will either reach that level of acceptance
over time or it will be improved upon little by little, that's all.
</P>
<P>
   It shouldn't be necessary to point out, on top of all of this,
that the Rose Bowl never got on board until the BCS was built. Yet
another reason to embrace the computer, with all its adjusted
deviations, and lean not unto our own understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Any plan that's saved up even a sliver of national championship
implications for the FSU-Florida game can't be all bad.
</P>
<P>
   Dave George writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
