<HEADER>
A4774 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-MUSEUM12-COX     11-11 1597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-MUSEUM12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Silicon Valley tech museum is living laboratory
 &HT;    By Lori Hawkins
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ The Tech Museum, the new $96 million
interactive monument to Silicon Valley, doesn't feel like a museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more like a hands-on classroom that informs and
entertains and inspires,'' says Regis McKenna, a leading Silicon
Valley consultant and an early board member of the Tech Museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of debate in the beginning about whether it
should even be called a museum. The Tech isn't about yesterday,
it's about tomorrow,'' McKenna said.
</P>
<P>
   The 132,000-square-foot museum in downtown San Jose is less a
record of what Silicon Valley has achieved _ including inventing
the many of the technologies that are part of everyday life
(microprocessor, semiconductor and the personal computer) and
putting them just about everywhere in the world _ than a living
laboratory where mind-bending exhibits illustrate how today's
technology works and where it's headed.
</P>
<P>
   You can don a bunnysuit and build a microchip in a
mini-cleanroom, take an ultrasound picture of your hand, and design
and ride in your own virtual roller-coaster simulator.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, which opened Oct. 31, plays several roles in Silicon
Valley: It shows off the technology developed in the Valley, it
provides a sense of place amidst the sprawl of glass and concrete
office buildings and it shows that tech companies _ which
cooperated to create the museum _ really can work together.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to take the mystery out of technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people who thought 'Oh, that's over my head' to walk
away saying 'Now I get it,''' says Peter Giles, chief executive of
The Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, museum designers kept it as simple as possible.
Text descriptions are kept to fewer than 40 words so that visitors
spend little time reading.
</P>
<P>
   The feel of the place is young and hip _ walls are curved and
painted with blinding hot pinks, purples and yellows. Neon strips
zig-zag like lightning across high ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   Computers are kept to a minimum because of their intimidation
factor. In fact, exhibits explaining how computers work were
postponed because museum organizers couldn't figure out how to
explain binary mathematics in a way that was open and easy to
understand. (The plan is to add exhibits showing the inner workings
of computers in the next two years.)
</P>
<P>
   The galleries hands-on experiments are the heart and soul of the
Tech, which is divided into four galleries.
</P>
<P>
   The Innovation gallery focuses on cutting-edge inventions and
innovators who helped the area earn its high-tech reputation
</P>
<P>
   Here you can create a laser-scanned 3-D image of your head, or
watch as grains of sand are transformed into silicon wafers. A
electron microscope lets you test a batch of real microchips.
</P>
<P>
   The Life Tech gallery looks at new ways to save lives and
enhance human performance. An ultrasound machine lets you see the
inside of your hand, and you can take a virtual tour of the human
body via an image database of a human body sliced in quarter-inch
sections.
</P>
<P>
   The Exploration gallery takes visitors to the surface of Mars,
the bottom of the ocean and back to the 1906 San Francisco
earthquake; and the Communication gallery explores how technology
helps humans create, harness and share information.
</P>
<P>
   Before building the 200 interactive exhibits, creators
interviewed area non-techies about what they already knew, what
they wanted to learn and how that could be achieved. Before
roll-out, people of all ages and backgrounds tested the interactive
controls, games and activities.
</P>
<P>
   The Tech also includes a 12,000-square-foot IMAX theater and a
learning center named after Robert N. Noyce, the late co-founder of
Intel Corp. and the first chief executive of Sematech Corp. in
Austin. The center will offer science and math activities for
teachers and students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to take the very coolest stuff in high-tech and make
it accessible,'' says Wayne LaBar, who oversees exhibit creation.
</P>
<P>
   The concept works, visitors say.
</P>
<P>
   On opening night, nine9-year-old Vincent Woo is hanging out at
an electronic cafe, where tables are embedded with laptop computers
that let you create a personal avatar, or cartoon identity. The
avatar travels through a 3-D graphical environment to chat with
characters created by other visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the coolest place I've been,'' says Woo, whose named
his avatar Bubba. ``A lot of kids still don't have computers, so
this is a way for them to learn how they work.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Helen Woo, a systems analyst at Chevron, says that
even though many families have PCs, the Tech goes far beyond what a
desktop computer can do. ``We have your basic PC in the den, but
what you can do on it is pretty limited,'' she says. ``Here kids
can be an astronauts on Mars or doctors doing genetic testing. It
opens up a lot of possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a place The Tech, its organizers hope, will provide an
anchor to Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley's engineers work inside glass and steel buildings
full of floors of cubicles. There's little to tour, short of
sneaking into Netscape or Sun Microsystems. And even then,
computers and cubicles are about all you'd see.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is intrigued by Silicon Valley, and they want to
explore it. But the problem is, there's nothere there,'' Leonard
Hoops of the San Jose Convention and Visitors Bureau says,
borrowing Virginia Woolf's remark about Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do you go when you get here?'' asks the man who's in the
business of selling San Jose as a destination for business
travellers and tourists. ``You can't just show up to Intel or Apple
and knock on the door. There's really nowhere to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tech is changing that. When it opened last weekmonth, the
eye-walloping electric mango and blue domed building became an
instant downtown landmark. Now the hope is that the Tech, as it's
called, will give some definition to the region that has spawned an
ongoing technological revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a fascination with technology and those who create it,
science centers and technology museums are flourishing. More than
400 science museums exist in 43 countries, according to the
Washington, D.C.-based Association of Science-Technology Centers.
Last year they attracted more than 40 million visitors.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose has long regarded itself the capital of Silicon Valley,
which, loosely defined, is a collection of towns arrayed along the
west side of San Francisco Bay south of San Francisco. They include
San Jose, Cupertino, Mountain View, Palo Alto, Menlo Park,
Sunnyvale and Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, the area was best known for its orchards, and
San Jose boasted of being the prune capital of the world. Over the
past few decades, fruit trees have since given way to Apple, Intel,
Sun, AMD, Hewlett-Packard, Netscape and other high-tech companies,
and Silicon Valley has become known as the world's high-tech
capital.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the museum had been bouncing around the Valley for
more than 20 years, with much of the time devoted to deciding on a
site (San Jose, of course) and raising money.
</P>
<P>
   The Tech is also an example of how high-tech companies that
compete fiercely for products, patents and personnel can come
together to create a cultural institution. All in all, the Tech
raised $30 million in private contributions and another $25 million
in in-kind gifts of equipment. It also received $40 million in city
redevelopment funds. Its board is made up of executives from
companies including Hewlett-Packard Co., the Kleiner Perkins
Caulfield &AMP; Beyers venture capital firm, Applied Materials and
Intel.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose boosters are hoping the Tech is the draw it needs to
attract out-of-towners. Other than business, there has never been
much reason for visitors to go downtown. Even business travelers
tend to skip out as soon as their work is done.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest challenges in turning that around has been
that the city has lacked an easily marketable identity. The Tech,
designed by reknowned Mexico City architect Ricardo Legorreta, who
designed the eye-popping enchilada-red San Antonio library, could
be San Jose's solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tech is one more sign that San Jose has arrived,'' says
Kim Polese, chief executive of hot Silicon Valley startup Marimba,
who attended opening festivities. ``It's more proof that San Jose
is a serious city that knows how to have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech Museums are flourishing around the world. Here are some of
the others and their Web sites:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Computer Museum, Boston. www.tcm.org
</P>
<P>
   _ National Air and Space Museum, Smithsonian Institution,
Washington, D.C. www.nasm.edu
</P>
<P>
   _ Intel Museum at Intel Corp., Santa Clara.
www.intel.com/intel/intelis/museum
</P>
<P>
   _ Deutsches Museum, Munich, Germany.
www.deutsches-museum.de/eindex.htm
</P>
<P>
   _ Teknikens Hus (House of Technology), Lulea, Sweden.
www.luth.se/th/eindex.html
</P>
<P>
   _ The Exploratorium, San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   www.exploratorium.edu
</P>
<P>
   _ Lawrence Hall of Science, Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   www.lhs.berkeley.edu
</P>
<P>
   _ Arizona Science Center, Phoenix. www.azscience.org
</P>
<P>
   _ Pacific Science Center, Seattle. www.pacsci.org
</P>
<P>
   What: High-tech museum
</P>
<P>
   Where: 201 S. Market St., San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Admission: $8 general; $6 children, $7 seniors
</P>
<P>
   Hours: Through 1998, Tuesday to Sunday, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   (Call for updates.)
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (408) 795-6100
</P>
<P>
   Web site: www.thetech.org
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
