<P>
   MCCOY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Ten thousand dead. Ten thousand
dead. Hurricane Mitch's toll in Central America is so mind-numbing
you shut it out as instinctively as you shield yourself from the
midday glare. How do you put your arms around a number like that?
Do you picture one out of 10 people walking around Dayton? The
student body of your college? The audience at your last Nutter
concert? We find it easier to grasp a much smaller number: One. It
was the story of Isabel Arriola de Guity that finally forced me to
look at the tragedy. (McCoy, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EZZARD-COLUMN _ The Christian Right is sometimes slammed for
using houses of worship for partisan campaigning, while little is
said about traditional Democratic treks to black churches,
especially in the South. Either way, it's not the church's role.
(Ezzard, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Cue violins. The Don paced the
floor, taking care not to pace too close to windows that would
expose his wideness to machine-gun fire. How had it come to this?
Minutes earlier he had been met by his chief deputy, whose face had
assumed the color and consistency of alfredo sauce. ``Don Gingrino,
the situation is critical.'' And so it was for Newto (The Hack)
Gingrino, embattled underworld prince. (Young, Waco Tribune-Herald)
MOVED.
</P>
