   NEWS-QUESTIONS _ Shuttle launches, Gingrich funds, missing
yacht. (Bessonnette, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (l, a) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SOUTH _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD _ ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-NUTS _ We associate nuts with the holidays, because they're
in season and because they are one of the special treats we indulge
in now more than any other time of year. Yes, they can be a lot of
work; but their value is measured in terms other than cupfuls.
(Langhenry, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH COLOR PHOTO and
LAYOUT.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-NUTS-RECIPES _ Recipe page to go with NUTS story
centerpieced on AJC weekly food section. (Langhenry, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH LAYOUT.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-RECIPESWAP _A weekly recipe exchange column. This week:
Kentucky Poundcake. (Langhenry, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-CYBERSPICE _ A weekly column looking at the plethora of
recipes on the Internet. (Parham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-BABIES _ Babies whose mothers are HIV-positive may benefit
from preventive drug therapy even after birth, says a new study in
the New England Journal of Medicine. Expectant mothers in the U.S.
who are HIV-positive are supposed to get a few months' of the drug
AZT to prevent transmission of the virus to their babies. But the
drug appears to be effective even if it isn't given for the full
course _ and it's also effective if the babies take it within 48
hours after birth. (Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   EIGHTIES-NOSTALGIA _ E-mailed and newsgroup lists of elliptical
'80s song lyrics are a hot guessing game among Gen X'ers, who while
away the hours in front of their computers trying to figure out who
sang s uch lines as ``I've seen a million faces, and I've rocked
them all.'' Now a couple of guys have put out a book called ``Who
Can It Be Now,'' with more than 500 one-line lyrics to keep the
game going. It's tapping into the '80s nostalgia that has several
Atlanta radio stations programming '80s shows. Interview with book
authors. Book jacket art. or decorate with Boy George and other
icons of the '80s. (Lizlee, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EIGHTIES-LYRICS _ Ten song lyrics, with answers and a couple of
'80s Web sites with more quizzes. (Lizlee, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TV-TROUBLES _ The new TV season is in trouble. Ratings for five
of the six networks are down, way down. Part of the blame goes to a
lackluster crop of new shows, but there's a pervasive sense that
old favorites are struggling: ``ER'' needs some paddles on the
chest, ``Frasier'' is mopey rather than funny, and the only thing
``Ally McBeal'' fans are talking about is Calista Flockhart's
weight. A look at what's wrong and why. Commentary/analysis.
(Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TV-TROUBLES-RATINGS _ Look at ratings on selected returning
series, which are up and down. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TV-SURFER _ PBS' ``Mystery!'' starts its second series: ``The
Life and Crimes of William Palmer,'' the true story of a 19th
century British doctor who poisons most of those he comes in
contact with. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ Book notes. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WEEKEND AT HOME _ ETA: 5 p.m.
</P>
