<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: Requiem for a godfather
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Cue violins.
</P>
<P>
   The Don paced the floor, taking care not to pace too close to
windows that would expose his wideness to machine-gun fire. How had
it come to this?
</P>
<P>
   Minutes earlier he had been met by his chief deputy, whose face
had assumed the color and consistency of alfredo sauce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don Gingrino, the situation is critical.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it was for Newto (The Hack) Gingrino, embattled
underworld prince.
</P>
<P>
   The bad-news bearer was Dickie (The Book) Armey. He had been
sounding out the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suggestion is that you step down as syndicate boss or that
you will be 'escorted' out.'' The Book gestured toward the window
that looked out onto an empire the Don had presumed to be his.
</P>
<P>
   How was this happening?
</P>
<P>
   It had only been a few days since the Gingrino family was poised
for its greatest coup: hearings for Willie (The Slick) Clinton,
head of the Clintonostra clan, on _ of all things _ a morals
charge.
</P>
<P>
   How sweet it was. The Don's mind flashed back to the heady days
of October . . .
</P>
<P>
   At Gingrino strategy sessions the laughter had rippled with the
vino.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's to the Slick; what a chump,'' they had toasted. ``To be
caught with a broad. It's undignified.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We treat our broads with respect,'' said a deputy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a respectable syndicate,'' Gingrino had said. ``We deal
in soft money, patronage, paybacks from our polluting friends. And
to our friends in the vice industries, we are ever true.''
</P>
<P>
   Whenever they convened over linguini and marinara, fine smokes
were passed out courtesy of those who bankrolled so much of what
kept the Gingrinos in power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah,'' inhaled the Don, ``there's nothing like a smoke-filled
room.''
</P>
<P>
   Running a syndicate came down to two simple rules: (1)
perpetuate your power; (2) have a good time doing it.
</P>
<P>
   The road to the top had been heady for the Don. As a henchman
skilled at breaking opponents' kneecaps, he'd caught the attention
of the Reaganzano family.
</P>
<P>
   The Reaganzanos were one of the most powerful syndicates of the
century. In 1980 they had avenged the removal of Dick (The Trick)
Nixono, patriarch of the Nixono family. Reaganzano lieutenant
Gorgio Bush had four years at the helm. He is known to have raised
two ambitious sons.
</P>
<P>
   As for the other side, there had been the hated Kennedino clan,
headed by Teddy (The Tippler) Kennedino, and the short-lived reign
of Jimmy (The Prude) Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the '80s and into the '90s, the Reaganzanos ruled.
But in 1992 The Slick staged his takeover. He, too, knew how to
play the soft-money game. He, too, knew how to seize and hold power
and shower patrons with attention. Indeed, he was beating the
Gingrinos, the Reaganzanos, at their own game.
</P>
<P>
   And then came the scandal that, Gingrino assured, meant it was
all over for the The Slick: A woman. Imagine that? How unseemly.
How undignified. And she wasn't even a starlet. She was just a
nobody with a hall pass.
</P>
<P>
   For months the Gingrinos seized on the scandal. They demanded
``the truth.'' They issued long pronouncements about morality and
uprightness. Yet, came the ides of November and The Slick was
stronger than ever. Now, unbelieveably, it was the Don facing
removal.
</P>
<P>
   What had gone wrong? Had it been that the Don had otherwise
neglected his empire as he zeroed in on The Slick? Had the Don
forgotten his friends and patrons, his responsibilities to the
family?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, he was stepping down, retiring to his
Georgia vineyard while others offered themselves as upright, moral
and trustworthy to carry on the business of the syndicate. Cue
violins.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
