A4783 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASIA-SUMMIT-$ADV15-CO     11-11 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-SUMMIT-$ADV15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ASIANS IN A SOUR MOOD, THEIR FUTURE UNDER SHADOW, FOR CLINTON
VISIT
 &HT;    With photos placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    With ASIA-DATA-$ADV15; JAPAN-ECONOMY-$ADV15,
KOREA-ECONOMY-$ADV15, INDONESIA-ECONOMY-$ADV15,
CHINA-ECONOMY-$ADV15; ASIA-QUOTES-$ADV15; CLINTON-ASIA-$ADV15.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Nov. 15 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia _ Shellshocked by an Asian financial
crisis that seems to have no end, Asians are in a sour mood as they
await this week's visit by U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The near future for Asia looks as bad as this year. Maybe worse.
</P>
<P>
   Japan, the potential locomotive of Asian economic recovery, is
stranded in its worst post-World War II recession and keeps
slashing imports from the rest of Asia. Now, even China's
long-vibrant economy seems on the verge of stagnating.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, who will host Clinton
and 20 other Pacific Rim leaders at an economic summit here, has
vilified Western institutions in caustic language seldom heard from
a world leader since the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Blaming the Asian crisis on ``Western capitalist greed'' and
financial bungling by the American-backed International Monetary
Fund, Mahathir accused the West of ``a desire to dominate the
Asians and stop them from developing.''
</P>
<P>
   Other participants in the annual summit of the Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation forum (APEC) will be more polite-tongued than
the crusty Mahathir. But Clinton is likely to find other leaders
just as obstinate, especially on ticklish trade issues like Japan's
renewed efforts to shield markets against American exports.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is inexcusable for the second-largest economy in the world
and the largest economy in Asia not to fulfill its
responsibilities,'' complained U.S. Deputy Trade Representative
Richard W. Fisher this month, after Japan informed Washington it
couldn't keep its promises from an earlier APEC summit to cut
Japanese tariffs on forest products and fish.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton will find in his week-long trip to Malaysia, Japan
and South Korea, the region's leaders remain baffled about why the
16-month-old Asian crisis has endured so long and caused so much
pain.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of millions from Indonesia to South Korea are confronting
another year of unemployment and economic shrinkage -- still
without a safety net. A Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. study projects that
per-capita income will decline next year in India, Hong Kong, the
Philippines, Singapore, South Korea and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   Asia has been hit with a ``financial typhoon'' that left behind
a trail of devastation ``far greater than anyone imagined,'' said
Singapore's Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong this month. Goh added that
while there are some signs the storm's force has lessened, he sees
a 20 percent chance that Asia will suffer a ``second typhoon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can avoid a depression, but I think the credit
crunch will continue,'' ventured think-tank economist Susumu
Takahashi in Japan, where consumer spending has just fallen for the
11th month in a row.
</P>
<P>
   In South Korea, where homeless executives can be found sleeping
in Seoul public parks, social worker Park Eun-Kyung of World Vision
Korea said she hopes the economy will hit bottom next year.
``People say this is the worst disaster since World War II,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
