<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 10:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4785 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIA-ECONOMY-$AD     11-11 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-ECONOMY-$ADV15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INDONESIA: POVERTY, MALNUTRITION CREEP INTO COUNTRYSIDE
 &HT;    With ASIA-SUMMIT-$ADV15; Photos placed in the International
folder on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Nov. 15 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of a locator map, Kiara Payung is about 50
miles west-northwest of Jakarta.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIARA PAYUNG, Indonesia _ Hundreds of thousands of children in
once-prosperous villages like this are dropping out of school and
going hungry as Indonesia lurches into a Great Leap Backward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't go to school any more,'' says Supendi, a skinny
13-year-old boy with festering sores on his leg.
</P>
<P>
   Until six months ago, he attended the local public school that
required a fee of 3,000 rupiahs (US$.40 cents) a month. ``My mother
doesn't have enough money to pay the fee,'' says Supendi, who like
many Indonesians uses a single name.
</P>
<P>
   So the boy lounges away the muggy midday heat by crouching on a
tin-roofed porch and listening to the barefoot men talk about ``the
old days'' just one year ago.
</P>
<P>
   That's when ordinary people could afford to eat lamb or chicken
at least three times a week, recounts one of the story-tellers. His
name is Mista, and he is a 23-year-old laid-off factory worker.
</P>
<P>
   Mista lost his $25-a-week job in a chocolate factory six months
ago. He says he doesn't blame the factory for firing him, nor does
he expect to get hired back. ``The company had to buy materials
from abroad, and it got too expensive,'' Mista says.
</P>
<P>
   It's only been a year since this fast-growing, seemingly stable
nation of 212 million people was dragged down by the riptide of the
Asian economic crisis. In that time, the world's fourth-most
populous country has seen its economy shrink by about 55 percent,
inflation shoot up to 80 percent a year and its banking system go
into virtual paralysis where no loans are made or collected.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia is the country worst hit by the Asian economic crisis.
Its suffering will cast a long shadow over the Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation forum this week, as Indonesia and the region's
other leaders press for measures to make sure that their people
never endure a similar descent into hardship.
</P>
<P>
   World Bank specialist Richard Newfarmer estimates that school
enrollment throughout Indonesia has already dropped from 78 to 54
percent, as parents like Supendi's find even the nominal school
fees too high to bear.
</P>
<P>
   In two years the number of Indonesians living below the poverty
line has shot up from 20 million people to an estimated 100
million, dragging Indonesia down to a level of impoverishment not
known here since it was an underdeveloped backwater in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Mista says he, his wife and two-year-old daughter haven't eaten
meat in three months. Today they eat rice from the market and
fruits that they can find growing wild, like jackfruit. ``That's
the cheapest, at least it's filling.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kiara Payung (population 10,400), children don't suffer the
distended bellies and spindly limbs that have marked the
near-starvation of refugee camps in Sudan or Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
   But Tintin, the village pregnancy nurse, has just reported to
the district health office that in August she came across 12 cases
of malnutrition among children she treated who were under five
years old.
</P>
<P>
   Her colleague Suharto(CQ), a district civil servant in charge of
welfare, estimates that unemployment in Kiara Payung has risen from
40 percent to at least 75 percent in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   The district health office says that another 35 malnutrition
cases were reported in four nearby villages.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the deprivation of the Asian crisis looks less
acute in the capital Jakarta -- even in neighborhoods that were
torn apart by last May's anti-Chinese riots that burned scores of
Chinese-owned shopping plazas and killed nearly 1,200 people.
</P>
<P>
   F. M. Mendrofa, who has reopened his furniture store in the
burned-out Ciledug Plaza riot corridor, complains that banks won't
loan money, prices of materials have skyrocketed, and ``everything
is unstable.'' Somehow, says Mendrofa, he manages to sell about two
mattresses every day.
</P>
<P>
   For the poorest city-dwellers, the only way to avoid hunger has
been to resort to ``informal'' occupations that most Indonesians
consider degrading, like singing for a few rupiahs beside cars at
stoplights. Or hunting for metal and plastic bags at the Jakarta
municipal dump. Somehow, they are surviving.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
