<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 10:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4786 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-ECONOMY-$ADV15-     11-11 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECONOMY-$ADV15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JAPAN: RECOVERY SLOWED BY FEAR OF SHOPPING, DREAD OF FIRING
 &HT;    With ASIA-SUMMIT-$ADV15; Photos placed in the International
folder on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Nov. 15 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The personnel director of a major Japanese construction
company started his fourth whiskey-on-the-rocks, as he explained
his own gloomy role in the recession that stubbornly blocks Asia's
economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mission is to do the firing. If I don't do it, I will be
fired,'' said Tomihei Sudou, who was unwinding with three
colleagues at a shopping complex restaurant after a recent Saturday
of work.
</P>
<P>
   In 18 years he has fired ``not even 10 people'' at his
Tokyo-based firm, which has a payroll of 15,000 workers. In the
next three years, he must get rid of 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Some will quit or retire on schedule. But many, many more Sudou
will have to sweet-talk, cajole or coerce into leaving, defying the
once inviolable Japanese jobs-for-life tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Fear is an essential reason for Japan's persisting recession --
fear over who next will be squeezed out of the nation's weakened
industries, fall victim to the highest surge of bankruptcies since
World War II, or see wages or annual bonuses trimmed further.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Japanese start spending again, returning confidence to
their own corporations and recreating vital markets for neighboring
countries, Asia will be unable to heave itself up and out of the
regional economic crisis now deep into its second year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the health of Asia's economy -- and indeed the world --
depends on Japan,'' President Bill Clinton recently said, urging
the Japanese to move faster to rekindle the world's second largest
economy.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly 18 months of recession, Japan finally adopted
crucial bank reform legislation last month. Making $361 billion
available to debt-ridden banks, its goal is to get banks lending,
this time with some supervision. Only time will tell whether it is
enough to make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to what the Japanese government was like before, we
actually did pretty well,'' legislative leader Okiharu Yasuoka said
in countering the critics. Yasuoka, who steered the bank bill
through parliament, said that further plans include massive tax
cuts, mortgage rate reductions and public spending that would
target nontraditional areas such as information technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the government starting this, it should create a rhythm on
the consumer side and begin the spending,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Speeding consumer rhythm beyond a sluggish waltz will not be
easy.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics wonder whether the banks will do better with the new
government money, after losing hundreds of billions in unpaid
loans, and question whether public spending will be wasted away.
Confidence in government continues to slide, with 56 percent of
Japanese polled last month giving the ruling politicians a negative
rating.
</P>
<P>
   Few Japanese are going hungry or homeless, but many have seen
living standards drop more than in any economic downturn since
World War II. Others are too anxious to spend.
</P>
<P>
   Takashimaya Co. Ltd., retailer to royalty and regular Japanese
since opening in 1831, had to cut 2,800 personnel over the past
three years. It staffed a long-planned new department store by
moving 550 workers from other sites and using 500 temporary
workers, said spokesman Tetsuo Yamaguchi.
</P>
<P>
   Retail woes began in earnest when the government raised Japan's
consumption tax from 3 percent to 5 percent in April 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sales declined dramatically. After that in Japan, we had more
and more bad news,'' Yamaguchi said. In the first half of October,
sales dipped 10 percent from 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, intense shoppers crowd store aisles throughout Tokyo.
But Yamaguchi said they buy small and less. The furniture
department at one of his stores, for example, was literally empty
of customers on a recent Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   At the New Tokyo restaurant, located near the new Takashimaya
store, construction executive Sudou and his three buddies
exemplified the problem.
</P>
<P>
   One friend wanted to buy a car, but felt he couldn't. Another
said Japanese have stopped taking out loans for big purchases or
vacations.
</P>
<P>
   Their salaries haven't much changed, they said, but the bonuses
that differentiate employees have. Sudou said his was down about 25
percent, or about $9,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   That cuts into discretionary spending that once buoyed Japan's
economy and the economies of regional neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some good things have come out of this,'' Sudou said. ``Now we
have discount stores.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
