<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 10:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4827 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-ACC-CAPSULES-RESE     11-11 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ACC-CAPSULES-RESEND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    ACC MEN'S TEAM-BY-TEAM CAPSULES
 &HT;    FOR USE WITH AJC BASKETBALL PREVIEW PACKAGE
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. DUKE
</P>
<P>
   Last year: 32-4 overall, 15-1 ACC (1st).
</P>
<P>
   Coach: Mike Krzyzewski (505-212 overall, 432-153 in 18 years at
Duke).
</P>
<P>
   Returning starters (3): G Trajan Langdon 6-3, Sr. (14.7 ppg); F
Elton Brand, 6-8, Soph. (13.4 ppg); F Shane Battier, 6-8, Soph.
(7.6 ppg).
</P>
<P>
   Top newcomers: F Corey Maggette, 6-6, Bellwood, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Duke played four freshmen extensively, and they are
back, better than before. William Avery will take over the point
guard slot, while Brand, Battier and Chris Burgess form a strong
front line. Fifth-year senior Langdon is the team leader.
</P>
<P>
   2. MARYLAND
</P>
<P>
   Last year: 21-11 overall, 10-6 ACC (3rd).
</P>
<P>
   Coach: Gary Williams (371-240 overall, 164-112 in 9 years at
Maryland).
</P>
<P>
   Returning starters (3): F Laron Profit, 6-5, Sr. (15.8 ppg); G
Terrell Stokes, 6-0, Sr., (5.4 ppg); C Obinna Ekezie, 6-10, Sr.,
(12.8 ppg)
</P>
<P>
   Top newcomers: G Juan Dixon, 6-3, Baltimore; G Danny Miller,
6-8, Mt. Holly, N.J.; G Steve Francis, 6-3, Takoma Park, Md.
(Allegany Junior College); F Lonny Baxter, 6-8, Silver Spring, Md.
(Hargrave Military Academy).
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: The Terps look to be loaded and in a position to
challenge Duke for the ACC lead.
</P>
<P>
   3. NORTH CAROLINA
</P>
<P>
   Last year: 34-4 overall, 13-3 ACC (2nd).
</P>
<P>
   Coach: Bill Guthridge (34-4 overall, 34-4 in one year at North
Carolina).
</P>
<P>
   Returning starters (2): G Ed Cota, 6-1, Jr. (8.1 ppg); F Ademola
Okulaja, 6-9, Sr., (8.0 ppg).
</P>
<P>
   Top newcomers: G Ronald Curry, 6-3, Hampton, Va.; F/G Jason
Capel, 6-8, Chesapeake, Va. F/C Kris Lang, 6-10, Gastonia, N.C.; F
Orlando Melendez, 6-8, Juana Diaz, Puerto Rico (redshirt).
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: The Tar Heels return only 27 percent of their scoring
and 17 percent of their rebounding from a year ago. Brandon
Haywood, a 7-0 center, could step forward, but look for freshmen
Curry and Capel to make an impact.
</P>
<P>
   4. WAKE FOREST
</P>
<P>
   Last year: 16-14 overall, 7-9 ACC (T-4th).
</P>
<P>
   Coach: Dave Odom (220-135 overall, 182-93 in 9 years at Wake
Forest).
</P>
<P>
   Returning starters (4): G Robert O'Kelley, 6-1, Soph. (16.6
ppg); F Niki Arinze, 6-5, Soph. (7.0 ppg); F Rafael Vidaurreta,
6-9, Soph. (4.5 ppg); F Josh Shoemaker, 6-9, Soph. (3.0 ppg)
</P>
<P>
   Top newcomers: G Roderick Hicks, 6-1, Houston; G Jim
Fitzpatrick, 6-0, Fairfax, Va.; F/C Darius Songaila, 6-9,
Marijampole, Lithuania; G Ervin Murray, 6-5, Teachey, N.C.; F
Antwan Scott, 6-8, New Bern, N.C.; F Craig Dawson, 6-5, Kinston,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Wake started three or four freshmen for most of last
season, and five freshmen in two games, and still has the youngest
team in the league this year. O'Kelley led the Deacs in scoring
with a 16.6 average.
</P>
<P>
   5. CLEMSON
</P>
<P>
   Last year: 18-14 overall, 7-9 ACC (T-4th).
</P>
<P>
   Coach: Larry Shyatt (19-9 overall, first year at Clemson).
</P>
<P>
   Returning starters (3): G Terrell McIntyre, 5-9, Sr. (13.9 ppg);
C Tom Wideman, 6-10, Sr. (4.4 ppg) F Tony Christie, 6-6, Sr. (8.0
ppg)
</P>
<P>
   Top newcomers: G Will Solomon, 6-1, East Hartford, Conn.; G
Tywan Harris, 6-0, Greenville, S.C.; G Dustin Bracklick, 6-4,
Charleston, S.C.; F Chuckie Gilmore, 6-8, Fayetteville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Three starters and nine lettermen return. McIntyre was
the leading scorer last year and senior Harold Jamison grabbed 7.3
rebounds a game. Vincent Whitt, Johnny Miller, Mohamed Woni and
Adam Allespach all played plenty last season, to give Shyatt one of
the most experienced teams in the league.
</P>
<P>
   6. N.C. STATE
</P>
<P>
   Last year: 17-15 overall, 5-11 ACC (8th).
</P>
<P>
   Returning starters (3): G Justin Gainey, 6-0, Jr. (5.3 ppg); F
Kenny Inge, 6-8, Soph. (11.0 ppg); C Ron Kelley, 6-10, Soph. (8.3
ppg).
</P>
<P>
   Top newcomers: G Brian Keeler, 6-2, Cary, N.C.; G Ron Anderson,
6-6, Fayetteville, N.C.; F Keith Bean, 6-8, Fontana, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: The most notable returnee is 6-8 forward Damon
Thornton, who missed all but three games last year with a foot
injury. Archie Miller is one of the best shooters coming off the
bench in the ACC.
</P>
<P>
   7. GEORGIA TECH
</P>
<P>
   Last year: 19-14 overall, 6-10 ACC (T-6th).
</P>
<P>
   Coach: Bobby Cremins (426-274 overall, 326-204 in 17 years at
Georgia Tech).
</P>
<P>
   Returning starters (1): C Alvin Jones, 7-0, Soph. (6.8 ppg).
</P>
<P>
   Top newcomers: G Tony Akins, 6-0, Lilburn; G Darryl LaBarrie,
6-3, Stone Mountain (transfer from Florida A&AMP;M); F Jason Collier,
7-0, Springfield, Ohio (transfer from Indiana).
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Sophomore guard Dion Glover, who averaged 18.4 points
per game last year, is out with a torn ACL. Starting point guard
Travis Spivey transferred to Iowa State and backup center Pablo
Machado transferred to Loyola Marymount. With Matt Harpring and
Michael Maddox graduated, Tech is not overwhelmed with
experience.Tech will return 15.8 points of offense per game.
</P>
<P>
   8. FLORIDA STATE
</P>
<P>
   Last year: 18-14 overall, 6-10 ACC (T-6th).
</P>
<P>
   Coach: Steve Robinson (64-32 overall, 18-14 in first year at
FSU).
</P>
<P>
   Returning starters (1): G. Terrell Baker, 6-5, Sr. (12.0 ppg).
</P>
<P>
   Top newcomers: F Antwaun Dixon, 6-5, Marietta; G Adrian
Crawford, 6-5, Soph., Akron, Ohio (transfer Tulsa); F Damous
Anderson, 6-6, Jr., Greenville, S.C. (transfer from Metro Atlanta
College); G Emanuel Mathis, 6-3, Atlanta; F/C Justin Mott, 6-10,
Jr., Chula Vista, Calif. (transfer from Barton C.C.).
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Four of Robinson's players have played at other
Division I schools: Crawford (Tulsa), Oliver Simmons (Kentucky),
Anderson (South Carolina) and Mott (Washington State). The problem
for the Seminoles is that few on the roster have played together as
a team, although forward Ron Hale and center Karim Shabazz saw
plenty of playing time last season.
</P>
<P>
   9. VIRGINIA
</P>
<P>
   Last year: 11-19 overall, 3-11 ACC (9th).
</P>
<P>
   Coach: Pete Gillen (274-128 overall, first year at Virginia).
</P>
<P>
   Returning starters (3): G Donald Hand, 5-11, Soph. (4.7 ppg);
G/F Willie Dersch, 6-5, Jr. (6.5 ppg); C/F Colin Ducharme, 6-9, Jr.
(7.8 ppg).
</P>
<P>
   Top newcomers: F/G Adam Hall, 6-5, Katy, Texas; F/G Chris
Williams, 6-5, Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: Prospects for Gillen are not bright. The Cavs return
three starters, but they also happen to be the only three with any
experience. In fact, the Cavalier roster lists only eight players,
period.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Arey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
