EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, Nov. 11, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Thursday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PHYSICIAN-SUICIDE (San Francisco) _ Californians may find
physician-assisted suicide on the public agenda again soon, as an
advocacy group works to gather support to change state law to allow
terminally ill patients to get a doctor's help in ending their
lives. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   ENDANGERED-SALMON (San Francisco) _ Commercial fishermen and
environmentalists say California's plan to distribute water
statewide and restore the ecological health of San Francisco Bay
will, in fact, accelerate the destruction of California's dwindling
salmon runs. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION (San Francisco) _ California's voter-approved
anti-affirmative action initiative has prompted many contractors
and public agencies to resist efforts to diversify, eroding
advancements women and minorities have made in education and
employment, a new study asserts. By JULIE CHAO.
</P>
<P>
   YOSEMITE-RANGERS (San Francisco) _ It's more dangerous than
working as a Drug Enforcement Agency agent, a federal prison guard,
a border control officer or even a U.S. Postal Service employee.
National Park Services employees get injured at a higher rate than
workers in just about every other federal agency, according to the
Occupational Safety and Health Administration. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ORACLE-MICROSOFT (San Francisco) _ Larry Ellison, the brash
visionary of Oracle Corp., says the Justice Department should break
up Microsoft Corp. for violating antitrust laws. ``It's not a
question of did Microsoft break the law,'' Ellison said. ``The
question is, `Why did a smart group of people break the law over
and over again?' I think the answer is the Internet.'' By WENDY
TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   WORKPLACE-LAW (San Francisco) _ A San Francisco company has
created Winning Through Prevention, a Trivial Pursuit-type game
designed to help companies avoid being pursued in some
not-so-trivial court cases. The game is easy to tailor to a
company's needs, inexpensive enough for a small business and, best
of all, it helps you understand workplace law by using human
examples. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   FURNITURE-MARKET (High Point, N.C.) _ In the movie ``Gypsy,''
the strippers sang ``You Gotta Get a Gimmick.'' Manufacturers at
the International Home Furnishings Market have adopted it as their
theme song. Making good-looking furniture doesn't seem to be enough
today. Manufacturers feel the need to offer the consumer something
to identify with _ a well-known name, or a story to tell. By
MADELEINE McDERMOTT HAMM.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ANGEL-BLUE (San Francisco) _ Steven Kovacs had a confident smile
on his face when asked if he courts controversy. ``Absolutely,'' he
says. The San Francisco State University film professor may get his
wish after his film about an affair between a man in his 40s and a
teen-ager makes its debut Sunday on Lifetime under the title ``My
Neighbor's Daughter.'' By G. ALLEN JOHNSON.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-THRILLERS (Undated) _ If you read only one thriller this
year, make it Jeffery Deaver's extraordinary ``The Coffin Dancer.''
The plot twists are amazing, yet never out of place in this
thriller full of intriguing characters and crafty detective work.
By BOBBIE HESS.
</P>
<P>
   MICHAEL-MUSIC-REVIEW (Undated) _ The irony _ and marketing
possibilities _ of a much publicized sex scandal have not been lost
on pop star George Michael, whose double-disc ``Ladies and
Gentlemen _ The Best of George Michael'' (Epic Records), has hit
the record stores. By JOEY GUERRA.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WINE-COLUMN (Undated) _ Nov. 19 is the day the Nouveau
Beaujolais arrives. Nouveau Beaujolais is the young, fruity wine
from the southern part of France's Burgundy region, originally
intended for Paris bistros. But in the 1970s _ thanks to a lot of
hype and promotion _ Le Nouveau caught the world's fancy. By
MICHAEL LONSFORD.
</P>
<P>
   BREAD-PUDDING (Undated) _ Like fruit cobbler, bread pudding is a
homey comfort dessert that's made it to the big time. Devised by
thrifty cooks as a way to recycle stale bread, bread pudding has
been traced to Colonial times. Bread pudding has made a great
resurgence in the '90s. By ANN CRISWELL.
</P>
<P>
   With: BREAD-PUDDING-RECIPES
</P>
<P>
   CHOCOLATE-CAKES (Undated) _ The Died-and-Went-to-Heaven
chocolate cake is from Eating Well magazine. The Chocolate Praline
Cake was a Pillsbury BAKE-OFF winner in 1988. Both cakes are
scrumptious. By ANN CRISWELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The devastating storm damaged in
Central America, and the vast outpouring of help for the countless
victims, shows how small the world is. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
