<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOWEENIES NEED TO ROAM, TOO
</HEADLINE>
 CPT- COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram  DEAR DR.
BOMBAY: Having become frustrated with America Online, would you
please recommend a more effective, yet user-friendly, server?
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ American Offline
</P>
<P>
   DEAR AMERICAN: Gee, I hate to be the one to break this to you,
but it doesn't get much easier or effective than AOL, even for the
cerebrally challenged. I know what you're looking for, though.
</P>
<P>
   AOL is a nice little place to get used to the online world. You
can learn how to e-mail and browse and mouse-click your way around.
You can even learn to chat with other users, who will most
certainly want to know A) what you're wearing right now and B) if
you will send them a naked picture of yourself.
</P>
<P>
   But AOL is only one small part of the Internet, like a corral
out on the prairie. Horses can come and go through the gate,
providing the system wrangler can keep it open. Many of these
horses are happy just to stay in the corral, chatting amiably with
other horses, wondering what they're wearing and trying to get them
to send naked pictures of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   What you're looking for is a true ISP _ an Internet service
provider. These are the people who let you dial into their big,
expensive computer that's connected to the entire Net. In the olden
days, two or three years ago, it pretty much took a four-eyed,
Xena-worshipping technoweenie to hook things up right the first
time. Well, we can look back on those primitive times and burst out
laughing now. If you can set up AOL, you can set up a Web browser
and a dialer. The ISP should give you software, instructions and a
help line number.
</P>
<P>
   Will you use the Internet when you're on the road? Try some
national or statewide company with a long list of local access
numbers unless you can handle the long-distance bill. If it's just
for home use, you'll probably find a cheaper deal with a local ISP.
</P>
<P>
   Pick your ISP carefully, which is to say, do it when you're
sober. Don't sign a year-long contract right away, because the ISP
may stink or be otherwise unreliable. Find out how long the company
has been in business and how many users it has per available
connection. Nothing more frustrating than a busy signal. Talk to
tech support and pretend to be totally in the dark. Big stretch,
huh? If you're not comfortable with the help desk dweeb, take a
walk. Lastly, ask the biggest nerd at work what he uses. He may get
so excited that somebody actually talked to him he'll do that trick
where he shoots milk out of his nose. I never get tired of watching
that.
</P>
<P>
   STUPID SOFTWARE TRICK: Here's something to try if you have
Windows 98 and are really bored. Click the Start button, open the
Programs menu and go to Accessories. Right-right click on an
application (like Notepad), then pick Properties from the menu that
appears. Now click the Change Icon button. Double-click on the icon
already in use and then click OK.
</P>
<P>
   Click on the Start button again. Hover just between Shutdown and
the Start button and a scroll arrow appears. Now on the list:
``Eject PC,'' which is what many of you Win98 users would love to
do.
</P>
<P>
   This trick doesn't always work the first time, so please don't
whine about it. I'm very sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay is warning you: Send in
some software tricks or he won't be responsible for what happens.
He can be reached at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com, via snail-mail
at Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101, or
fax: (817) 390-7257. His real name is Michael Gerst, editorial
systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-06-98 1544EST &QL;
