<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-GOLF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER GOLF  
 &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
 CPT- xxnt07 nt08 nt17 nt22 nt26 nt31 nt06 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
raxx nypt   By LONNIE BROWN    
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger    
 c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A friend of mine and I have been playing computer golf for so
long that we have putted on the greens of Leaderboard, an Access
Software title for the now-defunct Commodore 64 and long-retired
Apple computer.
</P>
<P>
   The greens of Leaderboard were flat (and only one color of
green). On the early versions of the mid-1980s, there were
sandtraps and water hazards, but no trees. Back then, a ``software
upgrade'' was the addition of trees along the fairway that looked
as if they'd been cut from a block of wood using crosscut saws.
Adding leaves to the trees and texture to the fairways came a
version or so later.
</P>
<P>
   It was a great game, however. It was the first golf-sim title to
actually give the feeling of playing golf.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Links LS 1999 was released. It had its beginning
with Leaderboard, which has now grown into a game that became the
first and only golf game endorsed by Arnold Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   The new edition offers plenty of new features. St. Andrews is
included on the course list, along with Palmer's Bay Hill Club &AMP;
Lodge, Latrobe Country Club, and Entrada at Snow Canyon. Video
tours of the courses and nearby attractions are included on the
four-disk set. The virtual tour of Palmer's office, workshop and
trophy room at Latrobe also is included.
</P>
<P>
   Latrobe now can be played during the fall, when the leaves are
in full color. Even if you bogey every hole, the trip around the
course is enjoyable for the scenery.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than two dozen new features, including two new
swing options. In addition to the two clicks of the mouse used to
control the swing's power and straightness, a three-click option
has been added. Players can also make shots and putts by moving the
mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Taking something from another golfing program, a ``tournament
environment'' adds spectators to the fairways and allows players to
select the size crowds they want, ranging from a few onlookers to a
throng rivaling Arnie's Army.
</P>
<P>
   Depth of the screens has been improved, giving more of a feel
for looking down a fairway. In addition, overhead objects have been
added, including blimps, airplanes, birds and hot-air balloons that
move across the screen.
</P>
<P>
   A ``caddie book'' gives tips for shooting par on each hole. In
addition, players can now record their own comments (in .WAV files)
and add them to the program.
</P>
<P>
   Access is trying to expand golf play for the Internet, and this
addition of Links includes a real-time voice chat for Internet
play. In addition, the company has set up the LS Tour Web site
(www.LSTour.com) which has live leaderboards and free tournaments
for Internet golfers of varying skill levels.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best features of Links LS 1999 is it takes the
customer into consideration: There are two versions of the product.
One is for people who already have purchased Links LS 1998 and only
need to upgrade. The other is the full version of the program for
the first-time buyer. The full game sells in the $40-$50 range; the
upgrade version is available for about $25-$30.
</P>
<P>
   Cut-Up Time For Kids
</P>
<P>
   Here's a neat little idea for youngsters for a playtime
experience at the computer: Tonka's Workshop (Windows 95/98; about
$40). It's a collection of plastic workshop tools _ saw, plane,
hammer, screwdriver, drill and spray-paint can. They're housed on a
plastic case that straps to the computer's keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   Using a tool causes a key lined up beneath it to be pressed.
Kids use this no-tech interface to help Tonka Joe onscreen as he
guides them through building various projects in his workshop and
performing fix-it chores in the barn, storage shed, pickup truck,
tree house and cellar. It's designed for children ages 3 and older
and works with nearly any keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   While the projects sound complex, building them is not. A few
swipes of saw cuts a sled from a piece of board. Twist the
screwdriver a couple of times and the runners are bolted in place.
Press the spray can lever a few times and the project is complete.
</P>
<P>
   For its oversimplistic approach to the tool shed, Tonka Workshop
has drawn some reviews that imply Hasbro Interactive (the
publishers) should be taken out behind the wood shed. True, the
can't-make-a-mistake world of Tonka Joe's tool bench isn't going to
win any awards from the carpenters down at the union hall who never
had the luxury of an ``undo'' button.
</P>
<P>
   But it's for young kids, for goodness sake, who want to hammer,
pull and twist. The not-so-favorable reviews have come from the
general computing press. The reviews from organizations that cover
children's software specifically have been much more favorable.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the kids seem to enjoy the program, even if saws
never cut a crooked line or threads never strip. The old
carpenter's advice of ``measure twice, cut once,'' need not apply
in Tonka Joe's workshop.
</P>
<P>
   And to a youngster, that's just fine.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call tollfree, 800-400-1352; Web site,
www.hasbro-interactive.com
</P>
<P>
   Who Knows Jack?
</P>
<P>
   The message on the outside of the box containing HeadRush, a
trivia game for the younger generation, says the game is, in so
many words, ``not for geezers.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless the purchaser knows the names of the South Park
characters, along with other timely, seldom worthwhile,
information, he or she might want to consider another trivia game.
</P>
<P>
   This one (Windows/Macintosh; about $30) is from Berkeley
Software, which has a line of trivia software under the ``You Don't
Know Jack'' title. Company officials said the younger crowd was
shying away from the line, which covered ``crusty old '70s
trivia,'' in the words of one company executive.
</P>
<P>
   So the ``You Don't Know Jack'' concept was kept, but given
additional graphics and a ``coolness factor,'' a company
spokeswoman said. It also has more than 550 questions offered in a
variety of formats, and allows three players to compete with each
other or a computer opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Questions are introduced by cartoons. Sessions have a break for
the ``game show'' fictitious sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   And to appeal to the younger audience, the CD contains one audio
track from three bands recording on Mercury Records: Motorbaby, 2
Skinnee J's and Swirl 360.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is The Ledger's associate editor. He can be
reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. His recent computer
columns are on the Internet at
http://www.theledger.com/business/tech/)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
