<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-GINGRICH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JIM WRIGHT IS HAPPY `GENTEEL PERSON' IS TO BE NEW SPEAKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB MAHLBURG 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Former House Speaker Jim Wright of Fort
Worth, who resigned from Congress amid an ethics investigation
pushed by Newt Gingrich, says he's ``happy for the country'' that
Louisianian Bob Livingston will succeed Gingrich as speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be good to have a more genteel person who is not
obsessed with trying to discredit and embarrass others,'' Wright
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Tuesday that he hopes a change in speakers will mean
more civility and tolerance and greater attention to the nation's
problems, rather than what he described as petty scandals and
constant attacks on members of the other party.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, who was visiting Cuba with U.S. Rep. Esteban Torres,
D-Calif., last week when Gingrich announced his decision to step
down, said he cannot recall his reaction to the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not weep,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he sees a sense of justice in Gingrich's
departure, Wright replied: ``I'm not going to gloat over it. I'm
not someone who's interested in carrying on vendettas; I gain no
joy from anyone else's misfortune.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright said he remembers Livingston, who is expected to become
speaker when the House votes Nov. 18, as ``quiet and not flamboyant
and bombastic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for the country that this fellow Bob Livingston is
not mean-spirited,'' he said. ``A number of my Democratic
colleagues on the Appropriations Committee have told me he's a man
with whom you can work and a reasonable person and not obsessed
with trying to discredit and embarrass someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright resigned as speaker in 1989 in what he called a protest
against ``mindless cannibalism'' that he said was paralyzing
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   He decried personal and political attacks leveled against him
during a House investigation into allegations that he violated
congressional rules on outside income.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, who led the assault on Wright, months later became one
of the top Republican leaders in the House and eventually won the
speaker's job.
</P>
<P>
   Wright said he believed that his resignation as speaker would
jolt Congress into being more civilized. But he said that thought
may have been naive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believed that such a dramatic act would shock and shame the
Congress on both sides into restoring the civility which people
like Mr. Gingrich and others had sacrificed,'' Wright said.
``That's why I did it. That's what I expected it to achieve. But it
did not. Conditions only got worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright said political infighting and an emphasis on scandal,
such as President Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky, have
hurt Congress and the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The obsession for months has been over petty scandals rather
than trying to achieve objectives for the country,'' he said. ``I
think everyone has seen that in this last session of Congress.
Members have seemed more intent on discrediting someone in the
other party than \Ron\S achieving a worthwhile objective.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright said he hopes that changing speakers will turn that
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it does, I will feel richly vindicated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of thinking of our colleagues in the other party as
our enemies, we need to be thinking of common solutions to problems
such as education, guaranteeing everyone's right to health care and
preserving the Social Security fund.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright said he had heard rumors for months that support for
Gingrich, a Republican from Georgia, was slipping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in the inner circle these days, but I'm not
surprised,'' he said. ``It became obvious to him that he didn't
have enough votes. It would have been somewhat humiliating, I'm
sure, to go to the well and not have the votes to stay on as
speaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright said he always tried to follow in the mold of his mentor,
Sam Rayburn, a former House speaker and a fellow Texan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember him telling us repeatedly when I was a young member
that the greatest asset of a lawmaker anywhere in the Western world
was the ability to disagree without being disagreeable,'' Wright
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich filed ethics complaints in the late 1980s that led to
the investigation that ended Wright's political career.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, Gingrich became the first speaker in history to
be punished for ethics violations. Lawmakers voted to reprimand
Gingrich and assess a $300,000 penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich acknowledged that he gave ``inaccurate, incomplete and
unreliable'' information to Congress and violated ethics rules by
failing to get legal advice before using tax-exempt charitable
donations for projects that could be considered political.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
