<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGEL-BLUE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABLE MOVIE EXPLORES AFFAIR BETWEEN GROWN MAN, TEEN-AGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By G. ALLEN JOHNSON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sinking back onto the couch in his home, Steven
Kovacs had a confident smile on his face when asked if he courts
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco State University film professor may get his
wish after his film, ``Angel Blue,'' makes its national television
debut Sunday on Lifetime under the title ``My Neighbor's
Daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Sam Bottoms and Lisa Eichhorn and featuring an
appearance by Karen Black, the film is a ``Lolita''-like tale of a
married man in his 40s (Bottoms) who enters into a relationship
with the high school daughter (Yeniffer Behrens) of his good
friend. The $1.1 million film is not a satirical black comedy, as
is Vladimir Nabokov's book, nor is it a film that cautions against
such a relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The affair is depicted almost positively, as if condoning
liaisons where one of the partners is, legally, underage. Behrens,
who was 21 when the film was shot in 1996 but plays a teen-ager of
16 or 17, briefly appears nude in the theatrical version of the
film, which includes a literally steamy sex scene in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Kovacs even included a manifesto, ``The Intolerance of Love,''
in the press kit, in which he states, ``My aim was to present the
moral and emotional complexity of such a relationship. In this
movie the lovers are at fault, but so is society. ... But it is
also an indictment of the contradictions in our culture, at once
youth-crazed and intolerant of young love.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even the sunlight, which poured through the picture windows
of his home overlooking the ocean, could make Kovacs blink when
that statement was read.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an uncomfortable topic,'' Kovacs admitted. ``It's not
just perverse old men who rob the cradle. These affairs happen all
of the time. Many women my age I spoke to were horrified of the
idea (as a film topic). But when I talked to them, all of them had
at least a mentor who was much older, and a number of them had
affairs with older men when they were in their late teens and early
20s.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I decided to stir things up a little bit and to create a
story which seems very middle class, very ordinary, yet it's
troublesome _ and especially troublesome to those who believe in
the sanctity of a home, because it really destroys a home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it seems like I am advocating it, it is only because
general opinion is against it. And I think it is the duty of a
filmmaker, of the writer, to question any belief that a society
has.''
</P>
<P>
   A 52-year-old widower who is raising two daughters, Kovacs said
both his family and his students helped inspire the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's because I have kids, because I teach students, so there's
always that tension there,'' Kovacs said. ``It's one of the oldest
things, relationships between professors and students. So it's all
around, so maybe I'm more aware of it than other people. I think
maybe I began to be aware of teen-agers when my older daughter
reached that age. Maybe that was the inkling for the idea. And
stories about families are important to me, because my family is
very important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The lead character in ``Angel Blue'' is charged with statutory
rape and is fired from his job, throwing a cloud over his unashamed
love for the girl. When asked, Kovacs _ who calls American
attitudes a swinging pendulum between ``hedonistic'' and
``Puritanical'' _ said the age for statutory rape should be lowered
to about 16. Not only does it makes sense, he postulates, but it
brings America more in line with its youth fixations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the ads, and always youth is what's up on
billboards and what's on television,'' he said. ``So we have this
incredible pressure on people and people think of the attractive
sexual, healthy features as being young. Yet there seems to be a
hands-off attitude when it comes to a serious relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Warner, who is vice president for planning, scheduling and
acquisitions at Lifetime, a cable network dedicated to programming
for women, defended the presentation of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would not have bought it and made judicious cuts if it was
not appropriate for Lifetime,'' Warner said by telephone from his
New York office. ``But putting movies on does not mean we take a
position of advocacy. We put movies on that cover all facets, that
really cover the gamut of women's emotions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
