<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A SMALL THE WORLD, DISASTER AND ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The three-room Honduran Consulate in San
Francisco is too small to hold all the love and grief.
</P>
<P>
   In the inner room, the Honduran consul, Ramon Andres-Torres, was
communicating with home by Internet, the only reliable way to get
through. It was his first day on the job.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Hurricane Mitch, he was late arriving. And because of
Hurricane Mitch, his job had changed. He told me his country needs
food, clothing and medicine of all kinds.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle room, Allan Talbott answered unending phone calls,
in Spanish and English, from people who wanted to help survivors of
the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott told callers to drop off goods at San Francisco's
Mission Neighborhood Center, where 500-pound containers are filled
each day to send to Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, trust me, I've been there,'' he told one caller.
``You're going to find a bunch of boys with big smiles on their
faces. I hope those smiles are still there.''
</P>
<P>
   In the outer room, there were lines of people dropping off
checks to the Honduran Relief Fund, and a few people getting
passports to return to Honduras to help their families.
</P>
<P>
   Consular attache Faril Cortez asked Luis Moya where his family
is. Moya named a village on a river near San Pedro Sula in the
north of Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wiped out,'' Cortez said. ``There's nobody there now.''
</P>
<P>
   Moya threw his hands over his face. When he regained his
composure, he left with his friend Rocky Gonzales, and everyone
said, ``Buena suerte.'' Good luck.
</P>
<P>
   Moya and I had just been talking about what we had in common. I
told him that I spent the summer after high school in Honduras
working for a mining company near Danli, in the mountains near
Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   He showed me an old ID card identifying him as a mine mechanic
for a Honduran company. He said, ``Small world.''
</P>
<P>
   Small world. That's what it is. When I was an 18-year-old
working with Honduran miners, I discovered they knew all about
North Americans. After all, Americans owned most of the companies
Hondurans worked for. But the average American knew nothing about
Hondurans.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, in 1964, miners were paid a dollar a day for a
12-hour day of hand-drilling with hammers and bits, using their
teeth to crimp blasting caps onto fuses.
</P>
<P>
   On days off, my Yanqui friends and I would take horseback rides
in the mountains, where families gave us tortillas hot off griddles
and coffee brewed in cans. One tiny dirt-floored home, dozens of
miles from the nearest road, had a portrait of John F. Kennedy
looking down from the wall.
</P>
<P>
   For years thereafter I tried to find stories about Honduras in
the New York Times. The newspaper carried about one story out of
Honduras a year, except during the contra war.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly that's changed, but for how long?
</P>
<P>
   ``We just talked about that,'' Cortez said. ``We're afraid
people will forget about us in a few days or weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Cortez was opening piles of envelopes containing checks made out
to the Honduran Relief Fund (c/o Honduran Consulate, 870 Market
St., San Francisco, CA 94102). He said the response to the disaster
in his country was astonishing, with one woman even writing a check
for $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Cortez was sending back receipts and thank-you notes in Spanish
and English. The last sentence is sweet and gracious in the
Honduran manner: ``We thank you and we hope God compensates you a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The devastation caused by Hurricane Mitch in Honduras,
Guatemala, El Salvador and Nicaragua has caused an unprecedented
outpouring of generosity.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines that serve Central America, such as American and TACA,
have volunteered to fly donated food, clothing and medicine.
Doctors have headed to Central America, including my father's
doctor on Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   Churches have opened their doors for donations, and they've
poured in. The Rev. Wayne Campbell, pastor of St. Felicitas
Catholic Church in San Leandro, Calif., donated all of Sunday's
collection to Catholic Relief Services to help the people of
Central America. Parishioners gave $21,000, twice the usual Sunday
donation. One woman wrote a check for $4,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really heart-warming,'' said Campbell, who devoted
Sunday's homily to the devastation in Central America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked about my own struggle with last week's events,'' he
said. ``There was the election, and the vast amount of money spent
on it. There was the space flight, the meaning of which I don't
understand. Then there was this terrible thing in Central America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have used my remote to skip over it, but it really
bothered me. I basically said how lucky we were not to be born
there.''
</P>
<P>
   These very poor, now ruined countries are not so far away. Like
the man said, small world.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
