<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-LAW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU'RE GAME, YOU CAN LEARN WORKPLACE LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Believe it or not, you can discuss workplace law
without either mentioning President Clinton or making it drier than
a Windex martini. You can even make a game out of it, which is what
a San Francisco company did.
</P>
<P>
   Employment Law Training Inc. has created Winning Through
Prevention, a Trivial Pursuit-type game designed to help companies
avoid being pursued in some not-so-trivial court cases. The game is
easy to tailor to a company's needs, inexpensive enough for a small
business and, best of all, it helps you understand workplace law by
using human examples, not words like ``thus'' and ``whereas.''
</P>
<P>
   Suppose someone gets hurt by a violent co-worker. He might be
able to sue the co-worker and the company, of course, but who else?
The property owner? The security company? The attacker's previous
employer? Yes, yes and yes.
</P>
<P>
   The property owner and security company could be sued if they
didn't do enough to prevent a potentially dangerous situation. And
the previous employer could be sued if he knew about the violent
tendencies and still provided a positive reference.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical game, players are in small teams; ideally, each
team has members of both sexes and people with different lines of
authority. Their answers move them around the game board,
struggling to earn the title of Team Leader of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   The game comes with 300 questions in 15 categories, such as
employee privacy, preventing sexual harassment and improving
performance evaluations. It normally takes a couple of hours, but
can be shortened or lengthened.
</P>
<P>
   The legal expertise comes from Littler Mendelson, a firm
specializing in employment law, which has become a booming
business. Nearly 1,500 workplace-related lawsuits or claims are
filed nationwide in a typical day.
</P>
<P>
   Because the questions are in categories, it's easy to tailor the
game to different workers. Certain categories are for everyone;
others are aimed at managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jodie applies for a job with Stop-and-Go Corp.,'' one question
says. ``As part of her pre-employment screening, may the company
require her to submit to a medical examination?
</P>
<P>
   ``A. Yes, if the examination is job-related and consistent with
business necessity.
</P>
<P>
   ``B. Yes, but only if the examination is conducted during
business hours and is paid for by the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``C. No, unless the examination is required for insurance
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``D. Yes, but only if the examination is performed by a member
of the same sex as the employee.
</P>
<P>
   ``E. No, a pre-employment medical examination is not
permissible.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams briefly discuss the potential answers, then decide.
Sometimes the debates get loud; after all, the title of Team Leader
of the Year is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   In Jodie's case, E is the ``most correct'' answer, as the game
puts it (you can't escape lawyers completely). Because of the
Americans With Disabilities Act, pre-employment medical exams are
pretty much out the window.
</P>
<P>
   Bosses can ask whether potential employees can perform essential
duties, and they can make job offers contingent on passing a
physical _ as long as they require the exam for all entering
applicants for a particular job, not just those who appear to be
disabled.
</P>
<P>
   The game sells for $99, strategic marketing consultant Cathy
Blagden says. An optional $799 Training Edition lets up to 200
people play and has such extras as a facilitator's guide that
explains the answers more thoroughly, and discs and slides that
help the facilitator present the game to large groups.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My only concern is that employers need to view the game in
context. It provides the legally correct steps to take, but
sometimes those could lead to problems.
</P>
<P>
   One question, for example, describes a company that prohibits
overtime without advance authorization. So what does it do when an
employee works overtime without authorization? The ``most correct''
answer is to pay the overtime and discipline the employee for
violating company policy. Paying the overtime is required by law,
and if you simply remind the employee that future overtime must be
approved in advance, you could set yourself up for trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``If an employer is inconsistent if its enforcement of the
policy,'' the game warns, ``the employer may not be able to rely on
the policy to justify an employee's termination when it needs to do
so.''
</P>
<P>
   So if you're a boss, now you know the correct legal step. But
what if the discipline turns an enthusiastic employee into a
cynical one? What if the discipline makes it absolutely certain
that no one will ever work overtime again, even when the
circumstances call for it? Is the legal protection worth it?
</P>
<P>
   Winning Through Prevention offers all sorts of valuable lessons,
as long as you remember that common sense is still the best
teacher.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the career search editor at the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120; e-mail:
murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
