r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-THRILLERS-HNS &LR;      11-11 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-THRILLERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAVER'S `COFFIN DANCER' IS THE THRILLER OF THE YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBIE HESS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you read only one thriller this year, make it Jeffery
Deaver's extraordinary ``The Coffin Dancer'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
$25, 358 pages).
</P>
<P>
   Quadriplegic Lincoln Rhyme is the world's top analyst of
criminal evidence. Five years ago, two of Rhyme's assistants were
killed by a bomb planted at a crime scene by a professional hit man
known as ``The Coffin Dancer.'' The only victim who lived long
enough to give a description told of a tattoo on the killer's arm
depicting the Grim Reaper dancing with a woman in front of a
coffin.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the feds believe the Coffin Dancer is back. A congressional
aide tied to an arms deal is killed in Washington. A pilot who was
a key witness in a case against a powerful arms dealer is blown out
of the sky. Two other witnesses, the pilot's wife, Percey Clay, and
her co-pilot, Brit Hale, are put in protective custody. The New
York City police, the FBI, Rhyme and his beautiful red-headed
assistant Amelia Sachs must keep Clay and Hale alive for 45 hours
so the two can testify Monday morning against the arms dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Rhyme knows that the Coffin Dancer is the consummate planner and
will do anything to eliminate his targets _ once he cut off the
hands of a victim, skinned the hands and used the skins as gloves
at another murder scene.
</P>
<P>
   Deaver has constructed a compelling page-turner that is almost
impossible to put down. The tension mounts as the clock ticks down
to Monday morning and the bodies pile up. Rhyme is brilliant in
figuring out what the Coffin Dancer will do next, but the Dancer
always seems to be just a step ahead of Rhyme.
</P>
<P>
   The plot twists are amazing, yet never out of place in this
thriller full of intriguing characters and crafty detective work.
``The Coffin Dancer'' is terrific.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (``The Hammer of Eden.'' By Ken Follett. Crown Publishers.
$25.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Follett's latest thriller may be a little far-fetched, but it
sure is fun to read.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office has decided to build a dam, thus flooding
a valley in Northern California. Members of a small cult who live
in the valley and grow grapes decide to fight back. Led by Priest,
the Hammer of Eden calls a radio station and threatens to create a
man-made earthquake if the governor doesn't back down.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the governor's office nor the San Francisco FBI office
believes the threat, but it has to be investigated. A new
supervisor unfairly assigns FBI agent Judy Maddox to check it out.
Meanwhile, Priest and his lover go to Texas and steal a seismic
vibrator _ ``a machine designed to detect oil on a seismically
volatile fault.''
</P>
<P>
   After the cult sets off a small quake in an isolated valley,
Maddox contacts seismologist Michael Quercus, who has developed a
theory of how to locate stress points along fault lines where
earthquakes are likely to occur. Unknown to him, his estranged wife
has joined up with Priest and stolen Quercus' research to use in
selecting where to place the seismic vibrator to cause the most
damage.
</P>
<P>
   After a second quake causes massive destruction south of San
Francisco, Maddox and Quercus rush to find the perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hammer of Eden'' spends too much time developing the history
of the cult, but when the action starts, the tale is driven by plot
and unique characters. Priest is one of the better villains of
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (``The Hanging Garden.'' By Ian Rankin. St. Martin's Press.
$24.95. 333 pages.)
</P>
<P>
   Rankin's latest Scottish police procedural featuring Detective
Inspector John Rebus is a rich probe of the dark underpinnings of
the criminal mind.
</P>
<P>
   Rebus has been assigned to investigate a suspected war criminal
responsible for wiping out a French village in World War II. But
when war breaks out between Tommy Telford's and Big Gar Cafferty's
gangs in Edinburgh, Rebus is drawn into the investigation. Telford
is into drug running, prostitution and just about anything that
brings him an illegal buck. He has close ties to Mr. Pink Eyes, a
brutal gangster who is smuggling refugees into Scotland to work as
prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   When Rebus tries to protect a young Bosnian prostitute, his
daughter is the victim of a hit-and-run-accident that Rebus is sure
Telford ordered. Now Rebus will do anything to bring Telford down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hanging Garden'' is a very dark and gritty read that never
disappoints. Rankin's character development is first rate and the
dialogue rings true. Somehow, Rankin adeptly juggles seemingly
disparate plot lines into realistic tale of war against organized
crime.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (``As Time Goes By.'' By Michael Walsh. Warner Books. $25. 417
pages.)
</P>
<P>
   It takes a lot of guts to write a sequel to ``Casablanca,'' and
author Michael Walsh almost pulls it off.
</P>
<P>
   As the Lisbon plane disappears in the distance, Rick and Louie
walk to the end of the airfield where Sam is waiting with Rick's
Buick convertible. Rick tells Sam to step on it, ``we've got to
make Port Lyautey by daybreak.'' The plan is to avoid the Gestapo
and catch a plane to Lisbon and hook up with Ilsa and Victor. Of
course on the drive to Port Lyautey, they are chased by the
Gestapo, but the Nazis are all killed in the shootout.
</P>
<P>
   When Rick, Louis and Sam get to Lisbon, they discover Ilsa and
Victor have left for London. The three eventually make contact and
agree to join Victor's plan to kill Reinhard Heydrich in Prague.
</P>
<P>
   In flashbacks, we learn how Rick hooked up with a Jewish mobster
in New York, and why he had to flee.
</P>
<P>
   The dialogue really sounds like the movie dialogue, and you
picture the cast of ``Casablanca'' as the tale progresses. But ``As
Time Goes By'' really calls out for a less happy and less
predictable ending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 1234EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
