A5046 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN12-COX     11-11 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: What those old oaks whisper
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Dreamsville is an occasional series in which readers share
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   From little acorns grow mighty oaks, and some mighty fine
memories, too. Here's a story from Tony Garrett of Mesquite, Texas:
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're afraid of bridges, you'll never make it to
Whispering Oaks in East Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only one way across Lake Tawakoni, the Two-Mile
Bridge, once considered the longest bridge in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's worth the effort. When you finally hit the east side
you'll see the small neighborhood of Whispering Oaks, where I lived
with my grandparents in the 1960s and 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather, G.W. Roseman, drew the plans for the house he
had built there, and if there ever was a perfect lake house, rustic
but with modern conveniences, this was it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside, the house was rough cedar and looked like a lake
house should look. Inside, the walls were knotty pine, the big
kitchen had an L-shaped bar built around it and the fireplace ran
the entire length of the living room, crowned with a gun rack from
which a variety of aging weapons dangled.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go back today to the little park at the far end of the
lake, memories are everywhere. This is the same park where my
grandfather and I sat in his big white Buick and talked for hours
while listening to the car radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my favorite country singer, Don Gibson, came on, he would
let me crank up the volume until the music rattled the car windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved it when we would go for long drives together, never
really going anywhere, just riding around through the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandmother would take my sister and me swimming every day
during the summer. Afterwards, we would visit the nearby store for
a corny dog, or cross the bridge for barbecue sandwiches and ice
cold bottles of Coke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small, underpowered motorcycles were popular at that time, and
I acquired a Honda 90 as did some of my buddies. We'd blast around
Whispering Oaks, making too much noise and ripping through the
woods when the mood struck us.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me a while to get up the nerve to ask Judy Morris to
go for a ride with me, and even longer to find the courage to try
to kiss her. But after burning a month's worth of gas, I felt I had
earned the right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never attempt two things at once on a motorcycle. We were
riding along when suddenly I turned around and kissed her _ and in
the process, veered from the road and ran over a mailbox.
</P>
<P>
   ``She stormed off, heading home on foot and swearing she would
never ride with me again. Personally, I thought the whole
experience was the most romantic venture of my young life. Maybe
Judy did, too. Eventually, she rode with me again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Whispering Oaks is so important to me because I had so
many `firsts' there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judy Morris was the first girl I ever kissed (and the last one
I ever kissed from a moving motorcycle.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I drove my first car there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I built my first tree house in the big oak down by the lake.
When I couldn't sleep I'd sneak out of my bedroom, climb up into
the tree house and watch the moon rise over the lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned to swim in Lake Tawakoni.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wore my first pair of bell bottoms to a party there in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned to play the guitar there, all alone in my room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned to catch a pass in Gary Jensen's yard while playing
touch football.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather taught me how to fish there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw war for the first time there, every night on the TV
news.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I saw death up close when my grandfather died in the house
he drew the plans for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last time I drove through Whispering Oaks, three things came
to mind:
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss my grandfather as much now as the day he died.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't play Don Gibson on the radio much anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I wonder who Judy Morris is running into mailboxes with
these days.''
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story you'd like to share, send it to
Dreamsville, c/o Joe Murray, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin, Texas 75915.
If your story is used, you will receive $25.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
