<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORACLE-MICROSOFT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORACLE CHIEF URGES BREAKUP OF MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Larry Ellison, the brash visionary of Oracle
Corp., said he believed the Justice Department should break up the
Microsoft Corp. for violating antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a question of did Microsoft break the law,'' Ellison
said Tuesday. ``The question is, `Why did a smart group of people
break the law over and over again?' I think the answer is the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Microsoft's monopoly in the software industry has
quashed the efforts of other high-tech companies, including Oracle,
to gain a greater share of the software market. He theorized that
the exploding use of the Internet prompted Redmond, Wash.-based
Microsoft to ``damage'' other companies that develop tools for the
World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft chief Bill Gates ``says, `All we ask for is the
opportunity to innovate,''' Ellison said. ``But Microsoft is not an
innovator. It's one of the great copiers of the world. ... They
copied database stuff from us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellison made his remarks to reporters during the Oracle
OpenWorld, a four-day conference being held in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is on trial in Washington in an antitrust case brought
by the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   At the Oracle OpenWorld, Ellison delivered a keynote address
that touted the virtues of Oracle 8i, the company's new Internet
software application. Ellison said creating databases on the
Internet is the future for all businesses, from the smallest to the
largest.
</P>
<P>
   He said traditional client-server software, or networks of many
PCs connected to one central computer, is becoming obsolete because
it doesn't consolidate information well enough and doesn't make the
information accessible to every worker in a company.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Ellison said: ``Internet computing uses standard
browsers and everyone in a company can use the network. ... Imagine
you're a doctor. Do you want to buy a server and teach your
receptionist how to use it when you can go to the Web and use an
accounting program for free for six months?''
</P>
<P>
   Ellison also said Internet computing helps companies
dramatically reduce their costs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his criticism of Gates and Microsoft, Ellison said he
wouldn't mind having the company's market dominance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to the day Oracle is so dominant we have a
monopoly and are regulated by the government,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 1316EST &QL; 
