u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-LIVINGSTON-BOS &LR;      11-11 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-LIVINGSTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVINGSTON SEEN AS `A MAN OF PROCESS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He opposes abortion, supports anti-union
legislation, and wrote the ``three strikes'' bill to jail repeated
felons. He is a military hawk who crusades for a Star Wars-style
missile-defense system. He wants lower taxes and a smaller
government.
</P>
<P>
   And yet Representative Bob Livingston of Louisiana, who appears
to have sewn up the race to succeed House Speaker Newt Gingrich, is
not considered a leading conservative by many lobbying groups on
the political right.
</P>
<P>
   In short, he is conservative but not dogmatic. Where Gingrich is
a self-described revolutionary, whose bows to the most conservative
members sometimes tied the House in knots, Livingston is seen as a
man who will not let his deeply held beliefs override the orderly
process of governing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a man of process and believes that the procedures of the
House are to be richly observed,'' said Representative Joseph
McDade, a Pennsylvania Republican who serves on the House
Appropriations Committee that Livingston chairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is as conservative as Gingrich is,'' said Representative J.
Joseph Moakley, the South Boston Democrat. ``The difference is not
on substance. We're talking about style here.'' While Gingrich saw
many bills vetoed by the White House, ``Bob knows that to get a
bill through, he's got to make some concessions.''
</P>
<P>
   For those reasons, such socially conservative groups as the
Christian Coalition and the Family Research Council say they like
Livingston's ideals, but they wish he pushed the issues harder. A
leading group of fiscal conservatives, the National Taxpayers
Union, also urges Livingston to work harder for tax and spending
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would view a Speaker Livingston as a flag-carrier who would
need plenty of reinforcement from the rear,'' said Pete Sepp of the
taxpayers' group.
</P>
<P>
   As speaker, Robert Linlithgow Livingston, 55, would be second in
line to the presidency, after only the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   He is a former New Orleans lawyer and former federal prosecutor.
For four years, he has played a central role in Congress as
chairman of the House Appropriations Committee, which controls more
than one-third of the $1.7 trillion federal budget. It is a role
that has forced him to navigate conflicting currents within the
House, from budget-cutting conservatives to influential Democrats.
Both are often needed to build a winning bloc of votes for
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues say he handled the task with good cheer. When first
given the chairmanship in 1995 by Gingrich, who had passed over
three more-senior committee members, Livingston brought an
alligator-skinning knife to meetings to show his commitment to
budget cutting. He is known for leading meetings while standing up,
his lanky 6-foot-4-inch frame showing he is firmly in control of
the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's almost to say, `I'm here. I'm in charge. If you've got
a problem, bring it to me,' '' said Hunter Ridgway, chief of staff
to Representative John Olver, the Amherst Democrat on the
Appropriations Committee. ``He shows a good combination of
authority and diplomacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Several times, Livingston has helped host ceremonies for the
Silvio Conte Joy of Politics Award, named after the former
Massachusetts congressmen and given to people who practice a
gracious style of politics.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1996 dinner, Livingston presented history buff and former
Oregon Senator Mark Hatfield with an ``original'' letter to Ulysses
S. Grant by Abraham Lincoln _ then made a show of ``accidentally''
spilling his drink on the document. Hatfield was horrified, until
it dawned on him that Livingston played a prank.
</P>
<P>
   In recent comments on the possible impeachment of President
Clinton, Livingston said that lawmakers need to weigh the public's
apparent opposition to impeachment in deciding how to proceed. He
appeared to be more conciliatory than Gingrich, who has insisted
that Congress not be swayed by public opinion in the impeachment
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   But on other matters, Livingston has sided with Gingrich. ``I
can't think of a single issue on which they disagreed,'' said Ralph
Helman, lead House lobbyist for the National Federation of
Independent Business, a small-business group.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston earned a perfect 100 percent on the last Christian
Coalition scorecard, meaning he sided with the group on all major
issues. He co-sponsored bills to ban ``partial birth'' abortions
and to make English the official language of the United States. He
signed onto a plan to abolish the tax code by the year 2000, which
might force Congress to replace it with something better.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston also authored the ``three strikes'' bill that
requires life sentences for defendants in federal cases convicted
of a third violent felony. He backs the right of workers to opt out
of union membership at unionized workplaces, a measure strongly
opposed by organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   A powerful friend of the oil and shipbuilding industries in his
home state of Louisiana, Livingston also claims credit for steep
budget cuts over the past few years. He wants to eliminate
inheritance taxes and close the Commerce and Energy Departments,
positions that win him praise from fiscal conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the National Taxpayers Union faults Livingston, as well
as Gingrich, for failing to enact those longstanding proposals into
law. ``That's been the problem for three years now. We've got lots
of great legislation, but there's not enough follow-through,'' said
Sepp of the taxpayer group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
