<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-DUNN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON'S DUNN SEEKS POST OF HOUSE MAJORITY LEADER  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Jennifer B. Dunn is making a run for history.
</P>
<P>
   Known as a unifier and facilitator, the representative from
Washington state wants to be the first female House majority
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn's timing is excellent. Known as the party's point person on
women's issues, she has cultivated a moderate image without losing
her conservative credentials and is well positioned to take
advantage of the disarray in the Republican leadership following
Newt Gingrich's resignation as speaker last week.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing her bid for majority leader, Dunn is challenging
two white males who are buttoned-up, bare-knuckled conservatives.
The congresswoman is regarded as neither visionary nor brilliant as
a strategist, but her colleagues say she is a ferocious
sweet-talker with impeccable political instincts, and a knack for
striking deals and smoothing feathers.
</P>
<P>
   Such qualities are in such short supply in the fractious world
of congressional politics that political observers said Dunn may be
the antidote to a party on the verge of ``cannibalizing itself,''
as Gingrich put it last week.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn is the latest member to challenge the majority leader, Dick
Armey of Texas, who has been criticized by some as having
lackluster leadership skills. Still, Armey has the support of many
of his colleagues and his office said he is close to getting the
votes he needs to maintain his leadership role.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Steve Largent of Oklahoma, a football Hall of
Famer, entered the race Friday afternoon, hours before Gingrich
announced his resignation and threw open the leadership races.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Foreman, chairman of Washington State Republican Party,
said of Dunn: ``She's just right for the job. She's a woman. She's
smart. And she's experienced in dealing with rancorous internal
party debates and still presenting a positive vision.''
</P>
<P>
   In her role as state party chairman for 11 years, Dunn
successfully fought off repeated attempts to unseat her as state
Republicans debated gay rights, abortion rights, and other
hot-button issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miraculously, she was able to keep both her job and both sides
talking, exactly the qualities she'll need as majority leader,''
Foreman added.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Slade Gorton, a Washington Republican, said Dunn's
political skills helped distinguish her with Republican leaders
during her first term. By her third term, she was vice chairman of
the House Republican Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn rode the ``Year of the Woman'' wave into Congress in 1992.
However, the single mother of two boys _ one named Reagan, after
the former president _ lost support of liberal and moderate women's
groups with a series of unpopular votes, including one against the
Family and Medical Leave Act, which guaranteed time off from work
for new parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jennifer Dunn is a very articulate, sensible member with a
real opportunity to be the next majority leader,'' said
Representative Christopher Shays of Connecticut, a moderate who has
not yet committed to a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn, however, has not fooled Republican moderates into
believing she will be their ally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's be clear: None of the moderates consider Dunn a
moderate,'' said a congressional staff member who asked not to be
named. ``The reason they'd be inclined to support her is because
she is a woman and she's vaguely pro-choice. And Largent is to the
right of her.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn is considered to be generally in favor of abortion rights,
but she voted against funding for international family planning
efforts that included abortion, and for efforts to ban
``partial-birth'' abortions as well as RU-486, the so-called
abortion pill.
</P>
<P>
   Groups, including Republicans for Choice, are thrilled at the
prospect of seeing Dunn rise in the leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great that the Republican Party has finally
evolved to a point that they have competent women who can run on
the basis of their competence and not their sex,'' noted Barbara
Ledeen, executive director of the Women's Independent Forum, a
conservative women's Washington think tank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 1320EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
