<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5063 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEFORESTATION-FLOODS-     11-11 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEFORESTATION-FLOODS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFORESTATION WORSENED MITCH'S TOLL, FORESTERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras _ Just about everyone agrees that
Hurricane Mitch was the worst natural disaster in Central America
in decades. But now scientists are arguing that humans made the
devastation even worse.
</P>
<P>
   Clear-cutting logging, hillside farms and rampant housing
developments exacerbated mudslides and floods, the experts say. The
damage was most extreme in Honduras, where loggers and farmers have
stripped away about 225,000 acres of forests every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hurricane was a natural disaster but it was worsened by
the action of man's deforestation,'' said Dr. Carlos Medina, a
physician and biologist who served as the country's first
environmental minister from 1992-96.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists fear that the desperate need to provide jobs
and housing for hundreds of thousands of displaced people may
prompt Central Americans to and chop down more of their forests and
build on precarious hillsides and riverbanks.
</P>
<P>
   Mitch, which left bilions of dollars of destruction, at one
point was a ``Category 5'' hurricane, the fiercest known. Medina
and others agree that even if forests had been intact, Honduras and
neighboring countries would not have been protected from surging
rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers for the Peace Corps, which has sent dozens of
conservation experts to Honduras in the last few years, reported
that clear-cut areas were devastated by mud and avalanches. Reports
from farmers to the California-based Sustainable Harvest Coffee Co.
indicate that Mitch barely had an impact on small, experimental
``shade-grown'' plantations that mix coffee with traditional trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, a lot of places where they had clear-cut,
the soil structure collapsed and the plants have literally slipped
down the slope,'' said Dave Griswold, founder of the importing
company.
</P>
<P>
   A helicopter flight over central Honduras last week showed that
heavily forested areas were relatively unscathed. But regions where
trees had been plundered and (itals)colonias(unitals), or slums,
had sprouted on hills were denuded. Even the houses had tumbled
into rivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of those mudslides could have been avoided if people had
not built colonias there,'' said Patricia Panting, executive
director or Pro-Lena, a non-governmental group in Tegucigalpa that
tries to preserve forests. Bruce Cabarle, director of global forest
programs for the World Wildlife Fund, called the settlements
``disasters waiting to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists say the plundering of Central America's
forests has been staggering in recent years. In mountaineous
Honduras, the thin topsoil quickly washes away in a regular rainy
season _ and Mitch dumped a year's worht of rain on Honduras in
less than a week.
</P>
<P>
   A survey by the UN Food and Agricultural Organization in 1990
found that 41 percent of Honduras was forested in 1990. Only five
years later, the FAO said that 35 percent of the country was
forested, and environmental groups say those figures are overly
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   In a report prepared before Mitch and released last week, the
Central American Commission on Environment and Development
suggested deforestation was imperiling prosperity. The report had
been compiled before the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly if you cut down forests on hillsides, you increase
the vulnerability to sliding _ that's been demonstrated all over
the world,'' said Edward A. Parson, an associate professor who
specializes in international environmental policy at Harvard's John
F. Kennedy School of Government.
</P>
<P>
   At the United Nations Foundation, set up by Ted Turner, experts
said that Mitch was reminiscent of floods in China and Bangladesh
this year. Blaming clear-cutting, along with other factors, China
laid off tens of thousands of loggers. Bangladesh conceded that
ruinous environmental practices had worsened the flooding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, there are some ecological underpinnings to many of
these natural disasters,'' said Ian Bowles, a vice president of
another group, Conservatation International.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech in Washington Tuesday, James Lee Witt, director of
the Federal Emergency Management Agency, said the United States,
too, must curb construction projects in flood-prone areas. ``We
need to protect or flood plains, our wetlands that act in nature as
sponges ... and not fill them in for redevelopment or
development,'' Witt said. ``The truth is we can prevent people from
becoming disaster victims and protect our environment at the same
time.''
</P>
<P>
   In many developing countries, including Honduras, those who
speak out against clear-cutting risk their lives. Just a few weeks
ago, in the small town of Catacomas, a self-taught
environmentalist, Carlos Luna, was gunned down in front of his
family, according to colleagues from Honduras and the United
States. Luna had decried logging in what is supposed to be a
pristine ecological ``buffer zone'' in the mountains outside of the
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Private companies, some with ties to former Honduran army
officers, are behind the logging, environmentalists say.
</P>
<P>
   At the US State Department, a new office coordinates efforts to
preserve the environment in developing countries. But a State
Department officials say they have not spoken with Central American
leaders about what appears to be mankind's complicity with
Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a delicate thing to raise at the moment,'' one US
official said. ``You want to focus on assisting the victims, not
blaming them for deforestation.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from detecting a new attitude in Central America,
development workers say that they hear of plans for more clear
cutting. Lumber sales will give villages quick infusions of cash
and newly-opened fields will offer fresh topsoil for planting corn
and beans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad thing is that to recover from this catastrophe, they
will probably deforest Honduras even more,'' said Helen Mills, a
Peace Corps volunteer from Riverside, Calif.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 1322EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
