<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5065 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAITI-CONSUL-ART-BOS &LR;      11-11 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-CONSUL-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAITI'S CONSUL LOOKS TO THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANCIE LATOUR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The soft punch of a stapler and the buzz of climate
control were the only muted sounds emanating from the office of
Boston's Haitian Consulate, tucked away at the end of a hall in an
office building in Copley Square.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the recently appointed consul general, Andrine Constant,
was quietly trying to solve a problem: how to arrange to ship the
tons of clothes, food, and other donations that had flooded her
office and other agencies in response to devastation left by
Hurricane Georges &UR;  &LR; in September.
</P>
<P>
   As Constant's voice melded with the hum of multiple phone lines
and the polite greetings from the lobby, there was no trace of the
chaos that ushered in the last consul, or the clashes that defined
a place Haitians here once viewed as the spying outpost of a brutal
dictator.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, scores of angry Haitians led a demonstration to the
doorstep of the consulate, shaking high fists and crying for the
overthrow of longtime Haitian dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier. Days
later, after Duvalier fled in exile, Haitians stormed the office,
destroying furniture, burning flags, and demanding to install local
activist Jean Geneus as consul and eject the man who had been
Duvalier's representative in Boston for years, Wesner Chamoine.
</P>
<P>
   Now, more than a decade after the unrest, Constant said her
mission is to continue and expand on the changes begun by Geneus,
who saw the diplomatic post through the turmoil and created a
consulate for Haitians to use, not fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to build an office that is honest and really serves
people, not one that does business like Haiti, where you have to
bribe someone to get anything done,'' said Constant, 32, who served
as vice consul under Geneus for four years. ``I want to be a
catalyst for helping to get people to come together, and ... also
be looking to the larger diplomatic community and all friends of
Haiti.''
</P>
<P>
   The first woman to run the New England-based consulate since it
was established in the early 1980s, Constant is a trained physician
and a single mother to 6-year-old daughter Anais; the two live in
suburban Malden. Constant spent her own childhood in the small
southern coastal town of Les Cayes, the oldest of three siblings
and the daughter of teachers who she said taught her the meaning of
discipline and hard work.
</P>
<P>
   Since her appointment last month, an onslaught of demands has
kept Constant focused on the immediate, pressing needs of Haitians
at home and in Massachusetts, which has the third-largest
population of Haitians in the United States. Besides working on
hurricane relief, she helped coordinate protests after a stinging
joke about Haitians and AIDS in the Hollywood movie ``How Stella
Got Her Groove Back'' erupted into controversy and demonstrations
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   But the consulate she imagines is one that ultimately promotes
Haitian art, encourages Haitian business owners to expand, and
looks at the complex, internal problems that have stifled Haiti's
economic and social progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as Haitians need to take responsibility for our future and
for what we do. We have to be able to build institutions and have
professionals who are willing to play by the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Constant fled Haiti in 1994, as then-president Jean-Bertrand
Aristide remained in exile after he was overthrown in a 1991 coup.
After 28 years living in her homeland _ the last six of those years
studying in medical school and working as a women's activist _ she
abandoned her childhood dream to practice medicine in her own
country and joined relatives in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never planned to come and live here,'' Constant said. ``When
the coup happened, I thought it was going to last maybe days. I was
always expecting things were going to get back to normal. But they
never did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
