   EDITORS, attention features, technology page editors:
</P>
<P>
   Here is a list of selected computer-related stories from the
past week from  &UR; The N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  and its partners.
</P>
<P>
   These stories are being repeated with a distinguishing ``CPT''
in the slugline and an ``a'' general news category code.
</P>
<P>
   Similar stories planned for Thursday's New York Times will be
listed on  &UR; BC-CIRCUITS-BUDGET-NYT &LR; , moving later this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT (Undated) _ Microsoft Corp. does not go
softly into hardware. When it decides to enter a hardware niche, it
typically has a good reason. The rise of graphical user interfaces
like the Windows shell demanded a mouse, and Microsoft is now the
big cheese in computer mice. By Peter H. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ As the recent national
elections proved, there's a lot to be said for incumbency. Same
thing in the tech trade, though around here we have a suitably
clunky term for it. We call it ``the first-mover advantage.'' Win
this bit of technological high ground and you'll probably stay
there for quite awhile. By Hiawatha Bray.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX (Undated) Technoweenies need to
roam, too. Computer Q&AMP;A by Dr. Emilio Bombay.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS-MACOS-BOS (Undated) _ While speech recognition
software is available for the Mac, it doesn't have the power of
Naturally Speaking. By Simson Garfinkle.
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT-COX (Atlanta) _ OS 8.5, the latest version of the
Apple Computer operating system, represents another incremental
step forward for the Mac. By and large, OS 8.5 is a collection of
small but important tweaks. The one exception is a potentially
important new technology called Sherlock. It's a search engine that
replaces the Mac's aging Find application. But more on that later.
By Bill Husted.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE-COX (Atlanta) _ For folks who don't often cook or are
more used to zapping the night's dinner in the microwave,
Thanksgiving dinner for kinfolks can be a traumatic experience.
Truth is, the traditional Thanksgiving meal is an easy one to cook.
And the Internet's World Wide Web offers plenty of help with
recipes and suggestions, even with ideas about what to do with all
the leftovers. By Bill Husted.
</P>
<P>
   TECHTOOLS-COX (Atlanta) _ All Hallow's Eve has come and gone,
I'm gorged with candy scarfed up before those annoying little
trick-or-treaters could get it, and the ghost still resides in my
computer, turning it on at midnight every night. Since I reported
this phenomenon, I've received several kindly suggestions from
readers. By Jack Warner.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY-COX (Atlanta) _ For the first time in nearly two
years, I hooked my ham radio station up to an antenna and _ in just
seconds _ I was 13 years old again. By Bill Husted.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ASSESS-NYT (Undated) _ As its antitrust trial moves
into the fourth week, Microsoft Corp. finds itself trying to
deflect a flood of charges of threats and bribes. The litany of
shameful misconduct, according to the government, was directed not
only at Microsoft's rivals but just about everyone in the industry
_ including personal computer makers, Internet service suppliers
and others. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-TECH-NYT (San Francisco) _ A new technology intended to
replace the traditional home videocassette recorder is expected to
get an important vote of confidence on Monday with the announcement
that a co-founder of Netscape Communications Corp. has invested in
one of two companies developing digital television recording
systems. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-RESIGN-NYT (Washington) _ Ira Magaziner, the author of
the Clinton administration's ill-fated national health plan, who
most recently has led government efforts to foster the growth of
the Internet and electronic commerce, said Friday that he would
leave the White House before the end of the year. By Jeri Clausing.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-TRAVEL-AZR (Undated) _ They're the window shoppers of the
online world, and they're giving the Internet travel industry fits.
Maybe you're one of them _ a traveler who checks out the online
travel agencies in search of a low fare or hotel bargain but never
clicks the ``Buy now'' button. By Dawn Gilbertson.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTINGQ&AMP;A-SFCHRON (Undated) _ What's the true status with
online security these days? Is it good enough so I don't have to
worry about giving my credit card number online? By David Einstein.
</P>
<P>
   TEENS-ONLINE-NYT (Undated) _ In the age of the household with a
computer and multiple phone lines, the teen-ager who years ago
would have secreted herself away in the closet with her Princess
phone now has vastly expanded communications, thanks to America
Online or other instant-message services. By Catherine Greenman.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS (Undated) _ Computer Q&AMP;A. By Dwight
Silverman.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS (Undated) _ Forget the phrase ``browser
wars.'' When it comes to creating software used to surf the World
Wide Web, Netscape Communications Corp. and Microsoft Corp. are
playing a game of leapfrog. Now it's Netscape's turn to hop ahead.
By Dwight Silverman.
</P>
<P>
   EROTICA-PROFILE-NYT (Undated) _ Let it simply be said that Mark
Tiarra works most days in a nondescript building in New Jersey
producing, marketing and carefully manipulating the most popular
commodity on the World Wide Web: adult entertainment. By David
Firestpone.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-BROWSER-NYT (Washington) _ As late as last year,
Microsoft Corp. was so worried about Netscape Communications
Corp.'s lead in Internet software that its senior executives wanted
to delay an upgrade of Microsoft's Windows operating system to gain
an edge in the browser battle, according to internal Microsoft
documents released this week by the government. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   ONTECH-SFCHRON (Undated) _ Supercomputers are all the rage these
days, with the latest models capable of performing trillions of
calculations per second _ speeds unimaginable just a few years ago.
And supercomputers, which now are used mostly for government and
academic research, soon will become affordable tools for business,
SGI chief executive Richard Belluzzo told a supercomputer industry
conference this week in Orlando, Fla. By David Einstein.
</P>
<P>
   EMAIL-EVIDENCE-NYT (Undated) _ Never mind monopoly power in the
marketplace; the real lesson corporate America is taking away from
the Microsoft antitrust trial is that e-mail can be a mine field of
legal liability, not to mention a source of public embarrassment.
By Amy Harmon.
</P>
