<HEADLINE>
NETSCAPE PIONEER TO INVEST IN SMART VCR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A new technology intended to replace the
traditional home videocassette recorder is expected to get an
important vote of confidence on Monday with the announcement that a
co-founder of Netscape Communications Corp. has invested in one of
two companies developing digital television recording systems. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 1331EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5082 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INNOVATIVE-MANAGER-2N     11-11 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INNOVATIVE-MANAGER-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... the mid-1980s.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A personable and witty guy who insists that all those famous
names he frequently drops (``there was that Wyoming barbeque with
Ron and Nancy'') are really just references to hard-earned
meetings, Kobrick spends less time watching stock prices than a
casual observer might expect. ``It's an input, not an end,'' he
says. ``Research and thinking are our calling cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides,'' he adds, ``it's a green day,'' meaning that more of
the 100 stocks he owns are going up than down. ``If it were a red
day, I'd have to find out if it was the market or me.''
</P>
<P>
   In their brief lifetime, Kobrick's funds have done well. The $41
million Kobrick Cendant Capital fund is up 20.5 percent for the
year through Nov. 4, compared with the average mid-capitalization
fund's 1.9 percent loss. Over the same period, the $38 million
Kobrick Cendant Emerging Growth gained 11.2 percent, head &UR;  &LR; and
shoulders above the average small-capitalization fund's 10.3
percent loss, according to Morningstar Inc., a fund tracking firm.
In a new era of spectacular failures by high-risk money ventures,
Kobrick's $100 million hedge fund _ a private fund for wealthy
investors _ returned 25 percent over the first 10 months of this
year. And the hedge fund, unlike his mutual funds, even owns
battered Cendant stock.
</P>
<P>
   A growth fund he launched in September is too young to have
meaningful returns.
</P>
<P>
   Kobrick needs at least one year's strong performance to ratchet
up marketing of his funds and grow his business, which lends a
do-or-die quality to his stock-picking skills this year. At stake
is a market in which the nation's top 20 asset management firms,
which include giants like Fidelity Investments, control only half
of the $4.9 trillion mutual fund industry. Indeed, a recent Goldman
Sachs study found that smaller money managers are increasing their
market share. Other prominent Boston portfolio managers who
recently left big companies to set up their own operations include
Warren Isabelle, formerly of Pioneer Group Inc. and Keystone
Investments, and ex-Fidelity staffer Larry Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   But with freedom come greater risks. ``If you see big returns at
a fund in the first year, the fund probably didn't get there in a
conservative fashion,'' says Russell J. Kinnel, equity fund editor
at Morningstar. ``The smaller guys have the biggest incentives to
take risks to go for the bigger returns.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By noon, Kobrick, his partner, portfolio manager Michael Carmen,
and his stock analyst, Todd Brooks, are wolfing sandwiches hauled
in by a Robertson Stephens marketing executive. Kobrick, who wants
to know more about the investment bank's research and what his
visitor's &UR;  &LR; top five stocks are, pencils ``Direct Hit _ new co.'' in
the margins of his notebook. The talk ranges from whether retailer
Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch Co., a stock Kobrick owns, can remain hot, to
technology companies the Robertson Stephens executive says fib
about growth rates. As Kobrick vows to poll his fashion-conscious
21-year-old daughter on Abercrombie, his visitor moves to find out
what stocks he likes and how the relationship with Cendant has
gone. ``It has not been what I expected,'' he says later of his
venture with the troubled company. ``They rained on my parade.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1:45, Kobrick has checked the markets (the Dow is up about 90
points and hovering around 8460), winced at a stack of unanswered
phone message slips, pow-wowed via phone with a New York hedge fund
executive whose name he doesn't want mentioned, caught a taped CNBC
interview with auto retailing mogul H. Wayne Huizenga (``I'm so
glad I own this stock,'' Kobrick says), tinkered with a draft of
his ``Seven Points of Investing'' brochure, which posits that
inside every American is a secret investor just crying to come out,
and scribbled in his notebook a hiking itinerary through Kazakhstan
and Kyrgyzstan.
</P>
<P>
   The blue notebook _ wirebound and filled with cramped writing
from the dozens of conversations he has each day _ has the
intensity of a manic poet's journal. It goes everywhere he goes.
``Got years of this stuff,'' Kobrick says. ``Scares me.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; At 2:10 p.m., a Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette economist arrives
to explain where it's all heading. Kobrick, tempted by the John
Glenn space launch, invites him into the trading room to watch. By
4:15, after the market has closed, Kobrick scans headlines on his
stocks, then circles the wagons with Carmen and Brooks. Carmen, who
has possibly the world's most ragged fingernails, is edgy, and
debates whether sunglasses maker Oakley Inc., a stock in Kobrick's
portfolio, can get away with peddling a $1,500 watch in a newly
cost-conscious climate.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Most money managers are vigilant with their stocks, but those
running new funds have extra cause to be on edge. ``There is a
danger in reading too much into a strong start,'' Kinnel says,
pointing out that smaller sums are generally easier to manage than
large ones. ``A lot start strong and fade fast.
</P>
<P>
   Kobrick then decides to review his financial stocks. In October,
when shares in banks, brokerages, and insurers got spanked, Kobrick
went shopping, snapping up more Chase Manhattan, Citicorp, and
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., among others, and nearly tripling the sector
to 24 percent of his portfolio. He cut his retail stocks _ Home
Depot Inc., Wal-Mart Stores Inc., Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, and golf
apparel maker Cutter &AMP; Buck Inc. are his top picks _ in half, to 16
percent. Technology stocks, including Lycos and other Internet
outfits, are still a quarter of his holdings.
</P>
<P>
   That night, driving to home to Sudbury after a drink with
colleagues at the tony Meridien Hotel, Kobrick decides to sell 7
percent of his portfolio to raise cash to buy more semiconductor
and computer equipment stocks. Having toyed with the idea for
weeks, he decides the market has risen enough to take a tidy
profit. If financial stocks fall again, he'll buy more of those,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely sleep less these days,'' he says of the market's
volatility, which he only sees continuing. ``But we laugh a lot
here. Executives with no sense of humor are probably going to make
bad decisions because of stress, which makes me more cautious about
investing in their companies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
