<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA VOTERS NIX THE `GORILLA' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. -- California's politicians wanted to throw
around the state's weight in national politics, moving its
presidential primary from June to March, right after New
Hampshire's. But the state's voters last week refused to exempt the
presidential contest from the state's open-primary law.
</P>
<P>
   Two cliches thus collide in a hideously mixed metaphor: The
``800-pound gorilla of American politics'' has stumbled unprepared
into a ``beauty contest.'' King Kong's lip gloss is askew. Mighty
Joe Young is having a bad eye-shadow day.
</P>
<P>
   Can California cosmeticize its way out of this mess? The
electorate voted no by a 54-46 percent margin, dooming California's
plan to become the champion chimpanzee of the quadrennial circus.
The election returns suggest that a 1999 ballot question may
encounter similar hostility, skepticism, and mischief.
</P>
<P>
   A proposed law, the Save the Presidential Primary Act of 1998,
appeared as Question 3 among 11 statewide referendums. Democratic
and Republican politicians endorsed it, as did most of the state's
news-papers, everyone but the voters. Californians chose to save
their ``open primary,'' which they approved by referendum in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   This law allows voters to zig-zag though the ballot, helping
nominate a Democrat for governor, a Republican for lieutenant
governor, a Peace and Freedom Party nominee for attorney general, a
Natural Law Party choice for insurance commissioner, and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of California fun, say the Democratic and Republican
national committees, but we want only our own partisans to choose
the delegates who nominate a presidential candidate. Any contest in
March 2000, they say, will be a nonbinding ``beauty contest'' for
would-be presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Californians, seeking openness in a closed process, have
encountered the Law of Unintended Consequences, a Godzilla who
snacks on civic virtue, having devoured successive ``reforms'' in
the past 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   But do they care? Nominating presidents is important to many,
but in the nation's largest state, it is a civic afterthought.
Finance reports detail how $188 million was spent on November's
ballot questions. Electric utility interests spent $41 million, the
forces for and against Indian casinos shelled out $91 million, and
those opposed to horsemeat spent $1.2 million. Question 3 was
totally unfunded.
</P>
<P>
   In September, when Governor Pete Wilson signed legislation for
an early presidential primary, Secretary of State Bill Jones basked
in its glory. ``My job is to boost turnout, and this will help do
it,'' the Fresno farmer-businessman said. Last week, Jones survived
a Democratic tidal wave, winning reelection against a 30-year-old
Democrat, Michela Alioto, by 50,000 votes among 8 million cast.
</P>
<P>
   Jones will attend a Washington meeting this month of other state
election officials, a committee chaired by William Galvin,
secretary of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts, who's ``delighted
that the question lost. This recuts the cake and helps us find
another way to change a presidential primary process that has
served the country pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   Galvin has been pushing for a New England regional primary on
March 7 for which California's presence would mean ``a disaster''
that ``would create a de facto national primary.'' Galvin says,
``The big-bang theory of primaries is favored by people like Al
Gore and George W. Bush, but if you're Bob Kerrey or Bill Bradley
or John Ashcroft, how do you run with limited resources?''
</P>
<P>
   The secretaries of state hope to find some way to rotate
regional primaries so every time zone has a chance to shine after
New Hampshire. Before the voters spoke, Bill Jones said in
September: ``There's been a lot of talk about rotating regional
primaries, but now California's is a fact of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones now avoids the cliche du jour, but Galvin doesn't: ``The
800-pound gorilla has died. We now have an 800-pound carcass to
dispose of.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
