<SLUG> BC-AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY SAYS CALIFORNIA LAW HAS HURT MINORITIES, WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California's anti-affirmative action initiative
has created widespread confusion that has eroded advancements women
and minorities had made in education and employment, according to a
new study.
</P>
<P>
   The voter-approved Proposition 209 ``has seriously set back
efforts to integrate California's public institutions. That impact
is going to grow over time,'' said Theodore Wang, program director
of Chinese for Affirmative Action, which released the study
Tuesday. ``The immediate impact has been in education, which serves
as a pipeline to employment and other areas.''
</P>
<P>
   The law barred preferences in hiring and contracting in state
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The overall effect of the law is unknown because of Gov. Pete
Wilson's executive order in March barring state agencies from
collecting data on woman- and minority-owned companies that win
state contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, co-sponsored by the Equal Rights Advocates interest
group, was conducted by submitting questionnaires to 68 local,
state and educational agencies across California, conducting
interviews and gathering statistics through public records.
</P>
<P>
   It found that Proposition 209, which voters approved in 1996,
caused widespread confusion among contractors and agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The language of 209 refers to `preferences,' but it doesn't
say what preferences are,'' Wang said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, some governments have continued their
affirmative-action programs while others have eliminated them.
Several are trying to find an acceptable middle ground, focusing on
outreach to women and minorities without using their race or gender
as a factor in hiring and admissions.
</P>
<P>
   The most extreme example in the survey was San Diego County,
which eliminated its Equal Opportunity Office, including all 15
staff members.
</P>
<P>
   ``By eliminating that office, you eliminate even looking at
whether there's any discrimination, and if there is, any efforts to
try to reverse that,'' said Beth Parker, program director of Equal
Rights Advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Another source of confusion and resistance to diversity arose
with federal contracts, which are not affected by the state law.
Any project with federal funding still has affirmative-action
requirements, but contractors sometimes are unwilling to comply.
</P>
<P>
   The co-sponsors of the survey opposed Proposition 209. They
recommend increased funding for outreach and recruitment efforts to
lure minorities and women.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
