u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONADVERTISING-COLUMN-     11-11 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONADVERTISING-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNING FURBY INTO A HOLIDAY HIT TAKES SKILL, LUCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; If the Furby isn't a hit toy this holiday season, it won't be
for a lack of marketing effort.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to make an animatronic plush animal the Cabbage Patch
Kid of 1998, Furby's maker, Tiger Electronics, has enlisted major
toy retailers to stage glitzy promotional events in many major
cities around the country.
</P>
<P>
   In the $22.6 billion toy industry, something like Furby has to
be more than just a good idea; it also needs a marketing plan _ and
a bit of luck. That's especially true for a toy that, unlike
Teletubbies or Blue's Clues, doesn't have its own TV show that
serves as an ongoing ad for its licensed toy lines.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Tiger has stage-managed some nice buzz around Furby, a
Gremlin sort of creature that emits weird noises. But
self-manufactured buzz is one thing. Delivering the blockbuster toy
of the season may be quite another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Furby has had great PR,'' notes Jim Silver, publisher of the
Toy Book, a trade publication. Tiger ``built a lot of excitement
for it even before it hit the toy store shelves.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides its own TV show, what makes a toy a holiday hit these
days? ``The consumer press,'' says Silver.
</P>
<P>
   That elastic phrase covers TV talk-show hosts Rosie O'Donnell
and Bryant Gumbel. On-air plugs from these worthies helped make
Tickle-Me-Elmo a smash item two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   According to Silver, this year's toy king-maker could be Wired
magazine. In its September issue, Wired described Furby as ``Giga
Pets 2.0'' (a reference to Tiger's last hit). Furby, according to
Wired, is an interactive toy children can nurture, teach, and play
with, and is likely to have frantic parents scrambling to find it
before the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, only a few obscure trade publications made such
predictions, but now every talk-show and newspaper is on the
lookout, and once one pundit anoints something as a hot toy, a
pack-journalism frenzy of me-too stories quickly ensues. For
example, following a Furby appearance on the Today Show, the Boston
Herald among others gave it a big splash.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how the snowball begins,'' Silver says.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Tiger, a recently acquired subsidiary of Hasbro Inc.,
wasn't poised to add to the snowball's momentum. In mid-October, it
launched an ad campaign for Furby, and even earlier, it approached
key retailers to help incubate a hoped-for craze.
</P>
<P>
   With the same tone that brewers use in their public service
announcements about sensible drinking, Tiger insists it would never
try to create demand for a toy it couldn't meet.
</P>
<P>
   It may be good strategy for a maker of collectible products,
such as Beanie Babies, to keep some items deliberately scarce. But
for most toymakers, it doesn't make good business sense to
disappoint customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger's policy is to never manipulate demand,'' says company
spokeswoman Lana Simon.
</P>
<P>
   In evolving from an inventor's idea to a production order at a
Chinese factory and, finally, to a product on a US retailer's
shelf, many toys need lead times of a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the case with Furby. The idea for Furby was presented
to Tiger in the fall of 1997, leaving the company only 14 months to
develop, ship, and market it, says Simon.
</P>
<P>
   Because the finished toy became available late in the cycle,
Furbys are being shipped from China to the United States by air
rather than by sea, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to ship one to two million pieces by the end of the
year, which is a lot of product for a $30 toy,'' says Simon.
</P>
<P>
   Between now and Christmas, Toys `R' Us has been promised 200,000
Furbys, says chain spokeswoman Rebecca A. Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are hot toy items,'' she says of Furby shipments. ``As
quickly as we get them in, they get sold pretty fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The fear of not having enough of a hot toy can make retailers
very nervous, especially toy retailers, which are seeing such
chains as Wal-Mart and BJ's Wholesale Club eat into their toy
business. Afraid of being left out, toy retailers seemed eager to
jump on the Furby bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   In negotiating with Tiger, toy retailers were given chunks of
geography where they were allowed to introduce Furby to the
toy-buying public with much hoo-ha and fanfare.
</P>
<P>
   In early October, FAO Schwarz debuted Furby in New York. Toys
`R' Us got Los Angeles. And K-B Toys, the Pittsfield, Mass.
division of Consolidated Stores Corp., was allowed to unveil Furby
in such urban areas as Boston, Miami, and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   While declining to say how much K-B spent on Furby's launch,
communications manager John Reilly explained why KB felt compelled
to act.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want our share, too,'' he says. ``We want our chance to
shine with a hit toy.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Furby got off to a late start, it may not generate the
sales of holiday toy hits of yesteryear. And in vying for the title
of top toy for 1998, Furby may get stiff competition from Blue's
Clues Sing-Along Blue, Bouncing Tigger, Spice Girl Dolls, Talking
Teletubbies, and Barbie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of one toy that sells 5 million items this year, I
think you're going to see five or six toys that sell 1 million or
so items each,'' says Silver of the Toy Book.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
