<SLUG> BC-HEART-AMINO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1998 
 
LINK BETWEEN HEART DISEASE, AMINO ACID YET TO BE DEFINED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
EDITORS: This story is a re-send of story filed Tuesday, Nov. 10,By RUTH SoRELLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The link between homocysteine and heart disease has yet
to be defined, prompting experts Tuesday to advise against
screening the population for elevated levels of the amino acid or
vitamin treatments except in rare cases.
</P>
<P>
   Of 11 studies performed to define the link between homocysteine
_ an amino acid _ and development of cardiovascular disease, six
showed a correlation between high homocysteine levels and five did
not, said Dr. Ronald Krauss, immediate past president of the
American Heart Association's nutrition committee, which wrote the
advisory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the fact that vitamin intake lowers the homocysteine
level, there are no studies to prove that lowering homocysteine
reduces the rate of cardiovascular disease,'' Krauss said at AHA's
meeting here.
</P>
<P>
   Folic acid, vitamins B6 and B12, can reduce homocysteine levels
in the blood, Krauss said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the U.S. Food and Drug Administration requires that cereals
and grains be fortified with folic acid, mainly to reduce the rate
of children born with abnormalities of the spinal cord and brain.
</P>
<P>
   Krauss said, however, the fortification adds 100 micrograms (one
millionth of a gram) of folic acid to the daily diet. That plus a
regular eating pattern that includes fruit and vegetables can
reduce homocysteine levels adequately in most people, Krauss said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until testing (to determine whether reducing homocysteine
decreases heart disease risk) is done, the emphasis should be
placed on meeting the recommended daily requirements for folic acid
by increasing intake of fruit, vegetables and fortified cereals,''
Krauss said.
</P>
<P>
   In some instances, he said, physicians who see patients with
high risks of developing heart disease may want to measure
homocysteine with a test that can cost as much as $100, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an individual physician judgment,'' he said. If it seems
obvious that the patient cannot meet the recommended daily intake
of folic acid and the B vitamins, doctors may prescribe a
multivitamin to deal with the problem, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Without adequate levels of vitamins that act as metabolic
co-factors, &UR;  &LR; homocysteine can build up in the blood, Krauss said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter Wilson has evaluated homocysteine levels in 1,947
women and men who are part of the Framingham, Mass., Heart Study
that began 50 years ago. He found that as levels of homocysteine in
the blood climbed, the risk of stroke climbed.
</P>
<P>
   He said he does not feel that his data are a mandate to
encourage people to eat more than the 400 micrograms of folic acid
now recommended in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have enough experience with vitamin levels and
homocysteine,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
