<HEADLINE>
JOHN HANCOCK UNVEILS DRAFT PLAN FOR DEMUTUALIZATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co. is providing the first
peek at details of its plans to become a publicly traded company,
from how shares and cash would be distributed to antitakeover
defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock's first draft proposal, a 32-page plan, delivered to the
Massachusetts Division of Insurance this week, is the initial step
in a ``demutualization'' approval process that could take the
better part of the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Among the details proposed: how stock and cash distributions to
policyholders and others would take place just before an initial
public stock offering; limits on stock options and awards to top
insiders; and a form of anti-takeover protection that would last
for three years.
</P>
<P>
   It proposes an actual transaction in 2000, leaving open the
possibility of a later date if the stock market is unreceptive to
new issues at that time.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hancock document, sure to be debated and negotiated at
length before approval, is sketchy or outright moot on many other
details.
</P>
<P>
   As a mutual insurance company, Boston-based Hancock is
technically owned by its policyholders and some other customers.
The plan submitted to regulators would give those customer-owners
cash or stock in a new holding company, which would immediately
raise more money by selling additional shares to investors in an
initial public stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Hancock would become a publicly traded stock
company.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation of mutual insurers into public companies is a
hot topic around the country. Insurers insist they need access to
capital markets to compete in a consolidating financial services
world. Critics worry that policyholders can get left out in the
cold if their interests are not carefully protected by regulators.
</P>
<P>
   MONY Group Inc., the new holding company for Mutual Life
Insurance Co. of New York, is expected to complete the process
today. Shares in an IPO, forecast to raise about $250 million, are
scheduled to be priced by underwriter Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. before
the day is out.
</P>
<P>
   In Pennsylvania, regulators approved a demutualization plan for
Provident Mutual Life Insurance Co. and its 300,000 policyholders
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Hancock plan would create a holding company called John
Hancock Financial Services Inc. That company would own three
subsidiaries: John Hancock Life Insurance Co., managing the
company's domestic business; a Canadian Hancock unit; and a
subsidiary containing all other foreign business interests.
</P>
<P>
   Policyholders could swap their mutual ownership interest for
shares of John Hancock Financial Services or request a settlement
in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The good news on cash: Hancock proposes paying out at a rate
commensurate with the stock value set by its IPO or the average
price of its shares over the first 20 days of trading, up to a
maximum of 120 percent of the IPO price. The payout would be pegged
to the higher of the two figures. The Hancock document describes
the plan as ``unprecedented.''
</P>
<P>
   The bad news on cash: It probably won't be around for everyone
who wants it. Hancock suggested paying out cash, as it lasts,
beginning with the smallest policyholders and working its way up.
Once there is no more cash to distribute, customers would get stock
for their interests. This isn't such a bad deal since the stock
could be sold almost immediately, once the IPO is launched and
there is a public market for the shares.
</P>
<P>
   State Mutual Assurance Co. of Worcester, now known as Allmerica
Financial Corp., demutualized in 1995 and raised about $250 million
in an IPO. About $25 million to $30 million in cash was made
available to policyholders who did not want stock, issued on a
little-guy-first basis similar to the Hancock plan.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock's initial plan does not mention an amount of cash
available, nor does it discuss reserving any portion of money
raised in an IPO to help cash out policyholders.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also places some limits on the stock and option
interests of top Hancock brass. It suggests prohibiting awards of
options or stock grants to directors and elected Hancock officials
for six months after the IPO.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would limit the stock holdings of that same group
to 5 percent of Hancock stock for the first 2 1/2 years, and 18
percent after that time. It also would prohibit top insiders from
receiving any stock benefits as a consideration for insurance
policies issued after May 11, the day Hancock's board authorized
managers to prepare a demutualization plan.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock's initial plan would prohibit any stockholder from
purchasing more than 10 percent of the company's shares for three
years, effectively creating a limited antitakeover defense. The
company described the three years as ``a reasonable period of time
to implement its strategy as a new public company,'' adding that
the breathing room is specifically authorized in the state law
covering demutualization.
</P>
<P>
   Allmerica received more protection when it converted to public
ownership in 1995, blocking any investor from acquiring more than 5
percent of the stock for one year. Allmerica was also prohibited
from making acquisitions during the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Among issues not mentioned in the Hancock plan: what rights, if
any, policyholders should have to buy additional shares during the
IPO.
</P>
<P>
   Shares that mutual insurance companies convert are frequently
priced at a discount to their book value in an IPO. In a
demutualization, policyholders swap for stock at a rate set exactly
to book value, and some consumer advocates suggest those customers
should be allowed to buy more shares in the IPO to compensate for
any dilution they suffer.
</P>
<P>
   That issue came up in the MONY case, but regulators did not
insist on IPO access for policyholders.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
