<SLUG> BC-WOM-CHEERLEADER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR TEEN, CHEERS OVERCOME CHILDHOOD DISEASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEDFORD, Mass. _ A pile of huge white bows, their ribbons
cascading down the front of a living-room chair, greeted Amanda
Colford Monday night as she breezed in from practice.
</P>
<P>
   Although destined as merry props for a competition this weekend,
they could just as well have been waiting to adorn the raven-haired
17-year-old captain of the Bedford High cheerleading squad, whose
grace and poise and very life are gifts beyond measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these things have faded,'' said her mother, Laurene,
trying to detail the life-threatening illnesses, the crises, the
alarms _ oh, those endless alarms _ that punctuated Amanda's
childhood before she emerged as the leaping, jumping, athletic
cheerleader she is now. ``It doesn't seem real.''
</P>
<P>
   What's real these days is the excitement of mother and daughter
as they look forward to their January trip to Hawaii, where Amanda
will participate in the All-American Scholarship Invitational in
Honolulu and the halftime show of the NFL Pro Bowl. This, on the
heels of being given the Miss New England Cheerleading Association
award at a recent camp at Babson College. And just last month,
Amanda was crowned homecoming queen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just took it one day at a time,'' said Amanda of the long,
often pain-wracked journey that will soon take her to her 18th
birthday, her graduation, and those sun-drenched islands.
</P>
<P>
   It's like living a fairy tale for Laurene, whose idea of
paradise not long ago was awakening to find her daughter still
alive. Just a day after Amanda came home from the hospital, a
friend of Laurene's hesitantly observed that the newborn didn't
look right. The new mother took her fears to her pediatrician, Dr.
Richard D'Entremont, who sent over a monitoring device to which
Amanda's tiny body was hooked via electrodes. The next morning, he
got a call from Laurene: something's wrong with the machine, it
beeped all night long.
</P>
<P>
   Wake her up, the doctor instructed. Disturb a sleeping newborn,
thought Laurene? ``Now she's crying,'' she reported, annoyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good,'' said the doctor, relieved. The persistant beeping had
been signaling apnea/bradycardia, a condition that can lead to
Sudden Infant Death Syndrome in which Amanda would quit breathing
and her heart would briefly stop while she slept. So Amanda's first
two months were spent in the hospital, and for four years she would
sleep attached to the monitor that would beep when she quit
breathing. The idea was to wait for the beeping to stimulate her to
resume breathing on her own; after 10 beeps Laurene would gently
shake her awake.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had a lot of alarms,'' Laurene said. ``I still wake up at
2 o'clock in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   When Amanda was 2, a new crisis suddenly appeared. An active
toddler despite the apnea, Amanda loved to attend her little gym
program and was already showing some talent. But one day when her
grandmother came to watch, Amanda began crawling and falling about.
``That's what I get for bragging,'' thought Laurene.
</P>
<P>
   But later that day while reading to her daughter, she looked
down. ``Her ankles were absolutely gigantic,'' Laurene said. The
diagnosis: rheumatoid arthritis. The prescription: 27 baby aspirins
a day, exercise such as dance and gymnastics in lieu of physical
therapy and, even when she's having trouble walking, don't pick her
up all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a really good thing they said that, too,'' said Amanda.
``It would have been harder for me to learn to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fifth grade, the arthritis abruptly worsened. For a while her
whole body was so stiff she could barely move, and she spent that
summer in a wheelchair. But when school started in the fall, she
slapped a pair of braces on her legs and stubbornly walked to the
bus. ``I never really liked making a big deal of it,'' Amanda said.
``I liked being normal.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, as serious as it was, few of her friends and not even
her cheerleading coach knew of her arthritis until recently. ``Yes,
I had it,'' said Amanda. ``But it was no different than if I had
blond hair or black hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness, said her doctor. ``A lot of the credit goes to
her and her mom, because a lot of times what happens when you have
a chronic illness is the parents start to overprotect the child and
the child starts to favor the illness,'' said D'Entremont, a
physician with Woburn Pediatrics. ``Suddenly, they're not doing
anything because they're not trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally weaned from the monitor after she outgrew the apnea at
age 4, Amanda and her mother were learning to cope with the
arthritis when the worst hit. At age 5, she was stricken with
epiglotitis, a potentially fatal swelling of the small flap that
covers the airway to the lungs. When Amanda began complaining of a
horrible sore throat and had trouble swallowing her medicine, her
mother became alarmed. Amanda, who was just learning about
ambulances, thought the ride was cool but was upset the siren
wasn't on. (Ironically, Dr. D'Entremont had ordered the siren be
left off so as not to upset the little girl.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a long year,'' her mother said. ``That year we just
constantly prayed. I just felt a peace that she was going to be all
right.''
</P>
<P>
   She was, except for a few broken bones and torn ligaments
(earned while playing basketball) that would give most teen-agers
something to brag about for years but are mentioned only as an
aside in this household. ``The epiglotitis was kind of like the
final hurrah, knock on wood,'' said Laurene, who still marvels at
what she calls the miracle of her daughter's current health. ``If
just one little part to that chain of events had been different,
she probably wouldn't be here.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of eighth grade, Amanda _ the arthritis by now
largely controlled by medication _ was out shopping when a girl who
cheered came up to her and said, hey, you do gymnastics, come on
down to cheerleading tryouts. She made varsity as a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   What lingers from Amanda's childhood struggles are the happy
memories and shared anecdotes: how Laurene would somehow turn every
dose of medication, every blood test, every treatment into a game
or party (``It helped me get through a lot of this,'' said her
daughter); how Amanda still sleeps with Pound Puppy, a delightfully
shabby stuffed animal she began using as an extra pillow when she
was 5 and the arthritis hurt too much to get to sleep without him
wrapped around her neck; how they both still jump when the beeper
on the french fry maker at Friendly's goes off because it sounds
exactly like the monitor Amanda was hooked up to until she was 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it was a miracle,'' said Laurene of her daughter's
life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
