<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-WOLFE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOLFE IN FULL CRY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The drumbeat for Tom Wolfe's new novel, ``A Man in
Full,'' has been sounding for more than a decade now, going all the
way back to 1987. That's when Wolfe painted himself into an
authorial corner by being so rash as to publish a first novel that
rapidly turned into a cultural phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bonfire of the Vanities'' was one of those rare works that
manages to define an era _ in this case the revved-up Reagan '80s.
A fabulous success, the book sold three-quarters of a million
copies in hardcover and bestowed on a grateful vernacular such
immediately ubiquitous terms as ``master of the universe'' and
``social X-ray.'' It also proved that the man who had
revolutionized journalism during the '60s and '70s could shake up
fiction-writing in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   What would the follow-up be? What could the follow-up be?
</P>
<P>
   ``I allowed the pressure to be much too big,'' Wolfe
acknowledges. ``I thought I had to come up with something so
gigantic the world would fall down.''
</P>
<P>
   What he finally came up with was a new novel in which it's the
main character's world that falls down. Charlie Croker, the man
fully in question, is an Atlanta real estate developer who has all
the things money can buy, from a 29,000-acre plantation in south
Georgia to a gorgeous second wife half his age. Alas, a
half-billion dollars of that money belongs to a bank, which rather
eagerly desires its return. How Charlie tries to square his
accounts (financial and otherwise) is to the new book what Sherman
McCoy's efforts to stay out of prison are to ``Bonfire.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe didn't apply the final touches to ``A Man in Full'' until
August, but the PR percussion began in earnest months ago. Rolling
Stone ran three excerpts last summer. Four weeks before publication
it was nominated for a National Book Award. Two weeks ago Wolfe was
on the cover of Time. Friday the book finally went on sale, and
it's already the best-selling title at the two biggest online
booksellers, amazon.com and barnesandnoble.com. Last night, Wolfe
traded quips with David Letterman on ``The Late Show.'' This
morning he's on ``The Today Show'' and tonight reads at New York's
Town Hall, with a ``60 Minutes'' film crew in tow, kicking off a
nationwide publicity tour with a reading at New York's Town Hall.
</P>
<P>
   With 1.2 million copies in print, ``A Man in Full'' is a very
big deal. For pre-tour interviews, Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, Wolfe's
publisher, has taken a $750-a-night suite at the Hotel Carlyle,
JFK's preferred residence when in New York and a citadel of Upper
East Side swank. Wolfe lives barely a dozen blocks away, but FS&AMP;G
is putting its money where its print run is to give him the sort of
PR treatment usually reserved for movie-star junkets.
</P>
<P>
   There's a certain logic to Wolfe's getting the full-Hollywood
treatment. The man is a consummate performer, both on the page and
in the flesh _ or, to be precise, in the cloth. ``I must say, I do
enjoy performing,'' he remarks. ``One of the great things about
writing, and about lecturing, which I also enjoy is that you can
become whoever you want to. You don't have to depend on your own
genetic resources, whatever they may be, and that's kind of a nice
thing. Dressing is the same way. People don't realize that dressing
is a way of telling the world both where you think you stand and
how you want to be treated.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe says this in a fine, papery baritone. The voice is part of
his performer's arsenal, too, its sedate tones complementing the
flamboyance of his attire.
</P>
<P>
   Today he's wearing a three-piece suit of white wool crepe,
double-breasted, with self-covered buttons, a subtle polka-dot tie
(only Tom Wolfe can make polka dots appear subtle), a white
handkerchief selvaged in brown, off-white socks with blue dots, and
brown-and-white shoes (``I like to think of them as faux spats,''
he says).
</P>
<P>
   The look is very French vanilla, with touches of fudge sauce and
blueberry for contrast. It's easy to believe Wolfe when he says his
favorite leisure-time activity is window shopping and that he owns
only one pair of jeans. ``I bought them in La Porte, Texas:
authentic Double XX Levi's, the kind with stovepipe legs.'' He
utters these words with the avidity of a vicar confessing a
more-than-venial sin. ``I've only worn them when I've had to force
myself to stay in the house to finish some writing, since I knew I
couldn't be seen in public in them.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he'd probably look pretty good in a pair of jeans.
Wolfe has a Henry Fonda lankiness: a refined angularity. His body
language somehow seems to reside in his joints, and in the
economical way he carries himself one can almost visualize Wolfe as
the college baseball pitcher he once was who, almost 50 years ago,
had a tryout with the New York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe is 67. He and his wife, Sheila, have two children.
Alexandra, 18, is a freshman at Duke, and Thomas, 13, is a junior
squash champion. Two years ago he suffered a heart attack and
underwent quintuple-bypass surgery. But other than a slight tremor
to his hands and a graying at the temples, he presents the same
oddly ageless appearance he has for more than 30 years now. Then,
as now, he seemed far too wise for (itals)enfant
terriblehood.(unitals) Now, as then, he seems far too boyish for
old masterdom. He's the dandy as an updated Dorian Gray (calling
such attention to one's clothes insures little attention is paid to
the person wearing them?).
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe's courtly manners match his elaborate style of dress.
They're something he comes by naturally, for behind the foppish New
Yorker is an old-style Virginia gentleman who's the great-grandson
of a Confederate veteran and son of the editor of a journal called
The Southern Planter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
