<HEADLINE>
NETSCAPE PIONEER TO INVEST IN SMART VCR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A new technology intended to replace the
traditional home videocassette recorder is expected to get an
important vote of confidence on Monday with the announcement that a
co-founder of Netscape Communications Corp. has invested in one of
two companies developing digital television recording systems. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 1342EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5111 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INNOVATIVE-MANAGER-2T     11-11 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INNOVATIVE-MANAGER-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRED KOBRICK, STOCK PSYCHOANALYST 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For a brief moment, the money manager becomes a
Viennese psychoanalyst, and the investment business seems less the
world of numbers and more the realm of the psyche.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell me everything you can about their CEO,'' Fred Kobrick
orders his telephone interlocutor, a stock analyst in Chicago who
follows a hot Internet firm, Lycos Inc., that Kobrick likes. ``What
kind of guy is he? Does he get along with people? How does he cope
with competition?''
</P>
<P>
   It is 9:45 on a clear October morning, and 55-year-old Kobrick,
one of Boston's best-known investment managers, is on a quest for
the unquantifiable. Up to his ears in voice mail and facing an
array of shimmying red and green stock quotes on a computer screen,
Kobrick had long ago crunched numbers on Lycos. Now, 15 minutes
before the Internet company's chief financial officer is due at his
office in Boston's financial district, Kobrick is tackling
intangibles. How he perceives the Lycos culture will later
influence what he does with some of the $250 million that 4,100
investors hold in his three mutual funds and one hedge fund.
</P>
<P>
   If the grapefruit-sized crystal ball in Kobrick's 10th floor
office could talk, it might intone that this is the golden age of
the small money manager, even in a market tarnished by volatility.
Having struck out on his own last year with Kobrick Cendant Funds
and Kobrick Capital Management, his mutual fund and hedge fund
firms, Kobrick is among a new breed of independent stock-pickers
staking fresh ground in the heart of America's fund industry.
</P>
<P>
   If the miniature red punching bag nearby had its say, it would
recount the blows Kobrick has endured _ from his partner and fund
distributor, Cendant Corp., a marketing and franchising company
mired in accounting fraud, and from critics, who carp about
Kobrick's surfeit of self-confidence and point out his stumble at
State Street Research &AMP; Management Co. Kobrick eventually managed
$4 billion at the Boston fund house, where his high returns made
him the star attraction for more than a decade before he tripped in
a market that did not share his penchant for small, fast-growing
firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' Kobrick greets Lycos chief financial officer Edward M.
Philip, who arrives 20 minutes late with two investment bankers in
tow, ``good thing with all this snazzy technology you guys have
that you don't have any competition.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses, then grins. Philip twitches, then launches a volley
of statements that make Kobrick happy he owns the stock.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the meeting, Kobrick will have asked his visitor
to describe the most fun part of his job as well as his nightmares.
He will have probed how the Waltham-based company handles the
cultural differences between its East Coast and West Coast
operations as well as how executives get along with each other. At
one pointKobrick jokingly asks Philip, a former Disney executive,
if Mickey Mouse signed his paychecks at the entertainment giant.
But mostly, Kobrick alternates between psychologist and cultural
anthropologist, probing how Lycos positions itself in a brutally
competitive industry. It is a style that stands out in Boston's
conservative money culture.
</P>
<P>
   In an era that has turned millions of Americans into steadfast
fund owners and transformed some big fund houses into regimented
bureaucracies, the daily world of the independent asset manager has
a fluid quality. But in a market now deciding which species, bull
or bear, it belongs to after eight roaring years, Kobrick's bouncy
demeanor belies the edginess most fund managers _ himself included
_ feel these days. While the small ``growth'' companies Kobrick has
always favored recently had their best three-week run in two
decades, such stocks have been pummeled in past years. And while
the Dow Jones industrial average has staged a mini-rally in recent
weeks, clawing back half of what it lost from its July peak,
Kobrick is still wary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fred's still an analyst, looking at companies,'' says Peter S.
Lynch, Fidelity Investments' legendary former stock-picker, who sat
next to Kobrick in 12th-grade English at the old Newton High
School. ``He's flexible; he'll look at all types of companies. Some
people get caught in a box.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Lycos meeting ends at 11:10 a.m., Kobrick strides into
his trading room. Seconds later, like it or not, shareholders in
Kobrick's Capital, Emerging Growth, and Growth funds have cast
their lot with 50,000 more Lycos shares.
</P>
<P>
   Kobrick wants not projector slides but a window onto the
corporate soul. Such views are gained over years of analyzing a
company's management. ``If I just heard the stories from the
brokers and never got to do my own grilling, I'd get taken,''
Kobrick says, peering over a wooden ``More buyers than sellers''
sign facing a prominently placed photograph of Kobrick and Clinton.
``I really like to know these companies in depth.''
</P>
<P>
   Large fund firms often send an array of analysts into meetings
with companies, leaving lead managers less leeway to conduct the
unexpected, intuitive questioning that is Kobrick's trademark. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, Kobrick nearly engaged in dissection of a different
sort &UR;  &LR; before the sight of a cadaver put an end to his original plan
to become a surgeon. A three-year stint as a Navy photographer took
him to Cuba and southern France before he returned to Boston to
study economics at Boston University. After finishing Harvard
Business School in 1971, he joined a small, local firm, Wellington
Asset Management, before jumping to State Street in the go-go
investment days of the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
