<HEADER>
A5115 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-WOLFE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     11-11 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-WOLFE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 NEW YORK: ... Southern Planter.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wolfe's affection for the South is evident throughout the new
novel, and Charlie Croker's first wife pays glowing tribute to his
hometown, noting, ``in Atlanta, things (itals)Richmond(unitals) ...
had (itals)authenticity(unitals).
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an extremely happy upbringing,'' Wolfe says. ``I
remember getting down on my knees every night to say my prayers _
we were Presbyterians _ thanking God for letting me live in the
best nation in the world and the best state in the nation. Virginia
did have the most presidents, after all. Is Massachusetts next? Ah,
I guess it's Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``From an upstairs window in our house, you could watch the
fireworks at the Virginia State Fair each fall. My parents would
give my sister and me a dozen nickels each and send us by ourselves
through the woods over to the fair. We'd spend all day there.
Everything cost a nickel. Imagine, even in Richmond, letting two
children off by themselves like that today. That's how simple life
was.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be so, but it was Wolfe's affinity for the ``wild,
bizarre, unpredictable, Hog-stomping Baroque'' complexity of modern
American life that made his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Virginia's Washington and Lee University
in 1951, he got a doctorate in American studies at Yale. ``I didn't
really know what I wanted to do,'' he explains. ``I always knew I
wanted to write, but that wasn't a job you could just walk into. So
I went to Yale.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing he knew he didn't want to do was join the
professoriate. Instead, he entered journalism: three years at The
Springfield Union; three at The Washington Post; and then a
marriage made in media heaven, four years at The New York Herald
Tribune. More than three decades after its demise, the Trib remains
unrivaled in the annals of American newspapering as the
quintessential writer's paper. When it hired Wolfe, it got a
consummate stylist about to burst his journalistic cocoon.
</P>
<P>
   Like the space program, American culture was taking off on
rocket boosters _ and Wolfe was the first one to provide the solid
fuel to put it into prose. Writing for Esquire and the Trib's
Sunday magazine, New York, Wolfe alternately celebrated and mocked
a new breed of eccentric-hero, characters like the record producer
Phil Spector, the stock-car racer Junior Johnson, the disc jockey
Murray the K, Playboy's Hugh Hefner. These were unfettered,
deliriously American creatures, and to limn them Wolfe forged a
comparably idiosyncratic style. Ellipses, italics, exclamation
marks, onomatopoeia, repetition, leitmotifs, a very knowing
hyperbole: the look, sound, and feel of journalism would never be
quite the same again. What Muhammad Ali was in the boxing ring,
Wolfe was in print: dead on precisely because he was so over the
top.
</P>
<P>
   It's long since become legend how Wolfe, facing a tight deadline
and unable to get a handle on the material he'd gathered for an
article about Southern California car customizers, typed up in a
single sitting all his notes for a 49-page memo to Byron Dobell,
Esquire's managing editor. Dobell simply lopped off the ``Dear
Byron'' at the beginning and ran it as ``The Kandy-Kolored
Tangerine-Flake Streamline Baby.'' That was 1963, and neither
American journalism nor Wolfe's career has settled down since.
</P>
<P>
   The New Journalism it was called. Wolfe may not have been its
first practitioner (that honor probably goes to Norman Mailer) or
its most daring (that was Hunter S. Thompson during his heyday),
but he was its acknowledged master. Even those who dismissed what
he was doing, such as the critic Dwight Macdonald, conceded Wolfe
was the most exotic of high-wire acts.
</P>
<P>
   No one seemed to have his finger on the racing pulse of postwar
America as Wolfe did. He offered up a string of titles that became
instant catchphrases: ``radical chic,'' ``the Me Decade,'' ``the
right stuff.'' And even when he went against prevailing fashion _
casting a cold eye on the drug culture in ``The Electric Kool-Aid
Acid Test,'' sending up liberalism a la mode in ``Radical Chic,''
deriding modern art in ``The Painted Word'' _ he remained the
center of attention.
</P>
<P>
   The slightness of much of his subject matter could make Wolfe's
stylistic flourishes seem excessive. But given the right subject,
as was in ``The Right Stuff,'' his paean to masculine courage as
personified by the Mercury astronauts and test pilot Chuck Yeager,
Wolfe had no journalistic peer.
</P>
<P>
   His ``Right Stuff'' days give Wolfe a somewhat iconoclastic
perspective on John Glenn's return to outer space. ``The greatest
thing in any country is the man who has protected his fellow
countrymen at the risk of his own life. That's what Glenn did back
then. He was a David against the Goliath of the Soviet Union.
Remember, a lot of NASA's rockets were blowing up. He was laying
his life on the line. It's indescribable how heroic that seemed at
the time. What he just did was boring to most Americans. I didn't
even bother to watch it. It was a great thing for NASA, though, and
they need all the support they can get. They can hardly keep the
lights on down in Houston. You've never heard a peep from them
about flying saucers, have you? They know that what they really
need is a sighting of some truly menacing UFO _ then you'd watch
their budget take off.''
</P>
<P>
   His 11-year struggle with ``A Man in Life`` has left Wolfe eager
to tackle new projects. He wants to write a book on neuroscience
(``What we amount to is a string of molecules hooked up to a
chemical analog computer''), as well as one on status in
contemporary America. Taking up the nonfiction cudgels doesn't mean
he's given up on the novel, though. He's already begun to research
one on education (``whenever I've mentioned this notion to people
it's made them yawn terribly, but I'm convinced it's a very hot and
exciting topic'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm still in love with the notion of what can and
can't be done with fiction. It's new to me, even though I'm 67....
And even though it's taken me a total of 18 years to write these
two novels, it still seems new to me. I'm still committed to
proving that detailed realism _ or naturalism, (the 19th-century
French novelst Emile) Zola called it _ is the only way to do
fiction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
