<SLUG> BC-CHOCOLATE-CAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOCOLATE LOVERS REJOICE! IT'S CAKE TIME 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANN CRISWELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chocolate cakes were requested for the upcoming holidays. The
Died-and-Went-to-Heaven cake &UR;  &LR; is from Eating Well magazine and was
published in the Chronicle a few years ago. The Chocolate Praline
Cake was a Pillsbury BAKE-OFF winner in 1988. The Chocolate Praline
Cake is a favorite for family birthdays. Both cakes are
scrumptious.
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Praline Layer Cake
</P>
<P>
   A Pillsbury BAKE-OFF grand prize winner in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Cake
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
{ cup butter or margarine &QL; 
\ cup whipping cream &QL; 
1 cup firmly packed brown sugar &QL; 
} cup coarsely chopped pecans &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 (2-layer-size) package pudding-included devil's food cake mix &QL; 
1 \ cups water &QL;
</P>
<P>
   cup oil &QL; 
3 eggs &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 325 degrees. Combine butter, cream and sugar in a
small, heavy saucepan. Cook over low heat just until butter is
melted, stirring occasionally. Pour into 2 (8- or 9-inch) round
cake pans; sprinkle with pecans.
</P>
<P>
   Combine cake mix, water, oil and eggs in large mixer bowl. With
electric mixer, beat at low speed until moistened; beat 2 minutes
at highest speed.
</P>
<P>
   Carefully spoon batter over pecan mixture. Bake 35 to 45 minutes
or until cake springs back when touched lightly in center. Cool 5
minutes. Remove from pans; cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Topping
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
1 } cups whipping cream &QL; 
\ cup powdered sugar &QL; 
\ teaspoon vanilla &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whole pecans and chocolate curls for garnish (optional) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beat cream in small bowl until soft peaks form. Blend in sugar
and vanilla; beat until stiff peaks form.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble:
</P>
<P>
   Place 1 layer of cake on serving plate, praline side up. Spread
with half the whipped cream. Top with second layer, praline side
up. Spread top with remaining cream. Garnish with pecans and
chocolate curls. Store in refrigerator. Makes 12 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eating Well's Died-and-Went-to-Heaven Chocolate Cake
</P>
<P>
   From Chronicle files.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
1 } cups all-purpose flour, plus more for dusting pan &QL; 
1 cup granulated sugar &QL; 
} cup unsweetened Dutch-process cocoa powder &QL; 
1 { teaspoons each: baking powder and soda &QL; 
1 teaspoon salt &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 \ cups buttermilk &QL; 
1 cup packed brown sugar &QL; 
2 large eggs, lightly beaten &QL; 
\ cup canola oil &QL; 
2 teaspoons pure vanilla extract &QL; 
1 cup hot, strong black coffee &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Lightly coat a 12-cup bundt pan
with vegetable oil spray. Dust pan with flour; shake out excess. In
a large mixing bowl, whisk together flour, granulated sugar, cocoa
powder, baking powder, soda and salt. Add buttermilk, brown sugar,
eggs, oil and vanilla; beat with electric mixer on medium speed 2
minutes. Whisk in hot coffee until completely incorporated. The
batter will be quite thin.
</P>
<P>
   Pour batter into prepared pan. Bake 35 to 40 minutes or until a
cake tester inserted in center comes out clean. Cool cake in pan on
a rack 10 minutes; remove cake from pan and let cool completely.
Set cake on a serving plate and drizzle Icing over top.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Icing
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
1 cup powdered sugar &QL; 
{ teaspoon pure vanilla extract &QL; 
1 to 2 tablespoons buttermilk or low-fat milk &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, whisk together sugar, vanilla and enough
buttermilk to make a thick but pourable icing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
