<HEADER>
A5118 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-NUTCRACKERS-COX     11-11 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NUTCRACKERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cheaper not better in nutcrackers
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There it sits. Sure, an occasional guest will pick up the
flimsy, silver-colored gadget sticking out of the bowl, hoping for
an interactive snack. But chances are they will be frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   What we really need is a more effective nutcracker, the better
to bring the nuggets out of their shells. With that in mind, we set
out to compare:
</P>
<P>
   The ubiquitous, cheap (Good Cook brand, $1.59 at Kroger, with
two picks) cast aluminum tool is made in China. It has two arms
separately mounted to a third crosspiece. You simply put the nut
between the arms and squeeze with one hand. While it works well
enough if you just need a nut or two, much more and your hand will
be sore tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   A step up is Bonny brand ($3.99, Publix), a handheld version
made in Italy. It has a hinge at the top connecting two coated
metal arms that swing open wide enough to accommodate any nuts or
shellfish. It is difficult to get a good grip on and seems to work
best with small hands and on nuts with soft or medium shells. But
after just a few uses, its painted coating was starting to wear
off. This one would do for a young person parked in front of the TV
watching Thanksgiving Day parades who still wants to make a
contribution to the feast.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, especially for people with larger hands, is the Bar
Works nutcracker made in China and sold by Ekco ($5.57, Wal-Mart).
It doesn't open quite as wide as the Bonny and is top-hinged and
designed to be squeezed with one hand. Its more substantial size
and weight help crack nuts with far less effort.
</P>
<P>
   For really effective nutcracking, though, you have to go beyond
the grocery to a hardware store _ beyond top hinges to tabletop
models employing leverage and cams.
</P>
<P>
   One is Duke's Easy Pecan and Nut Cracker ($9.49, Ace Hardware),
made in China of machined steel. A threaded cone adjusts for sizes
from large walnuts to small hazelnuts. Rest the nut between the
cones and pull down on the lever. With very little effort, you can
crack a lot of nuts in a little time. The design also protects the
nuts, delivering pressure on both ends and cracking them in the
middle, allowing you to remove the shells without mashing the
nutmeats more often than not. The unit sits on a plank of wood and
should be fastened to a work surface or, at least, screwed to a
heavier, wider wood plank like similar models made half a century
ago and still working well.
</P>
<P>
   None we tested compared with the simple charm, though, of an
antique owned by Brock Smith of Dawson County, who found it in an
old house in Florida. When his wife, Gail, needs some nuts for her
holiday baking, Smith attaches the small cast iron unit to the
porch railing at his Lake Lanier home, sending pecan shells flying.
</P>
<P>
   A hammer works, too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 1344EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5119 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-NUTS-COX     11-11 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NUTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Get Cracking
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a bowl of mixed nuts on your coffee table, remember?
</P>
<P>
   You scooped them out of the bins at the grocery store as one of
the first sure signs of fall and good things to come.
</P>
<P>
   So pretty, so seasonal. And probably, so ... neglected. Chances
are they will sit there decoratively, uncracked, through
Thanksgiving, a couple of holiday parties, maybe even till
Valentine's Day before winding up as squirrel food in the compost
bin.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they can be a pain to crack. But what a pity to waste the
crunchy morsels, their various flavors as rich and identifiable as
the shapes, tints and textures of the tough shells in which they
are locked. There may be a few common walnuts and pecans, but what
else? Hazelnuts that look like tiny acorns, dark and exotic Brazil
nuts, teardrop-shaped almonds. If only you had the time to crack
them open, you'd find the ingredients for distinctive holiday
creations, like an almond cake with bits of boiled orange peel or
green beans dressed up with mustard seeds and hazelnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for those of us unwilling to invest the labor, most
nuts are available, year-round, in forms that are just as
convenient as we desire _ cracked, shelled, whole, in halves,
pieces or ground _ so long as you're willing to pay the price.
Hazelnuts in the shell in the grocery bin may cost just $1.99 a
pound in November, but a 2-pound bag of shelled hazelnuts anytime
will set you back $18.50 at Williams-Sonoma.
</P>
<P>
   If you are lucky enough to have a few pecan trees, there are
still businesses around like Patrick Feed &AMP; Seed in Covington
(770-786-3220), where they will crack the nuts for you for 25 cents
a pound. If you're looking for crackers in other locations, try
asking at hardware or feed stores for the nearest one.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are folks eager to put in the effort to crack and
shell nuts, measuring the value in terms other than pounds or
cupfuls.
</P>
<P>
   For Kathy Attaway of Augusta, for instance, it's the memories
they conjure _ of helping her invalid mother make fruitcakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would always make two at one time,'' she recalled, ``one to
have for Thanksgiving and one to keep for Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   After her mother, Betty Jane Davidson, became too ill to cook,
she would sit at the kitchen table and instruct.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would crack the walnuts or pecans and pick out the nutmeat
pieces _ one nutmeat for me and one for the bowl,'' Attaway said.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Partee's nutcracking memories are not so fond. Through an
ad in the Farmers and Consumers Market Bulletin, she practically
begs scavengers to haul off the droppings of her five-tree
``nuisance'' crop of black walnuts in Social Circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good nut, if you can ever get to the meat,'' Partee
said. ``Sometimes, you can hit them with a hammer and it'll just
bounce off.''
</P>
<P>
   She said many older people, some in their 80s, have taken her up
on the deal. ``Up in that age they are willing to fool with them
and do what it takes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And what it takes sounds nutty to some.
</P>
<P>
   Lurene and Rogers Odell of Oakwood go through a ritual that
includes drying the green husks, hanging them in net bags and
cracking them with a hammer. Only then can the retired couple sit
down for one in an almost unbroken chain of long evenings picking
out the walnut bits.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the attraction isn't the $18 a quart they get selling
a quart of nutmeats through the Market Bulletin. It's just
something they've done for 20 years, enjoying both the work and the
result, Mrs. Odell said.
</P>
<P>
   When a cupful goes into a poundcake or a handful into a batch of
brownies, Mr. Odell may grimace at the amount of work being stirred
into the batter. But the result takes Mrs. Odell back to her
mother's kitchen and an icebox fruitcake that defined the holidays
when she was a child.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
