<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5120 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BREAD-PUDDING-HNS &LR;      11-11 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAD-PUDDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAD PUDDING MAKES IT TO THE BIG TIME 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
EDITORS: Photos available on the New York Times photo service By ANN CRISWELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like fruit cobbler, bread pudding is a homey comfort dessert
that's made it to the big time. Devised by thrifty cooks as a way
to recycle stale bread, bread pudding has been traced to Colonial
times.
</P>
<P>
   According to Linda Hegeman and Barbara Hayford, authors of
``New-Fangled, Old-Fashioned Bread Puddings'' (St. Martin's Press,
$10.95), it must have been an everyday dish. They found no
reference to it in formal menus from Colonial times.
</P>
<P>
   Bread pudding has made a great resurgence in the '90s. Modern
cooks are more concerned with taste than thrift. You'll find bread
pudding on most upscale restaurant menus. Trendy chefs have given
the humble dessert status by using such exotic ingredients as
croissants, specialty breads, gingerbread, apples, white chocolate,
macadamias, hazelnuts, chocolate chips, dried cherries or
cranberries, sweet potatoes, pumpkin, brandy, rum and liqueurs.
</P>
<P>
   Hegeman and Hayford define old-fashioned bread puddings as those
made from the basics _ stale bread, eggs, milk and sugar, with only
raisins and spice thrown in for flair. Newfangled bread puddings
are innovative combinations of ingredients such as those mentioned
above.
</P>
<P>
   Some chefs bake extra bread for bread pudding or use leftover
unused bread. Croissants, cinnamon-raisin bread, cranberry-orange
bread, rolls and muffins also can be used; adjust the sugar
accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Making your own
</P>
<P>
   The following tips are from ``New-Fangled, Old-Fashioned Bread
Puddings:''
</P>
<P>
   Bread:
</P>
<P>
   Use bakery or bakery-quality bread instead of commercial brands.
If you don't have a favorite bakery, check supermarkets; most have
in-store bakeries.
</P>
<P>
   Some acceptable commercial breads: Pepperidge Farm Original for
recipes requiring firm-textured white bread; canned New England
brown bread; and tortillas.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, French bread and Italian bread are similar
and may be used interchangeably as long as measurements remain the
same in cups or ounces. Because the shapes of French and Italian
loaves may vary, the number of slices is not an accurate
measurement when making substitutions.
</P>
<P>
   Crumbs are made from bakery breads. Never use commercially
packaged crumbs.
</P>
<P>
   Day-old or stale bread is bread that has lost some of its
moisture and is firmer, drier and more crumbly than fresh bread; it
is not hard or brittle.
</P>
<P>
   When you cannot use day-old bread immediately to make bread
pudding, wrap it in plastic wrap, overwrap with aluminum foil and
freeze until ready to use. Do not refrigerate bread; this does not
preserve freshness and does not stale the bread.
</P>
<P>
   Leftover bread, cranberry-orange bread, rolls and pastries may
be used instead of plain bread. Adjust sugar accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   To make ``instant'' stale bread: Place fresh bread slices, cubes
or crumbs in a 300-degree oven until they begin to lose some of
their moisture. Or leave bread uncovered to air-dry several hours
or overnight. Do not overdry the bread.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't wish to use the crusts, remove them before drying
the bread; it's harder to do after the bread is stale.
</P>
<P>
   Eggs:
</P>
<P>
   Use Grade A large eggs unless otherwise stipulated.
</P>
<P>
   Do not taste uncooked egg mixtures because of the potential
danger of salmonella poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   When beating egg whites, use a large clean, dry bowl. Egg whites
should be room temperature, Even a speck of yolk in egg whites will
keep them from beating up properly.
</P>
<P>
   Egg substitutes generally can be used instead of eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Milk:
</P>
<P>
   Hegeman and Hayford recommend using whole milk, half-and-half
and/or whipping cream.
</P>
<P>
   Nuts:
</P>
<P>
   Use fresh nuts. Toasting them improves the flavor. Store nuts in
airtight containers in the refrigerator or freezer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About the custard
</P>
<P>
   There are several correct methods for preparing the custard for
bread pudding, according to the book.
</P>
<P>
   In many recipes, the liquid is heated before it is added to eggs
or the egg mixture. Heating the liquid tempers the eggs to keep
them from curdling, starts the cooking process and shortens the
final cooking time.
</P>
<P>
   If using this method, bring the liquid just under the boiling
point. Remove from heat when it starts to steam, when a light film
appears on the surface or when bubbles appear at the edge. Add a
bit of the heated liquid gradually to eggs or egg mixture, whisking
constantly until incorporated to keep eggs from curdling. If foam
develops, skim and discard.
</P>
<P>
   In some recipes, the liquid is not heated but is added directly
to the eggs. In sweet recipes, when eggs and liquid are combined
without heating the liquid first, strain the custard through a
fine-mesh sieve.
</P>
<P>
   Some bread puddings are baked in a water bath. Set the bread
pudding pan inside a larger ovenproof pan, place in the oven and
add enough hot water to come halfway up the sides of the smaller
pan or baking dish. A water bath keeps eggs from cooking too
quickly and helps the pudding cook evenly from the outside to the
center. A pudding with a high ratio of custard to bread should
always be cooked in a water bath. With more bread than custard, a
water bath is not needed.
</P>
<P>
   To test doneness, a sharp knife is inserted into the pudding one
inch from the center; if it comes out clean, the pudding is done.
Lightly press the top of the area where the knife was inserted. If
liquid oozes out of the knife hole, the pudding is not done.
</P>
<P>
   Do not overbake. All puddings continue to cook slightly when
removed from the oven, Hegeman and Hayford say.
</P>
<P>
   When the pudding is done, remove it from the oven and from the
water bath, if used. Place on a wire rack and cool. To store, let
the pudding come to room temperature, cover and refrigerate. Keep
for no longer than five days. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 1344EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
