<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5121 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-NUTS-RECIPES-COX     11-11 3117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NUTS-RECIPES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Get cracking with recipes from Presley's
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EATONTON, Ga._ Georgians know pecans, producing more than any
other state. So it's not surprising that travelers who used to drop
by Presley's Nut House north of Eatonton came looking for pecan
pie.
</P>
<P>
   But Love Presley, who ran the business with her husband, David
Leon Presley, for 15 years, was too busy to bake, what with all her
shopkeeping duties.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she sold them the pecans they sought, along with
almonds, peanuts and her own pecan clusters. She also tossed in
tips picked up in the ``retirement'' avocation:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Freeze pecans to keep them fresh. Even if you thaw too many to
use at one time, go ahead and refreeze them. Because they're
oil-based, it's OK.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sprinkle almonds on any kind of salad to add a nice crunch.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Scatter chopped peanuts on a bowl of soup.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lightly toast any nuts to bring out a richer flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Listening to so many requests for pies and the like led Presley
to publish ``Treasured Recipes,'' a compilation of 48 years' worth
of her own and others' efforts, many calling for nuts. She sold it
as a souvenir, sending her customers home with the book, some nuts
and the potential to experiment on their own.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Georgia pecan crop is expected to be just over half
of last year's _ and the prices will be somewhat higher, making it
an especially good time to fish in the mixed-nut bowl for some
lesser-known nuts and try something new.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   My Mother's Applesauce Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings Preparation time: 20-25 minutes Cooking time:
about 1 hour and 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   When Kathy Attaway of Augusta, Ga., picked out the ``yucky'' red
and green chunks from the fruitcake she and her mother had made,
her mother developed this recipe using only ingredients her
daughter loved.
</P>
<P>
   1cup (2 sticks) butter or margarine, softened
</P>
<P>
   2cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   3large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1cup cherry or strawberry preserves
</P>
<P>
   2cups unsweetened applesauce
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   3cups all-purpose flour, sifted
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon ground mace
</P>
<P>
   1pound raisins
</P>
<P>
   1cup chopped walnuts or pecans
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon grated orange peel
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon grated lemon peel
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease a 10-inch tube pan.
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl, cream together butter or margarine and
sugar. Add eggs, one at a time, beating well after each addition.
Add preserves and mix well. In a small bowl, mix applesauce and
baking soda, stirring until soda is dissolved. Into another bowl,
sift together the flour, cinnamon, cloves, nutmeg and mace. Add the
raisins, nuts and grated orange and lemon peel to the dry
ingredients. Add dry ingredients to the butter mixture alternately
with applesauce, stirring well after each addition. Pour batter
into prepared pan. Bake 1 hour and 15 minutes or until toothpick
comes out clean. Cool 10 minutes on rack before removing from pan.
Allow flavors to mellow up to several days before cutting.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 496 calories, 5 grams protein, 18 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 32), 83 grams carbohydrates, 40
milligrams cholesterol, 226 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Love Presley's Pecan Pie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings Preparation time: 15 minutes Cooking time:
45-50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Love Presley doesn't know how many of these pies she's made
through the years, but it's one of her favorites. Adding
self-rising flour helps prevent a common problem with pecan pies _
runny filling _ and chopping the pecans before adding them to the
filling makes cutting the pie easier.
</P>
<P>
   3large eggs, slightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   1cup light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   1cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2heaping tablespoons self-rising flour
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons margarine, melted
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups pecans, chopped or halves
</P>
<P>
   19-inch deep dish pie crust
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees and heat cookie sheet in oven. In a
large bowl, stir together eggs, syrup, sugar, flour, margarine and
vanilla until well-blended. Stir in pecans. Pour into thawed or
frozen crust. Bake on cookie sheet 45 to 50 minutes or until knife
inserted halfway between center and edge comes out clean. _ Adapted
from: ``Treasured Recipes'' by Love Presley (Fundcraft Publishing,
$10)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 546 calories, 7 grams protein, 28 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 46), 72 grams carbohydrates, 119
milligrams cholesterol, 269 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Spiced Mixed Nuts
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 1/2 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   With just a zip of effort, you can add a lot of zing to the
party nuts. This is especially tasty with pecans.
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2cups mixed whole almonds, raw cashews, pecans and/or raw
peanuts
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4to 1/2 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 300 degrees. Place mixed nuts in large bowl.
Heat vegetable oil in heavy, small saucepan over medium heat. Add
chili powder and cayenne pepper to taste and stir until aromatic,
about 15 seconds. Pour over mixed nuts. Add sugar and salt and stir
to blend. Transfer to baking pan. Bake until mixed nuts are
toasted, stirring occasionally, about 20 to 25 minutes. Serve warm
or at room temperature. (Can be made 5 days ahead. Cover and store
at room temperature.) _ From Bon Appetit magazine, August 1991
</P>
<P>
   Per 1/4 cup: 228 calories, 5 grams protein, 20 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 80), 10 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 244 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Spicy Nut Salsa With Blue Cheese
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 1/2 cups Preparation time: 5-10 minutes Cooking time:
7-9 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Not your typical salsa, this is a rather innovative dip served
with endive spears or celery sticks. It's also a great topping for
lamb medallions.
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons hazelnut oil or olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4teaspoons dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons ground allspice
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup hazelnuts, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup pecan pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup slivered almonds, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1cup chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   1cup crumbled Gorgonzola cheese or blue cheese (about 5 1/2
ounces)
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   In heavy, large skillet over medium heat, heat oil, mustard and
allspice. Add nuts and saute until golden, about 7 minutes.
Transfer to large bowl. Stir celery, cheese and honey into warm nut
mixture. Season with salt and pepper. (Can be prepared 2 days
ahead. Cover and refrigerate. Bring to room temperature before
using.) _ From Bon Appetit magazine, July 1993
</P>
<P>
   Per tablespoon: 41 calories, 1 gram protein, 4 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 79), 2 grams carbohydrates, 2
milligrams cholesterol, 41 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Three-Nut Torte With Vanilla Glaze
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 45-50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Densely packed with nuts, this cake puts the contents of a
mixed-nut bowl to good use. Alter the combination of nuts depending
on what you like or what you have on hand.
</P>
<P>
   CAKE:
</P>
<P>
   1cup walnuts
</P>
<P>
   2/3cup Brazil nuts
</P>
<P>
   2/3cup toasted hazelnuts (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4cups sifted unbleached all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   4large eggs
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup dark corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2teaspoons vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup (1 stick) unsalted butter, melted and cooled
</P>
<P>
   VANILLA GLAZE:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups sifted confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   6tablespoons boiling water
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2teaspoons light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   3/4teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   12walnut halves for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Position rack in the lower third of the oven and preheat to 350
degrees. Butter a 9-inch springform pan. Cut out a circle of
parchment paper to fit inside the pan and press it into the bottom
of the pan.
</P>
<P>
   Place the walnuts, Brazil nuts and hazelnuts in the bowl of a
food processor fitted with the steel blade. Process 8 to 10 seconds
or just until the nuts are coarsely chopped. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   For the cake: Using a triple sifter, sift together the flour,
baking powder, baking soda, salt and nutmeg. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Put the eggs in the large bowl of an electric mixer. Using the
beaters or whip attachment, beat on medium-high speed until the
eggs are light in color and thickened, about 5 minutes. Add the
sugar, 1 tablespoon at a time, taking about 4 to 5 minutes to blend
it in well. Pour in the dark corn syrup in a steady stream,
scraping the sides of the bowl as necessary, and beat for 30
seconds longer. Reduce speed to medium. Blend in the vanilla. Pour
in the melted butter in a steady stream, taking about 30 seconds,
and beat 2 minutes longer. Reduce speed to medium-low. Add the dry
ingredients all at once. Scrape the sides of the bowl and mix for
20 seconds longer. Remove the bowl from the mixer and fold in all
the chopped nuts. Pour the batter into the prepared pan. Set the
pan on a 12-inch square of aluminum foil and bring the edges of the
foil up to form a drip pan.
</P>
<P>
   Center the pan on the rack and bake in the preheated oven 45 to
50 minutes, or until the cake begins to come away from the sides of
the pan and is golden brown, with the top springy to the touch.
(Cakes made with dark corn syrup tend to brown too quickly. If this
happens, place a square of aluminum foil over the top during the
last 10 minutes of baking.)
</P>
<P>
   Remove the cake from the oven and set on a rack to cool for 15
minutes. Run a thin knife around the sides of the cake, then remove
the sides of the springform pan. Invert the cake onto the rack,
lift off the bottom of the pan and carefully peel off the
parchment. Turn the cake top side up. While the cake is still warm,
prepare the glaze.
</P>
<P>
   For the Vanilla Glaze: Put the confectioners' sugar in a medium
mixing bowl. Add the boiling water, corn syrup and vanilla and
blend with a wire whisk until smooth. Brush glaze thinly on the
sides and top of the warm cake, reserving about 1/3 of the glaze.
</P>
<P>
   Add the walnut halves to the remaining glaze, turning the nuts
with a fork until coated. (If the glaze is too thick, thin with a
few drops of hot water.) Lift the nuts individually out of the
glaze and position in a circle 1 inch from the edge of the cake,
spacing them evenly. The cake should stand uncovered until the
glaze sets, about a half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   Storage: Store the cake at room temperature under a glass dome
or in an airtight container for up to 5 days.
</P>
<P>
   Note: To toast nuts, preheat oven to 300 degrees. Place nuts in
a single layer on a heavy flat pan with sides, such as a jellyroll
pan. Bake skinned nuts until they turn a light golden color. Bake
unskinned nuts until they develop a sweet, toasted smell. Whole
almonds and hazelnuts can take 12 minutes or more. Stir after 5
minutes and watch carefully so they do not burn.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 453 calories, 9 grams protein, 26 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 52), 48 grams carbohydrates, 127
milligrams cholesterol, 217 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   VEGETABLE
</P>
<P>
   Indian-Style Green Beans With Hazelnuts
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 20 minutes Cooking time: 18
minutes
</P>
<P>
   Adding chopped nuts to stir-fries and steamed veggies is an easy
way to make a dish more complex. Here, Indian-style spices and
coconut set these green beans apart from everyday fare.
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup clarified butter (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon mustard seeds (black seeds are preferable and are
available at Indian markets and some specialty foods shops)
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup chopped hazelnuts
</P>
<P>
   1large onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon grated peeled fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1pound green beans, trimmed, cut into 2-inch pieces and blanched
in boiling salted water for 2 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of cayenne
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup grated fresh coconut or unsweetened dried coconut
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons finely chopped cilantro, plus sprigs for garnish
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet or wok, heat the butter over moderately high
heat until hot but not smoking. Stir-fry the mustard seeds and
hazelnuts in the butter for 5 minutes, or until the hazelnuts are
browned lightly, and transfer the mixture to a bowl. To the skillet
add the onion, ginger, salt and black pepper and cook, stirring,
until the onions are softened. Stir in the green beans, cayenne,
coconut and chopped cilantro, reduce heat to medium-low and cook,
covered, stirring occasionally, for 5 to 7 minutes or until the
beans are crisp-tender. Stir in the hazelnut mixture and lemon
juice, cook until heated through and transfer to a serving bowl.
Garnish with the cilantro sprigs.
</P>
<P>
   Note: To clarify butter: In a heavy saucepan over low heat, melt
1-inch pieces of unsalted butter. Remove pan from heat and let sit
3 minutes. Skim the froth from the top, and then strain the butter
through a sieve lined with a double thickness of rinsed and
squeezed cheesecloth into a bowl, leaving the milky solids in the
bottom of the pan. Pour the clarified butter into a jar or crock
and store it, covered, in the refrigerator. _ Adapted from Gourmet
magazine, November 1990
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 162 calories, 3 grams protein, 14 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 75), 10 grams carbohydrates, 16
milligrams cholesterol, 204 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Orange Almond Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   If you like the intense flavor of orange-slice candy, you'll
love this flourless cake from the Middle East. Boiling the oranges
removes any bitterness from the bits of peel, which nicely balance
the almonds.
</P>
<P>
   2large oranges (preferably seedless navels)
</P>
<P>
   6large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups ground almonds
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   1cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   Garnish: Thin slices of peeled orange sprinkled with
confectioners' sugar and a touch of cinnamon, or fresh raspberries
</P>
<P>
   Whipped cream
</P>
<P>
   Wash the oranges and boil them whole, with their peels on, in
water to cover until very soft, about 30 minutes. Drain, cool, cut
into quarters and remove the seeds, if any. Process the oranges to
a fairly fine puree in a blender or food processor or by putting
them through a meat grinder. Don't make it too fine. The little
bits of skin, which will not be at all bitter after the long
boiling, are pleasant to bite on.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Beat the eggs in a bowl until
thick, then add the ground almonds, salt, sugar, baking powder and
orange puree and mix well. Pour into a deep 9-inch cake pan that
has been buttered and floured, and bake for 1 hour or longer, until
firm to the touch when pressed with the tip of your finger. Begin
checking after cake has baked for 45 minutes. Remove the pan to a
rack, allow the cake to cool, then turn it out of the pan onto a
serving dish. Serve garnished with orange slices or berries and
whipped cream. _ From ``The New James Beard'' (Knopf, 1981)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 356 calories, 12 grams protein, 19 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 48), 42 grams carbohydrates, 239
milligrams cholesterol, 188 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Black Walnut Cookies
</P>
<P>
   Makes 100 small cookies Preparation time: 25 minutes Chilling
time: at least 4 hours Cooking time: 12 minutes per batch
</P>
<P>
   Even with a ``very prolific'' tree in her yard, food stylist
Mary Ann Clayton of Jasper buys the black walnut meats for these
flavorful, tiny cookies. Husking, shelling and picking out even 1/2
cup of nuts is just too much work when they are readily available
in stores, she says.
</P>
<P>
   1 3/4cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   3ounces cream cheese, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup (1 stick) butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1egg, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup chopped black walnuts
</P>
<P>
   Sift together the flour, salt and baking powder.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, beat the cream cheese, sour cream and butter
until smooth. Add the sugar and beat until well blended. Add the
egg and vanilla and beat until well-combined. Stir the flour and
nuts into the wet mixture. Shape into a ball, flatten and cover
with plastic wrap. Refrigerate 4 hours to overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees and cover cookie sheets with
parchment paper. Divide the dough in half and return one portion to
the refrigerator until ready to use (may be kept refrigerated up to
two days). Roll out the other portion very thinly and cut with a
cookie cutter. Put cookies on cookie sheets and bake for 10 to 12
minutes or until the edges become lightly browned.
</P>
<P>
   Per cookie: 32 calories, less than 1 gram protein, 2 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 48), 4 grams carbohydrates, 6
milligrams cholesterol, 31 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   White Chocolate Covered Nuts
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 80 pieces Preparation time: 30 minutes Cooking time:
15-20 minutes Standing time: at least 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   We tested this recipe with hazelnuts, but you can use any nuts
you like. A pound of hazelnuts in the shell will yield about 1 1/2
cups of nuts and, if you've shelled them carefully and not toasted
them too long, which would make them brittle, you should have about
a cup of whole nuts.
</P>
<P>
   1cup whole toasted nuts, such as hazelnuts, almonds, pecans or
walnuts
</P>
<P>
   6ounces (6 squares) white baking chocolate
</P>
<P>
   In the top of a double boiler set over hot water, stir chocolate
squares until melted. Remove pan from heat and let the chocolate
cool until it is no longer runny. Transfer the chocolate into a
small deep bowl and have ready another bowl filled with hot water
over which to set the chocolate if it becomes too thick.
</P>
<P>
   Spear one of the nuts with a clean straight pin and dip it in
the chocolate, coating it completely and letting the excess drip
off. Transfer the nut to a sheet of wax paper and remove the pin
from the nut, gently pressing on the nut with a toothpick or tip of
a sharp knife and make a swirl in the chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Coat the remaining nuts in the same manner.
</P>
<P>
   Let the candies stand in a cool place until the chocolate is
set, at least 2 hours. Do not refrigerate. Put them in fluted paper
cases, fitting 3 or 4 in each, or wrap in small foil squares,
available at kitchen specialty shops, and arrange in one layer in
tins.
</P>
<P>
   Per piece (hazelnuts): 16 calories, less than 1 gram protein, 1
gram fat (percent calories from fat, 77), 1 gram carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, less than 1 milligram sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
