<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fruit and nuts add Kentucky kick to cake
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pecans from Georgia and pineapple from Hawaii provide the
fruit-and-nut flavors in Kentucky Poundcake, requested by Bev
Sibley.
</P>
<P>
   If you're buying pecans now during their peak to use later, the
Georgia Pecan Commission recommends putting them in plastic bags
and freezing them for up to two years.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky Poundcake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 hour and 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Butter and flour for preparing pan
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2cups self-rising flour
</P>
<P>
   2cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   4large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4cups vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon pure vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   18-ounce can crushed pineapple packed in syrup
</P>
<P>
   FROSTING:
</P>
<P>
   2cups confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   4tablespoons margarine, softened
</P>
<P>
   4ounces cream cheese, softened
</P>
<P>
   Grease and flour a 10-inch tube pan. Preheat oven to 350
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   For the cake: In a large mixing bowl, combine flour, granulated
sugar, eggs, oil, pecans, vanilla and crushed pineapple, with the
pineapple syrup, in a bowl. Blend and pour into the prepared pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 1 hour and 15 minutes, or until a cake tester inserted in
the center comes out clean. Remove cake from pan and cool.
</P>
<P>
   For the frosting: In a mixing bowl, blend confectioners' sugar,
margarine and cream cheese. Spread on cooled cake and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 514 calories, 5 grams protein, 30 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 52), 59 grams carbohydrates, 87
milligrams cholesterol, 328 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   -- Annette Wade is looking for a recipe to match Campbell's
Restaurant Style Broccoli Cheese Soup, a thing of the past. She's
also hoping to get the recipe for a hot open-faced chicken salad
sandwich that was served at Cashin's restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   -- Marie McNeil of Roswell is looking for a recipe she lost. Ham
and cheese were layered between slivers of eggplant and dipped in
egg and cracker crumbs.
</P>
<P>
   Where to write
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests for recipes for this column should be sent
to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Include a daytime telephone
number. E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
