<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`L.A. DOCTORS' MISSING A DOSE OF REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With ``Seinfeld'' dead and the ``X-Files'' on life support, I am
in the market for a new favorite television show. My first choice
is WB's ``Dawson's Creek,'' for its hilarious portrayal of Dawson's
parents' open marriage. But there are children in the house, so
``Dawson'' is a forbidden pleasure. Once they are safely in bed, I
can savor ``L.A. Doctors,'' which airs Monday nights at 10 p.m. on
CBS.
</P>
<P>
   The ``L.A. Doctors'' in question are four telegenic internists
who have rebelled against Big Medicine and have set themselves up
in a private practice ``where the care isn't managed and patients
matter more than the bottom line.'' Their Santa Monica office has
excellent lighting (and good feng shui, I wager), as well as an
attractive, courteous staff.
</P>
<P>
   Number One Doc Roger Cattan (Ken Olin) drives a Jaguar, dresses
to kill, and has sex with numerous beautiful women. Beautiful
people like basketball star Reggie Miller show up in his examining
room. One male nurse is so beautiful that he posed for
``Playgirl.'' Dr. Sarah Church, played by Sheryl Lee, could be
wearing Spandex on ``Baywatch.'' The lupus patient is beautiful.
She's the one who prepared a home-cooked Chinese dinner for her
care provider, Dr. Evan Newman, played by Canadian actor Rick
Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Their beauty is not just skin deep. These docs are noble on the
inside, too. They battle against hard-hearted HMO officials. They
pay more house calls than vaccum cleaner salesmen. They are so
gosh-darned compassionate, I picture them using ouch-less bandages
and penetration-free hypodermics. Judging from the four or five
shows I've watched, the number-one health need in LA is a Viagra
prescription, a conceit that is probably not so far-fetched.
</P>
<P>
   In ``L.A Doctors,'' even when things are bad, they're good. Dr.
Newman is the most genteel ex-husband you'd ever want to meet.
Divorced from his beautful, perfect (if hypochondriac) wife, he
sees more of his perfect children that I see of my own (nearly)
perfect children _ and I'm not busy saving the world from corporate
hyenas. Not only does Dr. N have a warm, loving relationship with
his ex-wife, but the writers are setting him up to romance Dr.
Church. On Monday night, she and Dr. Right were engaged in what
Bill Clinton would call inappropriate touching, at least until her
husband showed up. This is LA misery? Throw me in that briar patch!
</P>
<P>
   In a conversation with co-executive producer Gardner Stern, I
floated the notion that this practice seemed more glamorous than
many. ``Los Angeles is a minor character in the show,'' he said,
``and there are certain unique characteristics of doing things in
LA. Medicine is not excepted from that.''
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, there are occasional outbursts of crackerjack
writing, mostly accruing to the world-wise Olin character. On
Monday night, he challenged the doctors' code of omerta by
questioning the competence of an assembly-line plastic surgeon. A
couple of weeks ago, he bearded a crooked radiology technician and
explained to him ``how the world works.''
</P>
<P>
   In that vein, let me explain to you how the television world
works. CBS doesn't care what holier-than-thou columnists think
about its show. It cares about the ratings. So far, the ratings are
not great, but okay. ``L.A. Doctors'' loses its time slot to NBC's
trashy ``Dateline'' and to Monday Night Football, but does well
with female viewers. Stern is cautiously optimistic that the
network will order new shows for spring. A CBS spokeswoman says no
decision has been made.
</P>
<P>
   I am not the first to note that ``L.A. Doctors'' continues the
Los Angeles-ification of American television. On the heels of
``L.A. Law'' the networks offered up ``L.A. Firefighters,'' a
special on ``L.A. Lifeguards,'' and ``Leaving L.A.,'' a drama set
in the coroner's office. The logical sequel will be ``L.A.
Journalists,'' about a newspaper where the circulation is always
rising, the editors never speak sharply to reporters, and where the
scrupulously accurate columnists are always, always fair.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 1345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
