<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5124 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BREAD-PUDDING-RECIPES     11-11 2012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAD-PUDDING-RECIPES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
EDITORS: BREAD-PUDDING-RECIPES is a sidebar to BREAD-PUDDING
<TEXT>
<P>
   Black Labrador's Bread Pudding
</P>
<P>
   This Chronicle file recipe is from the Black Labrador Pub.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
2 apples (recipe developed with Granny Smith apples), cored and
thinly sliced &QL; 
1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice &QL; 
\ cup plus 1 tablespoon brown sugar, divided &QL; 
1 teaspoon ground cinnamon, divided &QL; 
1 { loaves French bread (large loaves, not baguettes) &QL; 
 &QL; 
3 { cups milk &QL; 
{ cup granulated sugar &QL; 
5 eggs &QL; 
\ cup brandy &QL; 
\ teaspoon almond flavoring &QL; 
{ teaspoon ground nutmeg &QL; 
2 ounces raisins (} cup) &QL; 
} cup apricot preserves &QL; 
Brandy Cream Sauce (recipe follows) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Soak apples in lemon juice, 1 tablespoon brown sugar and {
teaspoon cinnamon. Cover and refrigerate overnight before using.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Remove crust from 1 loaf French
bread and slice lengthwise down the middle, then cut into 8 pieces.
Pour milk into a small pot and add granulated sugar; bring to a
boil. Beat eggs, brandy and almond flavoring together. Whisk in a
little of the hot milk, then add remainder, whisking until mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Layer half the bread pieces in a 9-inch-square pan; pour half
the liquid mixture over it. Mash mixture with your hands, then pat
down into a layer.
</P>
<P>
   Mix prepared apples with nutmeg, remaining cinnamon, remaining
brown sugar, some of the remaining milk mixture and raisins; spoon
over bread. Remove crust from remaining bread; cut bread into 1
{-inch rounds. Overlap bread on top of apples, and pour remaining
milk mixture on top. Bake 25 minutes. Remove from oven; glaze with
apricot preserves.
</P>
<P>
   Cut bread pudding into servings; place each serving in a bowl.
Pour Brandy Cream Sauce over each serving; serve hot. Makes 9
servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brandy Cream Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
2 cups whipping cream &QL; 
2 ounces brandy &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 tablespoon ground cinnamon &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beat cream with brandy and cinnamon until mixture thickens.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Warm Croissant Bread Pudding
</P>
<P>
   A signature dish at Bistro Lancaster in Houston created by
former Lancaster Hotel executive chef Louis Cressy. This is an
all-time great bread pudding; the croissants give it a light,
delicate texture.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
8 egg yolks plus 1 egg &QL; 
1 } cups sugar &QL; 
1 tablespoon vanilla extract &QL; 
1 } teaspoons salt &QL; 
} cup milk &QL; 
3 cups whipping cream &QL; 
9 large croissants, torn into pieces &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dried Cherry Sauce (recipe follows) &QL; 
2 cups Rum Vanilla Bean Caramel Sauce (recipe follows) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Combine egg yolks, egg, sugar, vanilla and salt in a large bowl.
Whisk in milk and cream; strain through a fine strainer.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Arrange croissant pieces in an
11-by-7-by-2-inch baking pan. Pour in as much egg mixture as needed
to soak croissants, leaving a little of the croissants visible on
top; cover with foil. Place pan in a larger pan; fill larger pan
with 1 inch of hot water. Bake 45 minutes or until knife inserted
in center comes out clean. Remove from water bath; cool to room
temperature to serve. Serve with Dried Cherry Sauce and Rum Vanilla
Bean Caramel Sauce. Makes 8 to 10 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dried Cherry Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
1 { cups dried cherries &QL; 
{ cup sugar &QL; 
2 cups water &QL; 
 &QL; 
\ cup kirsch (clear cherry brandy) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Combine cherries, sugar and water in small heavy saucepan. Bring
to a simmer and remove from heat. Cool completely. Add kirsch.
Place about 2 tablespoons on top of bread pudding.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rum Vanilla Bean Caramel Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
{ cup water &QL; 
2 cups sugar &QL; 
1 vanilla bean, split and scraped &QL; 
 &QL; 
} cup unsalted butter &QL; 
3 cups whipping cream &QL; 
\ cup rum &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Put water in a heavy medium saucepan and add sugar, but do not
stir. Add vanilla bean; do not stir. Cook over medium heat until
dark in color; swirl pan if necessary, but do not stir. Watch
carefully; do not let burn. Stir in butter over low heat. Add
cream, then rum. Serve warm. Cover and refrigerate extra sauce for
future use. To serve, drizzle around and over bread pudding. Makes
about 5{ cups. Cressy recommends making the sauce in this quantity,
although you need only 2 cups for this recipe. The remainder can be
used with other desserts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sweet Potato Pecan Bread Pudding
</P>
<P>
   From Tommy Child, new executive chef at the Lancaster Hotel in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
3 medium sweet potatoes, washed &QL; 
4 eggs plus 6 egg yolks &QL; 
1 cup granulated sugar &QL; 
} cup brown sugar &QL; 
1 { teaspoons salt &QL; 
2 cups each: milk and whipping cream &QL; 
1 teaspoon each: ground cinnamon and ginger &QL; 
 &QL; 
{ cup each: raisins and pecan pieces &QL; 
\ cup melted butter &QL; 
8 cups crusty French or European bread, cut into 2-inch cubes &QL; 
2 cups Maple Whipped Cream (recipe follows) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Pierce potatoes with a small knife
or fork. Place on a baking sheet and roast in the oven 45 minutes
or until potatoes test soft when pricked with a knife or fork. (Or,
to microwave, pierce potatoes and place in microwave-safe dish;
microwave on high 6 minutes per pound.) Do not overcook. Let cool.
When cool enough to handle, peel potatoes. Dice into 1- to 1 {-inch
pieces. There should be 4 cups diced potatoes. Reserve 2 cups; mash
remaining potatoes with a large spoon or wire whisk.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine mashed potatoes, eggs, egg yolks,
sugars, salt, milk, cream, cinnamon, ginger, raisins, pecan pieces
and butter. Gently toss bread and reserved potatoes with mashed
potato mixture. Pour into a buttered 11-by-7-by-2-inch baking pan.
Cover with foil. Set a larger pan on middle rack of oven; place
baking pan in it and fill with enough hot water to come halfway up
the sides of smaller pan. Bake 45 minutes or until a knife inserted
in center comes out clean. Remove foil and let top brown slightly,
about 5 more minutes. Remove from water and cool to room
temperature, or keep warm until ready to serve. Serve with a dollop
of Maple Whipped Cream.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maple Whipped Cream
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
2 cups whipping cream (chill cream, bowl and beaters well) &QL; 
 &QL; 
\ cup good-quality maple syrup &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In medium bowl or mixer, whip cream to soft peaks. Add syrup;
whip until incorporated. Refrigerate until ready to serve. Makes 6
to 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Daily Review's Chocolate Cherry Bread Pudding
</P>
<P>
   From Claire Smith, owner and chef of the Daily Review.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
8 (3-ounce) chocolate or plain croissants &QL; 
{ cup dried cherries or dried cranberries &QL; 
\ cup orange juice &QL; 
1 quart whipping cream &QL; 
4 eggs plus 2 egg yolks &QL; 
 &QL; 
{ cup sugar &QL; 
\ cup creme de cacao liqueur &QL; 
\ cup rum &QL; 
1 cup semisweet chocolate chips (only } cup if using chocolate
croissants) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cut croissants into 1-inch cubes. Put in large nonreactive bowl.
Combine cherries and orange juice in saucepan over medium heat and
poach until cherries soften. In another bowl, whisk together cream,
eggs, egg yolks, sugar, crme de cacao and rum.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Pour cream mixture over croissants
and soak 10 minutes. Pour into a 13-by-9-by-2-inch baking dish.
Sprinkle top with chocolate chips. Bake 30 to 40 minutes. Makes 8
to 10 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   White Chocolate Macadamia Nut Bread Pudding
</P>
<P>
   Chef Louis Cressy, now at Tilman Fertitta's Aquarium in Kemah,
Texas, says this bread pudding from Aquarium pastry chef John
MacArevey is world-class. At the restaurant, it is made in
individual 12-ounce ramekins. It's rich and expensive to make,
MacArevey says, but worth every penny.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
15 eggs &QL; 
1 \ cups sugar &QL; 
3 cups each: milk and whipping cream &QL; 
1 tablespoon vanilla extract &QL; 
2 French bread baguettes (about 15 inches long), cut in cubes &QL; 
 &QL; 
2 { cups chopped white chocolate &QL; 
2 cups toasted, chopped macadamia nuts &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Combine eggs and sugar in nonreactive bowl; whisk to combine.
Combine milk, cream and vanilla; pour into egg mixture. Whisk well
and strain. Place bread in a 13-by-9-by-2-inch baking dish. Pour
egg mixture over bread and let soak 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Sprinkle white chocolate over
bread. Sprinkle macadamia nuts over chocolate. Place bread pudding
pan in a larger pan; place both in oven and pour hot water to
within 1 inch of top of bread pudding pan. Bake 45 minutes to 1
hour or until custard is set (internal temperature should be 160
degrees). Remove from oven and cool slightly. This bread pudding is
best when eaten warm. Makes 10 to 12 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pumpkin Rum Bread Pudding
</P>
<P>
   Created by pastry chef and cookbook author Nick Malgieri.
</P>
<P>
   Pumpkin Bread
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
1 cup currants (optional) &QL; 
\ cup spiced rum (recipe developed with Bacardi) &QL; 
1 cup (2 sticks) butter &QL; 
1 \ cups sugar &QL; 
3 eggs &QL; 
1 } cups all-purpose flour &QL; 
2 teaspoons baking powder &QL; 
 &QL; 
{ teaspoon baking soda &QL; 
\ teaspoon salt &QL; 
1 tablespoon ground cinnamon &QL; 
{ teaspoon ground nutmeg &QL; 
[ teaspoon ground cloves &QL; 
1 cup canned pumpkin puree &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease and flour a 9-by-5-by-3-inch
loaf pan. If using currants, soak them in the rum until it is time
to add to ingredients. In the bowl of an electric mixer fitted with
paddle attachment, cream butter and sugar on medium-high speed
until light and airy. Reduce speed to low and add eggs, 1 at a
time, until well incorporated.
</P>
<P>
   In separate bowl, whisk together flour, baking powder, soda,
salt, cinnamon, nutmeg and cloves. Stir rum and currants into
pumpkin pure. Add dry ingredients to butter mixture alternately
with pumpkin mixture, beginning and ending with flour. Pour into
prepared pan and bake 1 hour and 40 minutes, until firm to the
touch. Cool 10 minutes in pan, then invert cake onto a wire rack
and let cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   This is best made a day ahead if it is being used for bread
pudding. It can be made 5 days ahead and refrigerated, covered, or
can be frozen as long as 5 months. Makes 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Custard Mixture
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
3 cups half-and-half &QL; 
1 cup sugar &QL; 
4 eggs &QL; 
 &QL; 
2 tablespoons gold rum (recipe developed with Bacardi Gold) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mix half-and-half and sugar in saucepan. Bring to a boil,
stirring frequently. Whisk eggs and rum until foamy. Whisk in hot
half-and-half mixture until blended. Makes 4 cups (for 4 servings;
double recipe for 8 servings).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To assemble:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. With a serrated knife, level top of
Pumpkin Bread; loaf should measure 4 { inches wide and 2 { inch
high. Slice Pumpkin Bread in half lengthwise to make 2 square logs.
Cut 16 slices from the first log, then cut each square diagonally
to make 2 triangles. Wrap and freeze second log for another use.
(Or, if making 8 servings, cut second log into slices, then
triangles, in the same manner.)
</P>
<P>
   Place 8 bread triangles in each serving-size custard cup, lining
triangles with points facing up. Pour 1 cup Custard Mixture into
each cup over bread triangles. If desired, scatter 2 teaspoons
chopped candied ginger over each serving. Place cups in a roaster
pan; let sit 10 minutes to allow bread to soak. Place pan in oven.
Pour hot water into roaster pan 1 inch deep around custard cups.
Bake 30 to 35 minutes, until custard is set around edges but still
slightly soft toward the center. Remove custard cups from water as
soon as they are removed from oven. Serve warm. Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LeRuth's Bread Pudding
</P>
<P>
   From Chronicle files.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
} cup (1 { sticks) butter, divided &QL; 
4 eggs &QL; 
2 { cups sugar &QL; 
1 quart milk &QL; 
1 tablespoon vanilla &QL; 
\ teaspoon ground mace &QL; 
 &QL; 
} cup raisins &QL; 
{ loaf stale bread, cut into 1-inch thick slices &QL; 
{ cup whipping cream or sour cream &QL;
</P>
<P>
   cup sugar &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Spread { stick softened butter over
a 12-inch round baking pan. Mix eggs, sugar, milk, vanilla and
mace. Stir in raisins. Add bread and let soak 10 minutes. Pour into
pan. Bake until pudding is almost firm. Remove from oven. Increase
temperature to 425 degrees. Pour cream over top of pudding. Cut
remaining butter in pieces; place on top of pudding. Sprinkle
pudding with sugar. Return to oven; bake 10 to 15 minutes until
butter is melted and cream is firm. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
