<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5125 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-11 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUJOLAIS ACQUIRES FANS WHO APPRECIATE VALUE, ACCESSIBILITY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL LONSFORD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The third Thursday in November _ Nov. 19 _ is the day the
Nouveau Beaujolais arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Nouveau Beaujolais is the young, fruity wine from the southern
part of France's Burgundy region, originally intended for Paris
bistros. But in the 1970s _ thanks to a lot of hype and promotion _
Le Nouveau caught the world's fancy.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake: This is simple quaffing stuff, not something to
lay away for your child's 21st birthday, and the prices reflect it:
Almost all sell for less than $10, sometimes a lot less. That's
good news, Part 1.
</P>
<P>
   Good news, Part 2: Nouveau Beaujolais gets here just in time for
the holidays. Its easy drinkability, affordability, and flavors
that match up well with such holiday fare as turkey, ham and
cranberries make it the perfect holiday wine.
</P>
<P>
   Nouveau-style wines made from gamay grapes are now made in many
other countries, as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Red burgundy may be the red wine that inspires the greatest
passion. But it also causes the most frustration.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, there's nothing better; at less than its best, you
want to pour the dreck down the drain and send the winemaker
packing.
</P>
<P>
   Three main problems with red burgundy: very small production,
very high prices and an inconsistent product due to (a) the weather
or (b) lousy winemaking (it's probably a toss-up).
</P>
<P>
   Those old enough to remember when French wines didn't taste like
the rest of the world's know what I'm talking about when I use this
descriptor for red burgundy: barnyard. Doesn't sound very
appetizing, does it? Well, in small doses it can be, as a sort of
complexity index.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, when that barnyard gets too strong ..
</P>
<P>
   That's where the New World or International style of wines comes
in. Such wines are cleaner and usually fruitier. For many American
consumers, that freshness makes up for a lack of complexity that
would be found in the Old Country.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: Last January, while on a trip to New Zealand, I
tasted a pinot noir that was quite good. Problem was, it wasn't
available here. Now it is. The 1996 Gibbston Valley Pinot Noir _ 4
stars to 4 { stars _ has bright cinnamon, clove and smoked-bacon
nuances, just like a top red burgundy from, say, Morey St. Denis.
It's not a heavy wine, but it's an awfully appealing one. And it
would grace any holiday table, because the wine can go with so many
foods.
</P>
<P>
   This is definitely an International-style pinot noir _ not a
barnyard in sight. It isn't cheap _ in the high $20s _ but you'd
pay two or three times that for a red burgundy that might remind
you of a compost heap.
</P>
<P>
   From Prestige Wine Cellars.
</P>
<P>
   Mention single-malt scotch and don't be surprised to hear
someone say, ``Oh, I just love Macallan.''
</P>
<P>
   Macallan is a Highland single-malt that uses predominantly
sherry casks in which to age its whisky. Those sherry casks give
the whisky a full, round, deeply mellow flavor, unlike the sharp,
peaty scotches, say, from Islay to the west.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago, the distillery released Macallan 1874, a
blend especially formulated to imitate that of a bottle of 1874
Macallan purchased at auction for $7,000. The Macallan distillers
sampled the whisky and decided to see if they could replicate it.
They came pretty close. The ``new'' Macallan 1874 would've cost you
around $140 a bottle then.
</P>
<P>
   Now, just in time for the holidays, Macallan has released two
more single-malts. One, the 18-Year-Old Gran Reserva, is a slight
variation on the Macallan theme. The other is a vintage 1946
Macallan, and it is completely different from any Macallan I've
tasted, and I think I've tasted most of the commercial bottlings
around, including one called ``As We Get It,'' 107 proof, in
Scotland some years back.
</P>
<P>
   Macallan's main production consists of a 12-year-old, an
18-year-old and a 25-year-old, ranging in price from $40 for the
12-year-old to more than $200 for the 25-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   I talked with Macallan director Peter Fairlie and distillery
manager David Robertson one evening at Anthony's, and tasted these
two new scotches.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-Year-Old Macallan Gran Reserva _ 4 stars _ is actually a
1979 vintage whisky, and it's from casks that were
``first-filled,'' meaning the best of the best. Robertson said he
had to sample 150 casks to find the best, and ``that's a difficult
inventory to keep on top of.'' Somehow, he allowed with a smile, he
managed.
</P>
<P>
   The whisky has a deep mahogany color, and from the four
components, Robertson said, ``You get at once a floral quality, a
touch of orange and cloves, a certain oiliness on the palate and a
slightly resinous finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Fasten your selt belts, folks, it's going to be a bumpy
financial ride. The retail will be $140-$150 a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   The 1946 Macallan is an equine of another hue.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: For generations, Macallan was known for its smooth
whisky never ``tainted'' by peat. But during World War II,
distilleries didn't have top priority when it came to the use of
coal. So for several years, Macallan had to rely on peat.
</P>
<P>
   The 1946 Macallan reflects that, although not nearly as
pungently as an Islay malt such as Lagavulin. Peatiness in scotch
whisky is measured in parts per million and is referred to in the
business as ``phenolics.'' Lagavulin and Laphroaig, both from Islay
and known for their peaty qualities, have 35-40 ppm. The 1946
Macallan has about 4 ppm, Fairlie said.
</P>
<P>
   The 1946 Macallan _ 5 stars _ is lightish in color and has a
nuance of citrus, almost lemon, along with some peaty
herbaceousness. Surprisingly, it is not woody, although it was in
oak for 52 years. It is more delicate than the ``regular'' Macallan
bottlings, but it is an incredibly complex whisky.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously Macallan didn't make a lot of the 1946, and only 90
cases are coming to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The cost? I'm afraid this is one of those cases where, if you
have to ask, you can't afford it. (The answer follows, right before
the calendar.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Viognier is the floral, honeysuckle-laced wine from France's
northern Rhone Valley. Once just an esoteric blip on the wine radar
screen, it's become fashionable in many unlikely growing places,
including California.
</P>
<P>
   Only two problems with many California viogniers: They're too
expensive and they're overoaked, which turns them into chardonnay
wannabes.
</P>
<P>
   But there are exceptions. Case in point: the 1997 Martine's
Wines Viognier _ 4 stars _ with all the requisite flavors and no
distracting oak. While the wine could use a little more acidity,
it's clean and pure, and thus much better at $17 than some $30
California viogniers that taste like oak paneling.
</P>
<P>
   This wine comes from Martine Saunier, a Frenchwoman who lives in
California and imports many high-end wines, such as Leroy
burgundies.
</P>
<P>
   From Prestige Wine Cellars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's a bit of silliness:
</P>
<P>
   This from ``SPAM-ku: Tranquil Reflections on Luncheon Loaf'' by
John Nagamichi Cho (Harper Perennial, $7.95):
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some SPAM wine,
</P>
<P>
   A nineteen-ninety vintage.
</P>
<P>
   It's still quite lumpy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 1946 Macallan will retail for around $2,500 a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   E-mail correspondence to michael.lonsford at chron.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
