<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5127 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIGHTECH-PYRAMID-2ND &LR;      11-11 1367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHTECH-PYRAMID-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... the FTC.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's a mathematical certainty,'' he said, speaking about
pyramids generally and not specifically about Global, that at least
85 percent of participants will lose money.
</P>
<P>
   Global goes a step further than basic pyramids: Members said
they are pressured to ``step up'' to a second level where they
start the process all over again at a higher cost. They pay $6,250
to attend one of Global's so-called G-II seminars and then must
recruit two more people at the same cost, each of whom recruits
another two. (The July session in Newton was held to persuade
members to take the second step.)
</P>
<P>
   Just as before, members do not make money until the quota is
met. The process starts yet again at a third level, where members
pay $18,000 for a Global III seminar and must recruit others to do
the same.
</P>
<P>
   Members who do not step up lose seniority in the pyramid _ a
demotion called ``compression'' _ under a Global policy that steers
members to more expensive levels, former members said.
</P>
<P>
   Global has collected from its members in other ways. Some said
they paid as much as $1,500 a month for marketing aids Global
recommended, such as a special phone service, mass-mailed
postcards, and teleconference services. While acknowledging that
some Global leaders profited from companies that provided those
services, Andersen wrote that no members were required to use them.
</P>
<P>
   Another Global leader who contacted the Globe, Lorenzo Lamantia,
claimed most of those who buy the group's tapes and seminars do not
participate in Global's marketing efforts despite having paid
thousands of dollars for the program.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators doubt that claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why else would you spend $1,250 for a set of tapes,'' said
Greg Overturf, an attorney with the Montana Office of Consumer
Affairs, which has received numerous complaints about Global.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Mike, a construction contractor from Kentucky who asked that
his full name not be used, said he has been trying to make money in
the Global program since he received a Global postcard last year
advertising easy riches. Already a member of an antigovernment
group with chapters nationwide called the Patriots, he said he
decided to give Global a call.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fellow told me all sorts of things about how the
government is bringing fear and tyranny on the people,'' he said.
``The only way out is through financial freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   So he joined, thinking Global would give him that freedom. He
bought the tapes and listened to what they had to say: The IRS is
an illegal arm of the government; the Federal Reserve aims to
oppress the working classes; citizens should ``go sovereign'' and
close all US bank accounts and open accounts abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his best efforts, however, he said he has brought in
only one recruit. Even so, he stepped up to Global's second level
and attended two seminars. He stepped up again, paying $18,000 for
the third level. He said he paid for marketing services and that he
put thousands in the hands of brokers at Global seminars who
promised huge returns in foreign investments. He said that in all
he has spent $45,000 and has yet to make a dime. He plans to spend
more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure if I follow this thing through, I'll be set,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Global, recruiting prospects is a high-tech affair. Former
members said that upon joining they received a pass code, which
allowed them to receive sales forms, lists of prospects, and other
documents from Global's ``fax on demand'' system. The service
transmits forms from a remote computer prompted by commands punched
on a telephone key pad.
</P>
<P>
   The pass code also allowed members to access Global's phone
system, where training sessions and high-pressure group sales calls
are conducted.
</P>
<P>
   Each evening, members were instructed to ``go to the call,'' a
frenetic teleconference on Global's phone network.
</P>
<P>
   On one recent call, Global leaders for 90 minutes exhorted sales
people to ``go for the money.'' They rehearsed sales scripts and
tactics such as ``the quick flush'' and the ``pencil-you-in
close,'' a means of pressuring reluctant prospects by emphasizing
that waiting to join means coming in lower on the pyramid and
therefore making less money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for people who have the desire,'' said one
speaker, who identified himself only as Mike. ``I'm looking for
people who want to make $20,000 on a monthly basis. I'm looking for
people who are going to get excited about this and who are going to
come up with the money any way they can. I have an auto mechanic in
Wyoming who sold his motor home and his rifle to buy the program.
That's the kind of excitement I'm looking for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask them, `When do you want to start making money? Now or
never, yes or no?' You're looking for desire. No in-between. There
isn't a person in America who can't come up with the money. If they
say, `I don't have the money,' I say, `No. What you don't have is
the desire.'''
</P>
<P>
   Former members said that while participating in the scheme, they
flooded the country with solicitations, subscribing to
Global-controlled e-mail services that sent 10,000 pieces of junk
e-mail a week and to other services that sent out massive
quantities of computer-generated faxes, a process known as
``blasting.'' Global's mass mailer &UR;  &LR; sent out millions of postcards
on behalf of individual marketers, the former members said.
</P>
<P>
   Some cruised the Internet for easy marks. Even the Fraud Forum,
a Web site intended for victims of financial scams to share their
experiences, was fair game. The site shut down this year because of
Global solicitations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It proved to be impossible to discourage sales people from the
Global Propsperity Group from trolling on a daily basis for sales
prospects among the visitors to the Fraud Forum,'' the forum said
in a message posted on the site. ``In spite of scores of messages
advising (Global that the site) was a forum about fraud and
definitely not a platform for the sale of $1,250 cassette tapes and
a pyramid-type matrix scheme, they would not stop.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
-------- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Despite its enormous marketing machine, Global remains largely
hidden, investigators say. Members who step up to Global's higher
levels sign confidentiality agreements that, according to Global
materials, are meant to ``maintain the proper relationship with the
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Former members said they leased private mail boxes instead of
giving out home addresses. Global's only known addresses are leased
mail boxes in Lancaster, Mass., and Henderson, Nev., investigators
said. Mail is forwarded from Henderson to another box in Renton
that is registered in the name of a trust in the Turks and Caicos
Islands.
</P>
<P>
   The group's leaders seem elusive as well, often using mail drops
and unlisted numbers. ``Every individual, including me, has a
Constitutional right to privacy,'' Andersen wrote in his letter to
the Globe. Andersen's father, a Massachusetts developer, said he is
estranged from his son but believes he may have moved recently to
California.
</P>
<P>
   Struckman, according to those who have met him, is more visible.
A flamboyant disciple of get-rich ventures, he has set Global's
evangelical tone, former members say, conducting recruiting
seminars across the country where he reportedly whipped audiences
into near-religious fervors.
</P>
<P>
   The group's recruiting session in July at the Newton Marriott
was just such a meeting, according to members who attended, and it
drew the attention of Massachusetts regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on a tip from a former Global member, the state's
securities division drafted a cease-and-desist order, and the
division's director of enforcement, Matt Nestor, personally served
it at the hotel. But he and other state officials acknowledge that
such orders have had little effect. Indeed, the group held another
recruiting meeting in the state just weeks after the Newton
session, Nestor said. Global never responded to the
cease-and-desist order.
</P>
<P>
   ``Administrative action is not going to be enough'' to stop
Global, Nestor said. ``It's time for criminal authorities to step
in and seriously review these operations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
