<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FURNITURE-MARKET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S IN A NAME? FROM HEMINGWAY TO PGA, FURNITURE MANUFACTURERS
LOOK FOR WAYS TO REEL IN CUSTOMERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MADELEINE McDERMOTT HAMM 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIGH POINT, N.C. _ In the movie ``Gypsy,'' the strippers sang
``You Gotta Get a Gimmick.'' Manufacturers at the giant fall
International Home Furnishings Market here have adopted it as their
theme song.
</P>
<P>
   Making good-looking furniture doesn't seem to be enough in
today's highly competitive retail market. Manufacturers feel the
need to offer the consumer something to identify with _ a
well-known name, or a story to tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ernest Hemingway sat at a writing desk very much like this one
in the wilds of Africa ... ''
</P>
<P>
   ``The 18th-century piece that inspired this painted commode was
designed by Robert Adam for Osterley Park House in London and is
said to have been made in Thomas Chippendale's workshop. The
original is now in London's famous Victoria and Albert Museum ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``My sleigh bed was designed by Bob Mackie, the same fashion
designer who creates those fabulous gowns for stars such as Cher
and Carol Burnett and Bette Midler ...''
</P>
<P>
   The key to name-brand collections often is a licensing agreement
with a big design name, such as Lane's year-old blockbuster deal
with Eddie Bauer, which just keeps growing. The home furnishings
industry is on a brand-name binge. Lead singer at the recent market
_ the largest home furnishings trade show in the world _ was
Thomasville, with the scene-stealing Ernest Hemingway Collection.
</P>
<P>
   Two years of research and development went into this body of
furniture, accessories, gifts and textiles produced by 12
companies. The Hemingway Collection should be arriving in retail
stores next year in advance of the centennial celebration of his
birth on July 21, 1899.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the worldly lifestyle and fascinating places the
legendary writer called home, the collection was introduced to
furniture buyers and media at market with an elaborate display in
the Thomasville showrooms. Hemingway's first son, Jack _ who at 75
reminds you of ``Papa,'' as his father was known _ announced his
family's approval at the debut reception.
</P>
<P>
   The author's adventurous spirit is reflected in diverse
furniture designs, which range from exotic to luxurious, all with
informal overtones. The 96-piece collection is divided into four
sub-groups, each named for an influential place in Hemingway's life
and writings: Ketchum, Key West, Havana and Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   Early favorites with the opening night viewers included the
Nairobi Safari writing desk and folding chair, the hefty Papa
Hemingway leather chair and ottoman with nailhead trim, and the
romantic Havana Iron Canopy Bed with scroll design in the headboard
and footboard.
</P>
<P>
   Woven reed ``twill'' cushioned seat, back and arms give a
distinctive look to the peeled rattan Mombasa dining chairs, shown
with a handsome round dining table pedestal of four columns of
crossbanded rattan. Occasional pieces such as the tall, thin Los
Gatos rattan ``etagere'' and the chunky Tanganyika ottoman covered
in an animal-pattern chenille will make welcome accents in both
traditional and contemporary interiors.
</P>
<P>
   To assure authenticity of the licensed furniture, each
upholstered piece inconspicuously displays a small brass nailhead
branded with an ``H.'' Most other pieces have an unobtrusive metal
identification plate.
</P>
<P>
   Universal broke out of the broad pack of indistinguishable,
middle-of-the-road manufacturers several years ago by signing up
menswear designer Alexander Julian for the Home Colours Collection.
It scored an immediate success, giving Universal a new fashion
image, and each new Julian group has proved a winner. Consumers may
not remember the manufacturer, but they know Julian's name.
</P>
<P>
   This market, American Drew, another manufacturer not known for
setting trends or making headlines, made news with a collection by
fashion designer Bob Mackie, famous for glamorous creations worn by
stars on TV and the stage and at the Academy Awards. The debut
party had veteran buyers' heads turning as slinky models in Mackie
finery drifted through the showroom.
</P>
<P>
   Mackie focused on lavish detailing, such as ``twisted bracelet''
drawer handles and carving that looks like embroidery. ``I felt a
need for fancier things,'' he said. ``There's enough country and
Mission already.''
</P>
<P>
   The traditional 45-piece collection exhibits a definite
flourish, even drama, including silver leaf accents on some pieces.
Explaining the touch of fantasy some pieces evoke, Mackie said,
``When you close your door, your home can be whatever you wish: a
Moroccan palace, a French chateau, whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   The cherry bedroom, dining and occasional pieces in the Bob
Mackie Home Collection come in two finishes with fashion-inspired
names _ Sable and Baroque Pearl. Some designs incorporate brushed
steel and marble.
</P>
<P>
   This is Mackie's first venture into furniture designing, and he
readily admits that he had ``a lot of help from the pros.'' He is
already talking about upholstery designs for the next market and
the possibility of other Mackie products for the home.
</P>
<P>
   Two other makers of all-American furniture, Kincaid and
La-Z-Boy, hooked up with popular artist Thomas Kinkade to present
major collections inspired by his romanticized paintings of
landscapes, street scenes and cottages.
</P>
<P>
   Kinkade's work has the same nostalgic quality as that of his
idol, Norman Rockwell, and his images can be found on a wide array
of home accessories and collectibles, from limited edition
lithographs and pillows to candles and calendars. Furniture from
the licensed Thomas Kinkade Collection ranges from casual to formal
_ but demonstrates little to set it apart from many other
traditional furniture groups.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps fans of Kinkade's art will want the furniture because of
the small inscribed metal plate affirming the pieces' origins. Some
of the items _ such as the useful Chandler's Trunk with doors and
drawers instead of a lift top that means moving everything every
time it's opened _ have a charming cottage look.
</P>
<P>
   At least Kincaid did not decorate the solid pine pieces with
reproductions of Kinkade's art as Stanley did with the ill-fated
Norman Rockwell Collection a few years ago. La-Z-Boy's exclusive
fabrics from Mastercraft, however, do include signature tapestries
depicting scenes from Kinkade paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Imitation is said to be the highest form of flattery. But the
PGA Tour Home Collections from Keller and Vanguard missed the
subtlety of the popular golf-inspired Palmer Home Collection by
Lexington and the Pinehurst Collection from Drexel Heritage. Take
away the names, and with the exception of a few minor references,
both successful groups offer desirable, livable design.
</P>
<P>
   Keller, on the other hand, couldn't resist temptation in a few
signature pieces. Most obvious is the Chippendale-inspired dining
chair with the carved figure of a golfer worked into the quatrefoil
back splat and the claw foot gripping a dimpled (wood) golf ball.
An avid golfer might want the locker carved with the PGA logo in
his office, but will many hostesses want golf-themed chairs in the
dining room?
</P>
<P>
   Logos work on T-shirts, scarves and handbags, but Ralph Lauren
doesn't put that familiar polo player insignia on his high-priced
furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Famous museums' home furnishings collections, such as Colonial
Williamsburg and Historic Charleston, have long been skillfully
reproduced by quality manufacturers and purchased by discerning
consumers. Latest to join the classy ranks of faithful
reproductions, adaptations and inspired-by pieces is John
Widdicomb's V&AMP;A Museum Furniture Collection.
</P>
<P>
   The 14 exquisite pieces make up the beginning of the first-ever
American licensed collection of furniture from London's Victoria
and Albert Museum, considered by many to be the world's finest
museum of decorative art and design. Widdicomb vice president Hugh
Griffith pointed out that while they are starting with 18th- and
19th-century English furniture (Georgian and Regency styles), the
company's intention is to eventually produce designs from other
countries and periods found at the V&AMP;A.
</P>
<P>
   There are grand pieces, such as the plush, oversized sofa
inspired by an 18th-century settee with undulating back, high
scrolled arms and carved cabriole legs ending in ball-and-claw
feet. There's an absolutely elegant small Louis XVI-style oval
table inspired by David Roentgen, the furniture designer acclaimed
for his work for Catherine the Great.
</P>
<P>
   In a lighter vein, there's a mahogany stool upholstered so that
the pleated column is tied in the center to form an hourglass
shape.
</P>
<P>
   Accessorizing the Widdicomb showroom were other licensed V&AMP;A
pieces, such as a striking lamp by Lotus Arts &AMP; Windermere Lamps.
The gold base was inspired by a gilt bronze vase in the museum that
is decorated with cloisonne enamels in a flower and trellis motif.
Coincidentally, the traveling exhibit ``A Grand Design: The Art of
the Victoria and Albert Museum'' is at Houston's Museum of Fine
Arts through Jan. 10, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Coming on strong at the market are Asian themes, often with a
Western twist. Mission, Arts &AMP; Crafts and Shaker have paved the way
for the clean, simple lines of furniture from the Far East, spiced
by the current infatuation with bamboo, rattan and wicker.
</P>
<P>
   But this isn't pure Oriental styling. Most new collections,
including E.J. Victor's Boracay and Century's Silk Road, combine
East with West for more adaptable, contemporary looks. The industry
is calling it Asian Fusion, to borrow a term from the culinary
world.
</P>
<P>
   Century called its introduction Silk Road for the ancient trade
route that reached from the Mediterranean through China. This,
explained Century vice president Bill Hayes, allowed the designers
to incorporate diverse cultural influences in the collection.
Actually, it seems more contemporary than Asian.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most stunning pieces in Silk Road is a grand
headboard directly inspired by the graphic design of the famous
high-back, slightly curved chair conceived around the turn of the
century by Scottish architect Charles Rennie Mackintosh. Another is
an entertainment center, also available as a bar, that's pleasingly
scaled for any room at 6 feet tall, 49 inches wide and 26 inches
deep. Pocket doors make it even more flexible. With spare lines and
tapered legs, it could pass for Art Deco.
</P>
<P>
   And what about Classic Leather's Titanic furniture collection,
granted so much attention at the spring market? Insiders report the
company is hoping the release of the movie on video will bring a
new wave of interest and keep the pricey collection afloat. In the
meantime, Classic Leather announced a licensing agreement with
Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer. We can expect the first rollout of designs
based on furniture in those glamorous flicks from the '20s and '30s
at the April market.
</P>
<P>
   Licensing promises to continue to grow in the furniture
industry. After all, we still haven't seen Martha Stewart-designed
buffets _ to hold her holiday dining menus _ or chaises to collapse
on when the dishes are done.
</P>
<P>
   It may take a big name or a trendy theme to grab the consumers'
attention these days, but in the end, what sells the furniture is
still good design.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
