<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INITIATIVE HELPS YOUNG JEWS FIND MEANING IN THEIR FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Jewish community finds itself at a challenging
crossroad. A major rallying point is fading _ the question of
Israel's survival.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, fund-raising, fighting anti-Semitism, and political
support for Israel were the dominant themes in American Jewish
life. But now these once-energizing forces are crumbling because
Israel's existence is no longer as threatened as in the past.
</P>
<P>
   What's left for many Jews and their leaders is a basic question:
Why be a Jew?
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, Jewish leaders have been wrestling with that question
for years, pondering the future of a religious community no longer
as concerned about the fate of the Jewish homeland and enjoying,
for the most part, successful integration into American society.
</P>
<P>
   To much national acclaim, the region's Jewish community is
widely recognized as being on the vanguard of a national movement
to create strategies to stem Judaism's weakening hold on American
Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren B. Grabelle, a 22-year-old from Cherry Hills, N.J., is
one example of a new direction in Jewish activism. Grabelle is
spending a year working as a community organizer for Health Care
for All, a Boston nonprofit organization that tries to secure heath
care for the uninsured and underinsured.
</P>
<P>
   Grabelle is one of 10 interns working in various Boston agencies
as part of the Jewish Organizing Initiative, a program designed to
train young Jews in community work and to make clear the historical
link between Judaism and social justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judaism demands that we participate in `tikkun olam,' the
repairing of the world,'' said Grabelle, a Rutgers University
graduate who plans to become a rabbi. ``We have to be agents of
change in the world because we are commanded to do so by God and
our faith.''
</P>
<P>
   For Grabelle, that means working to make area hospitals,
especially in cities, accountable to their neighbors by sharing
funds and providing low-cost or free health care. ``We're doing
social justice and we're doing it as Jews,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of the Jewish Organizing Initiative, which pays the
interns an $18,000 stipend, plan on replicating the program in
other US cities. Some of the other agencies sponsoring Jewish
interns include the Allston Brighton Community Development Corp.,
the Citywide Educational Coalition, and United for a Fair Economy.
</P>
<P>
   By training a growing cadre of young Jewish community organizers
to work with low-income families, the program aims to reverse what
is seen as a decline of ``hands-on'' involvement in social justice
as Jews have become more affluent and moved out of cities.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish Organizing Initiative is a response to the challenge
issued the Jewish community by leaders like Barry Shrage, president
of Combined Jewish Philantropies of Boston and a major national
voice among American Jews.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure the future vitality of a 3,500-year-old religion,
Shrage argues that there needs to be a better connection between
serious Jewish learning and modern social justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``To survive, Judaism must be a living tradition, one that is
made relevant through the process of engaging with its laws, its
stories, its people, through drawing connections between the past
and the present,'' Shrage wrote two years ago in a paper on
building a Jewish community for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Jews must commit to social justice not just because their faith
commands them to, but ``because we must respond to the ideals of
our children, who want to be part of a community that is commited
to changing the world,'' Shrage wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Levinson, 24, who is trying to secure a union contract for
workers at a Brookline, Mass. nursing home, certainly sees his
effort as ``sacred.''
</P>
<P>
   As he strives to win community support from local rabbis and
other Brookline Jewish leaders for the union, made up mostly of
immigrants from Latin America and the Caribbean, Levinson frames
his argument in religious terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not according these people the respect and the dignity
that the Bible demands of us,'' said Levinson, who is interning at
Local 285 of the Service Employees International Union. ``Our duty
goes beyond our civil responsibility. There is something scriptural
behind this.''
</P>
<P>
   Grabelle sees projects like the Jewish Organizing Initiative as
viable strategies to energize younger Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people who feel alienated from Judaism
because they don't see that it has something meaningful to say and
bring to their lives,'' she said. ``I think these kinds of programs
show that, yes, Judaism does have something tangible and useful to
offer today.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Churches, synagogues, and temples around the country will be
participating in the annual National Donor Sabbath next weekend
(11/13-11-15) to highlight the importance of organ and tissue
donation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Comments may be sent to The Spiritual Life, c/o Diego
Ribadeneira, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; or via e-mail to
religion(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
