<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5139 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONDEMAND-VIDEO-ART-BO     11-11 1693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONDEMAND-VIDEO-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'S BRINGING HOME `VIDEO-ON-DEMAND' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  MAYNARD, Mass. _ In Bill Styslinger's perfect world, everyone
in America would watch a new movie at home every night of the week
_ without ever budging from the couch to rent videos.
</P>
<P>
   As with many dreams, this one always seems to be just out of
reach. Nevertheless, Styslinger, a cofounder and the chief
executive of SeaChange International Inc., is staking his company's
future on selling the computerized video servers and software that
will be needed to make it come true.
</P>
<P>
   The technology involved is called ``video-on-demand,'' or VOD.
Viewers will draw down their evening's entertainment with just a
few clicks of their TV remote controls, from centralized libraries
and archives containing hundreds of digital recordings of movies,
sports events, concerts, or historical events.
</P>
<P>
   As with taped videos, but not possible now with pay-per-view or
movie channels, they could fast-forward, rewind, or pause at will.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can watch what they want, when they want,'' said
Styslinger, 52, as he discussed the prospects for SeaChange's
product line.
</P>
<P>
   For all of its appeal, video-on-demand has long been an elusive
promise. Consumers taking part in pilot tests have liked it, but
technology has always been a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Now, &UR;  &LR; some of those barriers may be receding. Advances in
digital TV technology and the rapid installation of fiber optic
communications cable across America has some analysts predicting
VOD could make its commercial debut, in scattered parts of the
nation, by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Growth could pick up once a new generation of ``interactive''
set-top control boxes and remote-control devices is developed.
That, too, could happen as soon as next year, and if it does,
analysts expect as many as 7 million US homes will be able to buy
video-on-demand through their local cable systems by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely no more than about a quarter of the homes will
subscribe, says Bruce Leichtman of Yankee Group in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But for five-year-old SeaChange and others that make the video
servers and software that will house those movies and deliver them
on command, that could mean $1 billion in sales, with growth to
follow.
</P>
<P>
   Leichtman emphasizes this forecast is very uncertain. For
video-on-demand &UR;  &LR; via cable to work at all, the system must be able
to distribute digital signals and to establish two-way, interactive
communications capability, so customers can order up movies
electronically as well as receive them.
</P>
<P>
   Few systems now have both technologies. None of the major
Eastern Massachusetts cable operators do, and upgrading will will
be ``a bit by bit process'' requiring many years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't necessarily see this in Boston very soon,'' said
Leichtman. The question, he said, is whether SeaChange or &UR;  &LR; its
potential competitors ``can last it out.''
</P>
<P>
   One significant competitor for SeaChange, Diva Systems Corp. of
Menlo Park, Calif., with more than $250 million in equity and debt
financing behind it, has pushed forward anyway, with 1,700
Philadelphia area homes now hooked up to its systems in a pilot
test that involves two cable television companies there.
</P>
<P>
   Diva, founded by industrialist Paul M. Cook using technology
developed by the former Stanford Research Institute and RCA Corp.'s
old David Sarnoff Research Center, proposes to retain ownership of
systems it installs at cable-operator locations, paying the
operators fees based on usage.
</P>
<P>
   Other firms interested in this market, including SeaChange,
contemplate outright sale of their units. The list includes both
big companies _ Sony Corp., Unysis Corp., and Sun Microsystems are
a sample _ and small, niche manufacturers such as Concurrent
Computer Corp. of Fort Lauderdale, Fla., and CyberStorage Systems
Inc. of Nashua, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these rivals have chosen to wait out the lull &UR;  &LR; selling
systems to schools, companies, and government agencies for
educational and training use.
</P>
<P>
   SeaChange chose a different strategy. Since its founding by
three Digital Equipment Co. expatriates, SeaChange has targeted
cable systems, selling video server and software packages that are
tailored to insert local ads into network programming.
</P>
<P>
   These ads, bought by restaurants, auto dealers, retailers, and
others, are broadcast during breaks on CNN, ESPN, and other cable
channels, and bring cable operators significant revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Styslinger says cable operators welcomed automated digital
servers as an alternative to tape-driven systems that required
constant monitoring and were prone to frequent errors.
</P>
<P>
   SeaChange says its systems have been popular with cable
operators because, along with delivering better pictures than tape,
they store programming on disc drives in a format that all but
guarantees breakdowns won't interrupt schedules.
</P>
<P>
   This fault-tolerant format also lets multiple users call up
programming almost simultaneously. At cable stations, this means
the same ad can be scheduled on several channels within a matter of
seconds _ not uncommon during on-the-hour breaks _ but that only
one copy of the ad is needed.
</P>
<P>
   For video-on-demand, it means scores of home viewers could
decide right after supper to watch ``Casablanca.'' Again, only one
copy has to be stored. If, by chance, they all clicked on their
choice at once, some might have to wait a second or two _ but not
so long that they probably would notice, Styslinger said.
</P>
<P>
   SeaChange's systems sell for $100,000 for a single unit and $5
million or more for a multi-unit setup of the size now being
installed in Atlanta, a city of 400,000.
</P>
<P>
   The company says it has sold more than 3,000 servers since
production began in 1994 and claims these represent 65 percent of
all such units sold to US cable operators.
</P>
<P>
   Even competitors laud SeaChange's focus on cable TV, because
cable is expected to be the primary supplier of video-on-demand &UR;  &LR; to
home subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has allowed them to meet a lot of the folks who are going
to buy new video servers,'' said E.C. Siegel, chief executive of
Concurrent Computer.
</P>
<P>
   SeaChange also won points when it and Concurrent were chosen
earlier this year by Time Warner Cable as the two participants in a
shakedown test that could determine what the cable giant will buy
for its VOD service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way things work in the cable industry, everyone is content
to watch Time Warner and see if they stumble,'' said Stewart
Schley, VOD analyst for Paul Kagan Associates.
</P>
<P>
   That test could begin before Christmas. Time Warner, which did
an earlier, three-year pilot study of video-on-demand &UR;  &LR; in Orlando,
Fla., hasn't said where the new trials will be held.
</P>
<P>
   Unusual for a high-tech start-up, SeaChange's strategy also
produced profits for 12 straight quarters, from late 1994 to fall
1997, as sales rose from $5.7 million in 1994 to $67.9 million last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The company went public in November 1996 at $15 per share,
raising $24 million to finance future growth. By December, shares
were trading at 33 3/4. But sales began slipping by summer 1997,
and SeaChange has been in the red since. For the nine months ending
Sept. 30, SeaChange posted $52.5 million in revenues, compared with
$55.2 million for the comparable period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   SeaChange's shares hit a low of 5 3/4 last month, and closed
Tuesday at 8, down 1/8, in Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   High market penetration is partly to blame, but Styslinger says
threats last winter by telephone companies to compete for cable TV
customers has led to systems postponing new orders.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, efforts to crack two other potential markets, hotel
movies and broadcast TV, have moved slowly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  SeaChange last year bought out a Singapore-based hotel-movie
operator to improve its toehold in cable-related installations in
New York, Chicago, and Honolulu. But hotel movies now are dominated
by companies holding long-term contracts with hotel chains, some of
which won't expire until after 2000.
</P>
<P>
   US broadcast TV stations, which are trying simultaneously to
deal with the technical challenges of launching on-air digital
broadcasting, have also have been slow to buy server units.
</P>
<P>
   ``Broadcasters are a very snobbish lot,'' added Ralph Turk,
chief engineer at SeaChange's only on-the-air US customer to date,
KVOA in Tucson, Ariz. ``Broadcasters look at cable and say, `That's
too cheap for us.'''
</P>
<P>
   Styslinger said SeaChange expects no significant revenues from
either hotel or broadcast customers in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas sales have gone somewhat better, with sales since last
summer in Finland and France and a deal pending in Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   SeaChange's beginnings date to when Styslinger, Edward J.
Delaney Jr., 38, and Edward J. McGrath, 46, were working at Digital
on a project that was aimed at creating sales for its high-speed
Alpha chip, which had more power than most customers wanted.
</P>
<P>
   The team found no immediate markets, but did identify a future
in cable TV's need to store and recall huge amounts of video
imaging data. Styslinger got the OK from Digital founder Ken Olsen
to set up a new development unit. McGrath was the top technology
officer, the position he holds today at SeaChange, and Delaney
began cultivating customers.
</P>
<P>
   That was in 1991. Two years later, before the product could get
off the ground, Olsen's successor, Robert Palmer, closed down the
project as he battled the mounting losses that led ultimately to
Digital's sale to Compaq Computer Corp. this year.
</P>
<P>
   Styslinger, McGrath, and Delaney asked permission to continue on
their own, and got it. With Digital's sale to Houston-based Compaq,
Styslinger now likes to refer to SeaChange as ``the largest
corporate employer headquartered in Maynard.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, SeaChange hasn't used Alpha chips, but _ in an
effort to keep its own costs down by using generic ``off-the-shelf
parts'' _ relies on Intel Corp.'s Pentium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
