<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-05-98 2350EST &QL; 
U,A,: - BC-CIR-WEB-RADIO-NYT, -  &QL; 
 &UR; BC-CIR-WEB-RADIO-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WEB RADIO EXPANDS LISTENING HORIZONS &LR;  &QL; 
(af) &QL; 
 &UR; By RACHEL LEHMANN-HAUPT &QC;  &LR;   &QL; 
 &UR; c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   I was taught not listen to the radio while I worked. One of the
fastest-growing Internet industries, Web radio, is based on
breaking that very rule.
</P>
<P>
   There are two kinds of Web radio, both of which can be heard via
streaming-audio technology. One kind is really ordinary radio that
is heard over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Web now makes it possible to tune into an out-of-state
baseball game or listen to your favorite college radio station
without leaving town. The other kind of Web radio was created
exclusively for the Internet. Together, traditional broadcasters
and Internet-only start-ups offer more than 1,700 audio channels
that you can listen to through your computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a critical mass of choice,'' said Larry Magne, editor of
the original edition of ``Passport to Web Radio'' (International
Broadcasting Service, 1997), which describes stations from Texas to
Taipei. (An updated edition, edited by David Walcutt, appeared
earlier this year.)
</P>
<P>
   Web sites like www.broadcast.com and the BRS Radio Directory
(www.radio-directory.com) act as portals to thousands of
traditional and Web-only stations.
</P>
<P>
   Magne said that in traditional broadcast markets, many genres,
like classical, are losing out to programming that draws better
advertising. The Web provides a broader range of choice. For
example, Magne said that Radio Beethoven, a tiny classical station
that broadcasts from Santiago, Chile, is one of the best classical
radio stations around (www.beethovenfm.cl/RealAudio/ index.html).
</P>
<P>
   Many Web-only radio stations were founded on the idea of
countering a trend toward less broadcast diversity. Web technology
allows stations to offer niche programs. Some are homespun pirate
stations or stations devoted to only one band, like
www.deadradio.com, which exclusively plays the Grateful Dead.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the many independent stations, there are larger
Internet-only networks that offer multiple channels of music and
talk. Three of those reviewed here _ Imagine Radio, Netradio and
Spinner _ have eliminated audio advertisements and disk jockey
chatter. They offer a wide variety of programming and, in the case
of Imagine, personalizing programming.
</P>
<P>
   But personalized programming has made many record labels and the
Recording Industry Association of America worry that Web radio will
threaten CD sales. The Digital Millennium Copyright Act, which was
recently signed into law, further secures copyright protection on
line.
</P>
<P>
   While all Web radio stations are required to pay fees to artists
through Ascap and BMI, this new legislation will force Web radio
stations to pay a licensing fee to record labels as well.
</P>
<P>
   The act says customized stations must negotiate individual
contracts with all the labels whose artists they play, and it
forbids stations to play more than two songs in a row from a single
artist in a three-hour period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Record companies don't yet understand the power of user
customization,'' said John Adams, director of programming for
Imagine Radio. ``They have to realize that it can expose new
artists and increase record sales.''
</P>
<P>
   To listen to Web radio, you need Real Player, a technology
developed by the Real Networks Corp. that enables an audio signal
to be ``streamed'' over the Internet. Real Player is available free
at www.real.com and takes between 10 and 20 minutes to download.
</P>
<P>
   It can also be found through most Web radio portals and
networks. If your modem uses dial-up access, Web radio will eat up
half your bandwidth, and on any connection slower than an ISDN
line, Web broadcasts are accompanied by an AM radio-style buzz.
</P>
<P>
   But if choice and control are more important, and if you like
the retro charm of the AM buzz, then Web radio can be a listening
adventure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-04-98 1616EST &QL; 
U,F,: - BC-MICROSOFT-BROWSER-795, -  &QL; 
 &UR; BC-MICROSOFT-BROWSER-795&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BROWSER MEMOS POSE CHALLENGE TO MICROSOFT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (See also MICROSOFT-TRIAL) &LR;  &QL; 
(lb) &QL; 
 &UR; By STEVE LOHR &LR;  &QC;  &UR; c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As late as last year, Microsoft Corp. was so
worried about Netscape Communications Corp.'s lead in Internet
software that its senior executives wanted to delay an upgrade of
Microsoft's Windows operating system to gain an edge in the browser
battle, according to internal Microsoft documents released this
week by the government.
</P>
<P>
   The linchpin of Microsoft's defense in its antitrust trial is
that its Internet Explorer, or IE, browser is a seamless feature of
Windows _ not, as the government contends, a separate product
bundled with Windows in an effort to give it an unfair advantage
against Netscape. The origins of its product strategy, Microsoft
asserts, date back more than four years to a meeting of its
executives in April 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But internal Microsoft electronic-mail messages released this
week by the Justice Department seem to cast doubt on these defense
arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, however, argues that the e-mail mostly supports its
legal case. ``It shows that they regarded browsing functionality as
part of Windows and were willing to delay an upgrade schedule to
deliver a superior product,'' said Mark Murray, a Microsoft
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Still, an e-mail exchange between two senior Microsoft
executives in January 1997 _ more than a year after the company
introduced its software for browsing the World Wide Web _ talks of
competing with Netscape as ``pitting browser against browser'' and
refers to ``browser market share as job 1.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange suggests that at that late date, within Microsoft,
the browser and the operating system were not viewed as a single,
seamless product.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail on Jan. 2, 1997, James Allchin, a Microsoft senior
vice president, writes to Paul Maritz, a group vice president and
the most senior Microsoft executive scheduled to appear as a
witness in the trial, ``I do not feel that we are going to win on
our current path.'' Later, he adds, ``I am convinced we have to use
Windows _ this is the one thing they don't have.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Allchin urges Maritz, ``If you agree that Windows
is a huge asset, then it follows quickly that we are not investing
sufficiently in finding ways to tie IE and Windows together.''
</P>
<P>
   The more tightly Internet Explorer can be entwined in the next
upgrade of Windows, Allchin writes, ``the more Netscape will be cut
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Defeating Netscape, the e-mail suggests, was such a priority at
Microsoft that it was seen to outweigh the impact a delay of
Windows would have on the computer industry. Sales of new personal
computers, hardware add-ons and software all typically surge in the
wake of an upgrade of Windows, part of the central nervous system
that controls more than 90 percent of personal computers sold
today.
</P>
<P>
   Delaying Windows to embed the browser, is ``the only thing that
makes sense even if OEMs suffer,'' Allchin wrote, referring to
``original equipment manufacturers,'' jargon for computer makers.
</P>
<P>
   Maritz shared that view. In a response on the same day, he wrote
that he saw ``little option'' but to fully integrate the browser in
the operating system, ``even if it means missing the OEM window'' _
the delivery time frame that would allow computer makers to install
the upgrade on machines for the 1997 year-end sales season.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's Windows upgrade, code-named Memphis, was initially
scheduled to be released in August or September 1997. But its
arrival was delayed until June of this year, and it is called
Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1997, Microsoft started hinting to software developers
and analysts at industry conferences that Memphis might be delayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never the reason given in public, but industry insiders
believed that the real reason Memphis was being delayed was to
totally integrate the browser and help Microsoft in its
life-and-death battle with Netscape,'' said Richard Doherty,
president of Envisioneering, a research firm in Seaford, N.Y.
``This e-mail does seem to be proof of what Microsoft's intentions
were back then.''
</P>
<P>
   Memphis was delayed even more than Microsoft had thought in
early 1997, partly as a result of Microsoft's $425 million purchase
in April 1997 of Web TV Networks, an Internet-via-television
service. Afterward, Microsoft also decided to include Web TV
software in Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   Internet Explorer is fully embedded in Windows 98, but the
company released a stand-alone version of its browser, Internet
Explorer 4.0, in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In its defense, Microsoft has also said that it became company
policy after a meeting in April 1994 to ``make a big bet on the
Internet.'' Though few concrete plans were made that day, Microsoft
says, there was agreement that Windows should have built-in access
to the Internet, which eventually became its browser strategy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The meeting occurred a couple of days after Netscape was
founded, and suggests, Microsoft says, that its main intention in
the browser battle was to improve its operating system _ not to
crush Netscape, as the Justice Department contends.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in an e-mail written on June 10, 1994, Steven Sinofsky, a
Microsoft executive who helped organize the April meeting, portrays
a company ambivalent about the Internet and not yet planning a
browser of its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must admit,'' Sinofsky writes, ``that the thought of
`Internet evangelism' is a little like evangelizing water to
Noah.''
</P>
<P>
   He describes the Microsoft message for Windows 95 as ``all the
plumbing you need to connect to the Internet,'' mostly software
protocols for communicating on the network.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Sinofsky wrote, ``We do not currently plan on any other
client software, especially something like Mosaic.'' Mosaic was the
name of the browser developed by the programmers at the University
of Illinois, most of whom went on to help found Netscape. Even so,
Sinofsky added that Microsoft was ``investigating possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-04-98 2115EST &QL; 
U,F,: - BC-MICROSOFT-WINDOW-11/5, -  &QL; 
 &UR; BC-MICROSOFT-WINDOW-11/5 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A COURTROOM E-MAIL QUERY: WHERE'S BILL?
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is one in a series of occasional looks inside the
historic Microsoft antitrust trial.
</P>
<P>
   By MARY BETH REGAN
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bill Gates _ virtual or real _ wasn't anywhere to
be seen in U.S. District Court here Wednesday. Instead, a
semi-packed courtroom spent the day watching second string Sullivan
&AMP; Cromwell lawyer, Theodore Edelman, hammer away at curly-haired
computer scientist Avadis Tevanian Jr., a senior vice president at
Apple Computer, who goes by ``Avie'' in his e-mails. The sparring
centered on Avie's assertion that Microsoft intentionally put bugs
in its operating system, making Apple's QuickTime software crash
with error messages when running on a new version of Microsoft's
popular Windows.
</P>
<P>
   In the hallways, between sessions punctuated with laughter at
Avie's in-your-face retorts to Edelman's condescending questions,
though, most observers were whispering about the Main Man, himself.
Bill Gates. Some reporters were peeved that Department of Justice
honcho David Boies had sprung the Gates videotape on them Monday
without warning. A few missed the main attraction entirely. Other
spectators groaned when they learned they wouldn't get another
glimpse of Gates' videotaped deposition until Monday, at the
earliest. ``That's really why I came today,'' confided one DOJ
employee, who just dropped by to check out the action.
</P>
<P>
   It's no accident that Gates is about as far as you can get from
Washington these days. Unlike in many trials, District Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson has limited the witnesses in this case to 12
people for each side. Microsoft decided not to call Gates to the
stand. And the Justice Department didn't want to use up its
precious few witnesses with someone hostile to their cause.
Instead, Boies made an end run around the judge's decree by
introducing part of Gates' 20-hour videotaped deposition into court
as evidence. Microsoft's legal team wasn't happy. Of what was
shown, about 40 percent of what was shown was chosen by the
Microsoft legal team.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem hard to believe that Microsoft had a hand in picking
any of the Gates footage. By most accounts, the billionaire
computer whiz came across on a 10-foot courtroom screen as evasive,
defiant, even a bit arrogant. At times, the virtual Bill rocked in
his leather chair, scratching his head, giving short, snappy
answers. Or he'd sit in silence. For seconds. Then he'd give an
obligatory answer.
</P>
<P>
   While it was hardly an Academy Award performance, many find it
inconceivable that Gates' lawyers failed to advise him that the
deposition could be shown in court. Remember Bill Clinton's command
performance in the Lewinsky affair? ``Everyone knows video
depositions can show up in court,'' says one Washington litigator.
``That's why they show up with a camera.''
</P>
<P>
   In Gates' defense, many lawyers say it's more difficult to
appear convincing and compassionate on video. ``It's still a very
harsh medium,'' says Peter Bleakley, a partner with Arnold &AMP; Porter
in Washington. ``All your mannerisms come across as very
exaggerated.'' In addition, you don't have the benefit of reacting
to the body language of a judge or jury member. For example, Gates
had no way of knowing that Jackson would watch his deposition,
shaking his head and smiling at times _ almost as if he was
incredulous at the CEO's assertion that he didn't remember key
events.
</P>
<P>
   It's true the Microsoft team still could decide to put Gates on
the stand. The judge has given each side a silver bullet of sorts
to call another witness, or introduce a key deposition, if
absolutely necessary. But that's not likely. The Microsoft team
probably remembers Gates' other Washington performance, when he
appeared before Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah's judiciary committee
earlier this year. That time, the real Bill came across as even
more combative and condescending with his
``If-only-you-understood-technology'' attitude.
</P>
<P>
   While virtual Bill wasn't terribly helpful to Microsoft's case,
it could be that it's better than having the real Bill take the
stand.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-04-98 2000EST &QL; 
R,F,: - BC-FEA-MICROSOFT-COUNTER, -  &QL; 
 &UR; BC-FEA-MICROSOFT-COUNTERATTACK-BLOOM &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MICROSOFT ON TRIAL: BOIES, U.S.'S LEAD LAWYER, LOVES THE COMBAT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QC;  &UR; By James
Rowley &LR;  &QC;  &UR; c.1998 Bloomberg News &LR;  &QC;  (Repeating story published earlier
for weekend use.)
</P>
<P>
   Washington, Oct. 18 (Bloomberg) -- David Boies, the U.S.
government's lead lawyer in its antitrust case against Microsoft
Corp., is the consummate legal warrior who loves courtroom combat.
</P>
<P>
   Once a defense lawyer for International Business Machines Corp.
in its successful 13-year antitrust battle with the U.S. Justice
Department and its competitors in the 1970s, Boies, 57, has
switched sides. He's taken a big pay cut to do battle for the
government against Microsoft in a case that comes to trial
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Boies walked away from a partnership last year at the Wall
Street firm of Cravath, Swaine and Moore after a dispute over his
representation of the New York Yankees. That cost him a
compensation package of more than $2 million a year, although it
left him free to pursue work of his own choosing.
</P>
<P>
   ``David is a free spirit,'' says Houston lawyer Joe Jamail, both
an adversary and ally in several major court fights. ``He is not a
person who joins a club of collective thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   With the time Boies puts in on the Microsoft case, his
government salary of $100,000 a year translates into an hourly rate
of $50, the Justice Department says, a fraction of the $550 or $600
an hour he usually commands in private practice. Boies also was
required to sell his stock in Microsoft and IBM -- at a profit, he
noted -- to be part of history.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a handful of significant monopolization cases over
the last 100 years,'' he said. ``This is one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the biggest antitrust case since IBM, the Justice Department
and 20 states accuse Microsoft of illegally defending and extending
its Windows monopoly for personal computer operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   Boies said he likes the government's chances of defeating
Microsoft in court because ``there isn't any sensible human being
on the planet -- who is not paid by Microsoft -- who doesn't
believe that Microsoft has monopoly power.''
</P>
<P>
   Boies said his experience in the IBM case might have been a
small factor in the Justice Department's decision to hire him.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft case is very different from the government's
unsuccessful suit against his old client, Boies said. ``You didn't
have any allegations that IBM restricted the use of its products
once they had been sold the way Microsoft had done,'' he said.
``You didn't have any allegations IBM had gotten together with ...
competitors and tried to restrict competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department, which rarely hires outside counsel, said
it retained Boies because of his exceptional track record trying
complex cases. ``He's a brilliant litigator, he has a tremendous
amount of experience, he's one of the best in the country,'' says
Justice Department spokeswoman Gina Talamona.
</P>
<P>
   He's also worked for the government before. Boies was chief
counsel to the Senate Judiciary Committee in the late 1970s and
later represented U.S. bank regulators, helping them recover $1.1
billion from convicted junk bond king Michael Milken and Drexel
Burnham Lambert.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's bridge, lawn darts, soccer with his teenage
children or gambling in Las Vegas, Boies relishes competition.
Still, friends say, there's no doubt his favorite arena is the
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``David's exercise is his work,'' said Jonathan Schiller, with
whom Boies started a small firm last year. ``He tends to work every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Boies, who lives and practices law in suburban Westchester
County, New York, has crisscrossed the country, taking pretrial
depositions from computer industry executives on the West Coast and
economic experts in Boston. He questioned Microsoft Chairman Bill
Gates and other executives at the company's headquarters in
Redmond, Washington. He has worked out of the antitrust division's
main office in Washington and a field office in San Francisco,
where most of the government lawyers on the case are located.
Although he is often on the road, ``he stays in touch quite
frequently. He likes to call home,'' says his wife, antitrust
lawyer Mary Boies, who has her own firm in Bedford Hills, New York.
He will take a ``long flight from Florida'' to get home on a
weekend even if he has to go back Sunday night, she says.
</P>
<P>
   His almost 30-year career includes some of the highest-stakes
battles between large U.S. corporations. Friends and colleagues
attribute his success rate to a phenomenal memory and unusually
heightened powers of concentration.
</P>
<P>
   Boies can ``shut everything out of his mind but the moment,''
says Robert Joffee, the new managing partner of Cravath.
</P>
<P>
   ``He only focuses on the critical elements'' of a case, says
George Vradenburg III, a former Cravath colleague on the IBM case
and now general counsel of America Online Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Among Boies' biggest victories was his defense of CBS Corp.
against a $120 million libel suit by Gen. William Westmoreland, the
retired U.S. commander in Vietnam. The suit, challenging a CBS
documentary that said the U.S. military deliberately distorted
enemy strength during the Vietnam War, was dropped before it went
to a jury.
</P>
<P>
   Boies successfully defended IBM in a private lawsuit filed by
California Computer Products without ever calling a witness the
trial. The judge threw out the case in mid-trial, persuaded by
Boies that the company's evidence was insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Boies also helped Texaco Inc. survive a $10.5 billion jury award
for thwarting Pennzoil Co.'s takeover of Getty Oil. Texaco settled
for $3 billion, allowing it to emerge from bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``For David, if you raise the bar and take away the net, he's
happiest,'' says Mary Boies.
</P>
<P>
   The two met in the late 1970s during the fight over airline
deregulation when she was working in the White House for President
Jimmy Carter and Boies was chief counsel to the Senate Judiciary
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   He has already tried two other major cases this year. The trials
overlapped for several days, forcing Boies to shuttle between
Florida and New York City. He was in a New York courtroom when the
Florida jury awarded his client $95 million, an experience Boies
likened to ``winning the Kentucky Derby and taking off before you
get the roses.''
</P>
<P>
   Boies has had plenty of chances to hear juries give his clients
big-money verdicts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, he won a $100 million judgment against American
Airlines and $90 million against United Airlines for showing their
reservation systems discriminated against Continental Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   His unorthodox work habits might put off traditionalists in the
bar. ``He will read deposition transcripts at the U.S. Open Tennis
tournament, but not in his office'' or ``call you from an open Jeep
and pay phone in Wyoming,'' Vradenburg said.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Boies interrupted a cross-country Jeep trip with
his 13-year-old son, Alex, to appear at an emergency court hearing
in Philadelphia. ``We parked the Jeep at the airport in
Springfield, Missouri, flew to Philadelphia one night,'' Boies
said. The next day, he said, ``we had the hearing, flew back that
afternoon, got back in our Jeep and continued on our way.''
</P>
<P>
   Boies hardly looks the part of a Wall Street superlawyer. His
slightly shaggy brown hair drops below the collar of his blue suit
that Joffee says ``looks like it was bought off the rack at Sears
Roebuck.''
</P>
<P>
   Boies drags his suitcase on wheels into courts to be forever
ready for the airplane flight to the next trial date. He wears a
cheap-looking watch with a black rubber wrist band strapped around
the right cuff of his shirt and black Reebok athletic shoes.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a high-school history teacher, Boies grew up in
southern California where, after playing professional bridge and
working such odd jobs as a motel book clerk, he graduated from the
University of Redlands in Redlands, California. He attended
Northwestern University law school in Chicago, then transferred to
Yale where he got his degree.
</P>
<P>
   Married three times, Boies is the father of six children, four
of whom are now lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, loyalty to his favorite baseball team, the New York
Yankees, prompted Boies to give up his Cravath partnership. The
club had retained Boies for its fight with Major League Baseball
over the $93 million Adidas USA Inc. paid to use the team's logos
on sportswear.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute put him at odds with one of Cravath's oldest
clients, Time Warner Inc., which owns the Atlanta Braves. Boies had
to choose between a client and the lucrative partnership.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really can't abandon the client in the middle of
litigation,'' says Boies, who successfully settled the case so
Yankee owner George M. Steinbrenner III could keep the Adidas
royalties.
</P>
<P>
   Boies put out his shingle in an office park just north of New
York City and the small firm has grown rapidly. Its client list
includes CBS Corp., Unisys Corp. and comedian Garry Shandling.
</P>
<P>
   Not every case is a winner. In 1993, Boies lost a 1993
price-fixing case that Continental Airlines had brought in Texas
against American Airlines. Such losses aren't occasions for Boies
to fret, says Mary Boies. ``He's not Hamlet, he's always looking
ahead,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dislike losing more than most people,'' Boies said. ``But
once it's over, you move on. You strike out. You lose, you wake up
the next morning, You go play again.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-04-98 1546EST &QL; 
R,A,9 - BC-BC-WORLD-THURS-AMS-KA, -  &QL; 
 &UR; BC-BC-WORLD-THURS-AMs-KAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BILL'S WORLD &QC;  &LR; TO: Susan E, Jack T, Kevin D, NYLite staff, NY Times
News Service &QC; FROM: Bill Tammeus, KC Star &QC; SENT: 12:50 p.m. CST
11-10-98 &QC; Susan, Jack, Kevin and friends: This is the Bill's World
material for the NYLite you send out WEDNESDAY. Cheers, Bill. &QC;  &UR; (For
use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By BILL TAMMEUS &LR;  &QC;  {BILL'S WORLD}
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
By Bill Tammeus, The Kansas City Star
</P>
<P>
   Wheat prices are near an 11-year low. So there's one more great
cheap Christmas gift idea.
</P>
<P>
   The next House speaker, Bob Livingston, is 6-feet-4 and is said
to have an explosive temper. Yes, but is he tall and angry enough
to slam-dunk Dick Gephardt?
</P>
<P>
   Those who know Livingston say he's not shy about using power.
Still, he may find in his new job that wise use of authority is a
hard Newt to crack.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston used to be a prosecutor in New Orleans. One thing
we're sure of is that he didn't leave there because there was no
one left to prosecute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a manager,'' Livingston says. If he's right, we can think
of several baseball teams who may make him an offer.
</P>
<P>
   After Livingston's mother watched him on TV once as he shouted
on the House floor, she told him he looked like ``a raving
lunatic'' and to knock it off. Maybe she's the one who should be in
office.
</P>
<P>
   Newt Gingrich says the GOP needs unity so it can push its ``big
ideas.'' Maybe first it should answer our question: ``Hey, what's
the big idea?''
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary Cohen says ``time is running out'' for Iraq to
back down on the U.N. inspectors issue. It seems more like it's
walking out.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Clinton has decided to ease the sanctions imposed on India
and Pakistan for their nuclear testing earlier this year. Odd. We
didn't know sanctions, too, had a measurable half-life.
</P>
<P>
   In taped testimony at the Microsoft trial, Bill Gates has denied
trying to intimidate Intel. We'd like someone to intimidate the
computer industry as much as our computer intimidates us.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-10-98 1347EST &QL; 
R,L,: - BC-NON-CHRISTIAN-LEFT-NY, -  &QL; 
 &UR; BC-NON-CHRISTIAN-LEFT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THE OVERLOOKED ELECTION IMPACT OF THE NON-CHRISTIAN LEFT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Commentary) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or
fax her at (816) 822-1444.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JIM CASTELLI &LR;  &QC;  &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special
Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of this year's elections, the pundits have
spent a great deal of time discussing the impact of the Black vote
and of the Religious Right vote.
</P>
<P>
   But they have ignored the impact of an equally important group
that actually provided more votes for Democrats than the Religious
Right did for Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   This group could be called the Non-Christian Left -- Jews (3
percent of voters), other non-Christians (7 percent), and those
with no religious preference (9 percent).
</P>
<P>
   According to the exit poll conducted by Voter News Service, the
Non-Christian Left made up 19 percent of voters. In contrast,
whites who identify themselves with the Religious Right made up
only 13 percent of all voters. (White Religious Right voters may
belong to any Christian group).
</P>
<P>
   White Religious Right voters were three-to-one Republican, while
Non-Christian Left voters were two-to-one Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-three percent of white Religious Right voters went
Republican and 24 percent voted Democratic. Looked at from a
different angle, white Religious Right Republican voters made up
about 9.5 percent of all voters.
</P>
<P>
   Jews voted Democratic by 78 to 21 percent, other non-Christians
by 58 to 33 percent, and those with no religious preference by 65
to 32 percent. This means that Non-Christian Left Democratic voters
accounted for a little more than 12 percent of all voters.
</P>
<P>
   The Religious Right outnumbers the Non-Christian Left only in
the South (by 19 to 15 percent). The two groups are about equal in
the Midwest, where the Religious Right accounts for 13 percent of
voters and the Non-Christian Left accounts for 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the Non-Christian Left is much larger than the Religious
Right in the East and West. In the East, the Non-Christian Left
accounts for 19 percent of voters while the Religious Right
accounts for 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, the Non-Christian Left accounts for 25 percent of
voters while the Religious Right accounts for 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers view blacks -- one of the most religious groups
in America -- as the Democrats' answer to the Religious Right, and
there's no question that high black turnout was a key to many
Democratic victories this year.
</P>
<P>
   But elections are won by coalitions, and the Non-Christian Left
is a key part of the Democratic coalition, along with blacks, a
majority of Catholics, and a decent-sized minority of mainline
white Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   There are several major reasons why the Non-Christian Left votes
heavily Democratic. First, non-Christians are a minority in the
United States and therefore highly sensitive to the rhetoric of the
Religious Right, which often seems to imply that only Christians
can be good Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the Non-Christian Left is generally liberal on social
issues such as abortion and gay rights, which it often sees as
linked to minority rights.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, those who make up the Non-Christian Left are far more
likely than the Religious Right to see a positive role for
government in meeting social needs. They don't necessarily think
that a government program is always the best solution, but they are
puzzled by a mindset that celebrates a victory in defeating federal
funds to modernize and build school buildings.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Non-Christian Left is a major political force, it
lacks the cohesion -- not to mention the public relations -- of the
Religious Right.
</P>
<P>
   American Jews have long been a potent political force. But no
other non-Christian religion has become highly influential as such,
and there are no organizations representing people with no
religious affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, there is no umbrella organization attempting
to bring non-Christians together as a unified political force. That
may be just as well; ``The Non-Christian Left'' is probably not the
most potent organizing label ever devised, and those who make it up
share a belief in inclusion with mainline Christians.
</P>
<P>
   But when you see the umpteenth story about the ups and downs of
the Religious Right, it's a good idea to remember that that's not
the whole story.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Jim Castelli is the author of ``A Plea for Common Sense:
Resolving the Clash Between Religion and Politics'' (Harper &AMP; Row).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-10-98 1348EST &QL; 
R,F,: - BC-ONTECH-SFCHRON, -  &QL; 
 &UR; BC-ONTECH-SFCHRON &QL; 
Renaissance In Mammoth Computers &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
By David Einstein &QL; 
c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle &QC;  &LR; Supercomputers are all the rage
these days, with the latest models capable of performing trillions
of calculations per second _ speeds unimaginable just a few years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   And supercomputers, which now are used mostly for government and
academic research, soon will become affordable tools for business,
SGI chief executive Richard Belluzzo told a supercomputer industry
conference this week in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The most powerful supercomputers, costing up to $50 million, use
thousands of off-the-shelf chips that work together to solve in
just hours complex mathematical problems that would take an
individual with a hand calculator thousands of years.
</P>
<P>
   Dominating the high end of the market is SGI, with its Cray
division, and IBM, with its SP-class machines. (The Deep Blue
computer that deep-sixed chess champion Garry Kasparov was an IBM
SP.)
</P>
<P>
   But you don't need thousands of chips to have a supercomputer.
In fact, some corporate network computers costing less than $1
million are considered supercomputers even though they have 32
chips or fewer. If it can do about 17 billion calculations a
second, it's in supercomputer territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Standard microprocessors and other technologies from the PC
world are making supercomputing systems more cost-effective for
customers and vendors alike,'' Belluzzo said.
</P>
<P>
   The fastest supercomputers are being used to simulate weather
and climate changes. They can even predict such things as the path
of a tornado.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the middle of an amazing renaissance of
supercomputing that suddenly allows us to model, simulate and
forecast extremely complex systems,'' said John ``Beau'' Vrolyk,
senior vice president of SGI's Server and Supercomputer business
unit.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, for example, a report by the British Meteorological
Office predicted that the Amazon rain forest will be dead in 50
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ecosystem model predicts that this dieback will occur over
vast areas of northern Brazil, beginning in the 2040s, resulting
from decreases in rainfall of up to 500 millimeters per year and
increases in temperature of up to 7 degrees,'' the report stated.
``Many regions of tropical grassland will be transformed into
desert or temperate grassland, in areas of India, Africa and North
America.''
</P>
<P>
   One major result of this upheaval, according to the report, will
be a 50 percent increase in the amount of carbon dioxide in the
atmosphere by 2050. And that spells runaway global warming.
</P>
<P>
   The report was compiled using a Cray T3E that happens to be one
of the most powerful supercomputers in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its pedigree, however, the report generated only passing
interest in the media, which appears more concerned with what
supercomputers are capable of doing than with what they actually
do.
</P>
<P>
   The press takes its direction from the industry itself, which is
treating supercomputing like a super-heated competition. Every new
performance record is a cause for boasting, despite the fact that
the computers don't always operate at their limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a tendency to focus a little too much on the engine
rather than the activity it's used for,'' Vrolyk conceded.
</P>
<P>
   IBM, for instance, grabbed headlines two weeks ago with the
introduction of its latest world-beating supercomputer, dubbed
Pacific Blue. Located at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, it
can crunch data at nearly 4 trillion instructions per second,
making it the fastest supercomputer so far.
</P>
<P>
   It takes the speed title from Sandia Red, an Intel computer at
Sandia National Laboratory that has more than 9,000 Pentium chips.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-09-98 2200EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
