<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL WITHOUT THE BUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Minutes after the sun rises, Damaris Molero is up and about,
preparing for a 25-mile drive to Miami International Airport _ to
her secretarial job and her son's on-site public school.
</P>
<P>
   By 1:30 p.m., Molero has eaten lunch with her seven-year-old
son, Cesar, chatted with his teacher, checked his schoolwork, and
greeted other airport employees who stop by the classroom to see
children.
</P>
<P>
   Talk to Molero, 28, of South Dade County, Fla., and she will
tell you she has found the answer to an overwhelming problem: How
to balance the demands of her job with the educational and
emotional needs of her young son.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my son was in a school where I live, I'd have to hire
somebody to pick him up,'' she said. ``That wouldn't work for us,
but having him in school downstairs from my job does.''
</P>
<P>
   Work-site schools are a hot topic these days. The concept has
spread from its origins in Florida more than a decade ago to
Minnesota, Kentucky, and Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   Educators and corporate sponsors hail the concept. But some
workplace experts have voiced fear that the desire for more
flexibility and less stress is causing too many people to shape
lives around the demands of the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to ask ourselves: `Do we really want society to
basically conform to the corporation _ spatially, temporally, or
even in terms of governance?''' said a Harvard University
economist, Juliet B. Schor. ``That seems to be the trend here as
corporate life takes over, and we try to fit everything else,
including our children's schools, around the structure of the
corporation.''
</P>
<P>
   If corporations exist for the purpose of making profits, Schor
argues, then the more we build our social structures around the
corporate entity, the more difficult it is to organize our society
around other commonalities.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, work-site schools are catching on.
Hewlett-Packard, First Bank, Mall of America, IDS Financial
Services, and Target Stores have all created on-site schools for
the children of employees.
</P>
<P>
   In Minnesota, the Minneapolis School Department has joined with
companies to create public schools based at employee work sites. In
Belleview, Wash., Bright Horizons Family Solutions, a national
child-care chain based in Boston, launched a private school in
September for the children of employees from 20 local firms.
</P>
<P>
   Called Chestnutt Hill Academy, the school, grades 1 through 4,
serves employees of Microsoft, Eddie Bauer, and other local firms.
Working parents pay $8,000 per year to enroll one child in the
school, which says it wants to promote community feeling within the
school's four walls.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Regarded as an experiment, and the first private institution
of its kind in the country, the school currently enrolls 50
children, and is open 11 months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   For Microsoft business manager Maureen O'Hara, 43, of Redmond,
Wash., the school's summer program and lengthy school year have
eliminated worries about after-school care and camp for her two
boys, 6 and 10. ``Here, school ends in July and then summer camp
begins. That means we don't have to reinvent the wheel every
summer.'' &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Richard Green, a pioneer of work-school arrangements and
president of Jefferson Community College in Louisville, Ky., was a
human resources manager at Honeywell Inc. in Minneapolis eight
years ago when he helped develop a high school for teen mothers, on
the corporate campus.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the program has 50 students, and a similarschool has
opened at a work site in a Minneapolis suburb. While other at-work
schools served only employees of a given firm, this program was
developed by a company trying to serve its community.
</P>
<P>
   Most work-site schools are run either by private entities such
as Bright Horizons or by public systems that hire teachers, develop
curriculums, and manage classrooms. Employers finance construction
and maintain the buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absenteeism among employees is lower. The beauty of it is that
working parents now have time to take care of the meetings with
teachers and the school events,'' says Esterlene Lewis, Miami
Airport liaison to the Miami Dade County schools, which opened the
$470,000 school building at the airport in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the school-at-work concept is a novel idea, one that
points to a fundamental shift in the way we think about schools and
community, say critics. If, in the not-so-distant past, education
belonged to the community triad of home, work, and school, does
this new concept mean we are shifting our schools even further away
from the neighborhoods we barely have time to inhabit?
</P>
<P>
   Caryl Rivers, co-author of ``She Works, He Works: How Two Income
Families are Happy, Healthy and Thriving'' (Harvard University
Press, $15.95), says the school-at-work concept is part of a trend:
Americans are moving back to ``village'' living. These new villages
revolve around work.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days, people worked and lived right where their
kids were,'' Rivers said. ``They did not have to worry about what
the children were doing, because the children were right there.
Now, we are seeing corporations returning to a village culture. The
up side is that it offers parents reliable child &UR;  &LR; care and
flexibility. You don't have to worry about driving a half-hour to
speak to a teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   The down side? ``It could lock people into jobs,'' says Rivers.
``If you're unhappy at work and want to leave, you're going to have
to think twice about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy McKinley, principal of a Montessori school developed by
Target Stores and the Minneapolis public school system, says that
hasn't been a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when parents leave jobs at Target, we keep their kids,''
she said. ``Our school offers more diversity than suburban
districts, and parents like the curriculum, its proximity to
downtown, and the small classes. All those things count.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane E. Lewis is a Boston Globe staff member. She can be
reached at The Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107, or by e-mail at
work(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
