<HEADLINE>
TEAM WILL TELL WHETHER CARROLL CAN GET THE JOB DONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ It is the players who will eventually get
Pete Carroll exalted or fired. The next step in whichever process
is under way comes today, when the Patriots players and coaches
return to work toward what could be the most crucial game of the
Carroll regime _ Sunday in Buffalo against Doug Flutie and the
Bills.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots owner Bob Kraft is nowhere near a microphone or a
telephone this week. Last year, after the Patriots had just lost to
Tampa Bay to drop to 6-5, he declined to issue a vote of confidence
to his first-year coach, who, with the help of the players, turned
things around.
</P>
<P>
   The same situation is unfolding this year. Kraft was nowhere
near Foxboro Stadium Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As Kraft has said many times that when Bill Parcells left, the
organizational philosophy changed. Though winning was still
expected in the short term, the team got a lot younger.In fact,
they have the second-youngest team in the league. The feeling was
this would enable the Patriots to be a playoff-caliber team for
many years. They would be young, fresh, and competitive and every
few years more younger players would supplant the aging ones.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is times such as these when that philosophy is
tested. When injuries take several core players off the field, it
leaves the Patriots with young replacements who may not necessarily
be ready to start in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   That point is proven by the fact that this year's second
first-round pick, cornerback Tebucky Jones, despite being patted on
the back and verbally praised by his coaches, hasn't made it onto
the field in a key situation even with Chris Canty struggling and
Steve Israel coming off injury problems.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, the slide can't be blamed completely on young players
who aren't ready. Willie Clay and Ted Johnson have been missing
tackles; Max Lane, Todd Rucci, and Bruce Armstrong have been
allowing penetration and not opening holes for rookie running back
Robert Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   But it all comes back to a philosophy. If Carroll's job is in
jeopardy, then the philosophy is as well. &UR;  &LR; In many ways, Carroll is
the anti-Parcells, a nicer guy who uses a different approach to
players. He challenges them in private, but never berates them in
public, which is how Parcells seemed to do his best motivating.
</P>
<P>
   This is a crucial time for the Krafts. It is important for them
to remain a very good team while they sort out their stadium
options.
</P>
<P>
   For those reasons and others, the Patriots need to rebound. They
need their veteran players to show leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Clay has already come out and lambasted himself for his poor
play of late.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself one of the leaders on this team,'' he said,
``and if I can come out and say how bad I've been and show that I'm
doing everything I can to change it, then other guys can do the
same.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in situations where there have been a lot of one-on
one tackles rather than having 11 guys around the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually lead by example, by playing well, and I haven't done
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clay said Carroll indeed challenged the team Monday, but he
added, ``All of the guys watched that film, and whether or not you
thought you played good, you have to challenge yourself.
Collectively, to turn this around, it's going to take 53.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a play here and a play there. If a guy messes up one play
here or one play there _ and that's what's happening _ you're going
to have a bad game. It takes 11 guys to make things work.''
</P>
<P>
   Clay said the team probably won't be able to make many changes
because of the injury situation. Terry Glenn, Willie McGinest, and
perhaps even Vincent Brisby may be back this week, though
linebacker Todd Collins (groin) and Henry Thomas (ankle) look less
likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys like Henry, Chris (Slade), they tried,'' said Clay.
``They're hurt. We've got to have guys out there. Just their
presence will make us play better. We have young guys who aren't
ready to be thrown into the fire yet on this level. Maybe on
another team you can work with them. We've got to get our guys
healthy and get our aces back, or it might be too late.''
</P>
<P>
   One issue that has come up is whether players are taking more
time to return from injuries than they did under Parcells. Has Clay
noticed a difference in the recuperative powers of his teammates in
the Carroll era?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' said Clay. ``It's a matter of, when you're hurt,
you want to play, but you want to be effective when you play. If
you can play, you can play; if you're hurt, you're hurt. When
they're ready to come back, they'll come back. Everybody has to
play with some pain or else you shouldn't play in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   Clay said there is no magic potion for turning the team around.
The Patriots need a chemistry check; they need offense and defense
to work toward a common goal.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll must do his best motivational work, because there's
nothing wrong with the X's and O's on offense. Carroll must instill
in his players an attitude that they will not be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't do anything different,'' said Clay. ``We didn't do
anything different after that Tampa Bay game. We just played up to
our capability. You can practice great but unless you bring it out
there, it don't mean crap.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is precisely what the Patriots could be if the players
don't respond.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
