<HEADLINE>
AIR ATTACKS LEAVE PATRIOTS DEFENSELESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes defensive ranking text table)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One year ago, after 10 weeks of the 1997 National Football
League season, the Patriots' defense was ranked eighth in the
league in giving up first downs via passing.
</P>
<P>
   Today they stand 30th. Last.
</P>
<P>
   Where have you gone, Jimmy Hitchcock?
</P>
<P>
   There has been only one change in the starting defensive lineup
_ Hitchcock was traded to Minnesota during the draft last spring
for a future third-round choice.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe someday the Patriots can explain how you trade away a
starting NFL cornerback for a third-round pick, especially when
that cornerback becomes a starter for the team with the best record
in the NFC.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not going to put the demise of the Patriots' defense so far
this season on the shoulders of Chris Canty. This has been a team
effort.
</P>
<P>
   They have been terrible on pass defense. There is no getting
around it. Right now the big hole in the secondary is the thing
that will keep them out of the playoffs unless they repair it in a
hurry. You cannot win consistently in the NFL while giving up an
average of 14 first downs per game via the pass.
</P>
<P>
   The problem starts up front, where the Patriots have been
getting absolutely no pass rush. Their only sack against Atlanta
last week came on a safety blitz by Steve Israel. In fact, that is
their only sack in the last two games. In nine games this year, the
six defensive linemen have combined for 14 sacks.
</P>
<P>
   There is no consistent pressure on opposing passers. Most of the
time, the Patriots have to resort to blitzing defensive backs, and
when they do that, they leave the secondary vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' defense can't get off the field. There was one big
game, against Kansas City, when the Patriots held the ball for 41
minutes 48 seconds. But they average 28:46 in time of possession,
23d in the league. Without the Kansas City game, they would be dead
last.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, they miss Terry Glenn more than anything else. The
first thing out of Atlanta defensive back Eugene Robinson's mouth
after last Sunday's game was: ``When (Glenn) doesn't play for them,
it makes a big difference. They have no one to go to right away
with the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Patriots, they are 21-10 when Glenn is in
uniform. When he is not, they are 5-5.
</P>
<P>
   When Glenn and Troy Brown are playing, opponents do not press
the Patriot wide receivers at the line or blitz as much. When the
Dolphins beat New England last month, they blitzed the Patriots
more than they had any other opponent this year. The same is true
for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   This has put quarterback Drew Bledsoe in a bind. This year's
offense, under Ernie Zampese, is built on timing. When Bledsoe
drops back to pass, whether he takes three, five, or seven steps,
the ball is supposed to come out of his hand as soon as he sets up,
with the receivers presumably in certain spots on the field. That
timing is destroyed when the cornerbacks are better than the
receivers they are covering and can bump-and-run with them.
</P>
<P>
   That was the case last Sunday. Bledsoe was forced to stand back
there waiting to throw much longer than the passing scheme called
for. That's why he got sacked five times.
</P>
<P>
   No opponent fears the Patriot running game. It has not been
productive on a regular basis in decades. The Patriots are fourth
in the league in passing yardage but lack the offensive balance to
consistently score a lot of points.
</P>
<P>
   This coming Sunday in Buffalo, they will face one of the best
defenses in the league in long-yardage situations. The Bills, led
by Bruce Smith, can bring a lot of pressure in a hurry, though to
date, they have not been a big blitz team. But when they see how
Miami and Atlanta have blanketed the Patriots by jamming the
receivers and applying blitz pressure, don't be surprised if they
follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   For the New England defense, the key is not to stop Doug Flutie.
The way to beat Buffalo is to shut down the running game. The Bills
average 30 carries a game for 132 yards, better than 4 yards per
carry. What Flutie does best _ play-action and rollouts _ happens
after he fakes a handoff. When the Jets closed down the Bills'
ground game last Sunday (18 carries for 48 yards), Flutie had his
worst game in years.
</P>
<P>
   But the only thing that will keep the Patriots in the playoff
hunt is a defense that finds a way to stop giving up first downs
via the pass at such an alarming rate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NOT A PASSING GRADE &QL; 
($ used as column separator) &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Patriots are clearly having a problem defending the pass, which
is spelled out by their defensive ranking in various categories: &QL; 
 &QL; 
Category $ Total/avg. $ NFL rank &QL; 
Passing yds. allowed per game $ 225.9 $ 26 &QL; 
First downs allowed passing $ 125 $ 30 &QL; 
Third-down defense $ 40 pct. $ 23 &QL; 
Inside 20 defense $ 57.7 TD pct. $ 24 &QL; 
Total yards per game $ 307.5 $ 15 &QL; 
Rushing yds. allowed per game $ 81.3 $ 3 &QL; 
First downs allowed rushing $ 32 $ 1 &QL;
</P>
