<HEADLINE>
PHOTOS PUT ATHLETES IN A NEW LIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teresa Edwards on an outdoor basketball court in a slinky gown.
Swimmer Jenny Thompson looking more like Betty Grable. Disabled
track star Aimee Mullins in fishnet stockings. Cammi Granato decked
out in hockey skates and a swirling white party dress.
</P>
<P>
   You may have seen these athletes before, but probably not like
this. If women _ and men _ have long grappled with the issues of
sports and femininity, a new book dramatically portrays the two as
easily, gracefully intertwined.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, a favorable review in Publisher's Weekly asserted
that ``Women Who Win: Stories of Triumph in Sports and Life,''
published by Universe Publishing, would have been stronger if it
had resisted the temptation to show the feminine side of the 22
athletes portrayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the more feminine portraits, the athletes wouldn't
have wanted to be involved,'' said Christina Lessa, author and
photographer. ``They don't (often) get a chance to show their
femininity like that.''
</P>
<P>
   In her foreword to the 152-page, oversize book, which
intersperses essays by the athletes with photos both traditional
and surprising, skier Picabo Street agrees, writing that it is
``especially rare and wonderful to be portrayed ... as a person,
not just an athlete. I'm glad to show people that there is more to
me than a ski outfit and an action shot. The audience that reads
this book will see us in a different light and hear us in our own
voices.''
</P>
<P>
   Lessa, a 32-year-old from New York whose ``Gymnastics: Balancing
Acts'' was published last year, was motivated to immediately
propose the book by the women's Olympic ice hockey team that won
the gold medal in Nagano. After 2 1/2 months of frenzied contacts
and travel, it went to press in June. ``It was pretty grueling,''
said Lessa, whose son, Jake, just turned 1. ``I even went in and
out the same day to the West Coast a couple of times,'' she added,
to get home in time to care for the baby so her husband, actor Owen
Taylor, could get to his job appearing in ``Cats'' on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds as if she and sprinter Gail Devers had a lot to talk
about.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Avon in the running
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, the Avon Women's International Marathon was organized
to help prove to the Olympic organizers that women should have
their own marathon in the Games. In 1984, they got one, and Avon
began to fade from the women's runn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 1355EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
