<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-BEAR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GREAT BEAR RAINFOREST' MAKES CASE FOR CONSERVATION BEAUTIFULLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since B.C. Ferries began its ``Lost Coast'' service from Port
Hardy to Bella Coola, hundreds of American kayakers have
experienced the fjords, waterfalls and bears of British Columbia's
central coast.
</P>
<P>
   This fiercely beautiful place has become the center of a fierce
political struggle, which has spurred publication of ``The Great
Bear Rainforest: Canada's Forgotten Coast'' by Ian &AMP; Karen
McAllister.
</P>
<P>
   Using the expansive exhibit format, the McAllisters detail their
explorations of 80 virtually untouched watersheds along the wild
coast and their enchantment with the grizzly bears and wolves with
which they have kept company.
</P>
<P>
   The book is a gorgeous and effective piece of propaganda. Many
of the pristine valleys are scheduled for logging in the next few
years. Having preserved some critical areas, the British Columbia
government has sided with the forest products industry on opening
the rest to road building and chainsaws. B.C. Premier Glen Clark
made headlines last year by referring to Greenpeace protesters as
``enemies of British Columbia.''
</P>
<P>
   Exaggeration is a fundamental tool of the conservation movement,
and much is on display here.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we ever had country like that in the United States, we've
long since destroyed it with failed forestry practices,'' New York
environmental lawyer Robert F. Kennedy Jr. writes in the book's
forward.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong! Just north of British Columbia, giant tracts of Alaska
rain forest have been protected in the Misty Fjords and Admiralty
Island national monuments.
</P>
<P>
   RFK Jr. goes on to talk about British Columbia setting aside
only ``small tracts'' as parks. Kennedy ignores the 850,000-acre
Kitlope Heritage Conservancy Protected Area, touted by
conservationists in the early 1990s as the largest undisturbed
tract of temperate rain forest on Earth. Once a place gets saved,
the environmental movement seemingly forgets about it.
</P>
<P>
   Once the McAllisters get out in their trimaran, however, the
book gains credibility. They make a compelling case that the
coastline has been callously exploited. For instance, more than 3
million sockeye salmon used to return to Rivers Inlet and
watersheds around Owikeno Lake. After nearly 30 years of
clear-cutting and inattentive fisheries management offshore, the
runs have declined to 65,000.
</P>
<P>
   The McAllisters find a wolf den with ``a little mound of grey
pups'' in the still-wild Takush Valley off Smith Inlet. A dynamite
blast shatters the silence. International Forest Products is
building a road and soon will be logging the Takush. Interfor is
the same company whose shore-to-summit clear-cuts at Kyuquot Sound
on Vancouver Island were pictured in a National Geographic spread
that should be seen by all connoisseurs of ugliness.
</P>
<P>
   The authors are at their best photographing and writing about
grizzly bears. Convinced that grizzlies can sense when a human
intruder is dangerous, the McAllisters have gone gently into their
habitat. The result is a close-up look at one of the world's great
predators.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its agility and ferocity, ursus horribilis is vulnerable
to man and has been driven from the vast bulk of its habitat in
North America. One of the few hospitable places grizzlies have left
is the British Columbia coast.
</P>
<P>
   But grizzlies fishing for salmon are easy prey for hunters. The
McAllisters stumble on an illegal hunting blind in Fiordland
Recreation Area, as well as the skeletal remains of an illegally
killed female grizzly. The British Columbia government has no
reliable population figures, but it permits trophy hunting to
continue. The book accurately conveys a sense of lax regulation and
enforcement, and points to a poaching problem that the province is
loathe to admit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Great Bear Rainforest'' has one great weakness: Its
authors seem to have little contact with and little interest in
two-legged inhabitants of the wild coast. The book offers aerial
shots of Prince Rupert and Bella Coola. The McAllisters depict the
smelter-pulp mill town of Kitimat as a pit.
</P>
<P>
   But the book's purpose is not to find common ground with
loggers. It is to keep them out of wild places. The fight over
British Columbia's central coast is not for the fainthearted. With
a hostile government and an industry that still strips trees from
stream banks, international pressure is environmentalists' one
reliable weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its exaggerations, ``The Great Bear Rainforest'' makes a
compelling case that a big chunk of this country _ particularly
timbered estuaries where the grizzlies feed _ should be saved.
Canada is free with its environmental advice to other countries.
Here, it deserves to be on the receiving end.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufboox &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Great Bear Rainforest: Canada's Forgotten Coast
</P>
<P>
   By Ian &AMP; Karen McAllister. Sierra Club Books, $40, 143 pages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 1401EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
