<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIVIDED-BAPTISTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUNDAMENTALIST BAPTISTS SPLIT WITH MODERATE TEXAS CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUZANNE HOHOLIK  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Two Baptist groups met in the same city on the same
day, yet they couldn't have been farther apart.
</P>
<P>
   Members of both camps call themselves Baptists. They believe in
Jesus Christ, send missionaries around the world to convert
nonbelievers and read the same Bible.
</P>
<P>
   But that's where similarities end.
</P>
<P>
   Some call themselves fundamentalists. Others like to be referred
to as moderates. They have been unable to see eye-to-eye for more
than a decade on issues that go to the core of their faith: how to
interpret the Bible, whether women and homosexuals can be ordained
to lead congregations, and the role of women in their religion.
</P>
<P>
   So this year, for the first time, the fundamentalists broke away
from the more moderate Baptist General Convention of Texas to meet
as a separate group _ the Southern Baptists of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The General Convention met Tuesday at the George R. Brown
Convention Center with nearly 5,400 delegates, called messengers,
attending. Meanwhile, the 700 messengers of the Southern Baptists
of Texas gathered at a local Baptist church.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jeff Harris, pastor of the Castle Hills Church
Northwest in San Antonio, said the General Convention interprets
the Bible in ways inconsistent with Baptist beliefs. For example,
he pointed to the discussion among moderates that Jesus may not
have been born of a virgin.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain issues we don't feel you can waiver on,'' he
said. ``They may say it's a gray area. We don't feel it's a gray
area. They don't draw the hard line.''
</P>
<P>
   At the General Convention gathering, the Rev. Judson Edwards,
pastor of Woodland Baptist Church in San Antonio, said he found the
division sad, but maybe for the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad for Baptists that we all can't get along, but there's
always been tension and dissension, and that's not good. We've been
dealing with that for a while,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Baptists of Texas began organizing about four years
ago, aligning themselves with the Southern Baptist Convention, the
fastest-growing Protestant denomination in the United States with
15 million members worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The national group agreed to boycott the Walt Disney Co. for its
policy of providing benefits to unmarried partners of employees.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates also approved a resolution last summer at their annual
convention stating that wives should be submissive to their
husbands.
</P>
<P>
   The Baptist General Convention of Texas is aligned with the
smaller Baptist General Convention, which has about 2.7 million
members.
</P>
<P>
   Because their churches support both organizations financially,
Harris and the Rev. Gordon Graham, associate pastor at Castle Hills
First Baptist Church, attended both conventions.
</P>
<P>
   They said there was no grandstanding when they left the Baptist
General Convention of Texas meeting, no loud comments from the
fundamentalist Baptists, just a ``peaceful exit.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Graham said he had a lot of friends ``over there,'' he
said he was ``more comfortable'' with the Southern Baptists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not agree on fundamentalist differences. They don't
believe the Bible is the infallible word of God, which I do,'' he
said. ``They feel there's room for interpretation.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before adjourning Tuesday, General Convention messengers
approved a motion to pray for leaders of the Southern Baptists of
Texas as they formed their rival convention.
</P>
<P>
   In leading the prayer, a lay leader, Mary Humphries of San
Marcos, noted that Texas Baptists are diverse in their beliefs but
are united in God and Jesus Christ.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Ruben Hernandez, staff evangelist of Village Parkway
Baptist Church in San Antonio, attended the General Convention for
15 years, but said the Southern Baptists of Texas fill a void he's
felt for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you continue losing vote after vote you start to get the
message,'' he said. ``I believe it really started to come to a head
in 1991 when the Baptist General Convention of Texas went to
extremes. They see things in a more liberal way.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez was quick to say the General Convention does good
things in Texas and around the world, but basic beliefs are what
come into question.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much what they do not do, but what they believe
in, like the ordination of women,'' he said. ``I do not believe
that to be biblical.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
