A5218 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX     11-11 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALT-OF-THE-EARTH RECIPES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We're high on the sodium count this week.
</P>
<P>
   A reader writes looking for a recipe from a now-defunct tearoom
in Arlington, Texas. However, in our files, I found this recipe,
which sounds quite similar.
</P>
<P>
   The sodium is high, but if you use low-sodium tomato juice, the
numbers drop dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   SNAPPY TOMATO BOUILLON
</P>
<P>
   Yields 4 cups
</P>
<P>
   46-ounce can tomato juice
</P>
<P>
   1 celery rib, with leaves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped scallion
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   3 beef bouillon cubes, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   2-3 drops hot sauce, or more
</P>
<P>
   8-12 lemon slices, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Pour 2 cups tomato juice in small saucepan. Add celery with
leaves, onion, parsley, bouillon cubes, sugar, salt, pepper and hot
sauce. Bring to a boil, simmer 5 minutes over medium heat. Pour
into blender or food processor. Process until nearly smooth;
strain.
</P>
<P>
   In large pitcher, combine strained juice with remaining tomato
juice. Refrigerate until ready to use. Garnish with lemon slice, if
desired. Serve with cheese straws or cheese wafers.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per cup: 92 calories, trace fat, 19 grams
carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, trace cholesterol, 2,409 milligrams
sodium, trace of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   More from the salt mines: Pat Havelaar of Arlington saw our
request for a seasoned salt to package for Christmas gifts. As a
member of a community club in Rapid City, S.D., she made this salt
as a fund-raiser, packaging it in miniature fruit jars that had a
handle and a shaker top.
</P>
<P>
   SEASONED SALT
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 42 ounces
</P>
<P>
   26 ounces table salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 ounce red pepper, or less
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces chili powder
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces Accent, optional
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 ounces onion powder
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces celery salt
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 ounces black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   1/8 ounce ground oregano
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce cumin
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces paprika
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients; blend well. This is good for seasoning
meats, stews, soups, eggs, cottage cheese and vegetables, and is
especially good on pinto beans.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per teaspoon: 4 calories, trace fat, 1 gram
carbohydrates, trace protein, 0 cholesterol, 1,219 milligrams
sodium, 28 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Requests:
</P>
<P>
   Melody Smith of Fort Worth would like a recipe for a salad
called ``pink.'' Her daughter sampled the salad and thinks it
included cherries, nuts and Cool Whip but isn't sure what the pink
ingredient might be. Smith thinks maybe it also included coconut.
It's sweet enough to serve as a light dessert.
</P>
<P>
   Patty Goode is looking for a recipe for broccoli rice casserole
that includes eggs. It has almost a souffle texture.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 1421EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
