<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENDANGERED-SALMON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISHERMEN, GREEN GROUPS OPPOSE CALIFORNIA WATER PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Commercial fishermen and environmentalists say
California's ambitious plan to distribute water statewide and
restore the ecological health of the San Francisco Bay will
accelerate the destruction of the dwindling salmon runs.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition chose Tuesday, the start of the fall Chinook
salmon run through the Golden Gate Bridge, to criticize the CalFed
state and federal water program as a threat to fishing.
</P>
<P>
   It also was the day that Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt was in
Sacramento to discuss with CalFed officials a plan acceptable to
farmers, urban water users and environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   The CalFed Bay-Delta program was launched in May 1995 to devise
a plan to restore the ecological health of the Bay and delta and
improve water management.
</P>
<P>
   CalFed is scheduled to release a draft of its preferred plan in
mid-December. The fishermen and environmentalists say that it will
recommend more dams, offstream storage and possibly some version of
a peripheral canal to ship water around the delta to Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Nelson, a senior consultant to the Save San Francisco Bay
organization, said he had examined a draft of the plan, and
``basically it's a suggestion that CalFed should commit to a new
wave of dam construction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``CalFed must emphasize conservation and habitat restoration,
not new dams,'' said Zeke Grader, executive director of the Pacific
Coast Federation of Fishermen's Associations. ``Dams kill fish,
threaten the fishing industry and waste taxpayer money.''
</P>
<P>
   The coalition accused CalFed of ignoring alternative ways to
boost water supplies in Central California, such as demanding more
efficient water use from agricultural buyers, who are major users
of water.
</P>
<P>
   A CalFed draft report in March found that recycling and
conservation in urban areas can reduce the state's water use by 4
million acre feet a year _ nearly enough to fill Shasta Lake, the
biggest reservoir in California. But the CalFed recommendations for
agricultural users would take a fraction _ less than 1 percent _ of
the 33 million acre feet of water that California farmers use every
year.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Pete Wilson's administration has expressed interest in
several major dam projects that the coalition of fishermen and
environmentalists oppose. Those projects are enlarging Shasta Dam
and the Los Vaqueros reservoir in Contra Costa County, building
reservoirs on Stone Corral and Funks Creeks in Colusa and Glenn
counties, and building Los Banos Grandes, an off-stream storage
reservoir in Merced County.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 1438EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
