<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIONALBOOKAWARDS-1200-2TAKES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND THE WINNER IS ... THE NATIONAL BOOK AWARDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c. 1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Book Awards ceremony is only one of several
prominent celebrations of annual ``best-ofs'' in literature; the
Pulitzer Prizes and the National Book Critics Circle Awards are
others.
</P>
<P>
   But with the most recent titles by Gayl Jones and Tom Wolfe
included among its five finalists in the fiction category, the
National Book Foundation award ceremony Nov. 18 in New York City is
certain to attract the most attention this year.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' ``The Healing'' (Beacon Press, $23) received enough rave
critical commentary upon publication to attract law-enforcement
notice to her husband, Bob Jones, who had been a fugitive from
justice since 1984, when he was indicted on an illegal weapons
charge. When Lexington, Ky., police were alerted, they surrounded
the couple's home, and Bob Jones committed suicide. Gayl Jones,
after being placed in ``emergency detention'' and subsequently
released, now communicates with her publisher only by fax.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe's ``A Man in Full'' (Farrar, Straus and Giroux, $28.50)
was still a month from its Nov. 6 publication when its nomination
was announced. Scoffers suggest the book owes its presence on the
list of five solely to the fame of its author. Although thoughtful
evaluation may eventually suggest ``A Man in Full'' is a worthy
finalist, its inclusion has drawn the wrath of supporters of
writers such as Cormac McCarthy and Pam Houston, whose
well-received, ``already'' published novels didn't pass National
Book Award muster.
</P>
<P>
   But controversy is always part of the National Book Awards.
Besides Jones and Wolfe, the 1998 awards will probably be
remembered for its selection of John Updike as recipient of the
National Book Foundation Medal for Distinguished Contribution to
American Letters.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 National Book Award nominees:
</P>
<P>
   FICTION:
</P>
<P>
   Allegra Goodman, ``Kaaterskill Falls'' (Dial Press, $23.95):
Three Orthodox Jewish families confront secular challenge in
upstate New York. Critics have lauded Goodman for including minute
details about Orthodox life; her characters are fully dimensional,
too. ``Kaaterskill Falls'' is Goodman's first full-length novel,
and its depth has convinced literati that she has a superlative
career ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Gayl Jones, ``The Healing'' (Beacon Press, $23):
Free-association remembrances by an African-American woman who has
lived a varied, interesting life. Jones had not published a novel
for 20 years. Her previous titles, ``Corregidora'' and ``Eava's
Man,'' resonated with anger. ``The Healing'' is gentler; for the
first time, Jones uses humor as well as pathos to make her points.
</P>
<P>
   Alice McDermott, ``Charming Billy'' (Farrar, Straus and Giroux,
$22): Mourners at Bill Lynch's funeral recall his life. McDermott's
writing style has always avoided grand scenes. She prefers a
delicate approach and is more Jane Austen than Sylvia Plath.
Because of her innate delicacy, McDermott remains a writer whose
reputation among critics far surpasses her familiarity to the
general public.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Stone, ``Damascus Gate'' (Houghton Mifflin, $26): A
journalist becomes embroiled in a terrorist plot in Jerusalem.
``Damascus Gate'' is just the latest in a long list of impressive
Stone fiction _ ``Dog Soldiers,'' ``A Flag for Sunrise,'' ``Bear
and His Daughter'' and other novels and story collections have been
praised in most literary quarters. Stone is often compared to
Flannery O'Connor; his latest yarn follows his pattern of tossing
an American protagonist into unfamiliar foreign territory.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Wolfe, ``A Man in Full'' (Farrar, Straus and Giroux,
$28.50): Atlanta entrepreneur Charlie Croker tries to save his
crumbling business empire. ``A Man in Full'' has earned about 90
percent positive critical notices. Detractors say Wolfe has
indulged too much in florid details and that the ending is shaky.
But for sheer ability to weave complex, colorful tales of modern
American society, Wolfe is now the acknowledged master.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Stone's ``Damascus Gate'' gets the nod. He is a past
winner, and giving Wolfe the award would be overkill. Dark horse:
McDermott.
</P>
<P>
   NONFICTION:
</P>
<P>
   Edward Ball, ``Slaves in the Family'' (Farrar, Straus and
Giroux, $30): The author examines his own slave-holding family
history. Ball admits his family forbade discussion of five topics:
Religion, sex, money, death and ``the Negroes.'' Courageously, he
delineates his family's past, tracking mixed-race relatives and
even visiting Africa to better understand where his
African-American relations came from.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Bloom, ``Shakespeare: The Invention of the Human''
(Riverhead Books, $35): Examination of the Bard's work; less
scholarly than might be expected. Bloom is an outspoken expert, and
offers decided opinions on individual plays and characters. Many
believe the real value of this book will be in encouraging readers
to go back and re-read their Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   MORE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yaffa Eliach, ``There Once Was a World: A 900-Year Chronicle of
the Shetl of Eishyshok'' (Little, Brown, $40): Nine centuries of
Jewish life in Eastern Europe. The author is best-known for
creating the Tower of Life that has become one of the most famous
attractions at the U.S. Holocaust Museum in Washington, D.C.
``There Once Was a World'' is endlessly _ scoffers suggest
``tediously'' _ detailed. One sympathetic critic termed the book
``painfully personal microhistory.''
</P>
<P>
   Beth Kephart, ``A Slant of Sun: One Child's Courage'' (Norton,
$23): The author's infant son, Jeremy, is diagnosed with a disorder
related to autism. Kephart makes her living as a free-lance writer
of mostly magazine-length stories, but reader reaction to ``A Slant
of Sun'' probably means she'll concentrate on books from now on.
Her honesty in admitting she initially blamed her son's physical
problems on her self-perceived flaws as a mother would touch any
parent's heart. Jeremy, incidentally, has progressed enough to
express himself coherently.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Mayer, ``All on Fire: William Lloyd Garrison and the
Abolition of American Slavery'' (St. Martin's Press, $32.50): A
study of the editor/crusader, who the author argues was a key
figure in the anti-slavery ranks. ``All on Fire'' is, in fact,
revisionist history. Though Garrison is usually considered a
second-line character in most Civil War studies, Mayer argues he
belongs alongside Lincoln. The book is hampered, though, by
repetition. Its 700 pages could easily have been trimmed by
one-fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Ball. ``Slaves in the Family'' is a mesmerizing
read. Eliach's ``There Once Was a World'' could just edge Ball out.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The National Book Awards also recognize poetry and young
people's literature. This year's finalists include:
</P>
<P>
   POETRY: B.H. Fairchild, ``The Art of the Lathe''; Alicia Suskin
Ostriker, ``The Little Space: Poems Selected and New, 1968-1998'';
Linda Pastan, ``Carnival Evening: New and Selected Poems
1968-1998''; Carl Phillips, ``From the Devotions''; Gerald Stern,
``This Time: New and Selected Poems.''
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG PEOPLE'S LITERATURE: Ann Cameron, ``The Secret Life of
Amanda K. Woods''; Jack Gantos, ``Joey Pizga Swallowed the Key'';
Anita Lobel, ``No Pretty Pictures: A Child of War''; Richard Peck,
``A Long Way From Chicago''; Louis Sachar, ``Holes.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
