<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHYSICIAN-SUICIDE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUTHANASIA SUPPORTERS TO RALLY IN SAN FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Californians may find physician-assisted suicide
on the public agenda again soon with a conference on the subject
opening here Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The San Mateo-based Death with Dignity National Center is
organizing the conference with San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown and
the San Francisco Medical Society, aimed at gathering support to
change state law so terminally ill patients who are suffering can
get a doctor's help in ending their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the people fighting for a similar law in Michigan, or the
more fringe Hemlock Society, the Death with Dignity Center is
trying to be mainstream, moderate and to attract powerful people
who can lend credibility to the cause.
</P>
<P>
   That has the Catholic Church, right-to-life groups and others
opposed to assisted suicide concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's definitely the prelude to legislation somebody
will introduce, or court action,'' said Ned Dolejsi, executive
director of the California Catholic Conference. ``We've got to
watch it and recognize it, and be on guard.''
</P>
<P>
   With Oregon voters' recent reaffirmation that they support the
first physician-assisted suicide law in the nation, proponents
appear to be gaining momentum. Polls have shown that a majority of
Americans favor having the option at the end of their lives. And
AIDS groups have been in the forefront of the fight to allow dying
people to take charge of the way their lives come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   But physician-assisted suicide is opposed by mainstream groups
like the American Medical Association, as well as hospice and
disability-rights organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Californians defeated a physician-assisted suicide measure on
the ballot in 1992. It was a bruising campaign and proponents were
heavily outspent by the Catholic Church, conservative Christians
and medical groups, which also have raised large amounts to fight
initiatives in Oregon, Washington and Michigan. It left advocates
little enthusiasm for another try, according to Michael H. White, a
Los Angeles lawyer who helped organize the 1992 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A more realistic tack may be to try to round up support in the
state Legislature to introduce a narrowly worded bill, perhaps
modeled after Oregon's law.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the issue say they don't like to use the word
suicide because polls show that people are more uncomfortable with
the idea when it is presented that way.
</P>
<P>
   Dolejsi thinks the group is being deceptive not only in the
choice of words, but also in promoting the conference as a kind of
forum, since there are no opponents on the agenda. No Catholic or
other opposition groups were asked to the invitation-only
conference, although an invitation was extended after Dolejsi's
office called, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that the conference is an attempt to paint one side
of the issue, rather than have a full and open airing of the
subject,'' he said. ``It's a much more controversial issue that the
proponents appear willing to acknowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents see the conference as a way to build a broad base of
support for their cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel it is a very good starting place for our legislators,
our health officials, the leaders in our communities, to be aware
of what the facts are on this issue,'' said Charlotte Ross,
executive director of the Death with Dignity National Center.
``They need to know what patients and their families are going
through with end-of-life issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
