<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T THINK YOU WON'T HEAR FROM GINGRICH AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If his detractors were thinking that they'd heard the last of
Newt Gingrich, they'd better think again.
</P>
<P>
   The soon-to-retire U.S. House speaker showed up on television
Monday night, reminding some of his most devoted followers that his
decision to surrender the congressional gavel should not be
interpreted as an all-out retreat from public life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public office is not the same as public service,'' Gingrich
said. ``There are many avenues for a public life beyond the
speakership.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich didn't elaborate, saying only that he will be an
``active citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's see. Would an ``active citizen'' run for president?
</P>
<P>
   Newt for president? The guy just got himself hounded out of the
top leadership post in the House of Representatives _ by his own
party, no less. If he's goofy enough to run for president, who the
heck will support him?
</P>
<P>
   You might be surprised. Whatever his failures, Gingrich is still
looked upon as one of the great prophets of conservatism. He still
has a major constituency.
</P>
<P>
   And make no mistake. Newt remains one of the most effective
political fund-raisers on the planet. He'd have no trouble at all
scrounging up enough cash to finance a serious run for the
Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake about this, either: I am ``not'' predicting that
Gingrich will run for president. I am merely raising the
possibility that this is one of the activities he might choose as
he seeks ways to remain an active citizen.
</P>
<P>
   You won't catch me making any predictions about Gingrich _ pro,
con or neutral. Not after last week's wild-eyed guess that he would
hold onto his job as speaker despite an uprising by rebellious
House members who blamed him for Republican losses in the Nov. 3
elections.
</P>
<P>
   One of the hazards of making predictions in public, of course,
is the possibility _ the likelihood _ that the prediction will be
wrong. If I could make predictions with 100 percent accuracy, I
wouldn't be wasting my time trying to outguess politicians; I'd be
collecting zillions of dollars in lottery jackpots.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, I still believe that Gingrich would have prevailed if
he had fought for his job. Who would have figured that a political
alley-fighter like Newt would throw in the towel without so much as
reaching for the razor in his shoe?
</P>
<P>
   It never occurred to me that he'd just up and quit. It never
occurred to me that Newt Gingrich would back down in the face of a
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   In his televised speech to GOPAC, the political action committee
that he once used to promote his conservative agenda, Gingrich
insisted that his motives for quitting were selfless and noble.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a disruptive intraparty battle over his speakership,
Gingrich said, he ``had to make a decisive choice between my own
interests and what I believed to be the more important cause of the
country and my party.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On Friday it became clear to me that if I were to remain in
the House, I would be an excuse for divisiveness and factionalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ideas are too big, the issues are too important, for any
one person to put their office above the good of the country and
the party. That is why I announced my retirement on Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   OK. That's his story, and he's sticking to it. I'm sticking to
my theory that Newt just plain lacked the stomach for one more
rough-and-tumble political showdown.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe the truth lies somewhere in between. Maybe Gingrich
split the difference between selflessness and self-preservation,
sparing both the party and himself a bruising battle.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. Newt somehow seemed energized by his decision to quit
the speaker's job and his House seat. The Gingrich who spoke to
GOPAC sounded like the Republican prophet who rallied the nation
behind conservative precepts such as smaller government, lower
taxes and military readiness. He even made a pitch for one of
Ronald Reagan's pet projects: a missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   We haven't heard the last of Newt Gingrich, not by a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
