<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5333 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE-COX     11-11 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Traditional trinity: Corn, beans and squash
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Corn, beans and squash are enduring and familiar staples in our
gardens and on our tables, but to many American Indian tribes they
are nothing less than sacred.
</P>
<P>
   Known as the ``Three Sisters,'' they are revered as a treasured
gift from the Great Spirit, delivered from Heaven, by a crow, to
sustain and protect through all time.
</P>
<P>
   Legend holds that it was directed that the sisters should never
be apart from one another.
</P>
<P>
   So for thousands of years, they have been planted together,
eaten together and celebrated together by Native Americans, whose
spirituality recognizes the interconnectedness of all life.
</P>
<P>
   The sturdy cornstalks are used to support the twining beans, and
the spreading squash vines provide shade that traps moisture for
the growing crop. Bacteria in the bean roots then capture nitrogen
from the air and release some of it into the soil to nourish the
corn.
</P>
<P>
   In the past half-century, as modern agricultural science has
developed chemical fertilizers, herbicides and other technically
sophisticated (and sometimes environmentally harmful) methods to
increase the world's food supply, the story of the Three Sisters is
being viewed as more than just allegory. Scientists are
appreciating that there is much to learn from these growing
techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Since this is the season of the harvest, you may want to enrich
your knowledge of Native American legend and lore, increase your
appreciation of the Three Sisters and maybe find an authentic
Native American dish to add interest to your holiday table.
</P>
<P>
   For a Web site with 300 pages of the history and culture of
various tribes, which includes a list of cookbooks featuring
authentic recipes, look at http://indy4
</P>
<P>
   .fdl.cc.mn.us/(tilde)isk/mainmenu
</P>
<P>
   .htmlmainmenutop.
</P>
<P>
   At http://one-web.org
</P>
<P>
   /oneida/food-index.html, you will find a ``gift from the Oneida
people,'' which offers a brief story of the Three Sisters plus a
cookbook of recipes (not necessarily traditional) using corn, beans
and squash.
</P>
<P>
   An excellent source of authentic recipes and conversation
starters is http://www.
</P>
<P>
   wisdomkeepers.org
</P>
<P>
   /nativeway/nwidx2.htm
</P>
<P>
   tribe, where you will find dishes listed by tribes ranging from
Apache Fried Acorn Stew and Cherokee Yellow Jacket Soup to Choctaw
corn shuck bread and Iroquois fish soup.
</P>
<P>
   To put yourself in the mood for all this, scan http://www
</P>
<P>
   .geocities.com/Athens
</P>
<P>
   /2551/na.html. It features things having to do with ``Native
American Wisdom,'' from art to poetry, to history, religion and
fables.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Three Sisters Corn Casserole
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10, 1-cup servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil spray
</P>
<P>
   1pint fat-free sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup egg substitute, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1pound frozen corn
</P>
<P>
   1pound frozen green beans
</P>
<P>
   1pound summer squash, diced
</P>
<P>
   4tablespoons ( 1/2 stick) margarine
</P>
<P>
   1cup yellow cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup diced jalapeno peppers (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup diced reduced fat Monterey Jack cheese
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Coat 13-by-9-by-2-inch baking dish
with vegetable oil spray. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl, mix sour cream and egg substitute. Blend
well. Add corn, green beans, squash, margarine, cornmeal, peppers,
if desired, cheese and salt to taste, mixing well after each
addition. Pour into prepared baking dish. Bake 45 minutes or until
golden brown. _ From http://one-web.org/oneida/food-index.html
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 223 calories, 10 grams protein, 7 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 28), 33 grams carbohydrates, 3
milligrams cholesterol, 197 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Pueblo Pumpkin
</P>
<P>
   Soup
</P>
<P>
   Makes 5, 1-cup servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons butter or oil
</P>
<P>
   2tomatoes, peeled, seeded and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1green bell pepper, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1large onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon dried mint
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon grated nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   2cups cooked pumpkin, or one 15-ounce can pumpkin
</P>
<P>
   2cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup light cream or milk
</P>
<P>
   Chopped fresh cilantro, to garnish
</P>
<P>
   Heat butter or oil in a large skillet or saucepan. Saute
tomatoes, pepper, onion, mint, sugar and nutmeg 5 minutes. Add
pumpkin and broth and bring to boil. Stir until well-blended.
Reduce heat, cover and simmer 15 to 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl or measuring cup, mix flour and cream until
smooth. Add to soup. Stir until thickened. Garnish with cilantro. _
From http://www
</P>
<P>
   .wisdomkeepers.org
</P>
<P>
   /nativeway/nwidx2.htmtribe
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 140 calories, 4 grams protein, 8 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 50), 16 grams carbohydrates, 5 milligrams
cholesterol, 238 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
