<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5338 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIGITAL-DISSENT-$ADV1     11-11 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-DISSENT-$ADV15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WIRING SCHOOLS COULD COST BILLIONS AND YIELD LITTLE, SAY
DOUBTERS
 &HT;    830&AMP;add. With DIGITAL-DIVIDE. Moving in (a) national and (f)
financial categories for release Sunday, Nov. 15.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A band of dissenters is warning that as America
prepares to spend billions of dollars to wire classrooms to the
Internet, there is little proof that it will improve education.
</P>
<P>
   These doubters, most of them computer specialists, foresee a
generation of children who can point and click, but not think and
imagine. They speak of students who can send e-mail to pals across
the ocean, but not relate to classmates sitting next to them.
</P>
<P>
   And where proponents see vast information treasures in
cyberspace, techno-skeptics see mostly a time-consuming wasteland,
or worse. A few clicks, for example, can bring up video sex scenes
or on-line manuals for hacking into computer systems or building a
bomb.
</P>
<P>
   The skepticism has spurred a conference at Columbia University,
a handful of critical books, and a publication on the Internet
raising questions about the nation's infatuation with computers in
the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   In a bluntly worded essay in Time magazine last May, Yale
University computer science professor David Gelernter assailed
President Clinton's program to wire up every schoolroom, a
centerpiece of the administration's education agenda, as ``toxic
quackery.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrote Gelernter: ``First learn reading and writing, history and
arithmetic. Then play Frisbee, go fishing or surf the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the push to computerize is driven by expectations of
academic gains, researchers have yet to provide convincing evidence
that it will.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have tried to do research to measure achievement gains
and increases in 'higher-order' thinking of kids who use and don't
use computers,'' said Edward Miller, who surveyed a broad range of
findings when he was editor of Harvard University's Education
Letter. ``The bottom line is that the research is inconclusive,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the largest study yet on technology in schools, the
Educational Testing Service concluded in September that while
proper use of technology helped some students, computers offered so
little promise in elementary grades that they may not be worth the
expense.
</P>
<P>
   Such findings have not dampened enthusiasm for high technology
among school boards and politicians, however. ``In the scholarly
community of people who try to do serious research on the impact of
technology, there is a lot of caution and doubt,'' Miller said.
``But the people who make education policy don't pay much attention
to those folks.''
</P>
<P>
   The total expense of computerizing schools has been estimated as
high as $100 billion for the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Because high-tech companies stand to reap enormous profits,
``there's a juggernaut,'' said Peter Cookson, director of
educational outreach at Columbia University's Teachers College,
which late last year sponsored a conference on the potential
pitfalls in computerized education. ``I'm concerned that lots of it
is being driven by money. Education is a $600 billion business, and
there's the hardware and then the software.''
</P>
<P>
   These business interests work actively to keep educators and
policy-makers on their side. A major education software company,
Lightspan Partnership, recently teamed up with the American
Association of School Administrators to conduct a poll designed to
rebut the high-tech doubters. In their survey, released Oct. 13,
educators gave a ringing endorsement for spending more money for
technology, and 80 percent reported student gains through use of
computers.
</P>
<P>
   However, the high-tech push comes as many schools have far more
fundamental problems, such as buildings that are crumbling, teacher
shortages, too few textbooks, and many children who arrive in the
mornings too hungry or too frightened by neighborhood violence to
concentrate on studies.
</P>
<P>
   So far, teachers have raised no concerted objections to the new
stress on the hot new technologies, although some are beginning to
speak out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're making a huge mistake'' in forcing computers on
young pupils, said Russell Monke, who teaches advanced computer
science at a public high school in Des Moines, Iowa. His experience
in the classroom, plus his research, have convinced him that
computer training is unnecessary and perhaps harmful until high
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to make a serious change, a dramatic revolution in
the way that kids learn, and I don't see that the change is
particularly beneficial to children,'' Monke said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he said, the most computer-savvy students often do
poorly in his class because they lack more important life
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these kids live in a world that is abstract. They
spend time on TV, computers and video machines, and they aren't
getting involved with the community and neighborhood friends, or
even just climbing trees,'' he said. ``They need to bring into my
class at least a budding sense of moral and ethical sensibilities.
They need some sense of the world around them.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   As for falling behind on computer education, Monke said that
high school students can easily catch up on those mechanical
skills.
</P>
<P>
   Monke writes about such concerns in FutureNet, a twice-monthly
publication on the Internet edited by Steve Talbott.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott has traced the history of inventions, starting with the
radio and then the television, that were supposed to revolutionize
the classroom. ``The last piece of technology that has actually
stayed is the blackboard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He predicts that the computer, like radios and televisions, will
become no more than tools for educators.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proponents of these new technologies have taken their eyes
off the educational ball,'' he wrote in his newsletter. ``They have
not first identified an education problem and then gone out and
determined that, yes, computers do indeed look like the best of all
possible solutions to this problem. Instead, bedazzled by the
technology, they simply assume its necessity and try to figure out
how it should be used.''
</P>
<P>
   Is anyone listening to such advice? Monke said he believes
people are beginning to hear. ``It's almost like we've been drunk
from technophilia and we're going to have a long hangover, but I
think we're going to get sober and look at what's happening in
these kids' lives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the proponents are asking questions, as well. Michael
Hannafin, who holds a chair as ``eminent scholar'' of
technology-enhanced learning at the University of Georgia, said,
``My whole career lies in the future of technology and learning, so
I'm very hopeful.'' But he added that he saw both ``enormous
potential and enormous peril.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To wire every classroom (to the Internet) is a pretty naive
view,'' he said. ``A lot of people believe that's the answer.
People talk about building information highways, but you'd like to
have desirable destinations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a whole lot of money to spend if we don't get some
additional value. ``
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 1527EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5339 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIGITAL-DIVIDE-$ADV15     11-11 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-DIVIDE-$ADV15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ECONOMIC FUTURE DARKENING FOR COMPUTER HAVE-NOTS
 &HT;    With DIGITAL-SCHOOLS, DIGITAL-INDUSTRY, DIGITAL-RACE,
DIGITAL-ERATE and DIGITAL-DISSENT. Moving in (a) national and (f)
financial categories for release Sunday, Nov. 15.
 &HT;    By ERNEST HOLSENDOLPH
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The signals are strong and unmistakable: Being handy with a
computer is becoming a requirement for anybody who expects to
succeed in college or in the workplace, and this fact of life will
become even more pronounced in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   The signs are everywhere. Many colleges expect students to show
up with computers, and some others give laptops to all incoming
students and expect them to know what to do with them. Starting
this fall, the only way to apply to the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology is by computer.
</P>
<P>
   Well-prepared professionals from automobile maintenance to
graphic design cannot leave home without the computer, or a good
understanding of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ability to use a computer has now become so basic, to come
to work without it would be like a carpenter reporting without a
hammer,'' said Bart Keith, a training supervisor with Siemens AG,
the German electrical engineering and electronics company.
</P>
<P>
   Given this new reality that governs education and the workplace,
what about young people who fail to become computer-literate?
</P>
<P>
   The computer have-nots could be in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Talks with educators, employers and policy-makers underlined the
importance of young people gaining not just a knowledge of computer
technology, but also a comfort level that comes most readily from a
home environment that includes the computer and an Internet
connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no longitudinal studies yet that track the experience
of a youngster with a home computer, against a youngster without
one, to show what happens later to each of them,'' said Kathy
O'Neill, director of instructional technology at Georgia State
University. ``But we do know that kids who have access at school
and at home gain a better familiarity with computing.''
</P>
<P>
   Most experts emphasized that once young people get the computer
bug, it is best that they get everyday access that allows them to
become comfortable with the technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an overall advantage to all our employees to be
computer-literate,'' said Nancy Seipel, a human resources
specialist with Georgia Power. ``Though we do not require the
ownership of a computer when we talk to job candidates, it is my
opinion that it would be extremely helpful if a person used a
computer every day at home, where they could get a working
knowledge of the machines and the software that makes them run.''
</P>
<P>
   For students, experts emphasize the need to learn the range of a
computer's uses, and to learn that it is most of all a window on a
larger world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The child needs connection to the Internet because that is
what expands her access to knowledge,'' said Richard Skinner,
president of Clayton College and State University in suburban
Atlanta. ``In my view, without Internet connection, your computer
is not much more than a typewriter.''
</P>
<P>
   Many states and cities have fully embraced that idea, making
Internet research an integral part of instruction.
</P>
<P>
   One day last month in Judy Mack's third-grade classroom at
Normandy Elementary in Centerville, Ohio, a group of girls
clustered around a computer connected to an Internet site about the
sun. The girls rattled off solar facts, carefully recording their
findings on pads of paper. Beside them, Annie Lee, 8, surfed sites
as she developed a report on Neptune, excitedly announcing to her
neighbors that Voyager II visited the planet the same year she was
born.
</P>
<P>
   But wealthier school districts are more likely to provide such
technological enhancements. About 75 percent of students in richer
districts, where most students don't qualify for federally
subsidized lunch programs, used the Internet at school, the
Education Department reported in 1996. At poorer districts, where
most students were in the lunch program, only about half used the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For some districts, getting computers is only half the battle.
</P>
<P>
   Whittier Elementary School in Dayton, Ohio, is eligible to
receive top-of-the-line Pentium computers, but the building's
electrical system cannot handle the load of four computers switched
on at one time in a classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have these computers, but if you can't plug them in
they are a paperweight,'' said Principal Judy Warren.
</P>
<P>
   At Belmont High School, Dayton's computer technology magnet
school, the only Internet access is through teacher David Kraus's
laptop computer.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Nealon, chief information officer for Dayton Schools, said
wider Internet access depends on the district getting ``e-rate''
funding, money from telecommunications companies that is now being
held up by bickering in Congress and challenges from the companies.
</P>
<P>
   While some experts believe that children can significantly
improve their computer skills by using them at schools or
libraries, others are certain computers are needed in homes _ as
long as they are used for more than just playing games.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I have learned is that familiarity with computers
develops other skills, skills that could be just as attractive as
computing skills,'' said Nancy Hamilton, program director of a
nonprofit agency called Apple Corps, which offers free computers to
parents who volunteer to learn the machines and then commit
themselves to service in the schools of their communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, you cannot run a computer without reading. You can't
work a computer very long without being a problem-solver. You learn
flexibility as a computer operator,'' said Hamilton. When that
screen suddenly goes blank, you have to figure it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``What industry wants is problem-solvers, and people with the
flexibility to keep learning, keep developing in school and
competence. Well, familiarity with the computer is the beginning of
a lot of those skills.''
</P>
<P>
   But just as wealthier school districts are often better equipped
with technology, home computers are found mostly in high-income
households. More than 75 percent of U.S. households earning more
that $75,000 owned a computer in 1997, the Commerce Department
reported, compared to about less than 20 percent of households
earning under $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   This has sparked efforts by some private groups to create
computer centers where children can have ready access.
</P>
<P>
   Some centers have been established by businesses and church
groups. In Georgia, DeKalb County has established a half dozen
``family computer'' centers where children and parents can use the
machines.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the falling prices of computers and allied equipment
such as printers and monitors, financial affordability may become
less of a factor in who owns a home computer, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   New computers are now available for less than $500, the price of
a fancy cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems beyond dispute to me,'' said Lyndon Wade, president
of the Atlanta Urban League, ``that computers must become at least
as handy as telephones, because they are that kind of basic need.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Holsendolph writes for the Atlanta Journal and
Constitution. Lynn Hulsey of the Dayton Daily News contributed to
this article.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
