<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5344 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIGITAL-RACE-$ADV15-C     11-11 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-RACE-$ADV15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TECH GAP DIVIDES THE RACES
 &HT;    With DIGITAL-DIVIDE and DIGITAL-RACE-DATA. Moving in (a)
national and (f) financial categories for release Sunday, Nov. 15.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Barry Cooper remembers how it easy it was for him
and other black teenagers to get a job in his home town of
Wilmington, N.C., in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even though they were racially troubled times, coming out of
high school, if you were big and strong and had a good work ethic,
you could have a job in one of the factories _ with no training at
all,'' Cooper, now 42, recalled recently.
</P>
<P>
   But today, as experts predict that high school graduates will
need computer skills to compete for even entry-level jobs, minority
students remain on the wrong side of a widening ``digital divide.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, white households have been acquiring computers
at a faster pace than black or Hispanic households, Commerce
Department studies show.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're still raising basketball goals in housing projects and
community centers,'' said Cooper, founder and general manager of
Black Voices, perhaps the most popular World Wide Web site among
African Americans. ''The day must come when the truck arrives at
the community center and it's loaded with computers instead of
athletic equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   That day has come in Houston. Two years ago, the Boys and Girls
Clubs built a new sports facility near a public housing project.
Now, with the donation of computers from Compaq, the facility is
expanding its computer education program to meet the growing
demand.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the computer program has now eclipsed sports in
popularity, said John Havard, president of the Houston area clubs.
''My staff told me it would, but I'm still surprised,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 children, mostly African Americans and Hispanics, took
computer classes at the Houston Boys and Girls Clubs last year.
Bilingual staff members are available to help Hispanic children
overcome language barriers.
</P>
<P>
   To try to close the technology gap between affluent and
low-income communities, the Commerce Department has funded 332
projects in all 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first _ and most successful _ is ``Plugged In,'' a
program in East Palo Alto, Calif., that operates a community center
with computers and Internet access. It has spawned ``Plugged In
Enterprises,'' in which kids are operating their own computer
services business of producing Web pages for businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Private efforts are well under way at the local level as well,
and have intensified as the demands of the information age have
accelerated.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, the nonprofit Boys Harbor youth agency, which
educates underprivileged children in New York's Harlem and the
Bronx, introduced computers to the curriculum ''just to get them
comfortable with technology that we thought was going to be
essential in the future,'' said Bob Wallace, the agency's
curriculum director. ''We had no idea then how important it already
has become.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite efforts at the federal and local levels, the digital
divide has widened in terms of race and ethnicity, according to a
recent study by the Commerce Department that used Census Bureau
survey data from 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The study, titled ''Falling Through the Net II,'' found that
while the ownership of personal computers and access to on-line
services have grown significantly for minority groups since 1994,
African Americans and Hispanics still lag far behind the national
average _ and the gap between the races is growing.
</P>
<P>
   The gap is not limited to personal owership of PCs. It extends
to the schools, according to a recent survey by Vanderbilt
University researchers. That survey, published last April in the
journal ''Science,'' found that while 78 percent of the nation's
public schools have some sort of Internet access, only 63 percent
of the schools in communities with high percentages of poor or
minority students are connected.
</P>
<P>
   ''A significant segment of our society is in danger of being
denied equal access,'' said Donna Hoffman, who co-authored the
Vanderbilt study.
</P>
<P>
   But if government efforts have fallen short, the high-tech
industry that has spawned thousands of millionaires has been slow
to lend a hand in trying to bridge the technology gap, according to
critics such as like Barbara Moran, author of the ''Dummies''
series book, ''Internet Director for Kids &AMP; Parents.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The private sector ought to be ashamed of itself for not doing
more, especially the high-tech industry,'' she said. ''If nothing
else, they ought to be interested in building future customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Before writing her book, Moran worked for two high-tech firms as
editor of their childen's divisions. ''Our teams begged for a van
to take to poorer neighborhoods just to introduce parents and kids
to computers,'' she said. ''Didn't happen. Not 'cost effective.'
Too many 'liability issues'.''
</P>
<P>
   With prices of PCs and on-line services dropping so
dramatically, there may be little need for other incentives from
the private sector, however.
</P>
<P>
   A year and half ago, Cooper's ''Black Voices'' Web site was
experiencing about 1.4 million hits a month. Then the price of PCs
dropped below $1,000 and America Online, the nation's largest
on-line service, replaced hourly rates with a flat monthly rate.
Within months, Internet traffic to ''Black Voices'' doubled.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it's affordable and easy, the kids will play,'' said
Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   But in a speech in June to the National Urban League's summit on
technology, Larry Irving, President Clinton's top
telecommunications adviser, warned of the difficulties in
refocusing minority youths ''from high-tops to high-tech.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Most kids would rather grow up to be Michael Jordan than
(Microsoft founder) Bill Gates and spend time on a basketball court
than in a computer room,'' said Irving, who is black. ''Our
children should know as much about Paul Allen, the co-founder of
Microsoft and owner of the Portland Trailblazers NBA team) as Paul
Pierce (the Boston Celtics first-round draft pick), and as much
about Michael Dell (founder of Dell Computers) as Michael Jordan.
And our children should have a shot _ better than a three-pointer _
at being one of those computer success stories.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
