<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5347 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIGITAL-SCHOOLS-$ADV1     11-11 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SCHOOLS-$ADV15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCHOOLS WITH COMPUTERS NOW FOCUSING ON TEACHER TRAINING
 &HT;    640&AMP;add. With DIGITAL-DIVIDE. Moving in (a) national and (f)
financial categories for release Sunday, Nov. 15.
 &HT;    By SHARON JAYSON
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Nine-year-old Erik Park leaned toward the
computer monitor as he and Amy Byars, his fourth-grade teacher,
stared at an animated lion meandering across the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Creating that lion and making it move was a small step for the
pair, part of a group from Pflugerville, Texas, who spent a
half-day away from their classrooms learning a software program
called Hyperstudio that enhances student reports with sound,
graphics and movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank goodness he's here,'' Byars said of Erik. ``I think
children are better sponges than adults are. He's taking it all in,
and I'm kind of fighting to remember everything that she's teaching
us.''
</P>
<P>
   As technology gains ever-wider use in classes from math to
social studies, Pflugerville school officials believe that this
buddy system will make them more effective teachers and users of
computers.
</P>
<P>
   The effort is an example of how school districts around the
country are changing their focus on technology in education. Now
that they've spent billions of dollars to put computers in the
classroom, they are spending billions more to teach teachers how
technology can be used for more than word processing or an Internet
search.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools are not doing the long-term planning and investment in
professional development to take advantage of the hardware they're
putting in,'' said Jane Park, project director of the CEO Forum, a
Washington, D.C.-based partnership of business and education
leaders founded to promote equal access to technology.
</P>
<P>
   In a draft of a report to be released in February, the Forum
concluded, ``As we push forward to full technology integration, we
must ensure that all schools provide children with access to
technology and with teachers who can help them make the most of
that technology.''
</P>
<P>
   The surge in teacher training is partly spurred by the
realization that over the next decade, about two-thirds of the
nation's teachers will be replaced. An estimated 2 million new
teachers must fill those jobs, and knowing technology will be a
prerequisite.
</P>
<P>
   But training millions of teachers across the country _ those
currently in the classroom and those preparing to enter it _ is
trickier than it sounds. Skill levels run the gamut, from those who
know little more than word processing to those who incorporate
computers in their daily lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have anywhere near the robustness of a professional
development system that we need, because it's really expensive,''
said Cheryl Lemke, executive director of the Milken Exchange on
Education Technology, which aims to advance effective use of
technology in America's classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of training is getting teachers to think beyond their
traditional role and move into the role of facilitator. Using
technology in the classroom means students often work in groups
instead of sitting quietly as the teacher lectures.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the learning is project-based, which means students may
do an Internet search one minute and create a graphic or add sound
to a report the next.
</P>
<P>
   About 540 students use the Kettering Middle School's technology
lab each school day, typing in a code name to begin answering
questions specifically targeting their abilities.
</P>
<P>
   One student may be doing fractions, another word problems and a
third pre-algebra. Poor readers can hear the questions read aloud
over headphones to make sure their reading skills don't limit their
ability to answer the question. Teachers circle the room offering
assistance and checking students' progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could we ever do this in the classroom?'' asked lab teacher
Deborah Schlarb.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Technology forces teachers to re-examine their methods, and if
the teachers aren't comfortable with it, the students won't be
using it.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders in this professional development push are Florida,
Texas and California, due to their large numbers of teachers and
students as well as the big role high-tech plays in their
economies.
</P>
<P>
   Texas in 1988 became the first state to form a long-range plan
to ensure that the state's 250,000 teachers and almost 4 million
students are among the most computer-literate in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Revised in 1996, the plan now includes more than a dozen
initiatives to help bring technology into schools and help teachers
use it. It includes:
</P>
<P>
   _ A state financial technology allotment of $30 per student per
year to every
</P>
<P>
   district. The total projection for Texas schools during the
1998-99 school year is $111 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ A Telecommunications Infrastructure Fund, established in 1995,
that requires telecommunications companies to contribute to school
technology. Companies offer discounted services to schools and
contribute a total of $1.5 billion over 10 years
</P>
<P>
   to wire public schools, libraries, higher education, and
nonprofit health care facilities.
</P>
<P>
   _ A set of 12 technology standards that define computer
proficiency for teachers in the classroom. New certification
requirements for teachers will require a minimum level of
technology for all educators.
</P>
<P>
   _ More than $33 million in state-administered federal grants for
teacher technology training this school year, plus $500,000 in
grants to school districts for exemplary technology programs that
can be shared with other districts.
</P>
<P>
   _ A variety of supplemental training aids available through
professional development sites, a statewide satellite audio and
video network, a videoconferencing network and libraries.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Texas Educational Network, the nation's first large-scale
electronic system to
</P>
<P>
   let teachers communicate via computer with a phone line and
modem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we are providing staff development through more
variety of opportunities than in many states,'' said Anita Givens,
senior director of instructional technology at the Texas Education
Agency.
</P>
<P>
   For those just entering the profession, the stakes are higher.
The Texas Board for Educator Certification is developing technology
requirements that should become part of the certification process
by 2001, said the agency's Stephanie Korcheck.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're behind on the educator preparation side,'' she said.
``The state has invested an awful lot of money in technology.
Schools generally have more technology on campus than teachers are
really able to utilize effectively. The training and support
teachers need has not been as adequate as it needs to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Jayson writes for the Austin American-Statesman in Texas.
Lynn Hulsey of the Dayton (Ohio) Daily News contributed to this
article.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
