<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5350 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIGITAL-ERATE-$ADV15-     11-11 1303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-ERATE-$ADV15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    E-RATE PROGRAM TO WIRE SCHOOLS MIRED IN PARTISAN SQUABBLE
 &HT;    660&AMP;add. With DIGITAL-DIVIDE. Moving in (a) national and (f)
financial categories for release Sunday, Nov. 15.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The once lofty goal to open up the high-tech
glories of the Internet to all of America's schoolchildren has
degenerated into an increasingly nasty partisan squabble.
</P>
<P>
   In this fall's election campaign, Republicans accused the
Democrats of backing an illegal tax on all telephone users to
underwrite an ineffective bureaucracy that so far has done little,
if anything, to help more than 100,000 eligible schools get the
equipment and service they need to put the Internet in every
classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats portrayed a Republican-led bid to alter the funding
plan, known as the ``e-rate,'' as a move against improving
education, creating more useful libraries and investing in the
nation's future work force.
</P>
<P>
   Government regulators find themselves trapped in the middle of
this political fight, which will resume in the next Congress.
Although the e-rate program remains in force, it has been
substantially scaled back by the Federal Communications Commission
(FCC) in the face of sharp congressional protests.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the nation's large telecommunications companies, or
telcos, guardedly watch events unfold. They have a huge financial
stake in the eventual outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Under the landmark 1996 Telecommunications Act, the telcos are
obliged to offer all schools, from kindergarten through the 12th
grade, as well as all public libraries, discounts on their lowest
institutional rate for telephone and Internet services. These
discounts range from 20 to 90 percent, depending on economic need
as measured by the percentage of students eligible for the national
school lunch program.
</P>
<P>
   As lawmakers originally saw it, the e-rate discounts _ the ``e''
stands for ``education'' _ would be relatively painless to
consumers because the telcos could offset their costs with some of
the additional revenue they earned through deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   But the telcos, faced with a spate of mergers amid a newly
ultra-competitive climate, declined to continue a 60-year-old
tradition of hidden subsidies. Starting in July, they insisted that
their costs of subsidizing the school wiring effort _ a small part
of a longstanding ``universal access'' fee _ appear as a separate
charge on most phone statements.
</P>
<P>
   This fee increasingly began to be portrayed by opponents of the
program as yet another federal tax _ and worse yet, one that
Congress had never specifically voted into law.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans even had a politically convenient label, the ``Gore
tax,'' thanks to the vice president's prominent role in driving the
school wiring bill through Congress.
</P>
<P>
   One critic of the e-rate, Rep. Jerry Weller, R-Ill., said, ``the
FCC is incorrect in its contention that the 'Gore Tax' is a fee. A
fee is a charge for a service rendered; however, long-distance
users are not receiving a service. Thus, if a charge is levied and
no direct service is provided then it is characterized as a tax,
regardless of whether it shows up on your IRS 1040 form or your
telephone bill, and only Congress can impose a tax under the
Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with Weller, Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., wants the Congress
that will convene in January to cut the current 3 percent telephone
excise tax that pays for the hookups to 1 percent, and earmark that
money for state block grants for schools and libraries. Both
members sit on the House Ways and Means Committee, where all
revenue legislation originates.
</P>
<P>
   To further complicate matters, the telcos saw the changes made
to the universal service funding mechanism in the 1996 law as a
chance to once more put the entire question before the courts.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the U.S. Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals in New
Orleans is considering a case from Texas that challenges the
legality of the whole universal service program, including the
e-rate. A ruling on this issue could come by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The e-rate program builds on 1936 federal legislation that
created a special fund to subsidize basic telephone service to
every home in the nation, offering phone companies the financial
means to deliver a dial tone to even the most rural, sparsely
populated areas, where connections would otherwise be prohibitively
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   About 27 percent of classrooms in U.S. libraries and schools
have Internet connections. Roughly 2 million more need to be
connected, and within the next five years, some 10,000 new schools
will be built.
</P>
<P>
   The universal service fund was supposed to provide $2.2 billion
for Internet modernization in 1998. Since the total tab from the
approximately 30,000 schools and libraries that have applied for
aid came to slightly more than $2 billion, it appeared at first
that the federal kitty would more than fully support the actual
demand.
</P>
<P>
   But Congress soon raised alarms, fueled in part by a General
Accounting Office report that labeled the e-rate program a prime
candidate for fraud, waste and abuse. In response, on June 12 the
FCC cut e-rate funding by 43 percent, to $1.3 billion. And the
agency stretched out overall funding by six more months to June 30,
1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress originally saw the discounts as an entitlement to all
schools,'' noted David Byer, vice president for government affairs
for the Software Publishers Association. But, as matters stand,
only the very poorest school districts in the country will qualify
for inside (Internet) wiring.''
</P>
<P>
   In focusing on the discounts, Congress had failed to take into
full account that low-cost hookups were of little value to schools
unless they could be supported by a full panoply of switches,
routers and wires, to say nothing of training, needed to make the
system function effectively.
</P>
<P>
   But in focusing on the supportive Internet hardware, some school
administrators saw a fresh source of federal funds to fix up their
schools under the guise of making them ``Internet-ready.'' Reports
of such attempted end runs incensed key members of Congress and
helped force the FCC's decision to stretch out and scale back
funding.
</P>
<P>
   Through the end of June, the FCC had collected about $650
million to fund the e-rate program. Regulators plan to limit
collections for each subsequent quarter through mid-1999 to $325
million per quarter. Since the federal program can pay out no more
than has been collected, it's evident that many eligible schools
and libraries will not get the funding they want until well into
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Held up since July, the first allocation of $2.25 billion in
funds was to be paid out in late October. Meantime, the FCC
extended the application deadline for the next funding period to
Dec. 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times, I fear we may be losing our perspective on these
matters,'' said Rep. Earl Blumenauer, D-Ore, a strong backer of the
e-rate plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long-distance phone bills are now at their lowest point in
history,'' he said. ``The telecommunications industry has saved
billions in costs as a result of telecommunications reform to date.
And yet a controversy has erupted over one element that would
represent less than one cent per day per customer line to provide
Internet access for America's schools and libraries.''
</P>
<P>
   Concludes Blumenauer: ``Schools and libraries across the country
took the federal government at its word. They spent countless hours
and tens of thousands of dollars preparing applications to receive
funds from the FCC under the e-rate program. We must not break that
commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
