<HEADER>
A5351 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIGITAL-INDUSTRY-$ADV     11-11 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-INDUSTRY-$ADV15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HIGH-TECH INDUSTRY FOCUSES ON TEACHING, NOT HARDWARE
 &HT;    With DIGITAL-DIVIDE. Moving in (a) national and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, Nov. 15.
 &HT;    By MICHAEL E. KANELL
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When high-tech America began a high-profile critique of
education in the early 1980s, many executives rebuked schools for
churning out students whose math and science skills were inferior.
</P>
<P>
   When the personal computer boom arrived, the technology
companies campaigned to get the machines into classrooms, often
donating hardware or software, or offering discounts. With the
establishment of a national Net Day, the companies sent employees
into schools to install connections for linking to the global
information network.
</P>
<P>
   But as the millennium edges closer, the businesses are still
worried that future progress, innovation and growth will be stymied
by an inadequate work force.
</P>
<P>
   And while they continue to spend hundreds of millions of dollars
to supercharge the connection between education and technology, the
larger companies have a new focus _ on the teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Turning education into an industry clone would miss the point,
said Robin Willner, IBM director of social policy and programs.
``Vocational education has its role, but that's not what this is
about. We are not having trouble hiring entry-level workers for the
factory floor.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM, with offices around the nation and the world, wants a
well-educated citizenry and a strong economy wherever it operates,
she said. ``You can't have a successful business in an unsuccessful
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Teaching computer skills should not be the top priority, Willner
said. ``The priority is basic academic competence. If you have
basic academic skills, I can teach you how to use a computer.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM in 1994 committed $35 million to a program it is called
``Reinventing Education.'' Wary of the stereotype of a high-tech
company ridding itself of obsolete products while boasting of
philanthropy, the company tries to work with a school the way it
would with a customer, Willner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not coming to back up the truck and give you whatever
happens to be in the warehouse,'' she said. ``We work the same way
as we do with our best customers. We focus on a special problem
that you want to solve.''
</P>
<P>
   Lezlie(cq) Bishop, AT&AMP;T corporate affairs director, said the
company sees a distinction between vocational training and the kind
of experience that makes someone a better employee. Programs
supported by AT&AMP;T are not intended to just teach the narrowest of
skills that might be used in the workplace, she said. ``I don't see
it as job training, but I do see it as preparation for work. I'm
from the liberal arts point of view. If I teach you how to learn,
you can teach yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers are a key focus for AT&AMP;T, too. But the technology
brought to schools should not be seen as an end in itself, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the equipment in the world is not going to make any
difference until teachers understand it,'' Bishop said. ``I would
like to see teachers viewing technology the same way they view
textbooks, filmstrips and videotapes. They are tools.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T in 1997 committed $150 million to a long-term education
program known as the Learning Network. While infrastructure is a
large part of the picture, much of the effort is aimed at teachers,
Bishop said.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies have similar approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based BellSouth Corp. helps shape and pay for programs
in which teachers get out of classrooms to see how other jobs look
and feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 80 percent of teachers have never worked outside
education. This is designed to create models of how teachers can be
engaged in the workforce,'' a spokesman said. ``It is not just to
watch. Teachers have to deliver value.''
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt Thomas, executive director of the Morris Brown
Research Institute, which trains teachers and administrators, uses
a studio in Atlanta that can broadcast training sessions to schools
around the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is to be a vehicle to help teachers better understand and
utilize technology as a tool in the classroom. We are sure can't
manufacture more time for teachers, but we can help them utilize
their time much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal and
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
