<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5363 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-HELPLINES-ART-2TA     11-11 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-HELPLINES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVIGATING THE FRUSTRATING WORLD OF TECHNICAL HELP LINES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MATTHEW LAKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a popular myth that what counts in computer products is
features, price and performance. But if you listen to the people
who use computer products, or read what they're writing on message
boards and news groups, you get a different picture.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important to customers _ and maybe more so _ is getting
good technical support from a company once they have bought a
product. And they are not always getting it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always 20 or 30 minutes waiting for them to answer the
phone,'' said Bob Dunkelberger, a boat builder in New Jersey with a
two-year-old personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Kaplan, a research librarian for the Delaware County
Library System, said it was not unusual for a support staff member
to throw out a solution, any solution, to end a call quickly.
``Sometimes you know they haven't a clue what the problem is,'' she
said. ``You try it. It won't work. Then you have to call back. When
you finally get back to them, they act surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   On other occasions, support technicians actually refuse to help.
While using Microsoft Access to work on a database project, Michael
Patrick Ellard and Daniel Wright, members of the Berkeley Macintosh
Users Group, tried to get help on Microsoft's premium help line,
which charges $55 each time for solving problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The support person interrupted and said it was not a problem
with Access,'' Ellard said. ``It was with two programs working
together. Since Microsoft didn't support the other program, he
wouldn't try to help us.''
</P>
<P>
   As the prices of computers and software drop and companies look
for ways to stretch their money, tech support budgets can lose out
to the needs of marketing and research and development departments
or company shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   So companies are seeking ways to cut the cost of offering their
customers help. That often involves charging people who urgently
need help and want to talk to a tech support worker and providing
free online help, recorded help messages on voice mail and fax-back
services that cut down on personnel costs.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all support calls are bad experiences. ``I find
hardware tech support people to be much better,'' Ellard said.
``With companies like Micron and Gateway, it's probably a problem
with a driver and they've heard it 400 times before, so they're
great _ they get you what you need.'' Dunkelberger said, ``The
smaller companies seem to make more of an effort.''
</P>
<P>
   But getting phone support can still be stressful. Many people do
not like asking for help, and when they pick up the phone, they
often have to wait a long time to speak to anyone _ while toll-call
charges mount.
</P>
<P>
   And technical support personnel sometimes lack basic
communications skills. ``Some people talk down to you, like you're
a child,'' Ms. Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   But members of technical support staff have their own problems.
Some customers ``go into the call with an attitude,'' said Peter
McGarahan, executive director of the Help Desk Institute, a
professional organization. ``The friendly customer support guy gets
someone on the other end who's upset and aggravated.''
</P>
<P>
   Uncommunicative callers can be an even bigger problem. David
Ratti, who has offered technical support on the phone for six years
and is now at Intel's Answer Express, said some callers held back
because they felt responsible for ``breaking something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll deny adding any hardware or software because they feel
they'll be judged,'' Ratti said. ``If a tech is going to do his
job, he'll find out in the end anyway. You can save yourself a lot
of time by 'fessing up right at the start.''
</P>
<P>
   Support technicians say callers sometimes get upset if they do
not get the answers they expect. ``One user was complaining, `When
I type, it doesn't show up on screen,''' Ratti said. ``It turned
out he was trying to enter his password, and all he saw was
asterisks. And he didn't accept that there wasn't a problem. He was
upset and wanted to make it work right.''
</P>
<P>
   Mutual frustration between callers and company representatives
is not the only problem in technical support. In the past few
years, high-tech companies have steadily reduced their technical
support offerings.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, the Wordperfect Corp. provided free phone
support through a toll-free number. Nowadays, hardware and software
companies alike are reducing the scope of their free
technical-support offerings. And toll-free support lines are almost
nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   At Wordperfect, many programs now come with only 30 days of free
support, and that applies only to installation problems.
</P>
<P>
   It is becoming more common for people to pay for quick help.
Microsoft has a graduated pay-per-incident scale that ranges from a
$15 flat fee for help with a consumer product like Microsoft Money
to $35 for help with Windows or Office and $55 to $195 for
assistance with programming tools and databases.
</P>
<P>
   Intuit, which publishes the popular Quicken software, provides
premium support, which offers faster response time and a toll-free
number, for $49 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Recent changes in Intuit's policy of free technical support are
typical of current trends in the industry. In 1989, Intuit provided
unlimited free support but did not have a toll-free number. Then it
scaled back, offering free phone support for registered users for
only one year.
</P>
<P>
   Now only a few problems, like installation, qualify for the
first year's free support. People with other questions are referred
to other sources, like the company's Web site, an
automated-response phone system and fax-back system, and support
programs that charge fees.
</P>
<P>
   Intuit's new support policy is more liberal than some other
companies'. Microsoft, for example, provides only 90 days of free
support for Windows 98 (and many have complained that the free
support lines are constantly busy).
</P>
<P>
   Charging for a service that used to be free is bound to make
waves, even if paid support is faster, is offered through a
toll-free number and is covered by a flat rate of $50 a year. So
why are companies moving toward this model? Bill Rose, executive
director of the Software Support Professionals Association,
attributes the changes to tremendous expansion in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, 50 million multimedia PCs appeared under Christmas
trees _ amazingly complex boxes compared to a few short years ago _
and the majority were new users,'' Rose said. ``Most support calls,
about 85 percent, aren't about fixing bugs. They're what we
classify as usability issues. They're how-to calls.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   McGarahan said: ``The problems that come in have become a lot
harder. In the past, you had to be really technical to set up
networks in your home or publish Web sites. Now your neighbor's
doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   But when your neighbor runs into difficulties, the support
center phones begin to ring. And that means that free support lines
are often busy. Tougher technical problems _ and remedial questions
_ result in longer calls, so customers have to wait longer.
</P>
<P>
   The companies with the most generous support policies often come
across as the least responsive. ``If support is free, then demand
is insatiable.'' McGarahan said. ``Most people want to pick up the
phone and call. You attach a value to support by charging for it.''
</P>
<P>
   If hardware and software makers are going to keep customers,
they clearly cannot charge for all the support they provide, though
the idea of bypassing a half-hour of being on hold on a telephone
makes pay-per-incident charges seem more appealing.
</P>
<P>
   For many how-to issues, companies have turned to the Internet to
dispense help. The medium is well suited to self-help, with its
lists of frequently asked questions, tips and searchable databases,
like Microsoft's Knowledge Base, that quickly focus on problem
areas.
</P>
<P>
   And it is attractive to many customers, too, because online help
is available around the clock. But customers may need to be prodded
to use online help.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you set up self-help and self-support,'' McGarahan said,
``customers need incentives not to pick up the phone and call.''
The incentive is price. If customers go on line, there is no charge
for anything they find there. For companies, online assistance
reduces the burden on already crowded phone systems and busy
support staffs. And when help is offered by e-mail, that can reduce
the stress on support staffs and callers alike.
</P>
<P>
   On-line help has changed the face of technical support. Rose
said that about 80 percent of such support was provided through
phone calls and 20 percent on line. ``We're hoping to shift it to
60-40,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Larsen, vice president for customer support at Gateway,
said that ``we don't have to staff the call centers to the extent
we did two years ago'' because of self-help services, like
tutorials on CD-ROMs that are shipped with Gateway computers.
</P>
<P>
   Peer groups are another source of technical help. Part of
Intuit's support package for Quicken is a Web-based forum for
customers to discuss problems and issues with other customers. Such
forums are the most popular third-party source of help.
</P>
<P>
   The Windows User Group Network, called Wugnet, manages some 200
support forums, which include message boards moderated by system
operators. To Joel Diamond, Wugnet's technical director, the
strength of the message boards is the diversity of the enthusiasts
and system operators who tackle people's technical problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had a problem with an H-P computer, with a Diamond video
card and a Hayes modem running Windows NT, I could go to four
different vendors to get resolution,'' Diamond said. But if people
with problems post them in the right online message boards, they
can pick the brains of dozens of technical experts to hammer out
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   But resources must be chosen carefully. ``A dedicated news
server supplied by a vendor can serve as a superb channel of
support,'' Diamond said, ``but I say caveat emptor. You don't know
what you're getting. Tech support advice from a source you don't
know can be more dangerous to your system than viruses.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, many people are turning to professional help
desks to sort out their problems with multiple products. If a
customer is prepared to pay a software developer for technical
support for one product, it is a small step to pay another
organization to support a whole collection of products.
</P>
<P>
   PC Crisis Line, Intel's Answer Express, the Geek Squad and the
grandiose-sounding America's Help Desk are a few of the hired guns
of the tech support world. They charge metered fees that start at
around $3 a minute, flat-rate fees for each call or monthly
subscriptions of $10 or $20.
</P>
<P>
   But whether the support comes from the company that supplies the
goods or another company, one problem remains. ``Good tech support
people are hard to keep,'' McGarahan said. ``People take the job to
get into a company, then go for more glamorous or highly
compensated jobs. In the industry's eyes, tech support hasn't been
a valid career path.'' By some accounts, most phone support workers
stay in their jobs for 8 to 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage professional standards in the industry, the
Software Support Professionals Association is offering
certification for tech support programs. And the Help Desk
Institute offers certification for help desk staff members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of the certification criteria is aimed at human skills
sets,'' McGarahan said. That means, he said, ``making customers
feel that they're not idiots.''
</P>
<P>
   And some companies have begun to get smarter about keeping good
support representatives on the phones. At Gateway, for example, the
pay structure is based on customer satisfaction and the efficient
resolution of problems, so good tech support workers can advance
their careers without leaving the field.
</P>
<P>
   How does that approach sit with tech support customers?
``Anything that keeps good support people on the phone with me is a
good idea,'' Ms. Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
