<HEADER>
A5430 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-POETS-1112-CO     11-11 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-POETS-1112-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTACK OF THE POETS; IN BRITAIN, POETS INVADE WITH RHYME, REASON
 &HT;    EDs: ALL names are CQ.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ For more than a year, lawyers at the prestigious London
firm of Mischcon de Reya have been receiving poems mingled among
their e-mails about boosting billable hours and other office
tedium.
</P>
<P>
   Far from flirtations, these verses are part of the job, weekly
readings selected by the firm's resident poet, Lavinia Greenlaw.
</P>
<P>
   Greenlaw, who also penned a haiku for corporate Christmas cards,
selects poems to inspire, provoke or to just make the lawyers
think. ``Throughout the day they would write back with their
suggestions or their own poems,'' she said. ``Sometimes they were
baffled or amused, or simply didn't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least they were touched by poetry, which is the point of
the year-old ``Poetry Places'' project, funded by a $750,000 grant
from the National Lottery. The program is run by the national
Poetry Society, which intends to place 100 poets in schools,
businesses and other environments throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting in that it makes people think about their lives,
to think creatively and about the importance of words and poetry,''
said Christina Patterson, who manages the program for the Poetry
Society.
</P>
<P>
   Poets have been assigned to the BBC, the huge department store
chain Marks &AMP; Spencer, the London Zoo, the Botanical Gardens at Kew
and the Barnsley soccer club. The program also has dispatched poets
to inspire and be inspired by such disparate endeavors as garbage
collection -- verses are planned for trash bags -- and
fish-and-chips shops. The society also is considering placing a
poet on a natural gas platform in the North Sea.
</P>
<P>
   What the poets actually do at their workplaces varies. ``In most
places there would be some general meeting with staff, or a maybe
they'd go have a drink and talk about poetry,'' Patterson said.
``We want to get them to think about writing poetry, and in some
places there might be workshops with the staff.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   John Agard, the resident poet at the BBC, holds workshops and is
pushing for poetry spots in programming. ``Poetry is often
presented in the media as something very precious,'' he said in a
recent interview. ``But there's no reason why, if there's a program
on gardening or cooking, you can't have a poem on gardening or
cooking. Poetry can be presented in a much more vibrant way.''
</P>
<P>
   Agard believes the importance of poetry in ordinary life is
underestimated. ``People say they don't read poetry but they seek
out their favorite poems for weddings and funerals. So much of our
lives are marked out with linear maps -- poetry gives another
map.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Heloise Paull, spokeswoman for the law firm Mischcon -- with 32
partners, a staff of more than 200 and counts among its clients the
Princess Diana Memorial Fund -- considers having a resident poet an
employment benefit that enhances the firm's morale and culture.
``We really benefited enormously by it,'' Paull said. ``Lots of
staff have written poems who would never have thought about it
otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   She knows of lawyers who would spend their mornings languishing
in the dry precision of legalese and then emerge from lunchtime
poetry sessions revitalized from contemplating the mysteries of
verse.
</P>
<P>
   The poets also are rewarded, said Tobias Hill, the resident poet
at the London Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poetry can be lonely business if you're just sitting around
writing by yourself everyday,'' Hill said. ``This gets me out
meeting people. It's a gift in terms of material.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill is fascinated by what he calls ``the dark side of zoos.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the zoo's staff, Hill tries to reach the people
who come to see the animals, particularly children, with readings
and a poetry contest. He has created a poetry trail, displaying
verses to match the animals. D.H. Lawrence's ``Snakes'' is at the
reptile house.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important to Hill and other poets are the stipends
-- up to $16,000 a year -- which help them focus more on their art
rather than the other occupations -- such as journalism -- they
pursue to pay the bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allows me to buy time as a poet,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional poem follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Here's a sample from Peter Street, the fish-and-chips resident
poet:
</P>
<P>
   ``Mates''
</P>
<P>
   Last night's newsprint, tasting of chips wet, tanner a bag
</P>
<P>
   Folded artistically, to stop all that pea juice, dripping onto
best
</P>
<P>
   hand-me-downs.
</P>
<P>
   Walking home after last bus with mates you confess everything to
good
</P>
<P>
   friends, together
</P>
<P>
   in a meeting place, smelling of fish and chips.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
