<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5445 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAITI-AMWAY-1112-COX     11-11 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-AMWAY-1112-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AMWAY THRIVES IN HAITI, HEMISPHERE'S POOREST COUNTRY
 &HT;    With photos placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti _ After decades of barely scraping by,
Lionel Benjamin is now on a fanatical quest to make his life
better.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher has called on friends, neighbors, and anyone else he
can think of, goading them to attend a motivational seminar at the
dilapidated Rex Theater.
</P>
<P>
   And many of them come.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the gathering attracts an overflow crowd of 300 people,
who are all waiting to hear a speaker's roaring discourse on how to
make dreams a reality.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin is just a small part of one of the most peculiar
expansions in business today -- the expansion into Haiti of Amway
Corp., the giant, Michigan-based direct seller of vitamins,
shampoo, toilet paper, and a smorgasbord of household products.
</P>
<P>
   ``My salary as a teacher just wasn't sufficient to support my
family,'' said Benjamin, wearing a flashy, well-tailored suit.
``Now I'm in a business that's booming, a business that I truly
love.''
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin's been urging people to attend Amway's monthly meetings
for about three years.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Haiti is the Western Hemisphere's poorest country
doesn't deter his efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Haiti's 8 million people earn less than $250 a year
while living in grass huts with no access to safe water or adequate
sanitation. With an economy in shambles, Haiti also suffers from an
unemployment rate of more than 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yet more than 2,300 people here are pushing Amway, successfully
marketing a wide range of products. These products include
everything from toothpaste, sold for $4.68, to a 20-piece set of
cookware, sold for $941.
</P>
<P>
   Even company officials acknowledge that, at first, Amway and
Haiti may seem like an odd mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wondered how this could work in Haiti . . . but I've been
very impressed with the people there,'' said Kelly Savage, director
of Amway North America Administration. ``We are attracting middle-
and upper-class people there (as distributors) who have worked hard
and have a lot of heart.''
</P>
<P>
   She pointed out that Haitians, in general, are keenly interested
in nutrition so that vitamins and nutritional supplements have
become big hits, as have diapers, cosmetics, and skin-care
products.
</P>
<P>
   Amway is performing so well that the company launched its 49th
affiliate here in September -- Amway Haiti Limited.
</P>
<P>
   And Amway just finished work on a new service center, which sits
behind concrete walls across from a cow pasture.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bizarre sight, this modern investment by a
multibillion-dollar operation that is passed daily by scores of
poor peasants gracefully balancing huge baskets of rice, beans, and
various other foods on their heads.
</P>
<P>
   But the new center enables Haiti's growing number of
distributors to place orders one day and pick them up the next,
whereas before they might have had to wait months for orders to be
imported from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Amway was founded in 1959, and is supported by more than 450
personal care, household and other items. Today, the company has
more than 3 million distributors who peddle products in 80
different countries.
</P>
<P>
   In fiscal year 1998, Amway's worldwide sales totaled $5.7
billion, a drop from $7 billion the year before. The decline is
blamed on economic problems in Asia, where sales suffered a decline
of 18 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Amway products have been marketed in Haiti for nearly 20 years,
with the number of distributors continuing to climb steadily.
</P>
<P>
   The company's success in Haiti is not really that surprising.
Amway champions the dual themes of Christian morality and free
enterprise, both of which appeal to a conservative population fond
of the American lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the enticing incentive program doesn't hurt. The
company rewards its distributors -- or ``ambassadors'' in
Amway-speak -- with a portion of the sales that are generated by
those they've recruited, or sponsored.
</P>
<P>
   At the recent motivational meeting, a young, well-dressed man
named Al Colas took the stage like a flamboyant televangelist.
</P>
<P>
   As Amway's top distributor in Haiti, Colas even enjoys a
regal-sounding title: Diamond Haiti Distributor.
</P>
<P>
   He presented the Amway program as he might a passion for
religion -- whooping, stomping, hollering, and flapping his arms.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of prospective clients loved it, wildly applauding any
shot they might have at becoming rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amway allows us to take responsibility for ourselves, to be
our own bosses,'' said Freddie Clermont, who has distributed Amway
here for nearly two years. ``I know that the products cost a lot,
but they truly are excellent products.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that the shampoo, which costs more than $6 -- or more
than a week's salary for many Haitians -- might last three times
longer than local brands.
</P>
<P>
   She added that two of the most popular Amway products in Haiti
are soap and toothpaste.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Knowles, president of the Haitian-American Chamber of
Commerce here, said Amway products have become status symbols in
Haiti, the same way Tupperware products are throughout much of
Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very poor country, but we do have a tiny, tiny
minority of people who have a lot of money, and they want to spend
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Amway has been criticized in books and
articles for offering over-priced products and making promises it
can't keep.
</P>
<P>
   But that hasn't dampened the enthusiasm of Haitian entrepreneurs
like Benjamin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do Amway because I have lots of love in my heart and I
really want people to be happy,'' he said earnestly. ``The cookware
set, for example, comes with a lifetime guarantee, and you can't
beat that.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
