<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5449 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY12-COX     11-11 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DEBATE GEARS UP ON PRIVATE ACCOUNTS FOR SOCIAL SECURITY
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite a bumpy ride in the stock markets and an
election shake-up in Congress, both political parties are keeping
the door open to setting up personal investment accounts in the
Social Security overhaul expected for next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm willing to look at it,'' House Minority Leader Dick
Gephardt, D-Mo., said this week on CNBC's ``Hardball.'' House
Budget Chairman John Kasich, R-Ohio, restated his support for
putting a portion of workers' Social Security taxes in individual
savings accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Outgoing House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., has urged that his
party make its first goal next year to use the federal budget
surplus to begin ``creating a personal Social Security savings
account'' for every worker who pays into the Social Security
system.
</P>
<P>
   Calling it a ``great historic opportunity,'' Gingrich told
members of his party in his valedictory address Monday that such a
plan would ``save Social Security'' for current retirees, improve
it for the baby boom generation and guarantee retirement benefits
for their children in an account that ``no Washington politician
can touch.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts are sharply divided on whether such a plan would work,
and the debate is only beginning in Washington, where the House
Ways and Means will hold a hearing on Nov. 19 on reforming Social
Security. President Clinton has called a White House conference on
the subject for Dec. 8-9.
</P>
<P>
   Labor unions have objected to privatization, and their success
in turning out votes for Democratic candidates for the Nov. 3
elections could give them more say.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt, a longtime ally of labor, set strict limits for
considering individual accounts. He said the investments must be
directed by the Social Security's trustees or else reduced to three
safe options, much as the federal government oversees similar
accounts for its employees.
</P>
<P>
   As the debate gears up, extremes on both sides are offering
contradictory views, beginning with whether the program even needs
to be fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Weisbrot, of the liberal research group Preamble Center for
Public Policy, is preparing a book for early next year accusing
politicians of building up a ``phony crisis'' in Social Security so
they can ``save'' it. Weisbrot has written in opinion columns that
the system is fundamentally sound for 75 years. He traces the talk
of privatization to Wall Street financial firms that hope to reap
profits from the expanded market.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the libertarian Cato Institute is mounting a public
education campaign arguing that privatizing Social Security is a
``win-win'' proposal that would save money, make retirement
benefits more secure, and help blunt the antagonisms between
generations.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
