<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5419 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-SEASONS-NYTSF     11-11 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-SEASONS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEASONS OF HER LIFE
</HEADLINE>
  A Biography of Madeleine Korbel Albright 
 By Ann Blackman 
 Illustrated. 398 pp. New York: A Lisa Drew Book/Scribner. $27 
 ------ 
 FREQUENT FLIER 
 By JACOB HEILBRUNN 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Foreign policy makers are unlikely celebrities. Henry Kissinger
was the first. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is another.
Though Albright has never claimed to be an intellectual
heavyweight, the similarities between her career and Kissinger's
are striking. Like Kissinger, she is a refugee from Nazism who used
an academic post as a launching pad to public acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Seasons of Her Life,'' Ann Blackman, a veteran reporter for
Time, provides a revealing portrait of Albright. Blackman, who
writes with economy and dispatch, has combed the archives and
conducted almost 200 interviews with Albright's friends and
associates, including President Clinton. Her spadework has paid
off. Albright emerges as someone who has again and again reinvented
herself.
</P>
<P>
   Albright was decisively shaped by her father, Josef Korbel. Some
of Blackman's most original research centers on him. A Czechoslovak
diplomat, Korbel joined his country's government in exile in London
after the Nazi takeover. Blackman shows that while Korbel worked
briefly with the Communists following the war, he may have fudged
this fact after he defected to the United States. ``He sought to
bury any suggestion that he might have at one time believed that
Communists and democrats would work together in Czechoslovakia,''
Blackman writes.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most far-reaching step Korbel and his wife, Anna,
took was to abandon their Jewish heritage. In 1997, when the story
of Albright's Jewish ancestry made headlines, she was forced to
confront her past. Albright does not seem to have been eager to do
so. The Washington Post reporter Michael Dobbs, who broke the
story, told Blackman that Albright was reluctant to give him the
name of a surviving cousin living in Prague. According to Blackman,
``Albright appeared to be struggling to understand the motives of
her father. ... The careful cocoon he had woven ... had split
open.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright, however, had already encountered some bumps in her
life. After graduating from Wellesley in 1959, she married the
newspaper scion Joseph Albright. In 1982, he asked her for a
divorce. Albright was stunned. She started anew teaching at
Georgetown University, where she dazzled students with her outgoing
personality and blunt speaking style. She also devoted much effort
to running a salon in her Georgetown home as the Democrats worked
to regain the White House. She took a decidedly dovish line in the
1980's that she jettisoned with the end of the cold war. After
working on several political campaigns, including Michael Dukakis's
ill-fated run for the Presidency, Albright was chosen by President
Clinton to become Ambassador to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Together with her savvy aide, James P. Rubin, currently her
press secretary, Albright worked tirelessly to promote herself in
the news media. (In her introduction, Blackman says Rubin implied
that Albright would cooperate with her in exchange for favorable
coverage in Time. Blackman refused.) With Warren Christopher as
Secretary of State and Anthony Lake as national security adviser,
Albright was the only member of the Administration who could
communicate effectively. In the mold of such previous United
Nations Ambassadors as Daniel Patrick Moynihan and Jeane
Kirkpatrick, Albright won the spotlight as a doughty proponent of
American democratic values.
</P>
<P>
   With the backing of women's groups and Hillary Rodham Clinton,
Albright was sworn in as Secretary of State in 1997. The going has
been rockier than at the United Nations. Albright's record as
Secretary of State is still inconclusive, and Blackman is, of
course, able to give it only abbreviated treatment. Nonetheless,
she has done a fine job of explaining Albright's astonishing
ascent.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Jacob Heilbrunn is a senior editor at The New Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
