<HEADER>
A5421 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CHILDRENS-BRI     11-11 2511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CHILDRENS-BRIEFS-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARLENE SARDINE
</HEADLINE>
  Written and illustrated by Chris Raschka 
 Orchard, $15.95. (Ages 3 to 8)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the words ``easy-open book'' stamped in one corner and
``net wt. 12 oz.'' in another, the cover of ``Arlene Sardine'' is a
jaunty visual pun on a sardine can. The colors are a gorgeous swirl
of greens, pinks, yellows, reds and oranges. The first line of the
story, ``So you want to be a sardine,'' may initially strike the
reader as odd. But in this bright and cheery context, it seems
simply whimsical.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Raschka's cozy text -- ``I knew a little fish once who
wanted to be a sardine'' -- tells the story of Arlene, who was
``born in a fjord.'' ``She was a happy little brisling because she
had about ten hundred thousand friends.'' Raschka has painted a
school of them swimming along in sun-struck blue and yellow waters.
</P>
<P>
   Then Arlene swims ``into a big net, a purse net, a big purse
net.'' She ``swam around in the net for three days and three nights
and did not eat anything, so her stomach would be empty. There is a
word for this. The word is thronging.'' Another word is euphemism,
in this case for ``starving,'' but wait, the worst is yet to be:
``Here, on the deck of the fishing boat, Arlene died.''
</P>
<P>
   How many readers, of any age, will balk at the sudden transition
from Arlene-as-friend to Arlene-as-food? Death, of course, has an
established place in children's literature. Fairy tales do it
grimly; smart writers, like Judith Viorst in ``The Tenth Good Thing
About Barney,'' do it gently. Leo Lionni does it bravely. In his
classic ``Swimmy,'' a small fry's family is eaten by a big fish,
but Swimmy joins with new friends to frighten the predator away.
</P>
<P>
   It is far from clear, though, that ``Arlene Sardine'' is
intended to be about death. Raschka's prose is eerily detached:
``Delicately smoked was she.'' ``I'll bet Arlene felt well rested
on the conveyor belt.'' (Make that heavenly rested.) Arlene is
``closed up with no air inside, hermetically, and cooked in her
can.'' At its best, the text is a social studies lesson on sardine
processing, complete with new vocabulary. At its worst, it's a
twisted, prekindergarten version of Heaven's Gate, minus the comet.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Raschka is the author and illustrator of many wonderful
children's stories, such as ``Mysterious Thelonious,'' ``Can't
Sleep,'' ``The Blushful Hippopotamus'' and ``Yo! Yes!,'' a
Caldecott Honor Book. Unfortunately, with ``Arlene Sardine'' he has
missed his mark, whatever it may have been. _ MARGARET MOORMAN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; YOU CAN'T TAKE A BALLOON INTO THE METROPOLITAN MUSEUM &QL; 
 &UR; By Jacqueline Preiss Weitzman &QL; 
 &UR; Illustrated by Robin Preiss Glasser. &QL; 
 &UR; Dial Books for Young Readers, $16.99. (Ages 5 to 9) &QL; 
 &UR; HOW TO TAKE YOUR GRANDMOTHER TO THE MUSEUM &QL; 
 &UR; By Lois Wyse and Molly Rose Goldman &QL; 
 &UR; Illustrated by Marie-Louise Gay &QL; 
 &UR; American Museum of Natural History/City &AMP; Company/Workman, $12.95.
(Ages 5 to 9) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The question I hope my 3-year-old granddaughter, Rebecca, will
ask is, Where's Grandpa? He is not to be sighted in either of these
colorful accounts of young cuties who go courting culture with
their grandmas: one at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, one at the
American Museum of Natural History.
</P>
<P>
   While the grandma and granddaughter of Jacqueline Preiss
Weitzman in ``You Can't Take a Balloon Into the Metropolitan
Museum'' are shown in Robin Preiss Glasser's illustrations bingeing
wordlessly on masterpieces, their yellow balloon floats
mischievously around Manhattan, inciting chaos and finding
improbable connections between city scenes and paintings. Isn't
that Central Park Lake George Washington is crossing?
</P>
<P>
   Over on the West Side, meantime, in ``How to Take Your
Grandmother to the Museum,'' 10-year-old Molly Rose Goldman,
narrator and know-it-all, is showing off her acquaintance with
civilization from the dinosaurs to the museum shop, where her
grandma (Lois Wyse in real life, as drawn by Marie-Louise Gay)
comes across with a snowflake obsidian for Molly's rock collection.
(Molly, who is given to making pronouncements like ``We have to
save our wildlife,'' even sounds like a museum-shop artifact.)
</P>
<P>
   Both couples are evidently in training for the ladies-who-lunch
crowd at watering spots with a cultural ambience. (See Mary
Cassatt's ``Lady at the Tea Table.'')
</P>
<P>
   But the true cultural message is one of female refinement and
male superfluity. Where are the old gents? Have they passed on,
leaving the widows comfortable enough to spring for museum
admission fees and tchotchkes from the shops? Or have the bounders
gone to greener pastures? (Catch that top-hatted coot exiting a
limousine at the Plaza with a bride; maybe she's his granddaughter,
but she could be the bounder's fourth wife, a third his age. Molly
would never approve.)
</P>
<P>
   Are the men of the family still working away, without time or
inclination or aptitude for bonding with grade-school girls? Or,
and here's my suspicion, are grandmas being invested with the role
of culture carrier while grandpas are consigned to a television
stupor watching a ball game?
</P>
<P>
   The lesson for Rebecca seems to be that you can't take grandpa
to cultural playgrounds. It's the women who bear the higher values
of the human race, or as Molly would surely declare, ``We have to
save the good, true and beautiful.'' When female writers and
illustrators decide to send grandma and granddaughter on a visit to
the Metropolitan Opera, count on a glimpse of grandpa snoozing
during the big aria. _ WALTER GOODMAN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE 20TH CENTURY CHILDREN'S BOOK TREASURY &QL; 
 &UR; Celebrated Picture Booksand Stories to Read Aloud &QL; 
 &UR; Selected by Janet Schulman &QL; 
 &UR; Knopf, $40. (All ages) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are 44 of the century's most cherished picture books and
stories, chosen by one of publishing's most esteemed editors. The
volume is handsome, the color reproductions sparkling and the
selections unimpeachable, with everything from classics like
``Goodnight Moon'' to contemporary gems like ``Good Night,
Gorilla.'' Everything is here -- except the magic.
</P>
<P>
   In producing this volume the publisher has overridden the
obvious -- that the power of a picture book arises from the play
between the pictures and the text, and that the pictures are as
important as the words. All but two of these stories contain the
complete texts, but in every single case, the art has been altered,
with changes ranging from reformatting pictures to leaving some out
altogether. This version of Robert McCloskey's ``Make Way for
Ducklings,'' for example, retains only a third of the pictures. All
the books have been redesigned, so that as many as five pages'
worth of pictures now fit on a single page. The greater the art,
the worse it fares. Maurice Sendak's ``Where the Wild Things Are''
is reproduced in two tiers (with some of the art, unfortunately,
disappearing when it crosses the binding from left page to right);
readers can see the ``place where the wild things are,'' but,
reminded so strongly of the confines of the page, they no longer
have the illusion of being able to enter that place. Sendak's work,
like that of the others here, becomes a story instead of a world.
</P>
<P>
   The differences between the originals and these versions can be
subtle -- but then, so is the difference between good work and a
work of art. In ``Madeline,'' Ludwig Bemelmans used two
illustrations to show Miss Clavel, ``afraid of a disaster,''
rushing to the girls' dormitory in the middle of the night: ``Miss
Clavel ran fast'' (the nun swoops down a hall) ``and faster'' (the
nun advances farther down the same hall); the visual and verbal
rhythms accentuate each other. In one of the many alterations in
this ``Madeline,'' the whole sentence is paired with the second
picture. While this may seem a minor loss, such instances multiply,
and the reader's experience diminishes.
</P>
<P>
   This anthology is not without its place, but the true audience
for ``The 20th Century Children's Book Treasury'' is limited to
those who already know the works. To offer these half-strength
versions for a child's first encounter with the greats would be
immeasurably sad. _ ELIZABETH DEVEREAUX
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-CHILDRENS-BRIEFS-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: ELIZABETH DEVEREAUX) &QL; 
 &UR; CAT UP A TREE &QL; 
 &UR; By Ann Hassett &QL; 
 &UR; Illustrated by John Hassett &QL; 
 &UR; Walter Lorraine/Houghton Mifflin, $15. (ages 3 to 8) &QL; 
 &UR; CAT UP A TREE &QL; 
 &UR; By Anne Isaacs &QL; 
 &UR; Illustrated by Stephen Mackey &QL; 
 &UR; Dutton, $15.99. (Ages 3 to 5) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two new picture books with the same title, CAT UP A TREE, could
not be more different. The one by Ann Hassett, illustrated by John
Hassett, is funny and whimsical and engaging, while the one by Anne
Isaacs, illustrated by Stephen Mackey, is just pretentious. The
Hassetts' Nana Quimby, plump and bespectacled in sneakers, apron
and purple polka-dot house dress, is in the middle of baking
chocolate chip cookies when she sees a cat who needs help. Five,
then 10, then 15, on up to 40 cats end up in the tree outside Nana
Quimby's window. She calls the Fire Department: '' 'Sorry,' said
the firehouse, 'we do not catch cats up a tree anymore. Call back
if that cat starts playing with matches.' '' The police are
interested only if the cats rob a bank, and the pet store says,
``Call back if the cats wish to buy a dog.'' The zoo, the post
office, the library, City Hall, nobody wants to help, so Nana
Quimby throws the telephone out the window and into the tree, and
the cats walk across its wire and into her arms. When the town that
wouldn't help finds itself overrun with mice and calls her, they
find out just how much help they can expect in return: '' 'Sorry,'
said Nana Quimby, 'the cats do not catch mice anymore. Call back if
you wish to hear cats purr.' '' John Hassett paints a delightful
world with grape jelly-bean clouds and noodle cats with spaghetti
tails who curl and drape and leap in every which way and every
which color. This is a book to read and reread, with cats to count
and recount, and little visual details like satellite dishes and
mice on windowsills to spot with each new pass. Sadly, Anne Isaacs,
the author of the Caldecott Honor book ``Swamp Angel,'' loses her
footing with her collection of poems about a cat up a tree. The
verse is filled with embarrassing metaphysical vocabulary: how does
one explain phrases like ``Pour down your cold, transmuting fire''
to a small or medium-sized child, and why would one bother? John
Donne meets T. S. Eliot this ain't; and Stephen Mackey's murky oil
paintings of poets, pyramids and moonlight lack spark and wit.
What's in a name? _ JEN NESSEL
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ZOOM CITY &QL; 
 &UR; Written and illustrated by Thacher Hurd &QL; 
 &UR; Harper Festival, $5.95. (Ages 1 and up) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Noise, action and color -- the three basic food groups for
nourishing the imaginations of younger readers -- are amply
displayed in this offbeat board book about cars and driving. Using
a pop-art palette that runs to hot pinks and psychedelic pastel
swooshes, the author follows a family of brown dogs as it cruises
down city streets in multicolored autos, gets into a (painless)
fender-bender, is towed to a garage and, finally, merges back into
traffic, smiling. There's a loopiness to the computer-animated
drawings: most of the vehicles are vintage 1950's Chevys, Buicks,
Cadillacs and other classics that have been so fancifully retouched
that it seems completely appropriate to see them flying off the
roads into the air, leaving behind trails of colored stars. The
very simple text takes a back seat to the flashy visuals, but it is
sharp and lively. And what child won't enjoy hearing noisy lines
like ``Whiz, bang,/ka-BOOM'' and ``be-bop,/ka-ZOOM''? _ SCOTT VEALE
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NO, DAVID! &QL; 
 &UR; By David Shannon &QL; 
 &UR; Blue Sky/Scholastic, $14.95. (Ages 2 to 6) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   First, let's give David Shannon his due as a deeply serious
illustrator of children's books. He has collaborated with the
estimable Jane Yolen on such worthy volumes as ``Encounter,'' the
story of Columbus's discovery of the New World as recounted in
halting English by a native Taino boy, and the based-on-fact
proto-feminist fable ``The Ballad of the Pirate Queens.'' His
portrayal of America's mythic giant, Paul, avec famille et ox in
Audrey Wood's book ``The Bunyans'' earned an ABC Children's
Booksellers' Choice award. And the sports fable Shannon wrote and
illustrated, ``How Georgie Radbourn Saved Baseball,'' was a 1994
New York Times Best Illustrated Book. So it is with great relief
for children everywhere that I can now report David Shannon is
applying his considerable talents to the sillier side of life. To
wit: earlier this year ``A Very Bad Case of Stripes'' (a colorful
ode to self-acceptance) and now his latest book, NO, DAVID! (Blue
Sky/Scholastic, $14.95; ages 2 to 6) -- a hilarious compilation of
toddlers' wrongdoings. As the author's note explains: ``A few years
ago, my mother sent me a book I made when I was a little boy. It
was called 'No, David' and it was illustrated with drawings of
David doing all sorts of things he wasn't supposed to do.'' Shannon
remains true to the spirit of this earlier work with a restrained
prose style -- ``No, David!'' ``I said no, David!'' and ``That's
enough, David!'' Likewise, the quasi-stick-figure drawings of
little David are a clearly humorous homage to his original
depictions. Parents might weary of the chastising tone -- until
they start chuckling, probably about where I did, at the two-page
spread of an open-mouthed David hollering through a mouthful of
vegetables. Children, on the other hand, will recognize immediately
that they have found a kindred spirit. _ M. P. DUNLEAVEY
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO ORDERED THE JUMBO SHRIMP? &QL; 
 &UR; And Other Oxymorons &QL; 
 &UR; Written and illustrated by Jon Agee &QL; 
 &UR; Michael di Capua/HarperCollins, $12.95. (Ages 8 and up) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oxymoron is not a word that shows up on many school vocabulary
quizzes, but kids being kids, which means smarter than they're
given credit for, they know one when they see one. Actually, as
every parent knows, they wrote the book (so to speak) on spotting
the contradictions in the grown-up world. But thanks to Jon Agee's
delightfully ticklish ``Who Ordered the Jumbo Shrimp?'' defining or
spelling an oxymoron is a total waste of time when it comes to
enjoying some of the finer nonsensical phrases in life. Agee, who
also has two books of palindromes and a shelf of prize-winning
picture books to his credit, lets his nimble drawing do all the
talking. To verbalize a bit of the author-illustrator's line of
vision and to reveal an open secret about this almost perfect
collection of some 60 word pictures: it would be a near miss, if
not a minor catastrophe, not to take the calculated risk of
treating the whole family to this instant classic. If you don't,
good grief, things could even get pretty ugly. _ ABBOTT COMBES
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
