<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-SCOTLAND-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LAST KING OF SCOTLAND
</HEADLINE>
  By Giles Foden 
 335 pp. New York: Alfred A. Knopf. $25 
 ------ 
 PRESIDENT FOR LIFE 
 By MICHAEL UPCHURCH 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I'm not made for this kind of thing.'' That's the plaintive
sort of response that a young Scottish doctor named Nicholas
Garrigan gives whenever he's asked to take a stand on anything to
do with the repressive reign of the Ugandan dictator Idi Amin.
</P>
<P>
   Why should anyone bother trying to involve Nicholas in Uganda's
bloody politics? Because he is Amin's personal physician and, as
such, has a ``ghastly ringside seat'' to a number of the cruelties
inflicted on Ugandans by their self-proclaimed ``President for
life'' through much of the 1970's. Still, suggestions that Nicholas
use his privileged position to do something that might rub Amin the
wrong way _ or rub him out altogether _ are destined to fail. For
Nicholas, the narrator of this venturesome first novel, is the very
essence of evasion and appeasement. He may be the protagonist here,
but he's definitely not the hero. And therein lies the admirable
risk the British author Giles Foden takes in ``The Last King of
Scotland.''
</P>
<P>
   Foden, a literary journalist and editor who spent much of his
childhood in Africa (including Uganda), has written a tale of
terror as witnessed by a man who is, by his own admission, ``mired
in cowardice and indecision.'' The paradox of the novel is that
while it's easy enough to condemn Nicholas, it's far more difficult
to admit the truth of the matter _ that the average citizen, put in
Nicholas's place, might very well behave as weakly and indecisively
as he does. This unsettling realization makes the reader more
sympathetic to the hapless Scotsman than pure conscience might
dictate.
</P>
<P>
   Foden has drawn his material from dozens of authors and
interviewees, including ``personal informants'' who wish to remain
anonymous. Mentioned by name in the novel are a British hostage,
Denis Hills; Gottfried Lessing, the former East German Ambassador
to Uganda (and also the former husband of the writer Doris
Lessing); Amin's doomed wife Kay and several of the dictator's
children. Foden has invented a standard-issue British Ambassador to
fill in for the real-life British High Commissioner, Richard Mercer
Keene Slater, who served in Uganda in the early 1970's. The book's
facts feel reliable, and Foden's fiction blends in with them
smoothly, although the novel occasionally carries the whiff of the
library stacks, not to mention the sweat of a journalist diligently
stringing his notes together.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Foden has a trump card on hand that serves to electrify
his narrative any time he cares to play it: Amin himself, whose
brutality is so laced with buffoonery that he would be hard to take
seriously if it weren't for the estimated 200,000 to 300,000 deaths
that resulted from his eight years of misrule.
</P>
<P>
   The book opens with a tantalizing first glimpse of Amin in
action at a diplomatic dinner party attended by Nicholas. There
Amin offers ``a few introductory remarks concerning domestic and
international affairs'' whose mix of solicitous concern and daffy
non sequitur evokes a wildly volatile personality. ``I have noticed
there can be bad drunkenness in Uganda and indeed across the whole
world, from beer and from spirits,'' Amin declares. ``Yes, some
people look as though they are painted with cosmetics just because
of too much drinking of alcohol. And cosmetics too can be bad
themselves, and wigs: I do not want Ugandans to wear the hair of
dead imperialists or of Africans killed by imperialists.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the main course is over, Amin is discussing the taste of
``human meat'' with an air of authority: ``It is very salty, even
more salty than leopard meat.'' True confession or put-on? It's
difficult to say. And it's especially difficult for Nicholas to
say, even with ``the dubious benefit of hindsight.'' Holed up in
Scotland's Inner Hebrides, where he is trying to live down his
much-publicized association with Amin, Nicholas still appears to be
unsure of what happened to him, of how much he was to blame. All he
can do is go over the sequence of events that kept him so close to
Amin's side.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, Nicholas's bad timing seems like a portent. He
manages to arrive in Kampala on the very eve of the 1971 coup that
put Amin in power. Nicholas's posting is in a provincial town, so
he doesn't stay long in the capital. But when chance leads him to
treat Amin for a minor car-crash injury, an invitation soon follows
to be the dictator's in-house doctor, as well as a staff member at
Kampala's Mulago Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The preamble to this job offer occupies roughly a hundred pages
and isn't riveting in itself _ Foden resorts too readily to
formulas like ``infectious smile'' or ``nodded sagely'' _ but it
does supply pertinent information. The grim diseases that Nicholas
deals with are graphically described, and are evidence that he has
a strong stomach and can, when he chooses, be a reliable observer.
Nevertheless, he focuses more on immediate details than the big
picture, and there are hints that he's in the habit of tuning out
anything he doesn't want to hear. (It's no coincidence that he's
plagued with a sound-dulling ear infection almost from the moment
of his arrival.)
</P>
<P>
   On the personal front, his blundering manner with women signals
a raw immaturity of which he's well aware. His failure to return to
Scotland for his parents' funerals (his father and mother die in
quick succession shortly after his move to Uganda) indicates, more
disturbingly, that ``something in me had begun to close down.''
</P>
<P>
   In his favor are his instinctive kindness and his desire to put
his medical skills to much-needed use (his rationale for staying on
in Uganda when common sense suggests fleeing). His absence of
racial prejudice would be reassuring, too, if it weren't somehow
linked to his absence of confidence. Far from embodying the
Brits-know-best attitudes of his colonial predecessors, Nicholas
doesn't seem to know a thing. He's a power vacuum waiting to be
filled _ and Amin does the filling admirably, bringing Foden's
prose to life while he's at it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-SCOTLAND-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: he's at it.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Foden's Amin, again apparently an amalgam of reportage and
invention, sets rooms aquiver with tension and fear as soon as he
enters them, even when he's in his most affable mood. In this
portrait, his intimidating physical presence, whimsical tyranny and
freewheeling dementia are powerfully persuasive, as is his uncanny
mind-reading ability when it comes to his personal physician.
</P>
<P>
   What does Amin see in Nicholas? Not just a skilled doctor, it
turns out, but a potential fellow malcontent whose country has been
oppressed by the English for even longer than Uganda. Indeed, Amin
sees himself as a de facto Scottish freedom fighter: ``Many of the
Scottish people already consider me last King of the Scots.'' The
undiluted zaniness of Amin's fervor on these and other matters
elicits a feeling of protective fondness in Nicholas. There's even
a queasily erotic element in Nicholas's rapport with his
dangerously sensitive patient. Both of these factors distract
Nicholas from registering just how bloodily anarchic Uganda is
becoming.
</P>
<P>
   Reality checks _ in the form of Hitler comparisons voiced by
Kampala's British officialdom _ fail to penetrate. As Nicholas
grows more isolated and then more fearful, he squirms, flails and
babbles. When at last he tries to run away, it's a mistake _ not
just for Nicholas, but for the book. For whenever Amin slips too
far from sight, Foden's prose becomes less inspired, making us
wonder whether it's Foden's authorial resourcefulness or his
fidelity to the historical record that galvanizes this strange
horror story.
</P>
<P>
   The gist of the novel is plain enough, and embroidered with
enough detail to flesh it out convincingly. ``It only takes one
good man to do nothing for evil to triumph,'' Nicholas is told.
Nicholas is that good man _ one who, unfortunately, has all the
resolve of a wet paper bag.
</P>
<P>
   What we're left with, ultimately, is the real Amin alive and
well and living in exile in Saudi Arabia _ and a fictional Nicholas
not much wiser than when he started. He's regretful, sure, but
mostly because he wishes none of these terrible things had happened
to him. He clearly recognizes the mechanism by which he sidesteps
reality. ``My problem,'' he admits, ``is that because the world
doesn't deliver what I seek, I don't admit facts.'' But
recognition, it seems, isn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas, it bears repeating, may be more our kindred spirit
than we like to think. And Foden, in this ambitious debut, does his
best to let us know it.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Michael Upchurch's latest novel is ``Passive Intruder.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
