<HEADER>
A5423 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-ARC-NYTSF     11-11 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-ARC-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOAN OF ARC
</HEADLINE>
  By Josephine Poole 
 Illustrated by Angela Barrett 
 Researched by Vincent Helyar 
 Unpaged. New York: Alfred A. Knopf. $18. (Ages 6 to 10) 
 JOAN OF ARC 
 Written and illustrated by Diane Stanley 
 Unpaged. New York: Morrow Junior Books. $16. (Ages 6 to 10) 
 ------ 
 LIVES OF A SAINT 
 By MARINA WARNER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   How to be a saint in a world without God is one of the hardest
questions of our time, observed Albert Camus. Though Camus didn't
invoke Joan of Arc, he could have, because her remarkable life
escapes so many of the normal, defining features of Christian
sainthood. She is, rather, a pre-eminent female hero of history,
and her example has been an inspiration in this century to writers,
actors, activists, patriots -- and young women and girls far beyond
her native France. Two vivid new picture books continue the
tradition of telling her story.
</P>
<P>
   Joan of Arc didn't renounce the world; she didn't convert from a
life of sin; she didn't give away her goods to the poor (she didn't
have any); she wasn't a queen or an abbess or a scholar; and above
all, she was tried for heresy by a Roman Catholic Church tribunal
and burned as a heretic.
</P>
<P>
   It's rumored that the Vatican is considering rehabilitating the
fiery monk Girolamo Savonarola, who was hanged and then burned in
Florence, almost 70 years after Joan of Arc died in Rouen. If so,
Savonarola will be eligible to join Joan as one of the few
canonized saints who was, in fact, martyred by the church.
</P>
<P>
   The philosopher Bernard Williams, in a recent discussion,
pointed out that, as the defining principle of truth, accuracy has
been gradually eclipsed by sincerity. If what you are saying is
incorrect, it may still carry the force of conviction if it is
spoken from the heart. In the last century, Thomas Carlyle defined
``sincerity, a deep, great, genuine sincerity,'' as ``the mark of
the hero.'' In this respect, Joan of Arc is a truly modern figure,
a person who expresses unflinching, subjective truthfulness: under
protracted interrogation, she held to the reality of her visions,
the divine origin of her mission and her need to keep wearing male
dress. Like Galileo, she embodies the individual under duress, a
romantic rebel with a cause.
</P>
<P>
   In these retellings by the British writer Josephine Poole and
the American Diane Stanley, Joan of Arc's life has the quality of a
wonder tale, all the more wondrous because it took place. Poole's
version begins, ``This is a true story.'' She keeps the plot clear
and the psychology simple; chivalry and the love of God animate her
heroine. ``Joan simply did what God told her to do,'' she writes,
``and nothing, nobody could prevent her.'' The illustrations, by
Angela Barrett, recall millefleurs tapestries and ``Les Tres Riches
Heures du Duc de Berry'' and other illuminated manuscripts, and use
a wide, horizontal format with eloquence and energy. They also
heighten the intensity of the narrative, often picturing the
heroine in isolation, so that Joan seems truly a creature set
apart, marked by radical difference from the strife and pageantry
and pomp surrounding her.
</P>
<P>
   In one striking image, for example, Barrett shows Joan cutting
off her hair with a pair of carefully rendered medieval shears,
while beyond the mullioned window the willows are pollarded as if
to echo her action. Barrett also changes the viewpoint now and
then, to maximum effect: the English siege of Orleans is shown from
a dark, enclosed gun emplacement, with a gunner lighting the powder
on a cannon from a red-hot brazier. The most haunting illustration,
however, shows Joan on the riverbank, looking down at the corpse of
an English soldier, half submerged in a running stream, like John
Everett Millais's painting of Ophelia. ``And Joan wept for pity of
him, and of all who died that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Stanley, a prolific artist and a writer who has done a
number of illustrated biographies, provides a more complex,
historical understanding of Joan of Arc, and adds other pedagogic
features to help interactive reading: a guide to French
pronunciation, a map of France in 1429, a helpful introduction to
the dynastic tangles behind the Hundred Years' War and a thoughtful
afterword, where she admits, ``Sometimes, in studying history, we
have to accept what we know and let the rest remain a mystery.''
Her own illustrations also draw on contemporary illuminations, but
of military chronicles and other documents: she has faithfully
followed Jean Fouquet's portrait of Charles VII, complete with
piggy eyes and bulbous nose.
</P>
<P>
   Her Joan is a good little girl, her body language meek and
demure: she makes daisy chains as she tends the sheep, and is seen
spinning in the family kitchen, with a butter churn behind her and
her mother sweeping the dirt floor. ``The future savior of
France,'' writes Stanley, ``was much like all the other little
girls in the village of Domremy.''
</P>
<P>
   So, while the awkward questions about Joan's personality and
career -- her visions and actions -- are raised, Stanley often
interprets them in the most bland and kindly light. Joan's father
does indeed threaten to have her drowned if she leaves home to go
to war, but his earlier plan to marry her off is attributed to
loving paternal provision. Joan's male dress is a simple practical
measure. Her banner protects her from killing anyone in battle. Her
brothers are solid in support. Miracles are not much in evidence.
Toward the end, the old excuse is suggested, that male clothes were
left in her cell after she had recanted in order to trick her into
lapsing again.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing on historical context, Stanley's storytelling is
hampered by her anxiety to explain or, indeed, explain away, Joan's
story: ``It is important to remember,'' Stanley writes, ``that she
lived in the Middle Ages, a time when even educated people believed
in fairies, curses, prophecies, witches and magic.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Poole is all too brief, and Stanley occasionally loses
narrative focus, these are both beautifully produced picture books
that will introduce readers -- especially school-age girls -- to an
eternally inspiring story. At a moment when political opportunism,
historical fabrication, national corruption and individual
equivocation poison public life from Belgrade to Washington, Joan
of Arc's resolute stand makes her a necessary saint, a continuing
hero of our time.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Marina Warner is the author of ``Joan of Arc: The Image of
Female Heroism.'' Her most recent book is ``From the Beast to the
Blonde: On Fairy Tales and Their Tellers.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
