<HEADER>
A5424 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-LIGHT-NYTSF     11-11 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-LIGHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE LIGHT
</HEADLINE>
  By Walter Mosley 
 296 pp. New York: Little, Brown &AMP; Company. $24 
 ------ 
 PRIMARY COLOR 
 By MEL WATKINS 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The central metaphor in Walter Mosley's new novel was
foreshadowed in his short-story collection of last year, ``Always
Outnumbered, Always Outgunned,'' when the protagonist, Socrates
Fortlow, recalled his aunt telling him that God ``ain't black. ...
If he was there wouldn't be all this mess down here. Naw. God's
blue.'' She went on to explain: ``Blue like the ocean. Blue. Sad
and cold and far away like the sky is far and blue.'' In ``Blue
Light'' _ perhaps best described as fable-cum-science fiction _
that analogy is extended and stretched to its metaphysical limit.
Mosley moves far afield from genre fiction and the familiarly
gritty Los Angeles-based domain of his affably private detective,
Easy Rawlins. The setting for this visionary meditation on
spirituality, evil, race and the ultimate fate of mankind is the
San Francisco area and the longhaired, mutinous, free-love world of
Haight-Ashbury in the mid-1960's.
</P>
<P>
   The event that sets the novel in motion is the sudden appearance
of multiple shards of a mysterious blue radiance (``God's tears'')
that descends and abruptly shatters the calm of a Bay Area evening.
For those touched, the result is death, madness or bliss _ the
latter a state of heightened strength, perception, energy and
sentience that sets them apart from ordinary humans, who are
described as a ``base stock'' in whom the ``pattern of life''
exists but is ``inert and decaying.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 16 ``blues'' survive. Principal among them are Orde, a
frail blond former hippie who assumes the Christlike role of
prophet and teacher to the blues' small Close Congregation, and
Horace LaFontaine, a black former convict who is struck by the blue
light an instant after he dies of cancer. Horace's corpse is
immediately revived and used as a host by Gray Man, a powerful,
demonic entity who tells Horace: ``I am your master. . . . Grey
Redstar. Recently from elsewhere.'' Until the novel's final clash,
LaFontaine remains a tortured, wretched shell, whose spirit is
imprisoned in the ``Attica cell'' of Gray Man's mind. Although
numerous characters are introduced and occasionally take center
stage, it is the internal war for dominion between Gray Man (death)
and Horace (life), and the blues' struggle to escape Gray Man's
relentless attempt to annihilate them, that inform and adumbrate
this allegorical tale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue Light'' is related in a matter-of-fact, near-documentary
style by Lester (Chance) Foote _ later ominously called ``Last
Chance'' _ a half-crazed mulatto Ph.D. candidate who has been
driven to a suicide attempt by his marginal status in America: ``I
spoke the white man's language. I dreamed his dreams. But when I
woke up, no one recognized me.'' After meeting Orde and engaging in
a blood-mixing ritual that leaves him partly endowed with the
blues' powers (``a pool on whose surface shimmered the image of
God''), Chance is rejuvenated as the prophet's acolyte. He drops
out of the University of California, Berkeley, and begins writing
``The History of the Coming of Light.'' ``Blue Light'' is
essentially Chance's account of the struggles between life and
death, man's higher aspirations and baser impulses, that ensue as
Gray Man stalks the blues and faces them in a final encounter at
Treaty, the idyllic Eden to which the spritelike Juan Thrombone
(topiarist to the forest's magical singing and bellowing trees) has
led them.
</P>
<P>
   For readers accustomed to the gut-real encounters, sharp
dialogue and quirky perceptions that enliven the first-person
narrations of Mosley's Easy Rawlins mysteries, both Chance's grave
voice and the surreal nature of ``Blue Light'' may be a
disappointment. Although the novel is not without its fair share of
realistic depictions of mayhem, sexual and physical confrontations
and dramatic tension, it frequently succumbs to the pitfalls that
bedevil most fables and allegories. Chance's recitation often
skirts mundane detail to embrace allusion and abstraction. He and
the characters he describes slip too easily into sermonic discourse
and excursive asides. In too many instances characters are consumed
by caricature and prototype. Flesh-and-blood people meld into
fundamental archetypes in the person of characters such as Teacher,
Alacrity, Evil, Gray Man and even, to some extent, the narrator,
Last Chance.
</P>
<P>
   The fuel that energizes the novel is not its characters but its
plot, and Mosley's exposition of the blue light's puzzling
attributes. In this regard it bears some comparison to Ishmael
Reed's 1972 novel, ``Mumbo Jumbo,'' in the affinity between
Mosley's blue light and ``Jes Grew,'' the mysterious plague that
transformed Reed's characters. For Reed, Jes Grew symbolized a
resurfacing of the spontaneity and creativity of the human spirit,
which was born in Africa and, like jazz, inspired people to forsake
inhibitions and ethnic clannishness and, finally, to celebrate life
or just ``shake that thing.'' It is set against the forces of evil,
racism and artistic stultification that conspired to suppress it
throughout history. Mosley's blue light parallels the spiritual
force in Reed's Manichaean equation in that it alludes to a
spiritual power that transforms humans, freeing them from
repression and unveiling the natural life force within. It is also
driven by the magic of song and dance. ``Everything is singing all
the time,'' Thrombone tells Chance when asked ``What is the blue
light?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Singing and calling for what is missing. Your science calls it
gravity, but the gods call it dance. They dance and fornicate; they
listen and sing.''
</P>
<P>
   The raucous impiety and historical resonance of ``Mumbo Jumbo''
are missing from ``Blue Light.'' Instead, Mosley advances a
pantheistic belief in the immanence of nature and the natural
instincts of mankind and the oneness of existence _ spiritual and
material as well as racial. Through its final apocalyptic
denouement and the fate of the narrator, Last Chance, the novel
hints that we may have missed our opportunity for atonement and
reconciliation during the revolutionary 60's, when, for a brief
moment, the nation's youth, black and white, assailed traditional
authority with protests over war, racial segregation and misuse of
the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it suggests that to the racial problem there is but
one solution. As Orde tells Chance when combining their blood to
initiate him into the realm of the blues, ``See, the blood mixes
itself.'' They watch the ``darker blood and the lighter,'' which
``had formed into longish clumps like fat worms,'' as they
``twisted and turned against each other, sometimes slowly,
sometimes fast. Every now and then two worms would collapse and
fall together and then fall apart.'' Orde makes sure to underline
his point: ``When they're all the same color it will be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Mel Watkins is the author of ``Dancing With Strangers: A
Memoir.'' He is currently completing an oral history of the
20th-century African-American experience.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
