<HEADER>
A5429 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-HEART-NYTSF     11-11 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-HEART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLDIER'S HEART
</HEADLINE>
  Being the Story of the Enlistment and Due Service of the Boy
Charley Goddard in the First Minnesota Volunteers 
 By Gary Paulsen 
 106 pp. New York: Delacorte Press. $15.95.(Ages 12 and up) 
 DRUMMER BOY 
 Marching to the Civil War 
 By Ann Turner 
 Illustrated by Mark Hess 
 Unpaged. New York: HarperCollins Publishers. $15.95 (Ages to 8) 
 ------ 
 THE BOYS OF WAR 
 By HENRY MAYER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are various ways to write historical fiction for children.
Gary Paulsen's ``Soldier's Heart'' is a stark, utterly persuasive
novel of combat life in the Civil War that may well challenge
generations of middle-school readers, while Ann Turner's ``Drummer
Boy is an earnest but miscalculated attempt to address the horrors
of warfare in picture-book form.
</P>
<P>
   Paulsen has written many successful books (``Hatchet,''
``Nightjohn,''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Island'') that explore the intersection of physical and
moral challenges. ``Soldier's Heart'' is a notable continuation
that traces the fate of a 15-year-old farm boy, Charley Goddard,
from his 1861 enlistment in a volunteer Minnesota regiment through
the discipline and boredom of camp life to the carnage of Bull Run
and Gettysburg. Goddard was a real person (his daguerreotype graces
the frontispiece), but Paulsen has worked up from archival sources
and a scholarly study of the regiment a composite fictional account
that draws its power from a perfectly pitched narrative voice and
authentic detail.
</P>
<P>
   The reader feels the young soldier's awe as he rides a plush
train toward the eastern front and understands his bewilderment as
he sees the first poor farms and subjected black people in the
South. The horrors of combat -- the noise, the fear, the drinking
from a creek stained pink with blood, the piling up of corpses to
make a windbreak for a field surgeon's operating theater --
gradually drive away all thoughts of nationalism or abolition and
force Charley to concentrate on the imperatives of survival.
</P>
<P>
   HE does, but his life is shattered by what we now call
post-traumatic stress disorder and what was then known as
``soldier's heart.'' In a brief epilogue (which might have profited
from more detail), Paulsen sketches the physical and mental anguish
that led to Goddard's death in 1868 at the age of 23.
</P>
<P>
   In a novella just over 100 pages long, Paulsen has not only
rendered a historical epoch with documentary fidelity, but also
created a work that poses the hard questions of all combat
literature: What was it about? Was it worth it? Could I have done
it?
</P>
<P>
   On the evidence of ``Drummer Boy,'' the historical experience of
40,000 youngsters in the Union Army cannot be conveyed to very
young readers. Ann Turner's towheaded farm boy is drawn into the
war after seeing Abraham Lincoln on his way to Washington and
brooding about the unfairness of slavery. He runs away, lies about
his age and becomes a drummer. He is appalled by the scenes of
combat, but ministers to the dying and learns that the beating of
his drum covers the sounds of battle and gives courage to the
soldiers. He feels useful, but promises that when he goes home he
will stop off to tell Mr. Lincoln ``how it's all his fault, how his
great sad eyes made me go and see things no boy should ever see.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner chooses her words carefully, but lightens her tale with
so much sentiment that it becomes trivial. Mark Hess's richly toned
paintings are filled with authentically detailed uniforms and
equipment, but in the manner of museum dioramas, they provide scant
character development.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Henry Mayer is the author of ``All on Fire,'' a biography of the
abolitionist editor William Lloyd Garrison.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
