A5431 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-DOGS-NYTSF     11-11 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-DOGS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIRCLE DOGS
</HEADLINE>
  By Kevin Henkes 
 Illustrated by Dan Yaccarino 
 Unpaged. New York: Greenwillow Books. $15. (Ages 2 and up) 
 ------ 
 GRRRRR, GRRRRR, GRRRRR 
 By JAMES MCMULLAN 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have been on juries at graphic art competitions where a book
as handsomely designed and as full of elegantly simplified pictures
as ``Circle Dogs'' would certainly have been given an award. Dan
Yaccarino has illustrated Kevin Henkes's story of a day in the life
of two dachshunds with daringly minimal evocations of the people
and things that constitute the dogs' world. Each page is a
beautifully composed arrangement of sleek shapes that float on a
field of creamy paper, and the dogs of the title have indeed been
turned into circles, their ears into triangles and their tongues
into little ``u'' shapes.
</P>
<P>
   This is sophisticated picture making, but big questions quickly
come to mind. Is the visual ingenuity of this book more appealing
to other designers and visually hip parents than it is to children?
Are kids really interested in dogs that have been reduced to a
level of hieroglyphic flatness? Or in dog tails that enter the
edges of a page as abstract scythe shapes? Does the simplicity of
the pictures give a child enough to look at and to find on the
repeated readings that the text is sure to elicit?
</P>
<P>
   The title ``Circle Dogs'' and references in the text to
geometric terms like ``big square house'' and ``triangle ears''
suggest that at one level the book operates as a find-the-shape
story, and this may have been the conceptual origin of Yaccarino's
style. Yet Henkes's words strike me as having a much richer
intention that that. His simple sentences and words describing
noises suggest everyday experiences in the life of a child, and the
onomatopoeia requires imagination on the part of a listener to hear
the noises described and to figure out what actual physical action
is taking place. This is a typical passage:
</P>
<P>
   Or for the mail to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Stomp, stomp,
</P>
<P>
   whoosh, whoosh,
</P>
<P>
   bam, stomp, stomp.
</P>
<P>
   Grrrrr, grrrrr, grrrrr.
</P>
<P>
   The game, of course, is to imagine the mailman walking across
the porch, putting the mail through the slot, the cover of the slot
banging shut, the letter carrier walking away and the dogs growling
at him through the door. This seems a different and more
appropriate challenge to a child's mind than the relatively adult
challenge of seeing the dog in the circle, or the circle in the
dog.
</P>
<P>
   Henkes's words suggest a real place better than Yaccarino's
abstracted universe does. When I read the story aloud, I imagined a
world in which there is an inside and an outside, a quirky door and
maybe even a quirky mailman. It is a world that might have been
evoked by the lush painterliness of one of Yaccarino's previous
books, ``Goodnight, Mr. Night,'' or by the zany characterizations
in Henkes's own illustrations for his wonderful ``Lilly's Purple
Plastic Purse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Circle Dogs'' is an evocative piece of writing that would be a
joy to read aloud to a child. I can imagine that after the third or
fourth reading a child would have learned some of Kevin Henkes's
wonderfully noisy words and would join in on the wooof, wooofs and
the arf, aarfs. As much as I appreciate the elegant patterning of
Dan Yaccarino's artwork, this is a text for which I imagine
different pictures.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   James McMullan's most recent books are ``No No, Jo'' and ``The
Theater Posters of James McMullan.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
