<HEADER>
A5433 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-WALTON-1000&AMP;A     11-11 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-WALTON-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SAM WE TRUST
</HEADLINE>
  The Untold Story of Sam Walton and How Wal-Mart Is Devouring
America 
 By Bob Ortega 
 413 pp. New York: Times Business/Random House. $25.95 
 ------ 
 ATTENTION, SHOPPERS 
 By JUDITH NEWMAN 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thinking of buying this book? Chances are excellent you'll be
walking into a Barnes &AMP; Noble or Borders, two of the superstores
that are coming ever closer to obliterating independent
booksellers. And for that, says Bob Ortega, you must either thank
or curse Wal-Mart's founder, Sam Walton -- because it is Walton's
practices that are driving the trend toward Brobdingnagian chain
stores today. In his ambitious, exhaustive and sometimes exhausting
book, Ortega, a reporter who covers the retail industry for The
Wall Street Journal, asks us to consider a question fundamental to
the way America does business: How high is the cost of low cost?
</P>
<P>
   ``In Sam We Trust'' is really two books in one. Initially, it
comes off as an admiring biography of Sam Walton that tells the
story of his drive to become the biggest of the big among chains
like Sears and Kmart. Because neither Walton's family nor key
Wal-Mart executives would cooperate with the book, to tell this
story Ortega is forced to rely heavily on Vance Trimble's 1990
biography, ``Sam Walton: The Inside Story of America's Richest
Man,'' and on Walton's own 1992 autobiography, ``Made in America.''
Thus many of the credos and habits of the modest, down-to-earth and
``casually relentless'' Walton have already been well documented,
and so have the policies that made Wal-Mart the single largest
private employer in the United States today. In a nutshell: lowest
prices and highest product turnover equals biggest profit.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing rural America as the great unserved population, Walton
opened his stores in small towns where he faced minimum
competition, stole managers and useful ideas from his rivals and
cut deals on merchandise directly with manufacturers. Gentlemanly,
modest and notoriously chintzy -- he made his managers share hotel
rooms on business trips -- Walton was also a gifted leader. He was
one of the first retailers to institute a profit-sharing plan,
because he believed it was the only way to give every worker a
sense of having a stake in the business. (In an age of the paranoid
mogul, it is surprising to learn that Walton always kept a listed
phone number at home, so that even the lowest-level ``associates''
could have access to him.) Walton ``was to the faith of consumerism
what the Mahatma Gandhi was to nonviolence,'' Ortega writes.
</P>
<P>
   For the first half of this treatise, Ortega is seemingly
breathless in his admiration of Walton's achievements. Of the
opening of the first Wal-Mart, he writes, ``As with many epochal
moments in business history, it was decades before the significance
of this date became clear.'' Indeed, how one feels about ``In Sam
We Trust'' depends in part on how inherently dramatic one finds the
rise of discount retailing in America. If the reader's heart beats
a little faster at the start of such paragraphs as ``Meanwhile,
back at the Searcy distribution center,'' then he's come to the
right place.
</P>
<P>
   But midway through the book, the tone and focus change. ``In Sam
We Trust '' becomes another work entirely: an indictment of the
greed and excesses of a company bent on profit, whatever the human
cost. However much he admired the man, Ortega seems to deplore the
business he created.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, an economist at Iowa State University published a study
showing what happened to the economies of small towns after the
opening of a Wal-Mart on the outskirts. It wasn't pretty.
Noncompeting businesses like restaurants and bars did not suffer,
but on average Wal-Mart siphoned off three-quarters of the sales of
competing businesses in town. When the study engendered plenty of
bad press, Walton countered with his own study: a team of
researchers at the University of Missouri were paid a piddling
$10,000 to look at 14 Wal-Marts in that state. To no one's
surprise, their findings concluded that far from being hurt by the
giant stores, the counties ``almost all showed growth or
revitalization after the opening of Wal-Mart.'' At any rate, the
war between Wal-Mart and Main Street was on.
</P>
<P>
   While seeds of discontent had been sown before Sam Walton's
death (in 1992, from bone cancer), his folksy image provided a
shield against public charges of rapaciousness. But once his
handpicked successor, David Glass, took over, the company got
involved in one public relations blunder after another. There was
the bad publicity over the company's selective enforcement of rules
on staff romances (mixed-race couples were punished, for example,
while a married Wal-Mart attorney who got involved with a file
clerk was not) and the debacle over Wal-Mart's ``Made in America''
program (despite its claims to the contrary, much of Wal-Mart's
merchandise was and is made overseas). Then there was Kathie Lee
Gifford, with whom the company had developed a line of clothing.
She became a lightning rod for criticism when union sympathizers
got out the word that her clothing was being produced by children
in Guatemala and sweatshop workers in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Ortega veers, not always successfully, between the many stories
he's trying to tell. He'll end a chapter with the promise of the
Kathie Lee Gifford saga, and won't return to it again for another
60 pages. And once he gets there, do we really need a many-paged
recitation of Kathie Lee's entire career history, right down to the
bit parts she used to play on the soap opera ``Days of Our Lives''?
Someone badly needed to take a weed whacker to this manuscript.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-WALTON-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: manuscript.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finally, coming from a Wall Street Journal reporter, there's
something a bit overzealous, and perhaps naive, about Ortega's
conclusions. ``The history of the company,'' he writes, ``provides
ample evidence that Wal-Mart, like any corporation, is merely a
machine, an amoral construct with one imperative: the profit
motive. That pursuing that motive to the utmost may have a
corrosive effect on communities or individuals -- including people
within the corporation -- never enters into the equation.'' Duh.
Ortega ends with an exhortation to consumers to take control of
their shopping destinies. ``Whatever the issue -- buy American;
allowing independent monitors into factories; ending sweatshop
conditions and forced and child labor; treating its own workers
with dignity and respect; building stores that help rather than
hurt a town's sense of community -- Wal-Mart . . . will respond to
what the public demands from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ortega is right. Unfortunately, what America demands is not
fairness or decency, but cheap goods and lots of 'em. It's called
capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Judith Newman has written for Harper's Magazine, Vanity Fair and
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
