<HEADER>
A5434 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-ANTHONY-NYTSF     11-11 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-ANTHONY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG ANTHONY
</HEADLINE>
  His Story 
 Written and illustrated by Tomie dePaola 
 Unpaged. New York: G. P. Putnam's Sons. $16.99. (Ages 5 to 9) 
 ------ 
 A SORCERER'S APPRENTICE 
 By PERRY NODELMAN 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Strega Nona's Magic Lessons'' (1982), Tomie dePaola's witch
heroine tells her apprentices the secrets of her art: ``To learn
magic and practice it well . . . you must learn to see and not to
see. You must learn to remember and to forget; to be still and to
be busy. But mostly, you must be faithful to your work.'' These
words might be a description of dePaola's own magical art, as
practiced in the picture books about the witch and her terminally
inattentive assistant, Big Anthony, stories he has been producing
every now and then since ``Strega Nona'' in 1975. The latest, ``Big
Anthony: His Story,'' is as busy, as full of remembering and
forgetting, and of things seen and unseen, as its predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   The Strega Nona stories all take place in Italy, mostly in
Calabria, at some unspecified time in the past. Red-tiled roofs and
cobblestoned courtyards, happy feasts and joyful baptisms capture
traditional Italian life in authentic detail. But it is a time like
the ``once'' of fairy tales, more sunny and more cheerful, less
occupied with the existence of fleas or war or hunger, than any
time that ever actually existed.
</P>
<P>
   DePaola's illustrations confirm this precarious balance of
authenticity and nostalgia, remembering and forgetting, by seeing
things and not seeing them. With their solid blocks of warm color
surrounded by thick outlines anchoring objects to the page, their
minimal suggestions of eyes and smiles, their simplified shapes and
focus on repetitive patterns, these pictures represent an art so
decorative that it seems to aspire to be wallpaper.
</P>
<P>
   What is magical is the energy the pictures manage to convey in
the midst of the decorative stasis. It's not just the bursts of
anarchy, the floods of pasta, bread dough, wart-infested townsfolk
or dance-crazed women produced by Big Anthony's short attention
span, but also the expressiveness of the few lines with which
dePaola captures his characters' gestures and emotions. These very
still pictures are surprisingly busy.
</P>
<P>
   They are also filled with details that make their apparent
simplicity richly informative. The magnetic attraction Strega
Nona's equally substantial chin and nose seem to have for each
other from the moment of her birth implies a sad, unspoken story
about why she remains unmarried and a witch throughout life.
Pictures of Strega Nona's chosen successor, the equally round,
equally unattached and equally chin-and-nose-endowed Bombalona, and
of Strega Nona's lifelong rival, the obviously vain and always
outrageously overdressed Strega Amelia, appear in a number of the
books and add complexity to the tales.
</P>
<P>
   And there is the running joke of Strega Nona's pet rabbit,
peacock and goat appearing through windows or on roofs at weirdly
appropriate moments that make them emblematic of the moral status
of the human characters in the foreground -- their peacocklike
pride or bunnylike inadequacy or goatlike stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   A parallel to ``Strega Nona: Her Story'' (1996), which told of
the witch's early years, this latest book tells of Big Anthony's
experiences before he came to work for Strega Nona. Longtime
readers won't be surprised to learn that Anthony's inattentiveness
was causing problems from the time of his baptism. But surprise is
never the point in this comfortably conservative world, whose
citizens thrive on habit and ritual. It's a world in which Strega
Nona's decision to leave college life in the big city for the
stability of home is not a retreat but a victory, in which Anthony
always messes things up, and Strega Nona always fixes them again,
and a witch's duties always involve the same problems of finding
young women husbands and getting rid of everyone's headaches and
warts.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the specific messes dePaola invents here for the
younger Anthony are ingenious opportunities for slapstick,
including run-ins with a great painter in Florence, a cardinal in
Rome and a leaning tower in Pisa. And, as usual, the hard edges of
the comedy nicely control and allow the sentiment that underpins
all these stories. Occasionally, as in the unnecessarily soppy
``Merry Christmas, Strega Nona'' (1986) or in the not-so secret
declaration in ``Strega Nona: Her Story'' that love is the
ingrediente segreto of all magic, the sentiment escapes its bounds.
But usually, as in this book, the softheartedness is seen and not
seen, remembered and forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Anthony: His Story'' is enjoyable exactly because it is so
very much like its predecessors. Readers of all ages can be
grateful that dePaola remains so faithful to his work, and
continues to practice his magic so well.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Perry Nodelman's books include a picture book, ``Alice Falls
Apart,'' and ``Words.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
