<HEADER>
A5437 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-LOOK-1000&AMP;ADD     11-11 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-LOOK-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK-ALIKES
</HEADLINE>
  By Joan Steiner 
 Photographs by Thomas Lindley 
 Unpaged. Boston: Little, Brown &AMP; Company. $12.95. (Ages 3 and up) 
 WALTER WICK'S OPTICAL TRICKS 
 Written and photographed by Walter Wick 
 45 pp. New York: Cartwheel Books/Scholastic. $13.95. (Ages 5 and
up) 
 ------ 
 OPTICAL ALLUSIONS 
 By MOLLY E. RAUCH 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everything that has ever been lost ends up somewhere _ at the
bottom of the elevator shaft, behind the radiator, beneath the
porch slats, down the drain of the municipal swimming pool. But
imagine that it all ends up in one place, a place where dust and
sludge are miraculously wiped away, where the chaff of material
culture is reunited with a function. And imagine that it organizes
itself, creeping out of its primordial chaos, the way Precambrian
proteins must have organized themselves into the first cells. Enter
Joan Steiner's book ``Look-Alikes.''
</P>
<P>
   The true identity of this land, the Universe of Stray Stuff,
dawns slowly. At first, Steiner's miniature sculptures look like
cluttered, cheerful doll-house scenes, depicting a train station,
circus, general store, harbor and so on, through which the reader
is led by a garishly cheerful redheaded boy made of clay.
</P>
<P>
   But notice the water tower: it is, in fact, constructed of a
flour sifter, a dollar bill, wooden cocktail forks, chopsticks, a
wire whisk, a rubber stamp handle, a needle and thread, and a
fishhook. And once the water tower is deciphered, there are
handcuffs and mouse traps and dice and lipsticks, and there is no
stopping the thrilling wooziness of Las Vegas-style
overstimulation. In a delirium of serial recognition, everything
begins to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   Steiner, who made each of the 11 dioramas from (literally)
hundreds of everyday objects, possesses a keen sense of
architectural design, heeding the strong lines of disposable razors
(she stands them back to back as columns) and attuned to the
modern, glinting appeal, on a building's facade, of a nutcracker.
She also has wired many of her look-alike structures (a newsstand,
a jukebox, a merry-go-round, an organ, a chandelier) so they are
realistically lighted from within, and these illuminations mimic
the electric bursts of realization that reward a reader's patience.
</P>
<P>
   The entire book is electrified. Steiner places a tiny bulb
inside the percolator button on the coffee pot that's doubling as a
train engine. It makes a perfect, intimidating headlight. Lights
also shine from the baby-bottle nipples (a k a light fixtures) in
the candy store. And the amusement park is dotted with what must be
hundreds of reflective stickers, lighted against an evening sky.
The bustling fair positively glows.
</P>
<P>
   While the idea of the gingerbread house must have influenced
Steiner, that quaint, candy-studded esthetic is to her
``Look-Alikes'' land as Talbot's is to Gaultier. Dried apricots are
stool cushions in the diner, broccoli and kale are the trees in the
courtyard, a building facade is made of Melba toast, chocolate bars
are wood paneling in the swank hotel lobby, jelly beans fill the
ball jump at the amusement park, poppy seeds constitute the
playground's asphalt, and there are pretzels, candy corn, peanuts,
saltines, cheese rounds, pistachios, popcorn, potatoes, dog
biscuits, Fig Newtons, corn kernels, bubble gum, bouillon cubes,
cinnamon sticks, jars of jelly, flat-leaf parsley and black-eyed
peas.
</P>
<P>
   Those who cannot remember what that there thingamajig is called
will find relief in the back of the book, where each scene is
deconstructed, item by item, and every object tallied, so that the
true and proper name of a hair-perming rod, a suction-cup dart, a
potholder-weaving loom or an accordion-peg coat rack can never
again be doubted.
</P>
<P>
   But perusing those lists is not nearly as much fun as staring
into a ``Look-Alikes'' diorama, letting the familiar turn strange
and then back again. The objects that show up over and over _
toenail clippers, clothes hangers, egg slicers, pennies _ form
repeating patterns, like the rules of grammar in a foreign
language. Though the book's text adds little to the experience,
it's easy to ignore it in the face of Steiner's astounding
thoroughness, which has created a coherent, winking universe.
</P>
<P>
   Steiner's craft recalls the successful ``I Spy'' books, which
contain photographs of objects hidden in plain sight. The
photographer of those books, Walter Wick, is responsible for the
lively, dizzying swirl from which Steiner has clearly borrowed, but
he is busy with a different approach to visual acuity. His new
book, ``Walter Wick's Optical Tricks,'' is simple and streamlined,
depicting old-fashioned toys like marbles, wooden balls, toy
soldiers and clay.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite the crisply photographed, primary-colored
wholesomeness, something about each of the 12 photographs
confounds. In one, a wooden cube and sphere float in space; in
another, a brightly lighted box casts no shadow. Where the ``I
Spy'' books are fundamentally matching games, this book raises
questions about how the mind works.
</P>
<P>
   Some images are ho-hum (like the toy fish endlessly reflected in
a series of mirrors, a trick many children already will have
discovered in their medicine-cabinet mirrors), but a good number
are disarmingly odd. These are the ones whose riddles hinge not on
special mirrors or fancy lighting but on the principles of visual
perception. Readers (more accurately, observers) will learn that
the brain makes assumptions, based on experience, as it sifts
through information about shadows, light, perspective and color. It
is this system of visual perception that causes impressions in clay
to appear to pop out of the clay when the book is turned upside
down, and it is also what causes a checkered cube to lose all
dimension when it sits on a similarly checkered floor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-LOOK-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: checkered floor) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As an intellectual primer, ``Walter Wick's Optical Tricks'' is
stimulating, but as a picture book it is a one-shot deal. The
images themselves are not, for the most part, absorbing or
startling enough to warrant repeat visits. The text doesn't help,
because the illusions are laid bare and the thrill of discovery, so
delectable in Steiner's book, is tempered. Nevertheless, each image
is a reminder that left to its own devices the brain will follow a
well-worn path, even if the resulting perception is altogether
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   In our visual culture, sheer appearance can sometimes seem to
dictate everything from popularity to self-esteem. While both
Walter Wick and Joan Steiner have created books that arise from the
culture of artifice, they both also ask the reader to look again.
They show that image is a slave to perception, because things are
not always what they seem.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Molly E. Rauch conducts research on child care at the Bank
Street College of Education's Center for Family Support. She has
written for The Nation and Newsday, among other publications.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
