<HEADER>
A5438 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-PICTURES-1000     11-11 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-PICTURES-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO PRETTY PICTURES
</HEADLINE>
  A Child of War 
 By Anita Lobel 
 Illustrated. 193 pp. New York: Greenwillow Books. $16. (Ages 10 and
up) 
 ------ 
 WHY ARE THE GROWN-UPS CRYING? 
 By HAZEL ROCHMAN 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Should children today read about the Holocaust? Won't it shock
and horrify them, give them nightmares, turn them off reading?
Exciting escape adventure is one thing, but what about the truth?
Will it help them to think about their own moral choices as
potential perpetrators, victims, bystanders? Will they connect that
genocide with other accounts of what racism can do, through history
and now? As more and more states mandate the teaching of the
Holocaust in schools, and as the number of children's books on the
subject has grown to a flood, these have become serious issues.
</P>
<P>
   The search for an upbeat, hopeful message is what lies behind
the longstanding controversy about ``Anne Frank: The Diary of a
Young Girl,'' a controversy that was revived last year. Because her
story has been sentimentalized and that famous sentence about
believing in spite of everything that people are good at heart has
been wrenched out of context and trumpeted on stage and everywhere
else as a message of healing and hope, there are many who say
children should not read the diary -- including Cynthia Ozick, who
wrote in a devastating article in The New Yorker that the diary
should have been destroyed. The argument is that if the diary is
the only book children today read about the Holocaust, they come
away with a distorted view of the truth.
</P>
<P>
   That word ``only'' is the problem. Since the diary was first
published in 1947 it has sold more than 25 million copies in 50
languages. You shouldn't deprive young readers of a book that has
such enduring power to move them. But one book cannot do it all.
The answer is not to slam it or ban it, but to add to it from the
wealth of powerful Holocaust literature. Young readers find that it
is the personal accounts, like the diary, that are most moving.
</P>
<P>
   Anita Lobel's disturbing memoir, ``No Pretty Pictures: A Child
of War,'' a finalist for the National Book Award in young people's
literature, is neither sentimental nor exploitative. In fact, Lobel
is adamant that she will not ``sanctify'' herself with ``the pride
of victimhood.'' She is such a fervent New Yorker that it is hard
to believe that she learned English only when she immigrated to the
United States in 1952 at the age of 16. She is widely known for her
joyful, gorgeously colored illustrated books, including the
Caldecott Honor book ``On Market Street'' (1982), and for those she
did with her husband, the late Arnold Lobel. Her pictures give no
hint of her dark, terrifying childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Barely 5 years old when the Nazis came to her comfortable home
in Poland, she spent the next five and a half years in hiding and
on the run, from the ghetto to the countryside to a Benedictine
convent. Her younger brother was always with her, disguised as a
girl to hide his circumcision. Their grown-up protector was their
Roman Catholic nanny, Niania, who pretended to be their mother.
Then the convent was raided and their Jewishness was revealed. The
children were in lineups, marches, transports in trucks and boxcars
to the camps -- first Plaszow, then Auschwitz, then Ravensbruck,
places of hunger, mud, stench, corpses, chimneys. After the war
Lobel spent two blissful years recovering from tuberculosis, nursed
by kind caregivers in a Swedish sanitarium. She learned Swedish and
went to school in Sweden for the first time when she was 12. She
never wanted to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Those who expect one book to tell the whole Holocaust history
will not be satisfied. There is no commentary, no context. In fact,
the integrity of the storytelling is in the narrowness of the
child's viewpoint, the physical immediacy, the bewilderment. The
truth is that nothing makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   Why are grown-ups crying? Where is her father? What does
``deported'' mean? She is afraid to ask. She is ashamed to be
Jewish. She hates her ``sadly Semitic'' appearance when she is in
hiding and even after the war, when she is the dark one among all
the blond Swedes.
</P>
<P>
   There are no heroics. Lobel is not aware of her courage. She
takes it for granted that she and her younger brother are one
individual. When she finds a raw potato in the mud, he and she
alternate taking bites out of it. She devotes just part of a
sentence to the selections at Ravensbruck, when she dragged him to
the left, away from the chimneys. And his disguise is no big deal;
there's no drama about it until the Nazis raid the convent and make
him pull his pants down.
</P>
<P>
   There's a phys-cal quality to Lobel's memories of the terror.
(``The whispers of the trapped grown-ups sounded like the noise of
insects rubbing their legs together.'') The deprivation is
visceral. (``Feverish, always crouching, diarrhea dripping from my
behind, I dreamed of a day I could sleep in a soft bed with clean
sheets and sit on a toilet that flushed in a lavatory that had a
door that closed.'') Fear is stifled by wave upon wave of hunger.
It is just she and her brother; they are reduced to nothing but two
hungry, itching lumps. All they want is not to be noticed, not to
be singled out. She mourns the loss of her braids when her head is
shaved, but otherwise she barely mourns the loss of anything. She
does not think about her parents. Only Niania.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-PICTURES-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: Only Niania.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When she is safe, she celebrates: ``I had no lice in my stubby
hair anymore, no lice in the seams of my pajamas''; she cannot take
for granted the ``fat, slithering, luxurious sweetness'' of butter.
There is no heartfelt family reunion, just as there is no nostalgia
for a pre-Nazi Eden. When her father first writes to her in Sweden,
his words are flowery, as if he is learning to be a father again
after seven years of not having children. In contrast, she is cold,
shut off: ``I had almost forgotten that yes, there would be a
mother and a father. Yes. They had been found. From the other side
of the Baltic I had had letters. Yes. I had written to them. Yes,
of course.''
</P>
<P>
   Her relationship with her mother has always been distant. When
they meet again after the war, her mother nags her to cut her hair.
``Didn't she know about the shaved heads in concentration camps?''
the child rages. Niania is the one the child loves. That Niania is
sometimes anti-Semitic, not always nice, does not matter. She is
the grown-up who raised and nurtured and sheltered the children.
Lobel misses Niania in the camps, and always.
</P>
<P>
   The memory is raw. The storytelling frames it. The message is
that there is no meaning in this suffering. And yet, if luck was
the most important factor in Anita Lobel's survival, so also was
the humanity of a Catholic woman who mistrusted Jews yet protected
the sister and brother ``with the flapping wings of a demented
angel.''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Hazel Rochman is an editor at Booklist, the reviewing magazine
of the American Library Association, and the editor, with Darlene
Z. McCampbell, of ``Bearing Witness: Stories of the Holocaust.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
