<HEADER>
A5439 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-OCEAN-NYTSF     11-11 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-OCEAN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS NEW OCEAN
</HEADLINE>
  The Story of the First Space Age 
 By William E. Burrows 
 Illustrated. 723 pp. New York: Random House. $34.95. 
 ------ 
 WE HAVE LIFTOFF 
 By ALEX ROLAND 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What does it mean that humans have walked on the moon, that our
machines have flown out of the solar system, that instruments of
war operate beyond the earth's atmosphere? In the heady aftermath
of the first manned moon landing, the historian Arthur Schlesinger
Jr. opined that future generations would see Apollo as the signal
event of this century. Carl Sagan, in his television series
``Cosmos,'' reckoned that if humanity did not blow itself up, the
great achievements of our era would prove to be survival itself and
the beginning of our journey to the stars. Throughout the 1970s,
the proverbial man in the street asked, ``If we can send a man to
the moon, why can't we ... (fill in the blank)?''
</P>
<P>
   William E. Burrows takes up the question in ``The New Ocean,'' a
narrative history of space flight. He defines ``the first space
age'' as running from the first sputnik in 1957 to somewhere
between the explosion of the space shuttle Challenger in 1986 and
the end of the Cold War in 1991. In hindsight, he attempts to
discern what that era meant and foresee where it is heading.
</P>
<P>
   His history breaks no new ground. He focuses primarily on the
United States, with due attention to Germany in World War II and
the Soviet Union in the cold war. The drama opens with the
obligatory homage to the holy trinity of space flight: the Russian
theorist and visionary Konstantin E. Tsiolkovsky, the American
rocket experimenter Robert H. Goddard and the German scientist
Hermann Oberth. Thereafter, the usual suspects appear in order.
Wernher von Braun receives all the attention he deserves, and scant
apology for his membership in the Nazi Party and the SS. His
Russian counterpart, Sergei P. Korolev, wins comparable
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Refreshingly, less familiar characters also find a place in
Burrows's story. Nikolai Fyodorov, Tsiolkovsky's librarian,
inspired his client with mystic notions of the unity of nature and
the universality of life. Robert Welch, the founder of the John
Birch Society, argued that sputnik was designed to trick America
into a ruinously expensive space program, a view that was not far
removed from that of President Dwight D. Eisenhower. Nicholas
Johnson, ``the Hercule Poirot of Soviet space-program analysts,''
had ``a lot of fun'' trying to discern the capabilities of the
Soviet antisatellite program. Michael A. Minovitch, a doctoral
student in mathematics and physics, spent a summer internship at
the Jet Propulsion Laboratory developing a theory of ``gravity
propulsion'' that revolutionized deep space exploration, an
achievement for which Burrows believes Minovitch was robbed of
credit.
</P>
<P>
   Engaging narrative is not, however, Burrows's greatest
achievement. ``This New Ocean'' is most distinguished by the
successful integration of three different story lines: manned space
flight, the militarization of space and space science. Burrows, a
professor of journalism at New York University, holds uncommon
credentials for such an undertaking. He has previously written
books on satellite reconnaissance and space science. His
familiarity with the secret and arcane minutiae of these subjects
enlivens and enriches the more familiar story of manned space
flight. He juxtaposes developments in the three areas, often
showing how advances in one shaped seemingly unrelated events in
another.
</P>
<P>
   It is well known, for example, that NASA's space shuttle takes
some of its characteristics from the insistence by the Air Force
that it carry spy satellites. Less well known is what the scientist
James Van Allen called the ``slaughter of the innocent,'' the
transfusion of space science funding to replace the money
hemorrhaging from the shuttle program in the 80's. Though
chronology remains the organizing principle of the book, Burrows's
attempt at integrating three topical threads makes his the most
successful general survey of space history yet to appear.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the book has curious omissions. Countries other than the
United States, the Soviet Union and Germany receive scant
attention. Communications satellites, the only commercial success
in space and arguably the space activity that has most transformed
modern life, are barely mentioned. Still less is said about the
so-called ``applications'' satellites for weather, earth resources,
pollution monitoring and mapping. James E. Webb, the managerial
genius who led NASA through most of the Apollo program, acts in
this book but does not think.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest weakness of the book, however, is the failure to
instill meaning into the richly integrated tapestry Burrows has
woven. Rather, the reader is left with a thick description from
which any number of interpretations might be drawn. Burrows implies
some meaning by his periodization, measuring the first space age
from sputnik to the end of the cold war. But exactly what does that
mean? What unifying theme operates within this epoch? I have
likened it to the barnstorming era of atmospheric flight, when
humans flew mostly for the exhilaration of the achievement, before
they found practical applications in war and commerce. But Burrows
ventures no such judgment.
</P>
<P>
   One interpretation implied by his periodization of events is
that Daniel S. Goldin, NASA administrator since 1992, has
introduced a new era in space activity. Goldin has won deserved
praise and credibility for shaking up the agency and imposing his
mantra of ``better, faster, cheaper'' on an ossified bureaucracy.
But, as Burrows' account makes clear, Goldin is simply pursuing the
old agenda more efficiently. His program offers no hint that the
second space age will be different from the first. Sending John
Glenn on a nostalgia cruise suggests how wedded to the past NASA
is.
</P>
<P>
   What does loom, then, on Burrows's space horizon? He raises
tourism, mining and manned missions to Mars, only to knock them
down as currently impractical. Approvingly he presents a proposal
by the physicist Freeman Dyson for ``Astrochickens'' _ small,
self-replicating, exploratory spacecraft combining ``21st-century
genetic engineering, advanced artificial intelligence and solar
electric propulsion.'' These craft also want development, but at
least they conjure an imagined future that is truly original,
rather than a tired repackaging of the first space age. While that
future takes shape, Burrows's work helps to define where we have
been.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Alex Roland, a professor of history at Duke University, teaches
military history and the history of technology.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
