<HEADER>
A5440 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-EVERYTHING-NY     11-11 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-EVERYTHING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO EVERYTHING
</HEADLINE>
  Illustrated by Bob Barner 
 Unpaged. San Francisco: Chronicle Books. $14.95. (All ages) 
 TO EVERY THING THERE IS A SEASON 
 Verses From Ecclesiastes 
 Illustrated by Leo Dillon and Diane Dillon 
 Unpaged. New York: The Blue Sky Press/Scholastic. $15.95.(All
ages) 
 ------ 
 TURN! TURN! TURN! 
 By VALERIE SAYERS 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even Bible illiterates recognize many lines from Ecclesiastes:
``Vanity of vanities,'' ``The sun also rises,'' ``Cast thy bread
upon the waters'' _ and especially ``To every thing there is a
season, and a time to every purpose under the heaven.'' Many of us
cannot hear that last line without mentally humming the musical
version by Pete Seeger, ``Turn! Turn! Turn!,'' which the Byrds made
famous with their recording in the mid-1960's.
</P>
<P>
   Two new books illustrate, to very different effect, those
resonant verses from Chapter 3 of Ecclesiastes. The lines employ
simple rhythms to affirm the balance of life's cycles: planting and
harvesting, gathering and releasing, grieving and celebrating. Bob
Barner's ``To Everything'' aims to capture this simplicity in an
effusive celebration, while Leo and Diane Dillon's ``To Every Thing
There Is a Season'' is a more subdued yet ornate exploration.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Everything'' renders the natural world in lush colors.
Barner's medium is collage, paper torn by hand and glued; his
subjects include monkeys, lions, dolphins, sun, moon and stars. The
effect is vivid and cheery and may be especially pleasing to very
young children. The illustrations, however, highlight Ecclesiastes'
celebratory moments at the expense of the hard times on which the
text also insists. Barner illustrates ``a time to cry'' with one
monkey watching four others scamper about. ``A time to mourn, a
time to dance'' shows hummingbirds flittering to and from a flower,
no mourners among them as far as I can see. ``A time for war, a
time for peace'' is represented by a dove rising above barbed wire,
but the wire, I am sorry to say, is a confusing touch, since it
curls up as prettily as everything else in the illustration.
</P>
<P>
   Adults reading this book to children will have a lot of
explaining to do, and the book provides, in an afterword, many
suggestions for busy discussion. Talking about the pictures is not
a bad thing, but in the case of these rich, straightforward lines,
the verbal balance deserves a visual match.
</P>
<P>
   Leo and Diane Dillon, who have used many styles and techniques
in their often prize-winning books for children, use a much more
elaborate, and indeed a more balanced, approach. They illustrate
each verse in a different historical and cultural style: ``A time
to kill, and a time to heal,'' for instance, is patterned on a
seventh-century Mexican Mixtec screen-fold picture book, and
depicts in one panel a human sacrifice, in the other a healing. ``A
time to keep, and a time to cast away'' is in the mode of ancient
Chinese silk painting. A family painted in graceful strokes and
delicate colors gathers fish into their boat on one page, returns
them to the sea on the page opposite. My favorite panels _ ``A time
to rend, and a time to sew'' _ are acrylic paintings in the style
of medieval Russian iconography. The Dillons' understanding of the
lines is completely and appropriately literal: tailors tear cloth
in one panel, sew it up in the other.
</P>
<P>
   The Dillons provide a useful description of each challenging
illustration and its implications. They also provide a rationale
for their method: ``The timeless words from Ecclesiastes,'' they
write, ``remind us that there are things in life that all people
share, regardless of our diverse beliefs and cultures.'' The only
problem with this approach _ using all of human history, culture
and art for inspiration _ is that it creates an almost random set
of visual responses to what is a tightly unified set of verses.
</P>
<P>
   Each illustration is lovely, apt, sometimes even dazzling, but
the book's hurtling back and forth through times and artistic
styles disrupts the rhythms of Ecclesiastes. It's my guess that
respect for difference could have been much more eloquently
conveyed by concentrating on any one of these styles rather than
giving a nod to all of them (and thereby leaving out plenty of
other possible cultural approaches). The particular is often the
best illustration of what is common to common experience.
</P>
<P>
   Ecclesiastes is a book of seeking, one that moves between
cynicism and acceptance, worldliness and spirituality, anxiety and
serenity. Chapter 3 contains some of its most centered lines, but
the surrounding chapters suggest an underlying plaintive quality.
Though neither of these books captures that tension to my taste,
both honor Ecclesiastes' acknowledgment of the polarities of life
on earth, and both provide their own visual riches.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Sayers is a professor of English at the University of
Notre Dame and the author of five novels.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
