<HEADER>
A5441 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-SCIFI-NYTSF     11-11 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-SCIFI-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE FICTION
</HEADLINE>
  By GERALD JONAS 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a tough job, but someone has to do it: bring the
crime-and-thriller genre known as ``noir'' into the 21st century.
Fortunately, K. W. Jeter is up to the task, and in NOIR (Spectra/
Bantam, $23.95) he lays out the future with a cheerless tenacity
Raymond Chandler might have applauded.
</P>
<P>
   The setting, of course, is Los Angeles _ a city now metastasized
into an endless urban sprawl that has devoured most of the Pacific
Rim. The protagonist is a lone wolf named McNihil. He's a former
operative for the Collection Agency, an organization that has
evolved to protect intellectual property rights in an era of
instant communication and traceless reproduction, all made possible
by Internet technology. One of his clients, a writer whose work has
been pirated, describes noir as ``a literature of anxiety'' that
remains current because it accepts the certainty of betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   If you think McNihil's work is limited to computerized snooping
on unscrupulous hackers, think again. The on-the-spot justice he
delivers to software pirates is technologically inventive but
primally brutal. Spelled out in excruciating detail, it will test
the resolve of readers who wonder why they're rooting for McNihil
against the forces of corporate evil, personified by a
``silver-haired'' executive named Harrisch. Not to worry.
Harrisch's scheme to bring capitalism to its logical conclusion _
in which the controllers of production gain ``a stranglehold on the
human brain'' _ is horrific enough to make McNihil's freelance
viciousness look sympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter understands that noir as a genre is defined more by style
than by content. He also understands that science fiction, as
Ursula K. Le Guin has pointed out, gives writers the option of
freshening up tired figures of speech by making them concrete. Thus
a rival operative called November observes that ``the dead were
always a good source of information. It was their business'' _ even
as she is in the process of interviewing a dead woman. One of the
novel's conceits is that people who die owing lots of money can be
kept in a quasi-living state by their creditors until they make
good on their debts. Other than the marketable discards they
salvage from garbage dumps, the so-called ``indeadted'' have
nothing to sell but shreds of random gossip.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of Jeter's inventions are so apt. McNihil has had his
brain altered so he views the world around him in black-and-white
images that mimic the grainy detective movies of the 1930's and
40's. Aside from the inherent improbability of a street-smart
shamus doing something to his nervous system that interferes with
his perception of reality, this cumbersome device quickly grows
tedious; even the author seems to lose interest in it as the plot
heats up.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Jeter's attempts to anticipate the hard-boiled slang of
the next century _ ``Connect you, mother-connector,'' McNihil
snarls at one point _ provoke the kind of titter that threatens to
destroy the noir spell. But in general Jeter accomplishes his goal
of updating the genre, and he does so with commendable energy and
imagination. If the results are irremediably nasty, McNihil for one
would not be surprised. ``All writers were mean bastards,'' he
notes, adding with italicized approval: ``Must come with the
territory.''
</P>
<P>
   In THIS ALIEN SHORE (DAW, $23.95), C. S. Friedman borrows some
big ideas from writers like Cordwainer Smith, Frank Herbert and
Samuel R. Delany, and runs with them. Instead of stumbling under
the burden, she succeeds in making the recycled material her own.
</P>
<P>
   Millenniums ago, the invention of a spaceship drive that was
capable of faster-than-light speeds prompted a wave of emigration
from an overcrowded Earth. The emigrants had barely begun the hard
work of colonizing distant planets when it was discovered that
exposure to the drive played havoc with human DNA. Fearful of
genetic contamination, the authorities on Earth severed all ties
with its colonies. Now the home planet and its much-altered
children have re-established contact, and everyone is jockeying for
control of the galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line of the new society is that you have to be crazy
_ literally _ to attempt faster-than-light travel. It takes a
special kind of madness, controlled and channeled by specially
tailored drugs, to guide a ship through the spatial short cuts
known as ainniqs. Not surprisingly, a Guild of ``outpilots'' holds
a monopoly on such journeys. With all passengers ``chilled'' in
suspended animation or under heavy sedation, the outpilot fights to
outwit the deadly ``dragons'' that inhabit the other-dimensional
network of ainniqs.
</P>
<P>
   If all this sounds complicated, it is. And I have yet to mention
the novel's central character, a young girl named Jamisia, who is
plagued by voices in her head. Jamisia is a mystery even to
herself, a wild card in the game of galactic intrigue. Her slow and
painful process of self-discovery tethers the far-ranging plot to a
recognizably human predicament, even as rival groups of
conspirators seek to exploit her maturing powers.
</P>
<P>
   In interweaving the many threads of her narrative, Friedman has
created a potent metaphor for the toleration of diversity _ an
ever-evolving society where ``the genes of wild genius'' are
acknowledged as necessary for survival.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen F. McHugh's MISSION CHILD (Eos/Avon, $20) is not at all
flashy. The story, which follows the coming of age of an orphan
named Janna on a ramshackle colony planet, is full of violent
incident. But in her first-person narration Janna never raises her
voice. The murder of her family, the three gifts she receives from
a dying ``offworlder,'' her decision to pose as a young boy, her
apprenticeship to a shaman, her encounter with the plague are all
treated in a matter-of-fact manner that encourages the reader to
accept everything that happens as natural, commonplace, mundane _
just the way Janna herself does.
</P>
<P>
   As in her earlier novel ``China Mountain Zhang,'' McHugh writes
science fiction from the inside out, with the focus on character.
After a while the reader forgets the extraterrestrial setting and
the fairy-tale devices, concentrating instead on Janna's struggles
to find a purpose in her life. The quiet ending is both unexpected
and an inevitable outgrowth of what has come before.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
