<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5442 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-WINDOW-NYTSF     11-11 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-WINDOW-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINDOW MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
  By Anastasia Suen 
 Illustrated by Wade Zahares 
 Unpaged. New York: Viking. $15.99. (Ages 3 to 8) 
 SLOW TRAIN TO OXMOX 
 Written and illustrated by Kurt Cyrus 
 Unpaged. New York: Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $16. (Ages 3 and up) 
 ------ 
 LITTLE ENGINES THAT COULD 
 By ROBIN TZANNES 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Railroads hold a special fascination for adults and children
alike. The sweep and change of scenery, the excitement of going
someplace new and the speed and sway of the train itself combine to
make rail travel wonderfully satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Window Music,'' by Anastasia Suen, illustrated by Wade
Zahares, and ``Slow Train to Oxmox,'' by Kurt Cyrus, are both train
stories with beautiful pictures. But while ``Slow Train to Oxmox''
uses the train merely as a device to teach a lesson, ``Window
Music'' is all about the experience of riding on a train.
</P>
<P>
   The phrase ``window music'' is 1880's railroad slang for passing
scenery, and it is on this scenery that Suen concentrates.
Beginning and ending with ``Train on the track, clickety clack,''
the book strings together easy rhymes that toddlers will love to
hear over and over. The train goes up mountains and down valleys,
passing streets and cars, fields and horses, orchards and ocean.
Finally, we come to the city, and ``into the station, our
destination.''
</P>
<P>
   In illustrating ``Window Music,'' Wade Zahares has used a rich,
earthy palette with brilliant white accents. His drawings are full
of life and will have strong appeal for children. It is mildly
disappointing, however, that given the book's evocative title,
Zahares has disregarded its meaning. Instead of using the train
window as a constant frame for the ever-changing view, he has shown
the journey from the outside; only a few pictures show the
perspective of a passenger looking out the window. However,
Zahares's gorgeous drawings more than compensate for this minor
discrepancy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to illustrating the verse, Zahares has created a
lovely story line independent of the text, telling us in pictures
about a little girl returning home after a visit to her
grandparents. The title page just hints at another interpretation:
we see the little girl asleep by an open window, a train climbing a
hill in the distance. Could her entire journey, then, have been
just a dream, evoked by another sort of ``window music,'' the sound
of the train passing by her window at night?
</P>
<P>
   ``Slow Train to Oxmox'' is a different kind of train book, for
slightly older children. Again, the drawings are very fine. Done in
a style reminiscent of Thomas Hart Benton's, they are full of wit
and clever detail. Unfortunately, Kurt Cyrus is a better
illustrator than storyteller. While the tale is well written, the
plot is convoluted and illogical.
</P>
<P>
   The story starts out promisingly enough. Edwin Blink, a busy,
self-important man with a first-class ticket on the Oxmox Express,
finds himself by mistake on the Slow Train. Now you might expect
the story to unfold around the joys of taking one's time, enjoying
the ride, seeing the things you miss if you're always in a hurry.
But no. Oddly enough, this book turns out to be about cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   The Slow Train is full of strange characters, including a
rooster and a horse. Most of the humans aboard appear to be poor or
elderly; all are unconcerned about being on the inferior train. The
Slow Train begins a long, roundabout route full of obstacles, which
can't be overcome without the passengers' help. When the train
stops for geese, the passengers get out and lift the tracks so the
flock can cross beneath them. When it gets stuck in mud, the
passengers have to push. When the train falls into a creek, we
discover that Edwin is a mechanical engineer who can make bridges
out of rope. Edwin, who'd been in such a hurry before, is now happy
on the slow train, because he is able to help. And the train
rattles on.
</P>
<P>
   This book is unsatisfying for several reasons. For one thing, we
never actually see the train reach Oxmox. Even worse, this train
doesn't behave anything like a train. Trains are massive, powerful
machines, and should not be pushed, twisted and pulled around by
passengers. There is no explanation for why it takes such a
circuitous, difficult route, or why the passengers put up with it.
Are they really trying to get somewhere, or do they take this
arduous journey simply because they like to cooperate?
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cyrus is a talented illustrator, and his drawings alone
make this book worthwhile. Young readers may even enjoy the story,
not caring that it doesn't make sense. But if you're looking to
share an old-fashioned train book with your favorite 3-year-old,
take a look at ``Window Music.''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Robin Tzannes's books for children include ``Professor
Puffendorf's Secret Potions'' and ``Sanji and the Baker.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
