</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5443 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-WYETH-1000&AMP;AD     11-11 2412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-WYETH-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N. C. WYETH
</HEADLINE>
  By David Michaelis 
 Illustrated. 553 pp. New York: Alfred A. Knopf. $40 
 ------ 
 'PICTURES GREAT,' HIS PUBLISHER TOLD HIM 
 By ADAM GOPNIK 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For most of the 18th and 19th centuries, an American artist who
could make painted things look like real ones was regarded as a man
with something up his sleeve. Sargent, Whistler, even Church all
had a touch of the gentleman magician about them, the black cape
and top hat. Eakins claimed the mysterious authority of the
scientist, wrapping his obsessions in the solemn objectivity of
investigation, while lesser lights, like the trompe l'oeil painters
John Frederick Peto and William Michael Harnett, cultivated the sly
charm of the sleight-of-hand man. It was only with the coming of
the 20th century, and the widespread arrival of instant illusion in
the form of photography, that a new aura of honest craft and
stubborn integrity began to cling to the image of the American
realist. The painter of reassuringly recognizable objects had by
now become himself a reassuringly recognizable object _ not fluid
as mercury but solid as rock, a repository of deep, melancholy
truths.
</P>
<P>
   No American family has both suffered from and exploited this
transformation more than the Wyeths of Chadds Ford, Pa. David
Michaelis's book is the first biography of the patriarch of that
family, the illustrator and painter N. C Wyeth. It is a full-scale,
many-voiced, deeply researched study _ somewhat overproduced, one
might think, for a figure whose best-known accomplishments are
illustrating ``Robin Hood'' and fathering Andrew. Yet the author's
confidence in his subject in the end seems fairly won: N. C.'s
accomplishments turn out to be larger than one might have imagined
_ he is the Wyeth who counts _ and his life is larger than his
accomplishments. The Wyeths themselves, the art-obsessed clan who
were his invention, emerge as both more likable and more Gothic
than one had expected: half Pennsylvania Bruegels, half the Addams
Family.
</P>
<P>
   Newell Convers Wyeth was born in Needham, Mass., in 1882.
Despite the all-American name, he was descended, on his mother's
side, from a Swiss-American family, the Zirngiebels. Dominated
throughout his life by his neurotic mother, Hattie, he took her
identity as his own. N. C. _ his family called him Convers _ was a
mama's boy to end all mama's boys. When, at 22, he announced,
tentatively, that he might get married, Hattie had his picture
taken down from the family mantelpiece and replaced it with (as she
explained) ``Your large baby picture. I felt I must get you back in
that form.'' He never rebelled against this mother-love, and
eventually cajoled his wife too into his mother's orbit, keeping
her pregnant and stifled. Although the family valued truth in small
things, it was also the kind of family that could ignore monsters
sitting in the living room. In what is still the Wyeth house style,
the weirdly cryptic sits right alongside the excessively
plain-spoken.
</P>
<P>
   After dropping out of high school, N. C. became the star pupil
of Howard Pyle, the greatest illustrator of the late 19th century.
With Pyle as mentor, he produced a Saturday Evening Post cover (a
cowboy and bucking bronco illustrating Emerson Hough's ``Law at
Heart's Desire'') when he was only 21, and the next year, 1904, he
broke into the even classier Scribner's Magazine with ``The Moose
Call,'' a sepia-toned oil of an Indian hunter in a canoe.
</P>
<P>
   For all his success, N. C was moving into a dying form.
Illustration, which had been an important form of American
reporting and commentary throughout the 19th century _ a genre
strong enough to support the early Winslow Homer and impress van
Gogh _ had given way to the camera, and would soon be able to
support only ``illustration'' in the modern sense: pictures to
dress up a story. N. C. was, as Michaelis says, ``caste
conscious,'' but it is also fair to say that he had an art
conscience, or got one, along with everyone else around that time.
In 1908, after even more commercial success as a cowpunching
illustrator of westerns, he retreated into a house on a hill
overlooking Chadds Ford and announced that ``painting and
illustration cannot be mixed _ one cannot merge from one into the
other.'' But he couldn't go ``modern,'' either. He hated the
contemporary world, though his rage, oddly, was directed less at
photography, which was so obviously devastating his niche, as at
the automobile, a ``vibrating machine'' that would leave people
with nothing more than ``fleeting recollections of fantastic
blurred objects'' _ not a bad summation of the advanced painting
that would soon rise up in Paris and New York and leave him
stranded.
</P>
<P>
   For a couple of years he did dutiful landscapes of the
Pennsylvania scenery, dull as a toothache. He also took to reading
Thoreau, whom he called his ``worshiped friend.'' As Michaelis
writes shrewdly, ``The restless me-first individualism of the
American West was supplanted by the rigid me-myself iconoclasm of
Walden Pond.'' What to do? Like E. B. White _ another Thoreau lover
who fled the city to do more lasting work _ Wyeth found what he
needed in children's books. In 1911, Scribners asked him to do a
series of illustrations for ``Treasure Island,'' Stevenson's 1883
classic. Quickly, Wyeth painted 17 full-scale canvases _ the best
things he had ever done. The conventional thing to say about his
book illustrations is that Wyeth made such pictures more dramatic
than his predecessors had done. But in fact his genius lay in
making his pictures much less dramatic than pictures like this had
ever been before _ his gift was for slowing down and sobering up
book illustration so that it took on some of the gravity that had
in the past belonged only to high art. In his ``Treasure Island''
illustrations, there is a constant, spell-inducing tension between
the boys'-book excitements _ the cutlasses and shining swords and
pistols _ and the careful, sober, exact rendition of rigging and
wooden surfaces and late-afternoon shadows. (No one ever used long
shadows more expressively than Wyeth; he turned ``American'' light
into late afternoon light, as it remains to this day.) He called
his technique, poetically, ``sight seen,'' meaning that it was all
seen from the point of view of a single observer, so that the
viewer ``is actually the boy at all times.'' ``We are given,''
Michaelis writes (in one of his better phrases), ``the erotic power
of omnipotent invisibility.'' And something about the safety of
children's books allowed Wyeth to release his own iconography.
Michaelis reveals that the ``Psycho''-style house in the most
haunting painting in the series _ ``Old Pew,'' the blind man
working his way down a lane _ is a carefully rendered moonlight
view of Wyeth's childhood home.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-WYETH-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: childhood home.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Pictures great,'' Scribners wired when they saw the ``Treasure
Island'' paintings, and from that point on, the Scribners
Illustrated Classics became Wyeth's museum, his gallery, his
testament: ``The Boy's King Arthur,'' ``The Black Arrow,'' ``The
Last of the Mohicans,'' ``The Mysterious Island,'' ``The
Deerslayer,'' ``Westward Ho!'' _ more than 350,000 copies of
Wyeth's editions were sold by 1930. Though depression would plague
him in later life, it was never again rooted in disappointment with
his work. He began to raise his own family, and became a robustly
loving father and Santa Claus combined, supplying his five children
with the same fanatic exactitude in the service of fantasy that he
gave to his paintings: ``Early on Christmas morning, in costume, he
climbed a ladder to the roof of the house. Stamping his boots,
ringing sleigh bells, quieting the reindeer, he called down the
bedroom chimneys. Hidden behind a long-whiskered mask with spiky
white eyebrows and a peaked red hat, he would visit each child's
room, filling stockings, carrying 'the beautiful illusion of ``old
Kris'' as far as possible.' '' He even rigged up a dummy Santa so
that the kids would see St. Nick along with their father and not
catch on to the impersonation.
</P>
<P>
   But his was a smothering presence, too. For all his reputation
as a master of silverpoint exactitude, N. C. was a full-blown Grimm
Brothers romantic, who taught his children to ``feel everything'' _
and as Michaelis says, ``the romancing of things made separation
and loss central to their sense of themselves and the world.''
Andrew, the most sensitive and gifted child in the Wyeth art
academy, recalls that one of his earliest memories of Christmas was
of the humiliation of being so terrified by the bearded apparition
that he lost control and wet his pants. (One can't help wondering
if a less enclosing father might have pushed the prodigy Andrew
farther out _ to Paris, to New York, to the world _ and, in that
way, done him more good as an artist in the long run.)
</P>
<P>
   In the end the story takes a strangely incestuous and then a
heartbreakingly tragic turn. In the last years of N. C.'s life,
Howard Pyle's niece Caroline _ a girl so stunning that her sex
appeal still radiates through half-century-old family snapshots _
entered the Wyeth menage, and became a kind of Chadds Ford Lulu.
She flirted with various Wyeths, and eventually married N. C.'s son
Nat. N. C. grew obsessed with her, and may have become her lover;
even Michaelis is not quite sure. What is certain is that one
morning in 1945, he picked up Caroline and Nat's little boy,
Newell, and took him for a drive; the car stopped _ or stalled, no
one knows _ at a railroad crossing, and (it is almost unbearable to
imagine) the grandfather and small boy were killed together by the
milk train arriving at Chadds Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Did he have a heart attack? Did he simply panic? Chadds Ford
locals were sure that they knew the truth. They said that N. C. was
consumed with guilt over his relationship with Caroline, that his
``grandson'' was really his son, and that he killed himself and the
boy in a fit of remorse. Michaelis is convinced, and convinces the
reader, that this is probably just evil-speaking and myth-making.
The oddest thing about the tragedy is that for all they had lost in
one terrible morning _ both the family patriarch and its prince _
the rest of the Wyeths stayed put. They remained in Chadds Ford,
and Andrew continued to paint not far from the railroad crossing
where his father and nephew had died. The family enclosure that N.
C. had built kept them in, as it was meant to.
</P>
<P>
   Michaelis has assembled an excellent account of all these events
_ well written, conscientious and, on the whole, enthralling. He is
a demon researcher and can turn a phrase. (``Fathers who die
violent deaths inhabit shallow graves,'' he says of the aftermath
of N. C.'s death.) And he knows the value of understatement and
indirection. But he takes for granted the one thing you most want
him to prove, and that is the relevance of the Wyeth family story
(and tragedy) to the larger history of American art. In all the
standard telling, after all, N. C. barely rates a footnote. Yet for
Michaelis, the Wyeths might as well be the van Eycks. A reader of
this biography would have no idea that there were people who
doubted the importance or even the relevance of the Wyeths, or that
the world of illustration and realist painting that the book
describes was only a tiny microworld within a larger American art
world that was undergoing a revolution a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Michaelis would probably say that he was leaving this work to
the reader, and perhaps it can be quickly done. In retrospect,
Wyeth had two accomplishments, neither neglible. One was to
``package'' or popularize the line of stoic American melancholy
that begins in Homer and Eakins. The long, still shadows, the
careful, indiscriminate inventory, in which a dying hero and the
turn of a bedpost are given the same sober, positive caress _ all
this, though generally derived from Northern European painting, has
a particular American point and poignancy, and Wyeth was the first
to take it from the margins and inject it right into the nation's
bloodstream.
</P>
<P>
   His other achievement, closely related , was still larger. By
mixing the tight-lipped empirical inventory with fantasy stories,
he helped give birth to the visual style of American movies. The
movies, after all, are a form where pinpoint exactitude and
elaborately engineered fantasy are not just the goal but the given
_ all there is. Wyeth's influence on the movies has been immense.
Douglas Fairbanks begged him to come out to Hollywood, and the
style of Fairbanks's ``Robin Hood'' and ``Thief of Bagdad'' is
impossible to imagine without Wyeth's example; even the 1946 film
of Marjorie Kinnan Rawlings's novel ``The Yearling'' closely
follows the design of Wyeth's illustrations.
</P>
<P>
   Wyeth's peculiar inventions, or discoveries _ the omnipresent
viewpoint, the low, child's-eye view of violence and horror, the
``sight seen'' manner, all breaking with the conventions of the
proscenium stage, which haunted illustration up to to his time _
continue to be one of the dominant ways in which the movies see. A
lot of what we think of as somehow naturally ``cinematic'' begins
in his illustrations. If Steven Spielberg is to be placed in a
family tree of visual artists, then N. C. Wyeth is one of his
ancestors. (Spielberg famously collects Rockwell, but does he
collect the older Wyeth? He should.) A more expansive history might
elevate the Wyeth Michaelis has given us not by overpraising his
``serious'' art, but by folding him into a larger history of
popular entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   If one imagines the history of American art as a many-chambered
mansion, where a peculiarly American dialogue between fantasy and
exactitude, between transcendentalism and literalism, gets acted
out, then N. C. Wyeth's particular version of that dialogue _
adventure stories told as solemnly as psalms _ occupies a pretty
small room. But it was large enough to raise a family in, and it
had a big window.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Adam Gopnik is the Paris correspondent of The New Yorker and is
currently working on a book of lives of American artists.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
