<HEADER>
A5446 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-MARY-NYTSF     11-11 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-MARY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRY, HURRY, MARY DEAR
</HEADLINE>
  By N. M. Bodecker 
 Illustrated by Erik Blegvad 
 Unpaged. New York: Margaret K. McElderry Books. $16. (Ages 7 and
up) 
 ------ 
 A WOMAN WHOSE WORK IS NEVER DONE 
 By BETH GUTCHEON 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Picture books for young children appear simple and are often
slight. And yet they have to meet standards rarely or never imposed
on other branches of literature. How many books on your shelf could
you bear to read 800 times? How many new books that you love would
be equally appealing to your mother?
</P>
<P>
   Consider, too, the burden of social utility the picture book
lugs around. It is a book that a child loves enough to want to hear
over and over again until she has memorized every word (and she
cannot be fooled by any playful substitutions of phrasing her
captive reader may attempt the five- or six-hundredth time
through). Such a book has taught a child what every one of those
loved words looks like on the page. It has taught her what reading
is for, approximately how it is done, and that it is a delight. A
book that uses pictures not only to illustrate but also to comment,
to tell a slightly different story from what the words say, is
doing something very sophisticated indeed, and yet accomplishing it
with grace.
</P>
<P>
   Happy is the child who falls in love with a picture book of real
and lasting charm, and twice as happy the parent.
</P>
<P>
   In my son's childhood, the book of choice was ``Father Fox's
Penny Rhymes,'' by the Vermont sisters Clyde and Wendy Watson (a
gem worth tracking down, if you don't already know it). For many
new-minted book lovers it will be ``Hurry, Hurry, Mary Dear,''
another near-perfect collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   N. M. Bodecker, who died in 1988, was a Danish-American writer
and illustrator. Erik Blegvad explains in his introduction that he
and Bodecker met in Copenhagen in 1941, both married Americans and
immigrated to New England, where for years they shared a studio in
Connecticut, as well as a language and a friendship. Blegvad has
made wonderfully witty and appealing paintings, based on his
friend's own drawings of Mary, to illustrate Bodecker's
posthumously published nonsense rhyme.
</P>
<P>
   Mary is a New England farm wife, being urged to rush about her
autumn chores by her stout husband. In a striped dress and apron,
she picks the apples, dills the pickles and chops down trees for
wooden nickels. Her husband is glimpsed infrequently, rolling out
of bed or tying his tie at the upstairs window as Mary churns the
butter, smokes the hams, cans tomatoes and puts up jams; soon the
sky grows dark, the brown leaves blow past the window, and Mary's
nose grows red with cold.
</P>
<P>
   The blue, gray-green, brown and orange colors of the New England
landscape are wonderfully evocative, frame by frame, and it's fun
to keep track of Mary's cat, which is sometimes lurking far off in
the grass as geese honk by overhead in V formation, and Mary
struggles under a bushel of late tomatoes, or is playing with a
grape on the kitchen floor as the curtains blow, the kettle steams
and Mary makes jelly. Sometimes the pictures are deliberately
silly, like the one of Mary splitting peas, but the humor is mostly
subtle and based on juxtaposition. A child will understand more and
more of the jokes as she grows older, without feeling fooled or
left out of anything should she get none of them. As for the
delicious one at the end, no one will miss it
</P>
<P>
   The winter comes on as Mary's day progresses. The first flakes
of snow begin to fall as she takes in the last of the beans, and
the light has turned a flat, gray-green color that feels like a
storm. There's some black in the clouds in the next scene of Mary
up a ladder, taking down screens and putting up storm windows. (Now
there's a nasty job in any weather.) The cat is not helping; she is
down in the branches of a bare tree, enjoying the wind. But Mary
remains cheerful. By the time she gets indoors, the snow flurries
have become a full-fledged storm, and her husband is looking
forward to his tea.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to say just what is the last straw -- maybe the fact
that he thinks doughnuts are baked rather than fried -- but it
doesn't matter. Mary isn't planning to bake him any, anyway, and
absolutely nothing could spoil this charmer of a book.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Beth Gutcheon's most recent novel is ``Five Fortunes.'' Beth
Gutcheon's most recent novel is ``Five Fortunes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
