<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5447 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-WILD-NYTSF     11-11 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-WILD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WILD BOY
</HEADLINE>
  Based on the True Story of the Wild Boy of Aveyron 
 Written and illustrated by Mordicai Gerstein 
 40 pp. New York: Frances Foster Books/Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $16.
(Ages 5 to 9) 
 VICTOR 
 A Novel Based on the Life of the Savage of Aveyron 
 By Mordicai Gerstein 
 258 pp. New York: Frances Foster Books/Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux.
$17. (Ages 12 and up) 
 ------ 
 WHO IS THE REAL SAVAGE? 
 By KATHRYN HARRISON 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1800 a child was captured in the woods of Aveyron, in the
south of France. Naked, filthy, unable to speak, he was both beast
and human: he was, it seemed, a handy, home-grown example of
Rousseau's noble savage. He had no family, no history anyone could
decipher, and, thus unprotected, he was taken to Paris, where he
was ushered into the Age of Reason. At the Institute for Deaf-Mutes
a young and idealistic doctor, Jean-Marc Itard, succeeded in
forcibly civilizing the wild boy, whom he named Victor, to the
point where the child wore clothes, ate with cutlery and could
identify a few written words.
</P>
<P>
   Itard's methods of teaching went on to influence the educator
Maria Montessori, but his goal, to get Victor to speak, was never
realized; the so-called Savage of Aveyron's short life was spent on
the cusp of a society that could neither fully form nor accept him.
</P>
<P>
   From this true story, Mordicai Gerstein has rendered ``The Wild
Boy,'' a picture book, and ``Victor,'' a young-adult novel. For the
younger reader, Gerstein spins a fairy tale of salvation, similar
to that of Helen Keller and Annie Sullivan or of John Merrick (the
Elephant Man) and Dr. Frederick Treves. It's a familiar formula, in
which a feral child, a freak -- reviled, feared, exploited -- is
recognized by an enlightened benefactor as inherently worthy. The
doctor/savior/teacher guides the Victor/Helen/John character firmly
toward a fuller expression of his or her true, if hidden, humanity.
The path of discipline is complicated by the faithless, those who
consider the attempt hopeless, the student unredeemable.
</P>
<P>
   Success, after setbacks that provide suspense, is a fulfillment
of religious proportion: emotional, transcendent. Gerstein's
picture book leaves readers with an image of the young doctor and
Victor united in rapturous bedtime coziness, a clean boy bathed in
silver moonlight. His novel, which succeeds as a rare thing, a
novel of ideas for adolescents, is less reductive.
</P>
<P>
   What is civilization, and why should a wild boy who exults in
his wildness, untroubled by forks or alphabets, want any part of
it? The course of Victor's relationship with Itard is not one of
smooth advances but of halting steps toward a limited and costly
taming that ends in disillusion and rupture. It's a sad story that
raises uncomfortable questions.
</P>
<P>
   When the wild boy is captured, it is discovered that his throat
was once cut. Although the wound was not fatal, as his abandoners
perhaps intended, the scar still bears testimony to a wretched
past. Victor's life among other humans will always be marked by
fear and suspicion. As his doctor notes, the boy cares only for
food and freedom. He is fed, but the freedom he wants, a return to
the woods, is not the one that society conceives for him.
</P>
<P>
   He lived up in a tree,
</P>
<P>
   knew nothing of Liberty!
</P>
<P>
   And so we had to capture him,
</P>
<P>
   to tell him he was free,
</P>
<P>
   a Revolutionary citizen,
</P>
<P>
   just like you and me!
</P>
<P>
   goes a popular song, as the Savage of Aveyron's fame spreads. In
the wake of revolution, the Paris intelligentsia embraces science,
education, a forced march of progress for all -- one in which
pride, both nationalist and personal, plays a great part. Itard's
distinguished mentors allow him the opportunity to rehabilitate a
child whose potential they question, and to present the results of
his program before the Society of Observers of Man. Such pressure
is enough to inspire methods of teaching that are still used today,
and to drive Itard occasionally to beat a child he cannot reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I am an explorer in some unknown wilderness: this
boy,'' the doctor remarks to himself, ruefully, of his apparent
destiny. Watching Victor clutch a sack, Itard observes that it is
filled with ``things that may be lost or taken away; ownership is a
fragile state.'' Each comfort of civilization has its price. Even
the greatest gift Itard proposes to give the boy, language,
Gerstein reveals as alienation from all it seeks to identify: ``He
opens his mouth and bites. He has no word for potato. Nothing
separates him from it.'' This is a version very different from the
one we are given by the book we call our first, in which God gives
Adam dominion through the power of naming creation.
</P>
<P>
   BY turns demanding and guilt-ridden, Itard finally fails to save
Victor from his animal nature, rather too much of which Gerstein
sets out in scenes of masturbation. As Victor enters puberty he
falls under the spell of his genitals, touching them when he is in
public or in the company of his doctor. That Itard, who has
sacrificed his own sexuality to his career, can neither allow nor
control what he considers evidence of the boy's bestiality
</P>
<P>
   becomes a catalyst for their violent rupture.
</P>
<P>
   Victor's captors, men of science, of reason -- of Liberte,
Egalite, Fraternite -- judge grief to be a uniquely human emotion.
When they find him, the wild boy knows how to laugh but not to cry.
Perhaps his education is successful insofar as he learns, and
learns well, to weep.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Harrison's most recent books are ``Poison'' and ``The
Kiss.'' She is completing a novel.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
