<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5450 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-POPE-1000&AMP;ADD     11-11 1601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-POPE-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN RUSSELL POPE
</HEADLINE>
  Architect of Empire 
 By Steven McLeod Bedford 
 Illustrated. 239 pp. New York: Rizzoli. $60 
 ------ 
 BRINGING B.C. TO D.C. 
 By THOMAS S. HINES 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1937, when President Franklin Roosevelt invited Frank Lloyd
Wright to the White House to discuss proposed housing for the
Tennessee Valley Authority, the architect addressed him informally
but directly: ``Frank, you ought to get up out of that chair and
see what they are doing to your city here, miles and miles of Ionic
and Corinthian columns.'' While many architects, for well over a
century, had contributed to the form of neo-classical Washington,
John Russell Pope, in Wright's modernist view, was the most
conspicuous culprit, having recently designed for the Washington
Mall the National Archives, the Jefferson Memorial and the National
Gallery of Art. In a letter to the President in 1937, Wright
characterized the memorial as an ``arrogant insult to the memory of
Thomas Jefferson.''
</P>
<P>
   Pope was born in New York City in 1873. His parents were
professional portrait and landscape painters. He attended City
College, Columbia and the Ecole des Beaux-Arts in Paris before
apprenticing with Bruce Price, best known for his work in the
domestic Shingle Style. By the time Pope opened his own office in
1905, his chief neo-classical model and mentor was Charles Follen
McKim, whose support would be crucial in his career. Of equal
importance was Pope's strategic marriage to Sadie Jones, the
socially prominent step-daughter of Henry Walters, an entrepreneur
who was related to the Delano family, a fact that would assume
great significance for Pope when Franklin Delano Roosevelt became
President. On the basis of his Beaux-Arts training and his acquired
social credentials, Pope established his early reputation as a
designer of period revival houses and commercial office towers for
the business elite, as well as campus plans of historicist
formalism for Dartmouth, Johns Hopkins and Yale. Yet Pope left his
major mark in his design of grand neo-classical public buildings
and monuments.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from his social connections and his obeisance to
established norms, it is difficult to understand from reading
``John Russell Pope: Architect of Empire'' how Pope acquired such
power -- since the author, Steven McLeod Bedford, presents him as a
rather cold fish. His ``refusal to meet with clients he did not
like, or who were not prestigious enough, placed a great burden on
his employees, as they had to assume considerable responsibility
while Pope remained in the background.'' Such qualities of
temperament were reflected in his architecture, since he, like
other historicists, ``lacked the confidence to go beyond style,''
Bedford says, and therefore espoused ``a conservative belief in the
power and validity of classical form,'' averring that ``no new and
distinct style should be created.'' Yet he must have provided what
many clients believed they wanted. Like most architects, he was
something of a gun for hire, designing memorials not only to Thomas
Jefferson but to Warren G. Harding. For Harding, Pope composed a
simple, finely scaled Doric rotunda with a handsome dome. He failed
to win the commission, the author believes, because he ``made a
fatal error in designing a domed structure as a memorial for the
man whose Administration was rocked by the Teapot Dome scandal.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the criticism of Pope's architecture, the high
visibility of his major work makes it worthy of study. With
striking new photographs by Jonathan Wallen and a clearly written
text, this monograph is the first to assess Pope's achievement.
Regrettably, it suffers from several problems. It presents Pope's
work in chapters organized around the categories of residential,
commercial, public, university, museum and monumental structures.
This makes it static, depriving it of a sense of historical
progression, for if Pope's work changed slowly, his times did not.
</P>
<P>
   Bedford also seems uncertain about the nature of his audience.
The text contains arcane references familiar only to specialists.
Yet these very professionals will be alienated by an absence of
notes to documentary sources. Those needing footnotes, Bedford
blithely assures us, can check them by retrieving his Columbia
dissertation. Since a deluge of new Pope studies is not likely, the
decision to eliminate documentation was a serious error of
judgment. Finally, the author fails to explicate sufficiently the
cultural issues surrounding Pope's work. While there are occasional
references to modernist critics of the architect's retardataire
designs, there is no real effort to place that battle in its rich
historical context. In the late 19th and early 20th centuries, the
central ideological conflict between historicizing traditionalists
and avant-garde modernists in architecture entailed competing
claims for the necessity of inventing authentic, original forms
versus the need to retain tradition and continuity.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the conflict had a much longer history. Following
L'Enfant's late-18th-century plan for the Washington Mall and
Government center, James Hoban's White House and the multi-authored
Capitol building had established neo-classicism as the governmental
style, a precedent confirmed in Robert Mills's impressive Treasury
Building of the 1830's. In the next decade, James Renwick's
eclectic Smithsonian Institution broke decidedly with that
paradigm, as, later, did the State, War and Navy Building and the
Library of Congress. In 1902, the architects Daniel Burnham and
Charles McKim strongly urged in their Washington plan that major
new structures on or near the Mall return to the neo-classicism of
the Founders. That imperative was heeded in the 1920's in Henry
Bacon's beautifully composed Lincoln Memorial. But it was also
challenged by modernists who wanted governmental buildings to
celebrate a 20th-century architecture. This was the dialectic Pope
encountered in the
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-POPE-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: '20s and '30s.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1917, he became a member of the National Commission of Fine
Arts, a position that bolstered his stature. The first meeting he
attended received a plea from F.D.R., who shared his taste and who
was then Assistant Secretary of the Navy, that the exuberantly
Victorian State, War and Navy Building be radically remodeled in
neo-classical garb, the better to ``fit'' with the neighboring
White House and Treasury Building. The Commission endorsed this
dubious proposal and asked Pope to make sketches. Ultimately,
because of a lack of funding, the transformation did not happen, a
failure the author finds ``regrettable'' but for which most
observers have been thankful. Roosevelt's fantasized neo-classical
facelift of one of the capital's 19th-century treasures would have
been a sad loss to the texture of Washington as well as to the
national heritage.
</P>
<P>
   However left of center Roosevelt may have been on other fronts,
his architectural tastes were grandly conservative, not far removed
from those of his contemporaries, the dictators of Italy and
Germany. This book would have gained both substance and
significance by overt comparisons, formally and culturally, of the
architecture of Pope and the frequently similar work of the German
architect Albert Speer. Furthermore, the author is insufficiently
explicit on the continuing impact Roosevelt's support may have had
on Pope's career. There can be little doubt that it did not hurt
him. Pope garnered his three largest Washington commissions during
Roosevelt's first and second terms.
</P>
<P>
   Of these, Bedford agrees with the oft-stated view that the
Jefferson Memorial, however splendidly sited, is rather badly
proportioned. But Jefferson the architect is a tough hero to honor
in an architectural statement. Who could imagine writing a play to
honor Shakespeare? Bedford, who is an architect, is strangely
kinder to Pope's National Archives, which has problems of scale
even greater than the memorial's -- its Corinthian main portico
gratuitously tacked onto its hulking mass.
</P>
<P>
   Bedford supports the critical consensus that the National
Gallery of Art, however conservative, is almost perfectly
conceived, with its great stretches of unpunctured walls deftly
articulated by strong Ionic porticos and a beautifully proportioned
dome. Though arguably the ``wrong thing done well,'' it somehow
transcends its neo-classical packaging with continuing lessons in
the power of geometry. It comfortably embraces I. M. Pei's
successfully modernist East Wing addition of the 70's, while it is
ironically best viewed from the gunnery slot of Gordon Bunshaft's
less successful Hirshhorn Museum across the Mall.
</P>
<P>
   However one may view Pope's neo-classical temples -- as
appropriate or regressive 20th-century statements -- the story
surrounding their conspicuous presence is one that deserves
historical attention. While this book achieves a partial success as
a presentation of Pope's architecture, it fails to probe his work's
complex significance in American cultural and architectural
history.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Thomas S. Hines is a professor of history and architecture at
the University of California, Los Angeles, and the author of the
forthcoming ``Irving Gill and the Architecture of Reform.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
