<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CAMPUS-SECURITY-UNIVERSITIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURING THE CAMPUSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Colleges throughout the country are taking different approaches
to campus security. While all of them feel the effects of increased
concern on the part of parents and students, not all of them are
approaching the solution in the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sampling of how a few universities and colleges handle
security. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Cornell University, in a rural location, simply distributes
metal keys to the front doors of dorms. Electronic locks are used
only in some situations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Stanford University uses a diverse system of key locks for the
more than 200 buildings. Rodger Whitney, director of student
housing at Stanford, said the University has had few problems with
the current key system but may adopt an electronic system like
Princeton's as it rolls more and more functions into one plastic
card that now pays for photocopying, laundry and other campus
needs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ The University of Chicago has staff members sitting at the
front desk of each dorm. ``The standard practice in our residence
halls _ by the way, I live in one of them _ is to have a front desk
operation that is staffed 24 hours a day when school is in
service,'' said Ed Turkington, dean of student services at the
university. ``They serve a number of functions including
controlling access. Those who are full-time employees who are on a
regular shift get to know folks. They can begin to more easily
assess who is normally going through these doors and who is not.
That helps a lot to establish that kind of personal relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkington said the university is considering adding access
functions to its campuswide ID card but is hesitant about keeping
records of student's movement. ``That's one I would want to think
very hard about,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Yale University, in the urban environment of downtown New
Haven, uses an electronic pass system similar to Princeton's and it
keeps a record.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ At Hood College in Frederick, Md., Timothy Duff, director of
public safety, said there is an electronic entry system at the
dorms that records each student's entry and exit. Still, he said,
the information is rarely used because students often come through
the doors in pairs. The college does not back up the records. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Harvard University uses a variety of different card systems
throughout its dorms. All of the undergraduate dormitories, known
as houses, use the same system, but some of the graduate
dormitories use a different system.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Bradner, a network security manager, said: ``Harvard in
general has been quite paranoid about private information. The
faculty has been very careful.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
