<HEADER>
A5454 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-LAND-NYTSF     11-11 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-LAND-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS LAND IS YOUR LAND
</HEADLINE>
  Words and music by Woody Guthrie 
 Illustrated by Kathy Jakobsen 
 Unpaged. Boston: Little, Brown &AMP; Company. $15.95. (All ages) 
 WHEN I FIRST CAME TO THIS LAND 
 Retold by Harriet Ziefert 
 Illustrated by Simms Taback 
 Unpaged. New York: G. P. Putnam's Sons. $15.99. (Ages 4 to 8) 
 ------ 
 OF THEE I SING 
 By KATHLEEN KRULL 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The song ``This Land Is Your Land'' percolates so ubiquitously
as an unofficial national anthem that many assume it's in the
public domain, instead of a tune and lyrics Woody Guthrie wrote in
the winter of 1940 while hitchhiking around post-Depression
America. Have you ever recited the lyrics without singing them?
It's an engaging experiment in hearing how yeasty with meaning they
remain. It can be tricky to get through them without your eyes
welling up.
</P>
<P>
   This land is your land, this land is my land,
</P>
<P>
   From California to the New York island;
</P>
<P>
   From the redwood forest to the Gulf Stream waters,
</P>
<P>
   This land was made for you and me.
</P>
<P>
   Though they would mightily challenge an artist, you can tell
they could work as a powerful text for a picture book.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 60 years later, the noted folk artist Kathy Jakobsen has
taken the dare. She has coaxed pictures out of the many directions
suggested by the song, achieving what is almost a visual
deconstruction. In complicated oil paintings, with borders
influenced by the tramp art of the early 1900's, she depicts the
complete lyrics -- yes, even the sometimes censored ``subversive''
verses, including
</P>
<P>
   As I went walking, I saw a sign there,
</P>
<P>
   And on the sign it said ``No Trespassing.''
</P>
<P>
   But on the other side it didn't say nothing;
</P>
<P>
   That side was made for you and me.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the song's history, a broad selection of quotations
from other Guthrie lyrics and writings, a biography and information
about his music and its enormous influence on others.The book also
includes homages to iconic attractions offered by all 50 states and
musical notation (with guitar chords), as well as a tribute by Pete
Seeger (in which he admits that he didn't think much of the song at
first).
</P>
<P>
   In a work of just 32 pages, you'd think everything would be in
miniature, and most of it is. The book is accurately advertised as
suitable for all ages, but some of us will need our bifocals.
Breaking up the complex pages that carry the text of the chorus and
require some close visual attention are more dramatic spreads with
the verses. The images sweep the landscape, as a tiny Guthrie
travels ``from California to the New York island.''
</P>
<P>
   The horizontal format helps convey the deserts and valleys,
redwood forests, city skylines, majestic mountains, seedy
neighborhoods undergoing transformation and even the wheat fields
threatened by a frightening dust storm. Crammed into a three-page
fold-out panorama at the end, in the same meticulous folk art
style, is just about every kind of singing group America has to
offer -- from children training their dogs to sing, to a civil
rights march led by the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   This is an ambitious tribute to a popular song that will live as
long as the American spirit. Besides reminding children from all
backgrounds that America is indeed their land, it will acquaint
them with a key figure in American popular culture and may help
them start to wonder about topics in geography and history.
Families can decipher the tiny pictures together (hint: the more
you already know about Guthrie, the easier this will be), and
creative teachers will have a ball.
</P>
<P>
   Definitely for a younger audience is another tuneful ode to
American soil displayed in horizontal picture format: ``When I
First Came to This Land.'' A new immigrant, who looks to be from
Ireland, arrives with nothing but muscles. Scrambling to make a
life, he acquires a farm (called Muscle-in-My-Arm), a horse (called
I'm-the-Boss) and so on, until the happy days of getting a wife
(Spice-of-My-Life) and son (So-Much-Fun). Humor and rhythm dominate
here, and Simms Taback, a Caldecott Honor winner this year for his
wild and crazy rendition of ``There Was an Old Lady Who Swallowed a
Fly,'' propels the cumulative verse into a book children will want
to gather around. Cheerful yellow frames surround bold figures
against apricot backgrounds, punctuated by actual stamps, ticket
stubs, photographs of vegetation and newspaper clippings.
Everything floats in Marc Chagallian disarray, with the utter lack
of white space creating an extra-lively pulse.
</P>
<P>
   This version is in no way a scholarly tome, but musical notation
for the song would have been nice, as well as a more extensive
source note than ``brought to Pennsylvania over a century ago by a
German immigrant.'' (For example, at least three of the sources I
checked list the song as written in 1948 by the Canadian folk
singer Oscar Brand.) Preschoolers won't care -- they'll be shouting
along a la ``Old MacDonald Had a Farm,'' another verse that turns
verbal playfulness into a party.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Krull collected American folk songs into ``Gonna Sing
My Head Off!'' Her most recent book is ``Lives of the Presidents:
Fame, Shame (and What the Neighbors Thought).''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
