A5455 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-COST-1000&AMP;ADD     11-11 1589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-COST-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT ANY COST
</HEADLINE>
  Jack Welch, General Electric, and the Pursuit of Profit 
 By Thomas F. O'Boyle 
 Illustrated. 449 pp. New York: Alfred A. Knopf. $29.95 
 ------ 
 A LONG WAY FROM THE LIGHT BULB 
 By ROGER LOWENSTEIN 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thomas F. O'Boyle attempts not merely to condemn Jack Welch,
chairman of General Electric and one of the country's most admired
businessmen, but to banish him into darkest exile. Rather than the
stunningly successful executive we thought we knew, O'Boyle's ``At
Any Cost'' presents a thin-skinned monarch who has destroyed a
company and a culture in the pursuit of short-term profit.
According to O'Boyle, an assistant managing editor of The
Pittsburgh Post-Gazette and a former reporter for The Wall Street
Journal, Welch has increased profits but sold the company's soul.
</P>
<P>
   At the old G.E., a company that Thomas Edison, among others,
founded, ``progress'' was the ``most important product.'' The
company truly did stand for the good things, or at least the good
products, in American life (the ``all-electric home'' of its
pitchman, Ronald Reagan, circa 1954, was featured in company
advertisements). Workers were treated with care, and money was
lavished on research. At Jack Welch's G.E., the company spends less
money on its research laboratory ($1.5 billion in 1997) than its
NBC subsidiary spent to broadcast pro basketball ($1.75 billion).
Quality has slipped; workers are laid off without a moment's
thought; and traditional, nuts-and-bolts businesses like making
toasters have been jettisoned or now play second fiddle to finance.
Worst of all, the thirst for immediate profit has fostered dubious
accounting practices and a series of business and ethical mishaps.
</P>
<P>
   O'Boyle's muckraking is impressive, and so is the list of G.E.'s
embarrassments, running the gamut from fraud in defense contracts
to a bond-trading scandal to a sometimes careless approach to
nuclear safety. In refrigerators and again in jet engines,
designers were forced to meet unrealistic deadlines, resulting in
costly product failures. One G.E. employee involved in PCB
reclamation was told by his supervisors that the toxic chemicals
were ``no worse than a teaspoon of salt''; then lesions broke out
on his face, forearms, thighs and the bottoms of his feet.
Moreover, according to O'Boyle, whenever a whistle-blower has
surfaced, G.E. has tried to destroy him. This account would be more
convincing, however, if O'Boyle had displayed equal resolve at
getting both sides of the story. Generally, he doesn't. O'Boyle
seems more interested in depicting Welch and G.E. as actors in a
``vast American morality play'' in which the chief villain is the
short-term fixation of American business.
</P>
<P>
   O'Boyle is nostalgic for a time when G.E. was loyal to its
employees and towns, but it's not just G.E. that has changed -- the
world has. And contrary to the author's suggestion, G.E. is not to
blame for America's trade deficit or for its loss of manufacturing
jobs. It almost feels as if O'Boyle has written the wrong book --
blaming G.E. when his real target is the alienated quality of
modern America. Moreover, the transformation of companies like G.E.
is hardly an unmitigated evil. This is one lesson of the crisis in
Asia, where the profit motive was not wholly embraced. Society
functions better -- not perfectly, but better -- when companies
pursue selfish rewards in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   O'Boyle speaks of ``the price that we have paid'' for the fact
that G.E. now does more business with fewer workers. But he has it
exactly wrong. America has reaped a huge dividend: the added goods
and services that G.E.'s former workers contribute in other lines
of work.
</P>
<P>
   O'Boyle also complains that Welch distanced himself from ``the
human consequences'' of his cost-cutting policies, and that may be
so. However, we are rarely shown the human side of Welch. We learn
that his deeply religious Roman Catholic mother instilled ambition
and self-confidence in him, and that his quiet father, a train
conductor, had little influence on him. As an adolescent in Salem,
Mass., Welch was acutely conscious of having his nose ``pressed
against the glass,'' and he wrote in his high school literary
magazine that he yearned ``to make a million.'' He was captain of
the high school hockey team, and his brash, confrontational style
would set the tone for later. After earning a Ph.D. in chemical
engineering at the University of Illinois, he joined the plastics
division of G.E. in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Welch was so aggressive that he quit playing weekend softball
because his co-workers resented him. Yet what he lacked in polish
(he stammered and swore ``like a longshoreman'') he made up for in
drive, and in 1981, after campaigning on a plank to trim G.E.'s
bureaucracy, he was elevated to chief executive officer. Rather
than applaud this Horatio Alger story, O'Boyle demeans his subject
as someone who meets what he says is Samuel Johnson's definition of
the well-balanced Irishman -- ``a man with chips on both
shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   As the book progresses, Welch, the presumed architect of G.E.'s
profit-hungry spirit, is usually in the background, rarely center
stage. O'Boyle fills in the blanks with hearsay and occasional
slurs. For instance, after devoting a paragraph to Welch's
successful turnaround of NBC, he adds that underlings
``speculated'' that the real reason he had hung on to NBC was that
he liked ``hobnobbing with the stars.'' Who wouldn't?
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, after discussing the locker room style of the
``boys'' in the plastics division, O'Boyle quotes a woman who was
hired in plastics long after Welch had left. She says that the men
seemed to feel that ungentlemanly behavior (including making crude
advances) was acceptable ``because of the stories that circulated
-- but were never verified -- about Welch's past exploits when he
had been at plastics.'' If you're going to call a guy a sleaze, at
least prove it.
</P>
<P>
   O'Boyle tells us in an author's note that despite having made a
``serious effort,'' he failed to gain access to Welch, among other
targets. Then, as if to acknowledge that he expects his objectivity
to come under attack, he adds, ``Regardless . . . I have done
everything in my power to write a balanced and fair account.'' But
this is precisely what O'Boyle has not done.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, with regard to G.E.'s financial services business,
O'Boyle retells the story of Joseph Jett, a rogue bond trader who
caused a scandal at G.E.'s former Kidder Peabody unit. His
suggestion that Kidder's (and G.E.'s) obsession with the bottom
line fostered unholy temptations is, I think, fair. But nowhere
does O'Boyle address what Welch might, perchance, have done that
was right in financial services. And these services -- lending,
leasing, insurance and so forth -- happen to be Welch's crowning
success.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-COST-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: crowning success.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How did G.E. escape so much of the reckless lending that has led
to huge losses at virtually every other house of credit? How did it
become, in effect, the country's most successful bank -- without
getting burned by Orange County, Russia or Donald Trump? O'Boyle
doesn't provide the answer; what is worse, he doesn't pose the
question. Even the fact that G.E.'s finance business has grown
astronomically -- from 8 percent of total profit to 40 percent --
is presented to bolster the negative point that G.E. has
de-emphasized manufacturing, which O'Boyle feels is a superior
calling.
</P>
<P>
   More improbably, O'Boyle ignores Welch's skill at managing an
empire that stretches from light bulbs to superabrasives. Over and
over, we see Welch creating a ``tyranny of numbers'' that
encourages an overly ambitious corporate culture. But it ought to
matter -- just a teeny bit -- that the culture prospered, and did
so despite the prevailing wisdom that conglomerates were too
unwieldy. Indeed, Welch may be remembered most for managing G.E.
successfully in an era when giants like ITT, Westinghouse and AT&AMP;T
were being dismembered. We get a hint of his style when Welch
declares that broadcasting, far from being unique, ``is exactly the
same as the securities business.'' But what similarities does Welch
see? The point is never developed.
</P>
<P>
   The examples of bad business practices that form the heart of
this book are often disturbing and sometimes shocking, but they do
not add up to a total picture of G.E. or of Welch, who has presided
over a phenomenal and sustained increase in earnings. Therefore,
``At Any Cost'' is fatally out of focus from the very start.
O'Boyle begins his tale with an anecdote about a potential deal in
Japan that fell through because of Welch's impatience and disregard
for Japanese protocol. The story is engrossing, but is it
representative?
</P>
<P>
   Welch elevated G.E. from the 11th most valuable American
corporation to the first, and presided over a stock market gain of
1,155 percent in 16 years. That didn't happen only because Neutron
Jack was blowing deals. Once in a while he must have done something
right.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Roger Lowenstein, the author of ``Buffett: The Making of an
American Capitalist,'' is working on a book about the hedge fund
Long-Term Capital Management.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
