<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5456 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-TRUTH-NYTSF     11-11 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-TRUTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUTH COMES IN BLOWS
</HEADLINE>
  A Memoir 
 By Ted Solotaroff 
 Illustrated. 285 pp. New York: W. W. Norton &AMP; Company. $23.95 
 ------ 
 THE EMPEROR OF PLATE GLASS 
 By DAVID MARGOLICK 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to his son, whenever Ben Solotaroff was enjoying
himself, he'd draw his fingers across his lips. When something made
him sad, he'd rub his glasses on his shirttail. He spoke in a
peculiarly portentous tone when he gave someone the lowdown, in a
temporarily (and unconvincingly) gentle tone when he wanted
something. And he had his pet expressions: ``The best is good
enough for me'' or ``I know how to make an impression'' or, when he
wanted to keep you dangling, ``At the proper time.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no one has keener powers of observation than a child.
And perhaps no child notices or remembers more than one whose quest
for parental love and respect goes unrequited. All this is made
clear by Ted Solotaroff's elegant memoir of his New Jersey
childhood in the days before World War II. For all its pain and
sadness, ``Truth Comes in Blows'' is as touching as gratitude and
forgiveness, as exhilarating as truth. It reveals both the
components that help make an artist _ the loneliness, lack of
approval, sense of differentness _ and the fruits of that art.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, this is a book about a father and a son. By all accounts
(not just his son's) Ben Solotaroff, emperor of the Standard Plate
Glass Company of Elizabeth, N.J., was an astonishingly selfish and
heartless man, someone who sapped the spirit out of those closest
to him. If truth really does come in blows _ the thought comes from
Saul Bellow's ``Henderson the Rain King'' _ so, too, does
humiliation. Yet long after his death, the elder Solotaroff exerts
a powerful hold. Whenever Ted Solotaroff, an editor and critic,
sits at his desk, a tool from his father's trade _ a glass cutter _
is nestled among the pens and pencils of his own.
</P>
<P>
   During the early years of her marriage, Rose Solotaroff, the
wife and mother of the story, liked to sit at the piano and play
Schumann's haunting ``Traumerei,'' a piece that conjures up an
innocent, irretrievable past. There were few such times in the
Solotaroff household. Ben and Rose were, as one family friend put
it, ``ideally unsuited'' for each other; Rose was undisciplined,
sensitive, artistic; Ben was, as someone once called him, a ``deep
brute.'' They fought constantly, with Ben wasting no opportunity to
belittle or stifle his wife. He reduced her to an allowance of a
dollar a day for household expenses (forcing her to steal money
each week for her daughter's piano lessons), aggravated her
arthritis by forcing her to work in his unheated store, regularly
hurled horrifying imprecations at her. ``You make me feel like
going down into the cellar with some rat poison and never having to
see your stupid face again'' was but one.
</P>
<P>
   His father's cruelty forced Ted Solotaroff, even as a young boy,
to play husband to his mother. ``As soon as I'd hear his car start,
I'd get up from my bowl of Ralston, run to her, and put my hands on
her eyes, which in a minute or two would make her stop crying, and
then stroke her hair,''he writes. ``Smiling, she would pull me to
her, gaze at me, and say 'What would I do without you?' '' And yet,
as he realized whenever he was condescending or impatient with his
mother, Solotaroff was also very much his father's son _ ``Little
Benny,'' they called him.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the young Solotaroff was spared. Father viewed son, in
the Yiddish idiom of this book, as a luftmensch, someone with his
head in the clouds, destined to suffer, and properly, for his
softness. Petty infractions provoked beatings and threats to
``break your spirit for good.'' Ben Solotaroff discouraged his son
from playing sports, yanked him out of a school play, refused to
pay for his bar mitzvah. The undernourishment wasn't only
figurative. ``He would take the tender part of the steak, the
breast of the chicken, and then push the platter to Mom,''
Solotaroff writes. '' 'Eat bread, kids,' he'd say. 'Don't fill up
on meat.' '' He threatened to kill his son, his wife and himself if
Ted interfered in the stingy divorce settlement he planned to offer
Rose. Age often confers cuteness, but even as a wizened old man Ben
remained uniquely misanthropic.
</P>
<P>
   At times, the book reads like ``Long Day's Journey Into Night''
without the foghorn. Like James Tyrone, the character O'Neill
modeled after his own father, Ben Solotaroff is a cheapskate; when
young Solotaroff breaks his nose, his father refuses to take him to
a doctor. Small wonder, then, that when, shortly before his death,
his elderly father asks him for a massage _ to knead the once
ferocious arms and shoulders _ his son recoils at the thought.
</P>
<P>
   But massage him he does. Solotaroff struggles, as O'Neill did,
to understand and forgive, delving into his father's loveless,
hardscrabble childhood. ``He wasn't only domineering and oblivious
and not to be trusted, he was also unhappy, and unhappiness went a
long way with me,'' he writes of one childhood revelation. ``It was
what I was most at home with and understood.'' He credits his
father with his drive to succeed, if only to prove his old man
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   So powerful a presence is the father that ``Truth Comes in
Blows'' drags a bit when he's offstage. This could be a problem,
because so many of Solotaroff's themes are a memoirist's staples:
the sensitive Jewish boy struggling for self-awareness and
independence; the awkward sexual initiation (her name was Honey
Abrams); the neighborhood Irish toughs and high school Aryan
athletes; the anti-Semitism of both low-lifes and Ivy Leaguers;
love for baseball, especially the Brooklyn Dodgers; and crossing
the river (though he is coming from New Jersey, not the usual
Brooklyn) to civilization.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, though, some other vivid personality keeps up
the pace. This book is a powerful reminder of how people live on
through their deeds. Aunt Fan taught him about urban sophistication
and metaphors. Uncle Adrian _ ne Abe, the gay dentist, raconteur
and Upper West Side boulevardier _ turned him on to Charles Beard
and Karl Marx. A busboy named Herb Brichto at the summer beach
hotel told him about oxymorons and J. Alfred Prufrock. Then there
are those finely turned phrases _ for instance, one about a
delinquent school chum: ``The English he was learning to use
resourcefully was on a cue ball.'' Solotaroff devotes his English
to a higher calling, and we're all the beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   David Margolick is a contributing editor at Vanity Fair.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
