<HEADER>
A5457 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-SQUIDS-NYTSF     11-11 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-SQUIDS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SQUIDS WILL BE SQUIDS
</HEADLINE>
  Fresh Morals, Beastly Fables 
 By Jon Scieszka 
 Illustrated by Lane Smith, designed by Molly Leach 
 Unpaged. New York: Viking. $17.99. (Ages 8 and up) 
 ------ 
 'DON'T EVER LISTEN TO A TALKING BUG' 
 By PATRICIA MARX 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you want to write a blockbuster for the preschool crowd, your
book should feature a fluffy bunny who comes from a two-parent
family and talks about how nice it is in the neighborhood when
everyone smiles. If your audience is older, say 7 and up, the bunny
should not only talk, he should also work the words ``butt'' and
``doofus'' into the story and make reference to flatulence.
``Squids Will Be Squids'' does all of the above, minus the bunny.
And children love it. I know because I read the book to a bunch of
them, ranging in age from 4 to 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``Squids'' is a funny collection of warped fables, with morals
like ``It takes one to know one,'' ``Don't ever listen to a talking
bug'' and ``You should always tell the truth. But if your mom is
out having the hair taken off her lip, you might want to forget a
few of the details.'' (The last raises questions you may want to
leave unraised if you are a squeamish parent of a small child.) The
characters include a grasshopper who doesn't do his homework, a
duck-billed platypus who brags, a frog who can't skateboard, a
manipulative pigeon, an indiscreet little walrus, a cheeky piece of
toast, a stuck-up Beef Snak Stik, a bossy book of matches and, of
course, a squid (who's a bit of a drip).
</P>
<P>
   Like some of Jon Scieszka and Lane Smith's other picture books,
it sends up the genre it imitates. In ``The Stinky Cheese Man: And
Other Fairly Stupid Tales'' (1992), for example, the ugly duckling
grows up and turns out to be just a really ugly duck. In ``The Math
Curse'' (1995), the world becomes a nightmarish place where every
situation is a verbal math problem (definitely the book to read to
your children if you are in the mood to reminisce about your math
S.A.T.'s). In my favorite, ``The True Story of the Three Little
Pigs'' (1989), the much-maligned Big Bad Wolf tells his side of the
story so persuasively that you may wish President Clinton had used
him as his lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   In the introduction to ``Squids Will Be Squids,'' Aesop is
referred to as a ``funny-shaped'' or ``ugly'' guy who told stories
about people but called them animals so he could be snide. Scieszka
aims to follow in this gossipy tradition, offering ``fables that
Aesop might have told if he were alive today and sitting in the
back of class daydreaming.''
</P>
<P>
   As with all successful parodies, though, the reader does not
need to know the original to appreciate the caricature. In fact, a
few youngsters I talked to had no idea what a fable was -- ``Is it
like a fib?'' -- but enjoyed the book nevertheless. ``This book's
the best. Really cool and hilarious,'' a 6-year-old told me. ``Kids
almost 7 and up will love it.'' I asked him what it was about.
``Not a clue!'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Why do children like this book so much even when it is not
always within their understanding? Here's why, I think: Without
knowing exactly what ``Squids Will Be Squids'' is making fun of,
they know for sure it is making fun of something. The irreverent
tone and the wise-guy vocabulary signal that it is a subversive
book -- a book that a child thinks his parents might not like,
which is a draw for anyone getting ready for the age of rebellion,
or at least staying up until ``Saturday Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   Lane Smith's illustrations are ugly in a good way -- kooky,
dark, not lush. The art suggests ``My First Book of Surrealism'' or
``Dada for the Goo-Goo Set.'' Molly Leach, who is credited with the
book's design, uses a variety of typefaces and sizes in the text,
changing them throughout the book for no reason I could detect.
However, every child I spoke to found such craziness appealing,
perhaps because it is so similar to computer graphics. They like
``Squids Will Be Squids'' for not talking down to them. That and
the fact that the slug gets flattened by a steamroller.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, an adult (and for the sake of this review, I will
consider myself one) will regard this book as more silly than
seditious. While I was initially put off by what I felt was forced
outrageousness, I came to admire the sustained spirit of impiety.
So many children's books carefully transform the wayward character
into a goody-goody who finally eats his spinach, shares his toys or
smiles in the neighborhood. I am grateful for a book that does not.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Marx, the author of ``Meet My Staff,'' also writes
frequently for television and magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
