<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-BIBLE-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HIDDEN BOOK IN THE BIBLE
</HEADLINE>
  Restored, translated and introduced by Richard Elliott Friedman 
 402 pp. San Francisco: HarperSanFrancisco. $25 
 ------ 
 THE GENIUS OF J 
 By ROBERT ALTER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Richard Elliott Friedman is that rare biblical scholar who is
both able to address a broad audience and willing to raise large
speculative issues about the Bible. His ``Who Wrote the Bible?''
elicited wide interest. In ``The Hidden Face of God'' he made a
vigorous theological argument that the Bible's representation of
God moved progressively from anthropomorphism to abstraction, and
that this process of transcendent abstraction was then projected
forward in intellectual history all the way to Nietzsche and modern
physics. Now, in his new book, he proposes that we can detect in
the Bible, hidden amid the accretions and superimposed
book-divisions of later editors, the earliest long prose masterwork
in world literature, running from the creation story to the death
of David.
</P>
<P>
   He builds on the ``documentary hypothesis'' accepted by most
biblical scholars since the 19th century, but tilts it in a
surprising direction. According to the documentary hypothesis --
which Friedman lucidly explained in ``Who Wrote the Bible?'' -- the
first five books of the Bible, the Torah or Pentateuch, were woven
out of four distinct literary strands or ``documents,''
conventionally designated J, E, P and D. J and E are generally
considered the oldest strands, and the extraordinary literary power
of J has often been admired. (In an appendix, Friedman makes a
trenchant case against certain recent scholars who have sought to
discard these textual divisions and to locate the composition of
the Torah in the Persian or Hellenistic period rather than in the
early centuries of the Davidic dynasty.) ``The Hidden Book in the
Bible'' proposes that J, far from being limited to Genesis, Exodus
and some brief passages in Numbers, is a long narrative work that
was the original core of the Bible, tracing a grand chronological
arc from creation to the death of Moses, through sections of Joshua
and Judges and most of the Book of Samuel to the beginning of
Kings. He makes this argument in an introductory essay, buttressed
by more technical analytical evidence in an appendix. In between
these two, in the bulk of the book, he presents his own translation
of what he conceives as a continuous J narrative, so that readers
can see its literary integrity.
</P>
<P>
   The English version offered here is not quite a freestanding
translation, for it is framed to make visible the verbal evidence
of literary unity. Even so, Friedman's emphatic literalism serves
the Hebrew original rather better than the efforts of most modern
translators to transform it into an everyday modern English
abounding in explanatory paraphrase. He aims for a simple,
rough-hewn diction -- ``big'' instead of ``great,'' ``bad'' instead
of ``evil'' -- and preserves the parallel syntax of the Hebrew. On
the whole, this strategy works well enough, although, coupled with
the literalism, it does produce some flat-footed effects: ``I'm
setting up bad against you from your house''; ``Israel saw the big
hand that YHWH had used''; ``two peoples will be separated from
your insides.'' As the last of these examples suggests, there are
moments when the translation is neither Hebrew idiom nor English:
``their heart was in a good mood''; ``vindicated the case of my
disgrace''; ``Israel acted beaten before them.''
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the compelling appeal of the book is the thesis,
not the translation. In my view, Friedman, who teaches Hebrew and
comparative literature at the University of California, San Diego,
has devised a challenging, exhilarating theory that will force
biblical scholars to rethink some basic assumptions, but he has not
made a conclusive case. His argument for a single long book written
by J is based on proposed unities of theme, motif and, above all,
language. Much of what he says about theme is extremely
interesting: the emphasis in these stories on sibling rivalry, from
Cain and Abel to the struggles among David's sons; the special
focus on sexual relationships, and on rape in particular; the
repeated concern with spies. Friedman can be impressively
resourceful in seeing connections, as when he notes that at the
beginning of the narrative, Gihon is named as one of the rivers
issuing from Eden, and at the end Solomon is anointed king near the
Gihon brook. Other connections seem more tenuous, such as the
proposal that covering the shivering old David with clothes echoes
the clothing God provides the naked Adam and Eve.
</P>
<P>
   The most powerful evidence Friedman marshals is linguistic. He
has put together a table of 50 terms that he claims are distinctive
to this body of material within the biblical corpus. Some of his
instances are statistically striking and will not be easily
dismissed by skeptics. Over half of his examples, however, are
statistically questionable, because if a term occurs only two or
three times altogether, its absence elsewhere may simply mean it is
rare; and cases where there are five occurrences in these texts and
two elsewhere are not convincing proof that a term is distinctive
of J.
</P>
<P>
   Is there, moreover, a single underlying viewpoint in these
texts? Genesis and Samuel are brilliant narratives with distinct
affinities, but in the former God walks the earth and looks like a
man, whereas in the latter He is almost entirely absent from the
human stage. Friedman invokes his thesis of the progressive
occultation of God from ``The Hidden Face of God'' to explain the
disparity, but it seems a bit implausible that a single author
would have shifted grounds so drastically. Friedman properly
celebrates the genius for characterization that created Jacob,
Joseph and David, but what happened to that genius in the books of
Joshua and Judges? And did the writer scandalized by Simeon and
Levi's massacre of Shechem switch moral sensibility in those
blandly approving reports of the massacre of whole populations in
Joshua? Friedman includes the ark narrative (I Samuel 4-7) in his
``Hidden Book'' because in Numbers J is particularly concerned with
the ark of the covenant. But scholarly consensus has concluded with
good reason that the ark narrative is quite different from the
surrounding story in style, theme and theology (it turns on
miracles, reduces human characters to ciphers, drops Samuel
altogether and does not presuppose monarchy).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-BIBLE-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: presuppose monarchy).) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The weakest point of the single-book thesis is its treatment of
literary allusion. Friedman scarcely allows for the possibility
that the author of the David story or other writers might have
known J's narrative of creation and the patriarchs and made
purposeful use of it. The only allusion envisaged is self-allusion.
Thus, Friedman cites the grisly story in Judges 19 of the concubine
gang-raped to death at Gibeah as evidence of a single author
because it quotes extensively, nearly verbatim, from the Sodom
story in Genesis. There, as in Judges, two strangers are taken in
as guests and the townsmen surround the house intending rape.
Literary precedent suggests that such elaborate recycling and
transformation of an antecedent model is more likely to be the work
of a later writer putting new spin on an old text than of a writer
repeating himself. (Consider the re-use in ``The Waste Land'' of
Shakespeare's evocation of Cleopatra, ``The Chair she sat in, like
a burnished throne. . . .'') The writer's point in Judges 19 is
that in his fallen, politically savage world there are no saving
angels, so this time similar circumstances end in bloody
catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   THE rape of Tamar (II Samuel 13) is a related use of allusion to
define thematic reversal. Amnon's words to his sister before the
rape, ``Clear out everyone around me'' (my translation), are the
very words Joseph pronounces before revealing himself to his
brothers. The dialogue between Amnon and Tamar as he pulls her into
his bed quotes the dialogue between Potiphar's wife and Joseph in
her unsuccessful sexual assault on him. Finally, we learn that
Tamar, like Joseph at the beginning of his story, is wearing a coat
of many colors. The Joseph story, then, has been invoked in reverse
chronological order to represent an act of fraternal violation
instead of fraternal reconciliation. Perhaps the same writer wrote
both stories, but it seems more likely that one writer was
purposefully transforming another's material.
</P>
<P>
   There are other unanswered questions. Occasionally, for example,
the David story alludes not to J but to E -- as when Michal's
deception of her father to enable David's escape (I Samuel 19)
explicitly invokes Rachel's deception of her father in hiding the
stolen household gods (Genesis 31). But whatever the unresolved
issues, Friedman has put forth a bold thesis that should give
everyone pause. Some of his arguments are strong enough to make
even a doubter wonder whether, after all, he might not be right.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Robert Alter's translation of the David story, accompanied by a
literary commentary, will be published next year.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
