</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-BACKYARD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUR OWN BACKYARD
</HEADLINE>
  The United States in Central America, 1977-1992 
 By William M. LeoGrande 
 773 pp. Chapel Hill: University of North Carolina Press. $39.95 
 ------ 
 DITHERING IN CENTRAL AMERICA 
 By THOMAS CAROTHERS 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Foremost among the new truisms about United States foreign
policy in the 1990's is that as a nation America lacks the clarity
of purpose of the cold war era. Whereas Americans were supposedly
once united around the task of containing Soviet Communism, they
are now, it is frequently lamented, bereft of any unifying external
mission.
</P>
<P>
   Yet one need look back no farther than to Washington's
involvement in Central America in the 1980's to recall that at
times during the cold war the United States was in fact deeply
divided about its world role. The Reagan Administration's strenuous
efforts to combat leftist rebels in El Salvador and a leftist
Government in Nicaragua provoked sharp splits not just within the
policy elite but among the public as well. The various flash points
of United States intervention in the 1990's _ like Bosnia, Haiti,
Iraq and Somalia _ have all provoked domestic debates about the
appropriate American role, but never of the same intensity and
duration as the old screaming matches over Central America.
</P>
<P>
   William M. LeoGrande, a professor of government at American
University, takes a long, retrospective look at this turbulent
topic in ``Our Own Backyard.'' Although he starts with the Carter
years and ends with the Bush Administration, his focus is very much
the Reagan period. And while his stated subject is Central America,
like the Reagan Administration itself he concentrates almost
exclusively on two countries, El Salvador and Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   LeoGrande asserts that the United States debate over Central
American policy was rooted in two contesting foreign policy visions
that emerged out of Vietnam. Liberals were wary of seeing the
Soviet hand in every third world conflict, or of using military
force and supporting repressive anti-Communists in the name of
democracy. Conservatives were steadfastly suspicious of Soviet
intentions, ready to intervene when necessary to ``hold the line''
and willing to live with politically flawed allies.
</P>
<P>
   For the entire decade of the 1980's Washington was consumed in
endless arguments over whether the leftist rebellions in Central
America were local fights or Soviet-Cuban provocations, whether
United States support for the Salvadoran military and the
Nicaraguan contras was morally defensible and whether the stated
goal of democracy was rhetorical or real. Despite these debates,
the post-Vietnam division over cold war policy was never really
healed. It was simply eclipsed by events, buried in the enthusiasm
over the fall of the Berlin wall and the breakup of the Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
   LeoGrande's copious study is generally skillful and accessible.
He takes the reader confidently through a complex, often tortuous
story, starting with the Carter Administration's paralyzing
uncertainty about how to respond to the fall of the Nicaraguan
President, Anastasio Somoza Debayle, through the bitter Washington
battles over human rights in El Salvador and aid to the Nicaraguan
contras, to the Iran-contra affair and ultimately the 1990
Nicaraguan elections that ended Sandinista rule. Throughout, the
analysis is thorough and clear.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the points LeoGrande scores are telling. The Reagan
Administration appears as either blind to or cynically dismissive
of the wrongs committed by the military forces it supported, prone
to ignoring or deceiving the American public and stubbornly opposed
to peace initiatives until the bitter end. The limited but real
achievements of Reagan's policy in the region came at a very high
price to many Central Americans, and to the United States' image in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its strengths, LeoGrande's book is unlikely to change
many minds. It is a comprehensive version of the standard liberal
critique, a critique already well developed in the 1980's. Although
not tendentious, it is also not especially challenging. The author
conveys little in-depth feel for the internal politics of El
Salvador or Nicaragua. His relentless Washington focus ironically
results in his analysis reproducing the same shortcoming for which
he rightly faults the Reagan policy _ projecting internal debates
onto a poorly lighted foreign screen.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, LeoGrande takes little advantage of the passage of
time to find a perspective outside the territory of past debates.
He is still incredulous over Reagan's simplistic world view and
Oliver North's illicit schemes. The book is more a continuation of
the old arguments than a rethinking or reformulation of the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, LeoGrande fails to bolster the perennial weak spot of
the liberal critique _ the question of alternatives. Given that
supporting the Salvadoran military and the Nicaraguan contras put
us in a moral morass, what other possibilities were there? Should
the United States have simply lived with a leftist regime in
Nicaragua and the probable emergence of one in El Salvador? If so,
what would this have meant for those countries, the region and
United States policy elsewhere? His only hint of an answer is the
unconvincing assertion that Carter's policy toward the Sandinistas
was ``both realistic and successful, as far as it went.'' Yet by
mid-1980, United States-Nicaraguan relations were already on a path
toward confrontation over Sandinista support for the Salvadoran
rebels. Even less credible is LeoGrande's suggestion that the
radicalization of the Sandinistas was due to the Reagan hard-line
policy. Not all Central American dictators were United States-made.
</P>
<P>
   If not willing to live with leftist regimes in Central America,
how could the United States have prevented the Salvadoran rebels
from coming to power and the Sandinistas from consolidating
dictatorial rule without aiding dubious military forces? There may
be answers to this question, but they are not in LeoGrande's book.
He suggests in passing that the United States could have brokered a
peace in El Salvador in the early 1980's, but he presents no
evidence that the rebels and the Government were anywhere near
being ready to live with each other at that stage.
</P>
<P>
   By not facing head on the truly difficult predicaments presented
by Central America, LeoGrande leaves the old debate unresolved.
Even as the cold war recedes into history, it seems likely that, as
with Vietnam, the past disagreements about Central America will not
soon be replaced by any common understanding.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Carothers is vice president for global policy at the
Carnegie Endowment for International Peace. His latest book,
``Aiding Democracy Abroad: The Learning Curve,'' will be published
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
