<HEADER>
A5463 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-EUROPA-NYTSF     11-11 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-EUROPA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPA
</HEADLINE>
  By Tim Parks 
 262 pp. New York: Arcade Publishing. $23.95 
 ------ 
 IT'S ACADEMIC 
 By DAVID GATES 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No matter what they say in those catchpenny fiction-writing
manuals, a novelist can get away with a protagonist who's a bore, a
blowhard, a pill. Roth and Updike do it all the time; we sit still
for their often wrongheaded heroes because now and then their
creators vouchsafe us a wink or a roll of the eyes. In Tim Parks's
ninth novel, ``Europa,'' we keep waiting for some sign that he
doesn't take his narrator, Jerry Marlow, as seriously as Marlow
takes himself. Marlow shares with us at great length on such topics
as political correctness and the blandness of contemporary European
culture; he delivers such brow-smiting apercus as ``The condition
we live in is one of intimacy and distance.'' But as page after
page goes by and Parks still hasn't slapped him down, it becomes
dishearteningly clear that Marlow's fusty heterodoxy is supposed to
make him a significant figure.
</P>
<P>
   Marlow, an expatriate Brit, teaches at a university in Milan;
he's one of those academic sweat hogs novelists love to use as
their literary stunt doubles. His midlife love affair with a
colleague broke up his marriage; now his mistress's infidelity has
broken up the affair, but he's still obsessed. He and the beloved
aren't on speaking terms, and they've both joined a delegation of
faculty members and chummy students on a bus to Strasbourg, where
the teachers will lobby the European Parliament to save their jobs.
Marlow delivers an address and declines an opportunity to bed the
beloved for old times' sake; aside from that, Parks doesn't give
him a lot to do, and devotes much of the book to flashbacks and
inner bloviation.
</P>
<P>
   What energy there is comes from Marlow's doppelganger, Vikram
Griffiths, a borderline-probable Indo-Welshman who steals scenes by
default. True, he's less a character than a mix-and-match
assemblage of eccentricities, but he's easier to swallow than
Marlow's beloved, a Frenchwoman who combines naughty expertise in
the boudoir (but of course!) with high-end pedantry: ``So we read
Chateaubriand and Benjamin Constant and the Duchesse d'Abrantes and
Michelet, which had been her special area of study, and we read
Xenophon and Thucydides and Plato and Aristophanes, which had been
my area of study, and we discussed them together, usually after
making love.''
</P>
<P>
   For Marlow, the quixotic defender of boundaries (whether
political, intellectual, interpersonal or sexual), she's a wet
dream. For the reader, though, she's a cipher. We get the sinking
feeling that she's somehow to be identified with the mythic Europa
_ there's no other visible reason for the title _ presumably
because she has a complex of supposedly ``European'' attributes:
sensuality, intellectuality, moral fluidity. Parks withholds her
actual name until the last lines of the book. This device seems
intended to set her apart, but the effect is to render her even
more distant.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Parks doesn't have his head on straight: he hates
trendy blather and values the sovereign individual above the
tyrannical group. (Who doesn't?) It's just that he tends to forget
he's writing a novel. Early on, he shoots for the Woolfian sublime,
in which layers of perception, memory and cognition interpenetrate
in an instant of consciousness: ``How remarkable . . . that while
listening to Vikram Griffiths . . . and while observing Doris Rohr
. . . trying to find the space between one seat and the next to
cross her thick legs . . . how remarkable that while taking all
this in, and at the same time allowing once again the complex
misery triggered, absurdly, by the name Napoleon to explode in your
mind, you are nevertheless still able to marvel at the
extraordinariness of a brain that can do all this at once.''
</P>
<P>
   But as ``Europa'' wears on, Parks settles for punctuating
Marlow's internal filibuster with a periodic ``I thought'' _ or, if
he's especially conscience-stricken about the neglected narrative,
something along the lines of ``. . . I thought, watching the young
man flap his duster across the plastic surface.'' Parks may be an
old pro, but this is amateur stuff. All the fiction-writing manuals
warn against such self-indulgence, but it's still a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   David Gates' most recent book is a novel, ``Preston Falls.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
