<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5465 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-FICTION-BRIEF     11-11 1447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-FICTION-BRIEFS-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNING JAPANESE
</HEADLINE>
  By David Galef 
 Permanent Press, paper, $16  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his second novel, TURNING JAPANESE (Permanent Press, paper,
$16), David Galef captures the allure and peril of living as an
expatriate. And through the eyes of his young narrator, a
22-year-old aspiring writer named Cricket Collins, we see the
experience not just for Cricket and his fellow Americans but also
for those Britons and Australians who join them as English teachers
in Japan, flocking to the Orient in search of an alternative to the
traditional European adventure. It is the late 1970's, when life in
Japan is particularly enticing to an aimless recent college
graduate, and Cricket and his peers find the elegant beauty of the
tea ceremony, the calming discipline of Aikido and the politeness
of the Japanese people to be both alien and irresistible. But Galef
adds a layer of complexity to this account of Cricket's adventures,
revealing the vulnerability that may result from too rapid an
effort to shed one's own cultural skin. When Cricket hooks up with
a Japanese girlfriend, he hopes their relationship will increase
his sense of well-being, making him feel more firmly established in
her country. Not surprisingly, and much to his chagrin, his
contentment is brief -- and is followed by a breakdown that leaves
him weakened and shamed. In the months that follow, as Cricket must
choose between returning to a homeland where he no longer truly
feels at home and remaining in a place where he may never be truly
accepted, Galef produces a chilling denouement for this nicely
detailed exploration of cultural dislocation. _ PAULA FRIEDMAN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JOSANIE'S WAR &QL; 
 &UR; By Karl H. Schlesier &QL; 
 &UR; University of Oklahoma, $22.95 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the late spring of 1885, five bands of Chiricahua Apaches
decided to flee their reservation in Arizona, setting off the last
great Apache war. This novel follows the fortunes of one of these
groups, led by an Indian war captain named Josanie, as it struggles
against the combined military might of the United States and
Mexico. Brief alternating chapters present the action from both
sides, including incendiary news clippings, thus providing the
social context in which the tribe embarks on one last fight for its
land. But the anthropological detail by which Karl H. Schlesier
illustrates the Apaches' resourcefulness, spirituality and humanity
gets in the way of his storytelling. With little character
development, the individuals in his pages wind up being largely
indistinguishable; what's missing is fiction's imaginative leap
into feeling. ``Josanie's War'' is a readable and informative
re-creation of a tragic episode in the history of the American
West. Through its detailed documentation, it takes us into a harsh
world, showing how injustice and prejudice proved despicably,
needlessly destructive. But as a novel, it fails to explore the
internal war that must have gripped these warriors just as
fiercely. _ PETER BRICKLEBANK
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SAVAGE LIFE &QL; 
 &UR; By James Rogers &QL; 
 &UR; Serpent's Tail, paper, $12.99 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Set in London as the grasping '80s give way to the uncertain
'90s, bursting with foul language and fouler deeds, ``Savage Life''
follows the violent misadventures of Gaz Hoskins, an aspiring
burglar from the lower classes, and Colin Nutter, a rudderless life
insurance salesman with a tenuous grip on yuppiedom. What connects
these two sorry souls is the vile personage of Dorian Savage.
Misanthropic, immoral and rich, he's Colin's boss and personal
hero. Somehow, the hapless Gaz becomes convinced that Dorian is his
long-lost father and begins a plaintive quest for recognition that
sets in motion a train wreck of events. Three murders (and one
attempted murder) ensue, and no one comes to a good end by the
close of this aptly titled work. Full of vivid writing, the novel
brings to mind some of Martin Amis's dark comedies. Like Amis,
James Rogers has a talent for measuring the class divide and
bringing odious characters to life. Unfortunately, he skimps when
it comes to the central character of Colin, whose past history is
perfunctorily disgorged late in the novel. The book's weakest link,
Colin seems merely an alcohol-soaked nincompoop -- or is he
something more? If you're curious, ``Savage Life'' will keep you
reading to the bitter -- and I do mean bitter -- end. _ EILS LOTOZO
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLORA'S SUITCASE &QL; 
 &UR; By Dalia Rabinovich &QL; 
 &UR; Harper Flamingo, $23 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dalia Rabinovich's first novel tells the story of Flora and Dave
Grossenberg, a young Jewish couple who leave America for Colombia
in the 1930's, intent on starting a business with his extended
family. Told primarily from Flora's point of view, the novel traces
the couple's arduous journey and their trials and tribulations in
Medellin. Unfortunately, this basic plot is marred by bizarre
twists that are introduced with great fanfare only to vanish almost
immediately. Worse yet, Rabinovich plunges headlong into her own
brand of magic realism, in which physical characteristics are
erased by acts of nature and people can sleep for 10 days and
awaken with no memory of their previous lives or language. Despite
the exotic surroundings in which their story unfolds, the
characters in ``Flora's Suitcase'' have interior lives that remain,
for the most part, featureless and colorless, unknown to the
reader. _ BETSY GROBAN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-FICTION-BRIEFS-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: BETSY GROBAN) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NO SAFE PLACE &QL; 
 &UR; By Richard North Patterson &QL; 
 &UR; Knopf, $25.95 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A remarkable coincidence of bad luck for Bill Clinton and good
luck for Richard North Patterson has conferred topicality upon ``No
Safe Place,'' Patterson's torrid, breathlessly plotted novel about
a sexually compromised Presidential candidate and the female
journalist he loves. Kerry Kilcannon has risen from the boxing gyms
of Newark to the United States Senate. Though his older brother,
James, was killed while campaigning for the presidency, Kerry still
wants to pry the Democratic nomination away from the vapid Vice
President, Dick Mason. Unfortunately, Kilcannon harbors a secret --
a passionate affair with a reporter named Lara Costello that may
have resulted in an abortion. Patterson's vastly contrived plot
puts Lara into the press corps on the Kilcannon campaign, while
Sean Burke, a fanatical anti-abortion crusader, decides that
Kilcannon should die for his abortion rights views. Cutting rapidly
between Burke's determined stalking and the machinations of a
loathsome reporter who's out to reveal Kerry and Lara's liaison,
Patterson offers mawkish, rites-of-passage flashbacks, treating the
practice of politics as he does the law in his popular legal
thrillers. There, as lonely, well-intentioned professionals get
their fill of sex, sensationalism and scheming villains, love
conquers what it must and heroes always do the right thing. _ BILL
KENT
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A LIFE FOR A LIFE &QL; 
 &UR; By Ernest Hill &QL; 
 &UR; Simon &AMP; Schuster, $23 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Henry Earl visits a 15-year-old boy named D'Ray in his
prison cell, he whispers ``in a voice laced with a bone-chilling
calmness: 'Everything you took from me, you gonna give it back.'''
Despite this seeming threat, Ernest Hill's second novel, ``A Life
for a Life,'' isn't about revenge. Not much earlier, D'Ray had been
given another ultimatum by a ruthless dope dealer who was holding
D'Ray's 10-year-old brother, Little Man, hostage for $100 the older
boy owed him: ``You ain't back with my money in a hour, you can
tell your mama she got one less mouth to feed.'' Desperate, D'Ray
decided to rob a convenience store and in the process fatally shot
the store's young clerk. The murder confirmed what his mother and
the people around him always expected: ``It's just a matter of time
before he end up like World'' -- his father, a convicted murderer.
But Henry Earl, the dead clerk's father, has an agenda. Earl's son,
Stanley, was an honor student who won a National Merit Scholarship;
somehow, D'Ray will be made to fulfill some of that promise. And
so, through the years of D'Ray's incarceration, Henry Earl
faithfully visits him, hoping to inspire him to move forward. Hill
is a skilled storyteller, and though ``A Life for a Life'' is a
straightforward account of the conflicting forces that shape the
lives of young men like D'Ray, he keeps the reader in suspense.
Despite Henry Earl's iron determination, D'Ray's redemption is far
from a foregone conclusion. _ FRAN HANDMAN
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
