<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5489 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANANA-STICKERS-NYT &LR;      11-11 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANANA-STICKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BANANA AS BILLBOARD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Del., Calif.)   (bl)  
 By PHIL PATTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Look carefully at the bananas you bought yesterday:
we all know the Chiquita lady, but several million Dole bananas are
now selling something else. Little stickers tout the film ``Babe in
the City,'' the sequel to the popular children's movie, which opens
Nov. 20. On other Dole bunches you may find the familiar yellow
dots of ABC television's fall campaign. ``TV. Zero calories,'' one
slogan reads. Even more inevitable perhaps is the banana sticker,
produced with the California Milk Processor Board, that reads,
``Got milk?''
</P>
<P>
   No new inroad by the relentless machine of advertising and
marketing should surprise, I guess, even one into this little
crevice of the culture. But I've been thinking about produce
stickers for a while now, and how cleverly they already advertise
the fruit they label.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, I came across a peach label with pinstripes and
letters right off a baseball uniform that read simply, ``Peach.''
It was a tricky little message: baseball plus peach suggested the
Georgia Peach, Ty Cobb. The implication was that the peach was from
Georgia. In fact, it was a California product; the seal provided a
way to lie to the eye, or at least mislead.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of days before, I had heard a designer say that
``everything in the grocery store is designed these days except the
fruit in the produce department.'' But it occurred to me, produce
stickers serve to design the fruit they tag. And to package it, as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Another peach label, for a white fruit, bears the eye-catching
image of a shark's open jaws and the phrase ``Great White.''
Wrapping a peach in the image of a shark or totemizing an
Australian orange with a kangaroo is design and packaging together.
</P>
<P>
   Americans may be charmed by a movie pig that talks, but they
fear to buy a pig in a poke. Produce stickers provide minimal but
effective packaging. They civilize the fruit, even as they reassure
us how natural it is. The sticker on the fig is like the fig leaf
on the statue.
</P>
<P>
   The main function of the fruit sticker, of course, is to bear
the numbers assigned to fruit and vegetables by the Produce
Marketing Association, whose offices are in Newark, Del. These make
life easier for the checkout clerk in training. But they also tout
the fruit as fresh, organic, tree-ripened. They advertise the
banana or apple as much as they now advertise the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Like any package, fruit stickers have collectors. And no wonder,
since they pack a lot of design into a small space. Katie Foster is
a vivacious woman from Austin, Texas, who publishes ``Please Stop
Snickering,'' a newsletter for produce-seal collectors. The
Snicker, as she calls the publication, is dedicated to news about
``P-seals.'' She explained to me that stickers go back to the early
days of the century. Ms. Foster kindly sent me a 1917 Butler
Brothers seal for nonirrigated casaba melons.
</P>
<P>
   Serious collectors ``fly speck'' seals: they study minute
differences between them the way stamp or coin collectors do their
specimens. They know that there is a small letter to the lower
right of the Chiquita lady indicating where the banana was grown.
</P>
<P>
   P-seals become more interesting at this time of year, when fruit
begins arriving from distant locations _ mandarins from Morocco,
apples from New Zealand or mandacaru mangos, bearing code number
4051 inside the green-and-yellow diamond flag of Brazil. I think of
this as the time of antipodean fruit _ fruit whose price and
prestige increase as its point of sale approaches a point antipodal
from that of its origin.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of months ago, I met an obviously well-heeled woman who
told me she chose her vacation spots by the sounds of their names.
``Casablanca,'' she said. ``Marrakesh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Khartoum,'' I muttered to myself. ``Kashmir.''
</P>
<P>
   Do people choose their fruit this way? Fruit from halfway around
the world becomes, through its labels, a wondering testimony to the
powers of the container ship and cargo jet, as well as homage to
trade agreements like GATT or NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
   I think of these stickers as resembling steamer-trunk hotel
labels, tokens of how far fruit has come. Fruit, like Babe going to
the city, is about the natural confronting civilization. The same
process that turns a distant place into what the travel agents call
``a destination,'' turns a banana into a billboard, a 4011 into a
Chiquita, produce into product.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
