<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5500 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZ     11-11 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATMAN'S FATHER KNEW DARK SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somehow a big story slipped through our fingers recently.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Kane, the creator of Batman, died last week. He was 83. I
didn't read about it in the paper, nor did I see anything on
television.
</P>
<P>
   You may be saying, ``So what?'' Some guy invented a comic-book
character a long time ago. That's no big deal.
</P>
<P>
   You'd be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Batman isn't just a kids' comic-book hero. He is far too dark
for that. In an age when Marilyn Manson does nothing more than
raise a few eyebrows, it's hard to think of Kane's Dark Knight as a
truly subversive character, but that's just what he was.
</P>
<P>
   When Kane introduced Batman in ``Detective Comics No. 27'' in
1939, he didn't just make comic-book history _ he carved a niche
for himself in the annals of popular culture. Batman was an
anti-hero, a menacing loner who worked outside the law.
</P>
<P>
   And he was the GOOD guy.
</P>
<P>
   (If you think of Batman as a goofy buffoon, blame the kitschy
'60s TV show, with Adam West and Burt Ward, for the confusion.
You'd think it would be difficult for a live-action show to be more
of a cartoon than a comic book, but that version of Batman's story
stooped to the task.)
</P>
<P>
   With Batman, Kane ``changed the industry and the way superheroes
were done,'' said Mike Banks, general manager of All About Books
and Comics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brought different elements _ the grim and gritty hero,''
Banks added. &QL; 
WAYNE'S WORLD
</P>
<P>
   That's actually a kind description of the early Caped Crusader.
You know the story: As a boy, Bruce Wayne sees his parents
murdered. He inherits their millions and becomes a seemingly
virtuous paragon and benefactor of Gotham City.
</P>
<P>
   But like in any good story, all is not as it seems. At night,
Wayne dons his dark costume and roams the city, a nearly crazed
vigilante in a cape and cowl bent on avenging his parents' murder.
If he foils a few criminals along the way, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it, the guy's a bit of a nut.
</P>
<P>
   When Banks started collecting comics, one of his first finds was
a coverless copy of an early Batman. The illustration still sticks
in his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Batman, standing over a corpse with a smoking gun in
his hand,'' Banks said. ``That just blew me away.''
</P>
<P>
   It also illustrates just how dark a hero Batman can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Superman, he's got his code against killing and stuff,''
Banks said. ``Batman took a more realistic take. He knew that line
was there, and he walked it really closely _ and sometimes he
crossed over it if he thought the ends justified the means.'' &QL; 
WALKING A MIDDLE GROUND &QL; 
Other superheroes put villains in prison; readers could be sure of
that by the next issue; a jail break would lead to a rematch, a
story line that would play out again and again, sometimes for
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Batman,'' Banks said, ``sometimes he'd put them down for
good.''
</P>
<P>
   When you're a kid, Superman is usually the first superhero you
latch onto. He has all the cool powers: Nothing on Earth hurts him,
he has X-ray vision _ the guy can FLY, for goodness' sake. Good and
evil are spelled out in primary colors. It's a pretty simple world,
really, much like the one you live in as a child.
</P>
<P>
   It's when you grow up a bit and start noticing the gray shades
of life that Batman's appeal begins to draw you in. Good and evil
exist, but there is a big middle ground in between. That's the
space Batman occupies.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a fan, what always got me into Batman was I felt I could BE
Batman,'' Banks said. ``You could identify with him. He's got the
gadgets on his belt and the neat car and all that, but underneath
that, he's a normal person. You could just imagine yourself being
in his shoes. Or his tights.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of Kane's genius wasn't just the story he told but the way
he told it. The bright, happy colors of Superman's Metropolis gave
way to a dark, gothic Gotham City, bringing what Banks called the
``pulp-fiction feel'' to comics. Gritty _ sometimes, yes, ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Just like real life. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at 444-8828, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
