<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS: CHERIMOYAS AND IRESINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DORA GALITZKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Growing Cherimoyas
</P>
<P>
   Q. A few weeks ago in Chinatown I bought cherimoyas. I first saw
this fruit 25 years ago in Venezuela, and love its flavor, a
mixture of strawberry and pineapple. I scarified and soaked my
seeds, but sprouts never appeared. Is there hope in growing this
wonderful fruit in my own backyard?
</P>
<P>
   A. You can grow cherimoyas if your backyard happens to be in a
subtropical, frost-free region that doesn't get too humid in the
summer. Israel would do or Egypt, Chile, parts of South Africa or
areas of California.
</P>
<P>
   It's too humid in Florida, but Dr. Jonathan Crane, a specialist
in tropical fruit crops at the University of Florida's Tropical
Research and Education Center in Homestead, has experimented with
growing cherimoyas from seed. He found that the seed seems to have
an after-ripening requirement. Seeds that have been well cleaned
(don't want any fungus) should be left to age in a plastic bag at
room temperature for at least three months (six is better). Soaked
for a day and planted half an inch deep in well-drained growing
medium and kept moist, they will germinate in three to four weeks.
This works, however, only if the pot has bottom heat to keep the
medium at 80 degrees Fahrenheit.
</P>
<P>
   That's the easy part, relatively speaking, and it will result in
a large foliage plant that needs full sun. Fruit is another matter.
After three to eight years as a juvenile, your cherimoya may
flower, but the species of beetle that pollinates it will not be
around _ Food and Drug Administration inspections keep them out of
the country. And hand pollinating is tricky because the male and
female flowers bloom at different times. Well, you've got a few
years to figure out how to imitate a beetle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Colorful Latin Visitor
</P>
<P>
   Q. I've always loved iresine because I don't have enough light
for flowering plants and its magenta leaves were a lovely accent. I
even included it in my window box. When it got leggy I trimmed it
back and started new plants from the cuttings. But last year while
I was away it died. Before I could bring in one from the window
box, frost killed it, too. I have looked everywhere for a
replacement. Can you help?
</P>
<P>
   A. If I tell you where to get it, will you promise to keep an
extra cutting in a safe place? Iresine herbstii, commonly known as
bloodleaf, beefsteak plant or chicken gizzard, is a subtropical
South American plant (it hates frost), which should stay moist and
loves humidity. To have dried out one and frozen the other is just
adding insult to injury.
</P>
<P>
   Small and shrubby, iresine has waxy, variegated leaves,
frequently puckered. What makes it a standout is that the leaves
are magenta with pinkish midribs and veins, providing color even
without flowers. If your color sense tends away from Crayola, try
the variety I. herbstii Aureoreticulata, with green leaves, yellow
veins and bright red stalks and stems. Both need the same care _
give them plenty of light with some direct sun to keep the colors
bright and keep the soil moist without being soggy. Pinch the tips
occasionally to keep the plants bushy.
</P>
<P>
   Sources for iresine include Avant Gardens, 710 High Hill Road,
North Dartmouth, Mass. 02747, (508) 998-8819, catalog, $3; and
Davidson-Wilson Greenhouses, Route 2 Box 168, Crawfordsville, Ind.
47933, (765) 364-0556, catalog, $3.75. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to:
</P>
<P>
   Garden Q&AMP;A
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times
</P>
<P>
   229 W. 43rd St.
</P>
<P>
   New York 10036
</P>
<P>
   or by e-mail to gardening(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished
questions cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
