<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Thursday, Nov. 12. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Will move in ``i'' news file.)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.S. (Washington) _ President Clinton Wednesday ordered
substantial new forces to the Persian Gulf, including B-1 and B-52
bombers and 3,000 ground troops, and warned President Saddam
Hussein of Iraq that he was prepared to strike without further
warning. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PEACEPLAN (Jerusalem) _ The Israeli Cabinet is expected
to approve the land-for-peace plan, but may tie it to a series of
conditions that endanger the entire agreement. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-CRIME _ The man this city's top crime fighters calls a
mafia chieftain and a cold-blooded killer was decorously receiving
supplicants at his tenement headquarters here one recent afternoon.
Each of them reverently touched his feet before addressing him.
There have been a dozen gory shootouts here in just the past five
weeks and 81 of them so far this year, leaving 88 people dead. By
Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-DILEMMA (Washington) _ The House majority that Newt
Gingrich built is so deeply splintered that it seemed at times
during the last session to devolve into its 228 component parts,
each Republican member of Congress with a different idea of what
the Republican Party should be. However they decide to solve their
leadership problems, they still will face deep ideological
divisions. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL-GENERAL &LR;  (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS-TRAIL-TOWN (St. Mary's, Kan.) _ To a passer-by, this
small town has an idyllic air. Its wide main street is packed with
pickup trucks by day, empty and serene at night. Many of the women
and little girls wear long skirts, even for riding bicycles. Crime
is so rare that police statistics include ``cat bite.'' But in
1995, the town of 2,000 quickly became stereotyped as a hotbed of
heartland discontent.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIGRANTS-HOME-RELIEF (Undated) _ If she could fly, Reina
Palacios says, she would flap her wings and soar above her
apartment in Newark, N.J., fly across the country and down to El
Salvador, where she would frantically search for her children _
whom she has been unable to locate since a hurricane devastated
Central America two weeks ago. But Ms. Palacios can fly only in her
imagination because of a nightmarish web of federal laws and
regulations that make traveling abroad an almost impossible dream
for illegal immigrants or those in process of becoming legal
residents. By Mirta Ojito.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
