<HEADER>
A5650 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-WYE-1112-COX     11-11 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-WYE-1112-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PLO CHARTER VOTE ADDED ON AS CONDITION FOR ISRAELI WYE APPROVAL
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 700 words.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ After delays due to political resistance and a
suicide bombing, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
Wednesday won belated approval from his cabinet for the Wye peace
plan. But not without conditions attached that could threaten the
agreement signed just three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians were quick Wednesday night to accuse the Israelis
of trying to alter the deal, which passed narrowly by a vote of
eight to four, with five abstentions, and after seven hours of
debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they did tonight was a flagrant violation of the Wye
Memorandum,'' said Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat. ``We will
not allow any post-agreement negotiations. We will honor the
agreement to the letter.''
</P>
<P>
   American officials had for weeks been warning both sides not to
tinker with the delicate agreement, which was hammered out over
nine days of intense negotiations and signed by Netanyahu and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on Oct. 23 in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is largely a reaffirmation of the troubled Oslo
peace process. Under Wye, Israeli troops will withdraw from 13
percent more of the West Bank land captured in the 1967 war in
exchange for Palestinian efforts to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis insist they cannot begin implementing the plan until
both the cabinet and parliament approve it. The parliament is
expected to pass it Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu promised to continue carrying out the Wye agreement
and said Israel would soon release some Palestinian prisoners and
allow the opening next week of the first Palestinian airport, in
Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   But, Wednesday's cabinet resolution specified that the cabinet
will assess Palestinian compliance before giving approval for each
step of the 12-week plan.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the cabinet said that, after this 13 percent, only one
percent more of West Bank land can be handed over in the Oslo
process. That is less than Palestinians expect and Wye had
established a committee to negotiate that withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   The cabinet also threatened to retake lands already turned over
if the Palestinians carry out vows to declare statehood even
without Israeli approval next year.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the cabinet demanded a vote from the PLO to rescind
parts of its charter that call for the destruction of Israel. This
point was debated at Wye, where Israel signed wording that only
required that the PLO meet to ``reaffirm'' an earlier vote on the
charter.
</P>
<P>
   The cabinet vote had been delayed at least twice by Netanyahu
since he signed the Wye agreement. The first delays were political,
Netanyahu was seeking reluctant support from right-wing members of
his cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was again delayed last Friday after a suicide bombing
by two Palestinian extremists in a Jerusalem market filled with
Israelis. The bombing, apparently a botched attempt, killed only
the two bombers but provided ammunition to Israelis opposed to the
peace plan.
</P>
<P>
   In part because of the delayed cabinet approval, Israeli
officials said there will be a delay of some days in the first
troop withdrawals scheduled under Wye.
</P>
<P>
   The conditions attached to the cabinet approval were sought by
right-wing allies in Netanyahu's coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Schwartz, spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in Tel Aviv, said
the cabinet decision will have to be reviewed by the Clinton
administration before U.S. officials can comment on it.
</P>
<P>
   In preparation for the cabinet vote, Netanyahu had sought and
received several written assurances from U.S. officials about how
the agreement would be carried out.
</P>
<P>
   But there were long-standing rifts between the two sides on the
issue of the Palestinian charter even before the cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is a favorite among those in the Israeli right wing,
most of whom opposed the Oslo peace process in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   They see the charter as proof that Arafat and the Palestinians
still aim to destroy Israel, and that Oslo is just a stepping stone
in their effort.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians say the issue creates a tough political position
for Arafat. Many influential PLO members, including past and
present guerrilla fighters, live scattered around the world and are
opposed to Oslo and changes in the charter.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The charter, about six pages long, was passed by the PLO in
1968, when it was steeped in a terrorist war against Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Using revolutionary rhetoric, much of the charter repeatedly
calls for violence against Israel. It rejects any compromise.
</P>
<P>
   But Palestinians note that the PLO's 700-member governing body
already met in 1996 to rescind parts of the charter that conflicted
with Oslo. The meeting was greeted with approval from American and
Israeli officials.
</P>
<P>
   Just what happened at the meeting is still subject for debate.
It apparently was just a vote to start the amending process, never
completed.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Arafat restated that the charter was amended in a
letter to Clinton. During the Wye talks, it was agreed that Arafat
would ``invite'' the PLO back to affirm his letter.
</P>
<P>
   An American official close to the talks said recently that the
agreement and the Oslo process do not require a formal vote or, as
Israelis have demanded, that a new version of the charter be
rewritten with all the changes.
</P>
<P>
   He warned that any attempts to change the Wye plan could bring
it down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both sides are very sensitive about the wording of virtually
every part of the agreement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
