<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV15-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GINGRICH WAS WISE TO AVOID LAME-DUCK STATUS IN CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Nov. 15)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Newt Gingrich's bombshell decision to forsake
Congress and his speakership brings to mind the fate that befell
the last Republican speaker shorn of his power and influence as the
party's leader in the House.
</P>
<P>
   He was Joseph W. Martin. With the midterm election of 1954, the
speakership switched from Martin to the Democrats' Sam Rayburn. But
Martin held onto his post as GOP leader until he was overthrown
after the 1958 election.
</P>
<P>
   Then he became a pathetic figure in the House, often taking a
seat in the back row and viewing the legislative procedure, over
which he once presided, with sadness in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   He received a committee assignment, but his days of glory and
leadership were over. He looked and acted like a fatally-wounded
lion awaiting the final lethal blow, which didn't come until 1966,
when he was defeated for renomination by his home-district
Republicans in North Attleboro, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A man of medium stature with bushy eyebrows and a new England
accent, Martin owned the small town's newspaper and, like Gingrich,
was a symbol of Republican conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Gingrich, he also was a symbol of isolationism in the
years before America's entry into World War II.
</P>
<P>
   In ``FDR: An Intimate History,'' Nathan Miller recalled how
Franklin D. Roosevelt ridiculed _ with great success _ Martin and
two other GOP isolationists, New York Reps. Bruce Barton and
Hamilton Fish, in the 1940 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Martin also headed the Republican National Committee, and Barton
was chairman of Wendell L. Willkie's presidential campaign. Fish
represented Roosevelt's home district in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   At a rally in New York's Madison Square Garden, Miller wrote,
Roosevelt first chanted the names Martin, Barton and Fish ``in a
sing-song nursery rhyme cadence of Wynken, Blynken and Nod.''
</P>
<P>
   Thereafter, the moment Roosevelt mentioned Martin's name, his
audiences ``gleefully roared back `Barton and Fish.'''
</P>
<P>
   Willkie, the Republican presidential nominee, later said: ``When
I heard the president hang the isolationist votes of Martin, Barton
and Fish on me, and get away with it, I knew I was licked.''
</P>
<P>
   But Martin remained the Republican leader of the House for
nearly two more decades.
</P>
<P>
   He entered the House in 1925 and served as GOP leader from 1940
until 1959 when he was toppled in a coup that made Indiana's
Charles Halleck the GOP chieftain.
</P>
<P>
   Martin occupied the speaker's chair twice: in the 80th Congress,
which was elected in 1946 and became Harry Truman's primary target
in the presidential campaign of 1948, and the 83d, which was
elected when Dwight D. Eisenhower first swept to victory in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's power and prestige were so great within his party that
he was elected permanent chairman of five consecutive GOP national
conventions, from 1940 to 1956.
</P>
<P>
   But when he was in his mid-70s and no longer vigorous, Martin,
like Gingrich, was done in by a midterm election. In 1958 the
Republicans suffered a debacle, losing 48 seats in the House and 13
in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Like Gingrich in 1998, Martin was blamed by many Republicans for
their loss. The real culprits, however, were an economic recession,
Eisenhower's initial refusal to take seriously the Soviet Union's
advances in space exploration and the fact that the administration,
with a 68-year-old president at its helm, appeared old and tired.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans believed then, as they believe now, that they
would fare better with the public if they had new leadership.
</P>
<P>
   They got the new leadership in 1959, and in the next election,
1960, they picked up 20 seats in the House and two in the Senate
while John Kennedy was defeating their presidential nominee,
Richard Nixon. Still, they remained a long way from winning control
of the two houses, and Halleck was deposed as House minority leader
by Gerald Ford following the 1964 election.
</P>
<P>
   Under procedures of the House, a person who takes a leadership
position gives up his or her seniority on major committees. Thus,
Gingrich had no place to go in the House if he had been defeated
for another term as speaker.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, members of the leadership do retain their senior
positions on committees. When West Virginia Democrat Robert Byrd
decided to give up his job as majority leader, he simply slipped
into the chairmanship of the powerful Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, at 55 a much younger and more dynamic figure than
Martin was in 1959, would not have ended his House tenure in so
forlorn a manner.
</P>
<P>
   To the bachelor Martin, the House was his life. To Gingrich,
with a wife and children and a career as a historian, the House was
but one phase of his life. He now can write, lecture and try, as a
private citizen, to strengthen the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   But Gingrich would have found life difficult once his power was
gone, and the new speaker, Rep. Bob Livingston of Louisiana, would
have found it difficult with Gingrich looking over his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said he decided to sever all contact with Congress to
spare his party and his country further ``divisiveness and
factionalism.'' But he also benefited himself by avoiding the fate
of becoming another Joe Martin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
