A5738 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEPHARDT-FUTURE-HNS &LR;      11-11 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEPHARDT-FUTURE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEPHARDT SAYS HE WANTS TO FORGE LINKS WITH GOP MODERATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just six votes shy of a majority, House Democrats
are poised to build bridges to Republican moderates and seize much
of the legislative agenda from GOP conservatives in the new
Congress, House Democratic Leader Dick Gephardt said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans will be ``much less unified on what they want to
do'' than Democrats when the 106th Congress is gaveled into session
in January, Gephardt told reporters. ``We have a chance to unify
our party on major issues and reach into the Republican moderates
and attract enough of them ... to get things done.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a coalition, he said, could yield wins for Democrats on
such issues as legislation to reduce teen smoking, prop up Social
Security, regulate managed care health plans and raise the minimum
wage. By contrast, he said, Republicans will enter the next
Congress sharply divided between conservatives and moderates.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats must face the reality that the GOP majority will
dictate what legislation does or does not move to the House floor,
Gephardt said. Nevertheless, he predicted that the presumed House
Speaker, Rep. Bob Livingston, R-La., will have a tough time putting
a conservative coalition together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thinks it's far easier on Social Security, education, health
care and the minimum wage for us to put together a coalition with
largely Democrats and a few Republicans who last year were looking
in our direction on these issues,'' Gephardt said. ``We're going to
work very hard on that.''
</P>
<P>
   One Republican reacted to Gephardt's vision with a raised
eyebrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime the Democrats want to sit down with Republicans and
search for common ground, there is a distinct possibility of
passing legislation,'' said Clifford May, Republican National
Committee communications director. ``Unfortunately, for the past
year, the Democrats have not done that.''
</P>
<P>
   At the luncheon, Gephardt was ebullient over an election that
gave Democrats an unexpected gain of five House seats. The
57-year-old minority leader from St. Louis said he was ``flat-out
surprised'' by the results. The party's pollsters and experts had
predicted a Democratic loss of between two and 10 seats, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The subsequent exit of House Speaker Newt Gingrich _ a favored
Democratic target _ neither helps nor hinders Democrats, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Newt is their problem,'' he said. ``Their
problem is the far right dominates their party. Their party is far
more disunified than our party. Their agenda ... is not attractive
to the majority of the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt called GOP handling of the impeachment inquiry against
President Clinton ``defective.''
</P>
<P>
   During House debate last month, Gephardt proposed an inquiry in
which impeachment standards would be set before hearings took
place. Also, the inquiry would have a Dec. 31 deadline and be
limited to Clinton's conduct in the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, however, approved an inquiry with no limits on time
or subject matter. On Monday, a panel of the House Judiciary
Committee held a day-long hearing with academic experts testifying
on what constitutes an impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   The panel didn't adopt a formal definition. Independent Counsel
Kenneth Starr is scheduled to testify before the full committee
next week as impeachment proceedings get underway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost a lot of time,'' Gephardt said. Had the committee
started before the election, he added, members could have
formulated standards and weighed Starr's voluminous September
report on the Lewinsky matter against those standards.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt reiterated his characterization of Clinton's conduct as
``reprehensible.'' And he did not adopt the view of some fellow
Democrats that the charges of perjury and obstruction contained in
the Starr report fall short of impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Should the committee recommend articles of impeachment to the
full House, ``we will ... try to understand where we are and figure
out what we ought to do,'' Gephardt said. ``I don't know where
we're going to be. I'm troubled about how this whole thing has
transpired.''
</P>
<P>
   He urged a quick resolution to the inquiry but had no advice for
the Republican majority on how to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to put the whole thing back together again,'' he
said. ``It has not been bipartisan in any way. It's been a totally
us-versus-them kind of procedure from day one.''
</P>
<P>
   On his own political future, Gephardt said he is weighing a
presidential bid in 2000 or, if Democrats regain the House majority
that year, ascension to the House speakership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either goal is a very daunting goal,'' he said. ``I always
believed in life you have to set a goal, and then throw yourself
completely within the reach of that goal.'' A decision on whether
to make a presidential run should come sometime around January, he
added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 1720EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
