<HEADLINE>
CLEANING OUT THE CACHE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. How do I clear my browser's cache files without throwing away
needed files? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Cache files are little pieces of Web pages that your browser
has saved on your hard drive. Having a page cached makes
downloading it faster each time you go back. But when the cache is
full, it can cause performance problems. Here's how to purge the
caches of some common browsers:
</P>
<P>
   For the Windows version of Netscape Navigator 4.0, go to the
Edit menu and select Preferences. Click the Advanced category and
then select Cache. Click on Clear Memory Cache and Clear Disk
Cache.
</P>
<P>
   For the Macintosh version of Navigator 4.0, go to the Edit menu
and select Preferences. Click on Advanced, and then Cache, and then
Clear Disk Cache.
</P>
<P>
   For the Windows version of Internet Explorer 4.0, go into the
View menu to Internet Options. Click on the Advanced tab, then
Settings, then Empty Folderand OK.
</P>
<P>
   For the Macintosh version of Explorer 4.0, go to the Edit menu
and select Preferences. In the Web Browser section of the box,
click on Advanced, and then on the Empty Now button in the Cache
section. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West
43rd Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
QandA(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
