u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-2TAKES     11-11 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEEK NOTES: HI-TECH NEWSWATCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Calif., N.Y.)  (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft's New Market: Digital Speakers
</P>
<P>
   First it just made software. Then it made mice, joysticks and
telephones. Now the company that gave the world a little something
called Windows is getting into the speaker market.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. plans to sell the Digital Sound System 80, a
pair of PC speakers that it insists will better take advantage of
(surprise) its own Windows 98 operating system. The reason is that
the speakers are designed to be compatible with features in Windows
98 and work with a type of data transmission called Universal
Serial Bus that is built into newer computers.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft contends that the digital speakers, which go for $249,
excluding a $50 rebate, will create better sound than many existing
speakers.
</P>
<P>
   A second Microsoft selling point is that the speakers make it
unnecessary to own a sound card to listen to music and other audio.
But some people may still want a sound card, which can perform
other functions, like connecting video game devices that are not
yet designed to be used with the Universal Serial Bus. These
capabilities may undermine some users' interest in looking to
Microsoft for speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign Promises Not Welcome by E-Mail
</P>
<P>
   The staff members of Florida's Democratic Party have been
cleaning up in the aftermath of Election Day, including clearing
some boisterous complaints out of their e-mail in boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks ago the campaign sent out a mass e-mail message in
support of Democratic gubernatorial candidate Buddy MacKay. The
e-mail urged voters to reject the ``negative campaigning'' of
Republican candidate Jeb Bush, who ultimately defeated MacKay. Some
voters decided to reject the e-mail overture instead, accusing the
Democratic Party of spamming voters with unsolicited e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   John Mozena, a national anti-spam crusader and co-founder of the
Coalition Against Unsolicited Commercial E-mail, said the campaign
e-mail was not only unsolicited, but also indiscriminate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to one guy in Ithaca, N.Y., who got it,'' Mozena
said. ``The targeting was abysmal.''
</P>
<P>
   Mozena said the Florida party was not alone, noting that a
handful of other candidates nationwide employed mass e-mails during
their election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Welch, a spokesman for the Democratic Party in Florida,
said that while party officials did not consider the messages to be
``commercial'' and thus Spam, they will reevaluate the strategy.
``The party has heard the message loud and clear,'' Welch said. But
he added: ``Don't forget, people in the party make phone calls to
households and knock on doors. Now they're knocking on computers
too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet Doesn't Intercept Football Fans
</P>
<P>
   The National Football League reports that its Web site has been
scoring high with sports fans during the first half of the season.
But the league is careful to explain that the viewers aren't being
drawn away from the television, and there's an $18 billion reason
that the league may want to hammer that point home.
</P>
<P>
   First, the facts: the NFL said traffic to its official NFL.com
site, which offers scores of games in progress, text-based
play-by-play descriptions and post-game articles, continues to see
rapid growth. The site had 423,544 individual visitors on Oct. 18,
which the league proudly pointed out is equal to one visit for
every man, woman and child living in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the spin: the league is very happy with this turnout, but
wants to make it clear that Web surfers aren't immigrants from
television who have set down the remote control and picked up the
mouse. ``We don't believe anybody really wants to sit at their
computers and watch a game in text,'' said Dennis Lewin, the NFL's
senior vice president for broadcasting and network television.
</P>
<P>
   It's understandable why the league would want to send such a
message. Last January it sold television rights for NFL games for a
whopping $18 billion. The networks, some of which are seeing a drop
in ratings, may be tempted to blame computers.
</P>
<P>
   Lewin added that that while the NFL plans to continue to enhance
its site, it will not turn it into an alternative to television.
``We won't enhance our site in any way, shape or form that will
ultimately draw people away from the game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Free Web Access Is an Expensive Gamble
</P>
<P>
   The promise of advertiser-supported Internet access has hit a
few more roadblocks. Bigger.net, a San Jose, Calif., company that
offered free, advertising-supported Internet access, declared
bankruptcy in October. The company had more than 18,000 customers
who had been promised ``unlimited lifetime access'' in exchange for
a one-time fee of $60 and their willingness to put up with a
constant stream of advertising on the browser.
</P>
<P>
   For subscribers, the story may yet end well. Tuesday, a Seattle
company, Brigadoon.com, received court approval to purchase
Bigger.net for the fire-sale price of $275,000. A Brigadoon.com
official told the court that the company intends to keep the site
up and running.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Brigadoon.com will have its hands full: One reason
Bigger.net was bleeding money was that it simply couldn't attract
enough advertisers to support the high cost of offering Internet
access to thousands of Web users.
</P>
<P>
   It is not alone. As many as 100,000 registered users of a free
Internet service provider called the Tritium Network were told last
month to find another provider. Tritium, based in Cincinnati, has
``temporarily suspended operations'' while it finds additional
investors, said Todd Telford, the company's director of advertising
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Telford said the company asked its subscribers to try another
ISP for awhile, but then to come back.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the struggles of advertising-supported Internet access,
entrepreneurs continue to jump in with new variations on the theme.
A southern California group last month started the
advertising-supported Netzero Inc.; in its first 10 days, the
company signed up 20,000 users, said company president Ronald Burr.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know all about the mistakes made in the past,'' Burr said,
noting that his company will invest ``multimillions of dollars''
and contract out its technology. ``These guys took the rinky-dink
approach. We've done it the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A New PC Card Offers Cellular Net Connections
</P>
<P>
   The good news isthat a new generation of modems has emerged that
enables handheld Windows CE devices to make wireless connections to
the Internet over cellular telephone lines. The bad news is that
the transmissions can be as finicky and limited as cellular
telephone transmissions, and the modems are expensive to boot.
</P>
<P>
   The latest is called the Aircard CE, a PC card from Sierra
Wireless of Richmond, British Columbia, that will hit stores in
December. Industry analysts say they are high on the Aircard
because, unlike other PC card modems designed to hook into cellular
networks, it does not have a Tootsie Roll-sized extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the nicest piece of engineering I've seen in a long
time,'' said Andrew Seybold, editor-in-chief of The Outlook, a
newsletter in Boulder Creek, Calif., that covers mobile computing.
``They're pushing the state of the art.''
</P>
<P>
   But the modem has a hefty $450 suggested retail price. Type II
cards that give Windows CE devices wireless capability typically
sell for more than $300, said Seybold, who noted that the price is
too high to attract many people, who originally paid $800 for the
CE devices.
</P>
<P>
   Great Sets, Great Acting, Terrific Verb Tenses
</P>
<P>
   Two Colgate University professors have created an innovative
technology to promulgate a simple teaching philosophy: feature
films fun, textbooks boring.
</P>
<P>
   The professors created a computer program to help students learn
another language by immersing them in foreign films. And now the
technology is coming to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The technology splits a computer monitor into four squares: one
square shows a foreign film; a second shows the script of the film;
a third shows commentary on the movie in English; and a fourth
provides a foreign-language dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   The project is the work of Alexander (Sasha) Nakhimovsky, a
Colgate computer science professor; his wife, Alice, a professor of
Russian; and Tom Myers, a computer programmer.
</P>
<P>
   A linguist by training, Nakhimovsky said the idea is that
students will not only pick up language more quickly when they see
it in the context of a film, but they will also be able to discern
the subtleties of a foreign culture. ``The amount of cultural
information you can get in every screen shot is incomparable to
what you can get in a textbook,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, ``a Russian `salat' is totally different from an
American salad,'' Nakhimovsky said. ``When a textbook says a
`salat' equals a salad, it's totally misleading.''
</P>
<P>
   Faculty members at Colgate, in Hamilton, N.Y., have been
experimenting with the system for several years. Thursday,
Nakhimovsky is scheduled to demonstrate an Internet version. He
believes the tool can ultimately gain widespread use over the Net,
as increasing band width makes it possible to transmit video
content more easily.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
