<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5764 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLIDAY-FOOD-LADN     11-11 3978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-FOOD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO START PLANNING THOSE HOLIDAY MEALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(PHOTO ADV: One color picture   of Natalie Dupree and her holiday
food has being transmitted to NYT Photo Service Clients.
Nonsubscribers may purchase the photo by calling 212-556-4204.) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The holidays will be here before you know it _ and
that means parties galore. If you're contemplating throwing a
holiday bash, it's not too early to make plans.
</P>
<P>
   A great way to entertain friends and family is with a
spectacular hors d'oeuvres buffet in the late afternoon or early
evening. Gather your thoughts, guest list and invitations _ and get
moving, as you'll want to get your party on your friends' holiday
calendars in a timely fashion.
</P>
<P>
   For party givers who want to orchestrate and direct the
production themselves at home, we've turned to Nathalie Dupree,
cookbook author, television cooking-show personality (she has been
on PBS stations for nine seasons and has done more than 300 shows
for the TV Food Network) and Georgia hostess. Whether your style is
casual or dressy, you'll find a wealth of information for
successful parties in her recently released ninth cookbook,
``Nathalie Dupree's Comfortable Entertaining: At Home With Ease and
Grace'' (Viking; $29.95) which coincides with her new 29-episode
PBS series, ``Comfortable Entertaining,'' now airing. The book is
designed to show what Dupree does best _ create spontaneous
hospitality and wonderful food. ``The key ingredient in
entertaining is the desire to be hospitable,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Entertaining is a mind-set, an attitude as well as a practice
_ not quite an art form but more than a craft. Like most artistic
endeavors, it is a marriage of personal expression and technique
learned through observation and experience,'' noted Dupree during a
recent stopover in the Los Angeles area.
</P>
<P>
   Her entertaining philosophy boils down to: ``The guest is the
most important _ that's why you're having him or her over. Make
your guests comfortable in your home and truly welcome them.
Everything else _ menus, decorations, table settings _ come after
that.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the food, Dupree suggests serving something you
know and make well. Don't try to compete with restaurants, as
restaurant food is quite different from home food. However, she
advises looking at what restaurants serve in terms of what can be
done ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Planning is crucial, she emphasized repeatedly, noting that
you'll need both a master plan defining your vision for the
gathering as well as a tactical plan outlining what has to be done
and when. The master plan should include the guest list, place,
date and time of the event, a budget of how much you can afford in
both time and money, and what you decide to serve. Be realistic
about what you can and can't do. The budget should include food,
beverages, decorations (including candles and flowers), dishes,
rentals, laundry expenses and any serving and cleanup help.
</P>
<P>
   Figure out how much time you can give the event _ in bits or
pieces spaced out over weeks _ or one big chunk of time on a
weekend _ to prep, cook and freeze. ``Consider the value of your
time to you, weighing preparation time against the cost of
ingredients,'' pointed out Dupree. A casserole may be cheap, but
might take longer to prepare than a pricey salmon or tenderloin,
which requires less time and energy from market to table. ``Balance
is key to a comfortable, workable menu _ not just the balance of
foods (consider combinations of flavors and textures for overall
appeal) but the balance of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, decide how you will serve _ for instance, do you plan to
pass hors d'oeuvres or simply set them out on a table or buffet _
or a combination of the two.
</P>
<P>
   The book features more than 250 creations _ what Dupree refers
to as life-is-not-perfect recipes _ for occasions ranging from a
``Buffet for Twelve to Fifty, in Four Hours or Less,'' to an
``All-Desserts Buffet'' to ``Three Simple Suppers,'' ``Two Hors
d'Oeuvres Parties'' and more. By life-is-not-perfect, Dupree means
that ``you can never expect to have everything you need _ such as
the right pan, etc. _ or the perfect situation (your mother may be
ill) when you entertain.'' Her recipes are flexible and will work
even if you have a child pulling on your apron strings, she noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be perfect. You can make mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life has not been perfect for me,'' continued Dupree, who
taught cooking classes at Rich's Department store in Atlanta for a
decade during the 1970s and '80s. However, Dupree has managed to
entertain through the years in tiny apartments and on tight
budgets, planned galas for hundreds and put on parties on a
moment's notice. And it all started when she was 10 years old,
hosting a party with home-baked cookies and cheese straws.
</P>
<P>
   But her entertaining has not been without a few faux pas along
the way. Like the time in New York when she roasted an 18-pound pig
over a small wood fire (the pig fell in the flames a few times) for
Thanksgiving. The pig was not done in time for dinner _ and guests
(including her boss and his family) ended up eating veggies and
go-alongs. The pig didn't get done until everyone had gone home.
``It was a disaster,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Or the time when Dupree was just learning to cook in London when
she ended up with puff pastry on the ceiling and brown sauce on the
floor just before a dinner party. ``It was a mess!''
</P>
<P>
   More recently, she was expecting company for dinner, but had
taken a nap and fallen sound asleep, only to be awakened by guests
ringing the doorbell. She had the food on the buffet table within
15 minutes and guests were amazed. Planning does pay off.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some cooks who abhor the thought of freezing party foods,
Dupree takes the opposite approach. ``I love freezing stuff,'' she
emphasized, ``and the book's recipes include make-ahead and
freezing instructions. For a busy person, making and freezing ahead
is the only answer when entertaining. You can cook when you're not
pressured.'' However, she also advocates buying good ready-made
substitutes when you don't have time to make everything from
scratch.
</P>
<P>
   But she is not into low-fat. ``When you entertain, it's not the
time to sacrifice flavor for calories,'' noted Dupree, who
entertains a group of five or six for dinner several times a month
and has larger parties a half dozen times a year.
</P>
<P>
   Writing the book, which she did before she filmed the companion
television shows, was not difficult, noted Dupree. She said she
relied on some of her core menus and recipes, which she changed and
dressed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone should have core recipes that they do over and over
again.'' Among Dupree's standbys are beef tenderloin, roast
chicken, roast turkey and sliced ham, which are easily adapted
party foods. Mango Salsa is the current accessory to her old
grilled salmon. And grilled or roasted tenderloin is dressed up
with red peppers in balsamic vinegar or in a marinade of mustard
and ginger.
</P>
<P>
   Be aware that you can't serve alcohol at a party without
offering a substantial protein dish, emphasized Dupree, adding that
her favorite is a beef tenderloin _ which can serve 40 at an hors
d'oeuvres party or 10 for dinner. For cocktail party fare, marinate
the tenderloin in mustard, roast, cut in half lengthwise, and then
slice into rounds and serve with rolls or baguette slices.
</P>
<P>
   For an hors d'oeuvres party, Dupree recommends serving red and
white wine, soft drinks and plenty of bottled water. ``Never serve
just champagne.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the book includes a two-hour cocktail party that would
take two people two hours or one person four hours to prepare,
Dupree pulled together a stand-up-plates-only buffet with some of
her show-stopper recipes _ Spinach Tart, Elegant Cheese Platter
Garnished With Sugared Grapes, Buffet Tenderloin Mini-Rounds,
Grilled Sides of Salmon, Hot Mango Salsa, Stuffed Cherry Tomatoes,
Caponata With Cucumber Rounds, Chicken Sate, Drop Brownies and
Pecan Crescents _ for a holiday get-together. She designed it so
the food can be easily eaten without forks while standing.
</P>
<P>
   While several of the recipes in the book are lengthy _ not the
quick and easy variety many cooks prefer these days _ Dupree is
quick to point out that she believes recipes with more ingredients
are more interesting and flavorful than those with less. ``With
fewer ingredients, you have to do more work to get more flavor,''
she added. Some cooks may disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am most interested in saving people time _ not throwing
something on the table at the last minute. I don't like tension or
last-minute cooking,'' she added. Dupree prefers serving food at
room temperature or reheating food that has been prepared in
advance of the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can only learn to host successfully by doing it,'' said
Dupree, so you may want to get started this holiday season. Start
small with what you know and go from there. Be yourself and enjoy.
Remember, it's your party, too.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some inspirations from Dupree's new cookbook,
``Comfortable Entertaining.'' Practice them first _ at a dinner
party _ before you tackle them for a large holiday cocktail party. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SPINACH OR BROCCOLI TART
</P>
<P>
   With the cream cheese and blue cheese as deliciously rich
thickeners, this cheese tart is particularly suited for an hors
d'oeuvre or appetizer.
</P>
<P>
   A tart pan with a removable bottom is a good addition to the
kitchen because it makes for a much prettier presentation than a
pie pan or plate. If you are using a pan without a removable
bottom, slice and serve the tart in thin wedges.
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces blue cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 package (8 ounces) cream cheese, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons snipped fresh chives
</P>
<P>
   5 ounces frozen chopped spinach, thawed and drained OR 1/2 cup
broccoli florets, lightly steamed and well drained
</P>
<P>
   1 (9-inch) prebaked pastry shell in a round tart pan with a
removable bottom
</P>
<P>
   In a bowl of a food processor or electric mixer, blend blue
cheese, cream cheese, butter and cream. Add eggs, salt and cayenne
to taste and process or mix. Sprinkle chives over mixture and pulse
machine twice or stir in well.
</P>
<P>
   Scrape custard into prebaked pastry shell and sprinkle spinach
or broccoli evenly over pie.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 375-degree oven about 25 minutes or until tart
is puffed and pastry is golden brown. Cover edge of pie with foil,
if it gets too dark. Let cool on a wire rack.
</P>
<P>
   For hors d'oeuvres, remove from pan and cut a circle 3 inches in
diameter in center using a biscuit cutter. Cut outer ``doughnut''
and inner circle into bite-sized pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Tart can be kept, refrigerated, 1 to 2 days or frozen 3 months,
tightly wrapped and in a sturdy food container. Makes 6 to 8
servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ELEGANT CHEESE PLATTER GARNISHED WITH SUGARED GRAPES
</P>
<P>
   Brie makes a particularly elegant presentation, but certainly
other kinds of cheese could be used _ or several different types _
but keep in mind that their flavors must be compatible and that
working with one cheese is easier than working with several. You
may buy rounds of Brie up to a kilo, in which case you would need
to double or triple the grapes and sugar.
</P>
<P>
   If serving Brie on silver, take care as the cheese knife may
scar the silver. Marble, wood and other natural materials enhance
the appearance of cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Gingersnaps vary widely in quality. I use Moravian cookies when
I'm feeling flush or the best kind of gingersnaps I can find.
</P>
<P>
   1 wheel (8 ounces) Brie cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 large bunch seedless green grapes
</P>
<P>
   Nonstick spray OR vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   Thin gingersnaps OR crackers
</P>
<P>
   Place cheese on a large round serving platter. Cut a small wedge
out of cheese and turn small wedge on its side on top of round.
</P>
<P>
   Leave rinsed grapes attached to stems. Put on a rack in a
jellyroll pan. Spray grapes lightly with nonstick spray. Put sugar
in a fine sieve and shake over grapes until lightly covered. Drape
grapes on top of cheese allowing them to cascade off edge. Surround
cheese with gingersnaps. This dish can stand at room temperature up
to, but not more than 4 hours, depending on ripeness of cheese.
Makes 8 to 10 servings as an appetizer.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Brie should be fully ripe but should not have ammonia-like
smell that indicates ripeness. At room temperature, it should feel
soft to touch, especially in middle. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
STUFFED CHERRY TOMATOES
</P>
<P>
   2 pints small, firm, ripe cherry tomatoes (one-bite size)
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches parsley
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces Monterey Jack cheese, finely shredded OR finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup finely chopped cooked ham OR chicken
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely chopped pimiento
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   Fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   With a very sharp knife, slice off top quarter of each tomato
and set aside. Remove insides and seeds with a small spoon,
grapefruit spoon or melon baller and discard. Invert shells on a
wire mesh rack or paper towels to drain.
</P>
<P>
   Up to a day ahead, finely chop 1 1/2 bunches parsley, reserving
remainder. Mix together chopped parsley, Jack cheese, ham,
pimiento, onion, mayonnaise, thyme and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon mixture into tomato shells or use a piping bag with a
large tip. Top can be set back on, a little askew, if not broken.
Keep refrigerated until needed, preferably stored in a sturdy
airtight food container.
</P>
<P>
   Garnish with remaining parsley sprigs. Makes 10 to 16 servings
as an appetizer. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CAPONATA WITH CUCUMBER ROUNDS
</P>
<P>
   This tasty dish makes a handy appetizer dip. I keep it in the
freezer in small containers. It goes well with bagel chips, toasted
pita triangles, Melba toast or on cucumber or zucchini rounds. It
can also serve as sauce for hot cooked pasta and can be spread on
bread for a sandwich with cheese or turkey slices.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 large red onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 stalks celery, chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 garlic cloves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 medium regular OR 3 long Italian eggplant, peeled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 can (28 1/2 ounces) Italian plum tomatoes, drained
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped green olives
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup chopped roasted red bell peppers
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup capers, drained
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped fresh oregano OR marjoram
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Thin cucumber rounds
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in a large skillet over medium heat. Add onion and
celery and cook until soft, 5 to 7 minutes. Add garlic and eggplant
and cook until soft, about 5 minutes more.
</P>
<P>
   Add tomatoes, olives, red peppers, capers, parsley, oregano,
vinegar, tomato paste, sugar, salt and pepper to taste. Simmer
about 5 minutes, stirring occasionally to break up tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Caponata may be kept refrigerated 3 days or frozen. Turn
caponata into a serving bowl, place on a tray and surround with
cucumber rounds. Makes 10 cups caponata. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHICKEN SATE
</P>
<P>
   Skewered chicken tenders make great finger food. Consider
combining the sate with another appetizer or two for a tapas-style
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   6-inch bamboo skewers
</P>
<P>
   Water
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds chicken tenders OR 4 boneless, skinless breasts
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon toasted sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon rice wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   8 to 10 green onions, white and pale-green parts only
</P>
<P>
   Spicy Peanut Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Soak skewers in water while you work.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat broiler or heat a grill. If broiling, grease a large
baking sheet with nonstick spray or cover with foil.
</P>
<P>
   If tenders are not available, slice chicken breasts across grain
into 1/2-inch-wide strips.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, mix garlic, sesame oil, vinegar, salt and
pepper. Add chicken and green onions and toss to cover. Marinate 30
minutes to 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Thread meat onto bamboo skewers. Place on prepared baking sheet.
Remove green onions from marinade and place on baking sheet with
skewers.
</P>
<P>
   Broil or grill 4 to 5 inches from heat source 5 to 8 minutes,
turning once.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with Spicy Peanut Sauce. Makes 16 to 20 small skewers or
toothpicks.
</P>
<P>
   SPICY PEANUT SAUCE: In a blender or food processor, combine 2
tablespoons finely chopped fresh ginger, 2 garlic cloves, chopped,
1/3 cup red wine vinegar, 1/3 cup creamy peanut butter, 2 teaspoons
hot red pepper flakes and 1/3 cup soy sauce. Process until well
blended. Chill. Sauce can be made and refrigerated up to 2 days in
advance. Makes 6 to 8 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
BUFFET TENDERLOIN MINI-ROUNDS
</P>
<P>
   2 cups Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup crumbled fresh rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup finely chopped fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   4 garlic cloves, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 (about 5-pound) trimmed beef tenderloins
</P>
<P>
   100 (2- to 3-inch) store-bought sandwich rolls, halved
</P>
<P>
   Mix mustard, rosemary, ginger, garlic, Worcestershire, oil, salt
and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Trim off excess fat and membrane from meat. To make cylinders,
slice each tenderloin lengthwise from end to end to form 2 pieces
of meat from each tenderloin. Turn about 2 inches of thinner end
under to make a uniform cylinder. Tie each cylinder at about 2-inch
intervals with kitchen twine, forming a cylinder shape of same
diameters as bread rolls. Repeat with remaining 3 pieces of beef.
Spread mustard mixture all over 4 pieces of meat and set aside. (At
this point, you can wrap meat and refrigerate up to a day.)
</P>
<P>
   Reserving mustard mixture, put tenderloins in a heavy baking
pan, leaving space between them. There must be plenty of room to
let heat circulate and meat brown rather than steam.
</P>
<P>
   Roast on top shelf in preheated 425-degree oven in batches, if
necessary, until an instant-read thermometer inserted in middle of
tenderloin registers 135 degrees F, about 15 to 20 minutes longer
if straight from refrigerator. Remove roasts from oven and let
stand at least 15 minutes. Remove strings and carve meat into thin
slices. (They can be made ahead up to 2 days and refrigerated and
carved a day or two later. It's easier to carve a cold roast.)
</P>
<P>
   While meat is standing, add any leftover mustard mixture to
roasting pan and bring to a boil, scraping up browned bits on
bottom and sides of pan. Boil until juices have reduced by about
half. Let cool.
</P>
<P>
   Put cold or room-temperature meat on a serving tray and pour any
reduced mustard mixture over meat. Put tray on buffet and place
sandwich rolls nearby. If you are making up sandwiches, put 2 or 3
thin slices of meat on a roll. (It is easier to eat 2 thin pieces
than 1 thick one.) Otherwise, let everyone help themselves. Sliced
tenderloin may be kept, frozen, up to 3 months. Makes 100 rolls.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: The purpose of tying meat is to form cylinders about the
diameter of rolls so filled rolls may be eaten easily at a stand-up
meal without need for forks. Mustard-covered surface means forgoing
extra mustard and sauces, which speeds up ease of service for
guests. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
GRILLED SIDES OF SALMON
</P>
<P>
   2 (2 1/2- to 3-pound) sides of salmon, bone removed, skin on
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup extra-virgin olive oil OR basil-flavored olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Hot Mango Salsa; curly lettuce; sprigs of herbs, such as basil,
dill OR fennel; tomato rose or edible flowers; lemon slices OR
wedges and cucumber slices for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Prepare grill.
</P>
<P>
   Place salmon sides in a glass or plastic food container that is
long enough to accommodate them unfolded and with high enough sides
to keep marinade from spilling when you move salmon to grill.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, mix olive oil, lemon juice, basil, salt and
pepper. Pour marinade over salmon, cover with plastic wrap and
leave at room temperature while grill is heating, about 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Place salmon sides on grill so that nonskin side is down so that
hot grill will mark presentation side. If salmon sides are 1-inch
thick, cook 5 minutes, then turn using a wide spatula to loosen
fish underneath carefully before turning. Cook 5 minutes on second
side. (It is better to undercook salmon slightly, since it will
continue to cook on platter from residual heat.)
</P>
<P>
   Using 2 wide spatulas, remove salmon sides from grill to serving
platters. Don't panic if salmon splits into pieces when you lift it
from grill. If you are careful, you can rearrange it on serving
platter so that the break will not be evident to guests.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon can be served hot, or it can be refrigerated, covered
with plastic wrap and served cold.
</P>
<P>
   Garnish with Hot Mango Salsa, curly lettuce, herb sprigs, tomato
rose, lemon slices, cucumber slices, as desired. Makes 20 to 30
appetizer servings.
</P>
<P>
   HOT MANGO SALSA: Mix together 1 (14-ounce) mango, peeled, seeded
and chopped (about 2 cups), 1/4 cup chopped green onions, 1/4 cup
chopped yellow OR red bell pepper, 1 teaspoon chopped cilantro OR
basil, 1 to 2 teaspoons chopped jalapeno chiles, preferably fresh
and 2 tablespoons fresh lime OR lemon juice. The salsa can be kept
refrigerated up to 1 week. Makes 2 1/2 to 3 cups. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
DROP BROWNIES
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces semisweet chocolate bits
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   2 1/4 cups coarsely chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   Grease or spray 2 cookie sheets with nonstick spray.
</P>
<P>
   Remove 3/4 cup chocolate bits and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Place remaining chocolate bits and butter in a heavy 2-quart
saucepan and melt over low heat (or melt in microwave), stirring
until smooth. Let cool slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on a piece of wax paper, sift together flour, baking
powder and salt.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl of an electric mixer, beat eggs, sugar and
vanilla until well combined. With mixer on slow speed, add cooled
chocolate mixture, then dry ingredients. Blend well. Stir in
reserved chocolate bits and nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Drop by heaping teaspoons, 1-inch apart, onto prepared cookie
sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven 8 to 10 minutes. Or for 2-inch
cookies, drop by heaping tablespoons 2 inches apart and bake 10 to
12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cookies puff but won't firm up until cool, so don't overbake.
Place pan on a rack to cool a few minutes and then remove cookies
to rack to cool completely. Serve at room temperature. Cookies can
be stored, tightly covered, up to 3 months. Makes 50 to 60
cookies. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
PECAN CRESCENTS
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound (2 sticks) unsalted butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Pinch salt
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cake flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups finely ground pecan pieces
</P>
<P>
   Powdered sugar for rolling
</P>
<P>
   Line 2 baking sheets with parchment paper or foil.
</P>
<P>
   In a mixer bowl, beat butter, granulated sugar, vanilla and salt
together until well blended. Beat in flour and then nuts, scraping
down sides of bowl to incorporate. Chill dough if too sticky.
</P>
<P>
   Roll about 1 teaspoon of dough between floured palms into a
2-inch rope. Place on prepared baking sheet and curve to form a
crescent.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 325-degree oven 20 to 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Let crescents cool on baking sheets. Be sure they are completely
cool before you try to pick them up. Sift powdered sugar onto a
sheet of wax paper and roll crescents in it.
</P>
<P>
   Store crescents in a sturdy airtight food container between
layers of wax paper. Cookies may be frozen 3 months. Makes 60
cookies.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: When you make cookies ahead and freeze them, let them thaw
in a closed food tin. Then give them a quick sifting of powdered
sugar and serve.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
