<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5789 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-TROUBLES-COX     11-11 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TROUBLES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When good TV goes bad
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fall down, fall back, fall off, fall flat. All those falls and
more describe this fall's TV season.
</P>
<P>
   Ratings are down (for five of the six broadcast networks and
many old favorites) and grousing is up.
</P>
<P>
   Oh sure, blame the new shows. That's easy, and everybody does
it. But every new autumnal batch of TV series has more cheese than
a Wisconsin roadside stand. And this one was no worse than usual,
with several series _ ``Cupid,'' ``Felicity,'' ``Sports Night,''
``Trinity'' _ showing signs of real quality.
</P>
<P>
   Look instead to the returning series, and particularly the
A-list series, the ones with the big Nielsen numbers or the buzz or
both, the ``appointment TV'' the networks so desperately want to
create.
</P>
<P>
   Among the stragglers and strugglers:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``ER'' needs some paddles to the chest. The emphasis on new
character Lucy Knight (Kellie Martin) has skewed the No. 1 show on
TV, although it's bounced back a little. Ratings are down 7 percent
this season.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Frasier'' is more mopey than funny, with the travails of the
unemployed shrink sucking up time from the excellent supporting
cast. NBC knew ``Frasier'' wouldn't get ``Seinfeld'' ratings, but
is disappointed in the tune-in so far.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Ally McBeal,'' last season's buzz baby, has come up with
more dipsy-doodle stuff (the much-abused frog, the inscrutable
Ling), but most of the fan chatter has been about star Calista
Flockhart's weight.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Stalwarts ``The Drew Carey Show'' and ``Homicide: Life on the
Street'' have yet to connect on a memorable episode.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can just see they're not compelling,'' says Dorothy
Swanson, founder of Viewers for Quality Television, who says her
membership polls this season reflect widespread dissatisfaction
with many series. ```Party of Five' viewers are complaining that
the warmth is gone,'' she says. ```Mad About You' has completely
dropped off our list of endorsements.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all returning series are struggling. ``NYPD Blue'' has been
at its most riveting as it gently pushes Bobby Simone into that
good night, ``Friends'' seems brighter than usual, ``Everybody
Loves Raymond'' is finding the audience it deserved all along and
``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' is kicking keister. Ratings for all
four are up over last season.
</P>
<P>
   But, says Swanson, ``everybody in the country agrees about
'Frasier.' Where has the quality gone? Where has the writing
gone?''
</P>
<P>
   Why the problems?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Too many shows and not enough writing talent. Ten years ago
there were 66 prime-time entertainment shows at the beginning of
the 1988-'89 season. This fall's schedule had 96 entertainment
series, due to the expansion of Fox and the addition of WB and UPN.
Has the pool of talented writers increased by more than 30 percent
as well? Not hardly. More writers are being hired out of college.
More producers are getting deals with less experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real drain on talent, there's no question about
that,'' says Warren Littlefield, outgoing president of NBC
Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Producer Joel Shukovsky, who's seen hits (``Murphy Brown'') and
misses (``Living in Captivity''), uses more pungent language to
describe the mess:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a bunch of lemmings trying to crawl over each other
for the same talent at the same time for, in many cases and ways,
many of the same shows.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The networks have become more interested in whether they own
the show than whether the show is any good. That's perhaps an
overstatement, but closer to the truth than it should be.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the ``ER'' deal last season, the networks were
moving toward airing shows they own themselves rather than ones
they buy from studios, because they realized how much more money
they could make that way. But when Warner Bros. held up NBC for $13
million per episode for ``ER,'' that clinched it. Network
executives are now forced to focus on business issues more than
quality issues much more than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Successful creators are pressured to create more shows, which
diverts attention away from their continuing shows. John Wells,
executive producer of ``ER,'' launched ``Trinity'' this fall, just
as fan complaints about ``ER'' kicked in. Steven Bochco has
attempted four additional series since ``NYPD Blue'' debuted. One
prevalent theory as to why ``Frasier'' isn't as good is that the
creators went off to launch ``Encore! Encore!'' which bombed!
bombed!
</P>
<P>
   David Milch, Bochco's partner, notes that last season, they
produced 57 hours of TV, with ``NYPD'' and the failed series
``Brooklyn South'' and ``Total Security.'' ``There's no question
that if you're doing 22 (a typical season), you'll probably do
those 22 better,'' says Milch. With Milch and Bochco concentrating
on ``NYPD'' this season, that's obviously the case.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the late '70s, when cable TV, VCRs and remote
controls started becoming prevalent, the broadcast networks have
been declining. But the 1998 season may see the biggest
single-season drop-off yet. Overall ratings are down 9 percent for
the networks, with only WB showing an increase over last year.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's Thursday night lineup has suffered without ``Seinfeld,''
which is no surprise; what is shocking is how the audience for
``ER'' started the season strong at 32 million, then dropped
steadily over the next four weeks by a total of 4 million. That's
not a ``Seinfeld'' problem _ that's a rejection problem.
</P>
<P>
   Cable, meanwhile, is up 15 percent. Again, that's a continuation
of a trend, but it's a sizable jump in the increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``The networks are in a very difficult situation,'' says Bill
Cella, executive vice president of media buyer McCann-Erickson.
``It's hard and it's only going to get harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, most viewers don't care about cable vs. broadcast
trends. They want their favorite shows to be better.
</P>
<P>
   So get a job, Frasier. Get dancin', Ally. Get a grip, ``ER.''
Get back to giving us what we expect, networks.
</P>
<P>
   And for ``NYPD's'' Bobby Simone, whose fading heartbeat has been
this season's most compulsive hand-wringer: Get well.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
