<HEADLINE>
HERE'S A SWITCH: COMPANY MINES FOR GUIDES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Janet Ratzloff of Wheat Ridge, Colo., is known to be passionate
about rodeo and the Internet _ and it's paying off.
</P>
<P>
   For the past three years _ which, in World Wide Web years,
amounts to about 150 years _ she has maintained a quality homemade
site about rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   But like the rodeo competitors she loves to follow, Ratzloff
wanted to take her efforts up a notch and increase rodeo's
exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Upon advice from an acquaintance, she found the opportunity at
the Mining Co. (www.miningco.com), a New York-based company that
provides Web space for online users who specialize in a certain
subject.
</P>
<P>
   Ratzloff is the rodeo guide for a company whose motto is: ``We
mine the `Net so you don't have to.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mining Co.'s guide concept makes it stand apart from other
online efforts. The company certifies its guides, who must develop
and maintain their areas with appropriate content, links and
interactivity.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, guides are paid from advertising proceeds while the
Mining Co. markets their sites. At first, the rates were flat, but
now they're based on user traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guides are doing well financially,'' said Andrew Eisele,
the Mining Co.'s sports editor. ``Some we have on
getting-started-monthly stipends.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an elite group; only 25 percent of applicants are accepted.
The Mining Co. scrutinizes their sites during a screening process.
</P>
<P>
   The Mining Co. has guides in 13 categories, including sports.
The sports section alone has about 50 guides, including Ratzloff,
who brought with her a rodeo community she had cultivated since
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within each hub, there are a couple of star sites that you
wouldn't anticipate would be that popular,'' Eisele said. ``But
because the guide had their own Internet community set up
elsewhere, they were able to bring it to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Janet is an example of one of those who bought into the
philosophy and was able to hit the ground running. With some of the
other guides, it's taken a bit longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding a hub for a particular subject is a refreshing approach.
It puts all facets of a subject in an easy-to-access site (each
guide must follow an official Mining Co. page template to ensure
consistency). The hub concept also reduces the amount of time users
deal with search engines.
</P>
<P>
   Eisele said the Mining Co. is looking for reliable guides. As of
yesterday, the sports section needed guides for bowling, boxing,
college ice hockey, rugby, skateboarding and weightlifting.
</P>
<P>
   Ratzloff, who enjoys the creative freedom of writing a weekly
column on her site, said the Mining Co. makes Web surfing
practical.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our links categorized and you won't find that anywhere
else,'' she said. ``I like that because it makes it easier for
people.''
</P>
<P>
   And isn't that what makes for a good guide?
</P>
<P>
   (Tommy Cummings writes about the Internet for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7397. E-mail:
dragon(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
