<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 UPDATE &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Thursday, November 12,
1998.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SUSAN-SMITH _ UNION, S.C._ Linda Russell cannot reach into her
daughter's sick mind to understand her horrible crime. So she looks
for answers along the desolate highway where Susan Smith drove the
night she drowned her two little boys in a lake. For the first
time, Russell is talking publicly about the ghastly small-town
tragedy that sent chills down America's spine. Divorced now and
selling the brick ranch house where the saga unfolded four years
ago, the 54-year-old mother portrayed as cold, uncaring and
hard-edged is telling her story. ``I don't know that anybody
realizes how my family has grieved over all of this,'' said
Russell, sipping coffee and smoking Salem Lights on her back-porch
swing. It's the same place she sat, stunned and silent, on the
night of Nov. 3, 1994, after learning that two of her
grandchildren, Michael and Alex, were dead and their mother had
been charged with murder. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This story is the result of more than two years of efforts
by Burritt to get an interview with Linda Russell. Russell would
not agree to a photo, but Burritt took shots at John D. Long Lake
and at the memorial to the dead boys. File art of Russell should be
available.
</P>
<P>
   AUS-UT-REGENTS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ UT regents are expected to
approve the creation of a Regional Academic Health Center in the
Rio Grande Valley that is expected to cost an additional $20
million _ money likely to come from the Permanent University Fund
which funds ``excellence'' programs at UT-Austin and other schools.
The Legislature already has appropriated $30 million to build the
health center, which cities in the Valley have been competing for
heavily. This additional money will enable the board to create
medical research and training facilities to placate Valley cities
that lost out on the center. (Roser, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES-RESIDENTS _ EAST EVERGLADES, Fla. _ For decades,
they've lived in an odd limbo, halfway between one of American's
toughest urban centers and one of its most primitive natural
settings. Now the 1,600 or so property owners in the 8.5 square
mile East Everglades are being told their soggy ranches stand in
the way of saving the threatened Everglades. State officials are
expected to decide Thursday (Nov. 12) whether they will buy out the
landowners and return the land to its natural state. If not,
residents hope to get federal money to further drain their land and
end flooding problems. Some residents have already sold out, but
others don't want to be forced off the land, which they've grown to
love. (MWilliam, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AUS-VETERANS-DAY _ AUSTIN _ Veterans Day is celebrated with
parades and other activities, including a lecture at Southwest
Texas State given by Tuskegee Airmen. (Kelley, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   AUS-GLENN-SCHOOL _ AUSTIN _ Texas primary and middle-school
students who helped prepare an experiment for the Discovery space
shuttle on John Glenn's flight, on whether bacterial biofilms could
clog the shuttle's water recycling system began examining the
results this week in San Marcos. Conclusions, drawn by SWT
biologist McLean and NASA scientists, could affect future flights
to Mars. (Stanley, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   ISAKSON-NEWT _ ATLANTA _ Johnny Isakson announces his 6th
District candidacy Wednesday from the Marietta Square. We look at
who this impresses whether moderate Republicans like Chuck Clay or
anti-abortion candidates like Clint Day will stay out of race. Does
Newt Gingrich's all-but-endorsement take the pro-choice hex out of
an Isakson candidacy? Looking for interviews with Clay, Day,
right-wing operatives.
</P>
<P>
   (Williams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-EMERGENCY _ ATLANTA _ It's the latest education trend
coming to your neighborhood school: A disaster plan in case there's
a shooting. The Georgia Emergency Management Agency, GEMA, the
folks known for coordinating civil responses to natural disasters,
are now training school officials and school security officers to
handle, and help prevent, bloodshed in the schoolhouse. Since June,
GEMA has brought such training to 2,500 people in Georgia schools.
Conferences, like one on Tuesday, have been held at the Georgia
Public Safety Training Center, said Karen Franklin, hired this year
as GEMA's first victims' awareness coordinator. (Cumming, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY _ WASHINGTON _ As President Clinton and Congress
prepare for the difficult decisions of how to shore up Social
Security's finances, the option of privatizing some part of
beneficiaries' retirement accounts is still on the table. (Malone,
Cox News Service). Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (FOR COX THURS. PMS ONLY). KOREA-HALL _ PYONGYANG _ Ohio
Congressman Tony Hall is interviewed by Cox Asia correspondents
Marcia Kunstel and Joseph Albright following his latest trip into
North Korea. (Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   AUS-HONDURAS-AID _ Medico in Georgetown is heading up efforts to
transport supplies from Central Texas to Honduras. They're stashing
all their donations in the old cafeteria at Southwestern
University, which was vacated last month when a new student center
opened. This week, students are helping box up the supplies. The
first shipment is scheduled to leave Austin on a Medico plane next
week. Will include info on other Austin-area relief efforts.
(LeBlanc, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-WYE _ JERUSALEM _ On Wednesday, Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu is expected to finally have his cabinet ratify
the Wye Memorandum. But, ratification, according to a statement
released Tuesday, will be dependent on the Palestinians voting to
revoke the parts of the PLO charter the calls for armed resistance
to Israel. Why is this so important to Israel? Didn't the
Palestinians already do this? Why are Israel and the United States
fighting over it? (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   ENGLISH-POETS _ LONDON _ Many firms in England have something
called a ``resident poet,'' whose job it is to produce verse to
enhance corporate culture and morale. Among the companies with
poets on staff are the department store chain Marks &AMP; Spencer and a
big London law firm. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-AMWAY _ PORT AU PRINCE, Haiti _ Haitians earn an average
of $250 a year. The economy is in shambles. The future is unclear
due to a political vacuum. But that hasn't stopped Amway from
taking Haiti by storm. About 2,200 Haitians now sell Amway products
in this dirt-poor nation. Amway toothpaste sells for nearly $5.
Amway's 20-piece set of cookware sells for $941. The products have
become a kind of status symbol here the same way Tupperware has in
some parts of Latin America. (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in both the International and Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-SUMMIT _ ATLANTA _ Setup for Japanese Grassroots Summit
starting here this week. About 200 Japanese, some of them traveling
abroad for the first time, are taking part in the program, which is
being held in Atlanta for the first time in its eight-year history.
(Woo, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BARRY-INTERVIEW _ Interview with Irish writer and social
historian Sebastian Barry, who sees a change of heart among Irish
Americans. (Graham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
