<HEADER>
A5866 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-COLLECTION-GIFT-N     11-11 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-COLLECTION-GIFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART MUSEUM IN TEXAS GETS TROVE OF 700 WORKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, N.Y.)  (bl) 
 By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the largest and most important collections of Old Master
paintings and drawings in private hands will soon have a new home
at the Jack S. Blanton Museum of Art at the University of Texas at
Austin, leaving two New York institutions somewhat the poorer.
</P>
<P>
   The trove, estimated to be worth more than $30 million, was
assembled over two generations by William Suida and Robert and
Bertina Suida-Manning, all influential art historians. It comprises
700 works by Poussin, Veronese, Rubens, Tiepolo, Boucher, Correggio
and other Italian, French and German artists of the 14th to the
18th centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of them have been on long-term loan to the Metropolitan
Museum of Art in New York City, including ``The Conversion of St.
Paul,'' painted by Daniele Crespi about 1623, which is considered
to be the artist's finest painting in the United States, and
Guercino's ``Landscape With Tobias and Angel,'' circa 1616-17, an
important landscape. Twelve other works are on view at the Frances
Lehman Loeb Art Center at Vassar College in Poughkeepsie, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The works, known as the Suida-Manning Collection, are a partial
gift to the Blanton Museum by Kurt and Alessandra Manning Dolnier
of Watertown, Conn. Three anonymous donors have contributed $4.75
million toward the acquisition, and the university has pledged to
raise $15 million to complete it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a strong collection in Latin American art and in
prints, and we have a good collection in 20th-century American art,
but, except for prints, we really lack the core of Western art
history,'' said Jessie Otto Hite, the museum's director. ``This
collection gives us that core.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dolnier's father, Robert Lee Manning, wanted the collection
to go to an institution in his native Texas and wanted it to be
kept together.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dolnier said that several museums had courted her, but that
``we felt it would have a more dynamic home in a university.'' She
added, ``If it went to a museum like the Met, only the greatest
hits would be on display, and the rest would be in storage
somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Met art director Philippe de Montebello said the museum knew it
would have to give up the paintings. ``Had I ever thought that it
might be a gain, I would consider this a loss,'' he said, ``but we
always knew he wanted to sell the collection, and we were not
interested in acquiring it.''
</P>
<P>
   (In any case, the Met was recently on the receiving end of a
more valuable transfer. It acquired two van Gogh drawings valued at
$40 million under the terms of a bequest by philanthropist Abby
Aldrich Rockefeller stipulating that the drawings would after 50
years pass from the Museum of Modern Art in New York City to the
Met.)
</P>
<P>
   George Wachter, the expert in Old Masters at Sotheby's who
valued the works for the Manning estate, said: ``It's a tremendous
collection. For years, people have been giving me offers for many
of these works. I've had very high offers for them.'' Still, some
of the collection's pieces are ``student-level, best for study,''
Wachter added.
</P>
<P>
   Masterworks in the collection include ``The Annunciation,'' an
altarpiece by Veronese from the 1580s; Sebastiano del Piombo's
``Portrait of a Man,'' from about 1516, a rare example of a High
Renaissance portrait; Sebastiano Ricci's mythological ``Flora,''
circa 1712-16, which evokes Titian and Veronese; Claude Lorrain's
``Pastoral Landscape,'' from 1628-30, a very early work, and
Tiepolo's ``Storyteller,'' from 1765, part of a famous series
depicting 18th-century Venice.
</P>
<P>
   The collection, which contains about 250 paintings, 400 drawings
and 50 sculptures, has dozens of examples of regional schools of
Italian painting.
</P>
<P>
   William Suida, an Austrian-born art historian who died in 1959,
started buying art in the early 1900s and became an authority on
Italian art, particularly Genoese painting. In 1939, he moved to
New York and worked as the principal adviser to Samuel H. Kress.
</P>
<P>
   Suida's daughter, Bertina, and her husband shared her father's
passion, and they added extensively to the family holdings and
promoted Baroque art in the United States. She became curator of
the Chrysler Collection; Manning was curator at the Kress
Foundation and later director of the Finch College Museum of Art in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   At their house in Forest Hills, Queens, New York City, paintings
hung on virtually every wall, including in the kitchen and the
cloakroom, and many more were stacked in cupboards and under the
beds. Bertina Manning died in 1992 and Robert Manning in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   About a year before his death, Manning paid a visit to the
Blanton and called Ms. Hite from the galleries. ``He said, `Hello,
I'm Robert Manning, have you ever heard of me?' I said no,'' she
recalled in a telephone interview. But she invited him to coffee
and called in Jonathan Bober, the museum's curator of prints and
drawings, who had seen many of the Suida-Manning acquisitions as a
student.
</P>
<P>
   Manning later invited Ms. Hite and Bober to his home. ``He took
us around to all the pictures _ he was testing Jonathan,'' Ms. Hite
said. ``It went on all day, and then they started on the
drawings.'' Bober apparently passed muster, and Manning began
planning to leave the collection to the Blanton.
</P>
<P>
   The Blanton, which owns 12,000 works of Western art dating from
antiquity to the present, is Austin's only encyclopedic museum. It
recently announced plans to construct a $40 million,
100,000-square-foot building that will bring together all its
holdings, and an architect is expected to be announced soon.
Selections from the Suida-Manning Collection will go on view in the
existing museum early next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
