<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILESTONES
</P>
<P>
   Not content with celebrating the 30th anniversary of his debut
with the New York Philharmonic, Sir Colin Davis will officially
assume his position as the orchestra's principal guest conductor
when he leads the first of three subscription concerts Thursday
night at Avery Fisher Hall. In this role, Sir Colin will spend at
least three weeks each season with the Philharmonic.
</P>
<P>
   SUCCESS STORY
</P>
<P>
   Flabbergasted when its letter to Queen Elizabeth II led to an
invitation, a previously unknown teen-age British rock band will
perform Friday at a 50th-birthday celebration for Prince Charles.
The Daily Mail reported Wednesday that the four members of Al!ve,
who are 16 and 17, wrote: ``Dear Your Majesty. We are four good
lads who don't do drugs, aren't scruffy and don't use foul language
(maybe that's where we've been going wrong!). Anyway if you can
give us a break it would really be cool. With our love to you and
the royal family.''
</P>
<P>
   RERUN
</P>
<P>
   What are they studying at Dartmouth? Friday through Sunday,
scholars will gather on the campus in Hanover, N.H., to discuss the
Russian filmmaker Sergei Eisenstein (1898-1948). The conference
``Eisenstein at 100: A Reconsideration'' asks to what extent a
world that has witnessed the decay of the Soviet Union can still
value Eisenstein, who worked under official auspices and produced
films like ``Alexander Nevsky'' that ostensibly upheld Soviet
ideals.
</P>
<P>
   REPARATION
</P>
<P>
   To return to their rightful owners more than 171 paintings
looted by the Nazis, the French foreign ministry is distributing an
illustrated catalog of the missing works to museums and art
galleries worldwide. Most of the works are by Flemish and Dutch
masters and were seized during World War II from Adolphe Schloss, a
Jew.
</P>
<P>
   NEW CHAPTER
</P>
<P>
   One of Sweden's leading literary critics, Horace Engdahl, has
been chosen to lead the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel
Prize in Literature. Engdahl, 49, will succeed Sture Allen as the
academy's permanent secretary. Allen, who has held the post since
1986, turns 70 on Dec. 31 and is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   PRIZED
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantic Theater Company has won the 1998 Jujamcyn Theaters
Award, carrying a $50,000 prize. The annual award goes to a
resident theater that has made an outstanding contribution to the
development of creative talent for the theater. Recent productions
by the Atlantic, an artistic ensemble founded in 1985 by David
Mamet and William H. Macy, are ``The Beauty Queen of Leenane'' by
Martin McDonagh, ``Mojo'' by Jez Butterworth and ``Edmond'' by
Mamet.
</P>
</TEXT>
