<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMEDY-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FUNNY WOMAN IS A DANGEROUS ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``A guy I know is in a men's group: `Single
Heterosexual Men Who Harbor No Hostility Toward Women.' What is
there, one member?''
</P>
<P>
   So go the jokes in Susie Essman's stand-up comedy routine. It
isn't that Ms. Essman has anything against men in general, but jabs
at the male gender are a staple of her act, perhaps because she
remembers a time not so very long ago when men treated women and
comedy as a contradiction in terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of male comedians would say, `Women just aren't funny,''
Ms. Essman said. ``It was a tremendous proving we had to do, and
did.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Ms. Essman, who would not tell her age, said the
comedy circuit is more welcoming to women but that it is still not
easy. ``It's hard to be a comic of any gender _ it's hard to go out
there and make strangers laugh _ but you have to be that much
better as a woman,'' she said. ``It's easier for a mediocre man
than a mediocre woman.''
</P>
<P>
   It is less to redress this disadvantage than to celebrate funny
women that Marshalls, the discount clothing chain, is presenting a
``Women in Comedy'' festival, which opened Wednesday night and runs
through Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The festival will feature more than 50 female comedians,
including established names like Rita Rudner, Joy Behar and Kathy
Griffin and several less well known like Dani Leon, Tracy Esposito
and Carie Karavas.
</P>
<P>
   The event, which opened with a gala at Carnegie Hall with Mary
Tyler Moore as host, will take place at venues throughout New York
and will benefit two nonprofit organizations that deal with
domestic violence, Victim Services and the Center for Children and
Families.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Essman, who will be performing on Saturday at the comedy
club Stand-Up New York, has been one of the more fortunate female
comics. She has become a regular fixture at clubs across the United
States, has appeared on several television comedy specials and is
the host of a daily local cable talk show, ``MSG Metro.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Essman said she was still the exception to the rule.
Many people still believe that women are not meant to make people
laugh for a living and that being funny is not feminine, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectation was that women could not control a crowd, that
they couldn't hold a crowd, they didn't have the power,'' she said.
``Tomboy funny is OK, fat funny's OK, bimbo funny's OK. Sexy funny
_ that's a combination that's really scary.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Ms. Essman said, some women hinder their own
progress as comedians because they lack the sense of entitlement
needed to take a stage. ``Stand-up is a very aggressive art form,
and a lot of women don't feel comfortable expressing that kind of
aggression _ they're taught not to,'' she said. ``If women could
get beyond that discomfort they feel with power, I think they could
be such great comics. Because part of stand-up is taking care of
the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Essman said that when she was growing up, there was a dearth
of female role models in comedy and the few that existed tended to
make jokes at their own expense. ``The only comics I remember were
Phyllis Diller and Joan Rivers, both of whom did self-deprecating
material _ I think because they had to at that time or the public
would not have accepted them,'' Ms. Essman said. ``And I didn't
want to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Essman, who grew up in Westchester County and now lives in
Manhattan, said she has no trouble being the center of attention or
putting herself on the line in public. That was her style even as a
child, she said, adding that her parents have supported her career.
``It's not that different for them from what I always did,'' she
said. ``When I was 9 years old, I was standing up on the kitchen
table and making fun of my grandmother and the neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just praying I don't talk about them,'' she continued.
``And I think they're happy to see me on TV; my mother hasn't left
the house for the last few months.''
</P>
</TEXT>
