<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5885 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-H     11-11 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL'S CABINET RATIFIES MIDDLE EAST PEACE ACCORD ... WITH
STIPULATIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ After a two-week delay, Israel's Cabinet Wednesday
ratified the U.S.-brokered Middle East peace accord, but attached
conditions for its implementation that likely will set the stage
for renewed conflict with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The vote of eight to four with five abstentions sets in motion a
three-month timetable during which Israel will transfer 13 percent
of West Bank territory to the Palestinians, release 750 Palestinian
prisoners, open an airport in Gaza and a safe passage connecting
the Gaza Strip to the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The Knesset, Israel's Parliament, will debate and vote on the
agreement during two days next week. It is expected to pass easily.
</P>
<P>
   The first land transfer of 2 percent should then happen, a few
days after the Nov. 16 deadline set out in the accords.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly seven hours of debate, the cabinet said Israel
would put the agreement into action only if Palestinians nullified
clauses of the Palestine Charter offensive to Israel and refrained
from declaring independence next May.
</P>
<P>
   It also limited to 1 percent any further West Bank land transfer
to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we intend to continue implementing the entire
agreement,'' Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said shortly
after the Cabinet vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``(But) we require the Palestinian side to comply with its
commitments in fighting terror and to re-convene the Palestinian
National Council to vote and delete the anti-Israel clauses in the
Palestinian Charter.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu added that the cabinet would convene to verify
Palestinians had complied with their commitments as each step of
the agreement was implemented.
</P>
<P>
   The conditions, which require Palestinians to go beyond what
they agreed to during nine days of marathon talks at the Wye River
conference center in the United States last month, underscore the
difficulty Netanyahu had in selling the agreement to his hard-line
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu had set out to convince a cabinet of religious
rightists and security hawks that the Wye accord ``plugged holes''
that he said were left in earlier interim peace accords, including
a Palestinian obligation to change parts of its national charter
that Israel interprets as a call for its destruction.
</P>
<P>
   But the cabinet demanded more stringent guarantees than were set
out in the Wye agreement. That agreement calls on Palestinians only
to ``reaffirm'' a decision taken two years ago to delete certain
clauses in the charter.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also stipulates that a joint committee will
negotiate the size of an additional West Bank land transfer to the
Palestinians, known as the third redeployment.
</P>
<P>
   The add-ons seem poised to trip up efforts to pull peace
negotiations out of a 20-month deep freeze just as they seemed
ready to thaw.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians lambasted the cabinet additions and warned that
they would ignore any demands not laid out explicitly in signed
agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're committed to implementing the Wye accords to the
letter,'' said Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat. ``But any
addition or anything outside the framework of the agreement will
not be considered by us.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the cabinet demands, it is likely the ceiling of 1
percent placed on the third redeployment most likely to rankle
Palestinians. The issue, a major stumbling block during the Wye
negotiations, was solved at the last minute by empowering a
committee to decide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider it a flagrant violation of the accord,'' Erekat
said. ``The agreement says that a joint committee will decide.
Israel is not negotiating by itself and Israel cannot decide by
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Palestinians say clauses in the charter offensive to
Israel were excised in April 1996, when most of the then-500-member
Palestine National Council convened in Gaza and voted by an
overwhelming majority to make the changes.
</P>
<P>
   They say the 170-member executive council of the PNC will
convene in Gaza in December to listen to an address by President
Bill Clinton and to ``reaffirm'' the earlier decision _ but the PNC
will not reconvene and the smaller Palestinian ruling body will not
take another vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position on that is very clear: The job that was demanded
of us was done a long time ago,'' said Marwan Kanafani, one of
Palestinian President Yasser Arafat's advisers. ``The matter to us
is mission accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians also left open the option of declaring statehood in
the West Bank and Gaza once interim peace deals expire in May 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The threat, which has clouded negotiations since Arafat first
broached the possibility months ago, has prompted Israel to counter
with threats to annex those parts of the West Bank still under its
control.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, both Netanyahu and Israeli Foreign Minister Ariel
Sharon repeated the threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Palestinians take unilateral decisions _ and we
recommend they don't _ Israel will consider itself free to adopt
unilateral measures, and one of them is to apply Israeli laws to
the areas of Jewish settlement and military areas (in the West
Bank),'' Sharon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government took that decision today,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   In what appeared to be efforts to convince right-wing skeptics,
Sharon, Israel's reigning security hawk, described cabinet members
as doing all they could to safeguard Israel's vital interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made every possible effort not to damage the areas around
Jerusalem, to protect water resources, to safeguard the places holy
to Jerusalem, the defense areas and the access routes,'' he said
after the cabinet vote.
</P>
<P>
   His words and the extra cabinet conditions failed to sway tens
of thousands of Israelis who gathered in Tel Aviv to protest
ratification of the accord under the banner ``We remain faithful to
the land of Israel'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Horan is a free-lance journalist based in Jerusalem. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
