<HEADER>
A5892 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLIMATE-ARGENTINA-240     11-11 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIMATE-ARGENTINA-240&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARGENTINA JOINS EFFORT TO CURB GASES LINKED TO GLOBAL WARMING 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By WILLIAM K. STEVENS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In what was described in several quarters as an important
breakthrough, Argentina signaled Wednesday that it would
voluntarily become the first developing country to adopt binding
targets and timetables for controlling emissions of heat-trapping
industrial waste gases believed to cause global warming.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, developing countries have presented an uncrackable
united front in resisting specific limits on their emissions of
greenhouse gases like carbon dioxide, which are produced by the
burning of coal, oil, wood and natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   Rich countries agreed in Kyoto, Japan, last December to make
emissions reductions averaging about 5 percent below 1990 levels in
the period 2008 to 2012, but the poorer nations have refused to
follow suit until the industrialized countries are actually showing
results.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, at a follow-up conference to the Kyoto meeting in
Buenos Aires, Argentine President Carlos Menem said his country
would establish ``goals'' for carbon-dioxide emissions and in about
a year would announce its commitment to those goals for the period
2008 to 2010.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emerging countries also share the responsibility to assume
their own initiatives to face and solve every challenge of the 21st
century,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Julia Alsogaray, an Argentinian who is also presiding over
the Buenos Aires meeting, later described the goals not as
emissions reductions but as limitations on emissions growth.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While Menem's speech was somewhat general, Stuart Eizenstat, the
head of the U.S. delegation, said he had been told by the Argentine
president that Argentina would spend the next year analyzing its
emissions profile with the objective of producing a specific,
binding emissions target.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major, major move,'' Eizenstat said. ``We think it's
truly historic.''
</P>
<P>
   There were indications that other developing countries might
eventually follow now that Argentina has led the way, some
participants in the Buenos Aires talks said. ``No one wants to be
the first one out of the box,'' said Connie Holmes, the chairwoman
of the Global Climate Coalition, which represents fossil-fuel
producers and users. She called Argentina's action ``great,'' if it
can find a way to follow through. ``If they want to do it, more
power to them,'' said Ms. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   But, she pointed out, it may be difficult for Argentina to be
brought into the international process under the Kyoto Protocol to
the 1992 global climate treaty, since no developing countries are
covered by it. How that might happen remains to be worked out over
months or even years. Argentina wants to pursue its
emissions-control program by taking advantage of some of the
protocol's cost-cutting mechanisms like trading of emissions
rights, Eizenstat said he was told. This, Menem said, implies the
creation of a ``new way,'' under the 1992 treaty, to involve his
country and others like it.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, said Ms. Holmes, Argentina's shift will not in itself
satisfy the U.S. Senate, which has made participation by key
developing countries a condition for ratifying the Kyoto Protocol.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists hailed the development. ``It is a major
breakthrough,'' said Michael Oppenheimer of the Environmental
Defense Fund. ``I don't think there's any doubt about it.'' He
called the Argentine move ``a significant first step'' in
satisfying the Senate's requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The move also represented ``a clear break'' from the developing
countries' past insistence that binding limitations would put a cap
on their economic growth, said Alden Meyer, a spokesman for the
Climate Action Network, a global environmental coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Menem said Argentina's economy had grown by 6 percent a year in
the last decade while greenhouse gases per capita had grown by only
1 percent, and he said his country's purpose was to erase ``the
false option between economic growth and environmental
protection.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
