<HEADLINE>
TEXAN FROST COULD BE ELEVATED TO CHAIRMAN OF DEMOCRATIC CAUCUS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While Republicans are still fighting over a new
House leadership team, Democrats will hold their own elections on
Monday that could elevate Rep. Martin Frost of Texas to the No. 3
spot in the minority as chairman of the Democratic caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Frost currently holds down the No. 4 job as head of the
congressional campaign committee, where he has spent the last four
years raising money, recruiting candidates and helping the party
recover many of the seats it lost when the Republicans took control
of Congress in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Frost is in a tight race against the more liberal Rep. Rosa
DeLauro of Connecticut to replace retiring caucus Chairman Vic
Fazio of California. If he pulls it off, the moderate Texan would
be in position to help shape the Democratic legislative agenda for
the next two years and communicate the party's message as it heads
toward the presidential and congressional elections of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I couldn't tell you whether Martin or Rosa has it
locked up,'' said one Democratic aide. ``I think the conference is
pretty much split because they both have a lot to offer and have
done well in the jobs they hold.''
</P>
<P>
   Working for DeLauro is the fact that she a liberal in a
Democratic conference that has traditionally elected more liberal
members to high-profile leadership positions. The fact that she is
a woman is also appealing to many members, who would like to see a
female in one of the conference's top three posts for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   Another plus for DeLauro is that she was in charge of getting
the party's ``daily message out'' during the legislative battles of
the 105th Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Frost on the other hand, has spent the last four years as head
of the DCCC building a power base of money and IOUs from old and
new members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   At 56, Frost was just re-elected to an 11th term. He is seen as
someone who can bring together the various factions of the
Democratic caucus. In addition to having the support of his Texas
Democratic House colleagues, he has also managed to gain backing
from influential conservative and liberal members of the 211-member
conference, as well as a sizable chunk of the 23 freshmen Democrats
who will be sworn in next January.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to present a more moderate image and Martin, I think,
will do that for us,'' said Rep. Gene Green of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Frost appears to have edge at the moment over
DeLauro. ``Before the election (which gave the Democrats five more
seats in the House ) I was concerned about it. But I feel better
about it now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's voting in the caucus is not expected to change the
faces at the very top of the Democratic leadership. House Minority
Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri, for example, will remain as the
No. 1 Democratic leader in the House, while Rep. David Bonior of
Michigan will be returned to his No. 2 job as minority whip.
</P>
<P>
   Texans Chet Edwards and Green are also expected to remain in
their appointed positions as deputy whips.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of members will be running against one another for
the job Frost is leaving as head of the DCCC. They include Reps.
Patrick Kennedy of Rhode Island, Frank Pallone of California and
Nancy Pelosi of California.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, meanwhile, were still embroiled Wednesday in
their own leadership shootouts. Although Rep. Bob Livingston of
Louisiana has the biggest job of all _ speaker of the House _ all
locked up, House Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas is still in a
fight for his survival.
</P>
<P>
   Although his aides insist that he will have the 112 votes needed
to be re-elected when the 223-member GOP conference meets next
Wednesday, his opponents Steve Largent of Oklahoma and Jennifer
Dunn of Washington dispute that.
</P>
<P>
   There is also talk of others jumping into the race against
Armey, as more and more members indicate they would like to see the
Texan replaced. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
