<HEADLINE>
FRANCE HAS ITS OWN SEX-AND-POLITICS SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ France dismissed the Monica Lewinsky affair as
puritanical persecution of President Clinton, but it is in the
middle of a sex-and-politics scandal of its own, the seamiest in
years.
</P>
<P>
   The man at the center of it, Roland Dumas, the country's
fifth-highest official as head of the independent Constitutional
Council, said on Tuesday that he had no intention of resigning
despite a call for his removal by former President Valery Giscard
d'Estaing.
</P>
<P>
   Dumas, 76, was foreign minister in 1991 when his close friend
and fellow Socialist Francois Mitterrand, the president at the
time, allowed a $2.7 billion sale of six French-built warships to
Taiwan to go ahead after Dumas dropped his longstanding opposition
to the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators placed Dumas under investigation, considered one
step short of indictment, in April and are trying to find out
whether a lobbyist friend of his named Christine Deviers-Joncour
got him to change his mind, possibly in exchange for money,
clothing and other favors.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Deviers-Joncour has told investigators that she was paid
$11.3 million and given a lavish Paris apartment by the big French
oil company Elf Aquitaine SA, then state-owned, just for using
longstanding personal connections with Dumas. Elf Aquitaine is
alleged by prosecutors to have offered her services to the
contractor that built the frigates, Thomson-CSF, also
state-controlled at the time. Elf Aquitaine has not commented on
the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   All this had been bubbling quietly until last week, when Mrs.
Deviers-Joncour came out with a book titled ``The Whore of the
Republic,'' published by Calmann-Levy.
</P>
<P>
   Excerpts from the book and photos in France's leading gossip
magazine, the weekly Paris Match, showed the silver-maned Dumas
nuzzling up to the lobbyist, both in bathing suits on the sands of
Aquitaine in southwest France, and lunching romantically with her
in New York at the River Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Elf Aquitaine sent her to New York in 1991, she wrote, on a
crash mission to sweet-talk the foreign minister into getting
Mitterrand to stop during a Middle East swing in a country where
the oil company was hoping to make a major deal. She did and Elf
Aquitaine got it, and thought she had earned her pay on that alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``To live such an intense relationship with a man on an
emotional basis while at the same time knowing this relationship
served economic interests was not easy for me to do,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   She made no charge that Dumas had been paid off. But some of his
conservative critics began to wonder how, with all this unseemly
publicity, he could go on impartially hearing and deciding major
issues in the Constitutional Council.
</P>
<P>
   A few conservatives, like Giscard, began making noises
encouraging their fellow conservative, President Jacques Chirac, to
dismiss him or force him to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac remained silent, and until Tuesday, so did Dumas, who as
a practicing lawyer had a long list of prominent clients in the
arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had nothing to do with Elf executives when I was foreign
minister, outside of my official functions,'' he said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not receive before, during or after the period when I
was the head of French diplomacy any money for any reason from the
officials of this company, or from its agents, among whom I include
Christine Deviers-Joncour, who was among the persons on its
payroll,'' he said. ``Having a clear conscience, I will continue in
all serenity and in all objectivity to preside over the
Constitutional Council, whose functioning is not affected.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you here for me or for Elf Aquitaine?'' Mrs.
Deviers-Joncour wrote that Dumas once asked her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you doubt that I will always be here for you?'' she said
she replied.
</P>
</TEXT>
