<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-KILLING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLEGED LEADER OF FATAL ATTACK AGAINST BLACK MAN PROCLAIMS HIS
INNOCENCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a rambling, convoluted letter written from his Livingston,
Texas, prison cell and sent to a newspaper, the alleged leader of a
fatal attack against a black man in Jasper, Texas, has proclaimed
his innocence and blamed one of his co-defendants.
</P>
<P>
   John William ``Bill'' King, one of three white men charged with
capital murder in the June dragging and decapitation death of James
Byrd Jr., claimed in a seven-page letter to the Dallas Morning News
that the crime grew out of a dispute over the sale of steroids. He
said it was not racially motivated, as authorities allege.
</P>
<P>
   King, 24, contended in the letter that he was an uninvolved
witness to the killing by his co-defendant Shawn Berry, 23, whom he
described as an abuser of steroids with an ``irate temper.'' Byrd,
King wrote, was Berry's source for the body-building drugs, the use
of which can lead to erratic behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities dismissed King's letter as a transparent attempt to
point the finger at someone other than himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is common. It's not unusual at all,'' said Jasper County
District Attorney Guy James Gray. ``We have already looked into the
things set out in that letter.''
</P>
<P>
   Jasper County Sheriff's Chief Deputy Paul Brister said
authorities found no evidence that steroid sale or use was
connected to the killing.
</P>
<P>
   King's attorney, C. Haden Cribbs of Beaumont, said his client's
letter to the newspaper was written against his recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he's a prolific writer,'' Cribbs said Wednesday. ``I
haven't seen this letter ... but I have a standing policy of
telling clients not to make comments that can come back on them.''
</P>
<P>
   King's father, Ronald King of Jasper, typed the statement for
his son and released it to the newspaper at his son's request. It
is the defendant's first public comment since his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, which quoted Mark Twain and Garrison Keillor,
Bill King conceded that he and the third suspect, Russell Brewer,
had accompanied Berry on a nightlong cruise through the Jasper
area.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, King said, had used a chain to pull down roadside
mailboxes. As Berry became increasingly intoxicated and
belligerent, King said, he and Brewer asked to be taken home.
</P>
<P>
   Berry then stopped to offer a ride to Byrd, 49, because he
wanted to discuss ``business'' with the Jasper man, King said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities later found Byrd's battered and decapitated body at
the end of a three-mile-long trail of blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't make anything of it (King's letter),'' said Berry's
attorney, Lum Hawthorn of Beaumont, Texas. ``Our position is, as it
always has been, that Mr. Byrd was beaten and dragged by King and
Mr. Brewer. My client was present when that occurred and tried to
stop it. He did not participate in it to any degree. That's the
only comment we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Christie Marcontell, Berry's girlfriend of four years, dismissed
King's letter as ``a bunch of crap.''
</P>
<P>
   And James Byrd Sr., father of the slain man, denied that his son
had any connection with steroids or other drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter to the Dallas newspaper, King also suggested that
the apparent Nazi- and Ku Klux Klan-related tattoos on his body
were misinterpreted.
</P>
<P>
   King denied that he and Brewer were members of any ``confirmed
hate group,'' but ended his letter, which was titled ``Logical
Reasoning,'' by noting, ``I, John W. King, remain White and
Proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Byrd's killing, relatives of Berry reported that
King previously had written vitriolic, racist letters while in
prison for violation of parole on a burglary charge. (King and
Berry served time for the same burglary.)
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just unbelievable _ all about being racist, about
hating black people,'' said a woman, who asked for anonymity. ``
`Hail to the Brotherhood,' and all that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the letters, written to a teen-age girl, were so
frightening that the teen's parents asked prison authorities to
intercede to stop the letters, the woman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were crazy letters,'' the woman said. ``It really scared
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman said King long was known for making racial jokes,
though he never, to her knowledge, acted on his beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill has always done the racial thing,'' she said, ``but we
didn't believe he felt it in his heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, lawyers confirmed Wednesday that the defendants will
be tried separately. King's trial will be held in February,
Brewer's in March and Berry's late next year. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
