<HEADER>
A5944 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELAY-PROFILE-TEX     11-11 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELAY-PROFILE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELAY MAY BE LAST TEXAN STANDING IN THE HOUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Maria Recio 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He's just as conservative as departing House
Speaker Newt Gingrich, and he can be just as tough on his
Democratic foes as House Majority Leader Richard Armey. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although Gingrich is on his way out and Armey is fending off
challengers, House Majority Whip Tom DeLay is the only member of
the House hierarchy headed for unopposed re-election when
Republicans vote for leadership positions Nov. 18. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The secret of DeLay's success lies in the very culture of the
House of Representatives. The Republican-controlled House is, in
many ways, like a small town _ albeit one where everyone has a
large ego _ in which residents have day-to-day needs and demands. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And in the House, as in a town, there is a Man to See: Tom
DeLay. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His ability to take care of members has given him such a
formidable power base that many Republicans look to him as a
kingmaker who can tip a race, especially for the majority leader
position held by Armey, a Texan like DeLay. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several members credit his quick endorsement of Rep. Bob
Livingston, R-La., as decisive in locking up the post after
Gingrich announced his resignation. Livingston's only rival, Rep.
Christopher Cox, R-Calif., soon quit the race. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the hotly contested three-way majority leader race,
members want to know: What will DeLay do? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom DeLay is the guy that every leadership candidate wants in
their camp,'' said Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., an Armey supporter.
DeLay commands a loyal 66-member whip team, so is the one leader
who could conceivably swing an election. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, 51, is holding back so far on picking a favorite in the
Armey race, and aides say he will stay out of the contest. But just
the fact that he hasn't endorsed his fellow Texan, with whom he has
an uneasy relationship, has blown open the race. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Armey is the front-runner, but he faces challenges from the GOP
right wing _ Rep. Steve Largent of Oklahoma _ and moderate wing _
Rep. Jennifer Dunn of Washington state. And at a time when the GOP
has a tenuous majority, some members are agitating for a more
diverse leadership profile as well as a house-cleaning. None of the
three has the 112 votes needed for a majority win on the first
ballot, GOP insiders say, although Armey press secretary Michele
Davis says Armey has ``over 100'' votes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What's most fascinating is the emergence of Tom DeLay as
perhaps the most powerful person on Capitol Hill,'' said Marshall
Wittman, director of congressional relations at the Heritage
Foundation, a conservative think tank. ``He has emerged as
kingmaker.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ideologically, DeLay speaks on behalf of the cultural issues
that some Republicans say dilute the party's emphasis on fiscal
conservatism and tax cuts. And he has been a relentless critic of
President Clinton, calling for his resignation and pressing for
impeachment even as his GOP colleagues worried that attacks on
Clinton turned off voters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the eyes of House Republicans, DeLay, a 14-year House
veteran, is an exceptional asset. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the chief vote-counter, DeLay is also the chief vote-getter
for tough pieces of legislation, and he has developed an
extraordinary information network to determine what it takes to get
a member's vote, from a project to legislation. As the GOP's hold
on the House has narrowed, he has managed to deliver enough votes
to pass legislation, sometimes by a vote or two. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows everyone's quirks and what punches their buttons,''
said Rep. Henry Bonilla, R-San Antonio. ``He's extremely
detail-oriented. He knows what everyone's needs are.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Each of the 66 members of DeLay's intelligence network is
assigned a small group of lawmakers to lobby on key votes. As a
result, his reach extends to every Republican member. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DeLay's deputy chief of staff, Tony Rudy, said DeLay fields bids
for everything from pork-barrel projects to a committee assignment
to a game of golf. ``No request is too small and no request is too
big,'' Rudy said. His office even provides meals in the cloakroom
when sessions run late; barbecue is a big favorite. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DeLay comes by his nickname, ``The Hammer,'' honestly; if
members don't vote with the leadership, they will hear from him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jay Dickey, R-Ark., knows firsthand. When the House voted
Oct. 8 to open an impeachment investigation of President Clinton,
Dickey was the only Republican to vote for the Democratic
alternative. Democrats wanted a limited inquiry that would conclude
by year's end, but Republicans prevailed in an open-ended
investigation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DeLay did not want a single Republican to endorse the White
House-backed plan, and he confronted Dickey on the floor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He was genuinely upset at first,'' Dickey said. ``He was angry
and said, `You don't know what you're doing.' He was very adamant
that it was a poor political decision.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For all his arm-twisting, DeLay remains popular because of his
reputation as a straight shooter. Member after member cites his
candor after an aborted coup attempt against Gingrich in the summer
of 1997. A group of conservatives unhappy with the speaker's
compromises wanted to unseat him and sought the support of the rest
of the leadership. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the plot came unglued, DeLay acknowledged his complicity in
a public meeting of all Republicans, but members felt Armey was
less than truthful about his role in the plot. The episode also
eroded the longtime friendship between Armey and DeLay. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When the coup occurred, DeLay told the truth. He didn't
varnish it,'' Dickey said. ``It's fared him quite well.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DeLay also became better known nationally after last summer's
Capitol Hill shooting, which left two police officers dead,
including one in the whip's suite. The Texan's eulogy and show of
support for the families enhanced his standing, congressional aides
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As restive House members challenge the leadership Nov. 18,
DeLay's skills at the inside game could mean that he will be the
last Texan standing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maria Recio, (202) 383-6103 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   mrecio &LR; krwashington.com &QL;
</P>
