<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE CAN LIVE WITH HIGHER SPEED LIMITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: The nanny state and its advocates were dealt a big
setback recently, but many Americans may have missed this
development because of lack of media interest.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad, because it was one of those good-news stories that
deserved a lot more attention than it received. In case you haven't
heard, the death rate on America's roadways fell to a record low
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The rate was 1.6 deaths per 100 million miles, which was the
lowest since the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration
began keeping records 30 years ago. The National Safety Council
also has reported that last year's 16.1 traffic fatalities per
100,000 people was the third straight annual decline and tied a
record set in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   What makes all this particularly remarkable is how the
improvement followed dire predictions three years ago that
eliminating federally mandated speed limits would be a national
disaster. The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration went
so far as to predict 6,400 additional road deaths a year if a 65
mph speed limit became the national norm.
</P>
<P>
   Since Congress repealed the national speed-limit law in '95,
however, the roads have become safer rather than more dangerous
despite a trend toward higher speed limits. Last year's actual
death toll of 41,967 was slightly lower than the previous year's
and slightly higher than 1995's.
</P>
<P>
   It's also worth noting that the declining roadway death rate
occurred when the economy was growing, which usually boosts highway
deaths because good times equate with increased driving.
</P>
<P>
   All of which would seem sweet vindication for those who not only
have contended all along that the speed-kills theory was flawed,
but also offered strong support for their case. The opposition
never got much respect, though, because of the superior persuasive
powers of the nanny-state lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Even, for instance, as federal safety officials were predicting
more carnage from higher speed limits, there were reputable studies
indicating otherwise. Moreover, practical anecdotal evidence from
driving experience on Germany's autobahn showed it to be
statistically safer than U.S. roads even though it has no posted
speed limits and denser traffic than America's highways.
</P>
<P>
   Artificially low speed limits, however, were symbolic of the
nanny-state mind-set. The feds first imposed 55 mph limits in the
early '70s as a gasoline conservation measure. When the petroleum
problem was revealed to be a creature of ill-advised government
regulation, those loath to see government lose control over drivers
shifted the focus from conservation to safety.
</P>
<P>
   The economic burden it created in lost time and money for the
surface transportation industry is incalculable. The reciprocal,
the cynics noticed, was that this government intrusion into the
nation's driving life created some interesting economic
beneficiaries who got on the speed-kills bandwagon. Insurance
companies and local governments, for example, were said to favor
low speed limits because speeding tickets boosted both auto
insurance premium income and municipal revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the worst result was a growing contempt for the law as
most drivers ignored posted speed limits and drove at what they
considered prudent speeds, which is what students of driving
behavior said was always the case anyway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 1911EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
