<SLUG> BC-VETERAN-MEDAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 80 YEARS, FRANCE PAYING TRIBUTE TO WORLD WAR I VETERAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE PENN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ McKinley Wooden, at age 103, was to be
decorated for military service.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the 80th anniversary of Armistice Day, he was to
receive the Legion of Honor, France's highest medal. French
officials were to be in Kansas City to present the award to Wooden
during Veterans Day ceremonies at Liberty Memorial, the monument
dedicated to soldiers who fought in World War I.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the only recognition the Lee's Summit, Mo., resident is
getting this week. Sunday night, the former chief mechanic of
Battery D _ the World War I artillery unit commanded by Harry S.
Truman _ was featured in a History Channel documentary exploring
the struggles of American veterans.
</P>
<P>
   French President Jacques Chirac instituted the campaign to honor
surviving members of the U.S. armed forces who fought on French
soil during World War I. An estimated 3,200 American veterans of
World War I are still alive; half are believed to have served in
France.
</P>
<P>
   Wooden was to accept the honor on behalf of his entire unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be the only one around here to have it,'' Wooden said
recently. ``It's going to be a big deal. There were 210 of us
altogether. But they're all gone now.''
</P>
<P>
   Wooden's memories of the war are as crystal clear as they were
80 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it all,'' Wooden said. ``Nobody here's got anything on
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Wooden joined the service in 1917, becoming a member of D
Battery of the 129th Field Artillery under Truman.
</P>
<P>
   He can recall the day Truman took over the company _ July 18,
1918.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a pretty tough outfit,'' Wooden said. ``We had gotten
rid of three captains.''
</P>
<P>
   He still vividly recalls the first time Truman addressed his
outfit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truman says, `I didn't come over here to get along with you
fellas. You're going to get along with me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of days after that, Wooden said, Truman made him his
chief mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Thank you sir, I'll do my best,' '' Wooden recalled.
``I was the only soldier in the company he addressed by my first
name.''
</P>
<P>
   Wooden's job: Care for the battery's four French 75mm 1897-model
field guns.
</P>
<P>
   Wooden's outfit saw plenty of action. It participated in the
battles of St.-Mihiel and the Meuse-Argonne. His recollection of
those battles is pristine.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, that was the biggest artillery battle the world
had ever seen,'' Wooden said of the battle at Meuse-Argonne. ``It
just seemed like the sky was afire. The next morning we started
forward. We didn't run into any opposition. We had shot everything
all to hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Wooden remembers Nov. 11, 1918, when the war was declared over.
He also remembers the day he returned to the states.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got off the boat Easter Sunday in New York in 1919,'' Wooden
said. ``They mayor had a welcoming committee, a boat, band, colors
and lots of pretty girls. But what impressed me was the Statue of
Liberty. I had read so much about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wooden will be decorated by the deputy consul general of France,
Jean-Pierre Tutun.
</P>
<P>
   Two other World War I Army veterans _ Urban Schick, 102, and
Elmer Rash, 100, both from Kansas City _ will also be at the event.
Because their paperwork hasn't gone through, they will not be
presented with the Legion of Honor at this time.
</P>
<P>
   For Wooden, receiving the honor is just one more highlight in a
life full of memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen four presidents,'' Wooden said. ``I've shaken hands
with two of them. I've sat at the dinner table with Margaret
Thatcher,'' all due to his status as a World War I veteran. ``Yes,
I guess you could say, I've seen it all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
