A5960 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AZT-INFANTS-BOS &LR;      11-11 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZT-INFANTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATE DOSES OF AZT SHOWN TO BLOCK AIDS IN INFANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Antiviral drugs can sharply reduce mother-to-infant transmission
of the AIDS virus even when treatment is delayed until childbirth
or shortly afterward, scientists say in a report that is good news
for developing countries hard hit by the AIDS epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, it was shown that treatment with the antiviral drug
AZT during the last weeks of pregnancy could sharply lessen the
chances that an HIV-positive woman would transmit the virus to her
newborn.
</P>
<P>
   This is because over half of newborns who carry the HIV virus
are infected only very late _ around the time of childbirth.
</P>
<P>
   However, infected women often don't come for prenatal care, so
they're not diagnosed and treatment isn't begun until they are in
labor. And, in developing countries, the high cost of AZT and
similar drugs makes it impossible to treat women for as long as
previous studies had indicated would be effective. In one study,
women received AZT for 14 weeks; in a more recent study in
Thailand, when mothers took the drug for an average of 25 days
through delivery, it worked almost as well.
</P>
<P>
   What wasn't known, however, was whether treatment of the mother
or the infant would be effective if the drug was started after the
infant had become exposed to HIV during labor or delivery.
</P>
<P>
   In the current New England Journal of Medicine, scientists from
New York state report on the outcomes of treatment in infected
women who got no prenatal care or came to the clinic late in their
pregnancy. Data were compiled on 939 infants exposed to HIV in
1995, 1996, and early 1997 at hospitals in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   When treatment was begun during pregnancy, only 6.1 percent of
newborns contracted the virus, report Dr. Nancy A. Wade and
colleagues from the New York State Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   That infection rate rose to 10 percent when treatment did not
begin, because the mother had not sought medical care or had not
been tested for HIV, until she was in labor, said the researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, when the at-risk babies didn't get treatment until
after they were born _ but treatment started within 48 hours of
birth _ the rate was still only 9.3 percent. (Treatment begun on
the third day of life or later was much less successful, resulting
in a more than 18 percent infection rate.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The new, although not entirely unexpected, finding was that
even when treatment began during labor, transmission of HIV was
often prevented,'' wrote Dr. Kenneth McIntosh, head of infectious
diseases at Children's Hospital in Boston, in an editorial
accompanying today's report.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was more surprising, however, was that the infection rate
was significantly lower when the mothers received no prophylaxis at
all and postexposure zidovudine (AZT) was administered only to the
infants, beginning within 48 hours after birth.''
</P>
<P>
   McIntosh added in the editorial that the findings should prompt
more questions ``about inexpensive preventive regimens that may be
suitable for use in many parts of the world where the prevalence of
HIV infection is high and resources are severely limited.''
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, births of HIV-positive infants have
dropped sharply over the past several years in the wake of
recommendations for counseling and testing pregnant women for HIV
and treating them and their infants with AZT. By late 1997, the
number of infants infected with HIV had dropped to about 500 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Deborah Cotton, assistant provost for clinical research at
Boston University Hospital and a national expert on HIV in women,
commented: ``This study adds to our growing awareness that we could
end this epidemic (of HIV-positive infants) virtually overnight
with the use of routine HIV testing and antiviral therapy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
