<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWA-MACHINISTS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIATION BOARD SETS DEC. 1 DATE FOR TWA, MACHINISTS TO RESUME
TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Trans World Airlines and the Machinists union
will resume negotiations with a federal mediator Dec. 1 in an
effort to reach a new contract.
</P>
<P>
   The National Mediation Board has scheduled intensive bargaining
sessions for the first 11 days of December, TWA and union officials
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   If little or no progress is made, union officers said, the
federal agency will consider allowing a 30-day ``cooling off''
period to begin, after which the union would be free to strike or
take other job actions.
</P>
<P>
   TWA has 22,000 employees systemwide, about 16,200 of whom are
represented by the Machinists union, according to TWA spokesman Jim
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   TWA has about 2,200 union employees in Kansas City at its
overhaul base.
</P>
<P>
   TWA's Machinists _ a group that includes mechanics, passenger
service employees and flight attendants _ have been working under
their old contract, which was to have expired Aug. 31, 1997. Talks
have produced little progress on such issues as wages, outsourcing
and the future of certain facilities, union officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``On behalf of the company, we're thrilled that the IAM says
they're ready to negotiate,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials also were pleased with the National Mediation
Board's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sign that we're coming to the conclusion of all of
this,'' said Keith Nelson, president of Machinists Local 1650 in
Kansas City. ``It's a step that needed to come about.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said that, excluding union concessions made during TWA's
two bankruptcy reorganizations, he could recall only one instance
in which the Machinists reached a new contract with TWA without
resorting to the 30-day countdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be wonderful if we could reach an agreement during the
so-called `supermediation' period,'' he said. ``But the company has
yet to offer an acceptable economic package.'' He also said the
company had refused to sign a protective covenant for its
facilities to ensure continuing operations.
</P>
<P>
   In the previous contract, TWA agreed to keep the huge overhaul
base in Kansas City as long as the airline continued to operate. In
recent years, TWA's work force at the base has shrunk as the
carrier modernized its fleet and basically quit doing work for
other airlines.
</P>
<P>
   TWA has said its maintenance operations are too big for the
airline's size. No decisions have been made, however, regarding the
future of any of TWA's maintenance facilities, the airline has
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wages also remain a sticking point. TWA employees have been paid
less than the industry average for years during the airline's
financial difficulties. The Machinists union is seeking a wage
package that would bring its employees back to industry standard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 1913EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0366 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5964 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STRIDE-CEO-BOS &LR;      11-11 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRIDE-CEO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESKRIDGE NEW CEO AT STRIDE RITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER BABSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ending a six-month search, Stride Rite Corp. Wednesday announced
it has chosen James A. Eskridge, formerly of Mattel Inc. and
Fisher-Price, as its new chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The Lexington, Mass. shoe company markets active footwear for
children and adults and owns several brand names, including Keds,
Sperry Top-Sider, and Tommy Hilfiger.
</P>
<P>
   Eskridge, 55, held various positions at Mattel, including
president and CEO of its Fisher-Price division, and was also
Mattel's executive vice president and chief financial officer.
Before Mattel, he was an executive with General Mills Inc., and
General Motors Corp.
</P>
<P>
   He replaces Bob Siegel, 62, Stride Rite's retiring chairman and
CEO, who is relocating to South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``His leadership style and his ability to leverage this company
in some growth activities is very positive because he has a lot of
experience,'' Siegel said. ``He is a very strong leader to bring
in.''
</P>
<P>
   In recruiting Eskridge, Stride Rite bypassed a leading in-house
candidate: Diane Sullivan, who runs the company's licensed brands
division.
</P>
<P>
   Eskridge will be assuming the helm of Stride Rite as the company
continues to attempt a rebound after sales slipped in the
mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my goals here is to have consistent and predictable
sales and earnings growth,'' Eskridge said. ``A good third leg to
that stool will be an acquisition, but it will have to be a good
strong acquisition.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a difficult year at Stride Rite.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial comeback of one the company's premier products _
Keds _ pushed third quarter sales up 17 percent from the previous
year to $168.5 million but was not enough to keep Stride Rite's
stock from losing much of its value on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Stride Rite stock closed at $10 a share, down 1/8 on
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   And last month, the company announced it would stop marketing a
footwear line made under a licensing agreement with Levi Strauss &AMP;
Co., and take a fourth-quarter charge of $3.2 million after the
footwear line did not meet initial sales expectations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the company earned $19.8 million on sales of $515.7
million; now analysts say Eskridge needs to shift Stride Rite's
focus to leveraging its balance sheet, a strategy likely to include
new acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Ritcher, an analyst for Tucker Anthony who has followed
Stride Rite closely, said Eskridge's hiring should help the
company's transition into a period of expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a strong addition to the management team,''
Ritcher said. ``He brings in a big corporate background along with
the financial perspective.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
