<SLUG> BC-PAYLESS-STOCK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYLESS CASHWAYS STOCK PRICE, TRADING VOLUME SOAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Payless Cashways Inc.'s stock went wild
Tuesday, closing at almost double its Monday price while trading at
more than four times its average volume of the last 10 trading
days.
</P>
<P>
   Payless Cashways stock closed at 1 9//16, compared with its
close Monday of 13//16. That, coupled with its frenzied trading
volume, made for an interesting day for those who follow the
troubled home-improvement retailer, including investment adviser
Jerry Duggan.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wondered whether the stock wasn't being driven by
buyout rumors.
</P>
<P>
   On a day of fairly low volatility in the market as a whole, he
said, Payless Cashways' volume of 736,100 shares _ 19 times
Monday's volume _ was remarkable. Its volume Tuesday was far higher
than that of Sprint Corp., for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``Volume drives price...and clearly, the buyer or handful of
buyers who drove this thing to close to (almost) a buck and
three-quarters thought they knew something, and that something they
think they knew had to do with an acquisition,'' Duggan said.
``These things don't happen by accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, acquisition rumors have long swirled about Payless
Cashways, which is based in Kansas City. The speculation started
before the company filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in July 1997. It
continued through the reorganization and persists today, almost a
year after Payless Cashways emerged from bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Management declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't control the stock price and we don't comment on it,
and we don't comment on rumors and speculation, and that's where we
are,'' said company spokeswoman Linda Ward.
</P>
<P>
   But one company that has popped up continually is Leonard Green
&AMP; Partners, a Los Angeles investment firm that last year put
together two troubled home-improvement retailers, Hechinger and
Builders Square.
</P>
<P>
   After buying those two companies, Green's firm put Mark
Schwartz, a former retailing executive from Wal-Mart Stores Inc.,
in charge of turning around the company. Millard Barron, the chief
executive officer of Payless Cashways, is also a former retailing
executive with Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   Because Hechinger is privately owned, there's no word yet on how
Schwartz is doing. But in a recent interview with The Washington
Post, he said the word was great.
</P>
<P>
   Calls on Tuesday to Green and Schwartz weren't returned.
</P>
<P>
   The lone equity analyst who follows Payless Cashways said
Tuesday that he hadn't heard anything about the Leonard Green
rumors other than from a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it looks like someone has figured out there is some
value there,'' said Deepac Raja of Wiley Bros.-Aintree Capital in
Nashville, Tenn. ``We're happy to see same-store sales turning
around, and we see some optimism about next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Payless Cashways still is reporting negative same-store
sales _ sales at stores open at least one year _ the numbers are
narrowing.
</P>
<P>
   Raja said that he had a target price for the company but that
his firm was keeping the price private.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he expected the company to make more moves to
improve its bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect them to close a couple more stores, tighten the
belt, work on margins and continue to focus on the professional
contractor,'' Raja said. ``It looks as if they're heading in the
right direction, and I think people are seeing that finally.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he thought a Payless Cashways//Hechinger
combination made sense, Raja clammed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't talk about it,'' Raja said. ``I'm sorry. I don't
know anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
