<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-U.N.-280&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. PANEL TO VISIT CAMBODIA TO STUDY KHMER ROUGE ATROCITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Three legal experts appointed by
Secretary-General Kofi Annan are scheduled to go to Cambodia to
study documents on Khmer Rouge atrocities and recommend how and
where a tribunal should judge those crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations' chief human right monitor on Cambodia,
Thomas Hammarberg of Sweden, said at a news conference last week
that the United Nations estimated that about 1.7 million people
died under Khmer Rouge rule between April 1975 and early January
1979. Many were executed by the radical communist movement for
``crimes'' as trivial as wearing eyeglasses; many others died in
forced labor or from dislocation, disease and starvation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There hasn't even been an apology, even by those who have
defected to the government side,'' said Hammarberg, who has served
as the secretary- general's special representative for human rights
in Cambodia since 1996. He added that no contrition had been
expressed by Ieng Sary, one of the highest-ranking Khmer Rouge
leaders still alive, who was given amnesty by the Cambodian
government two years ago and moves freely around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The legal panel, which is going to Cambodia on Saturday,
consists of Sir Ninian Stephen, a former governor general of
Australia; Steven Ratner, an American expert on international law
and war crimes from the University of Texas and the Foundation on
Interethnic Relations at The Hague, and Rajsoomer Lallah, a former
chief justice of Mauritius. They are expected to report to Annan by
the end of January.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of documentation on what actually happened,''
Hammarberg said. ``Like the Nazis, the Khmer Rouge did take
notes.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The panel will consider what international charges might be
applied to the Khmer Rouge. Some scholars question whether genocide
is the correct charge, or whether the broader charge of crimes
against humanity would be more appropriate. The panel will also
recommend whether any tribunal that may be set up should be based
in Cambodia or elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   According to Hammarberg, all Cambodian political leaders have
said they favor the establishment of a tribunal, including Acting
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who was a Khmer Rouge official when the
movement came to power. He was later installed as head of
government when the Vietnamese occupied the country.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the U.S. Congress, led by Rep. Dana Rohrabacher,
R-Calif., have passed an unopposed resolution asking that Hun Sen
be put on trial.
</P>
<P>
   Hammarberg said King Sihanouk, who was first a figurehead for
the Khmer Rouge and then their prisoner, was eager for a tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   Cambodia is now without an elected government. Hun Sen seized
total power in 1997 in a coup that ousted his coalition partner,
Prince Norodom Ranariddh. Since a disputed July election left him
short of a parliamentary majority, Hun Sen has been unable to
persuade the prince and other opposition leaders to join in forming
a government.
</P>
<P>
   Hammarberg reported to the General Assembly on Friday on human
rights in Cambodia over the last tumultuous year. Despite some
steps by the government to deal with institutional abuses, the
picture was bleak.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main problem as I see it is the continuous problem of
impunity,'' Hammarberg said. ``Serious crime, often with a
political connotation, including killings, takes place without
anyone being arrested or prosecuted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 1927EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5982 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VETERANS-PARADE-HNS &LR;      11-11 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VETERANS-PARADE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON CROWDS CELEBRATE VETERANS DAY APPLAUDING FIGHTING FORCES,
GLENN AND ASTRONAUT CORP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RAD SALLEE 
and STEFANIE ASIN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ An appreciative crowd lined downtown streets Wednesday
to watch the first Veterans Day parade here in years, applaud
America's fighting forces and astronauts and wave at John Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   At 5-feet-10 _ one inch under the maximum allowed height for an
original Mercury astronaut _ the 77-year-old Glenn was barely
visible in the plush back seat of an open 1927 Rolls-Royce touring
car he shared with wife Annie and Mayor Lee Brown, who towers by
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't get a picture at all,'' said Rick Hurt, who had
come mainly to see Glenn. ``We had to stay behind the rope line,
and because of all the reporters and the cops on horseback, I
couldn't see him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the parade was great. They ought to do this kind of thing
more often.''
</P>
<P>
   Police stuck closely to Glenn after a young woman approached the
car and tried to kiss him.
</P>
<P>
   The Glenn car followed six vintage Thunderbird convertibles
carrying the other shuttle Discovery crew members who lifted off
from Cape Canaveral, Fla., on Oct. 29 and returned Saturday: Curtis
L. Brown, Steven W. Lindsey, Stephen K. Robinson, Scott E.
Parazynski, Pedro Duque and Chiaki Mukai.
</P>
<P>
   All wore their sky-blue astronaut jumpsuits, as did about 50
other members of the astronaut corps riding on three fire engines.
Some weren't even born in 1962 when Glenn became the first American
to orbit Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The clear sky and perfect weather brought many downtown workers
outside, along with some who made special efforts to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Ana Calvo, 19, born without limbs, and Andre Gaines, 61, left a
quadriplegic after an accident, had a good view from their
motorized wheelchairs on the sidewalk in front of City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very historic event, a once-in-a-lifetime thing,''
Calvo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I normally follow the missions,'' said Gaines. ``I'm
interested in the whole crew.''
</P>
<P>
   ``John,'' a 52-year-old Vietnam veteran, was in Florida on
business and drove to view Discovery's launch last month. While he
wanted to see Glenn and the rest of the crew, he came Wednesday
mainly ``because it was a Veterans Day parade and the older I get,
the better I feel about being a veteran.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Stone, who brought her three young children from Clear
Lake City, Texas, said Glenn's recent journey into space could
benefit NASA in much the way Mark McGwire's home run record this
season sparked renewed interest in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We watched the liftoff _ and we love parades,'' said Stone's
friend Adele James.
</P>
<P>
   Law clerk Katherine Miller, 49, said ``everyone over 40'' should
have turned out. ``He (Glenn) is close to our last American hero,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   When the astronauts passed by, Miller took about 30 pictures.
``I'm a flag waver,'' she explained.
</P>
<P>
   Amber Howard, 12, wondered aloud how someone Glenn's age could
go into ``outer space.'' But she was just as interested in the
veterans who passed by in fatigues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They shouldn't have to pay taxes,'' she said. ``If they have
to go through a bloody battle, why should they have to pay money?''
</P>
<P>
   Christine Dantche was there to see astronaut Robinson, her high
school classmate, and held a sign with the name of their hometown,
Moraga, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other guys have to get acknowledged, too,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The parade had another meaning for Dantche. Her father, who died
recently, was a World War II veteran. ``I'm thinking of him
today,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the vendors hawking balloons and T-shirts, Jennifer Weiner
of the Houston Downtown Management District had one of the odder
jobs _ handing out cornstarch ``peanuts.'' The biodegradable white
blobs, resembling foam packing material, were tossed from the
sidewalks like confetti.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted Houston to look like New York City (in a ticker-tape
parade),'' Weiner explained. But few buildings here have windows
that open, she lamented.
</P>
<P>
   Symra Lanclos, 32, brought son Jetaime, 4. ``I came mainly for
the veterans,'' she said, naming three family members who served in
Desert Storm and one in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, the retiring Democratic senator from Ohio, is a retired
Marine Corps colonel and a decorated pilot with 122 missions in
World War II and Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Before the parade, he and the other honorees lunched at Wortham
Center with Mayor Brown and Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Glenn) is truly a modern-day hero, an inspiration to all
of us,'' Brown said. The mayor joked that he is personally thrilled
by Glenn's role in research to reverse the aging process.
</P>
<P>
   Shuttle commander Curtis Brown asked the audience to use the
excitement generated by the mission to support the international
space station project.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he wants to be sure space exploration is funded in
Washington. ``Ponce de Leon,'' he quipped, ``went looking for the
fountain of youth and found Florida; John Glenn went to Florida and
found the fountain of youth.''
</P>
<P>
   Being among the younger crew, Glenn said, he felt like ``costume
jewelry at Tiffany's.''
</P>
<P>
   Rephrasing a famous line from the Apollo 13 moon-landing
mission, he told the crowd: ``Houston, today we have no problem,
and we want to keep it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The city has staged at least two previous downtown parades in
honor of astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   Apollo 8's Frank Borman, James Lovell and William Anders, the
first humans to circle the moon, were honored Jan. 13, 1969, after
being feted in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   An even bigger celebration erupted here Aug. 16, 1969, for the
Apollo 11 crew of Neil Armstrong and Edwin ``Buzz'' Aldrin, the
first to walk on the moon, and Michael Collins, who remained in
orbit during their landing.
</P>
<P>
   Those festivities were capped by an Astrodome program, emceed by
Frank Sinatra, for all who took part in the Apollo and Gemini
programs. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
