<HEADER>
A6028 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BIG-12-FOOTBALL-R     11-11 1384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIG-12-FOOTBALL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
 
McCOWN IS BEST CHOICE FOR AGGIES 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two quarterbacks. One football.
</P>
<P>
   One wrong decision and an outside shot at a national
championship disappears.
</P>
<P>
   That is the predicament facing Texas A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum, who
must decide if his sixth-ranked Aggies (9-1, 6-0) are better off
facing No. 13 Missouri (7-2, 5-1) with a healthy backup quarterback
or a semi-healthy starter at 11:30 a.m. Saturday at Kyle Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what I do, some people will think I should have gone
in the other direction,'' Slocum said. ``So, I can't let that
bother me.''
</P>
<P>
   Slocum said he will wait until pregame warmups to decide between
Branndon Stewart, the backup who threw for 234 yards in last week's
29-0 victory against Oklahoma, or Randy McCown, the starter who
continues to take daily treatments for a separated shoulder
suffered Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M players, including Stewart, agree the job should revert to
McCown once he is recovered. But that time will be difficult to
pinpoint because of the nature of his injury.
</P>
<P>
   McCown, who has yet to throw during practice this week, said
trainers told him it would take four to six weeks for a full
recovery. They also told him that, as of Monday, he was in no
danger of suffering additional damage from being tackled and could
play if he could stand the pain.
</P>
<P>
   During light throwing sessions on the side, McCown said the only
pain he has felt is a minor ``tweak'' on his follow-through.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of right now, I plan on playing,'' McCown said.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum, of course, reserves the right to change that plan. He
remains unclear how effective McCown could be under game
conditions. That brings him to Stewart, who stunned teammates last
week against Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a fire in his eyes and we drew from that. To tell you
the truth, I hadn't seen that look from him this year,'' wide
receiver Chris Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was more vocal than I'd ever seen him,'' tight end Dan
Campbell said. ``When people made plays, he would compliment them.
Things like that go a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart downplayed the change but acknowledged Slocum and
quarterbacks coach Ray Dorr had encouraged him to be more
demonstrative toward teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want the quarterback to be more assertive, but I can't
change who I am,'' said Stewart, a Stephenville native. ``I'm not a
rah-rah guy. You're not going to see me run across the field and
jump on someone's shoulders after a big play.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, that is precisely the sort of thing teammates like best
about the effusive McCown. It is the intangible that, in Campbell's
estimation, makes this McCown's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still our man,'' Campbell said. ``If he's healthy, we
expect him to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he's not 100 percent, McCown remains the quarterback
most likely to elevate the performances of peers in a big game that
could be a nail-biter. Trainers say he can't make the injury worse
by playing.
</P>
<P>
   If I'm Slocum, I let McCown start and ride him until his
shoulder shows he can't be effective.
</P>
<P>
   But this is your call, R.C. All that's riding on it is a
potential shot at a national championship.
QUICK HITS Making his own name
</P>
<P>
   During last year's Texas-Texas Tech game, the Runnin' Rickys
combined to carry 46 times for 211 yards and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   If both players reach their season averages Saturday night in
Lubbock, Texas tailback Ricky Williams and Texas Tech tailback
Ricky Williams will carry 60 times for 338 yards and four
touchdowns. Regardless of what happens, Texas coach Mack Brown
said, one thing is clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think their Ricky Williams has outgrown being called `Little
Ricky,''' Brown said of the handle given the Tech tailback because
he is 3 inches shorter and 35 pounds lighter than his Texas
counterpart. ``He's his own person and has made his own name for
himself. But it's unique to have two great players named Ricky
Williams in the same game.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Tech's tailback outrushed his Texas counterpart,
131-80, in last year's 24-10 victory by the Red Raiders. But it is
the Longhorns' version of Ricky Williams who leads the nation in
rushing (191.6-yard average) this season, with his Tech counterpart
(146.1) at No. 5.
Heading home
</P>
<P>
   Texas defensive end Aaron Humphrey, a Lubbock native, has spent
much of this week trying to line up tickets for friends and family
members wanting to attend Saturday's game against Tech. By
yesterday, he had found 12 but needed more.
</P>
<P>
   None of them, he said, has expressed regrets that he jilted the
hometown Red Raiders to play for the rival Longhorns. In fact, he
made his rooting section sound like a bunch of Mac Davis wannabes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a lot of them cared if I went to Tech or not,'' Humphrey
said. ``If they had chances to leave Lubbock, they'd have left,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis is famous for the song ``Happiness is Lubbock, Texas in
the Rearview Mirror''.
Blake digs in
</P>
<P>
   Guaranteed of a third consecutive losing record, Oklahoma coach
John Blake said he is not concerned about being fired after the
Sooners (3-6, 1-5) complete their season on Nov. 21. If OU falls in
Saturday's game against Baylor (2-7, 1-5), the Sooners will finish
last in the South Division.
</P>
<P>
   During his weekly news conference, Blake said he needs two more
recruiting classes to turn the tide, then added: ``The wins will
come. I know they will. The good things have outweighed the
negatives by a long shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Blake, Oklahoma is 10-22. Even with victories in their
final two games, the Sooners would finish with the worst three-year
mark in school history. Athletic director Joe Castiglione said he
would review Blake's performance and make a recommendation on his
status to the school's board of regents ``as soon as possible''
after the season ends.
</P>
<P>
   Bet the house on a new coach being in place before the Big 12
championship game is played on Dec. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Several names have been floated as potential successors,
including Georgia's Jim Donnan, Oregon's Mike Bellotti and Tulane's
Tommy Bowden. Another name to consider is Lou Holtz, the former
Notre Dame coach who retired after the 1996 season because his
wife, Beth, was in declining health.
</P>
<P>
   Holtz, 61, has a relationship with Oklahoma regent Robin
Zeigfried. His wife is much-improved physically and, in private
discussions, friends say he has expressed a desire to return to the
sideline.
</P>
<P>
   From all indications, Castiglione would prefer to hire a younger
coach. But he answers to school president David Boren, a former
politician who might be swayed by a groundswell of public opinion
for Holtz.
EXTRA POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Seeking an indication of how things have changed at Oklahoma
since Barry Switzer ran the show? In 1988, Switzer's last season,
the Sooners' roster included 44 players from Texas. A decade later,
OU has 27 . . . Saturday will mark the fifth time for Texas Tech
coach Spike Dykes to face Texas with the Red Raiders coming off an
open date. Tech is 3-1 in those games. When Dykes has not had the
extra week to prepare, his teams are 2-5 against the Longhorns. ...
A&AMP;M linebacker Warrick Holdman has 22 tackles on third down this
season. The next closest teammate, Lombardi Award finalist Dat
Nguyen, has 10. ... Two clarifications for record watchers as we
head down the stretch: Under NCAA rules, A&AMP;M's forfeit against
Louisiana Tech does not affect the team's 9-1 record or impact its
position in the Bowl Championship Series rankings. If Texas
advances to the Big 12 title game, tailback Ricky Williams' rushing
totals in that contest will count as part of his career statistics.
That gives Williams the possibility of a third game in which to
rack up the 204 yards he needs to surpass Tony Dorsett (6,082) on
the NCAA career list. ... Texas officials, by the way, have invited
Dorsett to attend the Nov. 27 A&AMP;M-Texas game, which will be
Williams' final home appearance. ... Despite the game's potential
championship ramifications, ABC will not budge from its 10 a.m.
kickoff time for the A&AMP;M-Texas contest. The schools are
contractually bound to that time slot as part of a Big 12 agreement
with the network that expires after this season. A date and kickoff
time for the teams' 1999 contest has not been determined.
</P>
</TEXT>
