<HEADLINE>
STUDIES VARY WIDELY ON PERCENTAGE OF PEOPLE SUFFERING HEART VALVE
DISORDERS AFTER TAKING DIET DRUGS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RUTH SoRELLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Different studies indicate that estimates vary widely
on what percentage of people suffer heart valve disorders after
taking the diet pills popularly known as Fen/Phen and Redux,
researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is great discordance,'' Dr. Robert Bonow, chief of the
division of cardiology at Northwestern University of Medicine in
Chicago, said at the 71st scientific sessions of the American Heart
Association meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Bonow headed a heart association committee that drafted
treatment guidelines for all form of heart valve disease and
devoted two pages to the new disorder arising from use of the diet
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Most agreed that the likelihood of developing a problem with a
heart valve depended on the length of time people took the drugs
and on how much they took.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stay tuned,'' Bronow advised. ``We don't know the true
prevalence and we still don't know what the public health impact
will be.''
</P>
<P>
   All researchers at the conference agreed that the decision to
withdraw the drugs fenfluramine (Pondimine) and dexfenfluramine
(Redux) from the market was a wise one given the potentially deadly
nature of the problems associated with them, but Bonow said it
should not discourage further research into diet pills.
</P>
<P>
   The data from the studies presented at the conference showed
that up to 29 percent of the people who used the diet drugs
suffered heart valve disorders.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bruce A. Samuels, attending cardiologist at the Heart Center
of Los Angeles, studied 89 patients who had taken either Redux or
the Fen/Phen combination and found that 26, or 29.2 percent, had
``significant valvular leakage,'' an indication that the valve is
not closed properly.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-five percent of the patients with leakage had it to a
severe or moderate amount, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A study by Dr. Charles A. Herzog of the Hennepin County Medical
Center in Minneapolis, confirmed the association between use of the
drugs and valve disease with about 20 percent of patients suffering
the disorder.
</P>
<P>
   He also found that patients who had taken the diet drug had a
two times greater risk of having high pulmonary artery pressure,
indicating a risk of developing a potentially deadly ailment called
pulmonary hypertension.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of 388 people, Dr. Ravin Davidoff, director of
clinical cardiology at Boston University School of Medicine, found
that 12 percent of patients had evidence of disease in the aortic
valve of the heart.
</P>
<P>
   However, Dr. Bruce Shively, associate professor of medicine at
Oregon Health Sciences University, studied 220 people who had taken
Redux and 192 who had not at 26 sites in 15 states.
</P>
<P>
   None of the patients had severe valve disease. However, he said,
7.3 percent of the treated patients had disorders of the aortic or
mitral valve.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad news is there is an increase prevalence of valve
disease (compared to the normal population),'' he said. ``The good
news is that the prevalence is low and that there were no severe
cases.''
</P>
<P>
   The heart association guidelines recommend:
</P>
<P>
   Everyone who took the Fen/Phen combination or Redux should be
examined by their doctors using a stethoscope after ceasing the
drugs and then six to eight months later if no problems are found.
</P>
<P>
   If a patient has had a murmur or symptoms of heart valve
problems, he or she should be examined by an ultrasound test of the
heart called echocardiography. In some cases, a heart murmur is
hard to detect on physical exam. Those patients should undergo
echocardiography before undergoing dental procedures because of the
risk of an infection of the lining of the heart muscle. In severe
cases, patients should undergo surgery to correct the defect. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
