<HEADLINE>
TODAY'S SPECIAL: AN ORDER OF GROUSE AND A SIDE OF CARP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is it just me, or are some of my favorite shows slipping?
Consider, for example:
</P>
<P>
   _Ally McBeal. The genius who decided that ``Ally McBeal'' is a
comedy should take a moment. A moment to reflect on the distressing
fallout of that decision.
</P>
<P>
   A year or so ago, while watching the pilot episode, I was one of
many who were captivated immediately and oh-so-willingly by Calista
Flockhart's expressive face, by David E. Kelley's tart script, by
the very differentness of the show. But was I the only one under
the impression that we'd become hooked on a lighthearted drama?
</P>
<P>
   Come to find out, at least as far as the Golden Globes and the
Emmys are concerned, we were hooked on a dramatic comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine my surprise. Imagine my disappointment. As the show has
stretched to fulfill those high comedic expectations, it seems
``Ally'' has evolved from light drama to heavy-handed silliness.
</P>
<P>
   Not entirely surprising, given Kelley's penchant for pursuing
the bizarre (such as the ``orange woman'' story line in this week's
episode). Not entirely fulfilling, either. John Cage's frog fetish
was tired _ and not very funny _ three episodes ago. Same goes for
Ally's tendency to fall. (Stay tuned: Next week, she falls into the
toilet. How much do you want to bet Cage asks if it was a fresh
bowl?)
</P>
<P>
   When ``Ally McBeal'' burst onto the scene, it introduced us to
interesting _ OK, odd _ people with a history. It became a breakout
series, with America tuning in every Monday to know more about this
young Boston attorney who was wise in matters of the law but a
little at sea in her personal relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Since receiving the ``comedy'' imprimatur, though, Kelley has
given up on serious characterization in favor of lame jokes and
physical comedy. So much so that no one affiliated with the show
seemed to notice that in this season's premiere episode, Ally said
she'd been a big Red Sox fan since childhood. This from the same
character who last season had no idea who the Chicago Cubs were.
</P>
<P>
   If Kelley needs a story editor, I might be available part time.
But I'd be happier if he'd just pay more attention to the quirky
folks he created and less attention to getting a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   _ER. Some career advice for Lucy Knight: Forget medicine,
concentrate on a field where your annoying tendencies won't be so
noticeable. Like driving a subway train. Or tarring roofs.
</P>
<P>
   After this season's premiere, a good friend declared that she
absolutely hated Knight, a naive medical student played by Kellie
Martin. I suggested she wait a few weeks before rendering judgment.
Almost two months into the season, I don't think we need to wait
any longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``ER'' is always introducing new people, some of whom have
stayed (Gloria Reuben, Alex Kingtson), some of whom have not
(Glenne Headly, Maria Bello). Each of their characters had a
certain accessibility, even though they may not have been the
nicest people. Heck, Peter Benton (Eriq La Salle) is a social
moron, but there's something in his character that makes the bad
personality barely tolerable.
</P>
<P>
   In Lucy Knight's case, it could be the writing, or it could be
Martin's acting. I'm not sure. But I wouldn't mind at this point if
Lucy died from an outbreak of beriberi during a November sweeps
programming stunt.
</P>
<P>
   _Dawson's Creek. Not sure if I can stay with this one much
longer. It's getting more depressing than a Sunday night movie.
</P>
<P>
   Where Kelley has abandoned all seriousness with ``Ally McBeal,''
Kevin Williamson seems to have embraced it with the
single-mindedness of Henrik Ibsen on downers.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Williamson gave us four overly precocious teenagers,
all articulate beyond their years but still capable of smiling and
laughing and acting like high school kids.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the cynicism of adulthood has invaded Capeside and
left Dawson, Joey, Pacey and Jen bereft of any sense of fun. Even
the addition of new characters has done little to lift the pall
that's fallen over the creek.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the high school years can be tough. But Williamson might
want to sneak a peek at ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer.'' Buffy Summers
has to slay demons and deal with being an outsider and she still
seems to have more fun than the morose Capeside quartet.
</P>
<P>
   _Frasier. Not much to say here. It's simply not as clever as it
used to be. Fortunately, we have reruns of the old ones to remind
us of the days when Frasier Crane (Kelsey Grammer) still had a job
at KACL.
</P>
<P>
   The show started losing its sparkle last season with a pregnant
Roz (Peri Gilpin). Now that she and Frasier are unemployed, the
show is rudderless and, sometimes, not so different from all those
other not-too-clever sitcoms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 2011EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
