<HEADER>
A6045 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARRY-INTERVIEW12-COX     11-11 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARRY-INTERVIEW12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barry: Most Irish just long for a 'normal life'
 &HT;    By Keith Graham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sebastian Barry was telling yet another story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, when I came over here 15 years ago, people would come
up to me and say, `A-h-h-h, I sympathize with your struggle,''' the
Irish playwright and novelist said, his eyes crinkling with the
irony. ``And I would think, `What does he mean: Paying the rent?'''
</P>
<P>
   Barry laughed. But, as with all his stories and the plays and
novels that have brought him renown, there was a serious intent.
</P>
<P>
   The people who had whispered in his ear were Irish-Americans, in
love with stories of their own about a romantic Ireland that would
someday be united, north and south.
</P>
<P>
   But Barry, who grew up in suburban Dublin and now lives in
County Wicklow, had witnessed a less romantic reality. He recalled
a day in 1974 when the troubles of Northern Ireland moved across
the border to Dublin, where he was studying at Trinity College.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was three car bombs,'' he said softly, ``and I was in
Trinity that day and came out when I heard this noise, as the whole
city did. And in the distance were what looked like packages,
burned packages lying on the ground, and these were the remnants of
shoppers and some of these packages were still alive entreating
people to help them.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because he has never forgotten that image, Barry today
was conjuring up a different notion of what unity might mean in
Ireland: a society in which all people, including the long divided
people of Northern Ireland, have the right to engage in a different
sort of struggle, living a normal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normal life _ the most difficult thing of all,'' he mused,
between engagements at Emory University in Atlanta, where he has
taken part in a series of events in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normal life is probably the hardest thing on God's earth to
deal with ... the thing we struggle with, like bringing the kids to
school, paying the mortgage and all this, the terrifying things
that you have to struggle with yourself in a healthy way. That is a
large requirement to put against people who have lived in a war
situation, which is in some ways a kind of bizarre distraction from
real life.''
</P>
<P>
   In highly successful plays like ``The Steward of Christendom''
and ``Our Lady of Sligo'' and his recent novel, ``The Whereabouts
of Eneas McNulty'' _ which was a best-seller in England and Ireland
_ Barry has mined rich veins of Irish history, its losses and its
enmities, with lyric force. He also wrote for The New York Times
about the peace process in Northern Ireland that resulted in this
year's Good Friday agreement. Today, he is hopeful that normalcy is
descending on the North. But he also knows that peace is not yet a
certainty.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Ireland, long seething with sectarian violence, is a
bit like an alcoholic family, he said. The alcoholic has stopped
drinking _ again _ but people aren't yet certain he has stopped
forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year something around the figure of 250 houses have been
burned in efforts to move Catholics into another district or
Protestants into another district, sort of tit for tat,'' Barry
said. ``The punishment shootings and beatings of both Loyalists and
Republicans have continued _ slightly less than last year, they
say, but there may be something like 150 punishment beatings.''
</P>
<P>
   Sectarian hatred has even increased in some areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is that if you talked to somebody maybe on the
Garvaghy Road now and said, `Isn't it wonderful that you have this
prospect of peace,' they might well say to you, `What peace are you
talking about?'''
</P>
<P>
   But no one can deny the positive signs as well. Barry cited the
Nobel Peace Prize won by Catholic leader John Hume, whom he deeply
admires, and the Protestant David Trimble. He cited what appears to
be a new statesmanship on Trimble's part. And he found cause for
cheer in the new neighborliness the peace agreement has brought
between Ireland and Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been remarkable scenes, where unimaginable things
have occurred,'' he said. ``A lot of people have shown themselves
to be of greater mettle than they appeared at first.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and former Sen. George Mitchell, the
negotiator for the peace talks, played helpful roles in bringing
about this transformation. But Barry also credited the masses of
Irish-Americans who are no longer as apt to whisper their
sympathies _ or to lend support to terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The change was to understand it wasn't a question of get the
Brits out, it wasn't a question of Irish unity. The question was,
and it was very simple, to stop the process by which shoppers _
Catholic, Protestant, girls going out with boyfriends _ were being
killed in the streets of Ireland by impulses that had become
perverted over time. If there ever were right reasons to do that,
those right reasons were long in the past,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, there has been a laying aside of the old stories
that stirred hatred throughout much of the Irish world. That shift
has meant the future for Northern Ireland is no longer predictably
melancholy, even if it remains uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the most hopeful thing about the future is that no one
really knows what it is anymore,'' Barry said.
</P>
<P>
   A Catholic who is married to a Protestant, Barry knows he could
not live and be left alone in some districts of Northern Ireland.
But that didn't stop him from offering up some hopes for that still
cloudy future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like ... the whole island to be grappling with the
tricky devils and angels of normal life,'' he said. ``I would like
to be able to go up to the North of Ireland and feel that no one
was in clear and present danger there, that you could go to any
district and talk at ease with anyone ... to be at ease in your own
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would certainly be my aspiration for Ireland. Not for
Irish unity _ you should dispense with those blind alleys in a way.
Not for a dancing at crossroads. But for a sort of imaginary dance,
a place where things can be said without fear of becoming a seed
for a murder up the line.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
