u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVERGLADES-RESIDENTS1     11-11 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES-RESIDENTS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Everglades residents fight for their homes
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Madeleine Fortin isn't a revolutionary. She's no
survivalist who fled society for the wilds, retreating in
self-imposed exile, hoarding guns and food and spouting conspiracy
theories, suspicious of everything government does.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Fortin is a plain-spoken, unassuming 48-year-old nurse
and college anthropology student who four years ago moved to a
rural neighborhood about 25 miles west of Miami, on the edge of
Everglades National Park.
</P>
<P>
   Now it appears the government and most of America's top
environmental groups want her off her land, which they say is
essential for saving the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   Fortin considers herself a nature-lover, even an
environmentalist. She loves the Everglades. She climbs the winding
spiral staircase to her roof most nights to watch the sunset,
gazing in awe at the vast expanse of sawgrass that surrounds her
otherwise nondescript three-bedroom, two-bath ranch-style house.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see fireflies and a million stars,'' she said. ``I
would never want to leave here. Sometimes flocks of birds fly
overhead. It's just beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fortin and several hundred other residents of an
8.5-square-mile area called the East Everglades may have to move.
Today, officials of the South Florida Water Management District
meet to discuss several plans on what to do about the neighborhood
_ and one of the options is to buy everybody out.
</P>
<P>
   That possibility _ after years of what residents say has been
government flip-flops, double-talk and evasion _ has Fortin and her
neighbors fuming.
</P>
<P>
   While some residents have already sold and are reportedly happy
with their prices, many who remain have become disillusioned.What
hurts the most to Fortin is that she doesn't believe flooding her
land would help restore the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   ``This area was never underwater,'' she says, spreading out a
thick U.S. Geological Survey hydrology report on her dining room
table. ``We're not part of the flow-way through the Everglades. You
can see how all of this land is labeled: `rarely subjected to
wet-season inundation.'''
</P>
<P>
   Officials from all levels of government have said they are only
trying to treat the homeowners fairly as they grapple with a very
complex problem.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for top environmental groups backing Everglades
restoration are sympathetic and say the residents should get fair
compensation. But they also believe the homes must go or the
Everglades plan may not work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want these people to be punished,'' said Mark Krause
of the National Audubon Society, which has been involved in the
Everglades effort. ``It's the circumstances. We've got to think of
the greater good.''
</P>
<P>
   But something bothers Fortin. She goes back to her Geological
Survey hydrology map. It shows the historical flow of water to the
Everglades passed through a part of Broward County that is now
covered by housing developments like Weston, the posh suburb where
rich people like Miami Dolphins quarterback Dan Marino lives.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is asking those people to move, Fortin says.
</P>
<P>
   She knows many people might simply blame her for her problems:
She shouldn't have bought property in the middle of a swamp,
especially as late as 1994, when talk of a massive Everglades
restoration was already brewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I checked with everybody,'' Fortin says. ``I called the
National Park, the water management district and the county, asking
if they had plans to acquire this land. They all said, `No.'''
</P>
<P>
   That's not the case now.
</P>
<P>
   Restoring the Everglades has become a huge national issue. A
month ago, Vice President Al Gore came to Miami to announce the
Corps of Engineers had finally finished a $7.8 billion plan to fix
the troubled wetlands.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody agrees the problems in the Everglades are man-made.
Decades of ditching, diking and road-building have interrupted the
broad, shallow flow of water that once coursed naturally over the
area and created its unique ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
   Wildlife populations have plummeted; fish, alligators, deer and
birds are struggling to survive.
</P>
<P>
   The restoration plan is mammoth and complex. It would take out
dikes, install culverts under roads, fill up canals, divert water,
pull farmland out of production and filter runoff water in natural
marshes to try to clean it.
</P>
<P>
   Fortin is already resigning herself to the most likely outcome:
that she'll be forced to sell at whatever price the water managers
offer. But having lived on the front lines and spent years
painstakingly educating herself about the issues, she worries about
the fate of the Everglades. She no longer trusts the crusaders who
claim they're out to save it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really can't believe it,'' she says. ``I'm going up against
the people trying to restore the Everglades, and what I truly
believe is that they are full of it. It's really arrogant of me,
but I believe they're really screwing up.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
