A6047 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISAKSON-NEWT12-COX     11-11 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISAKSON-NEWT12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Isakson announces race to fill 6th District seat
 &HT;    By Clint Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Johnny Isakson announced he will run for Newt
Gingrich's congressional seat on Wednesday, then waited to see who
would join him.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans Chuck Clay and Clint Day, both of whom ran for
lieutenant governor in the Republican primary this summer, are
contemplating campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Clay, a state senator from Marietta, said he may announce his
decision today. Day, who lost the primary runoff to Mitch
Skandalakis, said he would make his decision early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, Tony Center became the only announced Democrat
in the race. Center got 42 percent of the vote when he ran against
Gingrich in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Isakson made his entry surrounded by supporters in the Marietta
Square, before an audience that included several state legislators
and Cobb County GOP Chairman Don Hill.
</P>
<P>
   One day earlier, House Speaker Gingrich issued a public
statement encouraging Isakson to run _ a move many interpreted as
an effort to discourage opposition in the coming special election.
</P>
<P>
   Isakson, now chairman of the state Board of Education, said he
and Gingrich had much in common.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were Republicans when Republican wasn't very cool,'' said
Isakson, whose political career dates back to the 1970s. Isakson
said his campaign will focus on tax reform and reducing the size of
the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in the principals of economic conservatism, I
believe in the principals of local control and I believe in a
manageable government that takes less out of the pockets of the
taxpayers,'' said the east Cobb County resident.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's tacit endorsement of Isakson hasn't discouraged other
Republicans from considering the race.
</P>
<P>
   Clay said polling done on his behalf shows it is a wide-open
race. ``The numbers show that it is winnable,'' Clay said. His
decision to run hinges on family concerns, said Clay, who has a
10-year-old daughter and an 8-month-old son.
</P>
<P>
   Day said he also feels well-positioned to win the seat,
benefiting from months of campaigning for lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   Both Clay and Day said they consider themselves more
conservative than Isakson, who supports abortion rights, and that
might be an advantage in a special election.
</P>
<P>
   Day is a staunch opponent of abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Clay doesn't support a ban on abortion, but obtained a perfect
score on his legislative positions this year from the Christian
Coalition. Clay said his own polling shows that social issues such
as abortion are far less of a concern than economic issues such as
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Gingrich's support, Isakson has several advantages.
Political consultant Jim Lovejoy noted that when Isakson ran
against Guy Millner for the GOP nomination for U.S. Senate in 1996,
Isakson carried the 6th Congressional District. Isakson also can
quickly raise a large amount of money to conduct a campaign,
Lovejoy said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
