<HEADER>
A6048 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-EMERGENCY12-CO     11-11 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-EMERGENCY12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Schools studying bloodshed
 &HT;    By Doug Cumming
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORSYTH, Ga. _ It's the latest education trend coming to your
neighborhood school: A disaster plan in case there's a shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Emergency Management Agency, the folks known for
coordinating civil responses to natural disasters, are now training
school officials and school security officers to handle, and help
prevent, bloodshed in the schoolhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Since June, GEMA has taken such training to 2,500 people in
Georgia schools. Conferences, like one on Tuesday, also have been
held at the Georgia Public Safety Training Center, said Karen
Franklin, hired this year as GEMA's first victims' awareness
coordinator. GEMA's message is that every school should have a
disaster plan not only for acts of God, but for shootings, should
know its county emergency coordinator and should be ready for what
happened in the past two years at schools in Pearl, Miss.; Paducah,
Ky.; Jonesboro, Ark.; Edinboro, Pa.; and Springfield, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools have plans for natural disasters,'' said Bill Slade,
police chief of Pearl, Ga., where a 16-year-old student killed two
and injured six at his school on Oct. 1, 1997. But schools don't
have plans for mass shootings. ``We didn't have one,'' said Slade,
who addressed the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to the shootings from Pearl to Springfield, Ga., have
been tempered by the reality check of statistics. Experts have
pointed out that schools in general are far safer places than the
streets and homes that surround them, and that even the rare
incidents of school shootings have become less frequent, not more,
during the past decade. In Georgia, several panels looking at
school violence and student discipline have spent far more time
looking at less sensational issues such as character education, the
fairness of discipline procedures and peer mediation.
</P>
<P>
   But even if schools are relatively safe, no level of violence is
acceptable, and the fear of violence alone disrupts learning and
drives good teachers out of the profession, said Michael Dorn,
chief of police for the Bibb County school system.
</P>
<P>
   The federally recognized Bibb model of school safety features
the oldest school police force in Georgia _ 27 officers and six
civilians that started in the early '70s to stop white flight by
making white families feel safe in newly integrated schools. It
didn't stop white flight, Dorn said, but today it works well at
curbing violence. Weapon confiscations have been reduced 90 percent
this decade, and the only two school shootings in the decade have
been at local private schools, Dorn said.
</P>
<P>
   A key element is prevention, he said. Students know they are
subject to random, surprise searches, which Dorn said is a far more
effective tool than doorway metal detectors. Fights, one of the
``triggering'' events for later use of weapons, are taken very
seriously. Both students in a typical fight are always punished.
Dorn said to be easier on the student who didn't start the fight is
to become ``co-dependent'' with one of the fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
