<HEADER>
A6061 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-BUILDUP-BOS &LR;      11-11 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-BUILDUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS WARNED AS US BUILDUP INTENSIFIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as UN-Iraq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Fed up with a year-long diplomatic effort to
contain Iraq, the Clinton administration Wednesday showed every
indication that it is poised to launch a military strike against
Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department urged US citizens to get out of Israel and
Kuwait as hundreds of UN weapons inspectors and relief workers left
Baghdad in response to American warnings that their lives will be
in jeopardy if they remain.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon shifted its military build-up in the Persian Gulf
into high gear Wednesday, ordering 3,000 US combat troops, 129
warplanes, and two new Scud-busting Patriot missile systems.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton delivered a stern warning to Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein to reverse his decision to block UN inspections into
the country's illegal weapons program or face military action.
</P>
<P>
   In his first public effort to make a case for military force in
Iraq, Clinton warned that Baghdad has the capacity to rebuild its
weapons arsenal in a matter of months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to hope, indeed pray, that Saddam will comply, but
we must be prepared to act if he does not,'' Clinton said during a
Veteran's Day speech at Arlington Cemetery. ``A failure to respond
could embolden Saddam to act recklessly, signaling to him that he
can with impunity develop these weapons of mass destruction or
threaten his neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   The American moves sent diplomats at the United Nations into
crisis mode.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary General Kofi Annan raced back early from a tour of
North Africa, while Russia called the UN Security Council together
for an emergency meeting in an attempt to keep the diplomatic track
alive.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to previous standoffs, Annan appeared unwilling to
heed appeals from European, Arab and African nations to intervene
diplomatically to avert an American attack.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he chided Baghdad for missing a ``genuine opportunity''
to obtain relief from nearly eight years of crippling economic
sanctions imposed after it invaded Kuwait in 1990. And he appealed
to the Iraqi leadership to back down.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a Secretary General I always try to seek peaceful
settlements,'' Annan said. ``But of course the American decision
(to attack) is in the hands of President Saddam Hussein.''
</P>
<P>
   The depth of international support, or opposition, to American
military action in the Gulf remained unclear Wednesday. Amid signs
that France and other European countries were growing increasingly
sympathetic to America's tough stand, British Prime Minister Tony
Blair said Wednesday that London is prepared to join Washington in
a military confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia continued to press publicly for a diplomatic
solution. ``We believe that the possibilities for a political
solution are not exhausted,'' Russia's foreign minister Ivan Ivanov
said Wednesday. ``Any use of force would not only render the
situation in the Gulf more difficult, but there would be
far-reaching consequences across the whole of the Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
   Arab leaders also continued to urge the Americans to seek a
diplomatic settlement. ``As far as I know, there is no one single
Arab country that supports the use of force against Iraq,''
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak was quoted as saying in the
government daily Al-Ahram Al-Masaei.
</P>
<P>
   In Baghdad, Saddam Hussein, held meeting with cabinet members,
air force commanders and anti-aircraft defense specialists. Deputy
Prime Minister Tariq Aziz, meanwhile, said that the UN inspectors'
decision to leave the country, following a recommendation from the
US, ``fully proves that UNSCOM (the UN Special Commission) acts in
accordance with the orders of the government of the United States.
The allegation that UNSCOM is a subsidiary organ of the Security
Council...is a mere false cover.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the 1991 cease-fire agreement ending the Gulf
war, Iraq is obligated to destroy all of its long range missiles
and obliterate its chemical, biological and nuclear arms programs.
Baghdad is also required to grant unfettered access to UN
inspectors seeking to ensure that Iraq has lived up to it
obligations.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1997, in the first major crisis with the UN, Iraq
expelled all Americans on the inspection team, a move that brought
Baghdad to the brink of war with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A February agreement between Annan and Hussein that ended the
standoff has since unraveled. On Aug. 5, Iraq reneged on the
accord, announcing that it was barring all surprise inspections
until the council moved to ease economic sanctions. On Oct. 31
Baghdad went further, halting virtually all cooperation with the
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   US officials say they are growing weary of endorsing short-term
diplomatic solutions to the recurring standoffs. And they have made
it clear to their allies that they would not welcome another
diplomatic initiative to end the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see any need for further warning,'' State Department
spokesman James P. Rubin said Wednesday. ``The clarity of the
situation in terms of what he needs to do does not lend itself to
diplomatic negotiations, it lends itself to Saddam Hussein
reversing course.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to underscore the message, Defense Secretary
William Cohen signed an order Wednesday sending the additional
forces to Kuwait to join 1,500 American soldiers already stationed
there, as well as 18 B-52 and B-1 bombers along with 12
radar-avoiding F-117A ``stealth'' jets. Also sent will be Patriot
missile capable of shooting down Iraqi Scud missiles if they are
fired against moderate Arab states in the Gulf, Pentagon spokesman
Ken Bacon told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Chief UN arms inspector Richard Butler made the decision to
shutter the UN's headquarters in Baghdad and send more than 100
arms inspectors to Bahrain after receiving a ``strong
recommendation'' to pull out from US ambassador Peter Burleigh, the
acting chief of the US mission to the United Nations on Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Butler said that the UN inspection teams, which are now in
Bahrain, would be ready to return to work within 24 hours if Saddam
reverses his position.
</P>
<P>
   Butler bridled at suggestions that UNSCOM would never be able to
continue its work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't accept the logic of those who say that a strike would
blow away UNSCOM. And I hear that said a lot,'' Butler said. ``If
such action were to be taken, I believe it would be taken to
enforce'' Baghdad's obligations to destroy its weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reinforced the sentiment. ``If the inspectors are not
permitted to visit suspect sites or monitor compliance at known
production facilities, they may as well be in Baltimore, not
Baghdad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The UN's humanitarian aid coordinator for Iraq, Benon Sevan,
said Wednesday that the UN oil-for food program _ which permits
Baghdad to sell up to $5.25 billion in oil every six months to buy
food and medicines, would continue at a limited level. He said
would withdraw 170 officials from Baghdad, leaving behind about 40
senior officials, including Annan's chief envoy Prakash Shah.
Another 231 UN relief workers will remain in the northern Kurdish
provinces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
