<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-WYE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL RATIFIES WYE PACT, BUT WITH STRINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ A wary Israeli cabinet narrowly ratified the new
land-for-security deal Wednesday, but linked it to a tough set of
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   After two weeks of delays and a spate of attacks by extremists
intent on destroying the peace process, the 17-member body voted
8-4 with five abstentions for a provisional approval of the interim
agreement with the Palestinians signed at the White House last
month.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference after the vote, Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu called the disputed land ``precious and important,'' and
threatened to annex parts of the West Bank if Palestinians follow
through on their vow to declare an independent state in May.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian negotiators immediately lashed out at the Israeli
conditions, calling them violations of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat said, ``We have worked
very hard to improve the trust level between us. By adding these
conditions, Mr. Netanyahu has done a great deal to destroy what all
of us _ the US, the Israelis, and the Palestinians _ had tried to
do. He has violated the agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The narrow vote in Netanyahu's fractious coalition, analysts
say, revealed the fragility of his hold on power. The conditions
that came with the vote illustrate his need to placate the far
right, which vehemently opposes the agreement and has threatened to
topple his government.
</P>
<P>
   The vote also shows that despite the dogged diplomacy of
President Clinton that helped produce this agreement, the US still
has a daunting challenge ahead to press Israel to honor the bargain
and ensure implementation of the agreement by both sides.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which was struck after a nine-day summit at the Wye
River Plantation in Maryland, calls for a further 13.1 percent
Israeli troop withdrawl from the West Bank in exchange for a
greater effort by Palestinians, with the assistance of the US
Central Intelligence Agency, to crack down on Islamic terrorist
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The West Bank, including East Jerusalem, was captured by Israel
in the 1967 Six Day War. The 13 percent phased troop withdrawal
called for in the agreement would leave the Palestinians with full
or partial control of 40 percent of the West Bank. Israel was
scheduled to begin the first of a three-stage pullback next Monday,
but has already said it will be delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's cabinet ratified the agreement with the following
conditions:
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Parts of the West Bank would be annexed by Israel if the
Palestinians follow through on their vow to unilaterally declare an
independent state in May.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)The next, or third, phase of further Israeli troop
withdrawals from the West Bank will be no more than one percent.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)The Palestinian National Council will vote to annul
passages in the Palestinian Liberation Organization's charter that
call for Israel's destruction.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)The Israeli cabinet will assess the Palestinians'
performance in living up to their obligations under the agreement
and will stop the process if they fail to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian negotiators charged that the Netanyahu government
had badly damaged what little trust had been reestablished between
the two sides in Wye.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have been different,'' said Erekat. ``We have urged
Mr. Netanyahu to refrain form the language of threats and
conditionality. We will not accept any post-agreement negotiations.
This is why it is essential that the Americans will join us in
ensuring implementation.''
</P>
<P>
   Erekat added, ``Netanyahu is giving one condition to (Foreign
Minister Ariel) Sharon, and another to the Jewish settlers, and
another to the religious parties. All of this makes for an
impossible balance between making peace and satisfying the
extremists in Israel. Why should the peace process suffer for
domestic Israeli politics?''
</P>
<P>
   The thorniest issue in the near future will be a meeting next
month in Gaza, which Clinton has said he will attend, of the
Palestine National Council and other bodies to delete passages of
the PLO charter that call for Israel's destruction.
</P>
<P>
   In this ratification, Israel made a demand not part of the Wye
agreement that the full council must vote on these changes. The Wye
agreement does call for the council to be invited to the
mid-Demember meeting, but does not require them to vote on the
formal changes to the charter. Palestinians insist that the council
already voted to annul those passages in 1996, a vote that was
recognized at the time by the United States and by Netanyahu's more
liberal predecessor Shimon Peres.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the (council) members will be invited, as the agreement
said, and the ratification has to be done by vote. There is no
other way,'' Netanyahu said at a press conference Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has written to Israel that the
gathering will ``reaffirm'' the 1996 Palestinian National Council
vote canceling anti-Israeli provisions in the document.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke with Netanyahu Tuesday night about the agreement
and the US confrontation with Iraq over weapons inspections.
According to Israeli press reports Wednesday, Clinton told
Netanyahu the tough US policy toward Iran was facing opposition in
the Arab world because Israel had not moved forward on the
implementation of the Wye agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The US-led coalition against Iraq in 1991 is widely credited for
setting the stage for the current Mideast peace process. And today,
as tensions mount again between the United States and Iraq, the two
remain inextricably linked.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.
</P>
