<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-GATES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATES TELLS SHAREHOLDERS HE'S EAGER FOR DEFENSE PHASE OF TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WARREN WILSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLEVUE, Wash. _ E-mail messages in which Microsoft Corp.
Chairman Bill Gates says he sought a ``win-win'' solution to a
dispute with Apple Computer is part of the evidence Microsoft will
present in its defense against government antitrust charges, Gates
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The notes would counter evidence offered by prosecutors last
week that Microsoft illegally pressured Apple to divide the market
for certain multimedia software, in part by threatening to stop
making products that Apple considered ``critical'' to the future of
its Macintosh operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Four witnesses have testified for the government so far in the
trial, which began last month in federal court in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Gates, speaking at the company's annual shareholders meeting,
said he is ``personally looking forward'' to the defense phase,
when Microsoft gets to present its own witnesses and evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Though he wasn't expected to dwell on the antitrust action, he
devoted a major portion of his speech to it and fielded questions
about it from the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Restating the key theme of the company's defense, he said the
key principle at stake is its freedom to design its products as it
sees fit _ a freedom he called the ``engine of innovation'' in
business.
</P>
<P>
   With software prices low, the high-tech industry thriving and
venture capital flowing to startups at a record pace, he asked
rhetorically if the lawsuit was brought on behalf of consumers, or
at their expense, on behalf of a ``handful of competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't specifically address the government's claim that
Microsoft has shown a pattern of anticompetitive behavior. But he
vowed that by the time the trial is over, Microsoft will show that
the facts in the case ``simply don't support the government's
claims.''
</P>
<P>
   He would be hard-pressed to find a more supportive audience than
his shareholders, who have watched Microsoft's stock soar in value
70 percent in the past year alone. They gave three standing
ovations to Gates and three other top executives in the first five
minutes of the hour-long meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the antitrust trial was clearly on the minds of
many. One questioner asked for the executives' thoughts on a
possible breakup of the company, a topic about which chief
operating officer Bob Herbold politely but firmly said the company
would not speculate.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the company's relationship with Apple, in light of
critical testimony last week, Gates said Microsoft was the only
company to ``bet our future'' on Apple and have products ready when
the Macintosh was introduced in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft remained Apple's ``greatest supporter'' through
lengthy litigation over the point-and-click interface that Apple
claimed Microsoft had stolen and a later dispute over $1 billion in
patent claims, Gates said.
</P>
<P>
   He denied claims that Microsoft had sabotaged Apple's QuickTime
multimedia software and said independent lab tests had shown that
the problems an Apple executive discussed in his trial testimony
were the result of Apple's own bugs, not anything that Microsoft
did.
</P>
<P>
   When introduced at the trial, Gates said, his e-mail messages
will demonstrate that his dealings were ``based on there being a
clear win-win'' for the two companies.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of future earnings, Herbold warned shareholders that
Microsoft's revenues aren't likely to grow as quickly as they have
in the past, that it has squeezed almost all the fat out of
expenses and it plans to keep throwing money at research and
development in order to maintain its leadership.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, he said, the company is poised to release a
major upgrade of its SQL database program at next week's Comdex
show in Las Vegas, and new versions of its Office productivity
suite and Windows NT, newly renamed Windows 2000, are due out later
in the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
