u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IPO-MARKET-BOS &LR;      11-11 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IPO-MARKET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET FOR INITIAL PUBLIC OFFERINGS IS HEATING UP AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The heart of Wall Street is starting to beat again.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate stock and bond sales were arrested by the turmoil in
financial markets in August and September. But a handful of initial
public offerings, or IPOs, especially by high-technology companies,
have shown particular vigor in recent days as institutional
investors return to small-company stocks in a stabilized market.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; EarthWeb Inc., riding the craze for Internet stocks, tripled
Wednesday in its first day of trading, gaining 3411/16 to close at
4811/16. Investors Wednesday snapped up stock issued by News Corp.,
which spun off a 20 percent stake in its Fox Entertainment Group
division. The Fox stock, which was priced Tuesday at $22.50 a share
and raised $2.8 billion for the company, gained $2 a share
Wednesday in trading and closed at 24 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you'd asked me three weeks ago if we'd see any IPOs by
year-end I'd have said, `Absolutely not.' The market's changing
very quickly,'' said Kathryn Kirk, a managing director in the
Boston office of investment bank Hambrecht &AMP; Quist. She predicted:
``We'll definitely see more activity by year-end.''
</P>
<P>
   The economy continues to send mixed signals about the future,
and companies nationwide are paring their payrolls. But despite the
summer bear market, investors have pushed the Dow Jones industrials
index up 11.6 percent this year. The S&AMP;P 500 and Nasdaq indexes
have gained 15.5 percent and 18.6 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The bond market is also seeing more action. Corporations are
tapping debt investors who have become more receptive to something
other than the extremely safe securities sold by the US government.
Saks Inc., MBIA Inc., and AT&AMP;T Capital Corp. are among the
companies that have waded into the bond market this month.
</P>
<P>
   An interest rate cut by the Federal Reserve has made money
extraordinarily cheap for companies such as Sprint Corp., which
this week sold $5 billion in the corporate bond market in the
second-largest bond deal in history. These deals have dispelled
concerns, for now, of a liquidity crunch, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in early November eagerly snapped up Raytheon Co.'s
short- and medium-term bonds, which carried yields of 5.7 percent
to 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``We went to the market with the intention of doing $750
million but the demand was so healthy we ended up placing $1.4
billion,'' said spokeswoman Toni Simonetti. Proceeds of the bond
issue were used to repay higher-yielding debt issued to finance the
acquisitions of the defense units of Hughes Electronics Co. and
Texas Instruments Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide, markets were so unstable last summer that bond
investors fled to US Treasuries, pushing yields on the government
bonds to new lows. As markets have calmed, corporate treasurers
``are saying rates are down a lot and I want to take advantage of
it,'' said Robert MacIntosh, a vice president at Eaton Vance
Management in Boston. ``It's as simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   Disarray last summer was even greater in stocks after a mad rush
to the market early in 1998 as the Dow climbed to its July 17 high.
IPO sales in the third quarter plunged to $6.38 billion, compared
with $11.31 billion in the same quarter last year when the market
was more robust, according to BT Alex. Brown, a Baltimore
investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   Existing public companies also shied away from raising money in
the stock market: Secondary offerings plunged to $8.85 billion,
compared with $20.25 billion in the third quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   While some uncertainty lingers, financial markets ``seem to be
more tempered than panicky and people have a much more balanced
perspective on it,'' said William Burgess, co-head of corporate
finance in the Boston office of BT Alex. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence of this, while not overwhelming, is notable: A
total of four IPOs came to market in all of September and October,
while the first 11 days of November have seen three, said Jennifer
McBrien, an analyst for Renaissance Capital Corp., a Greenwich,
Conn., money manager and IPO research company.
</P>
<P>
   Institutional investors are eager to acquire big-name companies.
And McBrien was not surprised to see investors' strong reception to
Fox's deal, because the company has ``such a well-known brand among
investors that it's bound to be popular.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, whose properties include the Los Angeles Dodgers and the
hit movie ``Titanic,'' originally planned to sell 85 million shares
but ultimately sold 125 million, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to EarthWeb and Fox, November has yielded stock
sales by MONY Group Inc., the parent company of one of the nation's
biggest insurers, Mutual Life Insurance Co. of New York. MONY's
stock garnered strong enough demand that underwriter Goldman, Sachs
&AMP; Co. raised the price range on the 11.25 million-share deal to the
$21.50-to-$23.50 a share range, from $18.50-to-$21.50.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in Internet stocks are pushing them to irrational
levels. The stock of eBay, for example, sold at $18 a share on
Sept. 24, raising $63 million for the Internet auctioneer. EBay
closed Wednesday at 115 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   Ticketmaster Online-City Search Inc., Infinity Media, and E TEK
Dynamics are expected to test the new issues market in coming
months.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service Material was used to prepare this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
