<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY TARGETS INHERITANCE, ESTATE PLANNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ She turned the public charity arm of the nation's
largest mutual fund firm into the biggest grant maker of its kind,
tapping into the philanthropic ambitions of newly rich investors.
Now Jamie B. Jaffee, who stepped down Wednesday as head of Fidelity
Investments' Charitable Gift Fund, is gearing up to tackle how
investors give money to heirs.
</P>
<P>
   Jaffee will head up a new Fidelity initiative to woo customers
grappling with inheritance and estate planning. The project, still
under wraps, reflects Fidelity's new efforts to tap into the
private side of wealth transfer as well as retain customers at
every stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have lots of customers who face the issue of inheritance
every day,'' said Fidelity marketing head Stephen A. Cone, under
whom Jaffee will work. ``Jamie is in the right position to have the
right product offerings.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaffee, 42, was succeeded at the gift fund by Cynthia L. Egan,
43, a nine-year Fidelity executive who most recently worked in
trustee services at Fidelity's trust company.
</P>
<P>
   In its seven-year life under Jaffee, the $1.7 billion Charitable
Gift Fund, the nation's number-one grant maker among public
charities last year, distributed $750 million to 50,000 charities.
In her new role, Jaffee will seek to do for private inheritors what
she did for public charities.
</P>
<P>
   Eric M. Kobren, publisher of the independent Fidelity Insight
newsletter, said the initiative reflected efforts by privately held
Fidelity to keep investors' dollars from cradle to grave and
beyond. ``Fidelity starts with small investors and then sometimes
loses them when they become big investors'' with pension plans that
must be ``rolled over'' to other investment products upon
retirement, Kobren said.
</P>
<P>
   The Charitable Gift Fund recently attracted criticism for
improperly allowing some donors to direct contributions to private
foundations to buy event tickets and fund college scholarships.
Fidelity put an end to the practice, which was not widespread, last
summer, and was reaffirmed as a public charity by the Internal
Revenue Service in August.
</P>
<P>
   Jaffee's new title is executive vice president of retail
marketing at Fidelity's Personal Investments &AMP; Brokerage Group, the
fund giant's main sales, distribution, and marketing unit. Cone
said Jaffee would coordinate four areas, including the gift fund,
college investment trust unit, regular trust section, and personal
investments review group.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has really looked at these four areas holistically at
Fidelity,'' Cone said. Jaffee's brief, which Fidelity termed `a
major wealth transfer initiative', would not lead investors to give
less to charities and more to heirs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Community foundations, which do not have corporate Fidelity's
advertizing budgets, have complained that Fidelity's gift fund has
an unfair advantage in attracting charitable donors. Fidelity,
which had total assets under management of $645.4 billion as of
Sept. 30, counters that it has made philanthropy more accessible to
ordinary investors.
</P>
<P>
   For as little as $10,000, the gift fund lets investors direct
money to charities or set up foundations. It invests in some
Fidelity mutual funds but does not pay donors any money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
