<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCKOUT CONTINUES WITH NO END IN SIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is what it has come down to: The executive director of the
NBA Players Association Wednesday held a conference call to reveal
that he may call the league Thursday to see if commissioner David
Stern wants to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the NBA lockout continues with no end in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday more than 30 players met with union chief Billy Hunter
for about five hours and decided that they needn't offer anything
new for discussion. Hunter did say he might call Stern to see if a
meeting could be arranged to get the stalled talks going again.
</P>
<P>
   However, Hunter said he expected no response from the league,
adding that Stern and the owners are waiting for the players to
start missing paychecks, the first of which are due Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The period hasn't passed where our players are expected to
cave,'' Hunter said in a conference call with reporters. ``(The
players) have not broken ranks, and I can assure you we're not
going to break ranks.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said he thinks the league is pointing to a Jan. 1
start-up date after making the players ``sweat a little.'' He
added, however, that after meeting with the union's executive
committee and player representatives, he finds that the vast
majority of the players still are united and that there is a
``greater resolve'' to stick to their latest proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The sides are far apart on the key issue: how to divide the
lucrative NBA pie. The players received 57 percent last year and
are disinclined to take less. The league is asking for a 50-50
split. Various plans have been discussed to make sure neither side
gets more than agreed to, but those plans are meaningless without a
number with which to work.
</P>
<P>
   Before the conference call, Hunter revealed that the union is
trying to stage an exhibition in Las Vegas the first week of
December. He indicated that Michael Jordan would attend but not
necessarily play, that the game might feature players from the
three Olympic Dream Teams, and that Showtime had expressed interest
in televising it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players are interested in keeping themselves busy, and we
think that one way to do it is have some sort of an exhibition
competition,'' Hunter said. ``The proceeds would go to the
(union).''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter made no reference to the game during his 45-minute
conference call. Instead, he again criticized the NBA for refusing
to negotiate and for thinking that the players will crack once the
paychecks don't arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Most players are paid twice a month, so already, they will miss
both November checks. Given the glacial pace of negotiations, it
seems likely they also will miss the Dec. 15 check; the league has
said there will have to be a three- to four-week period before the
start of the season for teams to have training camps and for free
agents to test the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players have taken a stand, and it's a stand based on
principle,'' Hunter said. ``If you think their demeanor is going to
change on Nov. 15 or Nov. 30, you're going to be let down. They are
prepared. But that is the antiquated thinking of the league. Well,
Nov. 15 is going to come and go, as is Nov. 30.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been no serious discussions since Oct. 28, a pace
that has some agents a little upset. There was a brief meeting last
Friday, at which time the union was thinking of ``tweaking'' its
latest proposal. It didn't. Stern has authorized clubs to talk to
players about the league's proposal _ the NBA said the chats should
be ``informational only'' _ thinking it will show the majority that
the league's offer is equitable.
</P>
<P>
   The union disagrees. Hunter said the union has been making all
the concessions _ he said some were historic in relation to other
sports _ and won't offer anything new because ``we'd basically be
bargaining against ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
