<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0406 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6089 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      11-11 1724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEELY   -- OLDER, HEAVIER -- BACK ON THE ICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Mass. _ He stepped on the ice at 11:38 a.m., right
after coach Pat Burns and before forward Anson Carter. For the next
47 minutes, all eyes _ those of teammates, coaches, management, and
media _ were on Cam Neely, who Wednesday participated in his first
Bruins practice since February 1996.
</P>
<P>
   At 33, Neely acknowledged he is a few years older and a few
pounds heavier since his forced retirement before the 1996-97
season because of a chronic hip injury. But the once-fearsome right
wing said he will know in the next 12 days whether he will be able
to come back. The Bruins have unofficially earmarked Nov. 23 as the
day they expect to determine whether Neely has a legitimate chance
to return.
</P>
<P>
   Neely said Wednesday's workout, which was impressive, given his
long layoff, had only one guideline: ``Get off when you feel like
you're going to throw up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I can still shoot,'' he said. ``I can still pass. I
don't feel like I've lost a lot of skill. It's a matter of
conditioning and how my health is going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time, beginning in midseason of 1995-96, when Neely
couldn't sleep at night because he was in constant pain. In an
interview with the Globe in Edmonton right after he played what
turned out to be his final game in Anaheim Feb. 21, 1996, Neely
said that if his extreme discomfort continued, he would have to
consider retirement. It was thought in the months that followed
that the bone spurs in his arthritic hip would lead to a hip
replacement by the time he was 40.
</P>
<P>
   Now physical therapist Dan Dyrek, whom experts believe added
five years to the career of Celtics great Larry Bird, has helped
give Neely a completely different outlook. Neely felt so positive
about his progress that he turned down job offers from the
Islanders, who wanted him as an assistant coach, and Fox-TV, which
wanted him as a hockey analyst in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I would really be a fool for not giving it another
opportunity,'' he said. ``I didn't want three or four years down
the road to say, `What if I did give it the extra two or three
months and work a little harder to see if I could play again?' I
didn't want to be upset with myself down the road. If in another 10
days my hip tells me I can't do this, then I can absolutely walk
away and say I gave it an honest effort and I gave my hip a chance
I never thought I'd be able to give it and it just didn't work
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Neely has never found anything outside the sport that stirred
the kind of career passion he had while playing in the NHL. In
addition, he didn't go out of the game on his own terms and has had
a hard time accepting that. But Neely said he won't jeopardize his
long-term health chasing a dream. Judging from his performance in
drills Wednesday, his skills are still very evident, though his
conditioning is obviously lacking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been able to put hockey completely out of my mind
because it wasn't my decision to pack it in,'' he said. ``I still
feel skillwise I can play, it was just healthwise. I do love
playing the game and I do love being around the guys and in this
atmosphere. It's just a matter of getting the tissues and muscles
back into condition.''
</P>
<P>
   The magic Dyrek has been able to work revolves around extensive
stretching exercises that lengthen the tendons and muscles in the
hip joint. The regimen got Neely to the point where he was able to
work out privately with coach Pat Burns and assistant Jacques
Laperriere, who endorsed full participation in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have bone spurs in the hip socket, but my hip socket
was compressed and the muscles and tendons have shortened,'' he
said. ``(Dyrek) went in and broke down the scar tissue. We're
trying to elongate those muscles and tissues around the hip. If I
skate four days in a row and my hip is barking at me, that's all
she wrote. I'm not going to go through the pain I went through when
I went to pack it in. That's just not worth it to me. Four days of
good, hard skating may tell me, `Hey, this is just not happening.'
My hip is allowing me to take it to this point. Will it allow me to
get to another point? I don't know yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Neely's balky left knee, which was the subject of
daily updates for a couple of seasons, is the least of his
problems. It was once theorized that the reason Neely wound up with
a right hip problem was that he was overcompensating for the knee
problem on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   ``The knee is so much better than it ever was, it doesn't
concern me at all,'' he said. ``I feel if I can come back, I hope I
can come back to an everyday player and practice every day.''
</P>
<P>
   He is tempering his enthusiasm, as are the Bruins, because all
partries know one day won't decide anything. Yet the first day
wasn't discouraging, and perhaps that is encouragement enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a couple years of pain in everyday life with my hip,
and one thing I said was I don't want to get better to get worse,''
said Neely. ``The only way I'm going to continue this is if I know
I won't jeopardize any long-term health. If I do continue this,
there will be periodic treatments with my hip. Hopefully, it won't
give me any problems in my future. That's really what I want to
avoid. If it shows it's going to do that, then I won't continue to
try to play. My hip felt pretty good. I feel it more in the longer
strides. If my lungs felt as good as my hip, I'd be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Neely, who defined the position of power forward in
the NHL with his punishing hits, fierce play in front of the net,
and cannon shot off the right wing, said contact doesn't concern
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the least of my worries, getting physical with this,''
he said. ``It's more just use of the muscles and tendons around the
joint than anything about taking contact or banging against the
wall. I expect to experience some pain for some part of the day.
Hopefully by the end of the day, it will be gone and (today) I
won't feel anything again. It all depends on how that goes. If I
feel it (today), I can expect to feel it worse the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Neely won't do is come back at half speed. Reason No.
1 is that he wouldn't be able to make a contribution. Reason No. 2,
which is more significant, is that his pride won't let him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't feel I can play at a level I want to play at, I
won't continue this,'' he said. ``It's just not worth it to me (to)
not play as well as I'd like to play. The Bruins are giving me an
opportunity to take it to another level and get some quality
practice time that I can't get by myself. I'm not concerned about
anything else right now except giving my hip another test.''
</P>
<P>
   President-general manager Harry Sinden, who was in attendance
with assistant GM Mike O'Connell, said he couldn't help but be
enthused about the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I'm excited, but I'm realistic, too,'' said Sinden. ``I
don't see any hitch in his movement, but who knows if he wakes up
tomorrow and ... it's touch-and-go. I'm as realistic as he is. The
odds are against him. He feels better with the treatments he's been
getting that he began a few months ago and he thought, `Well, let's
keep going until something tells me to stop,' which might happen
and then we'll all hang our heads. I'm keeping my expectations
where they should be. I've told the coaches the same thing, and the
players understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sinden can't help being enthused about the prospects of
getting a 50-goal scorer back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of those players you never forget, not only because
of what he did on the ice but the attitude he brought to the game
was fantastic,'' said Sinden. ``We've had a number of players like
that _ (Bobby) Orr, (Ray) Bourque, (Terry) O'Reilly, and (Gerry)
Cheevers _ and I don't forget those players, either. They really
brought an attitude to the team that helped us immensely. It's nice
to have him around.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said Neely is covered for medical insurance, an
arrangement similar to that for players who come into training camp
for a tryout. Neely's representative, Jay Fee, who was also in
attendance, said he and Sinden have had preliminary discussions
about a potential contract.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Neely will continue to skate every day (with the
exception of tomorrow, when the club will be in New York to face
the Rangers), and only time will tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a movie script,'' said right wing Steve Heinze, one of
the few Bruins left who played with Neely. ``Obviously, it's going
to attract attention. I like having him here as a friend in the
locker room. But we don't have a 50-goal scorer. On the ice, he
attracts attention by the style he plays, the big hits, the fights,
and the goals. What else do people come out to watch hockey for?
The bone-crunching hits, the flashy scoring, the fights _
obviously, that's what people come to watch. No knock to anyone in
this locker room, but we don't have one guy who's doing all of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Young Joe Thornton said he had met Neely but knew him mostly as
``a scoring machine. He's just a tank out there. He used to run
over guys. It's a little strange, but I think it's exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinze, Bourque, and Don Sweeney had a lot of experience with
Neely. Defenseman Kyle McLaren was just beginning his career as
Neely's appeared to be ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was hurting for sure (when the two were on the same
squad),'' said McLaren, whose tenure overlapped Neely's during the
defenseman's rookie season of 1995-96. ``Still, he can probably
beat me up, even today. His worst day is probably one of my best
days. I thought he looked good, real good. He was skating well and
shooting well. I'm happy for him.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Left wing Sergei Samsonov was the lone Bruin who didn't skate
Wednesday. Samsonov, who injured the bursa sac in his elbow during
last Thursday's game against Toronto, had to have the sac drained.
He's expected to play Friday ... The Bruins learned that former
goaltender Frank ``Mr. Zero'' Brimsek, who played for them in the
1930s and '40s, died at the age of 83 at his home in Minnesota.
Brimsek played in 444 games for Boston, compiling a record of
230-144-70 with 35 shutouts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
