<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-IRAQ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. PREPARES FOR MILITARY ACTION AGAINST IRAQ 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon bolstered forces in the Persian Gulf
Wednesday as President Clinton said he was preparing for possible
military action against Iraq unless Saddam Hussein stops defying
international arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations Security Council met in New York in emergency
session as Clinton ordered his national security team to develop
military options.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen signed an order dispatching
another 129 military aircraft and 3,000 Army troops to Kuwait. The
aircraft carrier Enterprise also was moving toward the region.
</P>
<P>
   The United States already has 170 fighter jets and bombers and
20 Navy ships, several with the capability of firing Tomahawk
cruise missiles, stationed near Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   In response to U.S. warnings, the United Nations Special
Commission (UNSCOM) evacuated its 400 arms experts and staff from
Baghdad. The State Department authorized nonessential personnel to
leave neighboring Kuwait and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The president, speaking at Veteran's Day ceremonies at Arlington
National Cemetery, said failure to act against Saddam could
encourage the Iraqi leader to act recklessly and could undermine
the credibility of the United Nations Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to hope, indeed, pray, that Saddam will comply,
but we must be prepared to act if he does not,'' Clinton told
veterans.
</P>
<P>
   As he has repeatedly in the past 12 months, Saddam instigated
the international crisis by refusing on Oct. 31 to cooperate with
U.N. arms inspectors charged with determining the status of Iraq's
chemical, biological and nuclear weapons capabilities. The Iraqi
dictator is demanding that international economic sanctions, which
have crippled the oil-rich nation, be lifted.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq agreed to the inspections as part of the 1991 peace accord
dictated by U.S.-led allies who repelled Saddam's invasion of
Kuwait. But in recent years, the inspections have amounted to a
cat-and-mouse game as Saddam sought to thwart the experts.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said the additional forces moving to the gulf
include 12 B-52 bombers armed with Tomahawk missiles, six B-1
bombers and 12 F-117A stealth fighters capably of avoiding radar.
Other fighter jets and support aircraft also are part of the
package.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's order also adds two Patriot anti-missile batteries to
the region in addition to the three already there. The Patriot
system was used in the 1991 Persian Gulf War to counter Iraq's Scud
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect that the first units will be leaving in the next few
days. It means that (President Clinton) has more options at his
disposal. It gives him more flexibility,'' said Ken Bacon, the
Pentagon spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 23,500 U.S. military personnel in the
region, including 1,500 Army troops already in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright delayed her departure for
Malaysia where Clinton and other Pacific Rim leaders plan to gather
this weekend for the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation forum.
</P>
<P>
   James Rubin, Albright's spokesman, said Saddam would receive no
warnings if the United States decides to strike. ``We don't see the
point or the need for further warning,'' Rubin said. ``The clarity
of the situation in terms of what he needs to do does not lend
itself to diplomatic negotiation. It lends itself to Saddam Hussein
reversing course.''
</P>
<P>
   Army Gen. Hugh Shelton, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, said during several television interviews that Saddam has
had enough warnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``A decision has not been made as to the use of force,'' Shelton
said on NBC's ``Today Show.'' ``I think Saddam clearly understands,
as we have said publicly, that all options are on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright spoke to foreign ministers in Russia, France and
Britain as well as U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan and informed
them of the decision to also reduce its State Department personnel
in U.S. embassies in Kuwait and Israel. Iraq fired on Israel during
the 1991 conflict although Israel was not a party to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   In Kuwait, the U.S. Embassy also advised the 8,000 U.S.
civilians there to consider leaving the country in light of
possible military action against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations evacuated its arms inspectors and their
staff, as well as some humanitarian U.N. aide workers, within hours
of receiving warnings from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was obliged to act quickly, to take the decision that I
took, because of the strong recommendation that had been put to me,
which could have an impact upon the safety of our people,'' said
UNSCOM Chairman Richard Butler, adding he received the warning from
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Butler appeared at the U.N. Security Council session convened
after Russia, which has opposed military action against Iraq,
demanded an explanation for the evacuation of personnel. The U.N.
staff was moved to Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council has been divided over the use of force
against Iraq. Russia and China insist fresh council approval is
needed for such a move.
</P>
<P>
   Annan, who is returning today from a North Africa trip because
of the crisis, urged the Iraqi government to ``rescind its decision
and resume immediate cooperation'' with inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   In his Veteran's Day address, Clinton said the international
community remained united and that Saddam could not ``have it both
ways'' by keeping his weapons of mass destruction and by getting
rid of the economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Saddam must not only cooperate with the inspection
teams but allow them unfettered access to suspected sites. Without
such access, Clinton said Iraq would have a window of opportunity
to ``rebuild its arsenal of weapons and delivery systems in months,
and I say again, in months, not years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A failure to respond could embolden Saddam to act recklessly,
signaling to him that he can with impunity, develop these weapons
of mass destruction or threaten his neighbors,'' Clinton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
