<HEADLINE>
SCELZI FITS IN AS `NOT-SO-FAMOUS' NHRA CHAMPION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gary Scelzi figures to leave Pomona Raceway this weekend a world
champion times two.
</P>
<P>
   Two seasons in a Top Fuel dragster and two National Hot Rod
Association Winston world championships confirm that this driver is
a special talent. But don't try selling Scelzi on that idea.
</P>
<P>
   Ask about his ability to routinely manhandle a Top Fuel coupe at
320-plus mph, and Scelzi humbly defers to the tuning expertise of
car owner and crew chief Alan Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody says, `We all know Alan's great. But what's the deal
with his driver?' '' said Scelzi, winner of five races a year ago
and a record-tying six finals this season. ``Maybe I'm harder on
myself than I need to be. But I'm driving for the best. And he
expects the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Suggest that Scelzi's skills, then, make him worthy of mention
alongside multiple NHRA champions and peers Joe Amato, Kenny
Bernstein and John Force, and he cringes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different when you hear your name mentioned with these
great people I grew up watching and who are my heroes,'' said
Scelzi, a 38-year-old resident of Fresno, Calif. ``It's like, which
name doesn't belong here? It's almost frightening. I'm
not-so-famous. But I'm here. We're in the big leagues. We won a
championship last year, and it looks like we're going to do it
again this year. It's a great feeling. It puts me in awe.''
</P>
<P>
   Scelzi holds a 115-point lead over friendly rival Cory
McClenathan heading into the season-ending Winston Finals in
Pomona, Calif. Round One of professional qualifications is
scheduled today, and Scelzi could secure the title with his first
quarter-mile pass. Qualify for the 16-car field, and the
championship is his.
</P>
<P>
   The scenario is similar to last November, when Scelzi bagged the
NHRA championship with his first qualifying attempt at the Winston
Finals. He also became the first rookie to win an NHRA championship
in any professional category.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, neither Amato nor Bernstein nor Force _ who count 17
championships in Top Fuel and Funny Car among them _ could pull
that off as rookies. And none of the above captured his first
championship amid the emotions swirling around Scelzi in 1997.
Recall that Scelzi was hired to succeed the late Blaine Johnson,
Alan's brother, after his death during qualifications for the 1997
U.S. Nationals.
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies the part of this speedy equation that keeps Scelzi
so self-effacing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in a car that's under a microscope,'' said Scelzi, driver
of the Team Winston Dragster. ``My biggest problem is I'm driving a
car that should win every single race. I have the best tuner out
there. My crew has the utmost confidence in Alan Johnson. When he's
onto something _ even if things don't go right 10 times in a row _
he knows that's the direction he's got to go. And he doesn't
stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: Team Winston was mired in eighth place after four
events in mid-March and looking every bit like a one-hit wonder. It
was because, Scelzi said, Johnson was attempting to refine a clutch
combination that would transfer to the rear wheels all the
horsepower his new cylinder heads were producing. It took Johnson
until the season's 18th race at Heartland Park Topeka to figure it
out.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Scelzi has swept the national events at the Texas
Motorplex and Houston Raceway Park and transformed an 11-point
deficit to McClenathan into his current triple-digit runaway. In
addition, Scelzi has lowered the Top Fuel elapsed time (4.525
seconds) and raised the speed (326.44 mph) national records in one
very red-hot, red hot rod.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always driven cars that were good cars, but never the
dominating car,'' said Scelzi, a multiple champion in the NHRA's
Sportsman ranks. ``So, I always went out with nothing to lose. And
I think that's what made me so successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that he has the car and the tuner to run for world
championships, Scelzi said nothing else counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain amount of pride you put out when you are a
Winston champion. We didn't want to lose that,'' Scelzi said.
``Let's face it. We all want to wear a crown and we all want to be
on stage at the end of the year. Anybody who tells you they don't
is a liar.'' \Ntagtop:John Sturbin, (817) 390-7408
THE BUZZ NASCAR
</P>
<P>
   A slew of impressive records has accompanied Jeff Gordon's run
to a second consecutive NASCAR Winston Cup championship and third
in the past four years. The most visible, of course, are the 13
victories that tied Richard Petty's record for the modern era
(since 1972). But here are some astonishing stats. Gordon compiled
a 1.90 finishing average in the season's last 20 races, and
averaged 175.3 points per race (of a possible 185) during that
period. His victory in the season-ending and rain-delayed NAPA 500
at the Atlanta Motor Speedway on Sunday night was his 19th top-five
finish in the past 20 races. His only result outside the top five
during that marathon span was a seventh, at Phoenix International
Raceway, on Oct. 25. Incidentally, that was the only race of the
last four that Gordon did not win. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a little upset about some things this season and maybe
that anger turned into determination,'' said Gordon, driver of the
No. 24 DuPont Automotive Finishes Chevrolet Monte Carlo. ``Maybe
certain criticisms we took this year kind of drove us to get more
out of ourselves and to prove to people out there that we're
legit.'' Recall that Gordon drew plenty of guffaws _ and a
collection of alarm clocks _ after oversleeping before a practice
at Charlotte Motor Speedway in May. ``My being late at Charlotte
fired me up, and I wanted to show the team that I'm dedicated to
this program,'' Gordon said. ``I was early for practice the rest of
the season.'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Irwin Jr. won the 1998 Winston Cup rookie-of-the-year
title by 13 points over Kevin Lepage. Irwin, driver of the No. 28
Texaco Havoline Ford Taurus, became the first driver to win the
rookie honor and post winnings in excess of $1 million. That was a
nice weekend package for Irwin, who won his first Cup pole at
Atlanta Motor Speedway on Friday. ``I couldn't write down
everything I've learned \Rthis season\S because I've forgotten some
of it already,'' said Irwin, who had only one top-five finish and
one DNQ (did not qualify) in 1998. ``People talk about how would
you grade yourself, but I don't grade myself. You \Rthe media\S
grade me, Robert Yates grades me, the team grades me. That's how I
get my report card. Some weeks I feel like we're ahead of the game,
and some weeks I can't see the top. I don't know where it's going
to end. Hopefully, I'm here for the long haul.''
NHRA
</P>
<P>
   Seven-time Funny Car champion John Force will carry a 91-point
lead over Ron Capps into the season-ending National Hot Rod
Association Winston Finals at Pomona (Calif.) Raceway beginning
today. ``The Brute'' can clinch his record eighth title by winning
one round of eliminations. But Force has other goals on his agenda.
Force owned drag racing's all-time speed record of 323.89 mph until
Top Fuel champion Gary Scelzi blasted off a lap at 326.44 mph
during the Matco Tools SuperNationals at Houston Raceway Park in
Baytown this month. ``I was happy to see Gary Scelzi run the
mile-per-hour record, because I was getting tired of trying to
explain why I did it,'' said Force, driver of the Castrol GTX Ford
Mustang. ``We all know the Top Fuel dragsters are the kings of the
sport. But I'm going after the speed record next year with my new
car. As much as I love Gary Scelzi and the \RAlan\S Johnson family,
they've given me something to shoot for. I just don't chase the
Funny Car guys, I chase the dragster guys. It's the chase.'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   Capps stands to finish No. 2 in points to Force despite winning
more national events. Capps has bagged five races to Force's three.
Capps, who is wrapping up his second season for car owner and
mentor Don ``The Snake'' Prudhomme, hardly is complaining. ``I'm
still pinching myself that I'm driving for Snake,'' said Capps,
driver of the Copenhagen Chevrolet Camaro Z/28. ``Sometimes I sit
back and think, `Wow, is my life great.' It really is. At the same
time, I'm never satisfied. One thing I've learned from Snake is if
you relax out here and fall back on your heels for one tiny second,
you're going to get passed.'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   Scelzi is the ninth driver to win six NHRA Top Fuel races in a
single season. No one has won seven, but Scelzi and runner-up Cory
McClenathan are in position to do so during the Winston Finals. In
addition to Scelzi and McClenathan (1997, 1998), the others to have
won six races in a season are Don Garlits (1985), Darrell Gwynn
(1988), Gary Ormsby (1989, 1990), Joe Amato (1990), Kenny Bernstein
(1991), Eddie Hill of Wichita Falls (1993) and Scott Kalitta
(1995).
FAST LAPS
Little E's coronation
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt Jr. will add mightily to his family's racing
legacy Sunday, when he officially becomes NASCAR's first
third-generation champion.
</P>
<P>
   Little E, son of seven-time Winston Cup champion Dale Earnhardt
and grandson of former NASCAR Sportsman champion Ralph Earnhardt,
only needs to start the Jiffy Lube Miami 300 at Homestead, Fla., to
secure his first Busch Grand National Series crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying not to think about the championship until
Homestead,'' said Earnhardt Jr., 24, who scored his first BGN
victory in the Coca-Cola 300 at Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth
in April. ``I raced this year with Matt Kenseth and he's a pretty
good buddy. I hate to beat him out of the championship. I hope
we're still friends. That's the only thing I'm worried about.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt Jr., driver of the No. 3 ACDelco Chevrolet Monte
Carlo, will weigh those feelings against the emotions of clinching
the title before his famous father and car owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it will sink in,'' Earnhardt Jr. said, ``once I look
in my daddy's eyes.'' Nuts and bolts
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolet captured the 1998 NASCAR Winston Cup Manufacturers'
Championship by five points over Ford. But Taurus drivers compiled
100 top-five finishes of a possible 165 (61 percent), compared to
50 for Team Monte Carlo (30 percent) and 15 for the Pontiac Grand
Prix (9 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Cup regular Mike Skinner plans to race a dozen Busch Grand
National events in 1999. Skinner will drive Chevrolets sponsored by
Yellow Freight Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has selected Dan Stuczynski, a 15-year veteran engineer
with Ford Special Vehicle Operations (SVO), as program manager for
the BGN series.
</P>
<P>
   CART FedEx Championship Series runner-up Jimmy Vasser finished
1998 with 169 points, 15 more than he scored during his title
season of 1996. Last words ``''All we can do is take our hat off to
John Force. He's a warrior. Get him in a corner and tell him he's
too old or fat, he comes out swinging.'''' _ Ron Capps, on chasing
the reigning NHRA Funny Car champion.
</P>
