<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL'S MOVE BODES WELL FOR TECHNOLOGY
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Intel Corp.'s announcement that its fourth-quarter
results would exceed Wall Street estimates not only bolstered its
stock to a new high on Wednesday, but analysts said it boded well
for a broad range of technology stocks, particularly those whose
fortunes are tied to the personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   Intel said on Tuesday that stronger-than-expected demand for
personal computer products across all market segments and
geographical regions would raise fourth-quarter revenue by 8
percent to 10 percent, compared with third-quarter revenue of $6.7
billion. The company also said that profit margins would be up a
couple of points from 53 percent in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Intel shot up Wednesday on the report, gaining $6.125
each, to $103.6875.
</P>
<P>
   And Intel's news was buttressed on Wednesday by a bullish
forecast from the Semiconductor Industry Association, which
predicted that the global chip market would rebound next year. The
association said strong demand for microprocessors, memory and
digital signal processors would increase sales by 9.1 percent, to
$133.4 billion, and that sales would rise an additional 15.2
percent in 2000 and 18.2 percent in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts scrambled to raise estimates on Wednesday, taking the
consensus to $1.05 a share for the fourth quarter from 95 cents a
share, and to $3.41 a share for the full year for $3.31 a share,
according to the First Call Corp., which tracks company earnings.
Analysts raised their estimate for Intel's 1999 earnings to $4.16 a
share from $3.92 a share.
</P>
<P>
   But Intel pre-announced strong earnings in the third quarter
only to exceed even the revised estimates, and many analysts expect
the company to do the same this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intel historically has not pre-announced very often, and when
they do they are very careful,'' said Mark Edelstone, an analyst
with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``The company had a break-out
quarter in Q3, and and I expect more of the same in Q4.'' Edelstone
continues to rate Intel a strong buy.
</P>
<P>
   Intel has long been a leadership company: It invented the
microprocessor and the dynamic random access memory chip, or DRAM,
without either of which the personal computer would not exist.
Analysts say it is now also a leadership stock, one whose
performance serves as a bellwether for the whole technology group,
much the way IBM once did. If demand for Intel microprocessors is
growing, so too should demand for memory, disk drives and other
personal computer components.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Murphy, editor of the California Technology Stock
Letter, has been predicting for some time that Intel's stock price
could reach $120 by the end of the year. He said
stronger-than-expected fourth-quarter earnings for Intel pointed to
a broad-based technology rally. ``It's the right sign for the
technology sector because what it's saying is there is still
genuine double-digit growth in PC's,'' he said. That growth was
hidden by the inventory glut that hung over the sector for the
first two quarters, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Intel's good news, Tom Kurlak of Merrill Lynch retained
his neutral rating on the stock, as did eight of the 32 analysts
polled by First Call. One raised a neutral to a strong buy, one a
neutral to a buy. That left the stock rated a buy by 9 analysts and
a strong buy by 14.
</P>
<P>
   Those not recommending Intel point to concerns about increased
competition at the low end the market, where Advanced Micro Devices
Inc. has been coming on strong, and less need for ever greater
processing power at the high end, which in the age of the Internet
is more driven by band width than by microprocessor power. Some
analysts say the surge in demand now is mostly inventory
replenishing, a temporary phenomenon created by efforts to clear
the previous glut.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that was almost set up to happen and now it is
occurring,'' said John Rossi, an analyst with BancBoston Robertson
Stephens. ``We should enjoy things as they are now, but realize it
will also go through the usual seasonal cooling off in mid- to late
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Longer term, however, Rossi said he expected traditional
blue-chip companies to suffer more from the Asian economic crisis
and to spend more on technology to improve productivity and cope
with the Year 2000 problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at it as a great place to put money for 1999,'' he
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
