<SLUG> BC-DEM-CONVENTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON SEEN IN FINAL 3 FOR CONVENTION  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Boston is expected to be selected as one of two or
three finalists to host the prized Democratic National Convention
in 2000, although Los Angeles is highly favored to win the
lucrative contest, several Democratic Party sources say.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Boston's strong showing, party officials are likely to
use the city as a bargaining chip as they press Los Angeles leaders
to enhance their package of financial incentives to host the 2000
convention, according to party sources.
</P>
<P>
   The sources said Wednesday that Boston could still win the
competition if Los Angeles fails to significantly improve its
current bid of $35.3 million in cash and services to stage the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston has done a very impressive job,'' said a Democratic
Party source who is close to the selection process. ``But if Boston
wins, it will be by default.''
</P>
<P>
   With the party's site advisory committee scheduled to select the
finalists Thursday in Washington, Denver is the only other city
with a solid chance of entering the last round of the nearly
year-long competition.
</P>
<P>
   The other contenders _ Miami, Minneapolis, and New Orleans _ are
not expected to make the cut.
</P>
<P>
   The winner will be selected by President Clinton, Vice President
Al Gore, and party officials and is expected to be announced in
January.
</P>
<P>
   The city that hosts the 2000 convention will receive an
estimated $140 million boost to the local economy, in addition to
prestige and a place in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston has been a major player since Day 1, and we expect them
to be a major player until the end of the process,'' said a party
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Thomas M. Menino has led an intensive campaign to persuade
party leaders to choose Boston as the site. The city, which has
never hosted a major party convention, has pledged $32 million in
financial incentives, which is considered more generous than the
Los Angeles bid because of the extra travel and production costs
associated with staging the four-day spectacle on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   But sources said that Clinton, Gore, and party leaders favor
California for several political reasons, most importantly the
necessity of the presidential candidate in 2000 capturing the
state's 54 electoral votes. By contrast, the New England states
account for only 35 electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   Although Los Angeles could be uncomfortable for Gore because of
his controversial appearance there at a fund-raiser in a Buddhist
temple that has been the focus of federal investigations, Clinton
is expected to push for Los Angeles behind the scenes. The 2000
convention is likely to provide the backdrop for Clinton's last
major speech to party loyalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a strong sense that he wants it there,'' said a source
who is familiar with the process. ``And he is going to have a big
say in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Denver has offered nearly $34 million in financial incentives to
host the convention and is considered a strong contender, mostly
out of deference to Colorado Governor Roy Romer, the party's
general chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic national chairman is Steven Grossman, a
Massachusetts businessman who has been instrumental in leading the
party out of massive debt after the 1996 elections. But party
officials said that Boston has edged out nearly every other city in
the convention contest mainly because of Menino's lobbying, the
financial bid, and the city's success at showcasing itself when the
advisory committee was treated to a whirlwind visit last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Boston was among 28 cities the party invited last year to
compete for the 2000 convention. The field was gradually cut to
seven semi-finalists, although Philadelphia dropped out of the
running last week when it was selected to host the Republican
national convention in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia had been considered a leading contender for the
Democratic event, which is expected to attract as many as 30,000
delegates, journalists, and other visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles always saw Philadelphia as the obstacle to LA
getting the convention,'' said Bill Carrick, a Democratic
strategist based in Los Angeles. ``The overwhelming sense here now
is that LA is in the driver's seat. The other sentiment is that
Boston is the only other player.''
</P>
<P>
   Party officials said the 51-member site advisory committee will
discuss a slate of finalists that will be recommended Thursday by
the panel's leaders, including the chairman, Joe Andrew of Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   The committee will then vote on the recommendations, as
representatives from the semifinalist cities, including Boston,
look on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
