<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6114 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-COMMITTEE-NYT     11-11 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-COMMITTEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS PRESSURE HYDE FOR QUICK VOTE ON IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Mich., Va., Pa., Mo., La.)  (Eds: See also REPUBS-DILEMMA) 
(mk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seeking to capitalize on the public's distaste with
the inquiry against President Clinton, Democrats on the House
Judiciary Committee called on the panel Wednesday to vote early
next week on whether the allegations in the independent counsel's
report are grounds for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats knew how Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the committee
chairman, would reply _ (``No'') _ even before they delivered the
request to him Wednesday night. But they didn't particularly care.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by their unexpected Election Day gains and the growing
number of Republicans outside the committee who now say the full
House is unlikely to vote to impeach Clinton, committee Democrats
are trying every tactic to force Hyde to fold his tent.
</P>
<P>
   In the Democrats' letter, Rep. John Conyers of Michigan, the
committee's ranking Democrat, and Rep. Robert Scott of Virginia,
the lead Democrat on the constitutional subcommittee, asked Hyde to
``help us avoid a divisive inquiry that is not warranted by the
Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee has called the independent counsel, Kenneth Starr,
to testify on Nov. 19. But Democrats insist that before summoning
witnesses, the committee should decide whether the main charges in
Starr's 445-page report _ lying under oath, obstructing justice and
witness tampering _ constitute impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Republicans had not yet received the Democrats' letter
Wednesday night, but the arguments are familiar ones and
unpersuasive to Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact-gathering process comes first and the committee will
get to the question of whether or not the allegations against the
president warrant impeachment at a subsequent point,'' a Republican
committee spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   On another front, the House Democratic leader, Rep. Dick
Gephardt, D-Mo., criticized the Republicans' handling of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought for some time that a majority of Republicans were
bent on not only considering impeachment actively but bringing many
other issues into this, in a process that I think is defective and
not well thought through,'' Gephardt told reporters over lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said that after hearings and a committee vote on
articles of impeachment, ``We're then, I guess, going to go to the
floor with an impeachment resolution. The House is not terribly
prepared to deal with it because it's been done in my view very
poorly.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Democrats' criticisms, there was fresh evidence
Wednesday of waning support for impeachment among Republicans
outside Hyde's committee.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., of the Judiciary Committee, suggested
in an article on the Op-Ed page of The New York Times and again at
a news conference that the impeachment inquiry be abandoned in
favor of criminal prosecution of Clinton after he leaves office in
2001.
</P>
<P>
   Specter said that lawmakers were ``searching for a way out'' of
an impeachment process that was ``going nowhere.'' The senator said
he had broached the idea to Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the majority
leader, and Rep. Robert Livingston, R-La., the likely successor to
Newt Gingrich as speaker of the House. Both men were noncommittal,
Specter said.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, speaking in Wheaton, Ill., said the hearing with Starr
will go ahead, as would other committee deliberations. ``Sen.
Specter's always ahead of the curve,'' Hyde said. ``But he'll get
his chance to express himself authoritatively, ultimately, I
suspect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
