A6115 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-POLLIN-NYT &LR;      11-11 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-POLLIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA'S SENIOR OWNER SPEAKS OUT, AND BLUNTLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Abe Pollin bought the Washington Wizards 34 years ago, when they
were called the Baltimore Bullets and the National Basketball
Association consisted of nine teams and was was more than a decade
from becoming a global marketing phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it is a 29-team league and Pollin not only owns the Wizards
and the Washington Capitals hockey team, but also the $200 million
MCI Center in downtown Washington.
</P>
<P>
   At 74, he is the senior owner in the NBA, one of three left who
have worked with Walter Kennedy and Lawrence O'Brien, David Stern's
predecessors as commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry and I hired David Stern,'' he said during a telephone
interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Stern's leadership in the lockout, which has prevented the
start of the season, has kept Pollin's Wizards idle, while Pollin's
Capitals continue playing on his MCI Center ice.
</P>
<P>
   During the lockout, now more than four months old, owners have
hardly been heard from as Stern has forged a management unit by
cautioning them not to talk about the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   In discussing the lockout, Pollin did not provide sensitive
details and did not break with Stern. But he provided an unusually
candid view of the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is generally optimistic about a deal being reached,
Pollin said the owners must get a fair deal. Or, he said: ``We're
prepared to gut the season. We went into this knowing that if we
can't make a fair deal, the season would be gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, Pollin doubted that the NBA would require a long
period of recovery if it shutters the entire season. Major League
Baseball needed until this past season to heal the wounds from the
1994-95 players strike that scotched the 1994 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the NBA will recover quicker,'' he said. ``There's no
question the league will survive. It's not something you look
forward to, but I'm sure we have some good ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollin praised Stern's leadership, but said he is not an
omnipotent commissioner towing the owners behind him. ``He doesn't
do this by himself,'' Pollin said. ``But we agree completely. There
is 100 percent unity. There is no split.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollin said the economic model that helped the NBA flourish
financially for the past 15 years is no longer fair _ to owners.
``It doesn't work,'' he said. ``We need one that works. When you
have a system where most of the teams aren't getting any type of
return on the value of their investments, and for many it's
negative, the system doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the Wizards' finances, he said, ``I'm not getting
anywhere near a fair return.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said the lack of revenues from Wizards games will not
hurt his ability to pay the debt service on the arena. ``I've never
missed a payment and I never will,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   NBC and Turner Sports will make their full $16 million-a-team
payments this season, cushioning teams' loss of revenue from ticket
sales and concessions. Pollin's bottom line is also comforted by
revenues from Capitals games and other events.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Pollin is peeved by the suggestion that if the
return on his Wizards investment is so small, well, maybe he should
sell the team _ a recommendation made by Michael Jordan during a
negotiating session last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to let Michael Jordan or anybody else tell me to
sell my team,'' he said, anger cutting his genial tone. ``Nobody is
going to tell me I have to sell my team.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollin has maintained his affection for his basketball team
despite years of disappointment since Washington's 1978
championship. He was prompted to propose changing the team's name
in 1995, from the Bullets to the Wizards, after his friend Yitzhak
Rabin, the Israeli prime minister, was assassinated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this sport and I love this team,'' said Pollin, a
widely respected owner who is deeply involved in Washington-area
charities. ``This team and this league have been a big part of my
life. I love the players individually. I get to know the players'
wives. They come to my home. I've taken them to China and Israel.
This team is a very important part of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollin has been involved in nearly every major issue in the NBA,
and served on nearly every major committee. ``You enjoy having
someone like Abe, with his experience, with his league mentality,
who's also very charitable and has a great sense of humor,'' Stern
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pollin is still yearning for a second NBA championship to add to
the team's 1978 title. ``I just hope we get better,'' he said. ``I
think we will.''
</P>
<P>
   But first he wants to change the system. The owners want to
limit players' salaries to 50 percent of league revenue, not the 60
percent players have proposed, and below the 57.1 percent players
made last season. Owners also want to limit rookie salaries and
alter the so-called Larry Bird exception that lets teams exceed the
salary cap when they re-sign their own free agents.
</P>
<P>
   The system, he said, has resulted in ticket prices rising far
beyond the capability of families to attend games without financial
hardship. ``That disturbs me,'' he said. ``My greatest pleasure is
to see families and children come to my building to see an NBA game
in a clean environment. So the escalating salaries have to be
addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollin retains an optimism that an agreement can be reached,
``but I can't say when _ it's up to the players.'' Unfortunately,
he said, players don't seem to trust the owners' proposals or
claims about team finances, among them that 15 teams are losing
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not putting blame on owners or the players for the way
things are,'' he said. ``We signed a deal in 1995 that doesn't
work, so we have to change it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
