<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-GOV-EXPENDITURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUBERNATORIAL RACE EXPENSES HIGHEST EVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In his grueling campaign to win a full four-year term,
Governor Paul Cellucci spent $6.9 million, a record for a
Massachusetts gubernatorial race, finance records show.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the 1998 Massachusetts gubernatorial contest _ in which
candidates spent over $18 million _ was the most expensive campaign
for a state office ever waged, breaking the $14.8 million mark set
in 1990 when five candidates ran for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic nominee Scott Harshbarger spent more than $5.5
million and state Treasurer Joseph D. Malone used more than $3.3
million to challenge Cellucci in the GOP primary. Two other
candidates, Democrats Patricia McGovern and Brian Donnelly, spent a
combined $2.8 million in their primary races.
</P>
<P>
   Those figures _ compiled by the Office of Campaign and Political
Finance _ are based on reports covering the period up to Oct. 31,
the last filing deadline. With a host of bills still outstanding
for each candidate, the final expenditure figures will increase
even further. The figures include spending in the year previous to
the election.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci spent far more than any other single candidate in a
Massachusetts governor's race. For example in 1990, John Silber,
the losing Democratic nominee, spent $3.8 million, while William F.
Weld spent $3.4 million to win.
</P>
<P>
   Weld spent $4 million in his re-election bid four years later,
four times what his Democratic opponent, Mark Roosevelt, spent.
Harshbarger's spending includes the nearly $945,000 he received in
public funding.
</P>
<P>
   The spending figures for this year's gubernatorial race surpass
the $16 million spent in the 1996 US Senate race when Weld tried
unsuccessfully to unseat Senator John F. Kerry. But the record for
one race still rests with the $19 million Senator Edward M. Kennedy
and GOP rival Mitt Romney spent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the reason we need the Clean Election Law,'' said Jim
Paisner, chairman of Common Cause of Massachusetts, when told of
the money spent for this year's governor's race. Common Cause is a
public interest group that focuses on campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Paisner noted that, while the candidates broke spending records,
voters last week overwhelmingly approved a sweeping campaign
finance plan _ the Clean Election Law _ which provides 85 percent
in public financing to candidates who agree to overall spending
limits and to accept no invidual contributions of more than $100.
</P>
<P>
   The law, which is expected to be challenged on constitutional
grounds, would completely change the way state-wide campaigns are
run. It has already created confusion among current office holders
and political aides, who are trying to understand its details and
its far reaching implications.
</P>
<P>
   But Paisner claimed a significant benefit of the statute is that
it will allow candidates to spend less time fund-raising and more
time campaigning. ``Once politicians are weaned from this current
system, there will be much more time for them to spend delivering
the politcal message they need to deliver to their constituents,''
Paisner said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the gubernatorial race, Massachusetts voters may
have also seen the most ever spent by one committee on a ballot
question. The electric industry, through its committee, Yes on 4,
spent $7.8 million as of Oct. 31 in its effort kill the proposed
rollback of the electric industry deregulation law.
</P>
<P>
   The industry expenditures dwarf the $285,000 that proponents,
who argued the law gave most of the savings to utilities and not
consumers, said they spent as of the Oct. 31 filings.
</P>
<P>
   The spending on this year's Question 4 could challenge the
record set in 1988 when the nuclear industry and its opponents
spent $9.1 million on a ballot initiative over whether to ban
plants that produce nuclear waste. It was defeated. The cigarette
industry spent more than $7 million in 1992 in its failed bid to
defeat a cigarette-tax proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The gubernatorial expenditure reports do not include the ``soft
money'' funds that were spent by third parties, such as the two
major state parties and labor unions, on behalf of either candidate
in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Cellucci aides estimated that the state Republican
Party spent about $500,000 on Cellucci's behalf, mostly for
advertising, phones, and mail. Harshbarger was aided by a
television ad by the Massachusetts Teachers Association. The
AFL-CIO also spent large amounts for mailings, phone banks, and
leaflet drops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
