<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6118 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRTRAN12-COX     11-11 1456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRTRAN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AirTran not out of the clouds
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. -- AirTran Airways offers low fares and service
basically indistinguishable from that of a big carrier. It has a
zippy ad campaign and a generous frequent flier program.
</P>
<P>
   What it doesn't have are enough passengers or profits.
</P>
<P>
   The Orlando-based discounter, Atlanta's second-biggest carrier,
was among the few U.S. airlines of any size that lost money in the
summer quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The surprising third-quarter loss, which came amid ideal
conditions of high travel demand and low fuel prices, dashed
earlier indications that AirTran was on the verge of consistent
profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Now the question is not just when, but if, the airline will ever
achieve that goal.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Executive D. Joseph Corr calls the loss a temporary
setback caused by unusual costs and the government's refusal to
police unfair price competition by big carriers.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview this week, he said fourth-quarter results will
be close to break-even, owing to declining costs and fall route
changes that shift AirTran's focus even more heavily to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Corr said efforts to attract business fliers are slowly boosting
both ridership and per-passenger revenue, and he added the airline
still plans to begin acquiring new Boeing 717s next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we do seems to work ... the rebranding, going after
weekday travelers. It's all working. All we really are is short a
couple of load factor points,'' said Corr, referring to the
percentage of seats sold.
</P>
<P>
   Hired to guide recovery
</P>
<P>
   Corr was hired in 1996 to take over ValuJet Airlines' effort to
recover from the shutdown that followed the Flight 592 crash that
year. One year ago he led ValuJet into a name-changing merger with
AirTran, coupled with a service and marketing overhaul that
included the addition of business-class sections and other changes.
Company headquarters were moved from Atlanta to Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``We run a very competitive product, have nice clean airplanes
and good on-time and reliability rates,'' Corr said. ``If we can
continue to build loads at the rate we have, I see no reason we
can't be profitable long-term.''
</P>
<P>
   The airline filled 56.7 percent of its seats in October, up from
a year earlier but still well below load factors posted by larger
airlines. Atlanta-based Delta, AirTran's biggest competitor, filled
71 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who follow AirTran and its low-flying stock, which
hovers around $3 a share, aren't encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conditions have been so good for the last few months,'' said
Ed Starkman of Warburg Dillon Read. ``Even as the second guy in
Atlanta sweeping up the crumbs from Delta, you should be able to do
very well. The fact they didn't is worrisome.''
</P>
<P>
   James Parker of Robinson-Humphrey expects another loss in the
fourth quarter and says the outlook for 1999 ``is very uncertain.''
</P>
<P>
   AirTran logged its first post-merger profit in the spring
quarter. Corr predicted then that it would be ``solidly
profitable'' for the full year.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than gain momentum in the summer, AirTran posted a
$10.9 million loss for the July-September quarter, laid off workers
and made plans to return two of its 50 jets to lessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I was overly optimistic,'' Corr said. ``If you do what I
do you just get mad and work harder.''
</P>
<P>
   As the poor summer results emerged, Corr moved to ditch the
remnants of the original AirTran's Orlando-based route system and
add flights to the old ValuJet network out of Atlanta. Those
changes were completed this month, giving AirTran 130 daily
departures to 29 cities from Hartsfield International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Corr said yields _ the amount of money generated by each
passenger _ are 40 percent higher on Atlanta routes because of the
business travel market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're back on track now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive attributes the summer results to three
factors. AirTran spent $3 million preparing for a threatened flight
attendant strike and suffered a rash of engine problems that
required extra maintenance. That helped boost unit costs to 8.6
cents per seat-mile, almost as high as Delta's.
</P>
<P>
   The Delta factor
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, AirTran contends it lost passengers to an escalation
of predatory price-matching by Delta. The Department of
Transportation had proposed new guidelines to define and police
predatory pricing, but the rules were delayed after a lobbying
campaign by big carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They folded their tent and went home,'' Corr said of the DOT,
although he added he is hopeful the agency will yet act. He said
AirTran has presented specific allegations to the DOT, but he won't
discuss details.
</P>
<P>
   Delta officials hotly deny any wrongdoing and say the DOT
guidelines will do more harm than good. They say offering varying
numbers of seats at the same fares as AirTran is clean competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their accusations are baseless,'' said Mark Drusch, a Delta
senior vice president who heads pricing. ``We've been vigorous but
aboveboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Drusch said Delta has laid out its actions to the DOT, which
lodged no objections. He suggested AirTran ``should be censured''
for its public accusations, made prominently in news releases. ``I
really think you've got an airline looking for an easy way out from
its own problems,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are split about the merits of AirTran's complaints, but
they agree it faces broader problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bigger problem for them is that Delta is able to compete
much more effectively than they did when ValuJet started up,''
Parker said. ``The (1996 crash) changed the competitive situation
immensely by prodding people to make the first call to the
brand-name airline. That's still a factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Pulling out right stops
</P>
<P>
   Delta also has refined its ability to offer significant numbers
of matching fares without diluting profits, Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   Those factors raise the elemental question of whether AirTran
can compete long-term in Delta's shadow at Hartsfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are those who say we shouldn't operate out of
Atlanta, but I don't know what numbers they see because the ones I
see say we should,'' said Corr. ``It's just too big a market.
Delta's vulnerable to a well-run alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   Corr and other AirTran executives say fares would soar on many
routes if their carrier left the market.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff MacKinney, senior vice president for marketing and
planning, said numerous small and medium-size companies have voiced
that concern and cut volume-based travel deals with AirTran since
it installed business class.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have the size to have much leverage with Delta, and
they see in us a very attractive alternative. Atlanta's full of
those companies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   MacKinney says AirTran's marketing and route strategy won't
change much in the next few months. The next big move will come
next summer when new 717s begin arriving to replace the carrier's
aging DC-9s and 737s.
</P>
<P>
   New image planned
</P>
<P>
   Corr said AirTran will be able to lease the planes despite its
lack of profits, though it may pay higher financing rates. He said
the 717s will be cheaper to fly and maintain and will help AirTran
build a fresh image.
</P>
<P>
   He conceded the stigma of the ValuJet crash remains an obstacle
and will for sometime. ``The world treats us differently,'' he
said. ``It's just something we have to strive to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   AirTran appears to have an unremarkable safety record,
notwithstanding the recent accident in which one of its jets ran
off a Hartsfield runway after an emergency landing prompted by
hydraulic problems. Prior to that, AirTran/ValuJet's only accident
since late 1996 came last spring, when a jet flew through hail over
North Georgia and made a forced landing.
</P>
<P>
   (During the same time frame Delta had 24 safety incidents,
ranging from very minor to serious, according to the National
Transportation Safety Board database on the Internet.)
</P>
<P>
   Corr, who previously held top jobs at Continental and TWA and
casts himself as a turnaround specialist, has a year left on his
contract. He answers to a board of directors that includes ValuJet
co-founders Robert Priddy and Lewis Jordan, who remain major
stockholders.
</P>
<P>
   When AirTran posted the third-quarter loss, the trade journal
Aviation Daily reported Corr's job was in jeopardy. The airline
denied any shake-up was considered. Corr says he still has full
control and wouldn't stay on if he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said I wasn't here for the long run,'' he said.
``Had this business been going great by now I would be leaving.
It's a matter of finishing the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 2057EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0429 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6119 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKSTUDY12-COX     11-11 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKSTUDY12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Black manufactures may hold tools to boost poor Atlanta areas
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ William Peel doesn't think of himself as a central
player in economic development. Rather, he calls himself a
``real-life, old-line toolmaker from Detroit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta businessman custom-builds tools and machines that
make everything from salt and pepper shakers found in fast-food
restaurants to parts for high-speed trains. As owner of Peel's
Technical Services on West Marietta Street in downtown Atlanta, he
employs three people, all of them black.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of work but not a lot of toolmakers'' or other
skilled workers, says Peel, who moved here in 1971 because he saw
Atlanta ``as fertile opportunity for small, flexible
manufacturing.''
</P>
<P>
   A new study on black Atlanta released today suggests that Peel
and other black manufacturers may be the key to jump-starting
Atlanta's poor neighborhoods. Manufacturing firms have the highest
profits of any small businesses and pay an average yearly wage of
$30,642 in the Atlanta region, according to the report by Clark
Atlanta University's Southern Center for Studies in Public Policy.
The Status of Black Atlanta report examined 120 black manufacturers
that employ 2,811 people in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manufacturing was one of the more viable sectors to develop,''
said Goro Mitchell, a Southern Center researcher and one of the
study's authors. It also is the most logical industry to help
scores of blacks isolated from job opportunities in the suburbs,
Mitchell added. The 125-page report, patterned after the National
Urban League's yearly State of Black America, also looks at
politics, housing and women's issues. Clark has done the annual
study since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Revving up manufacturing in the black community is one of many
recommendations in a report that essentially says progress for
blacks in Atlanta has inched along since the 1996 Olympic torch was
extinguished.
</P>
<P>
   Despite public-private efforts to lure more middle-class
families back to the city and an infusion of $100 million in
federal money into so-called empowerment zones, little has changed
for many black Atlantans, the report concludes.
</P>
<P>
   The report draws heavily on U.S. Department of Commerce data on
black businesses, much of which is at least 5 years old. But
Southern Center director B-- b Holmes said data from more recent
sampling indicates conditions for black Atlantans haven't changed
considerably this decade despite the metro area's healthy economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state of black Atlanta is not very good,'' said Holmes,
another of the study's authors. ``The trend, if one goes back 15
years or more, shows that progress has been slow and incremental.
But there has also been ... an increase in the disparities between
blacks and whites in Atlanta in housing, manufacturing, income and
unemployment.''
</P>
<P>
   The study looks only at the city of Atlanta, and the authors say
that's because many of the city's blacks haven't shared in the
economic growth of the region. ``Unfortunately, the rapid economic
growth which has characterized metropolitan Atlanta during the last
two decades has not occurred at the same rate inside the city
limits,'' Holmes added.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the wage gap: Many middle-class blacks have moved
to the suburbs, leaving the city with a large number of blacks who
work in low-paying jobs in the fast-food, hotel and retail
industries, said Holmes, a political science professor at Clark
Atlanta. At the same time, many of the small businesses in Atlanta
have few financing options to grow, thus further blocking economic
growth in some of Atlanta's toughest areas.
</P>
<P>
   The study cites one encouraging trend: the new wave of black
entrepreneurs who are more highly educated. Eighty-three percent of
black business owners in Atlanta and Fulton County have some
college, 62 percent have bachelor's degrees and 22.2 percent hold
graduate degrees, the study noted.
</P>
<P>
   If the city is to flourish in the future, the study suggests
bolstering black manufacturers through training programs for
workers and managers, loosening the grip on bank loans and other
financing for blacks and helping black manufacturers become more
technologically savvy. The study said more black-owned
manufacturing firms need to be in the empowerment zone.
</P>
<P>
   While black manufacturers tend to be in predominantly black
neighborhoods and employ more blacks than their white counterparts,
they face their own set of challenges. They tend to be younger and
smaller and generate lower sales than the white firms, and they
have a harder time getting capital, which is essential to a
company's ability to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Machine shop owner Peel doesn't see himself as an economic
catalyst but he agrees black manufacturers and entrepreneurs in the
city need encouragement. ``There's a lot of work out there, ``
Peel, 55, said. ``But to get that work to the inner city where the
majority of jobs are needed and then have the kinds of jobs people
can do _ everything can't be computerized _ takes a plan, not a
wish. It's a long-term plan and anything less than five years in
duration isn't going to work.'' He said small-business owners need
a steady flow of contracts and more apprenticeships for workers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
