A6120 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INSURE-GA12-COX     11-11 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURE-GA12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Robust economy failsto ensure insurance
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The percentage of Georgians under age 65 without
health insurance stayed virtually the same in 1997 as the previous
year, despite a robust economy.
</P>
<P>
   A Georgia State University study found 19 percent of Georgians
under 65, or about 1.3 million residents, lacked coverage in 1997,
the latest year such statistics are available. That's a slight drop
from 20 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past four years of strong economic growth, the Georgia
uninsured figure has ranged from 18 percent to 20 percent, Bill
Custer, a Georgia State economist, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we go into recession, the percentage of uninsured would go
up dramatically,'' Custer warned, citing a similar rise during the
early 1990s economic slump.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, more than 43 million Americans, or 18 percent of the
non-elderly, lacked health coverage last year, up from 41.4 million
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance figures are tabulated from a Census Bureau survey
conducted in March. Almost all Americans 65 and older are covered
by the federal Medicare program.
</P>
<P>
   Hawaii and Wisconsin had the lowest rates of uninsured, at 9
percent, while Arkansas and Arizona had the highest, at 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the uninsured tend to be younger, male, at lower income
levels and working in smaller firms.
</P>
<P>
   Two of three uninsured Georgians live in families where there's
a full-time worker. Many employers, though, don't offer coverage to
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the principal reason for the rise of uninsured Americans
over the past 15 years is the increase of health-care costs as a
proportion of family income, Custer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens as health care costs go up is that more people
take the risk that they don't need health insurance _ or that they
can fund whatever care they need out of savings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But those without health insurance tend to postpone needed care,
which leads to higher medical costs later. And when health-care
bills aren't paid, those costs are borne by taxpayers, the
privately insured, doctors and hospitals, Custer noted.
</P>
<P>
   One positive development in health insurance is the
federal-state initiative to extend coverage to uninsured children.
In Georgia, the PeachCare for Kids program, which will debut
statewide in January, aims to cover more than 100,000 of the
380,000 children in the state who have no insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could make a significant dent'' in the uninsured figure,
Custer said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
