<SLUG> BC-SUPERSHOW12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Super Show a no-show for 2002
 &HT;    By Maria Saporta
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Goodbye, Super Show _ at least for 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's largest and glitziest convention won't return to the
city in 2002 and probably won't come here in 2001, according to Dan
Graveline, executive director of the Georgia World Congress Center.
He called the loss ``devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   The Super Show, which brings more than 100,000 delegates to
Atlanta for its January convention and has an economic impact of
$70 million, will likely go to Orlando in 2001 and 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Super Show couldn't be reached, but Bill
Peeper, president of the Orlando/Orange County Convention &AMP;
Visitors Bureau, said he was ``really optimistic'' the show will go
to the Florida city.
</P>
<P>
   Graveline said the Super Show will return to Atlanta in 1999 and
2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Show, the convention of the Florida-based Sporting
Goods Manufacturers Association, has convened in Atlanta since its
inception in 1986. In recent years, it has outgrown space in both
the GWCC and adjacent Georgia Dome. Last year, it used 400,000
square feet in pavilions in the Dome parking lot in addition to one
million square feet in the Dome and GWCC.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it's the GWCC's hope to expand that forced the Super
Show to look elsewhere. If the proposed $225 million,
450,000-square-foot expansion of the GWCC is approved by the
Legislature, it would be built on the Dome's northern parking lot,
thus making that space unavailable for exhibits for several years
during construction.
</P>
<P>
   However, without the expansion, Graveline said the city is
certain to lose the convention permanently.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the expansion is not approved in the next session, we stand
virtually no chance of getting the Super Show back,'' said
Graveline. ``We simply can't accommodate them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orlando convention center plans to double its 1.1 million
square feet of space. Atlanta convention officials fear that even
with an expansion here, they could have a hard time winning the
show back.
</P>
<P>
   Gov.-elect Roy Barnes already has heard the pitch for the
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm dedicated to the idea that we have got to build the next
phase (of the GWCC),'' Barnes said. ``But, first I want to get a
comfortable feel for the growth revenue of the state. We have got
some (financially) unstable times internationally.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
