<SLUG> BC-MEDPARTNERS-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDPARTNERS PLANS TO DIVEST ITSELF OF BUSINESS OF PHYSICIAN
PRACTICE MANAGEMENT
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By MILT FREDUENHEIM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the latest admission of failure in the business of physician
practice management, Medpartners Inc. announced on Wednesday that
it was leaving the field.
</P>
<P>
   Medpartners, which is based in Birmingham, Ala., plans to
concentrate on more profitable units that provide managed care drug
benefits for health plans and coordinate treatments for such
medical conditions as hemophilia and growth hormone deficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Medpartners has been the largest publicly traded company that
specializes in buying and operating physicians' practices. It tried
to squeeze savings and profits by centralizing information and
billing systems, marketing to health plans and generally promoting
efficient operations.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors involved often sold their practices to Medpartners
for stock that later plunged as earnings growth stalled. On
Wednesday, some doctors complained that the executives in
Birmingham did not understand their needs.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin Crawford, a turnaround specialist who became chief
executive of Medpartners in March, questioned whether publicly
traded physician practice management companies were viable.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he said, ``It's a question whether the physician
business fits well in a public company setting.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Medpartners would try to sell the medical groups
to hospitals, venture capitalists and back to the doctors
themselves. The company, which plans to complete the divestiture
within 12 months, said it might also spin the physician practice
unit off to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physicians are just plain bad employees,'' said Kenneth
Abramowitz, a health care analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein. ``It's
not a lot of fun managing 3,000 prima donnas who don't think it's
the best thing to work for you.''
</P>
<P>
   The departure of Medpartners, the largest company in physician
practice management, would leave the field to Phycor Inc., which
said last month that it was considering offers to take it private
in view of its low stock valuation. FPA Medical Management, another
big manager of physician practices, filed in July for protection
under Chapter 11 of the bankruptcy laws.
</P>
<P>
   Medpartners shares dropped 25 cents, to $4.125, Wednesday on the
New York Stock Exchange in relatively heavy trading of 5.2 million
shares. The price plunged to $1.625 on Sept. 10, from a 52-week
high of $26.625 a year ago. Phycor rose 31.25 cents on Wednesday,
to $7.5625, on Nasdaq.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Dr. Kenneth Brin, board chairman of the 85-physician Summit
Medical Group in Summit, N.J., said Medpartners did not inform
member groups like Summit of its plans until after the stock
markets closed on Tuesday. The Wall Street Journal reported the
plan on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Brin said the divestiture was ``the best resolution for all
concerned for an industry that is clearly going through the pains
of growth, trying to redefine itself in a marketplace that is
changing extremely rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressure from managed care buyers and a slowdown in the growth
of government medical payments have intensified the financial
problems of medical groups.
</P>
<P>
   Brin said physician groups would still need access to capital to
grow and consolidate, as companies like Medpartners had promised.
But he said the management of clinics ``needs to be provided at the
local level.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Many in the industry believe there will ultimately be a new
version of the physician practice management companies,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   William McKeever, an analyst at Paine Webber Securities, said
the companies would have to ``revamp themselves to create more
value'' for doctors by providing a menu of optional services.
</P>
<P>
   Abramowitz said many hospitals were eager to buy physician
practices, even though they often turn out to be money losers,
because the doctors provide a steady flow of patients to fill
hospital beds.
</P>
<P>
   Medpartners reported net income of $7.7 million, or 4 cents a
share, on net revenue of $1.74 billion for the three months that
ended on Sept 30. That was down 84.3 percent from profits of $49.2
million, or 26 cents a share, on net revenue of $1.61 billion a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The company projected 10 percent growth in 1999 in its Caremark
drug benefit unit, half from new customers and internal growth and
half from rising drug prices. Pharmacy benefit managers negotiate
discounts with drug makers and offer selected products to health
plans at reduced prices.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford said Caremark would handle 43 million prescriptions
this year through 53,000 affiliated pharmacies and its mail-order
center. He said Caremark had 7 percent of the $30 billion annual
sales of drugs through pharmacy benefit management companies. The
business is dominated by units owned by drug manufacturers, Merck &AMP;
Company, Eli Lilly &AMP; Company and SmithKline Beecham PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Medpartners said Caremark had revenue of $661 million in the
quarter, up 7 percent from the year before.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 2100EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
