<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T OVERREACT? SURE, THAT'S EASY FOR HIM TO SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Mass. _ The problem now, of course, is to simply
hold your horses. That was Sinatra in ``Nice 'n Easy.''
</P>
<P>
   But how can we? We can't help ``Dreamin'.'' That was, as I
recall, Johnny Burnett.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it's all about ``Wishin' And Hopin''' (Dusty
Springfield).
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible _ I mean, is it really (itals)possible(unitals)?
_ that Cam Neely can make it back, all the way back, to become a
viable member of the Boston Bruins?
</P>
<P>
   I don't know. Harry Sinden doesn't know. Cam Neely doesn't know.
But there he was, gliding up and down the Ristuccia Center ice
Wednesday, looking indistinguishable from the other Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, wow. ``What A Day For A Daydream'' (Lovin' Spoonful).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing this on a day-to-day basis,'' he explained in the
wake of a 47-minute workout. ``If, over the next 10 days, my hip
tells me I can't do it, I will walk away and feel I gave it a good,
honest effort. That's all I'm asking.''
</P>
<P>
   Let me explain something to anyone coming to this story a little
late. This wasn't some Ordinary Joe Schmoe talking. This was
(itals)Cam Neely(unitals) talking. Cameron Michael Neely. A
one-of-a-kind hockey player.
</P>
<P>
   If Neely can return to the Bruins' lineup at _ pick a number _
75, 80, 90 percent of his old swashbuckling self, the Bruins
automatically will be a better hockey team. They will surely be a
more interesting team. We are, after all, talking about Cam Neely.
</P>
<P>
   That's why it's so hard not to let your imagination take a
1-yard gain and turn it into a 95-yard touchdown run. Getting Neely
back is a tantalizing proposition.
</P>
<P>
   If you're assistant general manager Mike O'Connell, you are
trying very hard to let your head overrule your heart. ``Daydream
about getting him back?'' inquired O'Connell. ``I've been doing it
all summer, like everyone else. But he came to us and explained the
situation. It's a (itals)trial(unitals), he said, and so we're
looking at it the same way. We'll just take a look and see where he
stands.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Harry Sinden himself. Harry is exquisitely
human. He can start out a sentence being a head guy, but before
he's finished his thought, he has turned into a major heart guy.
You think this Neely comeback bid isn't putting a strain on the
Sinden emotions?
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I start to dream about what could happen here,''
Harry said, ``Cam keeps me in line, because he himself is very
aware of the odds. I've had two or three discussions with him after
his skates. He'd say, `Pretty good, but I'm not where I want to be.
The pain is going away quicker, though.' Keeping in touch with him
has helped me from getting too excited.''
</P>
<P>
   About two minutes later, Neely put on a burst of speed and
unloaded one of those mortars on the goalie. ``Did you see that?''
Harry exploded. ``Not exactly a light skate, is it? I thought he'd
be out there floating around.'' About two minutes after that, Neely
did something else Harry liked, and suddenly, you could tell he was
back in the late '80s or early '90s, back in one of those 50-goal
years, back when Cam Neely was inserting a basketball term _ power
forward _ into the hockey lexicon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wasn't he a devastating body checker when he was healthy?''
Harry blurted out, to no one in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Of course he was. Everyone knows that. Cam Neely was a new blend
of power and finesse, unlike anything the NHL had known. There had
been tough-guy scorers, people like the legendary Gordie Howe,
whose great extracurricular expertise involved clever use of the
stick when the referee wasn't looking. Neely wasn't like that. His
game was to knock the snot out of an opponent with a legal body
check on one shift and then swoop in for a goal a power play or
shift later. There was, quite frankly, no one quite like him.
</P>
<P>
   Neely didn't hand out assists. No Gretzky, he. Neely was a
professional finisher. Now ask yourself: If you could give the
Bruins one thing, what would it be? A professional finisher, that's
what.
</P>
<P>
   There is no Willie McGee, where-would-we-put-him? issue here.
Cam Neely _ the old Cam Neely, or some reasonable facsimile _ would
have a place on the 1998-99 Boston Bruins. Hence all the dreaming.
</P>
<P>
   He is News, with that capital N. There were eight minicams to
record the historic first practice. One channel thought it was
important enough to do a midday live shot. On a normal practice
day, there might be a half-dozen media folk present, tops. We may
have approached triple figures Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Do not underestimate the enormity of the task in front of him.
Say the damaged hip says it's a go by the end of next week. That
doesn't mean he'll be racking up a hat trick against Tampa Bay or
the Florida Panthers the week after that. This man has not played a
serious game, against serious top-shelf competition, since Feb. 21,
1996. Once he has established his physical viability, there will be
the rather daunting matter of regaining his timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Practice is like riding a bicycle to a guy like him,'' warned
O'Connell. ``But the timing needed to play a real game is something
else. When do you break into the open? When do you retreat? When
someone throws something at you, how do you react? When you see the
subtle hand or feet movements of either an opponent or a teammate,
will you react instantly, the way you used to? The ability to read,
and read quickly _ those are going to be the hard parts.''
</P>
<P>
   All true, of course. But we're talking about Cam Neely, right?
Cam can do it if anybody can do it, right?
</P>
<P>
   I can't help but be excited. I'm pumped. I can't help it. I
mean, ``I Can Dream, Can't I?'' (Andrews Sisters).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
