<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6150 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRIGHT-INTERVIEW-ART-     11-11 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-INTERVIEW-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 FORT WORTH: or education.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At age 75, Wright has the wavy white hair, deepset eyes and
bristly eyebrows to lend oracular weight to his pronouncements. But
he takes pains to contrast Gingrich's outrage and hyperbole _ he
repeatedly called Wright ``a crook'' and ``the most corrupt House
speaker of the 20th century'' _ with his own restraint, even
self-deprecation. He now calls himself ``an ersatz columnist and an
ersatz professor,'' given his light writing and teaching loads for
the local newspaper and the college.
</P>
<P>
   Wright resigned after the House ethics committee charged him
with 69 ethics violations. He was accused of improperly taking
gifts from a developer who had a direct interest in legislation and
using sales of an earlier book, ``Reflections of a Public Man,'' to
lobbyists and supporters to circumvent restrictions on outside
income.
</P>
<P>
   Wright still hopes that historians who review his 7,000-word
departure speech and the documents he submitted for the record will
agree that he broke no laws or House rules.
</P>
<P>
   Wright began pointing out the accumulating ironies a few years
ago when Gingrich got into his own ethical scrapes. On Jan. 21,
1997, the House formally reprimanded him and fined him $300,000 for
using tax-exempt money to promote Republican goals and giving the
ethics committee false information. By then, Gingrich had returned
to Rupert Murdoch a $4.5 million book advance that, as Wright's
supporters say, was far more than Wright ever earned from his book.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich resigned not over his transgressions, however, but over
what his Congressional flock saw as his responsibility for his
party's reversals. Gingrich has said that political as much as
ethical considerations motivated his pursuit of Wright, for he
feared that the speaker had the skill and power to extend
Democratic domination of Congress indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Wright agrees that historians could fairly count him and
Gingrich as House speakers who helped keep Congress from being
reduced to merely reviewing presidential actions and initiatives.
At least initially, Wright said, ``I admired the parliamentary
skill with which Gingrich pursued the items on his chosen agenda,
the Contract With America. I thought that was leadership, though I
didn't embrace his goals.''
</P>
<P>
   But by the end of the Gingrich reign, Wright said, Gingrich was
using the same tactics against President Clinton that Gingrich had
used against him. ``Isn't it obvious?'' Wright said, adding that
even when he resigned he also warned of overreaching by zealous
special prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Wright calls for campaign finance changes to reverse the
alienation of an electorate whose participation declined to 38
percent in this month's election. He recalls how in 1954 he mounted
his successful first congressional campaign, against an incumbent,
with just $34,000 raised mostly from individuals and 6,500 block
captains who rang every doorbell in the district.
</P>
<P>
   Now, when campaigns are waged by commercials, he said, ``People
don't feel they're involved. All they hear on television is
negative stuff about candidate A and candidate B, so they go away
disenchanted and disillusioned, and they don't vote.''
</P>
<P>
   As the most prominent Republican winner in the elections, Wright
said, Texas Gov. George W. Bush demonstrated the moderate,
accommodating style that Clinton has used to his advantage. ``He
contrasted with the political practitioners whose tactics have been
repudiated by the voters,'' Wright said. ``He has not gone out to
defame or discredit anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Just about then, Wright's assistant, Norma Ritchson, interrupted
to say that Wright even showed sympathy for Gingrich. ``Poor man,''
Ms. Ritchson recalled Wright saying earlier this week. ``He must
feel bad.''
</P>
<P>
   At that, Wright admitted he didn't remember putting it quite so
warmly. ``I didn't weep. I didn't shed tears,'' Wright said. ``But,
hey, we're all in this together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
