<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 POP-KELLY-COX &HT;    `R' always has something to say
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe a No. 1 hit and three Grammy Awards have convinced Mr. ``I
Believe I Can Fly'' that he can try anything now. Rapping? R. Kelly
does that in tolerable Puff Daddy fashion on ``If I'm Wit You.''
Wait, is that R. yodeling? Yep, at the end of ``Get Up on a Room.''
And four album tracks later he takes on, briefly (thankfully),
opera.
</P>
<P>
   These kinds of surprises, coupled with Kelly's incredible gift
for arranging, make getting through one of contemporary R&AMP;B's few
double albums a lot easier. But what about, simply, his singing?
</P>
<P>
   After two solo efforts, fans should know that Kelly's limited
alto has never been as interesting as what he has to say. Remember,
this is the guy who sang about some woman reminding him of a Jeep.
And he proves just as clever crafting a plea for monogamy in the
guise of ``Half on a Baby.'' Then, he has some usually aggressive
hip-hop artists (Jay-Z, Noreaga) on ``We Ride,'' a song that would
nestle comfortably next to a Babyface ballad.
</P>
<P>
   But the mystifying trick Kelly continues to pull off is
borrowing blatantly from Jeffrey Osborne, Lenny Williams and, too
often, his own ``Down Low'' song _ and still coming up with hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``R''
</P>
<P>
   R. Kelly. Jive.
</P>
<P>
   29 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   The verdict:
</P>
<P>
   ``R'' must be short for a really good use of Kelly's pop
sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
