<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-POP-CHESNUTT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `The Salesman and Bernadette' turns silly and sublime
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes, listening to Vic Chesnutt, I think he may be as
succinct and profound a songwriter as Willie Nelson. Other times,
when his knack for crafting what sound like grown-up nursery rhymes
teeters toward surreal self-indulgence, I laugh out loud at his
utter disregard for formal propriety.
</P>
<P>
   Much more than an artifact of his abortive major-label deal with
Capitol Records, Chesnutt's latest album (picked up by
Atlanta-based Capricorn) is the best of both those sides of the
singer's personality. Partnered with the protean Nashville ensemble
Lambchop, whose horn arrangements sprawl from English Beat-style
exuberance to the ragged dirge of a New Orleans funeral procession,
the Athens, Ga.-based performer finds the coherence lacking in his
previous effort (1996's ``About To Choke''). Along with his gallery
of amusingly observed characters (''a man dripping with Vitalis,''
a ``self-ordained Faustian''), Chesnutt happens onto a surprising
Al Green falsetto and, in the brooding, Dylanesque folk-rock of
``Parade,'' evokes an existential sadness that may be one of the
forgotten qualifiers of great art.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Salesman and Bernadette''
</P>
<P>
   Vic Chesnutt. Capricorn. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: By turns silly and sublime, a local favorite flirts
with a masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
