</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-POP-SPRINGSTEEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Tracks' traces 23 years of the Boss
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   An ultimate keepsake for any hard-core fan of Bruce Springsteen,
the expansive ``Tracks'' covers 23 years of the singer's career _
from his nascent ``street poet'' phase heralded by ``Mary Queen of
Arkansas'' to the mature, Woody Guthrie-influenced populist of
``The Ghost of Tom Joad.'' Compiled by Springsteen and cleanly
remastered, the songs offer a parallel perspective on the Boss's
indefatigable rock classicism and New Jersey grit.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps predictably, the 1970s outtakes are the most compelling.
As feverishly over the top as such micro-epics as ``Zero and Blind
Terry'' and ``Thundercrack'' are, they pack a snake-hipped charisma
and loquacious drive that puts you in mind of a really good Martin
Scorsese movie: marinara sauce for the soul.
</P>
<P>
   Gems are scattered amid a lot that rings redundant, but the
reward of this sort of package is how it sketches the arc of an
artist's development. What's clear is that, while Springsteen can
be dully consistent (the early '90s weren't kind), his compassion
never wanes. It's the core of his work, and the key to this
collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tracks''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Springsteen. Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   66 tracks (4 CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An open vault of alternative versions and
unreleased songs meant to indulge the faithful.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
