<HEADER>
A6167 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-ERINGEL12-COX     11-11 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-ERINGEL12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Earlier Elizabeths had the regal stuff
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The British royal family has been so reduced to tabloid fodder
that it's nice to be reminded that wearing the crown of England
once meant something more than polo matches and People magazine. On
Nov. 20, ``Elizabeth,'' an admirable new film about Queen Elizabeth
I, opens in Atlanta. The star is Cate Blanchett, from last year's
``Oscar and Lucinda.'' She has quite an act _ make that quite a few
acts _ to follow. Don't worry; she does just fine. But consider
these royal talents who proceeded her.
</P>
<P>
   HER MAJESTY BETTE DAVIS
</P>
<P>
   (THE FIRST TIME)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Private Lives of Elizabeth and Essex'' (1939): The
31-year-old Davis endured excruciating age makeup (including
shaving her hair back two inches) and 65 pounds of costumes to play
the 60-ish monarch in this lavish adaptation of Maxwell Anderson's
Broadway play. Ironically, her co-star and romantic interest was
none other than Errol Flynn, the actor who had been suggested to
play Rhett to her Scarlett in one version of ``Gone With the
Wind.'' Davis said no to ``Gone With the Wind,'' and the search
went on. In order to play opposite Flynn here, she later said that
she simply fantasized that she was acting with Laurence Olivier,
who was her choice for Essex.
</P>
<P>
   HER MAJESTY BETTE DAVIS
</P>
<P>
   (THE SECOND TIME)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Virgin Queen'' (1955): This time, Davis was in her late
40s and she was playing a 50-ish Elizabeth, so it was less of a
stretch. Richard Todd, better known as television's Robin Hood,
plays Sir Walter Raleigh, the queen's ``favorite.'' A very young
Joan Collins, better known as television's Alexis Carrington, plays
a lady of the court loved by Todd. Reportedly, Davis got along with
Collins about as well as she did with Flynn. Still, Queen Elizabeth
was always one of her favorite roles; in fact, she had been away
from the movies for three years when she was lured back by the
chance to portray her again.
</P>
<P>
   HER MAJESTY FLORA ROBSON
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Fire Over England'' (1937): Set during the latter part of
Elizabeth's reign, when she was taking on the much-feared Spanish
Armada, this movie was meant to stir up similarly patriotic
passions in late-1930s Britain in respect to the storm clouds
gathering over Europe. Instead, it mostly stirred up the passions
of co-stars Laurence Olivier and Vivien Leigh. Already infatuated
with each other, they began a full-scale affair during the shooting
(both were already married). But that was offscreen; onscreen,
Flora Robson creates a monarch to rival either of Davis'
better-known efforts. She's majestic, imperious and wears a ruff
every bit as well.
</P>
<P>
   HER MAJESTY GLENDA JACKSON
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Mary, Queen of Scots'' (1971): Jackson had just finished
playing Elizabeth in an acclaimed six-part BBC series, ``Elizabeth
R,'' so portraying her again wasn't exactly what the actress had in
mind. She told the producers, ``I much prefer Vanessa's (Redgrave)
part.'' But that part, of course, was as Mary, so no dice. In the
interests of historical accuracy, Jackson allowed her hairline to
be shaved three inches; less accurate was a totally fictional
meeting between the rival monarchs on the Scottish border (Jackson
protested but was overruled). She was later unhappy with the movie
overall and called her performance ``a bit of a rehash.'' Consumer
alert: This film may not be readily available on video. But
``Elizabeth R'' is, and Jackson liked it better anyway.
</P>
<P>
   HER MAJESTY JEAN SIMMONS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Young Bess'' (1953): Probably closest in spirit to the new
``Elizabeth,'' this movie not only showcases the lovely and
talented Simmons but also offers Charles Laughton in a return to
one of his most famous roles: as King Henry VIII (unfortunately, he
dies early in the film). Deborah Kerr, who was originally
considered for the title role but was deemed too old by the time
production started four years after she was first contacted, plays
Catherine Parr, Henry's sixth and last wife. Stewart Granger, then
married in real life to Simmons, is a dashing courtier loved by
both women. Adding a certain art-mirrors-life aspect: Granger and
Kerr had had an affair while he was married to his previous wife.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
