<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0459 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6168 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-MINIS-COX     11-11 0378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN STORES THIS WEEK
 &HT;    By Steve Murray and Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Small Soldiers'' (PG-13) _ So many toys, so little fun in
this violent kid comedy about action figures that come to life and
wreck a suburban neighborhood. A lot of effort has been spent on
the computer-generated animation and the toy design. But somebody
should have bothered with the script, and the human characters
(including Kirsten Dunst and the late Phil Hartman). Though the
movie is bloodless, parents might be surprised by the ferocity of
the violence. (The warring toys use all kind of weapons, from
flamethrowers to chain saws.) Priced to own: $22.99. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Music From Another Room'' (PG-13) _ Badly off-key. With its
lyrical title and a cast including Jude Law (``Gattaca'') and Oscar
nominee Brenda Blethyn (``Secrets &AMP; Lies''), the movie sounds like
a charming character study. But it's mainly an endurance test. Law
plays Danny, who falls in love with the woman (Gretchen Mol) he
helped birth 20 years before. Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``I Went Down'' (R) _ In this blithely shapeless bit of
blarney, two mismatched Irish hoodlums _ one a mere amateur (Peter
McDonald), the other more hard-core (Brendan Gleeson) _ embark on a
mission for their boss that's more road-buddy movie than caper.
Director Paddy Breathnach seems perfectly comfortable with the
film's many detours, as do his delightful actors, both of whom do a
lot to help sustain its laid-back, shaggy-dog style. But a little
clipping around the middle might have helped. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Trevor'' (unrated) _ Peggy Rajski's Oscar-winning short
brings humor to the potentially maudlin tale of a 13-year-old
musical theater fanatic (Brett Barsky) who finds out he's gay. The
sly, exuberant tale follows Trevor through various stages: falling
in love with a school jock, getting rejected, deciding that maybe
it's not a great idea to dress up as Diana Ross for Halloween. It's
a credit to Rajski's sure hand that the 20-minute film can broach
the issue of teen suicide without ever losing its light touch. And
the Ross songs on the soundtrack don't hurt. Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
