</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-WHISPERER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BEST NEW RELEASE A long labor of love: `Whisperer' unfolds in
its own sweet time
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Horse Whisperer'' (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   Robert Redford's meandering self-help western only seems to take
longer than it would to read Nicholas Evans' book. Redford plays
the crusty-mystical cowboy-veterinarian who heals a wounded horse
and the psyche of its young rider (Scarlett Johansson). He also
romances, and calms, her Tina Brown-like editor mother (Kristin
Scott Thomas).
</P>
<P>
   Much of this thoughtful but slow movie is spent on scenic
horseback tours of the Montana landscape. On the plus side, every
time Redford and Thomas lope off on another picturesque ride, you
know you've got plenty of time to go to the kitchen and fix a
snack. They'll still be riding when you get back to the couch.
Unfortunately, all the big-sky scenery can't compensate for the
movie's thin mix of New Age tropes and simplistic view of Western
life. This is a place of lasso-happy white folks, from whom never
is heard a discouraging word.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is available in wide screen, pan-and-scan and DVD.
Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Also directed by Robert Redford: ``Ordinary People,'' ``A River
Runs Through It,'' ``Quiz Show''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
