 Levi's to Sell Clothing on Its Web Sites  &HT;       
 By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. will start selling Levi's and Dockers clothing
over its World Wide Web sites later this month, a move that may
boost sales for the troubled company but also could alienate the
retailers that sell its wares.
<P>
   Managing its own Internet sales is an opportunity for the San
Francisco company to control how its products are presented and
potentially increase profits, since it won't have to share revenues
with retailers.
</P>
<P>
   But by competing against the department stores and specialty
shops that have sold Levi's for decades, the company risks angering
its key accounts at a time when merchants are already unhappy with
the poor performance of Levi's products.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen percent of the jeans sold in the United States are
Levi's, down from 30 percent in 1990, according to Tactical Retail
Monitor, an industry newsletter. Top Levi's retailers include J.C.
Penney, Mervyn's, Sears, Kohl's and Macy's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The department stores are definitely going to get hurt'' by
the Web sales, said one Levi's retailer, who declined to be
identified. The impact will be small at first, but will grow with
the popularity of e-commerce, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Jay Thomas, director of digital marketing for the Levi's
brand, disagreed. He said Levi's will use the sites to get input
from customers on the fashions they prefer, and that information
will be used to create better-selling product.
</P>
<P>
   ``We honestly believe that by understanding our customers
better, we'll be a better partner at retail,'' he said. The Web
sites will include a store-locator service accessible from every
page of the sites, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Most Internet visitors are expected to do their actual buying in
stores, rather than on the Web, said Jeff Beckman, a Levi's
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Levi's executives believe they have failed to forge strong ties
between shoppers and the Levi's brand because retailers, rather
than Levi's, have direct contact with consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The company has attempted to run its own stores but has never
had much success. It operates a test Docker's shop in Troy, Mich.,
and has no current plans to open more. It also operates 28 Original
Levi's Stores, but seven of them will be closed by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Global sales of Levi's products, which include the Dockers and
Slates brands, are expected to drop this year by an estimated 10
percent, which follows a 4 percent decline in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The two Web sites,  &LR; www.levi.com &LR;  and  &LR; www.dockers.com, &LR;  will
attempt to develop relationships with customers by asking about
their fashion and lifestyle preferences, recommending clothing
based on their taste, and e-mailing them information about special
promotions.
</P>
<P>
   The sites also will showcase a much wider assortment of
merchandise than is typically found in stores, offering virtually
every available cut, wash and color.
</P>
<P>
   They will help surfers put together outfits and, on the Levi's
site, let surfers chat with rock musicians who wear Levi's clothes.
</P>
<P>
   The Levi's site has been around since 1995, and the Dockers site
was launched the following year. They will start selling products
on the Monday before Thanksgiving and will be promoted heavily in a
holiday advertising campaign, Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Levi's new Web initiative supplements a two-year direct
marketing effort that was also designed to develop a database of
Levi's customers and learn their fashion preferences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
