<SLUG> BC-COMPUTING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Get Right Back to Where You Started From  &HT;       
 By David Einstein  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  Once in a while I'll be surfing the Web and suddenly the
Back button on my browser won't work. Why does this happen, and is
there any way to get around the problem and return to the previous
page I was viewing?
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; Answer: &LR;  According to the experts at Netscape, this
frustrating predicament may be caused by a glitch in the
programming code used to create the Web page that won't let you
retreat. Fortunately, the problem is easily solved. Just
right-click the Back button, which will display a menu of the Web
pages you've visited during your current browsing session. Then
choose the page you want. (By the way, this procedure also works
with the Forward button.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Q: Can you recommend a software program that will translate
French into English?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: I can't recommend one, because I've never used such a
program, and besides, I can't speak French, so I wouldn't know
whether the translation was any good. But I can give you the names
of a few companies that make translation software. There's
Globalink ( &LR; www.globalink.com &LR; ), LanguageForce ( &LR; www.wforce.com &LR; )
and Transparent Language ( &LR; www.transparent.com &LR; ). Programs from
these companies typically cover many languages, not just French.
You can find them at CompUSA and other computer stores. Expect to
pay at least $50 for a program that can translate word processing
documents and Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do I put a shortcut on the desktop? I'd like to shorten
the process of opening programs. For example, currently I have to
go from the Start button to Programs to Expert Software to Bicycle
Bridge (solitaire game).
</P>
<P>
   A: Shortcuts are icons that let you open a program, file or
folder without having to track it down in a complicated menu or
file directory. If you use Microsoft Word every day, for instance,
you might want to put a shortcut on the desktop for it.
</P>
<P>
   Creating a desktop shortcut is easy. First, though, you have to
locate the actual file, program or folder on your hard drive. You
can do this by using My Computer, which you'll find in the upper
left corner of the desktop, or with Windows Explorer, which is in
the Program menu.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've tracked it down, drag the file, program or folder to
the Windows desktop with the right mouse button held down. When you
release the button, a menu will appear. Choose Create Shortcut(s)
Here.
</P>
<P>
   That's all there is to it. Oh, yeah, you can also put a shortcut
in the main Start menu, which is useful if you've got a lot of
windows covering up the desktop. To do that, follow the previous
instructions to locate the file, program or folder, right-click it
and drag it to the Start button rather than to the desktop. When
you release the mouse button, the shortcut will appear on the Start
menu.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am automatically logged off America Online if they detect
no activity after a certain period of time. This is very
inconvenient, particularly if you take a phone call or do something
off-line and miss their message asking if you wish to remain
connected. Is there anything that can be done about this? I thought
my contract with AOL was for unlimited use.
</P>
<P>
   A: The reason AOL automatically knocks people off is to prevent
them from staying connected for long periods without actually using
the service. Otherwise many users would log on in the morning and
not log off until bedtime, since the monthly rate for AOL is the
same no matter how much you use it, and there's no charge for a
local phone call to get connected. And if too many users were
always online, AOL's computers would not be able to handle the
load.
</P>
<P>
   Having said that, I can tell you that there are a number of
freeware and shareware programs designed to fool AOL's computer and
prevent it from knocking you off. Their names include StayOn, Wizon
and Popup Monitor, and you should be able to track them down with
any Internet search engine. Technically, AOL prohibits you from
using them, but in actuality the service can't detect if you're
using one.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EMACHINES.  &LR; Many readers have written asking for more
information about eMachines, the new company that's about to start
selling a complete PC, with a monitor, for $499. The eTower should
be available in the next couple of weeks at Fry's stores, Best Buy,
Office Depot and Costco. Information about eMachines and its
computers is available at the company's Web site,  &LR; www.e4me.com. &LR; 
Or you can call toll-free at (877) 566-3463.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Tip of the Week
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  In the market for a real bargain PC? Check out Computer Currents
and/or MicroTimes. These free magazines (you'll find them in
newspaper racks in the city or at computer stores) are full of ads
for great, inexpensive systems, like a Pentium II computer and
monitor for $988. The vendors are mostly small, independent shops
that assemble their own PCs. But many of them offer warranties
comparable to name brands.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to computers(at
sign)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
