<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MEETING-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
4 TEAMS IN PURSUIT OF JORDAN OF ST. LOUIS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ga., Md., Mich., Calif., Mo., Texas, Ariz., Mass.,
Ohio)   (jw) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPLES, Fla. _ Suddenly, Brian Jordan is in an economically
advantageous position that would be the envy of all free agents
except for the elite members of this year's market. The outfielder
is sought after by both New York teams as well as Atlanta and
Baltimore, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got the dominant team in the National League, where he
lives,'' Jordan's agent, Jim Turner, said Wednesday. ``You have the
most dominant team in baseball managed by someone he greatly
respects. You have the team in the city where he grew up and where
his parents live. You have the team that said they're going to do
everything they can do to be a contender and have added three
players.''
</P>
<P>
   In order, those teams are the Braves, the Yankees, the Orioles
and the Mets. Jordan, who batted .316, hit 25 home runs and drove
in 91 runs for St. Louis, is scheduled to meet Monday with the
Braves, who have joined the pursuit aggressively since trading
Michael Tucker to Cincinnati Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to sign him as soon as we can,'' John Schuerholz, the
Atlanta general manager, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, the Yankees called Turner and invited Jordan and
him to visit New York next Wednesday. Turner immediately accepted.
They presumably could visit with the Mets while they are in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Turner said he has received one four-year offer with the
possibility of a fifth year and ideally would like five years
guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want teams to know that we clearly would like to speed up
the timetable,'' Turner said by telephone from St. Louis. ``We
think that can be accomplished. We'd like to make it no more than
two weeks. I'd love to think it can be done much quicker than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   RED SOX TALKING TO VAUGHN
</P>
<P>
   Dan Duquette had a timetable, too. The Boston general manager
was scheduled to leave this southwest Florida town Thursday morning
and hoped to have Mo Vaughn signed by then. But it didn't appear
that he would have his wish granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making some progress in our talks that we hope will lead
to a deal,'' Duquette said Wednesday. ``We're making progress on
some issues that are important to Mo Vaughn.''
</P>
<P>
   But the progress apparently wasn't as significant as the issues
because Vaughn wasn't rushing to sign on the dotted line. The Red
Sox offered their first baseman $60 million for five years Monday
and made some modest changes in the offer Wednesday that did not
raise it to the level of the offer the Anaheim Angels made last
week for $72 million for six years. Duquette said he was ready to
move on if this round of negotiations didn't produce a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time we get to the point where we sign a
contract,'' he said. ``If we can't, we need to go out there in the
market and see if we can recruit some other players for the Red
Sox. ``
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that he is interested in Albert Belle and Bernie
Williams as possible replacements for Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   TIGERS SIGN ROYALS' PALMER
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit Tigers made an uncharacteristic but promised move
Wednesday, signing a free agent to a lucrative contract. They gave
Dean Palmer, Kansas City's third baseman, a five-year contract for
$36 million. Earlier in the off season, the Tigers had considered
making Bernie Williams the target of their new spending policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipated early that there wouldn't be a whole lot of
clubs in play,'' General Manager Randy Smith said. ``Then a bunch
of clubs expressed interest. We figured that hurt our chances. We
wanted to strike very quickly. We wanted to do something in a hurry
so it sets up anything else we're able to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers also had made an offer to Ken Caminiti, but Smith
said, ``Caminiti wasn't ready to make an affirmative answer and
Palmer was. Caminiti's preference, we've known all along, was to
stay in San Diego or go back to Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer, who in 1996 hit 38 home runs for Texas, hit 34 home runs
and drove in 119 runs for the Royals this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Diamondbacks signed two other free agents, giving
pitcher Greg Swindell $5.7 million for three years and first
baseman Greg Colbrunn $1.8 million for two years. The Diamondbacks
also traded pitcher Bob Wolcott to Boston for a player to be named.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
