r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKSIDE-SFCHRON &LR;      11-11 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKSIDE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Digital Books Could Be Your Big Break  &HT;       
 By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
This year, a book that was never published on paper was a nominee
for one of the world's most prestigious literary awards.
<P>
   ``The Angels of Russia'' by Patricia le Roy was distributed
exclusively over the Internet by Online Originals of London, one of
a new breed of electronic-book publishers.
</P>
<P>
   The critically acclaimed novel, which details a tragic love
affair set in Paris during the Gorbachev era, was nominated for
Britain's Booker Prize after &UR;  &LR; David Gettman, chief executive of
Online Originals, persuaded the five-member judge panel to consider
it. (It did not win.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Digital books are growing in respectability and sales, as
writers break into publishing by having their works showcased and
distributed by ``virtual bookstores'' on the Internet. But there's
a catch: Prospective writers pay the companies to have their
``e-books'' published on the Internet, although the writers can
earn royalties if their books find an audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until recently, your chance of being published was as good as
spotting the next Elvis,'' said Mark Smith, CEO of Spirit Virtual
Books in Richardson, Texas. ``This is the greatest thing since the
printing press.
</P>
<P>
   ``These digital, downloadable books give the future Hemingway
and Faulkner an opportunity to shine in an additional vehicle that
wasn't available a few years ago,'' said David Valenti, head of
NetBooks.com in Costa Mesa (Orange County). ``They will never
eliminate hardbound books, but it is a nice alternative for
struggling writers.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, publishing your idea of the great American novel has
never been easier.
</P>
<P>
   A collection of online publishers is distributing thousands of
electronic books featuring the words of first-time authors.
Startups with names like 1stBooks Library and Spirit Virtual Books
advertise and distribute authors' content on their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The books are typically distributed either via e-mail or as a
downloadable file. The publishers format the transmitted content
into chapters, with page numbers, photos and illustrations. Many of
the sites let you ``browse'' the books _ reading a chapter or two
for free. Some even let you buy a chapter at a time.
</P>
<P>
   However, many of these information-age publishers do not edit
copy or even read the original works (other than to omit
hate-mongering and sexually explicit material).
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Authors pay $300 to $500 for a six-month listing on the sites,
and a nominal charge (about $10) for each subsequent month. They
usually collect the first couple of hundred dollars earned from all
sales and 40 to 50 percent for every additional order.
</P>
<P>
   The e-books, which are heavily promoted on the Web sites, cost
readers $3 to $7. At least 35,000 are transmitted annually.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of online _ don't call them vanity _ publishers is
offering a forum for unpublished, and accomplished, writers. Among
them:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ 1st Books &LR;  ( &LR; www.1stbooks.com &LR; ). The Bloomington, Ind.,
company was co-founded by Tim Jacobs in 1996 after he
unsuccessfully pitched his children's books to major
publishers. &UR;  &LR; It is now the largest online publisher, with 1,300
books _ ranging from science fiction to cookbooks. By early 1999,
it should top 2,000 titles, making it the most prolific publisher
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   1stBooks' portfolio of publications include ``More Rough
Sketches,'' a collection of editorial cartoons by Pulitzer Prize
finalist Joel Pett, and ``Hearing the Noise: My Life in the NFL,''
an inside account of the NFL by former Dallas Cowboys running back
Preston Pearson.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Spirit Virtual Books &LR;  ( &LR; www.spiritvirtualbooks.com &LR; ). Named
after Smith's dog, it boasts a wide range of provocative titles
such as ``Murder Revisited,'' ``Web of Deceit'' and ``Matthias the
Birth of Evil.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Xlibris Corp. &LR;  ( &LR; www.xlibris.com &LR; ). The Princeton, N.J.,
company offers paper and electronic editions of books and
``on-demand digital publishing'' of single copies.
</P>
<P>
   Officials boast they employ the ``mother of all laser printers''
to print books. The room-size, high-resolution printers eliminate
the returns and inventory problems that often plague conventional
publishers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ UPublish.com &LR;  ( &LR; www.upublish.com &LR; ). It charges $249 to put a
book on the Web and $20 to print ``paperbound copies with a
wrap-around cover.'' The Parkland, Fla., company publishes a gamut
of works, including academic textbooks, fiction, nonfiction,
lecture notes, transcripts and scientific manuals.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; NetBooks.com &LR;  ( &LR; www.netbooks.com &LR; ). Launched this year by
Kanakaris Communications, it also lets authors post original works
for sale on the Net. Among its titles: ``Simple I Ching,'' a tome
on Eastern philosophies, and ``Aliens Above, Ghosts Below:
Explorations of the Unknown,'' a series of scientific articles on
paranormal events.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Online Originals  &LR; ( &LR; www.onlineoriginals &LR; . &LR; com &LR; ). &UR;  &LR; The Booker
Prize nominee ``The Angels of Russia,'' which sells for $7, is part
of a literary stable of several dozen titles that includes ``The
Paternoster Bead,'' a murder mystery set in medieval France.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
