<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 High-Tech Storytelling  &HT;       
 By Dan Fost 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
It was a dark and stormy site.
<P>
   Best-selling horror author John Saul led multimedia workers and
writers on a flashlight tour through the Winchester Mystery House
last Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   He was promoting ``The Blackstone Chronicles,'' a hybrid
combination of new media and traditional publishing. The title is
both a CD-ROM computer game that leads users through the dark maze
of a haunted asylum, as well as a novel, serialized into six short
books, that lays the groundwork for the asylum story.
</P>
<P>
   Saul is among a new wave of established and fledging authors who
are making creative use of technology to enhance their
storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   Whether fiction or nonfiction, on the Web or on a disc, for
promotion or for reader feedback, writers are finding interactive
media to be as invaluable as pens and paper. They aren't just
putting up Web sites; they're adding richness to their narratives
with video and sound, publishing some original content online, and
enlisting readers to help shape stories or even suggest titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new way of telling a story, adapted to this new
medium,'' Saul told the audience at the Winchester Mystery House.
</P>
<P>
   Popular spy novelist Tom Clancy is the most notable in the
field, as his Red Storm Entertainment makes CD-ROM games that are
tied to his latest novels. Although his initial foray, Politika,
was widely panned, his latest venture, Rainbow Six, is getting
positive reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Science fiction and fantasy novelists are among the first to
adapt their stories to new media. Alexander Besher, a San Francisco
novelist, is now publishing in serial form on the Internet a novel
about the horrors that may await the city thanks to the dreaded
Year 2000 computer bug. Another San Francisco writer, Joe Hutsko,
has his first novel due out next year, and _ perhaps in part
because the theme has something to do with handheld computing _
he's already sold the PalmPilot rights.
</P>
<P>
   Even Hunter S. Thompson, always known for pushing the envelope,
is getting into the act, sort of. The dean of gonzo journalism is
publishing his first novel, ``The Rum Diary,'' the manuscript for
which was written in the 1950s but only recently unearthed.
</P>
<P>
   Four independent Bay Area bookstores are stirring up interest in
the book, and adding to its appeal, with a ``Web ring'' _ a series
of linked sites _ that connects to other sites of Thompsoniana and
includes photos and hand-scrawled notes that are available nowhere
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hunter S. Thompson fans, I'm sure, are gaga over the chance to
see these sorts of things, and it's material that would otherwise
never come to light in print form,'' said Thomas Gladysz, the Web
manager at the Booksmith, a Haight Street bookstore that's among
the sponsors of the sites.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon is manifest in scores of other ways. Children's
book authors tap into the educational urge to include multimedia,
for example, letting kids hear the stories read aloud or ``play''
with the characters online. &UR;  &LR; Web sites _ notably those like
 &LR; Amazon.com  &LR; that sell books, but also others like America Online's
site at  &LR; www.thebookreport.com &LR;  _ build communities around authors
and reading.
</P>
<P>
   Even many of the authors and publishers who make forays into
multimedia and the Web are only scratching the surface. The medium
is still not mature, and its potential remains uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're moving a book onto the Net just like people moved the
old manuscripts out of monks' libraries and into print when
Gutenberg invented movable type. They just raid the old texts,''
said Robert Coover, a novelist and professor at Brown University.
</P>
<P>
   Computer storytelling will really take off as Internet
connections get faster to accommodate material like video and as
more people get hooked up to the Net, Coover predicts.
</P>
<P>
   Computer games based on novels are becoming increasingly common.
Good games can cost hundreds of thousands of dollars to produce,
and publishers want to bet safely on hits. Spinning a brand-name
novel into a game at least theoretically guarantees an interested
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Games based on novels are ``a natural,'' said Johnny Wilson,
editor in chief of Computer Gaming World. ``When people read a
novel they really like, they would like to play in that universe.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Wilson said, ``there have been a lot of false starts,''
such as the computer game based on William Gibson's ``Johnny
Mnemonic'' that Wilson labeled a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, many of the new online novels carry some type
of computer theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Bug,'' Besher's serial novel at  &LR; sfgate.com/thebug, &LR; 
features graphics, hyperlinks and a protagonist named Geronimo Poe
Smith _ GPS to his friends _ whose job is to ride around San
Francisco on a bicycle, making sure that those French self-cleaning
toilets are Year 2000-compliant.
</P>
<P>
   An unexpected bonus for Besher has been the contributions of
readers around the world. Bike messengers tell him ``how they view
the world from a bike. ... An African hip-hop DJ in Holland is
giving me interesting insights into a character who's Nigerian.
Some other guy is making sure my Swahili is fluent. How else would
I do that?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not just accessing sites, I'm accessing people's minds and
hearts,'' Besher said.
</P>
<P>
   And when a reader catches an author's mistake online, Besher
said, ``you can go back and make little corrections and fine-tune
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other authors may not publish online, but they still use the
Internet to take the pulse of their readers.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Fitzgerald, publisher and executive producer of
 &LR; thebookreport.com, &LR;  said ``some writers go in undercover and talk
to their readers,'' using assumed names in chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald's site publishes interviews with authors, who discuss
different ways they use the Internet. Clive Cussler said he
researched his latest book, about Atlantis, on the Web. Even
romance writer Nora Roberts conducts online research, as well as
maintaining message boards with her readers. Janet Evanovich has a
Web site in which she asks readers to name her next book.
</P>
<P>
   John Saul found that people who read his books, ``The Blackstone
Chronicles,'' were going online and inserting themselves into the
stories. ``One day, a werewolf moved in,'' Saul said, somewhat
incredulous. ``It was bizarre. You'd read this and you'd swear it
was all happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Saul conceived of ``The Blackstone Chronicles'' as a computer
game. He had ``always liked at least the idea of computer games, if
not the games themselves,'' he said. ``The story line was never
compelling. Whoever designed it knew a lot about gaming and
puzzling, and not a lot about storytelling.''
</P>
<P>
   Saul enlisted Bob Bates, president and game designer at Legend
Entertainment, who had worked with science fiction and fantasy
authors like Terry Brooks and Robert Jordan. Then Saul's publisher,
Ballantine Books, saw some synergistic potential, and commissioned
a six-part serial novel.
</P>
<P>
   The longtime horror writer sees several reasons these projects
are getting produced. ``Everyone's experimenting right now,'' he
said. ``They're excited with the new technology, and the
possibilities are going to expand as processors get faster and
storage gets bigger. People are going to keep trying to find new
forms of storytelling to use the medium.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, ``publishers are seeing book sales flatten
like crazy. They're slowly becoming aware that the book audience is
suddenly the Internet audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to go through five or six books a week. Now I'm lucky
if I read two or three books a month,'' Saul said. ``We've all
become slaves to our computers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 2135EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
