<HEADLINE>
TIPPER GORE VISITS REFUGEE CAMP FOR MITCH VICTIMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VILLA NUEVA, Nicaragua _ On the final day of a quick trip
through hurricane-ravaged Central America, Tipper Gore on Wednesday
led a clutch of U.S. lawmakers, aid workers and camera-clicking
journalists through this sprawling camp for storm victims on the
edge of the Nicaraguan capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here because we want to help the people rebuild their
neighborhoods, their lives,'' said Gore, the wife of Vice President
Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen people living in the streets, families ripped apart
and loved ones lost forever in this region,'' she said after
arriving in Managua from Honduras, where she slept in a refugee
camp Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's delegation caused a brief flurry as it swung through
Villa Nueva, where as many as 15,000 people left homeless by Mitch
live in hastily assembled hovels made out of heavy black plastic.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a military-style vest, Gore talked through interpreters
to people who lost their homes and most of their possessions to
Mitch's floodwaters. She toured a small health clinic set up in
tents. She watched as workers passed out wash basins, toilet paper
and toothpaste donated by the U.S. government to the newly
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Nicaraguan officials herded dozens of barefoot children to greet
Gore with an arm-waving chorus of ``gracias,'' or thank you.
</P>
<P>
   But most residents of the camp seemed too busy struggling to
build new lives to pay much attention.
</P>
<P>
   Before Oct. 31, most of the residents of Villa Nueva lived in a
slum on the shores of Lake Managua. Many worked as street vendors
in a public market also destroyed by the flood.
</P>
<P>
   Out of work, they now depend on charity for shelter, food, water
and medical care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they leave us a little something,'' said Nestor
Peralta, a 25-year-old father of two toddlers, as he watched Gore's
entourage pass. ``We've lost our homes, our jobs, the lives we
had.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad as things here may have seemed to the group from Washington,
Villa Nueva is something of a refugee-camp showcase. People here
have it far better off than many of Mitch's victims deep inside the
Nicaraguan and Honduran countryside, where aid has been slow to
arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Set up in cattle pastures and empty fields bought by the Managua
city government, Villa Nueva had been set aside for new housing
even before Mitch struck. The camp sits alongside Ciudad Sandino, a
community of 70,000 that began as a camp for refugees following the
1972 earthquake that destroyed central Managua.
</P>
<P>
   Families who have relocated here have received 24-by-36-foot
lots. The government has given them plastic to build shelters and
has promised that bricks to build walls and laminated tin to cover
roofs will come.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, water lines were installed. Spigots set about five
houses apart are now providing water for drinking and bathing.
Latrines are being dug. The government is handing out food.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross and other organizations are setting up facilities
to provide medical care and other services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The help is coming, but it's coming very slowly,'' said
Raymundo Bermudez, a young city engineer who was assigning lots to
refugees and distributing aid.
</P>
<P>
   Gore announced Wednesday that the United States will send an
additional $1.5 million in medical supplies to Nicaragua and other
countries hit hard by the storm. That came on top of the $10
million in relief she announced in Honduras on Tuesday, bringing
the total amount of emergency U.S. aid pledged to the region to
just over $80 million.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government, Gore said, will also send 12 more
helicopters to the area to help ferry relief supplies to remote
villages and outlying regions. Officials in Honduras and Nicaragua
have cited a shortage of helicopters as a major obstacle in the
effort to get aid to those who need it most.
</P>
<P>
   Both Nicaragua and Honduras _ the two countries struck hardest
by Mitch _ already rank among the poorest in the Americas. In
Nicaragua, per-capita income hovers at just $450 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Mitch killed an estimated 6,000 people in Honduras and 4,000 in
Nicaragua. The storm chewed up bridges and roads across the region.
</P>
<P>
   In Honduras, estimates of Mitch's damage range to as high as $3
billion, nearly equal to the country's annual economic output. In
Nicaragua, officials place the damage at $1 billion, about half the
annual value of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Honduras lost as much as 70 percent of its crops, including most
of its bananas, which provide much of its export income. In
Nicaragua, coffee, sugar and other crops were badly damaged.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. aid is destined purely for emergency relief operations,
said Brian Atwood, the director of the U.S. Agency for
International Development, who travelled with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's intention is to ``make sure people down here don't
get the diseases that usually follow something like'' Mitch, Atwood
said in Villa Nueva.
</P>
<P>
   A multinational meeting is planned for early December in
Washington to map out a long-term aid strategy for Central America,
Atwood said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need are plans that we all feel comfortable with,''
Atwood said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Atwood, Gore's delegation included U.S. Reps. Jim
Kolbe, R-Ariz., Xavier Becerra, D-Calif., Gary Akerman, D-N.Y., as
well as Democratic Sens. Christopher Dodd of Connecticut, Jeff
Bingaman of New Mexico and Mary Landrieu of Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Also along was Dennis Martinez, the Nicaragua-born pitching star
for the Atlanta Braves, who urged Nicaraguans to work together in
the wake of Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not forget this,'' Martinez said to the cameras at the
airport. ``We have to work hard as Nicaraguans. We can't only
depend on outside aid.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
