<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INTERNET STOCKS FALL SHARPLY AS INVESTORS TAKE PROFITS
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Yahoo fell $11.5625, to $165, and America Online
declined $7.375, to $137.125, as most Internet stocks slumped on
profit taking after recent increases. Although shares of the chip
maker Intel rose $6.125, to $103.6875, after the company projected
stronger-than-expected revenue for the quarter, it was not enough
to rally the Nasdaq, which decreased 3.51 points, to 1,862.11.
</P>
<P>
   Market gauges fell as investors pondered what seems little
better than an even chance that the Federal Reserve will cut
short-term interest rates again next week. The Dow Jones industrial
average fell 40.16 points, to 8,823.82, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index shed 7.29 points, to 1,120.97.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Earthweb, an online provider of technical information
for World Wide Web site designers, more than tripled on their first
day of trading. Earthweb rose $34.6875, to $48.6875, on trading of
11.5 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   GATES BLAMES RIVALS FOR CHARGES
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gates, the chairman of Microsoft, told shareholders that
the government's antitrust case against the software giant was
driven chiefly by the company's rivals.
</P>
<P>
   AILING NISSAN MOTOR IN LOAN TALKS
</P>
<P>
   Nissan Motor, Japan's No. 2 automaker, is negotiating with the
Japan Development Bank for a loan of about 100 billion yen, or $823
million, to help it write off some debt.
</P>
<P>
   THE SHERLOCK HOLMES OF TRADEMARKS
</P>
<P>
   As the intellectual property counsel for Compagnie Financiere
Richemont, the owner of such elite brands as Alfred Dunhill luxury
gifts, Cartier jewelry and Montblanc pens, Frederick Mostert helps
make sure no one steals or imitates the names, shapes or slogans of
the Swiss-based company's products. He is also the president of the
International Trademark Association, so he keeps his eye on other
companies' products as well.
</P>
<P>
   THE LAST DAYS OF CHRYSLEr
</P>
<P>
   After a history of close calls with bankruptcy, a federal
government bailout and a recent flood of profits from minivan and
Jeep sales, Chrysler Corp. will disappear as an independent company
Thursday, merging with Daimler-Benz of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   MEDPARTNERS EXITING A BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   Medpartners is leaving the business of physician practice
management. It plans to concentrate on more profitable units that
provide managed care drug benefits and coordinate medical
treatments.
</P>
<P>
   FEDERATED PROFIT CLIMBS 4.8 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Federated Department Stores said fiscal third-quarter profit
rose 4.8 percent as cost controls offset lower sales at its
Bloomingdale's, Macy's and other chains. Profit before a charge
rose to $110 million, or 50 cents a diluted share, a penny above
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   NO DEAL FOR BARINGS BONDHOLDERS
</P>
<P>
   Investors holding the bonds of Barings PLC, the failed British
bank, rejected a proposed settlement seeking to recover their
losses, saying the amount was a fraction of the $1.3 billion lost
in 1995 during a wild trading spree by one of the bank's Singapore
traders.
</P>
<P>
   BIOTECH COMPANY IN CELL DISCOVERY
</P>
<P>
   A small biotechnology company, Advanced Cell Technology of
Worcester, Mass., said that its scientists had for the first time
made human cells revert to the primordial, embryonic state from
which all other cells develop, by fusing them with cow eggs and
creating a hybrid cell. The method could eventually be used to
create replacement body tissue.
</P>
<P>
   PACIFIC LUMBER LICENSE SUSPENDED
</P>
<P>
   California forestry regulators, citing what they called
continuing egregious violations, have suspended the conditional
old-growth redwood logging license of Pacific Lumber Co. The
suspension could complicate a $380 million state and federal deal
to buy one of the world's oldest groves of virgin redwoods from the
company.
</P>
</TEXT>
