<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6199 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-MINIS-COX     11-11 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MINI REVIEWS
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray, Doug Hamilton and Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RHYTHM AND BLUES
</P>
<P>
   ``Dru Hill''
</P>
<P>
   Tick, tick, tick, tick.... As time passes and listeners slowly
forget about M.I.A. bad boys Jodeci, Dru Hill still isn't an easy
substitute. Sisqo can ache and riff like K-Ci of Jodeci. And when
Dru tries on a sexual persona (``Real Freak''), it seems to fit.
But someone should tell this technically fine quartet that cranking
a note up to the heavens isn't the only way to emote. Use this
album's ``Beauty'' or ``These Are the Times'' as examples of what
works, if you must. Anything to curb what occasionally feels like
unflattering mimicry.
</P>
<P>
   Dru Hill. Island Black Music.
</P>
<P>
   17 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Velvet Goldmine: Original Soundtrack''
</P>
<P>
   Even though actor Ewan McGregor (playing feral rock star Curt
Wild in director Todd Haynes' glam-rock movie fantasia) can't match
role model Iggy Pop's intensity on the movie's version of ``T.V.
Eye,'' this soundtrack of an era doesn't miss much. Loaded with
original tracks from Brian Eno, Lou Reed and Steve Harley and
Cockney Rebel, and copycat versions of Roxy Music and the New York
Dolls, it offers an entertaining gloss on music that was already
obsessed with artifice. New material from Shudder to Think, Grant
Lee Buffalo and Pulp is impressively stitched in, seamless
contemporary nods to rock's high mannerist phase.
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Polygram. 19 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Reunion''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this is sacrilege (or at least the devil-metal
equivalent), but I've always preferred bat-biting rocker Ozzy
Osbourne's solo material to his work with Black Sabbath. True,
Sabbath's relentlessly sludgy sound influenced everyone from
Metallica to Mudhoney, but even the most accessible hits, such as
``Iron Man,'' don't have the propulsiveness of Ozzy's ``Crazy
Train'' or ``Flying High Again.'' One listen to this live reunion
album, which features original Sabbath members Osbourne, Tony
Iommi, Geezer Butler and Bill Ward, confirms that the band's music
remains a sonic tar pit. You know you're in for a long,
head-splitting haul when Butler uncorks an interminable bass solo
two songs into the set.
</P>
<P>
   Black Sabbath. Epic. 18 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
