<SLUG> BC-BBN-TUCKER-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Did Braves get their money's worth in deal?
 &HT;    By Tim Tucker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Reading between the lines of the Braves-Reds trade:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Baseball players are like the stock market,'' Cincinnati
general manager Jim Bowden says, ``and Bret's at his highest
value.'' In Wall Street parlance, the Reds sold high. Nine teams
had expressed interest in Bret Boone, according to Bowden, and the
Reds were willing to trade him only if someone would overpay. The
Braves overpaid.
</P>
<P>
   _ A recent 20-game winner (Denny Neagle), a serviceable
outfielder (Michael Tucker) and an outstanding pitching prospect
(Rob Bell) represent quite a bounty for a slick-fielding,
unpredictable-hitting second baseman (Boone) and a journeyman
left-handed pitcher (Mike Remlinger). The only mitigating factor is
that the Braves dealt from an area of excess, pitching, to address
an area of dire need, second base.
</P>
<P>
   _ Boone would have been a much better buy a year ago, when his
stock was at an all-time low. He had a dismal offensive season in
'97, and the Reds were so eager to unload his four-year,
$11.4-million contract that they did not protect him from the
expansion draft. But Tampa Bay and Arizona passed on him, believing
_ along with everyone else _ that his contract was too lavish. Now,
after Boone's surprising 24-homer, 95-RBI season and another surge
in baseball salaries, the same contract is perceived as a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Braves needed to shore up their middle infield, and
defensively Boone is unimpeachable. He led NL second basemen in
fielding percentage in '95, '96 and '97, set a major-league record
for fielding percentage by a second baseman in '97, then won an
overdue Gold Glove this year. He makes both the routine plays and
the spectacular plays _ a combination not often found.
</P>
<P>
   _ Offensively, there is more reason for wariness about what the
Braves are getting. To an inconsistent offense overly reliant on
the home run, they have added another inconsistent hitter whose
value skyrocketed because of the career-high 24 homers. In fact,
few hitters in recent years have been as inconsistent as Boone. His
batting average has fluctuated from .320 in '94 to .223 in '97,
settling at .266 in '98. He strikes out a lot, and he is neither a
leadoff hitter nor a base-stealing threat, so those deficiencies of
the Braves' offense remain.
</P>
<P>
   _ Remlinger? He represents an effort to address the need for an
experienced left-hander in the bullpen, but his career record of
19-31, 4.63 ERA, is nothing to get excited about.
</P>
<P>
   _ The key pitcher going to the Reds was not Neagle. ``The key to
this trade,'' Bowden says, ``was Rob Bell. All of our people see
him as a 15-20 game winner down the road _ a cross between
(curveball pitcher) Darryl Kile and (power pitcher) John Smoltz.''
The Braves have a wealth of pitching prospects, yes, but it is not
a well to which they should go often in trades.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tucker's inclusion in the deal signals that the Braves intend
to upgrade right field, their other position _ in addition to 2B _
that was clearly not up to standards this season. It remains to be
seen, though, how they'll do it. Free agent Brian Jordan is
appealing but very expensive, and with Neagle gone, the team's most
tradeable chip has been used.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Reds say they intend to keep Neagle, rather than dealing
him for prospects, but if they're out of the race by midseason next
year, they probably will get a too-good-to-refuse offer from a
contending team.
</P>
<P>
   _ Neagle departs the Braves with class and characteristic good
humor _ surprised to be dealt to a non-contender, unsure how long
he'll be in Cincinnati, but nevertheless upbeat. ``I'm an
optimistic guy. I see the glass half-full instead of half-empty.''
He'll win a lot more games somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
