<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clemson to meet Georgia Tech tonight
 &HT;    By Norman Arey and Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ CLEMSON vs. Georgia Tech, Today, 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   After changing offenses several times, the Tigers seem settled
on a three-wideout formation that has enabled QB Brandon Streeter
to post better numbers. Streeter set school single-game records
with 27 completions and 329 yards in a 46-39 loss to N.C. State,
and he has thrown just four interceptions in his last five games
after throwing nine in his first four. ... Outside linebacker
Adrian Dingle needs one more sack to tie the single-season school
record of 10 held by William Perry, Michael Dean Perry and Jim
Stuckey.... Head coach Tommy West had a busy ``day off'' with the
Tigers idle last Saturday: His wife gave him a 12-chore list. ``I
told the team they wouldn't be getting any more days off because
I've worked harder on my day off than I have all season.''
</P>
<P>
   DUKE vs. Maryland, Saturday, noon
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since 1994 and the second time in the 1990s,
the Blue Devils have a chance to close their year with a winning
record. Coach Fred Goldsmith was asked if he thought the Duke
program had turned the corner. ``We've got the blinker on,'' he
deadpanned. ``After all the harassment we've gotten in the last few
years, we've got something to play for in November. This is an
opportunity to be a winner. This is so different than last year or
the year before. The last few years, we've just been running the
string out, and that's no fun.'' ... Goldsmith will have his top
two receivers, Scottie Montgomery and Richmond Flowers, available
for the first time in four weeks. Flowers missed three weeks after
an appendectomy, and Montgomery was out with a separated shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA STATE at Wake Forest, Saturday, 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bobby Bowden professes great confidence in Marcus Outzen,
who will start his first game at quarterback now that Chris Weinke
is out for the season. ``I've got a feeling he'll play pretty good
if he gets over his mistakes,'' Bowden said. ``If he makes some
mistakes early, how he responds to them will probably tell how he's
going to do. He spent two years going against our top defense in
practice. He's one of those guys you look at and say he's a winner.
When we signed him, we couldn't judge his passing because his high
school was a running team. ... We will not cut back as much as we
did when Weinke had that (six-interception) game against North
Carolina State. We made a big thing of getting our running game
cranked up. We'll run it some and try to help him.''
</P>
<P>
   MARYLAND at Duke, Saturday, noon
</P>
<P>
   With freshman QB Randall Jones continuing to struggle, coach Ron
Vanderlinden will announce his starter either today or tomorrow.
Neither Jones nor junior Ken Mastrole has been able to generate a
passing attack for the Terps, who throw for a measly 88 yards a
game. The two have thrown for just one TD each, the same as RB
LaMont Jordan. ``We felt we need to take some pressure off Randall,
and we felt we needed to give Kenny another chance,'' Vanderlinden
said. ... Jordan needs 274 rushing yards in his last two games to
reach 1,000 for the season. ... FS Tony Jackson, who has missed the
last three games with a knee sprain, is questionable, as is DT Kris
Jenkins, who has a pinched nerve in his shoulder and didn't play
last week against North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   NORTH CAROLINA at Virginia, Saturday, 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Carl Torbush says he's not worried about how freshman
quarterback Ronald Curry will react to antagonism from Virginia
players and fans. Curry had verbally committed to the Cavaliers
before switching to the Tar Heels. ``I'm not concerned about Ronald
Curry,'' Torbush said. ``He'll approach this just as he has every
game this season _ with maturity and poise and great concentration.
It's not Ronald Curry vs. anybody else. It's our team vs. theirs.
I'm sure the fans will get involved, but Virginia's always had a
great fan atmosphere. They get involved in trying to distract an
opposing team.'' ... Torbush said Virginia has the best running
attack North Carolina will face this season, with Thomas Jones and
Antwoine Womack.
</P>
<P>
   N.C. STATE at Maryland, Nov. 21
</P>
<P>
   Torry Holt is closing in on several key ACC receiving records.
With 3,113 career yards after picking up 404 in the last two games,
he is 205 yards shy of the league record held by Duke's Clarkston
Hines. He needs six catches to surpass the ACC single-season mark
of 77 set by Geroy Simon of Maryland in 1994. Last week against
Wake Forest, Holt had a career-best 15 catches for 179 yards. ...
Both State and North Carolina have sold approximately 30,000 of the
34,000 tickets they were allotted for their regular-season finale
Nov. 28 at Charlotte's Ericsson Stadium.... Freshman Ray Robinson,
a midseason replacement at tailback after a shoulder injury ended
Rahshon Spikes' season, is fifth in the ACC in rushing with 644
yards. He had 164 and two TDs in last week's win over Wake Forest.
</P>
<P>
   VIRGINIA vs. N. Carolina, Saturday, 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   As if the Cavaliers wouldn't have their hands full against the
Tar Heels anyway, defensive lineman Antonio Dingle has given
Carolina something to rally around. The 6-3, 300-pounder said he
wanted to hurt Carolina quarterback Ronald Curry and make him
scream. Coach George Welsh tried to downplay the controversy.
``These are just kids,'' Welsh said. ``I can't believe he really
wants to hurt him. It's Virginia vs. North Carolina; it's not
anything personal about anybody else. I don't hold anything against
him. I think too much has been made of it.'' But Welsh did say he
planned to discuss the controversy with his team. ``I intend to
talk to the players. I don't want this to take away from the game,
take away from their concentration. We need to be thinking about
North Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   WAKE FOREST vs. Florida State, Saturday, 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jim Caldwell says the absence of injured FSU quarterback
Chris Weinke won't affect his team's preparation too much. ``We
know Florida State is among the top recruiting programs in the
country, but their depth is so good and they have so many great
players, I'm certain they won't miss a beat.'' Caldwell said he was
aware that the Seminoles lined up once against Virginia last week
with wide receiver Peter Warrick at quarterback. ``Peter Warrick
could line up anywhere on the field and be an effective player,''
Caldwell said. ``If he lines up at quarterback, he would present a
little bit more of a problem.'' ... Marcus OutzenWake's leading
receiver, Desmond Clark
</P>
</TEXT>
