<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    I-AA playoffs in the picture for Bethune
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bethune-Cookman College, the smallest member of the
Mid-Eastern Athletic Conference, has evolved into one of the
biggest stories in I-AA football.
</P>
<P>
   Despite only 52 players on scholarship, 11 fewer than the I-AA
maximum, the small private school in Daytona Beach, Fla., has a 7-1
record and probably will make a postseason appearance. Picked to
finish seventh in the nine-team MEAC, the Wildcats already have won
homecoming games at South Carolina State, North Carolina A&AMP;T and
Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   According to second-year head coach Alvin Wyatt, who in 22 years
at Bethune-Cookman has been head women's basketball coach and a
football assistant during two separate stretches, the Wildcats have
generated shockwaves by using the ``Wyatt Bone'' offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a combination of the wishbone, the broken bone (and) the
dive option, as well as the shotgun,'' said Wyatt, whose son,
Antwuan, is a former Clemson and Bethune-Cookman receiver currently
on the Miami Dolphins' practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   Wyatt, 4-7 last season, did not implement the offense until late
August. He was encouraged to do so because of the presence of
quarterback Patell Troutman, a 5-10, 175-pounder from Daytona
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Troutman, along with All-America candidate James Adderley at
receiver, has the Wildcats ranked among the top 20 in the I-AA
Sports Network poll for the first time in school history, and
second behind state rival Florida A&AMP;M in the latest Sheridan poll.
</P>
<P>
   Playing huge roles in a program supported by a booster club that
is now 31 chapters strong, Troutman, Adderley and the Wildcats
defense have put themselves in the picture for the I-AA playoffs
and the Heritage Bowl. And they could share the MEAC title if they
beat Norfolk and then Florida A&AMP;M the next weekend in Orlando,
where a crowd at the Citrus Bowl might reach 70,000.
</P>
<P>
   Troutman has rushed for a team-high 672 yards and 11 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Rattlers benefit
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Bethune-Cookman itself, the biggest beneficiary of
the Wildcats' success so far is Florida A&AMP;M. After surviving a
scare and emerging with a 50-48 victory over Southern last weekend,
the Rattlers (8-1, 5-1) not only moved ahead of Hampton to the No.
1 spot in the Sheridan poll but also put themselves in position to
grab a share of the MEAC title as a result of the Wildcats' victory
over Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   But on Nov. 14, the Wildcats will try to take all of that away
from a Rattlers team that beat them 52-35 before a crowd of nearly
57,000 in Orlando a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   G-Men on brink of .500
</P>
<P>
   With a victory over Division II opponent Winston-Salem State on
Saturday, in a game to be played in San Diego, Grambling first-year
coach Doug Williams will have pushed his team to 5-5 heading into
the annual showdown with Southern in the Bayou Classic at the
Superdome in New Orleans Nov. 28.
</P>
<P>
   A Grambling victory also would enhance the chances of little
Livingstone College making its second appearance in the
Atlanta-based Pioneer Bowl Dec. 19 as the CIAA representative. The
team from the smallest school in Division II has won more games
(6-3, 5-2) than Winston-Salem State (5-4, 5-2), which will be an
underdog against the G-Men.
</P>
<P>
   CIAA
</P>
<P>
   Virginia St. vs. Elizabeth City St., 1:30 p.m.; Johnson C. Smith
vs. Virginia Union, 1:30 p.m.; Livingstone vs. Fayetteville St.,
1:30 p.m.; Winston-Salem St. vs. Grambling St., 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   MEAC
</P>
<P>
   Morgan St. at Howard, 1 p.m.; Hampton at Delaware St., 1 p.m.;
South Carolina St. at Florida A&AMP;M, 7 p.m.; Norfolk St. at
Bethune-Cookman, 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SIAC
</P>
<P>
   Morris Brown at Lane, 1 p.m.; Tuskegee at Savannah St., 1:30
p.m.; Fort Valley State vs. Albany State, 1:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SWAC
</P>
<P>
   Miss. Valley St. at Alabama St., 1 p.m.; Prairie View at Jackson
St., 1 p.m.; Alcorn St. at Alabama A&AMP;M, 1:30 p.m.; Texas Southern
at Southern, 6:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
