<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6208 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HUMMER-COLUMN12-C     11-11 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUMMER-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rankings shrouded in mystery
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Let's say you are a Tennessee football fan. Your world
has just become a very complicated place. Here, the Vols have
become the No. 1-ranked team in the country, positioned nicely for
an ultimate national championship game, and you don't really know
how.
</P>
<P>
   There are not enough fingers and toes to do the math involved.
Even if the whole family takes off its deerskin boots.
</P>
<P>
   No one can really help explain it, either. Whenever the
components of the Bowl Championship Series standings are broken
down, it always comes out sounding like this to the average Joe:
Buzzzzzzzzzzz. Quartile rank. Buzzzzzzzzzzz.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I'm fascinated by the new system. I haven't had this
exciting of a math challenge since the last time, long ago, I tried
to balance the checkbook. Football without long division just
wouldn't be as fulfilling.
</P>
<P>
   In the good ol' days, a team got to be No. 1 very simply _
enough media people had heard some rumor about it over drinks in
the hospitality room to vote it there.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with this complex formula guiding the future, every Tuesday
that they release the Bowl Championship Series standings is like
tax day. Some CPA juggles the numbers, and you either get a
pleasant surprise or take it in the neck.
</P>
<P>
   It has come to this: ``I've gotten a half-dozen calls from
mathematicians who said we had miscalculated the deviation,'' said
Charles Bloom, who handles media relations for both the SEC and the
BCS. So, this was the way to put academics back into college
football.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, adjusted deviation is not a White House strategy.
It's a device to mitigate the differences in the three computer
polls that are part of the BCS equation. And here we take one great
bit of comfort in the process _ computers never will get together
and take over the world, because they can't even agree on a No. 1
college football team. Three computer polls and currently three
different No. 1s: UCLA (Seattle Times), Kansas State (Sagarin) and
Florida State (New York Times). They're going to have to get
together and thrash this out over some frosted mugs of RAM.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, you are a Tennessee football fan, and you have so
many questions.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Times has a computer poll? That computer can't know
anything about college football. It's never even been to
Starkville.
</P>
<P>
   Let's get this straight _ I have to root for Florida? Well, as a
matter of fact, yes. No matter how many laws of nature that
violates. The better the Gators do from here, the better the Vols'
strength of schedule, an important aspect in the BCS standings.
</P>
<P>
   How safe is our position? Just keep the name Newt Gingrich in
mind.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't you just hate to be a Kansas State fan? Know there must
be one somewhere. The Wildcats currently are the unbeaten left out
of the national championship picture. They have to make up 1.26
points on the BCS No. 2, UCLA. What the hey does that mean? (Here
Bloom supplies a little perspective: ``That's the equivalent of 32
places in strength of schedule. Kansas State currently with the
79th-ranked schedule, plays Nebraska this weekend and can get a
sizable bump.'' Got that?)
</P>
<P>
   Remember when being No. 1 was a matter of opinion? Back when all
it required was a single index finger, convincingly raised?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 2154EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
