<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-AUBURN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bulldogs' defense has become source of concern, controversy
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ With three regular-season games left, Georgia has
a 6-2 record and a good shot at its second New Year's Day bowl game
in a row. Yet, Bulldogs coach Jim Donnan spent much of the past two
weeks addressing his team's lapses on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the different people that scrutinize your program
nowadays, with the talk shows and everything, it's just a lot more
prevalent to find out what's wrong with your team,'' Donnan said.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been two weeks of leisure for Georgia's players,
either. Instead of nursing various bumps and bruises, Donnan put
his team through two full-contact scrimmages at Sanford Stadium
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our tackling has been so poor that we really needed to go
live,'' Donnan said.
</P>
<P>
   As much progress as the No. 17 Bulldogs have made in their third
season under Donnan, the defense continues to be a concern,
especially its play in Georgia's biggest games. Under Donnan, the
Dogs are just 2-6 against the Big Three of Auburn, Florida and
Tennessee, with the opponents scoring an average of 35.6 points in
those contests.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's 38-7 loss to Florida in Jacksonville two weeks ago was
an especially bitter defeat for Donnan. While the offense gained
461 yards, Florida scored touchdowns on three of its first four
possessions in the opening quarter, putting Georgia in a hole it
couldn't claw out of. LSU and Kentucky also scored on three of
their first four series against the Dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the criticism has fallen on defensive coordinator Joe
Kines, in his fourth season at Georgia. The Bulldogs rank seventh
in the SEC in total defense, allowing 347.3 yards per game. Georgia
has been especially suspect against the run, surrendering 135.8
yards per contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of that criticism should be on me, not on the players,''
Kines said. ``That's going to happen during the course of the year.
But the only thing we're worried about right now is Auburn.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers, who host Georgia Saturday in a nationally televised
game, appear to be a good remedy for the Bulldogs. Auburn ranks
last in the SEC in total offense with only 263.2 yards per game,
including only 98 yards rushing. The Tigers have battled injuries
on the offensive line and are starting true freshman Gabe Gross at
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the Dogs faced in last year's Auburn game, when the
Tigers stunned then-No. 7 Georgia 45-34 in Sanford Stadium. Auburn
came into the game with one of the nation's worst running games,
gaining less than 50 yards on its previous 77 attempts. Yet, the
Tigers rushed for 159 yards and five touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's Coach Kines' fault,'' linebacker Dustin
Luckie said. ``We've got to go out and execute the game plan. When
we watch film, a lot of guys are lining up wrong and not doing
their assignments.''
</P>
<P>
   Some fans have complained about Kines' scheme, saying that it's
too much of a ``bend-but-don't-break'' approach. The Bulldogs tried
to pressure Florida quarterback Doug Johnson with seven blitzes in
the first 18 plays, while playing man-to-man coverage on a few
plays. But the Gators opened with a no-back set and five wideouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't expect them to be in no-back and running a no-huddle
offense,'' Luckie said. ``They caught us on our heels. We adjusted
late in the first period, but it was already 21-0. They kept
running the same four plays, but we couldn't stop them.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's problems on defense appear to start up front _ the
Bulldogs have just two sacks in the last two games. Defensive end
Marcus Stroud, a 6-foot-6, 297-pound sophomore, has the size and
speed of a dominating presence, but he has only 15 tackles. Seniors
Paul Snellings and Antonio Cochran, who have battled injuries, also
haven't been as productive as expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think our defensive line is as deep as some people
think,'' defensive line coach Rodney Garner said. ``We've got to
get some pressure. We've got to knock down the quarterback. We're
not going to sack them every time, but we've got to rattle them.''
</P>
<P>
   The linebackers generally have played well, but the secondary
has had some breakdowns. Junior free safety Larry Mann struggles in
man-to-man coverage, and strong safety Kirby Smart often is
criticized for his tackling ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's blown out of proportion a lot of times,'' Smart
said. ``It's just like baseball. If a guy hits .300, he's a
success, but at the same time he's a failure. Those guys (on
offense) are getting scholarships to break tackles, too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
