<SLUG> BC-FBN-BISHER-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Christian worthy of his name, on field and off
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Almost nothing about Bob Christian gives him away as a
football player. He's neither big nor tall, by pro standards. The
only player in the NFL who owns a dulcimer and can play it, also
the piano and the trumpet. One of the few players in the league who
needs no help changing a light bulb. He holds a degree in
electrical engineering. The only Atlanta Falcon ever cut by both
the Falcons and the London Monarchs. He has made it back to Suwanee
but never made it to Piccadilly Circus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a new camera and everything, ready to go, then they
called me in and cut me. That was a slap in the face,'' he said.
``You see, they trained at Orlando, then took the team to London.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons first drafted him in 1991, their last pick. Then cut
him at the round of 60 in preseason. Next came the Monarchs, and by
this time he began to wonder if there was a place for him in
football after Northwestern.
</P>
<P>
   ``During spring practice after my freshman season, our running
backs coach had told me he thought I could play in the NFL,'' he
said. ``That really gave me a boost. It became my goal,'' but here
he was, shot down twice, by one team that would finish 6-and-10 and
a migratory team from another continent. Then the Chicago Bears
called, and we get on with the story that led him to where he is
today, with the Falcons again, facing the San Francisco 49ers,
biggest game of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Christian is a throwback, to the day of the single-wing, when
the quarterback was the blocking back. He's a fullback who blocks.
That's his primary job. He came out of Northwestern a running back
who carried the ball 25-30 times a game. When he gets to run the
ball with the Falcons, it's stop-the-presses stuff. They do trust
him with it on passes now and then, and last week the screen pass
Chris Chandler threw to him set up the first touchdown against New
England.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can be dangerous when he gets his hands on the ball,'' Dan
Reeves said. ``He's as good a blocker as I've ever been around, but
he can do more than block.''
</P>
<P>
   Football computes about everything it does. No statistic is too
obscure to be logged, but somehow blocks got overlooked. No record
is kept of devastating blocks, killer blocks, pancake blocks. They
keep records on half-tackles, but the blocker who clears the track
goes unrecorded, except by the coach and the old blocker doing
analysis from the broadcast booth.
</P>
<P>
   To be a blocking back, you have to play without fear. ``It's
against human nature. You're bearing down on some guy as big as you
are, both going full speed. If you flinch, you lose. I put my faith
in God. I feel like He gives me the courage to do what I do, or I
wouldn't still be here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are the sixth stop he has made as a pro. The first
time, ``It was kind of crazy, as anyone who has ever played for
Jerry Glanville knows.'' Then the Monarchs. Then San Diego. Cut
again. Then the Bears, then to Carolina in the expansion draft,
then the Falcons again as a free agent. Here he fit into Reeves'
scheme and becomes a more important cog each passing week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I seem to be getting my hands on the ball more often, and
that's a thrill, but I knew my role was blocking, and I have to be
unselfish.''
</P>
<P>
   No pampered athlete here. He plays to serve, as he lives his
life. Last spring, he and some other athletes made a Christian
mission into South Africa and Zimbabwe, referring here to the
faith, not the family name.
</P>
<P>
   Blocking is no precise science. It has to be the nature of the
beast, to stick his head in a lion's den and hope to get it back.
Rare is the fan who has a full appreciation of it, unless it's in
full view. It's a life of sacrifice, but here's a man who has the
attitude for it, Christian the Christian.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
