</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-49ERS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Apparent mismatch pits the Falcons' pass defense vs. 49ers
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the ball was on its way, Falcons free safety
Eugene Robinson was yelling, ``Tip! Tip! Tip!'' In retrospect,
maybe he should have been screaming, ``Take cover.''
</P>
<P>
   That was pretty much the theme during the first half on Sept.
27, when the San Francisco 49ers took a 31-7 lead against Atlanta
en route to a 31-20 victory. The Falcons were talking about big
plays; the 49ers were making them.
</P>
<P>
   The second play of the game was the ugliest of all. Before the
fans had settled into their seats, future Hall of Fame quarterback
Steve Young threw 24 yards over the middle to future Hall of Fame
receiver Jerry Rice, who capitalized on several Atlanta mistakes to
score.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons cornerback Ronnie Bradford wasn't as deep as he should
have been in ``underneath'' coverage when Rice ran a slant from
Atlanta's right to left. Nickel back Juran Bolden was covering Rice
closely. Robinson slowed as he approached the play from behind,
figuring Bolden would tip the ball or knock it down.
</P>
<P>
   That assumption was the third Atlanta mistake in a span of about
1.5 seconds. Bolden didn't raise a hand, Rice caught the ball,
Robinson never touched him, and the resulting 66-yard touchdown
reception broke Atlanta's back.
</P>
<P>
   Young completed 20 of 27 passes for 266 yards and three
touchdowns in the first half, and the 49ers dominated.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons need to remember that game when they play the 49ers
on Sunday in the Georgia Dome for sole possession of first place in
the NFC West. Both teams are 7-2. The Falcons will place the NFL's
No. 29-ranked passing defense against the 49ers' top-ranked passing
offense. On paper, it's a mismatch.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Last time,) I did something that normally I wouldn't,''
Robinson said. ``Juran was in great position, so I played for the
tip. Next time, if I have a shot, I'm going to play for the hit,
not the interception. They came out playing so fast. We were
reeling the rest of the first half.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers' receiving corps of Rice, J.J. Stokes and Terrell
Owens and running back Garrison Hearst, who had a 65-yard screen
pass, ended up with 387 receiving yards.
</P>
<P>
   When Rice scored in the second quarter on a 26-yard pass down
the middle, Bolden again was in excellent position, but didn't make
a play. He was waived less than 48 hours after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't do a good job early in the game of making plays. We
were in position to make them, but we didn't,'' Atlanta secondary
coach Ron Meeks said. ``That's not good.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially against Young, 36, who scrambles as well as any
quarterback in the league to allow well-covered receivers extra
time to get open.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have a tough task against a 49ers receiving corps as
talented _ and big _ as Rice (6-foot-2, 196 pounds), Stokes (6-4,
223) and Owens (6-3, 217).
</P>
<P>
   Rice has 48 catches for 710 yards and five touchdowns; Owens has
40 catches for 613 yards and six touchdowns, and Stokes has 41
catches for 498 yards and six touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry Rice has just about all the attributes,'' Falcons
cornerback Ray Buchanan said. ``He might be lacking a little speed,
but he's still quick and elusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terrell Owens is more of a deep threat, running crossing
routes and things of that nature,'' Buchanan said. ``He's very
physical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then J.J. Stokes is more of a tall guy they just throw the
ball up to and let him make plays, especially in the red zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradford (5-10, 188), who missed the last two games with a
sprained knee, could play Sunday in a limited role. Starting
corners Buchanan (5-9, 195), Michael Booker (6-2, 203) and nickel
back Randy Fuller (5-10, 175) will be tested often.
</P>
<P>
   They'll need help from safeties Robinson (6-1, 197), William
White (5-10, 205), and Devin Bush (5-11, 210) _ and a steady pass
rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we play like we did last week, and knock receivers off
their routes, the only thing we might have problems with is Steve
Young scrambling,'' Buchanan said. ``Their entire offense is based
on timing, and the ball and the receiver arriving in a certain spot
at the same time. If you can throw the timing off, a lot of times
the play won't be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that simple against receivers who are good at beating
bump-and-run coverage, especially with the Young factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is to keep things in front of you and keep your
leverage (and balance),'' Meeks said. ``When you play San Francisco
and Steve Young, he's going to (scramble and) buy time for his
receivers. Our focus has to be on finishing the play. We have to
stay in coverage.'' ``Getting (Young) out of the pocket is big,''
Buchanan said. ``He can hurt you when he runs, but if he has time
to do whatever he wants, he can hurt you more.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said the key is to return to basics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to keep things simple,'' he said. ``We're not going to
worry as much about adjustments. We're just going to line up in
man-to-man, and say, `If you beat me, you beat me.' I think that's
how you eliminate all the confusion we had early in that game. We
were making too many adjustments (just before the play).
</P>
<P>
   ``And if something goes wrong, it takes a mature team to weather
the storm, instead of going, `Oh man, woe is me.' We didn't do that
last time.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
