<SLUG> BC-OLY-SKATE-BOBEK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOBEK QUALIFYING ATTEMPT TO TAKE PLACE IN SCOTTSDALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nicole Bobek, a five-time medalist at the U.S. Figure Skating
Championships, 1995 World bronze medalist and '98 Olympian, must
skate next month at the Pacific Coast Sectional in Scottsdale in
order to qualify for nationals.
</P>
<P>
   Because Bobek has not won an international medal since 1995,
missing by one place at Skate America two weeks ago, she is
required by the U.S. Figure Skating Association to go through a
sectional for the first time since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The top four finishers in senior, junior and novice divisions at
each of three sectionals plus automatic qualifiers advance to the
1999 U.S. Championships, Feb. 7-14 in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Bobek goes to the Pacific Coast Section because she represents
the Los Angeles Figure Skating Club, although she is training out
of Detroit and Richmond, Va., and her hometown is Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Coast meet is Dec. 6-12 at the Cellular One Ice Den,
which organizers said will seat 800 with portable bleachers. Bobek
is to skate Dec. 11-12. Tickets will be sold at the door but are
not currently available in advance.
</P>
<P>
   The senior ladies field also will include Amber Corwin (sixth at
1998 nationals), Sydne Vogel (ninth), Cohen Duncan (who withdrew
from nationals because of a hip injury) and Naomi Nari Nam (fourth
in juniors).
</P>
<P>
   Bobek, 21, and silver medalist Michelle Kwan, 18, opted to
remain eligible for international skating after the Nagano Olympics
rather than turn pro like gold medalist Tara Lipinski, 16.
</P>
<P>
   At 1998 nationals, Bobek completed five triples in her free
skate to beat out Tonia Kwiatkowski for an Olympic berth,
encouraging talk of an American sweep in Nagano.
</P>
<P>
   Lipinski and Kwan came through. Bobek, affected by a pre-Olympic
hip injury and bronchitis, missed all but one jump in her short and
long programs and placed 17th out of 24.
</P>
<P>
   Bobek then was an injury dropout from the World Championships in
Minneapolis and thought to be finished as an Olympic-eligible
skater. Instead, she again changed coaches and is working with
Richard Callaghan, who trained Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at it is that I've trained for 17 years and I'm
at least going to end my eligible career on a good note,'' Bobek
said before Skate America. ``I didn't want to leave it with the
Olympics. It's always been my goal since 1995 to win back my
national title. So right now I'm focusing on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobek's preparation for Skate America was marred by a training
accident at the Detroit Figure Skating Club when she ran into the
boards at full speed and was knocked unconscious and off the ice
for several days.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Coast senior men's field will include two-time
defending champion Michael Chack, who was the U.S. bronze medalist
in 1993 when nationals were held at America West Arena. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
