<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-VAUGHN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ALL UP TO VAUGHN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPLES, Fla. _ Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette, who has
increased the team's offer to Mo Vaughn, was hopeful Wednesday
night of bringing closure to the 18-month negotiations between the
team and its star slugger.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was Vaughn's to make as both the team and the free
agent first baseman's agents awaited word on how he wanted to
proceed.
</P>
<P>
   At midday, WednesdayDuquette denied a report by Channel 4's Bob
Lobel that the club had raised its five-year offer from $60 million
to $65 million. By Wednesday night, however, sources said Duquette,
who met twice with Vaughn's agents during the afternoon, increased
the team's offer to compete with the six-year, $72 million proposal
made last Friday by the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The average annual value of a five-year, $65 million deal would
be $13 million, which would match the industry ceiling set by Mets
catcher Mike Piazza when he signed a seven-year, $91 million
package.
</P>
<P>
   While saying he was not setting a deadline for Vaughn to make a
decision on the Sox offer, Duquette said he planned to leave the GM
meetings here Thursday morning, not to return to Boston but to meet
with prospective free agent signees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We owe it to our fans to present good players,'' Duquette
said, ``and there are a limited supply of good players.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette did not reveal his destination, but it was a clear
signal that he expected a definitive response from Vaughn.
Wednesday Duquette said he met twice with Vaughn's agents, Tom
Reich and Mark Gillam, and as he left for dinner with the Red Sox
contingent attending meetings here, he said he expected to have
further contact Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're about at that point where we're going to find out if
there's a deal,'' Duquette said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Sox ``were making progress on some issues important
to Mo Vaughn.''
</P>
<P>
   He reiterated that the Sox do not place no-trade provisions in
their contracts but questioned why that should be a deal-breaker
for Vaughn. He referred to the provision in baseball's Basic
Agreement that stipulates a player with 10 years of big league
service and at least five years with the same team has veto power
over any trade.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn will attain 10-5 status in another three seasons, he
noted. ``To me, it's not a big issue,'' Duquette said. ``If Mo
Vaughn wants to stay in Boston, he will be in charge of his career
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox' original offer, averaging $12 million a year, is
equal in annual value to the original proposal made to Vaughn by
the Angels, who were said to be willing to increase their offer if
it would expedite Vaughn's signing. For the moment, those are the
only two deals on the table for Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette was asked if the Red Sox might offer a sixth year as a
club option, meaning the team would have the right to decide
whether to exercise the option for an extra year or give Vaughn a
sizable buyout if it doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Structuring the contract in such a way would give the Red Sox
protection in the event Vaughn's skills eroded by the end of the
deal, while Vaughn would be assured of receiving at least some
compensation for not taking the guaranteed six years offered by
Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette did not answer the question directly, saying only that
some ``challenges'' remained to closing a deal.
</P>
<P>
   In other business, the Red Sox made a minor deal with Arizona
for righthanded pitcher Bob Wolcott, who made a brief splash three
years ago when he was a surprise Game 1 starter for Seattle in the
1995 American League Championship Series against Cleveland. Wolcott
won that game, but his career has spiraled downward since.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks took him in the second round of the expansion
draft last year, but Wolcott was unable to hold a spot in their
rotation, going 1-3 with a 7.09 ERA in six starts. Duquette said
the 25-year-old sinkerballer pitched well against the Sox, with a
career record of 4-1 and a 4.34 ERA, but even those numbers are
misleading.
</P>
<P>
   In his last two appearances against the Sox, Wolcott gave up 17
hits and 10 runs in just 8 2/3 innings. The Sox reportedly will
give up a pitcher from the lower minors in return.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox also officially lost lefthanded reliever Greg Swindell,
who signed a three-year contract for $5.7 million with Arizona. The
Red Sox had offered Swindell a two-year extension during the
season, but he turned it down.
</P>
<P>
   As a Class A free agent, Swindell, who cost the Sox three minor
leaguers in a trading deadline deal with Minnesota in July, will
net them an additional first-round sandwich pick as well as a
second-round choice in compensation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
