<SLUG> BC-HONDURAS-AID12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    M.E.D.I.C.O. heads up Honduras relief efforts
 &HT;    By Pamela LeBlanc
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GEORGETOWN, Texas _ The tables in the old cafeteria at
Southwestern University are hardly crowded now, but Mandy
Cleavinger wants to stack them high with boxes of food, clothing
and medicine for the victims of Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope we're bombarded,'' said Cleavinger, a 20-year-old
junior who is helping lead a student effort to assist people in
Honduras hit by the devastating October storm. ``If we're
bombarded, we can find people to help.''
</P>
<P>
   The students are part of a much larger relief effort, headed by
Georgetown-based Medical, Eye &AMP; Dental International Care
Organization Inc., or M.E.D.I.C.O., an independent non-profit
organization that since 1990 has sent medical supplies and teams of
doctors from around the country to rural Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   The agency is leading a Central Texas drive to collect donations
for the victims of the hurricane, which killed an estimated 10,000
people. Next week a DC3 aircraft loaded with up to 6,000 pounds of
goods gathered by M.E.D.I.C.O. is expected to depart Georgetown on
its way to San Pedro Sula, Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   Donations of all types are needed, from clothing, food and
medicine to bottled water, paper goods, blankets, insect repellent,
soap and money. As supplies arrive, students will sort, package,
label and weigh them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best description we've had was called in Friday,'' said
Norm Peters, co-founder of M.E.D.I.C.O. ``There are 400 children in
one refuge center without homes and more importantly without
parents. We'll lose a third of them within two weeks because of
lack of water and milk. . .Picture the Jarrell tornado and multiply
that by hundreds.''
</P>
<P>
   Packages of diapers, cartons of old shirts and sacks of rice and
beans are trickling into the old Commons Building at Southwestern,
which was vacated last month when the university opened its new
student center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have space, M.E.D.I.C.O. needed space. We have manpower,
M.E.D.I.C.O. needed manpower,'' said Ken Roberts, a professor of
economics and business at Southwestern who set up the arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Mitch formed as a storm on Oct. 22 and hit Central America with
hurricane winds three days later, causing massive floods and deadly
mudslides across Honduras, Nicaragua, El Salvador and Guatemala.
Since then, governments and aid organizations from around the world
have promised hundreds of millions of dollars in relief, ranging
from bags of beans to forgiveness of millions in foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, several groups, including the American Red Cross,
Salvation Army Disaster Relief, Catholic Charities, Honduran Unity
and El Buen Samaritano Episcopal Mission are collecting money and
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   M.E.D.I.C.O. board member Sandra Romero de Thompson of Austin,
whose family lives in Honduras, said the agency has been flooded
with phone calls and e-mails from people around the country who
want to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Help is going to be needed immediately and for many years to
come,'' she said. ``Just because the hurricane has left doesn't
mean the need isn't going to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials have said Mitch set back Honduras at least 50 years.
Dozens of roads and bridges were wiped out and hundreds of
thousands of people are homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to send teams down as we pull them
together,'' Peters said. ``We will do as much as we can afford to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   M.E.D.I.C.O. plans to send four doctors to Honduras next week,
and a boatload of supplies later this month. The agency works
directly with non-profit organizations in Honduras, including Save
the Children and the Lions Club.
</P>
<P>
   At Southwestern, collections will continue at the Commons
Building until Wednesday. The site is open 9 a.m. to 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts thinks the volunteers will get something out of the
experience. He said, ``It makes students realize that part of the
meaning of life is to help others.''
</P>
<P>
   This article includes material from The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
