u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENN-SCHOOL12-COX     11-11 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-SCHOOL12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Students begin to examine results from space shuttle experiment
By Dick Stanley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN MARCOS, Texas _ The only sound in Robert McLean's lab here
at Southwest Texas State University was the clicking of a
mechanical counter.
</P>
<P>
   Eight Texas primary and middle school students, so awestruck
that they spoke in whispers when they spoke at all, were making
history this week _ taking turns helping McLean, a professor of
biology, tally bacterial colonies grown last week aboard the space
shuttle Discovery.
</P>
<P>
   It was much more than show-and-tell, or even what the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration originally had intended:
simply a way to encourage young kids to consider science careers by
getting them involved in a space experiment.
</P>
<P>
   It had turned out that the students were helping hand NASA a
potential showstopper for interplanetary travel the first
scientific confirmation that bacterial biofilms, a
little-understood, multimillion-dollar problem on the ground, also
can occur in an orbiting shuttle's cabin.
</P>
<P>
   The slimy biofilms that clog water purification systems and
other industrial processes on Earth could jeopardize lengthy trips
to Mars, if a solution isn't found, by clogging water recycling
systems used for drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the only ones on Earth right now who know that biofilms
can form in space,'' McLean told the students from Travis Middle
School in Port Lavaca on the Gulf coast, and Scudder Primary School
and Bowen Intermediate School in Wimberley. ``That's the fun of
science.''
</P>
<P>
   McLean, a biofilm expert who volunteered the experiment when
NASA came looking for a way to get students involved in shuttle
research, wanted to use the shuttle's water recycling system for
the test. But NASA decided the experiment had to be flown in
equipment already approved for research.
</P>
<P>
   McLean, and his NASA co-investigator, biologist Marybeth Edeen,
hope to get a crack at the recycling system on a future flight.
</P>
<P>
   As the counting continued in McLean's lab, discovering hundreds
of bacteria colonies growing in each of more than 40 round, plastic
petri dishes flown aboard the Discovery with space hero John Glenn,
McLean was considering what he and Edeen have to do next.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead of them is tedious hours of counting, recounting and
measuring the bacteria, which would normally be carried aboard
spacecraft on crew bodies and equipment, to see if anything unusual
occurred in their growth in microgravity.
</P>
<P>
   McLean and other biofilm investigators long ago discovered that
the phenomena -- called plaque by dentists when the living films
form on teeth and cause cavities -- are made by slow-growing
communities and microcolonies of ordinary bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   So tenaciously do the colonies attach themselves to the surfaces
of things that, as any diligent toothbrusher knows, they are very
hard to dislodge.
</P>
<P>
   Putting one of the colonies on a glass slide under a microscope
attached to a desktop computer, McLean showed the students how the
colony looked when it was colored with a special stain to reveal
living (green) and dead (red) parts, and rotated in three
dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks real slimy,'' said Justin Franke, 13, from Port
Lavaca. Like the other Travis Middle School students, he wore a
black knit shirt with the words ``Slimy Biohunters'' on the pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slime is a pretty accurate description,'' McLean said. ``But
you can't just rinse them off. Even a brush can't always get at
them.''
</P>
<P>
   On the computer's video screen, the single bacterial colony,
grown during eight days of orbit around the Earth, looked like a
lumpy green cloud.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notice how the bacteria don't cover all the area,'' McLean
said. ``But they look completely normal. The whole thing is 30
microns thick. Each bacteria is about a micrometer long.''
</P>
<P>
   A micron, or a micrometer, is one millionth of a meter, which is
39.37 inches.
</P>
<P>
   A possible solution to NASA's biofilm problem, McLean said,
could be similar to one already used on the ground -- applying air
pressure of thousands of pounds per square to a spacecraft's water
recycling systems to blow the slime off the systems' filters.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what some people do now with water purification,''
McLean said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
