<SLUG> BC-WHOLE-FOODS-EARNINGS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Record sales in 1998 for Whole Foods
 &HT;    By R. Michelle Breyer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Whole Foods Market Inc. on Wednesday reported
record sales and earnings for fiscal 1998 _ the same day the
company's stock hit a 52-week low.
</P>
<P>
   ``By all standards of financial performance, fiscal year 1998
has been the greatest year in our company's history,'' said John
Mackey, Whole Foods chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Whole Foods, based in Austin, reported profit of $45.4 million,
$1.64 per share, a 70 percent increase from the previous year. The
profit was slightly higher than analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The company's fourth-quarter profit was $11.1 million, up 116
percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Results were released after the market closed Wednesday. Whole
Foods shares closed down $1.68 3/4 to $33.25 _ a 52-week low. More
than 3.3 million shares changed hands in heavier-than-normal Nasdaq
trading.
</P>
<P>
   Whole Foods reported annual sales of $1.39 billion, up 24
percent from a year ago. Fourth-quarter sales rose 21 percent to
$326.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Comparable-store sales _ one of the best indicators of a
company's financial health _ were up 11 percent for the year and
8.5 percent for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The fast-growing company _ the nation's largest chain of natural
foods supermarkets _ grew from 75 to 87 stores over the past year.
Leases have been signed for 10 new stores in such markets as
Winston-Salem, N.C., Baltimore, Md. and Minneapolis, Minn. The
company is currently developing 29 sites.
</P>
<P>
   The rumors are to be believed. The Nov. 16 issue of Business
Week quoted an analyst who said Whole Foods may be interested in
buying chief rival Wild Oats Markets Inc., which has 60 stores,
``for practical business considerations.'' Whole Foods has not
commented.
</P>
<P>
   Despite upbeat earnings over the past year and merger
speculation, Whole Foods stock has slid downward since hitting a
52-week high of $70.12 1/2 on March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Whole Foods' shares have been affected by a market that has been
inhospitable to companies in the ``healthy living sector.''
</P>
<P>
   In August, Whole Foods released its third-quarter earnings the
night before the stock market sell-off that resulted in the Dow
Jones industrial average's third-biggest point decline ever. It was
the same day that another industry giant, General Nutrition Cos.
(GNC), released its quarterly earnings and said it would slash
prices to fend off rising competition.
</P>
<P>
   Whole Foods stock plummeted more than $11 a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dietary supplement companies have been hit particularly hard,
and Whole Foods is being dragged down with them,'' said Steve
Hoffman, publisher of Natural Business, a Boulder-based trade
publication that tracks the natural foods industry.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Natural Business Composite Index'' _ which follows 70
publicly held companies in the natural and organic products
industry _ has fallen 31 percent this year. Just four months ago,
it was up 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street also has responded to the announcement last month
that Whole Food President Peter Roy would resign at the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six months ago (Whole Foods was) the darling of Wall Street,''
Hoffman said. ``Now, the industry is trying to emerge from a bear
market. Of all these companies, Whole Foods is one of the most
solid.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
