<SLUG> BC-ENTERTAINMENT-JOBS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWTH OF WORK SLOWS IN HOLLYWOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles County's entertainment industry has
slowed dramatically this year with job growth at its lowest level
since the 1992 recession, a forecaster says.
</P>
<P>
   Loss of production to Canada, a slowdown in big-budget feature
films and the threat of an actors' strike earlier this year were
the chief culprits, according to the Economic Development Corp. of
Los Angeles County.
</P>
<P>
   That means 2,600 new motion picture and television jobs will be
added by the end of the year, bringing the county's total
entertainment work force to 240,000. That's well off from the 1997
gain of 13,000 and the 94,500 jobs added in the 1993-97 period.
</P>
<P>
   ``The air went out of the balloon and now we're going through a
period of adjustment,'' Jack Kyser, chief economist with the
Economic Development Corp. said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This happens to a lot of industries when you have rapid
growth. So there's no sense of panic when you talk to people in the
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyser believes the industry will see a moderate rebound next
year with 7,000 to 8,000 new jobs _ still far short of the gain
last year and minuscule compared with a rise of nearly 30,000
entertainment jobs in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But the gain ranks well above the darkest days of the early '90s
recession, culminating in a loss of more than 10,000 jobs during
1992 as producers deserted Hollywood for lower-cost locations
outside California.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which is part of the EDC's semiannual forecast for
the county, comes on the heels of last week's disclosure of sharp
declines in production outside studio lots. Year-to-date off-lot
location production was off 5.6 percent for the first 10 months of
1998 after rising by 78 percent between 1994 and 1997, according to
the Entertainment Industry Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign of sluggishness, Woodland Hills-based Panavision
Inc. reported Wednesday a third-quarter loss of $700,000 compared
with profits of $7.6 million in the 1997 period while revenues for
the movie-camera specialist slid to $50.7 million from $55.8
million.
</P>
<P>
   Panavision had warned previously that results would be hurt by
softness in production of large-budget action films by major
studios.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
