<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0506 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6236 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UT-ART-COLLECTION12-C     11-11 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UT-ART-COLLECTION12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UT acquires art collection worth $35 million
 &HT;    By Michael Barnes
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Filling a void in the regional arts scene, the
University of Texas is acquiring a one-of-kind collection of Old
Masters paintings and drawings valued at nearly $35 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The art collection is a very big deal,'' said UT President
Larry R. Faulkner, who personally intervened to secure the
Suida-Manning Collection for UT's Blanton Museum of Art. ``This is
a great day in the cultural life of the university, the state of
Texas and the art community.''
</P>
<P>
   UT is expected to announce today it will obtain _ through gift
and purchase _ the prized collection of more than 700 artworks from
the Renaissance through the Rococo periods in Europe. Originally
assembled in Italy by art historian William Suida, the son of
Austrian textile manufacturers, the collection was later expanded
by his daughter, Bertina Suida Manning, and her husband, Robert
Manning, art historians as well.
</P>
<P>
   Born in tiny Mart, near Waco, Robert Manning, who lived most of
his life in New York and died in 1996, wanted the collection to
remain intact for display in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was of the utmost importance that it be kept together,''
said his heir, Alessandra Manning Dolnier, who arrived in Austin
Tuesday from their home in Connecticut. ``And my father wanted it
to end up in his home state.''
</P>
<P>
   To be unveiled at the Blanton in March, some of the
Suida-Manning Collection is now in storage, but other paintings
currently hang on the walls of New York's Metropolitan Museum of
Art and Vassar College's Lehman Loeb Art Center in Poughkeepsie,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The collection rings with the familiar names of the masters:
Rubens, Poussin, Tiepolo, Veronese, Boucher, Fragonard, Lorrain and
Correggio. It ranges from 14th-century Italian paintings to late
18th-century French drawings, with significant holdings of Italian,
French and German art. Certain Baroque masterpieces, such as
Giovanni Guercino's ``Landscape with Tobias and the Angel,'' were
actively sought by the nation's wealthiest musuems, such as the
Metropolitan Museum of Art and California's Getty Museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an absolute triumph for UT,'' said George Wachter, Old
Masters expert for Sotheby's auction house in New York. ``There is
nothing like it in private hands. There are several museums that
will be upset that they won't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas museum experts, some of whom lobbied for the collection,
agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major addition to the cultural resources of the
whole region,'' said Edmund Pillsbury, former director of Fort
Worth's Kimbell Art Museum, which houses the state's best gathering
of pre-1800 paintings. ``This is the sort of collection you just
can't put together on the open market.''
</P>
<P>
   Why did UT, with signficant holdings in prints, drawings, Latin
American and American art, but very few Old Masters, get the nod?
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that the university would be a more dynamic home for
the collection,'' said Dolnier, who trained as an art historian and
is now an interior designer. ``It is very cohesive, so it works
together beautifully in a teaching sense.''
</P>
<P>
   The collection does not come without more work to be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wonderful opportunity, but it's also a wonderful
challenge,'' said Blanton director Jessie Otto Hite. ``We have to
get the collection here, and figure out how to store it properly,
make sure we have adequate space for it in the new building and
security.''
</P>
<P>
   At least $37 million has been raised for a new museum structure,
slated to open in 2002 at the corner of Speedway and Martin Luther
King Boulevard. UT is seeking $10 million more to construct and
endow what it sees as a landmark building.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the matter of $20 million for UT's part of the
Suida-Manning acquisition deal. Three anonymous patrons have given
$4.75 million toward obtaining the collection, but the university
will need to raise the rest of the sum. Dolnier and her husband,
Kurt, a commercial photographer, are donating the remaining value
of the collection, which Sotheby's assessed at between $30 million
and $35 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``This collection transforms this museum completely,'' said
Blanton curator Jonathan Bober. ``This puts us on par with the
Menil Collection (in Houston) and the Kimbell as a very carefully
defined collections-based art museum going into an exemplary
facility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The boon to the study of art history on campus is
phenomenal,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Austin arts leaders expressed delight over the impending arrival
of the Old Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fabulous news because it is in an area (of art) not
available in Austin,'' said Elizabeth Ferrer, director of the
Austin Museum of Art. ``This will round out the UT collection and
give it a very strong historical foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   Blanton director Hite hopes the acquisition attracts more
donations, perhaps in other neglected areas, such as 19th-century
art.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't see these paintings without going to major
museums, not just in this country, but in Europe,'' Hite said.
``This will be an opportunity for everyone in Austin to take an
arts trip abroad, and for free.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
