<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0510 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6241 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UT-REGENTS12-COX     11-11 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UT-REGENTS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UT regents expected to OK health center in Rio Grande Valley
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Approving a plan they called historic, University of
Texas System regents agreed Wednesday toinject $50 million into
medical education, research, and public health programs in the Rio
Grande Valley, a region marked by poverty and high rates of
tuberculosis, diabetes and childhood diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The amount is $20 million more than the Legislature set aside
for the UT System to create a Regional Academic Health Center in
the four-county lower Rio Grande Valley. Harlingen beat out McAllen
and Brownsville for the center in a fierce competition, but the
added money will give the two losing cities and Edinburg their own
medical projects.
</P>
<P>
   The $20 million will come from the Permanent University Fund,
which mainly finances construction projects at 17 schools in the UT
and Texas A&AMP;M University systems. UT-Austin president Larry
Faulkner said he supported the Valley initiative and did not expect
his campus to suffer financially.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Eddie Lucio, the Brownsville Democrat who carried the
health center legislation, said he couldn't be happier to see his
region get a share of the coveted money.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is extremely historical and I'm pleased to be here to be
a part of it,'' he told the board of regents. ``This issue really
is about fairness, about equity for all Texans . . .I think you've
proven today that you care, that you care for people all over the
state, including the Rio Grande Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   The regents voted to spend $25 million rather than $30 million
to build the center in Harlingen for educating third- and
forth-year medical students and training medical residents. The
regents also put $15 million into building a medical research
facility at UT Pan American in Edinburg, $5 million for a public
health program at UT Brownsville and $5 million for a medical
education building in McAllen.
</P>
<P>
   The regents will ask the Legislature to earmark $5 million from
a huge tobacco industry lawsuit settlement to add to the public
health program at Brownsville. And they specified that McAllen will
have to come up with $5 million in matching money for its program.
</P>
<P>
   The regents cautioned that the projects would be doomed if the
Valley cities fail to negotiate acceptable contracts and land
donations for the new buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take a united effort behind it,'' said board
chairman Don Evans of Midland.
</P>
<P>
   Regent Tony Sanchez of Laredo, who was heavily involved in the
negotiations, said he did not expect any major problems.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if spreading the wealth was an attempt to make everyone
happy, Sanchez said not everyone was pleased, nor was that the
goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the cities competed fiercely. . .I felt all along
that it was important to establish the framework for a Regional
Academic Health Center which would include the entire Valley,'' he
said. ``This is going to be the first medical research division of
any medical school along the U.S.-Mexican border from San Diego to
Brownsville.''
</P>
<P>
   It will probably take about two years to build the center in
Harlingen, which is expected to create 300 to 400 jobs, Sanchez
said. The projects are expected to attract pharmeucetical
companies, medical suppliers and other health care industries to
the Valley, in addition to bringing new health care practioners.
</P>
<P>
   The economic impact of the projects is not known, but a previous
study estimated that the center alone could generate as much as
$100 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Some local doctors, fearing competition from the center,
objected and said they saw the center as a ``predator of private
practices.''
</P>
<P>
   Harlingen attorney Randy Whittington, president of the
foundation that was created to aide the Valley in its quest for the
health center, said he thought the doctors' concerns were subsiding
and expected the losing cities to be on board as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is absolutely fantastic,'' Whittington said. ``What the
university has done today has changed the entire complexion of
higher education, particularly medical education, and health care
in the Rio Grande Valley from here on out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is really a once in a . . . forever opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The regents delayed a decision on where to build the health
center in August, saying they wanted the cities to refine their
proposals. Kaludis Consulting Group of Washington, D.C., hired to
evaluate the plans had recommended Harlingen as the site.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
