symbol of erotic love, embodying both the female and male elements.
Since the fourth century, when Xie Lingyun, a poet, described one
blooming in the wild, they have found their way into Chinese
poetry, ceramics and paintings. Emperors grew them in their palace
gardens as early as the sixth century, and they have long been
associated with wealth and nobility. ( Carl Labianca/New York Times
Photo)
