<HEADER>
A6244 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCAM-CASE-CRACK12-COX     11-11 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCAM-CASE-CRACK12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Investigator cracks case of master scam artist
 &HT;    By Jason Spencer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Charles Kelvin Smith was a lot of things to a
lot of people.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, law officers say, Smith was a lot of people.
</P>
<P>
   A world-champion bull rider and celebrity mullett-tosser named
Dusty Rhodes, an Episcopal priest named Jeremiah Micah Rhodes IV, a
motor home dealer named Daniel David Johnston _ all were Smith,
police say.
</P>
<P>
   They should know. The FBI and agencies in five states have
warrants for his arrest, and with the help of a Williamson County
deputy sheriff and a rodeo association that had made a project of
catching Smith, he is now in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Arkansas state police and U.S. Marshals,
working on a tip from a confidential informant, arrested the
45-year-old high roller from Baton Rouge, La., on charges he faked
his identity to swindle expensive boats and vehicles from
Jollyville to Tennessee. A Williamson County investigator, Sgt.
Jerry Worrell, helped crack the case after a local man identified
Smith as the person who used a counterfeit certified check to steal
his $176,000 motor home in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe he has done a similar scam in numerous states _
about every state in Dixie,'' Worrell said. Worrell has been
tracking Smith since he visited the Austin area earlier this year,
allegedly posing as Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was arrested Monday night at a liquor store after officers
spotted him at a Little Rock-area RV park, Worrell said.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer who has represented Smith, David Mooney of Baton Rouge,
said he is unfamiliar with any evidence the police have against his
client.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have heard lots of those stories from the police. I know
nothing about it,'' Mooney said. ``I know of no facts to
substantiate the charges the police have told me have been made
against him. . .This is something any attorney would say about any
client.''
</P>
<P>
   Mooney said he recently represented Smith in a sales tax dispute
with the state of Louisiana, which claimed Smith owed the state
about $25,000. With Smith now in police custody, Worrell and other
investigators from throughout the Southeast plan to interview the
alleged scam artist who Worrell said is wanted by authorities in
Texas, Louisiana, Mississippi, Arkansas, Tennessee and the FBI.
Smith's arrest warrants include a felony forgery charge out of
Jefferson Parish, La. and a parole violation with the U.S. Marshals
Service. In Tennessee, Smith is accused of stealing a motor home
worth $240,000, Worrell said and in the North Texas city of
Cleburne Smith allegedly stole a high-dollar boat.
</P>
<P>
   Catching Smith became a near obsession for Worrell, who
contemplated calling the America's Most Wanted television program
about the fugitive only a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just took it as a personal challenge,'' Worrell said. ``I
knew if I kept after him awhile I'd catch him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting to this point was very difficult because the guy kept
changing his identification. We just kept pounding,'' Worrell said.
</P>
<P>
   Police believe Smith used the motor homes to travel the South
posing as a Professional Rodeo Cowboys Association (PRCA) world
champion bull rider named Dusty Rhodes.
</P>
<P>
   PRCA officials in Colorado Springs, Colo., said Wednesday they
have been aware of Smith's claim to the bull riding title for some
time and have been passing tips on to police each time the
pseudo-cowboy blows into a small southern town in his flashy tour
bus to hand out glossy autographed photographs and rub elbows with
local big wigs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not one of our world champions,'' said Kay Bleakly, PRCA
director of rodeo administration. ``We know about him because he's
popped up all year long. We've been working with law enforcement
agencies and giving them information.''
</P>
<P>
   It was at one of Smith's stops last summer near the
Florida-Alabama border that Charlotte Paterson met the flamboyant
bull rider while vacationing on the Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Sporting a neck brace and a colorful ``Garth Brooks-type''
button-down western shirt, Smith told her he was recently injured
in a bull riding accident. Large letters splashed across the motor
home proclaimed the man inside was Dusty Rhodes, ``world champion
bull rider,'' said Paterson, who lives in Fairhope, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   The pair dated about two months, and in that time the Orange
Beach, Ala. community embraced Smith as a celebrity, Paterson said.
A local bar called the Flori-Bama, which Paterson described as
being ``like a Gilly's in Texas,'' invited Smith to participate in
their popular mullet-tossing contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw the first one out,'' Paterson said. Such fish hurling
honors are typically given to big-time celebrities, she said _
``People like Ken Stabler and Dale Earnhardt; those kinds of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith helped organize a miniature rodeo to benefit children with
disabilities in Gulf Shores, Ala., where he signed autographs and
posed for pictures, Paterson said.
</P>
<P>
   About that same time, while dining at a Waffle House restaurant,
Smith showed her an Arkansas identification card with a picture of
himself wearing glasses and a priest's collar. The name on the card
was Jeremiah Micah Rhodes IV, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he was an Episcopal priest,'' Paterson said.
</P>
<P>
   Paterson said she began questioning the cowboy's identity when
she noticed discrepancies in the myriad stories he would tell her
about his exploits in riding competitions. She and a friend checked
with the PRCA, and were told the cowboy they had met was most
likely an impostor, Paterson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was like a little kid with costumes,'' she said. ``I just
kept thinking this guy has never been on a pony before.''
</P>
<P>
   Paterson said the relationship ended in late July when Smith
told her he was leaving town to pick up a new touring bus. She
hasn't seen him since.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
