<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-FUGITIVE-930&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSISTENT MEXICAN AGENT FINALLY LANDS HIS MAN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Calif., Colo.)   (jw) 
 By JULIA PRESTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ It began as one Mexican detective's dogged but
lonely search for an elusive banker who was wanted on 21 charges of
financial fraud amounting to at least $170 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the four-year international manhunt for the banker, Carlos
Cabal Peniche, finally succeeded, Mexican officials said, after top
American authorities recently decided to pitch in.
</P>
<P>
   Cabal, who was on the short list of men most wanted by Mexican
justice, was arrested on Tuesday afternoon at his tree-shaded
beach-front mansion in Melbourne, Australia, where he had been
living with his family for about a year posing as a merchant from
the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials moved Wednesday to seek his extradition.
</P>
<P>
   Cabal's capture gives a boost to cross-border cooperation
against crime, which faltered earlier this year after U.S. Customs
disclosed that it had conducted an undercover money-laundering
investigation of Mexican banks without informing Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials said that Attorney General Janet Reno gave new
support to the pursuit of Cabal after Mexican investigations turned
up signs that he was running a secret financial empire that reached
to the Caribbean, South America and Asia with a major base of
operations in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest of Cabal, 41, was a political success in the short
term for the Mexican government's financial officials, who have
been accused by the opposition of protecting corrupt bankers. But
if he is brought back to Mexico for trial, Cabal could add
explosive new fuel to several scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Bank documents recently unearthed by opposition leaders in
Congress show that he contributed at least $14 million during the
1994 election campaign to the political party that brought
President Ernesto Zedillo to power. And Raul Salinas de Gortari,
who is a brother of the former president and is under investigation
on suspicion of narcotics money-laundering, used accounts in
Cabal's banks to make secret transfers of at least $67 million,
according to an investigation by the police in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Cabal had a meteoric rise from a small-time shrimp exporter to
one of Mexico's wealthiest and most prominent financiers during the
presidency of Carlos Salinas de Gortari. The Salinas government
sold him two banks, Banca Cremi and Banca Union, and Salinas once
singled him out as a model Mexican business executive.
</P>
<P>
   Through his banks Cabal started agricultural businesses across
the Yucatan peninsula. In 1992, he organized a group of Mexican
agribusiness families to help him buy the Florida-based Fresh Del
Monte Produce Co., one of the world's largest fresh food companies,
for $535 million. Cabal also tried to close a $1 billion deal to
buy another branch of Del Monte in 1994, but it fell through when
he was indicted for fraud in Mexico and fled.
</P>
<P>
   In his heyday, Cabal moved to the center of power in Mexico,
hobnobbing with President Salinas and top leaders of the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, whose dominion over Mexico was
then unchallenged.
</P>
<P>
   A federal investigation revealed that Cabal had set up a fund in
1994 to channel $4.5 million in illegal funds to the gubernatorial
campaign of a PRI candidate, Roberto Madrazo, a friend of his.
</P>
<P>
   The federal inquiry showed that Madrazo had spent more than 30
times the legal limit to win that race, although the case was
dismissed two years later on a technicality.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican regulators charged in 1994 that Cabal lent hundreds of
millions to himself from his banks through a network of phantom
companies he set up.
</P>
<P>
   Standing eye-to-eye with Cabal as Australian police officers
took him prisoner was Juan Miguel Ponce Edmonson, head of the
Mexican branch of Interpol, the agency that links federal police
forces around the world. Ponce had made it a personal mission to
track down Cabal, but for years he felt he was getting indifferent
treatment from the American authorities.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from Melbourne on Wednesday, Ponce said
he could not help but smile when Cabal, his hair now gray and his
face slightly disguised with a close-trimmed goatee, opened his
door to the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was joyful, joyful,'' Ponce said.
</P>
<P>
   Ponce was able to crack the case after American authorities
started to help monitor Cabal's movements in earnest about four
months ago. That produced a pattern of information that always
seemed to lead back to Australia, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Ponce contacted the Australian police three weeks
ago, they turned up the immigration documents of a Dominican man
who nominally ran a business importing Italian wines but seemed to
be an intermediary for Cabal. Ponce noticed that the Dominican had
given the same birth date as the fugitive financier.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I said I have to see this guy's face,'' Ponce
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ponce said he had noted ``a radical change of attitude in the
American bureaucracy'' after Mexican Attorney General Jorge Madrazo
provided his American counterpart with details of ``the enormous
network Cabal had in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Cabal was able to elude capture for so long because he had
enough cash to buy false documents for himself, his wife and four
children from several countries, and to set himself up in regal
style wherever he settled. In 1995 Ponce just missed nabbing Cabal
at a 12-bedroom mansion in a Madrid suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Cabal continued to travel regularly to the United States
throughout his years as a fugitive, Mexican officials said. His
most recent trip ended when he left Los Angeles on Aug. 24.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   FBI agents discovered that Cabal owns a mansion in the ski
resort of Aspen, Colo., which he put up for sale for $12 million.
Mexican officials said they were working with the FBI &UR;  &LR;  to obtain a
search and seizure warrant for the home.
</P>
<P>
   In his absence from Mexico, Cabal became a central figure in the
scandal surrounding the privatization of the Mexican banks in the
early 1990s and their $65 billion bailout by the government in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   His downfall and flight caused many Mexicans to wonder why the
government sold him two banks in the first place. The sales were
handled by a committee headed by Guillermo Ortiz, a widely
respected economist who was Zedillo's first finance minister and is
now head of Banco de Mexico, the central bank. In recent weeks
opposition lawmakers have mounted a campaign to force Ortiz to
resign.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz has said that his committee was forced to make decisions
about the sales of state-owned banks based on limited information
that was available at the time under Mexican law about potential
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition lawmakers in the Mexican Congress have also charged
that the government spent vast sums of taxpayer money to pay for
the corrupt loans in Cabal's banks. Government regulators seized
Cabal's banks in 1994. They sold the healthy part of Banca Cremi in
1996 to Banco Bilbao-Vizcaya, a Spanish bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
