r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-FRENCH-COLUMN-LAD     11-11 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-FRENCH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZAMBRANO'S CONFIRMATION GOOD NEWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's difficult to blame the Galaxy's new owners for taking the
time to review every aspect of the club Coach Octavio Zambrano
included before determining what would stay and what would go.
That's how Philip F. Anschutz and his deputies do business, and
it's been a successful method.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Zambrano should have been confirmed as coach the
moment Anschutz took possession of the Galaxy last month. That
confirmation didn't arrive until Monday, but its sweep was such
that President Tim Leiweke acknowledged he no longer is seeking a
GM who'd be the team's director of player personnel, merely one who
would handle the team's business operations, deal with Major League
Soccer officials, and provide a bridge between the soccer side of
the organization and the suits in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano's record 24-8, with an MLS-record 85 goals scored an a
league-low 44 allowed his eye for talent (think Clint Mathis, Joe
Franchino, etc.) and the vibrant style his team exhibited was
evidence enough that he should remain in charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great news, tremendous news,'' said Galaxy captain Dan
Calichman, who downplayed reports of players' discontent with
Zambrano. ``You can't blame him for the year we had (not reaching
the final); you can only congratulate him.''
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of talk in the past few weeks about players'
unhappiness, including some that several players including some of
the team's most important had told Leiweke that they'd prefer
Zambrano not return. Leiweke admitted there were ``concerns'' about
Zambrano, but they weren't strong enough to force him out.
</P>
<P>
   Calichman swears there are no troubles between Zambrano and his
players. ``A lot's been said about Octavio, and 90 percent of it
has been positive with only 10 percent, maybe, negative,'' he said.
``That's a pretty good ratio. ... All the players realize the grass
isn't always greener (elsewhere). Listen, he does a good job, and
this is a great decision.''
</P>
<P>
   CORNER KICKS
</P>
<P>
   Southern California's favorite club sorry, Galaxy will be
playing for a trophy tonight in L.A.: Guadalajara takes on
Argentina's Gimnasia y Esgrima in the Coliseum Cup final at the
Coliseum at 8.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy forward Cobi Jones, D.C. United defender Eddie Pope and
Leicester City goalkeeper Kasey Keller are finalists for the 1998
Honda Player of the Year award, which will be presented Dec. 14 in
Los Angeles. Pope won the award American soccer's greatest honor
last year, and Keller is one of the top three for the third
successive year. Jones, the top American in MLS this year, is a
first-time finalist.
</P>
<P>
   Jones and Mathis will be wearing San Jose Clash uniforms Nov.18,
supplementing their rival's roster for an exhibition against
Mexican champion Toluca.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. national team's 1999 schedule is far from settled, what
with FIFA now considering moving the eight-nation Confederations
Cup scheduled Jan. 8-20 in Guadalajara and Mexico City back to
August. It's a move the Mexicans suggested after World Cup champ
France pulled out because its best players, competing in Europe's
top leagues, wouldn't be available for the event. Neither would
Brazil's, and so a switch to August would enable both to compete
with first-rate rosters. If the tournament is delayed, the
Americans will make their debut Feb.6 against Germany in
Jacksonville. The Germans will play Colombia on Feb. 9 in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Arena's final assignment as D.C. United coach begins Saturday at
RFK Stadium when his soon-to-be-former club, the reigning CONCACAF
champions, takes on South American titlist Vasco da Gama of Brazil
in the first leg of the Interamerican Cup. The second leg Arena's
D.C. finale will be Dec.5 in Ft. Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
   USC's women's soccer team takes a seven-game winning streak into
its NCAA Tournament debut this afternoon at the Coliseum, but the
Women of Troy (13-6-1) must wage battle against Washington (10-8-1)
without All-American Kim Clark
</P>
<P>
   (10 goals, 6 assists), who suffered a broken right leg in USC's
win 10 days ago over UCLA. USC is led by forwards Isabelle Harvey
(8 goals, 11 assists) and Courtney Barham (7, 4).
</P>
<P>
   Also in the postseason are UCLA's women (at home vs. Stanford or
Brigham Young on Saturday), Cal State Dominguez Hills' women
(Division II, at Sonoma State on Saturday), and Chapman's men
(Division III, at Cal Lutheran today).
</P>
<P>
   Former Mayfair High standout (and valedictorian) Dolores
Browning wrapped up a phenomenal career at Cal State Fullerton last
weekend in possession of every significant Titan offensive record,
single-season and career. In four years, Browning netted 61 goals
and dished out 18 assists for 140 points all Titan bests. She owned
the goal and point record by the end of her freshman season she got
the assist mark this year and has 37 more goals and 89 more points
than Amber Dickey, No.2 on both lists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
