<P>
   (NYT31) FORT WORTH, Texas -- Nov. 11, 1998 -- WRIGHT-INTERVIEW,
11-11 -- Former Speaker Jim Wright, a Democrat, resigned the
Speakership in 1989 after an ethics investigation initiated by Newt
Gingrich, who announced last week that he was resigning as Speaker
and leaving the House. On Gingrich's resignation, Wright says, ``It
would ill become me to gloat or to say, 'I'm glad you're gone, you
rascal, you.''' (Mark Perlstein/New York Times Photo) (NYT30)
MARIETTA, Ga. -- Nov. 11, 1998 -- INDIA-CRIME, 11-11 -- Arun
Gawali, identified by the police as one of Bombay's leading
gangsters, says he has reformed and now emulates Gandhi and Nehru.
``This part of my life I have dedicated to God,'' he said solemnly,
``and to my guru, Brahama Devi Prajapita.'' But police say this
sinner's declared reformation is a hoax. (Celia W. Dugger/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) WORCESTER, Mass. -- Nov. 11, 1998 -- SCI-CELL-FARMING,
11-11 -- From left: Michael West, Jose Cibella and Jim Robl, work
in a lab at Advanced Cell Technology in Worcester. Venturing deep
into uncharted realms of ethics and medicine, the small
biotechnology company said Wednesday that its scientists had for
the first time made human cells revert to the primordial, embryonic
state from which all other cells develop, by fusing them with cow
eggs and creating a hybrid cell (Rick Friedman/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) MARIETTA, Ga. -- Nov. 11, 1998 -- GA-NEWT-DISTRICT,
11-11 -- Johnny Isakson, 53, the chairman of the state school board
and a fixture in state Republican politics, announcing his
candidacy for Speaker Newt Gingrich's House seat. Isakson instantly
became the presumptive front-runner. Gingrich announced last Friday
that he would step down from the speakership and resign his House
seat because of Republican losses in last week's elections.
Isakson's daughter Julie is at right. (Alan S. Weiner/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) ST. MARY'S, Kan. -- Nov. 11, 1998 --
KANSAS-TRIAL-TOWN-2, 11-11 -- Leo and Denise Petit have a family of
ten children including their eldest, Heather Petit, right, and are
active in the St Mary's Academy and College. In 1995, amid rumors
of anti-government militias and hidden caches of guns, Federal and
state agents combed St. Mary's and its surroundings for links to
Timothy J. McVeigh and Terry L. Nichols, who had traveled in the
area just before the Oklahoma City bombing. (Todd Buchanan/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) ST. MARY'S, Kan. -- Nov. 11, 1998 --
KANSAS-TRIAL-TOWN-1, 11-11 -- Charles Ronnau has been farming the
land around St. Mary's all his life. In 1995, amid rumors of
anti-government militias and hidden caches of guns, Federal and
state agents combed St. Mary's and its surroundings for links to
Timothy J. McVeigh and Terry L. Nichols, who had traveled in the
area just before the Oklahoma City bombing. (Todd Buchanan/New York
Times Photo)
