<P>
   (NYT22) BOSTON -- Nov. 11, 1998 -- INNOVATIVE-MANAGER-BOS, 11-11
-- Fred Kobrick, president of Kobrick Capital Management, manages
money from his Boston office. Having struck out on his own last
year with Kobrick Cendant Funds and Kobrick Capital Management, his
mutual fund and hedge fund firms, Kobrick is among a new breed of
independent stock-pickers staking fresh ground in the heart of
America's fund industry. (Pam Berry/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) BOSTON -- Nov. 11, 1998 -- HAITI-CONSUL-BOS, 11-11 --
Andrine Constant, the new Haitian Consul General, oversees the
packing and shipping of relief goods to be sent to Haiti in the
aftermath of Hurricane Georges. Since her appointment last month,
an onslaught of demands has kept Ms. Constant focused on the
immediate, pressing needs of Haitians at home and in Massachusetts,
which has the third-largest population of Haitians in the United
States. (Pam Berry/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NORTHAMPTON, England -- Nov. 11, 1998 --
BRITAIN-CREDITCARDS, 11-11 -- a remarkable American invasion of the
credit card industry in Britain that has left big British credit
card issuers smarting. ``It's a battleground,'' acknowledged John
Eaton, the managing director of Barclaycard. The company is still
the dominant issuer of cards in Britain, but its share of the
market there has fallen to 31 percent last year from 37. (Jonathan
Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) SEOUL, South Korea -- Nov. 11, 1998 --
KOREA-ECONOMY-COX, 11-11 -- Tents pitched by the homeless fill up
an area in Sosomun Park in Seoul. South Korea is not a scene of
starvation and rampant poverty. It is the story of a proud and new
middle class suddenly gutted. A one-time ``Asian tiger,'' this
country has been deeply injured by the Asian economic crisis.
(Marcia Kunstel/Cox News Serive Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) TOKYO, Japan -- Nov. 11, 1998 -- JAPAN-ECONOMY-COX,
11-11 -- Clerks stand around waiting for customers in the furniture
department at the Takashimaya department store in Tokyo. Japan's
biggest store used to bustle on the weekend, but lately nobody is
buying. The sales slump is one symptom of how the Asian economic
crisis has spread. (Marcia Kunstel/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) BEIJING, China -- Nov. 11, 1998 -- CHINA-ECONOMY-COX,
11-11 -- Vendors wait for customers at the ``Russian Market'' in
Beijing. The stalls at the market are bulging with goods. The only
thing lacking are the Russian buyers, who used to come here and buy
hundreds of jackets, hats, gloves, and other items and take them
back to Russia in order to sell them. The sales slump in the
open-air market is one symptom of how the Asian economic crisis has
spread. (Marcia Kunstel/Cox News Serive Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) KIARA PAYUNG, Indonesia -- Nov. 11, 1998 --
INDONESIA-ECONOMY-COX, 11-11 -- In the long run, one of the most
devastating impacts of the Asian economic crisis is that it has
forced millions of parents to withdraw their children from school.
In this village, two of the forced dropouts are Supendi, 13, left,
and Abadnurdin, 8, both of whom have been forced to stop going to
school because their parents couldn't afford to pay the school fees
of 40 cents a month. (Joseph P. Albright/Cox News Serive Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) JAKARTA, Indonesia -- Nov. 11, 1998 -- ASIA-SUMMIT-COX,
11-11 -- As the Asian economic crisis drives tens of millions of
Indonesians into poverty, hundreds of families have been reduced to
hunting through the Jakarta municipal garbage dump for metal,
plastic or anything else they can sell to buy a little food. The
dump is located in Jakarta's eastern suburb of Bekasi, about 15
miles from the city center where riots occured last May. (Joseph P.
Albright/Cox News Serive Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) MIAPUR, Bangladesh -- Nov. 11, 1998 --
BANGLADESH-WATER-4, 11-11 -- Salim Uddin Mondal, father of seven,
pumps water from his tube well, despite government tests that
showed it was contaminated with arsenic. Bangladesh is in the midst
of what some experts say could be the biggest mass poisoning in
history. Dangerous levels of arsenic have been found in the ground
water, entering millions of people sip by sip as they drink from a
vast system of tube wells. Sores on this persons hand indicate
Arsenic poisoning. (Altaf Hossain/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) MIAPUR, Bangladesh -- Nov. 11, 1998 --
BANGLADESH-WATER-3, 11-11 -- Pinjira Begum, 25, holds one of her
three children, a 4-month-old daughter named Juthi, In Miapur,
Bangladesh. Begum has been told that she is dying from the effects
of arsenic poisoning from well water. ``She was pretty once,'' says
her husband, Masud Rahman. ``But now she is too thin and smells bad
and is uglier by the day.'' So he has taken a second wife. Such
misery is common in Bangladesh, which some experts say may be in
the midst of the largest mass poisoning in history. (Altaf
Hossain/New York Times Photo)*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) MIAPUR, Bangladesh -- Nov. 11, 1998 --
BANGLADESH-WATER-2, 11-11 -- Masud Rahman's wife is has been told
she is dying from the effects of arsenic poisoning. Bangladesh is
in the midst of what some experts say could be the biggest mass
poisoning in history. Dangerous levels of arsenic have been found
in the ground water, entering millions of people sip by sip as they
drink from a vast system of tube wells. Sores on this persons hand
indicate Arsenic poisoning. (Altaf Hossain/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) MIAPUR, Bangladesh -- Nov. 11, 1998 --
BANGLADESH-WATER-1, 11-11 -- Sores on this persons hand indicate
arsenic poisoning. Bangladesh is in the midst of what some experts
say could be the biggest mass poisoning in history. Dangerous
levels of arsenic have been found in the ground water, entering
millions of people sip by sip as they drink from a vast system of
tube wells. Sores on this persons hand indicate Arsenic poisoning.
(Altaf Hossain/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- Nov. 11, 1998 -- TREE-PEONIES, 11-11 -- Known
as the ``king of the flowers,'' the tree peony has long been a
symbol of erotic love, embodying both the female and male elements.
Since the fourth century, when Xie Lingyun, a poet, described one
blooming in the wild, they have found their way into Chinese
poetry, ceramics and paintings. Emperors grew them in their palace
gardens as early as the sixth century, and they have long been
associated with wealth and nobility. ( Carl Labianca/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) PORTLAND, Ore. -- Nov. 11, 1998 -- CIR-HELPLINES-2, 11-11
-- IntelUs AnswerExpress facility, in Portland, Ore.
Uncommunicative callers can be a tough problem for technical
support operations. Another problem support technicians complain
about is that callers sometimes get upset if they do not get the
answers they expect. (Shane Young/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) ARLINGTON, Va. -- Nov. 11, 1998 -- VETERANS-DAY-FLOATER,
11-11 -- Beverly Rambow, left, of Snoqualmie, Wash., and George
King, of Frazee, Minn., a Korean War veteran, watched from a
balcony during the retiring of the colors following a ceremony
honoring veterans at Arlington National Cemetery on Wednesday.
Earlier, President Clinton marked Veterans Day by signing an
increase in veterans' disability payments, extending priority
health care to Gulf War veterans and creating a system for averting
future combat-related health catastrophes.. (Paul Hosefros/New York
Times Photo) * LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- Nov. 11, 1998 -- HOME IMPROVEMENT B&AMP;W, 11-11
-- Stairs tend to creak and squeak over time. This happens when the
house settles or the wood ages and shrinks. The noises may seem
like a minor nuisance at first, but they can be an indication that
structural members have moved out of alignment. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNION, S.C. -- Nov. 11, 1998 --ADV. FOR THURS., NOV. 12,
SUSAN-SMITH-COX, 11-11 -- Linda Russell cannot reach into her
daughter's mind to understand why she drove her little boys to this
spot, released the emergency brake of the car and sent the children
to their deaths strapped in the back seat of the vehicle. For the
first time since a jury convicted her daughter of murder, Russell
is talking publicly about the ghastly tragedy that sent chills down
America's spine. (Chris Burritt/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Nov. 11, 1998 -- BLACKS-B&AMP;Bs-2, 11-11 -- The
Ashante Suite at The Akwaaba Mansion in Brooklyn's
Bedford-Stuyvesant. Throughout the United States there is a growing
number of bed and breakfasts owned by African-Americans, many in
inner-city neighborhoods. One such place is The Akwaaba Mansion,
from the Ghanaian word for welcome. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Nov. 11, 1998 -- BLACKS-B&AMP;Bs , 11-11 --
Throughout the United States there is a growing number of bed and
breakfasts owned by African-Americans, many in inner-city
neighborhoods. One such place is The Akwaaba Mansion, from the
Ghanaian word for welcome, which thrives in Brooklyn's
Bedford-Stuyvesant. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) PRINCETON, N.J. -- Nov. 11, 1998 --CIR-CAMPUS-SECURITY
11-11 -- Yasemin Esmer waves her security card to access her
dormitory on the campus of Princeton University. Princeton, like
many other institutions of higher education, worries about
protecting its students. And one way to protect those students,
when you have 4,600 of them, is with an electronic security system.
(Norman Y. Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) RIDLEY, Penn. -- Nov. 11, 1998 -- CIR-HELPLINES, 11-11 --
Gail Kaplan, a research librarian for the Delaware County Library
System, sits next to her computer in the town of Ridley, near
Philadelphia. As the prices of computers and software drop and
companies look for ways to stretch their money, tech support
budgets can lose out to the needs of marketing and research and
development. (Tim Shaffer/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Nov. 11, 1998 -- CIR-CARBON-PAPER , 11-11 --
Victor Blackman, a carbon coater at Korectype in Brooklyn, N.Y.,
pours ink into the machine that makes carbon paper. With today's
laser and ink-jet printers, word processors, and voice- recognition
and spell-checking software, carbon paper, invented by an
Englishman named Ralph Wedgewood in the 1820's, is but a shadow of
the crucial commodity it was. (Barbara Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
