<SLUG> BC-MARY-FOREIGN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MARY' ENJOYING ITS OWN TITANIC SUCCESS OVERSEAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``There's Something About Mary'' is becoming a
major hit in foreign theaters despite its gross-out humor,
underscoring the pervasive influence of American culture in
overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
   The lowbrow satire will likely top its $170 million domestic
take by the end of its recently launched foreign run. It already
has gone past $67 million in 24 territories and has yet to play in
several major markets, including France, Japan and Spain.
</P>
<P>
   The overseas performance of ``Mary,'' starring Cameron Diaz and
Ben Stiller, is impressive because the 20th Century Fox release
lacks the key ingredients of typical international hits _ major
stars, special effects and nonstop action.
</P>
<P>
   It collected $22 million in gross receipts in the United Kingdom
in six weeks, $10 million in Australia, $8 million in Italy in
three weeks, $5 million in Brazil and $4.2 million in its opening
week in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   `` `There's Something About Mary' was not supposed to be a $170
million film domestically, so I'd have to give it the benefit of
the doubt in overseas markets,'' said Barry Hyman, an analyst with
Ehrenkrantz King Nussbaum in New York. ``Overseas box-office
grosses are now an important part of the equation when it comes to
deciding which films are being made. Those revenues are the only
way studios can justify the prices they pay for stars and films.''
</P>
<P>
   Given its bargain-basement production cost of $23 million,
lucrative prospects as a home video and strong probability of a
sequel, ``Mary'' will be the single most profitable movie property
debuted this year. With box-office receipts generally split 50-50
with exhibitors, Fox parent News Corp. will see nearly $200 million
in profit from its theatrical run alone.
</P>
<P>
   A top Fox executive recently told the weekly Variety that
``Mary'' could reach $175 million overseas. That would place it
among the six highest-foreign-grossing comedies, led by the $211
million total from ``The Flintstones'' in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The take for comedies is dwarfed by action films, led by the
massive $1.2 billion gross for ``Titanic,'' since concepts like
shipwrecks, explosions and car chases can be easily understood by
foreign moviegoers. In contrast, ``Mary'' features
pushing-the-envelope jokes about the disabled and zipper accidents
that may offend or not make sense to foreign crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles-based analyst Tim Baskerville said the ability of a
nonaction film to succeed overseas, particularly if it already has
been a hit in U.S. theaters, stems from the growing popularity of
new multi-screen cinemas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Multiplexing creates more capacity and opportunity for movies
beyond the top three,'' he said. ``Most of the screens will be
filled with the best-performing American movies because exhibitors
are going to want to offer staggered start times of the top films
rather than show every film that's available.''
</P>
<P>
   Baskerville estimates the foreign box office will rise from 60.8
percent of worldwide revenues ($10.96 billion) to 65.6 percent
($15.37 billion) in 2007. In nine years, the number of screens will
grow 22 percent to 132,804 worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary'' ran into censorship in Malaysia and Singapore, where
several risque scenes were cut, but the film has managed to gross
$1.9 million in South Korea and $1.1 million in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would imagine that this type of film will go over in the
more Westernized countries,'' Hyman said. ``I think they're getting
used to our product and they're becoming more Americanized.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are greater opportunities to see our movies in theaters
and through videocassettes. It's one world now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
