<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
 
CADE McNOWN: KING OF TOUGH LUCK 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was somewhere around the fourth quarter of the 1996 USC game
that one concluded Cade McNown was going to be a great college
football quarterback, assuming he survived.
</P>
<P>
   Many can recall that McNown and the Bruins rallied from a
17-point deficit in the final seven minutes and won in overtime,
48-41. It is harder to remember that McNown was sacked, tackled,
battered, hammered and blasted by a Trojan defender on virtually
every play.
</P>
<P>
   He attempted a career high 47 passes, completing a career-high
29, and ran the ball another 10 times, accounting for 57 of UCLA's
68 snaps during a four hour and 23 minute game. Bob Toledo's
offense has matured since that raw 5-6 season, most thankfully for
McNown's personal well-being.
</P>
<P>
   But statements and reputations are made in games like that, too.
As its harrowing 1998 ride to 8-0 and a shot at the national title
has indicated, toughness and resilience are UCLA's best traits, and
McNown is by far its toughest character.
</P>
<P>
   And he's had to be. His plate in '98 has been buffet-sized.
</P>
<P>
   He has had to deal with the mental fatigue of being a Heisman
candidate. Even if one believes him when he says ``I stopped
worrying about (the hype) before the season began,'' he's still had
to answer all of the questions. No other Heisman candidate out
there has had to deal with that and a run at the national title.
</P>
<P>
   As the team's leader, he has had to face the now weekly
inspection of the team's title worthiness. McNown and the Bruins
have spent the last month apologizing for finding new and exciting
ways to win football games.
</P>
<P>
   Few quarterbacks have had to deal with as impressive a gauntlet
of opponents, like back-to-back games against unbeatens like
Arizona and Oregon. Certainly not Michael Bishop at K-State or Tee
Martin at Tennessee. McNown is UCLA's go-to guy, and every Pac-10
defense has known this for a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   And even fewer quarterbacks have had to shoulder as much
leadership. McNown is one of just seven senior starters at UCLA,
and the only senior at a skill spot. ``We have a lot of guys on
this team who were high school juniors or seniors in 1996,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Al Borges, the Bruins' offensive coordinator, can tell you when
McNown's mental toughness became apparent. It happened the day
McNown realized he didn't have to touch the ball on 57 of 68 plays.
``Some of his best games will be those when his stats do not
standout,'' Borges said back in September.
</P>
<P>
   Cade may have some of the most paltry stats ever for a
Heisman-worthy quarterback. He has made 40 starts in his career,
but only six times has he completed more than 20 passes in any
game. He has been asked to throw more than 30 passes in a game only
13 times.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty for 30 is a good half for Kentucky's Tim Couch, or for
Florida's Danny Wuerffel when he won the award in 1996, or for any
of BYU's half-dozen Heisman candidates of the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   After running for 311 yards as a freshman in 1995, McNown's
rushing stats have dwindled, too. Now, it's quality over quantity.
He has 104 net rushing yards this season, but you can isolate three
runs as critical to UCLA's 8-0 record.
</P>
<P>
   There was that 25-yard run against Oregon, the sprint that led
to his leaving his pregame snack at midfield; a 34-yard third down
run against Cal; and 30-yard run against Oregon State last week
that launched UCLA's comeback from a 24-17 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   McNown is doing more with less, which is splendid for unbeaten
teams but work against Heisman credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Not that McNown cares. One fancies he'd be more flattered
getting a Lombardi or Butkus vote than winning the Heisman.
Physical toughness comes natural for McNown, an intangible he
doesn't spend much time thinking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was growing up in Pop Warner football, I played
everything, defensive line, offensive line, fullback, safety,''
said McNown, who had 55 tackles and four interceptions to go with
2,432 offensive yards as a high school senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not run as much today as I did (as a freshman or
sophomore), but when I get in the open field, I revert back to what
I know about real football. In the open field, you can brace for a
collision.
</P>
<P>
   ``But a quarterback can not concentrate on protecting himself in
the pocket. If you do, your throw will be affected. I've been hit
enough to the point where I don't dread it.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a pole vaulter in track, the sport's high-flying act, and
he also wrestled. For fun, he snowboarded whenever he could and
climbed a few mountains. But this does not make him UCLA's resident
extreme athlete. ``I was doing that stuff when they didn't have a
name for it and ESPN2 wasn't following you with a camera,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He could use a old-fashioned breather this week against
Washington. But he doesn't expect it. Frankly, he isn't sure he or
his teammates would know how to act.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to score every time we have the ball, and that's
not lip service. I try to approach every drive the same. But there
are times when I like the play-calling more when we're tied or
behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, the urgency of the situation makes us play
better.'' For both UCLA and McNown, you can call it Tough Luck.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
