<HEADLINE>
ONLY AGREEMENT WITH HBO NEEDED TO MAKE HOLYFIELD-LEWIS A REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that Don King has signed contracts with Lennox Lewis and
Madison Square Garden on a heavyweight unification bout between
Lewis and Evander Holyfield, he has to reach an agreement with HBO
Sports, which will broadcast the fight on TVKO, before the fight
can become a reality.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, the World Boxing Council heavyweight champion, will earn
between $8 and $10 million for the fight. Holyfield, the
International Boxing Federation and World Boxing Association
champion, will earn $20 million. Madison Square Garden will pay $8
million for the bout, which is scheduled for March 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very satisfied with the deal,'' said Milton Chwasky,
Lewis' New York-based lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   King's contract with Lewis gives the promoter options on a
rematch with Holyfield and a title defense against Henry Akinwande,
the WBA's No. 1 contender, if Lewis defeats Holyfield and becomes
the undisputed heavyweight champion of the world. King already
promotes Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   King met with executives from HBO Sports and TVKO, HBO's
pay-per-view outlet, Wednesday. A possible unification bout was
scuttled last year when King and HBO couldn't agree on the number
of pay-per-view buys that the fight would do. Also, King said that
HBO wouldn't meet Holyfield's salary demands and wouldn't let him
take the fight to Showtime, HBO's major cable rival where King's
bouts are broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   TYSON ANNOUNCEMENT TUESDAY
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson, the former heavyweight champion, will announce his
first bout since the Nevada State Athletic Commission gave him his
license back on Oct. 19 in Manhattan next Tuesday. Tyson had his
license revoked for biting Evander Holyfield's ears and being
disqualified during a heavyweight championship fight on June 29,
1997.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that Tyson will meet Francois Botha of South Africa
at the MGM Grand in Las Vegas on Jan. 16. Botha has not signed a
contract and the MGM Grand has not signed a contract, although both
are close to agreeing to deals with Tyson. The bout will be
broadcast on pay per view by Showtime Entertainment Television.
Tyson has been working out in Phoenix, but hasn't set up his
training camp yet.
</P>
<P>
   HEAVYWEIGHT HOPEFULS
</P>
<P>
   Some promising young heavyweights will headline a show at
Roseland Ballroom in Manhattan on Dec. 8 in a card promoted by
Cedric Kushner. Shannon Briggs, Kirk Johnson, Ike Ibeabuchi, Obed
Sullivan and Alonzo Highsmith, the former National Football League
running back, will all be fighting on the card, which will be
broadcast on pay-per-view by USSB and Viewers Choice.
</P>
<P>
   No opponent has been scheduled for Briggs, whose last bout was a
world title fight against Lennox Lewis on March 28. Briggs had
Lewis in trouble early in the bout before Lewis rallied to score a
technical knockout in the fifth round. Briggs has been mentioned as
a possible opponent for Mike Tyson in his second fight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
