<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADEMARK-PIRATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS TRADEMARKS MULTIPLY, INFRINGEMENT DOES, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By YOUSSEF M. IBRAHIM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ At first glance, Frederick Mostert appears to be a
typically staid corporate lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in dark, conservative suits, Mostert on most days goes
to his office here at the Richemont group, the owner of such elite
brands as Alfred Dunhill luxury gifts, Cartier jewelry, Montblanc
pens and Rothmans cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   But Mostert sometimes leads another life, one that involves what
he calls ``undercover work'' _ dressing in blue jeans and posing as
a tourist _ in search of information.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there is no secret behind Mostert's actions. The
reason is as prominent as Richemont's brands: Mostert, 38, is the
intellectual property counsel for Compagnie Financiere Richemont
AG, working with a staff of 30 people to make sure no one steals or
imitates the names, shapes or slogans of the Swiss-based company's
products.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, since May he has been the president of the
International Trademark Association, so he keeps his eye on other
companies' products as well in such faraway places as Cyprus,
Brazil, Indonesia and China.
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's globalized economy, trademark protection is serious
money,'' Mostert said. ``When a pirate moves in to copy a Coca-Cola
can, shape or color, it is like placing a bet on a horse after the
race is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand names like Coca-Cola, IBM and McDonald's are so valuable
that even approximating their advertising slogans to sell similar
products can mean millions of dollars in lost sales to the
manufacturers of the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, Mostert has helped pursue trademark thieves
who used the Pizza Hut name to sell frozen pies in Cyprus and chase
after others who used Donald Duck and Mickey Mouse to promote a
golf game in Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
   He also testified against an engineer who registered a trademark
he dubbed ``Pentenium,'' deliberately blocking Intel Corp. from
registering its famous ``Pentium'' brand name in the Czech
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating his job is the fact that trademarks are multiplying
at a dizzying pace as the world's economy expands, increasing the
temptation to steal brand names and designs.
</P>
<P>
   According to the World Intellectual Property Organization, an
affiliate of the United Nations, the number of brand names
registered as trademarks exceeds nine million, more than double the
number in 1974. But trademark protection has lagged far behind this
growth.
</P>
<P>
   There is no global system for protecting trademarks, said
Geoffrey Yu, the director of global communications at the
Geneva-based organization.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has created even more opportunities for trademark
infringement.
</P>
<P>
   ``International treaties simply don't match the explosion of
digital communications,'' Yu said. ``It takes years, maybe decades,
to formulate an international treaty. The Internet explosion has
created a situation that was never foreseen.''
</P>
<P>
   Trademark hijacking on the Internet is growing in countries
where brand-name protection laws are weak. Mostert spends hours
surfing the Internet, following a growing population of what he
calls ``global pirates'' who have registered Internet addresses for
themselves that look identical to real trademark names.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the problems have become particularly widespread in
the last 15 years as advances in communications, including
satellite television and the Internet, bring instant images, sports
and world events to billions of viewers around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until recently, trademark was a territorial concept,'' Mostert
said. ``Now it's what I call a cross-border phenomenon.'' He said
that it was relatively easy to track people producing counterfeit
products within a specific region like North or South America or a
single country. But now, trademark infringements are occurring
throughout most of the world.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of these problems, multinational corporations like
Pizza Hut, Intel, Coca-Cola and scores of others are acting on
their own, hiring legions of lawyers and investigators to pursue
pirates, including those registering a brand name or an
approximation of it on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The International Trademark Association estimates that some
large multinational companies may have as many as 15,000 conflicts
of varying seriousness at any one time.
</P>
<P>
   The trademark association itself is an outgrowth of a group of
12 merchants in New York City who sought protection for their
brands 120 years ago. Today the group includes 3,500 companies in
120 countries.
</P>
<P>
   The volume of counterfeiting has also grown. The association
estimates that businesses lost sales of $2.1 billion to trademark
pirates last year alone.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the option for the legal owner of the trademark
is often lengthy and uncertain legal wrangling. In the absence of
an international body of laws that can settle matters swiftly, most
companies prefer to settle privately.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, for example, anyone searching the Internet
for information on elephants could find a Web site,
www.ringlingbrothers.com, that belonged not to Ringling Brothers
and Barnum &AMP; Bailey Circus but to the animal rights group People
for the Ethical Treatment of Animals.
</P>
<P>
   The group had registered the Ringling domain name in February to
lodge a protest accusing the circus of mistreating its animals.
Feld Entertainment, owner of Ringling, responded with a threat of a
trademark infringement lawsuit. The group then surrendered the
domain to the circus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
