<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS BEGIN INQUIRY INTO CONTRIBUTIONS TO VACCO
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., N.C.)   (jw) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Federal prosecutors have opened an investigation into
a series of political contributions that state Attorney General
Dennis Vacco's campaign received from donors linked to a large
car-leasing company on Long Island, lawyers involved in the
investigation said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney's office in Brooklyn issued a subpoena late
last month to the company, Oxford Resources, seeking documents
related to $46,000 in contributions that Oxford executives and
subsidiaries gave last year to the Vacco 1998 re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco conducted an inquiry last year into the business practices
of the company after receiving complaints that it was overcharging
customers.
</P>
<P>
   He settled the case through mediation, declining to force the
company to pay restitution or face other penalties.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported last month that during the inquiry,
Oxford executives and a company subsidiary gave $8,500 to Vacco's
re-election campaign, according to campaign records. And less than
three weeks after Vacco closed the inquiry on Nov. 4, 1997, his
campaign received an additional $37,500 from nine Oxford
subsidiaries on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that prosecutors are trying to determine whether the
campaign contributions played any role in how the attorney general
handled the case, lawyers involved in the investigation said,
speaking on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney's office declined to comment on the subpoena,
saying that it has a policy of not confirming or denying
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Wednesday about the subpoena, Oxford's lawyer, Gerald
Walpin, a senior partner at the firm of Rosenman &AMP; Colin, read a
statement: ``Oxford has complied with the law in all respects. If
there is any governmental inquiry, Oxford would provide any
information that is requested.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has been a big donor to Republican causes in recent
years, but had not contributed large amounts to Vacco before the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The company is now owned by Nationsbank of Charlotte, N.C., and
is called Nationsbank Auto Leasing.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Wednesday whether the attorney general's office
had received a subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Carey, a spokesman for Vacco, was asked on Tuesday whether
the office had, and he said he would check. Carey did not respond
to two subsequent messages.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney's office in Brooklyn is pursuing at least two
other investigations involving campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   One is examining whether donations to the Republican State
Committee influenced the awarding of a $97 million transportation
contract by the Pataki administration.
</P>
<P>
   The other is focusing on whether contributors to the campaign of
Gov. George Pataki were promised favorable treatment in cases
before the State Parole Board.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's aides have called those two investigations
politically motivated, noting that the U.S. attorney in Brooklyn,
Zachary Carter, was appointed by President Clinton. Carter has
declined to respond to that criticism.
</P>
<P>
   State election authorities have not yet determined whether Vacco
won a second term in the election on Nov. 3 against his Democratic
challenger, Eliot Spitzer. The tally on voting machines showed
Spitzer leading by less than 10,000 votes, but more than 200,000
absentee and other paper ballots have not been counted.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco's inquiry into Oxford's practices was not the first by a
New York attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, his Democratic predecessor, Robert Abrams, also
investigated the company, and ended up accusing it of deceptive
practices. Oxford settled by issuing refunds, paying a $10,000 fine
and promising to overhaul its practices.
</P>
<P>
   Both inquiries examined whether Oxford was assessing excessive
charges for damage to vehicles when leases expired.
</P>
<P>
   And the complaints have continued. Vacco's office received 48
complaints about the company in 1997, including the 10 that touched
off his inquiry. This year, with the investigation closed, the
office has received at least 45.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco and his aides repeatedly said last month that there was no
connection between the Oxford donations and his inquiry. The aides
acknowledged that Oxford had a higher rate of complaints than other
car leasing companies in the state, but they said Vacco had
concluded that Oxford did not break the law, so he was limited in
the actions he could take.
</P>
<P>
   They noted that the people who complained about Oxford last year
and then went to mediation under the auspices of the attorney
general's office had received money back from the company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
