<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COS JUST WANTS TO PLAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The player's physique and mannerisms suggested his
identity, but his presence on the practice field confounded most
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earl,'' he said. ``Today, I'm Earl.''
</P>
<P>
   Earl?
</P>
<P>
   It looked like Cos Abercrombie, Cal State Northridge's middle
linebacker sidelined since the second week of the season with a
broken jaw. Indeed, it was Abercrombie going incognito _ back at
practice for a day but without contact, awaiting doctor's clearance
for contact. He expects that to come, after which Abercrombie and
CSUN coach Ron Ponciano will have a difficult decision to make.
</P>
<P>
   After saying Abercrombie, a sophomore, would redshirt this
season, Ponciano might bring his best linebacker to Southwest
Missouri State as the 24th-ranked Matadors make a postseason run.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're sitting (in my office), and he comes in (and
says), `Coach, I have to play, I need to play,' you see what the
doctors say and it becomes an option,'' Ponciano said. ``The only
thing that matters is if Cos can go without being a high-risk guy.
. . . But we'd definitely get better the second he steps onto the
field. If he can't go this week, he's going to get the medical
redshirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Before a decision is reached, though, Abercrombie must weigh the
options.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN could win the Big Sky Conference, grab a playoff berth and
make this the most memorable season in the program's history.
However, the Matadors (6-3) could lose at Southwest Missouri State
or Idaho State and not make the postseason. Thus, Abercrombie would
give up his redshirt season for two meaningless games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, the only thing I can say about me coming back is
that I love it. I love it,'' Abercrombie said. ``I know it's a big
move and I might not be 100 percent for two games, but I love it. I
feel if I come back and I'm not the person they put in there, then
it doesn't make sense. But playoffs, that's something most people
never see.''
</P>
<P>
   Health is THE issue. At 209 pounds, Abercrombie is 11 pounds
lighter than he was Sept. 19, when he broke his jaw at Northern
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Although doctors cleared him medically to return, Ponciano is
concerned about the bullet lodged in Abercrombie's jaw _ an inch
from the break _ from a drive-by shooting that kept him out of the
1996 season.
</P>
<P>
   Abercrombie's path from Verbum Dei High, where he was the El
Camino Real League's Most Valuable Player as a senior, is filled
with unforeseen detours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if he gets cleared, there's some common sense a coach has
to use,'' Ponciano said. ``What if he makes three great plays and
gets his jaw broken again? That would be pretty sad to see. This
guy is a high-collision guy playing a high-collision position. But
if his body is sound, we'll let him go.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: CSUN wide receiver Anthony Ramos isn't expected to
practice much this week because of sore legs but is expected to
make the trip. . . . Wide receiver Mike Ogas (elbow) and defensive
back Donnell Day (hand) returned to practice. . . . Ponciano said
he'll decide today whether place-kicker Manny Marquez (quadricep)
will make the trip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
