<SLUG> BC-EARLY-VOTE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY VOTES KEY TO GOP VICTORY IN UTILITY PANEL RACE
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
Republican Tony West's eleventh-hour victory in the Corporation
Commission race affirms the in creasing power of Arizona's
vote-by-mail program.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Both sides in the contest say early voting made the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the early ballots that put (West) over the top,'' state
GOP Chairman Mike Hellon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did much better among the early ballots than he actually
did on Election Day.''
</P>
<P>
   The state GOP spent about $250,000 this year on an aggressive
vote-by-mail program, sending absentee bal lot requests to every
Republican household in the state weeks before Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   The investment paid off: In Mari copa County, absentee balloting
from Republican voters led Demo crats by a 2-1 ratio. In all, more
than 195,000 early ballots were cast in the state's largest county,
elections offi cials said.
</P>
<P>
   That lopsided margin nudged West past Democrat Paul Newman as
Maricopa County elections workers tallied 49,000 early ballots that
ar rived too late to count Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lose by 2,000 votes to Tony West, (early balloting)
certainly did pay off'' for the GOP, state Demo cratic Party
Chairman Mark Fleisher said.
</P>
<P>
   Fleisher said Newman, a state law maker, picked up steam too
late in the campaign, when he began a scathing media attack against
West. The negative salvos hurt the Repub lican, but West had banked
a sizable bloc of early votes that cushioned him against the
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Newman) peaked Election Day. That's not the way
campaigns work any more. You have to peak the whole three weeks
before,'' Fleisher said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, vote-by-mail has dramati cally changed the dynamics of
cam paigning in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates and political parties that once focused all their
efforts on getting the vote out on Election Day now expend large
amounts of energy and money on capturing votes cast by mail.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the state's Republican and Democratic parties mailed
out early-ballot request forms to more than 1 million voters
statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Fleisher said the Democrats spent about as much as the GOP on
the program. An attorney general's in vestigation into the party's
solicita tion of corporate funds did not damage the vote-by-mail
effort, but hurt its get-out-the-vote program, Fleisher said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, about a quarter of the vote in Arizona this year was
cast by mail in the weeks leading up to Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   In other states, the trend is even stronger. On Tuesday, Oregon
be came the first state in the nation to retire traditional voting,
passing a measure to conduct all elections by mail, 57 percent to
43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   To exploit the early-voting bloc, campaigns are spending heavily
on literature, television advertisements and fliers early in the
election season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only do you get a higher percentage of high-efficacy
voters, but it also has developed into a voter-recruitment tool,''
Phoenix GOP political consultant Chuck Coughlin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can actually get new voters who probably otherwise
wouldn't have voted.''
</P>
<P>
   Since its inception in 1991, vote by mail has paid off for many
cam paigns:
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Gov. Fife Symington's campaign waged a successful
effort to court voters before Election Day. Symington picked up
75,000 votes in early balloting even before results from polling
places began trickling in.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, wealthy publisher Steve Forbes used early balloting to
help him overcome a crowded field to win Arizona's first GOP
presidential pri mary. His campaign mailed out 165,000 early-ballot
requests, while other Republican presidential cam paigns fell
behind.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Hull's campaign not only targeted Republicans, but
sent absentee-ballot requests to thousands of independent voters.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hull, the governor's son and campaign manager, said
vote-by-mail was crucial to Hull's lopsided vic tory, allowing Hull
to ``put votes in the bank early,'' before Democrat Paul Johnson
could pepper the governor with negative attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's expensive, but it's worth it,'' Hellon said. &QL; 
 &UR; Michael Murphy can be reached at
 &UR; 444-8546 or at michael.mur
 &UR; phy &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
