r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      11-11 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HERO IN HIS OWN BACK YARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just after 11 a.m. Wednesday, a member of the color guard from
American Legion Post 115 pushed the ``play'' button on the tape
recorder he'd set on the ground near one of his shiny black boots.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing happened.
</P>
<P>
   The small crowd gathered in the back yard of Aldoph ``Doc''
Wussow stood in silence, waiting. Television cameras from four
local stations pointed at Doc or at members of the color guard,
waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hold this,'' the guard member said, handing his rifle to the
flag-bearer next to him. He carried the tape player to an outlet
near Wussow's back door, plugging it in near a table where Doc's
wife, Joy, had set trays of cookies and a big pot of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   A recorded version of ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' boomed forth.
</P>
<P>
   Doc Wussow's final flag ceremony had begun.
</P>
<P>
   In all the other places Doc and Joy lived, it was only family at
the flag raisings he'd stage on Veterans Day, Memorial Day, the
Fourth of July and so on. That's how he expected it would be when
he moved into the Del Webb development called Terravita, in north
Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   The Wussows have always had a flagpole in the backyard. Doc
served in World War II. His brother, Robert, was killed during the
war in a bombing mission over Germany on Oct. 8, 1943.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fly the flag for my brother and for all the boys who died,
in all the wars,'' Doc said. ``I never expected it to be a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was. Shortly before Wussow signed a contract with
Terravita, the development decided to ban flagpoles. Doc figured he
was covered by the old rule and installed a skinny, 20-foot pole.
</P>
<P>
   The homeowners association went after him. They took him to
court, saying, essentially, that the flagpole was a nuisance and an
eyesore. Doc fought back.
</P>
<P>
   He is in his 70s and has a heart condition. One of his adult
children is in a care facility for a brain injury. The stress was
terrible, but he fought back.
</P>
<P>
   And he lost.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Wussow agreed to pay the homeowners
association $20,000 to drop its suit against him. In return, he is
permitted to fly his flag eight days a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, this is it,'' Doc said Wednesday. ``After today, I won't
do it any more. It's just too much for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wussows have paid half their debt to the association.
There's a $10,000 lien on their house for the other half. A fund
has been set up at Norwest Bank to help them, Account No.
1272705885.
</P>
<P>
   During the ceremony in his backyard Wednesday, Doc lowered the
flag to half-mast. Some of those in attendance read poems and
patriotic passages.
</P>
<P>
   It was cloudy. The wind picked up enough to lift the flag. The
rustle and pop of fabric was more eloquent than the words being
spoken.
</P>
<P>
   At 11:15, taps was performed and Doc raised the flag to the top
of the pole.
</P>
<P>
   The tape player was switched on again, this time with Kate Smith
singing ``God Bless America.''
</P>
<P>
   That was it.
</P>
<P>
   Doc thanked everyone for coming, choking back tears as he spoke.
This happens, sometimes, to old soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked if his struggle with Terravita was worth it,
considering the toll it has taken on his health and his pocketbook,
all for a flagpole that disappears in the rolling desert like a
toothpick in the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd do it all over again,'' he said. ``Not for me, but for all
the boys we remember on days like today.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for us, even World War II couldn't scrub away the grit
from men like Doc.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sometimes wonder if people know what this country is all
about any more,'' he said. ``I'm not sure I know myself,
sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows this much, however. If you're not willing to fight the
battles on the home front, then all those soldiers who didn't make
it back died for nothing. &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
