<HEADLINE>
BONILLA BURDEN LIFTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Bobby Bonilla, who rarely provided the leadership
or left-handed power the Los Angeles Dodgers were seeking after
getting him last May in the Mike Piazza trade, was sent Wednesday
to the New York Mets in exchange for reliever Mel Rojas and cash.
</P>
<P>
   The switch-hitting Bonilla, who will be 36 in February, returns
to New York, where he spent 3{ stormy seasons in the early '90s
after signing one of baseball's biggest free-agent contracts.
</P>
<P>
   But it could not have been much worse than his half-season in
Los Angeles, where he struggled after undergoing surgery last
winter on his left wrist and left Achilles' tendon.
</P>
<P>
   The injuries especially hurt his mobility at third base and left
field, where his fielding mistakes often made him a target of
Dodgers fans.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla finished with a .249 average, 11 homers and 45 RBI in
100 games, his worst production since his rookie year in 1986. With
Bonilla's $5.9 million salary for each of the next two seasons and
a strained relationship with new Dodgers manager Davey Johnson from
two seasons in Baltimore, new general manager Kevin Malone made
trading him an offseason priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understood that his injuries hurt his effectiveness, but we
also thought we needed to move forward,'' Malone said. ``We are
prepared to go with Adrian Beltre at third base. He showed us last
year he is ready to play in the big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Dodgers are out from under half of Bonilla's $11.8
million salary for the next two seasons, giving them room to pursue
free-agent pitchers Kevin Brown and Randy Johnson. They also are
expected to go after Mets catcher Todd Hundley, who became
available after New York recently signed Piazza to a seven-year,
$91 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre, 20, often struggled after being called up to the majors
in July from Double-A San Antonio. He batted .214 in 77 games with
seven homers and 22 RBI. He also committed 13 errors.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Dodgers hired Johnson, who battled with Bonilla
about using him as a designated hitter, Malone began discussions
with the Mets during the World Series. Talks, however, stalled late
last week when New York general manager Steve Phillips was forced
to take a leave of absence after a former Mets employee threatened
legal action on a sexual-harassment charge.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips was replaced by former GM Frank Cashen, architect of
the powerful Mets club of the 1980s that was headed by Johnson.
Malone and Cashen spoke repeatedly this week in Naples, Fla., where
baseball general managers are holding their annual meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve set most of the groundwork and Frank and I were able to
finish it up today,'' Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   Rojas, who turns 32 next month, is reunited with Malone, his
general manager in Montreal when he appeared ready to become one of
baseball's top relievers. His best year was 1996, when he went 7-4
with a 3.22 ERA and 36 saves for the Expos. That season led to a
three-year contract with the Cubs, but Rojas never pitched well for
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Rojas quickly lost his closer spot to Terry Adams and was traded
Aug. 8 after going 0-4 with a 4.22 ERA and 13 saves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult for me because I was used to pitching a
lot,'' Rojas said Wednesday from his home in the Dominican
Republic. ``I enjoyed pitching for (manager) Felipe (Alous) in
Montreal and it was a big adjustment. It just never worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were hoping Rojas would return to form and eventually
replace veteran closer John Franco. Instead, Rojas went 5-2 with a
6.05 ERA and just two saves in 1998. There were reports he had
trouble keeping his weight down and maintaining his focus on the
mound.
</P>
<P>
   With the cross-town Yankees winning the World Series, the Mets
had no choice but to search for quick fixes. They re-signed Franco
for two more seasons and aggressively shopped Rojas.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla has 273 career homers, including 34 for the Mets in
1994. He rose to stardom with Pittsburgh in the late 1980s and
early '90s when the Pirates won three consecutive National League
East titles.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla was traded to Baltimore in the middle of the 1995 season
and signed with Florida as a free agent in 1997. He drove in 96
runs the first year and helped the Marlins win the World Series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
