<HEADER>
A6428 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VETERANS-DAY12-COX     11-11 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VETERANS-DAY12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tuskegee Airmen speak at Southwest Texas for Veterans Day
 &HT;    By Mike Kelley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN MARCOS, Texas _ When they finally got the opportunity, they
proved that they could do the job, two former members of the
Tuskegee Airmen, the first African-American flying units in the
Army Air Corps, told an audience here Wednesday at Southwest Texas
State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardship helped me to be more durable. This is a country
where opportunity is as great as the will,'' said Albert Whiteside
Jr. of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my wings were pinned on, it represented that I had
overcome; I had conquered my frustration and done the job I was
supposed to do,'' said Melvin P. Sikes of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Both men were members of the 477th Bomber Group, who trained in
Alabama during World War II to be fliers in an Air Corps which up
until then had offered African-Americans only menial positions.
Their lecture at Southwest Texas State was one of many Veterans Day
observances around Central Texas Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Whiteside said he'd had all of farmwork he wanted in the little
town of Jones Prairie, in Milam County. He'd heard that President
Franklin Roosevelt had created an all-black flying program, and the
17-year-old made his way to San Antonio where he passed the
flight-program admission test. He spent 18 years in the service and
later was a civilian employee of the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   Sikes, who ``all my life wanted to fly,'' followed the path of
another youth in his hometown of Gary, Ind., which led to the
Tuskegee program in Alabama. He left the Air Corps in 1946, became
a clinical psychologist, taught at the University of Texas and
retired in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   The first group of Tuskegee airmen were fighter pilots, who
blazed a stellar trail in the Mediterranean and Europe, flying
escort duty for bombers. No bomber under their protection was ever
shot down.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the success of those fighter pilots made life even
more difficult for the African-American bomber crewmen who came
after them, Sikes said. ``There was a lot of resentment because
(the fighter pilots) did make it,'' he said, in the face of an Air
Corps attitude that African-Americans weren't capable of being
pilots. ``The attitude became, `If we can't get them in one place,
we'll get them in another.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We always carried the weight of the race on our shoulders. It
was, `No one thinks we can do this, so we're going to have to do it
no matter what it takes.' I think we had no idea this was going to
happen . . . that we would be honored or be part of history and all
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Though most people in the audience lined up to get the two men's
autographs, Sikes told them: ``Don't honor us per se, but in terms
of what we tried to do. We need you to do that for us.''
</P>
<P>
   In the audience were several members of the San Marcos High
School Junior ROTC. One of them, 17-year-old Robert Gutierrez, said
``I was extremely impressed that they never referred to themselves
as victims. They simply said, `This is what was wrong; this is what
we did, and look how we succeeded.' They're leaders. They lead by
example.''
</P>
<P>
   Another ROTC member, Brandon Carroll, also 17, said, ``They
never complained or used their color as a crutch. If you have to
work twice as hard as the next person, well, life isn't fair. Don't
look for any handouts, because they didn't and look where they are
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
