<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Pinochet's Defense
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ A British law that provides immunity to former heads of
state would have protected even Adolf Hitler from arrest and
prosecution in Britain, lawyers for Gen. Augusto Pinochet told
Britain's highest court. Pinochet, the former Chilean dictator, is
resisting extradition to Spain, which wants him to face trial in
connection with crimes allegedly committed during his rule.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   China: Clinton-Dalai Lama Talk Irks Beijing
</P>
<P>
   BEIJING _ China has strongly protested President Clinton's
meeting on Tuesday with the Dalai Lama as well as the visit to
Taiwan by Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, calling their actions
interference in China's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
   China: South Korean Leader's Visit
</P>
<P>
   BEIJING _ President Kim Dae-jung of South Korea and a group of
more than 250 officials and corporate executives arrived in Beijing
for a five-day visit. China and South Korea have become major trade
partners although China remains a rare diplomatic ally of North
Korea.
</P>
<P>
   India: Harsh Words for Pakistan:
</P>
<P>
   Raising the level of acrimony in the contentious talks between
India and Pakistan, India's home minister, Lal Krishna Advani,
said, ``As far as we are concerned, Pakistan is a terrorist
state.'' Advani, a powerful figure in the governing Hindu
nationalist party, labeled India's rival as an international outlaw
for allegedly giving material support to Muslim militants in the
disputed Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Japan: Deal for Voucher Program
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The governing Liberal Democratic Party of Japan has
agreed to an opposition party's demands to issue gift vouchers in
an effort to stimulate domestic economic demand. The vouchers,
amounting to $5.7 billion, will be distributed to elderly
pensioners with low incomes, the disabled and families with
children. The plan has been criticized by other politicians,
business executives and economists as a gimmick.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   South Africa: De Klerk's Request Denied
</P>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ President Nelson Mandela has rejected an
application from his predecessor, F.W. de Klerk, for state funds to
cover legal fees incurred in his attempt to stop the Truth and
Reconciliation Commission from implicating him in human rights
violations during the apartheid era.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Chile: U.N. Withdraws Pinochet Officer
</P>
<P>
   A Chilean general linked by human rights groups to unlawful
executions during the era of Gen. Augusto Pinochet is being
withdrawn from U.N. peacekeeping duty in Kashmir. The
secretary-general's spokesman, Fred Eckhard, said that Chile had
promoted the officer, Brig. Gen. Sergio Espinoza Davies, to major
general and was appointing him inspector general of the Chilean
army.
</P>
<P>
   Chile: Leader Begins Pretoria Trip
</P>
<P>
   President Eduardo Frei flew to South Africa to begin a nine-day
international trade mission, putting aside concerns that domestic
political dissent could escalate if a panel of the British House of
Lords rules that Gen. Augusto Pinochet can be extradited to Spain
to stand trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
