<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEANING GOES BEYOND WHAT IS, OR ISN'T, SAID
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the quote-driven world of the morning sports page, what the
jock-populace has to say doesn't necessarily matter.
</P>
<P>
   But why it was said, when it was said, or maybe what was never
said _ all of that requires serious reading between the lines.
Which is often followed by something being lost in the translation.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Brett Hull. Or Ken Hitchcock. Or Joe Brodsky. Or
Chan Gailey. It's a diverse group, but they all fit into that
why-when-mum pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Hull came to Dallas with a marked tongue. His reputation arrived
before he did. When the Hull mouth opens, anything may tumble out.
In his St. Louis past, those loose lips were sometimes considered a
source of concern.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars knew this when they laid nearly $6 million a year at
Hull's free-agency doorstep. But the sonic boom from Hull's scoring
stick was what owner Tom Hicks wanted to hear.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness _ or unfairness _ to Hull, all of us in the local
media have been hanging on his every word, sitting on pounce for
something controversial to be uttered. Hey, it's all about
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Hull cracked this week. Or so it seemed. He commented
on lack of minutes played in the Stars' game on Saturday in Los
Angeles. ``There's no possible way Brett Hull can do anything in 11
minutes \Ractually it was nearly 12\S,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Until that game, Hull had been averaging 18 minutes. He would
like to have over 20. But the Stars won in LA, so his comments came
across as selfish, particularly after a victory.
</P>
<P>
   But was it selfish?
</P>
<P>
   Hull knew that a penalty binge had often left the Stars'
short-handed in that game, limiting his ice time. He also knew that
by playing on the Joe Nieuwendyk line, minutes might be reduced
because Nieuwendyk is still playing himself back into shape after
double knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   If desired, Hull's comments could have been placed in another
context. If Mike Modano had said the same thing, a different
meaning would have been reported.
</P>
<P>
   But this is Brett Hull, and this was the first chance locally to
link him with a controversial comment. Then again, Hull knows all
this, so why did he leave the outhouse door open? No matter his
intent, Hull knew there were some who would blow up the wording,
and did.
</P>
<P>
   So was Hull purposely trying to get a message across to the
coach about minutes? Why did he say what he said?
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock is a coach who knows only one message. If a player
wants to tell him something, do it face to face.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock's reaction to Hull was also interesting. He gave his
player some mild defense, believing the comments were overblown.
But Hitchcock then took the opportunity to publicly and strongly
remind Hull that this kind of stuff isn't tolerated around here.
</P>
<P>
   Had Hitch been waiting patiently for the first chance to deliver
that reminder? He could have gone easier on Hull, but he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   It all led to this kind of column, with questions being asked
about who meant what and why? Plus, let's also not assume something
wasn't lost in the translation.
</P>
<P>
   No translation is needed, however, for the Joe Brodsky quote
from Chicago. Brodsky hung out forever at Valley Ranch as the
Cowboys' offensive backfield coach before moving to the Bears for
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Brodsky confirmed yesterday what he had told the ``Chicago
Tribune'' last week: ``If you think every team in the league plays
hard every week, you better look around. We packed it in last year
in Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of us in the local media were writing and saying from
November on that many on the Cowboys had quit on the owner, the
head coach, and themselves. Ironically, Brodsky was the biggest
media critic in the locker room, chastising those who said then
what he says now.
</P>
<P>
   Honesty is good. In this case, it was a matter of ``when''
honesty would surface. For Joe Brodsky, it took a while and a job
change.
</P>
<P>
   But there are times when credit is not given for saying nothing.
Which brings us to Chan Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   The one major crisis Gailey has faced in his short Cowboys' head
coaching tenure came at Wichita Falls in August.
</P>
<P>
   The neck-slashing incident in the dorm now seems a long, long
time ago. Except it was hard on Gailey at the time _ for several
weeks he took a daily hammering of media questions.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey, to some of us, looked bad publicly because he refused to
come clean with details. But he only did his talking about the
incident to the players, particularly the core of team leaders.
</P>
<P>
   One of those players mentioned last week that the key to
Gailey's gaining the full confidence of the team was largely due to
his public handling of the neck-slash.
</P>
<P>
   There were those of us in the media who didn't agree in Wichita
Falls, but hindsight does indicate mum was magic for Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   It's a little something for Brett Hull to consider, although
don't count on it.
</P>
<P>
   (Randy Galloway is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
