</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAY IT AIN'T SO! JESSE A GOVERNING `BODY?'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somewhere, Fritz Von Erich is smiling.
</P>
<P>
   This was what he had in mind when he developed the dreaded Iron
Claw years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Domination. Not just of the ring, but of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Fritz was ahead of his time. Jesse ``The Body'' Ventura,
governor-elect of Minnesota, is right on time.
</P>
<P>
   We don't know whether to laugh, cry or tear up our Social
Security cards and flee to Tahiti.
</P>
<P>
   The election of Ventura by Minnesota, a state whose inhabitants
have clearly spent too much time inside those little ice-fishing
shanties sniffing paint fumes, has put a whole new spin on sports,
actors and politics.
</P>
<P>
   It's a joke, right? Somebody's kidding here. It's one thing to
put the co-star of Bedtime for Bonzo in the White House, but to put
a man who has spent most of his life referring to himself as ``Mr.
Body'' in charge of a whole state? This borders on lunacy.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody tell me we've disarmed all our nuclear missiles in the
silos up there. Please, Mr. and Mrs. Olaf, keep Mr. Body away from
the red phone, whatever you do.
</P>
<P>
   Think about the ramifications here. Now how do we keep Dennis
Rodman under control? Or Charles Barkley, who already has his eye
on Alabama. Or Will Clark, for God's sake. Clark is already the
self-proclaimed sheriff of ``Ballpark County.'' He runs the place.
Just ask him. You think for a minute he would hesitate to go
national?
</P>
<P>
   Or what if Michael Jordan decides he wants to be president
(though I doubt he could accept the pay cut)? I mean, he does have
a little free time on his hands right now.
</P>
<P>
   You think Jordan couldn't win the presidency if he wanted to?
Better think again.
</P>
<P>
   If Jesse ``The Body'' Ventura can talk about legalizing drugs
and prostitution and be elected governor of Minnesota, Jordan can
cakewalk into the Oval Office and do a 360-degree slam dunk in the
Lincoln bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Michael's Middle East policy: ``Get that guy Hussein on the
phone. Tell him we're gonna play a little one-on-one.''
</P>
<P>
   Jesse ``The Body'' _ Mr. Body to you and me _ was once a skinny
Minneapolis Roosevelt High School defensive end named Jim Janos. He
left town, bulked up and came back in the early '80s as the bad guy
in one of Verne Gagne's local wrestling shows at the St. Paul Civic
Center. Not many knew that Janos and Jesse ``The Body'' Ventura
were one and the same.
</P>
<P>
   Minneapolis Star-Tribune sports columnist Pat Reusse remembers
the review in the next day's St. Paul newspaper going something
like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Much has been made of our society's inability to bring
together this tapestry of humanity that is America, and this is why
it was such an affirming experience to be at the Civic Center last
night as Caucasians, blacks, Asians, Arabs, Hispanics and American
Indians, Roman Catholics, Greek Orthodox, Lutherans, Baptists,
Methodists, Presbyterians, Muslims, Buddhists, Hindus, followers of
Judaism, agnostics and atheists, Republicans, DFLers, independents,
Libertarians, Greens, Socialists and Communists, heterosexuals,
homosexuals, asexuals, bisexuals and transsexuals, feminists and
misogynists, pro-choicers and pro-lifers, wealthy, middle-class and
poverty-stricken, all of these people rose as one _ brother and
sister _ to shout `Jesse sucks.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously Minnesotans have changed their opinion of Mr. Body,
who hosts a local sports talk show on KFAN AM, a gig he'll
apparently swap for the state's highest political office.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't, you understand, make him a politician.
</P>
<P>
   When Timberwolves owner Glen Taylor, among others, phoned in
congratulations on Ventura's radio show after the election, the new
governor cut right to the chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the hell are we gonna see some basketball?'' he growled
at Taylor, which brought forth the usual hemming and hawing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't give me no political answer,'' Jesse snapped. ``I've had
enough of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings up another horrifying thought: What if Ventura's
upset victory, instead of inspiring another run of ex-athletes into
politics, is the vanguard of a spate of talk-show hosts running for
office?
</P>
<P>
   Rush Limbaugh and Howard Stern? Galloway and The Hardline?
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, George W., laugh.
</P>
<P>
   They ain't laughing any more in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Reeves is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 2316EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0536 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6439 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-POLLOCK-NYT &LR;      11-11 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-POLLOCK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING AT POLLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Thursday, Nov. 12: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Each age finds its own technique,'' Jackson Pollock said in
1951. The question remains whether each age also finds its own
means of sight, the tools for witnessing a technique and a body of
work as permanently startling as Pollock's. Pollock has been a
given for nearly half a century, and yet to look back at the
rapidity of his ascent during the late 1940s and early 1950s is to
wonder about the velocity of our culture. It moves so fast,
half-digesting everything in sight, abruptly shifting the terms in
which Pollock's art, for instance, can be viewed. What hangs
invisibly beside the canvases in the Jackson Pollock retrospective
at the Museum of Modern Art is the legacy of response. It has yet
to catch up with the paintings.
</P>
<P>
   A retrospective naturally follows a developmental line, the
movement, in this case, of Pollock's work from that first muddied
self-portrait to a final 1955 canvas, aptly called ``Search'' _ a
portrait, in a sense, of self-abandonment. The sequence of
paintings that hang on MOMA's walls form a declarative ``what,''
but we read them as an interrogative ``how'' or ``why.'' We trace
the obvious narrative lines in the life and in the life's work, the
steady dissolving of figure, the expansion of Pollock's ``drip''
techniques. When Pollock enters his greatest period, with ``Number
1A, 1948,'' his achievement is almost obscured by the fact that it
is easier to talk about how he works than what, in fact, he
achieves. The Hans Namuth photographs of Pollock painting in his
East Hampton studio, wonderful as they are, capture a cultural
fascination with Pollock's technique _ the painter as dancer _
leading the viewer stealthily away from the work itself.
</P>
<P>
   But there, in midtown Manhattan, hangs the work, not the
choreography for the work, not its psychological or biographical
underpinnings, but a gathering of paintings that stand apart from
the artist and are, at the same time, intimately (italics)of(end
italics) him. As viewers, we know only too well the way cultural
artifacts stand apart from us and are made, in fact, to stand apart
by the cultural apparatus that devours them. The trick is to make
these works intimately of us as well. How Pollock got to these
paintings is an interesting story. But what remains is what he saw
there, as each painting arose, layer by layer, pigment by pigment,
into what is both an ideal geography and a miracle of esthetic
turbulence. What remains is to see them with the confidence that
they repay all the looking in the world. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
