<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BUCKLEY-VALEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO RETHINK BUCKLEY VS. VALEO 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Thursday, Nov. 12: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court is expected to decide this week whether to
accept a Cincinnati case that challenges the Court to rethink its
disastrous ruling 22 years ago in Buckley vs. Valeo. The nation's
political system has suffered ever since from that decision, which
held that mandatory limits on campaign spending unconstitutionally
limit free speech. The decision did much to promote the explosive
growth of campaign contributions from special interests and to
enhance the advantage incumbents enjoy over underfunded
challengers. The court can now correct its original error.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati is defending limits on spending for city council
elections that were invalidated by a federal appeals court, relying
on the Buckley decision. The case may not be the ideal vehicle to
challenge Buckley _ the factual record is rather sketchy _ but it
is still an opportunity for the court to right an obvious wrong.
</P>
<P>
   In Buckley, the court drew a distinction between campaign
contributions and expenditures that does not stand up. It correctly
allowed limits on individual contributions _ to prevent the
appearance and reality of corruption _ but not on expenditures,
which the court mistakenly held do not create the same risk. That
set the stage for an escalating campaign arms race that has made
the political system increasingly vulnerable to favor-seekers who
can deliver badly needed campaign cash.
</P>
<P>
   Applying the narrow corruption rationale, the court also found
no basis for limiting what a wealthy candidate may spend on his own
campaign. That has produced two terrible results. It has permitted
rich candidates to drown out candidates with fewer resources, and
it has made the money hunt by those non-wealthy candidates even
more desperate. In deciding Buckley, the court's aim was to protect
free speech. What it produced in practice is an untenable
distortion of the First Amendment and the democratic process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 2318EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
