<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6446 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOHLS-COLUMN-12COX     11-11 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOHLS-COLUMN-12COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Today's the day for Barnes to get some players
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Majestic Mapp, a point guard whose game is as
strong as his name, severed the St. Raymond's, N.Y., pipeline that
delivered Reggie Freeman and Terrence Rencher to Austin and signed
with Virginia on Wednesday. Hollis Price, a blur of a point guard
at New Orleans, turned down the Longhorns and became an Oklahoma
Sooner. Texas Coach Rick Barnes got his foot in George Williams'
door, before Coach Clyde Drexler slammed it on him and lured the
Missouri City forward to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been told no before,'' Barnes shrugged. ``My wife told me
no three times before I got her to marry me.''
</P>
<P>
   They didn't all say yes, but the first-year basketball coach's
honeymoon goes on after signing three versatile prepsters _ two
forwards and a combo guard _ on the first day players were allowed
to sign national letters of intent. At least, it reverses the
latest trend of attrition, considering Texas seems to lose almost a
player a week. If the season doesn't start soon, Barnes will have
to appeal to the NCAA to play make-it, take-it, half-court ball.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes might sign two more recruits, preferably a point guard
and a post player, but not until next spring. Clyde can't sign 20,
can he?
</P>
<P>
   The Texas head coach has only been here eight months and gets
credit for enticing 6-foot-8-inch transfer Chris Owens from
Duncanville via Tulane for next season. Besides, UT signee William
Wyatt might have been the best player in the state before his knee
injury and the South Grand Prairie forward is still a strong enough
prospect to make Final Four team Stanford offer him a scholarship.
By Barnes' comments, future Horns Chris Ogden and Roosevelt Brown
are more versatile than a Swiss army knife.
</P>
<P>
   A true point guard by April would be nice. UT hasn't had one
since Roderick Anderson in 1995 and hasn't had a great one since
Johnny Moore in 1979. Barnes wouldn't mind one either, but he knows
how inexact recruiting can be.
</P>
<P>
   Like the time in 1980 that he was dispatched by the Davidson
head coach to Scarsdale, N.Y., to check out a player named Johnny
Revelli. The kid had 11 shots blocked, testimony that Barnes shared
with his boss. The heck with Revelli, who's the guy guarding him?
Tall, lanky sort, who's not being recruited by anybody, Barnes
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse was mildly interested in the shot-blocker, but North
Carolina signed Sam Perkins at the last minute. Of course, even
Revelli panned out, winning Pacific-10 freshman of the year honors
at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the Ohio State basketball camper who wowed a Barnes
assistant so much that Dennis Felton called Barnes and told him to
get on the next plane. Barnes, then head coach at Providence,
complied and quickly fell in love with an athletic chap named Tim
Duncan, but the strict school administration wouldn't allow Barnes
to offer a scholarship even though he said he'd have two available
the following spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Tim had signed with Providence,'' Barnes sighed, ``I'm not
sure I'd be here today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tim Duncan-long and short of it is that the
6-foot-9-inch-and-growing center enrolled at Wake Forest, and
Barnes was soon headed to Clemson, where he waged annual recruiting
battles with the likes of North Carolina and Duke. At Texas, he'll
have to pick his spots _ and fights _ against Drexler, Melvin
Watkins, Texas A&AMP;M's new coach, and others.
</P>
<P>
   It won't happen overnight, but it's got to get easier for Barnes
here than at Clemson, where last year he lost two players who had
committed _ Louisiana point guard Brandon Dean and Kentucky guard
Todd Tackett _ to Arkansas and defending national champion
Kentucky. Another point guard, Steve Francis of Maryland, signed
with the Terps because Clemson didn't offer a big enough national
stage.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball isn't all about tapping into the premier
blue-chippers and rolling out the ball. Barnes was successful at
attracting top-drawer talent to Providence, where there is a dearth
of in-state players. He signed only two in his six years. But he
opened eyes by signing future NBA players, such as Michael Smith
and Dickie Simpkins and Austin Croshere, the last of whom he lured
from his Southern California roots after he'd been turned down by
Stanford and UConn. And Maryland Coach Gary Williams has given
Barnes much of the credit for signing All-American Jimmy Jackson as
a Buckeye when both coaches were at Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes has shown a knack for mining nuggets such as then-unsung,
5-8 point guard Terrell McIntyre, whose 160 treys are No. 2
all-time at Clemson. He also had a roster sprinkled with players
from Lithuania and the Ivory Coast, which are not in East Texas.
</P>
<P>
   He says he'll do the same here and go anywhere an interested
recruit takes him or assistants Ricky Stokes and Brian Cousins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll look at foreign players,'' he said with a gleam.
``Besides, if there's some guy in France, that's my trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
