<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TOP-10-TEX </SLUG>
 
Electric Company: The Cowboys players with the light stuff 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ You'd have thought Emmitt Smith was having
convulsions. He was asked to name the most exciting players in
Cowboys history, and he broke out into a dance that was part funky
chicken, part Irish jig and part Michael Jackson. He shook his
legs. He gyrated his hips. Then, like some kind of dime-store
cowboy, he pretended to pull out two guns and stick them into
imaginary holsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' he said at a reporter who looked at him with amusement,
``this is what Butch Johnson used to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh. Right.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Johnson might have California Quaked when he was a Cowboys
wide receiver from 1976-83, but it takes more than just a dance to
crack the ``Star-Telegram'''s list of the 10 most electrifying
players in Cowboys history.
</P>
<P>
   Smith makes the list, placing fifth after breaking Tony
Dorsett's club record for career rushing yards Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Star-Telegram'' Electric Company is purely subjective and
was concocted after talks with several past and present Cowboys
players, one of whom voted _ unsuccessfully _ for ``himself.'' ``I
have to come to mind because of all the things I did,'' said former
linebacker Thomas ``Hollywood'' Henderson (1975-79), one of the
league's first glamour defensive players who dunked over goal
posts, but couldn't stay out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The Electric Company includes players who could score from
anywhere on the field at any time in the game, of players who could
take your breath away and not give it back, of, Smith said,
``people who charged the crowd, and made you get off the bench and
say, `Gawd Dog.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Electrifying means something that moves me, something that
excites me,'' added Cowboys cornerback Deion Sanders, an obvious
choice to top the list. ``Michael Irvin does that with his game and
with his charisma. Tony Dorsett did that for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Electrifying does not necessarily mean best ever. So, the list
does not include Troy Aikman, who has been as consistent as a
humdrum Texas sunrise. Yet, all quarterbacks are not excluded.
Roger ``The Dodger'' Staubach (fourth) had many hearts pumping as
he passed and ran the 1970s Cowboys to all those last-minute
victories.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, the Electric Company is nearly exclusive to
offensive players, for it's fairly difficult to be electric without
the ball in your hands. Hall of Fame defensive tackles Bob Lilly
and Randy White might have hit with the force of lightning, but
what makes one jump out of your chair more and shout, ``did you see
that?'' Sacks or touchdowns?
</P>
<P>
   We like touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   So, here's the juice, from Deion to Dorsett, from Herschel to
Hill. The 200-Watt Spotlight Club
</P>
<P>
   1. Deion Sanders, 1995-present: With an unequalled knack for the
dramatic, the speedy Sanders has scored via punt, fumble and
interception return, as well as a receiver and a rusher in his
Cowboys days. ``You can just feel it in the air when he gets the
ball,'' Preston Pearson (1975-80) said. ``The other team is going,
`Oh God, Oh God. Get him.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks are afraid to throw at his side. Punters won't punt
to him. Those brave enough to challenge him sooner or later get to
watch him high-step the other way for six.
</P>
<P>
   And when they do, Cowboys defensive tackle Leon Lett wants a
good seat for the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you catch yourself trying to get a good spot on the
sidelines to see what he's going to do,'' Lett said.
</P>
<P>
   2. Bob Hayes, 1965-74: Zone defenses did not exist before this
Olympic sprinter came to the Cowboys. But defensive coordinators
had to do something to stop him, thus the double-team was created.
One defensive back would cover him short and another would line up
20 yards off the line to cover him deep. He has the highest
yards-per-catch average in team history (20.0). He also returned
three kicks for touchdowns. ``Nobody ever knew how fast he really
was because we'd have 40-yard sprints and he'd never burn off any
4.1s,'' said Tex Schramm, former Cowboys general manager
(1960-1988). ``All he would do was beat the guy he was running
against. And that was everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   3. Tony Dorsett, 1977-87: People still tell him what they were
doing on that night in Minnesota when he reeled off a 99-yard
touchdown run. Dorsett's only regret: He didn't keep the ball. ``A
lot of people have called and said they'd send me the ball if I'd
send them some cash,'' he said. Dorsett was a money player who used
speed and shifty moves to run his way into the Pro Football Hall of
Fame. Said Schramm: ``Tacklers thought they had him and he'd just
disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   The 100-Watt Hall Light Club
</P>
<P>
   4. Roger Staubach, 1969-79: Before there was John Elway, there
was Staubach. ``Captain Comeback'' scrambled his way past would-be
tacklers to rally the Cowboys from behind 23 times in the fourth
quarter, including 14 in the last two minutes. He made fans believe
``Hail Marys'' could happen every game.
</P>
<P>
   5. Emmitt Smith, 1990-present: He isn't the fastest player, but
he has the now-you-see-me-now-you-don't moves that has him gaining
on the top five NFL rushers of all time. In Atlanta in 1992, he cut
back so deftly that one would have thought the Falcons defenders
would blow out their knees trying to tackle him. He did the same
thing on that 15-yard touchdown run in Philadelphia on Nov. 2.
</P>
<P>
   6. Drew Pearson, 1973-83: Every time a Cowboys quarterback
needed a miracle, there was Drew. He answered Staubach's 1975
prayer in Minnesota. He ran down Clint Longley's bomb to beat the
Redskins in 1974. He caught two last-minute Danny White touchdowns
to beat the Falcons in 1980. ``Drew was the greatest pressure
clutch receiver that I've ever known,'' Schramm said. The 60-Watt
Porch Light Club
</P>
<P>
   7. Mel Renfro, 1964-77: He was so fast and elusive that the
Cowboys considered making him a running back before an injury
forced his move to cornerback and safety. He is the club's career
leader in interceptions (52) and interception return yardage (626).
``When Mel played, he was looked upon like Deion is now,'' Schramm
said. ``He was an unusual athlete for his day, but he didn't have
the flair for the dramatics like Deion has.''
</P>
<P>
   8. Michael Irvin, 1988-present: Not necessarily known for his
speed, the brash, trash-talking Irvin still runs for big yardage
after the catch as well as most. Then he signals ``first down,'' as
a way to get the fans juiced up. He holds most of the Cowboys'
notable receiving records and should finish among the NFL's top 10
in receptions before he retires.
</P>
<P>
   9. Herschel Walker, 1986-89, 1996-97: He remains the only player
to ever put Tony Dorsett on the bench. He had sprinter speed and
brute strength. He was so good at everything that no one could ever
figure out what he was best at. He ran from scrimmage, caught
passes, and returned kicks for four different teams, and is No. 2
on the NFL's all-time combined yards gained list with 18,168 total
yards.
</P>
<P>
   10. Tony Hill, 1977-86: Alvin Harper might have been more
acrobatic, but Hill was more dramatic and more consistent when it
came to getting deep. His two long touchdown receptions in 1983
gave the Cowboys a come-from-behind victory in Washington. The
speedy Hill retired with a 16.7 yards per catch average, second
only to Bob Hayes and Frank Clarke (1960-67).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 2324EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
