<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6449 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT &LR;      11-11 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAVY READING 
NOT-SO-FAST LANES 
FILM DEAL
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``War and Peace'' or ``Tristram Shandy'' they are
not. But several just-published books are a heavy lift. And that's
before opening them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Century'' by Peter Jennings and Todd Brewster, described
on its picture-packed jacket as ``a magnificent chronicle of the
extraordinary 20th century,'' weighs 5 pounds, 1.2 ounces. As it
happens, that is exactly the same as another recent book _ which
will probably still be on coffee tables long after the millennium _
``The American Century,'' by Harold Evans, the editorial director
and vice chairman of The Daily News, U.S. News &AMP; World Report and
The Atlantic Monthly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality of the paper in ours is better,'' Jennings joked
Wednesday, noting that his book had 606 pages while Evans' had 722.
Jennings' book costs more, with a list price of $60; Evans' goes
for $50.
</P>
<P>
   As heavyweights go, they are well ahead of ``Bruce Springsteen:
Songs,'' which went on sale Wednesday. It weighed in at 4 pounds,
1.9 ounces and a mere 306 pages. But like ``The American Century,''
it costs $50.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Tom Wolfe's 742-page, $28.95 novel ``A Man In
Full.'' David Letterman, who had the white-suited Wolfe as a guest
on his talk show Tuesday night, held up the book and said: ``I
think this ought to be the size you should shoot for. I'm telling
you, this feels and looks like, well, gosh darn it, here's a book,
for heaven's sake.'' (This was after Letterman admitted that he had
not yet read it.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never reached three pounds before,'' Wolfe said. ``I
figured it was time.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wolfe fell short: ``A Man in Full'' weighs only 2 pounds 9.4
ounces in full.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps he handed in a 3-pound book and they edited it down,''
a spokeswoman for Wolfe, Amelia Durand, said. ``Who likes to read a
heavy, heavy book?''
</P>
<P>
   The Art of Bowling
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs at the Frick are the paintings everybody sees.
Downstairs is Henry Clay Frick's private bowling alley, which only
museum directors see.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Sachs II, the director of the Frick, invited a dozen or
so heads of other New York museums to a bowling party to welcome
Maxwell Anderson, the recently appointed director of the Whitney.
Although he did not choose the old-style ball with two _ that's
right, two _ holes, Anderson said, ``I actually know how to bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Sachs may have been the only two in the room who did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sams are perfect bowlers,'' said Rosetta Miller, whose
husband is the retired director of the Newark Museum. ``Sam Sachs
bowled two perfect strikes, and Sam Miller bowled two perfect
zeroes.'' (Miller eventually knocked down five pins.)
</P>
<P>
   Beth Sachs, the director's wife, said that this was only the
second time the two-lane bowling alley had been used since it was
restored last year. ``In fact,'' she said, ``I think we are the
first people to use it since Frick.'' He died in 1919, and his
daughter had the lanes covered and turned it into a storage area.
</P>
<P>
   Private Screening
</P>
<P>
   Only in New York could a celebrity doctor demand _ and get _ a
new movie for a benefit screening, in this case a
$150-a-person-and-up showing of Woody Allen's film ``Celebrity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They needed a plastic surgeon's office,'' recalled the doctor,
Richard Coburn. ``I said, `You've got to do a screening for the
National Hypertension Association.'' (He is a longtime board member
of the group.) ``They hemmed and hawed for a few minutes and gave
it to us.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``Celebrity'' does not contain all the film that Allen shot
in Coburn's brownstone on the Upper East Side. A bedroom scene with
the nebbishy, Woody Allen-like character (Kenneth Branagh) was
filmed in Coburn's living quarters, above his office. ``They did
the scene and it didn't go well,'' Coburn said. ``They did it over
again.'' Somewhere else.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 2326EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981111.0542 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6462 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BECKS-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      11-11 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BECKS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: GERMANS DO BEER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Who ever said you couldn't score points with a client by making
fun of his heritage?
</P>
<P>
   That was the formula settled on by a creative team from the
Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi unit of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC when they sat down
to figure out how to sell more Beck's beer for Brauerei Beck &AMP; Co.,
the German brewery. After flopping badly in the early 1990s, Beck's
has recovered enough to become the No. 5 imported beer in the
United States last year, according to sales data recorded by
Impact, a trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Beck's beer rose 11 percent last year, to 7.4 million
cases from 6.7 million, said Frank Walters, director of research at
Impact. That is still lower than the 8 million cases sold in 1990,
the peak year for Beck's in the United States, he noted, but the
brand is on the upswing, partly because of a new management team
and sales force. The brand is also buoyed by the growth of imported
beers in the United States in general. Sales of imported beers
increased by 12 percent a year in 1997 over the previous year and
left the flat domestic beer business in the dust.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of Beck's, based in Bremen, knew they wanted to
extend their turnaround. They were prepared to spend a lot of money
by their standards: $20 million, twice the size of any previous
U.S. advertising budget for the company, in the belief that more
advertising would add momentum to sales. ``We are totally committed
to the states,'' said Axel Meermann, Beck's global marketing
director. ``We want to double our business in six years, and we are
in year two right now.''
</P>
<P>
   And despite possessing normal amounts of patriotic pride,
somehow the company was also prepared to accept the recommendation
of the Saatchi team that the new ad campaign be centered on
commercials that poke fun at German stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   The Saatchi executives, Tod Seisser and Jennifer Laing, found
after conducting focus groups and what Miss Laing, chairwoman and
chief executive of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi North America, called
``psychological probes'' that the Germanic associations of Beck's
were what its drinkers _ described as males ages 19 to 35, well
educated, into sports and achievement of all kinds _ most admired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a boy brand,'' Miss Laing said. ``German is the ideal to
the American male. It's strong, and it's all about precision and
expertise. We said: `If you leverage your German-ness, that's
really potent for this particular target audience. It just triggers
all the things they want to think about themselves.''' But, Miss
Laing added, the brand lacked easy recognition, which means a lot
in the world of commercial buzz. Some people even have trouble
distinguishing it from Heineken, which comes in a similar green
bottle.
</P>
<P>
   After exploring a handful of options, she and Seisser concluded
that the best way to both capitalize on the Teutonic qualities and
appeal to potential Beck's drinkers was to take a humorous view of
certain German propensities. ``This one got ticks on all the
dimensions we cared about,'' Miss Laing said of the final campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The commercials, which will be broadcast during sports events
and late-night shows starting next Wednesday, make fun of a certain
Teutonic obsession with control, using various scenarios whose
humor would come through whether it was a beer ad or a late-night
comedy skit. They were heartily endorsed by Meermann, who might
have been a bit puzzled at first about what made them so hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   In one, a blond actor struggles to get comfortable on a couch
for a relaxation session. He is wearing a stiff white shirt and tie
and is listening to a compact disk titled ``Das Kalm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Commence relaxation now,'' an offscreen voice commands. It
does not work out well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Germans don't do laid back,'' the announcer intones in an
unmistakable German accent. ``They do beer.''
</P>
<P>
   In another, two actors are playing a key scene from ``Romeo and
Juliet.'' The dialogue is in German, and the actors are in
brittle-looking, larger-than-life costumes that Seisser, the chief
creative officer at Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi New York, said were inspired
by archival photographs of a Bertold Brecht play from the 1930s.
The actors lack any semblance of passion. ``Germans don't do
romance,'' the announcer says.
</P>
<P>
   And in a third, Michael Schenk, a German actor, plays a comedian
whose delivery and brand of humor fail to connect with his
audience. The room is almost empty, and Schenk's jokes, complete
with references to Berlin, fall flat. ``Thank you,'' he says, to a
smattering of hollow applause. ``I'll be here all ze week.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Germans don't do comedy,'' the announcer says.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very rich area,'' Seisser said. ``It could go on for
10 years. There are certain things Germans are very, very good at,
and certain things they're not good at, just like everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   References to old Beck's advertising were incorporated in the
new commercials. In all three spots, a bottle of Beck's is slammed
down on a counter for emphasis, just as in earlier Beck's ads. But
there is a new slogan this time: ``The best of what Germans do
best.'' As Seisser put it, ``It reinforces our superiority within
that set, and it sounded good.''
</P>
<P>
   Print ads are also scheduled to appear, along with billboards
and radio spots. And the humor, while it may have taken some
getting used to, is thought to be right for the American market.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's hard,'' Meermann admitted. ``I can smile, but
it's hard to think about whether that stereotype is realistic.''
But he added, ``As long as you, as a German, make a joke at your
own expense, it's OK''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
