<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-11 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6468 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELDERLY-ROAD-TEST12-C     11-11 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDERLY-ROAD-TEST12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Proposed road test for elderly draws fire
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A state lawmaker said Wednesday it is time for
Texas to force older drivers to prove they are roadworthy.
</P>
<P>
   A bill filed by Rep. Tony Goolsby, R-Dallas, would order the
Texas Department of Public Safety to come up with a way _ perhaps a
road test _ to make sure drivers 75 and older can ``exercise
ordinary and reasonable control in the operation of a motor vehicle
of the type that the license authorizes the person to operate.''
</P>
<P>
   Goolsby said he knows he is headed into a gray area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not trying to penalize anybody,'' said Goolsby, 65.
``We are trying to make the roads safer.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislative effort comes in the wake of two highly
publicized highway incidents involving older drivers. In June 1997,
Raymond and Lela Howard of Salado were killed when their car
plunged down a 20-foot ravine into a shallow Arkansas creek. The
Howards, with Lela at the wheel, were heading to a festival in
Temple but somehow wound up in Arkansas, 500 miles from home.
</P>
<P>
   Family members, concerned about Lela Howard's deteriorating
medical condition, had considered taking away her driver's license.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, five women were killed near Giddings when the van in
which they were traveling was struck by a car driven by Elsie
Nitsche, 84, of Giddings. She was indicted on a charge of
criminally negligent homicide. Investigators said she failed to
yield the right of way to the van.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Public Safety statistics for 1996, the most recent
complete data available, do not indicate that older drivers are
involved in a disproportionate number of wrecks. But the numbers do
not reflect the fact that older drivers tend to drive fewer miles.
</P>
<P>
   Goolsby said most older drivers do just fine behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's touchy,'' he said of his proposal. ``But I don't think
anybody could say there is not a lot of good logic to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Think again, Mr. Goolsby.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American Association of Retired Persons strongly
disapproved of that legislation being filed,'' said Candice Carter,
AARP's Austin lobbyist. ``It is discriminatory in all senses of the
word.''
</P>
<P>
   But Homer Lear of San Antonio, who has been speaker of the
Silver-Haired Legislature, said the idea has merit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no problem with it,'' said Lear, 78, who drives about
25,000 miles a year.
</P>
<P>
   Lear noted, however, that the state-sponsored advocacy group for
the elderly has not addressed the issue.
</P>
<P>
   In Sun City, a Williamson County enclave of active senior
citizens, Goolsby's idea got, at best, a yellow light. Proceed with
caution, said Charles Barnes, 76.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of older folks who do cause big problems,'' he
said, adding he would not mind taking a test as long as it was
convenient. ``I don't want to go through a tremendous amount of
trouble to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel Coffman, 66, said the state should not set an arbitrary age
at which everyone would have to be tested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see maybe a physician exam, and a doctor would say
this guy doesn't have good eyesight or physical reflexes,'' he
said. ``Then you would bring that to the DPS.''
</P>
<P>
   Several states require mandatory testing only for older drivers
with physical conditions or who rack up a series of wrecks or
tickets. Several other states require mandatory testing for every
driver above a certain age.
</P>
<P>
   The Goolsby plan is not supported by insurance industry
statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, older drivers are considered preferred drivers
because they drive fewer miles, they drive when traffic is not
quite as heavy and their driving record is usually very good,''
said Jerry Johns, president of the Southwestern Insurance
Information Service.
</P>
<P>
   Johns' organization is declaring neutrality on the Goolsby bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be helpful to everyone, because what it would do is
eliminate those drivers who don't possess the skills'' needed to
drive, he said. ``But you could make that argument for any age
group.''
</P>
<P>
   The Insurance Institute for Highway Safety, in a 1997 national
study, reported that elderly people have higher rates of fatal
crashes per mile driven than any group other than drivers under 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``A problem is that elderly drivers don't deal as well as young
ones with complex traffic situations, and multiple-vehicle crashes
at intersections increase markedly with age,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Transportation reports that older drivers
have fewer accidents than other age groups but have higher rates of
fatal accidents. And, the agency reports, the number of over-70
drivers has increased 47 percent in the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Goolsby said he understands what a car and a driver's license
mean to older Texans, even after they've stopped driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the worst mistakes I made with my own mother was I had
her sell her car,'' he said, convinced now that the vehicle offered
her a sense of independence, even if she never drove it. ``That
thing should have stayed in the garage and disintegrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Goolsby said he handled the situation differently with his
mother-in-law, who cherished her 1978 Cadillac long after she no
longer could drive it.
</P>
<P>
   ``She would start it up and let it run a while,'' he said. ``It
meant everything in the world for her to have her driver's license
and have that car out there.''
</P>
<P>
   American-Statesman staff writer Pam LeBlanc contributed to this
report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
