<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-KOKANEE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOKANEE: SPECTACULAR SPAWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP RICHARDSON, Calif. _ Brilliant scarlet hues. Humped backs.
Hooked jaws. The salmon's spawning characteristics are
unmistakable. But this isn't Alaska or Canada or the Pacific
Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Would you believe Lake Tahoe?
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the kokanee _ the lake's landlocked population of red,
or sockeye, salmon _ are running in Taylor Creek on Tahoe's south
shore.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are amazed. It's fish-watching at its finest. You get
to actually see the whole spawning phenomenon right there in front
you without traveling a great distance,'' said Jackie Faike, an
interpretive specialist with the U.S. Forest Service's Lake Tahoe
Basin Management Unit.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced as a game fish in 1944, the kokanee thrived with
little competition and lots of habitat. Today it has a
self-sustaining population. However, unlike their cousins to the
northwest who spawn in freshwater but live most of the time in the
brine, these specimens reside only in sweetwater.
</P>
<P>
   The kokanee have traditionally spawned in 2-mile-long Taylor
Creek, which is regulated by a dam at its source _ Fallen Leaf
Lake. The fish know where to find the creek because its scent is
imprinted on them at birth.
</P>
<P>
   Tahoe's other inlets are controlled only by nature's whim, and
in autumns following mild winters they often don't have enough
volume to satisfy the 40,000 to 60,000 kokanee that spawn for six
to eight weeks, usually starting in late September or early
October.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the creek is enjoying the kokanee's largest spawn
with an estimated 80,000 of the 18-inch, 3-year-old fish heading up
the creek.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why that is we're not sure,'' said Jeff Reiner, a Forest
Service fisheries biologist who also tends the dam to ensure proper
flows for the spawning process. ``It could be more favorable
conditions _ increased lake levels that supplied more shore-zone
habitat for younger kokanee. It probably relates to more of their
prey species _ zooplankton. And everything tiered off that.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, Reiner said, the kokanee had an excellent spawn three
years ago and that year class is spawning now. The evidence is
clear by the stench.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough for folks to go down the creek now because it's
very smelly,'' Faike said.
</P>
<P>
   As is the way of the salmon, to reproduce it must die, and there
are more expired fish in the water now than live ones. In short,
they expend all their energy spawning and afterward their body
mechanisms shut down. The final days are spent guarding their nests
as a fungus takes over their rotting bodies.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing is wasted in nature, and today's loss is tomorrow's
bounty for the coyotes, raccoons, crayfish and occasional bald
eagle that scavenge the carcasses.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask, `Do you clean up the creek?''' Faike said. ``I
tell them that just becomes food for somebody else. Those fish that
remain are flushed out in the high, heavy stream flows the
following spring.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, recycling at its finest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-11-98 2348EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
