u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-VAUGHN-3DL     11-11 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-VAUGHN-3D </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN `TO PLAY FOR SOMEONE ELSE,' RED SOX SAY 
</HEADLINE>
 LEDE-WRITETHRU-BOS  
 (Edits, new information)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPLES, Fla. _ The Red Sox' protracted, often acrimonious bid to
re-sign slugger Mo Vaughn ended for all intents and purposes
Wednesday night when general manager Dan Duquette said the free
agent first baseman had rejected the club's latest offer and
decided to look elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the general managers' meetings here, Duquette _ who
earlier in the day had sweetened Boston's offer, according to the
Vaughn camp _ said, ``It looks like he's going to play for someone
else.''
</P>
<P>
   That someone else is not necessarily the Anaheim Angels, who
gave the Sox a lofty target to aim at when they offered Vaughn a
guaranteed six-year, $72 million package last Friday when all clubs
became eligible to bid for free agents, not just the players'
present employers.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn did not indicate where he'd be heading, Duquette said
Wednesday night. ``He's going to put his efforts somewhere else,
and we are, too. We're going to look at some other options.''
</P>
<P>
   Other options for the Sox apparently involve Yankees center
fielder Bernie Williams, the American League batting champion, and
tempestuous Chicago White Sox slugger Albert Belle.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Gammons of ESPN, a Globe columnist, reported that Williams
will be in Boston next Thursday, and Duquette sounded enthusiastic
about the possible addition of Belle despite his notorious
off-field reputation. However, Williams reportdely is being heavily
courted by the Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, it seemed the Sox' chances of retaining
Vaughn had improved. In the wake of Anaheim's offer, they had come
up with a five-year, $60 million proposal _ in the neighborhood of
what they gave pitcher Pedro Martinez last December (six years, $75
million) when they made him the highest-paid player in baseball at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette indicated that the Sox had increased their offer in
terms of length Wednesday when they met twice with Vaughn's agents,
Tom Reich and Mark Gillam.
</P>
<P>
   That offer proved unacceptable, but in the final analysis, the
hostility that punctuated the 1 1/2-year negotiations may have been
the determining factor.
</P>
<P>
   During those talks, Vaughn had claimed to be insulted by several
Red Sox offers, most recently a four-year, $37.5 million proposal
at the All-Star break. He also had been miffed that the team
seemingly took care of other key players _ such as second-year
shortstop Nomar Garciaparra _ while keeping him dangling. And after
he indicated he was on the verge of re-signing in December, the Sox
gave their blockbuster package to Martinez, and all bets were off.
In January, Vaughn was charged with drunken driving after his truck
overturned late one night while he was returning from the Foxy Lady
strip club in Providence. Vaughn eventually was acquitted of the
charges, but in the meantime, the team insisted that he submit to
alcohol evaluation as a condition for getting a new offer, and from
there, relations deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
   While Duquette told Gammons Wednesday night, ``You never say
never,'' seemingly keeping the door ajar for a change of heart by
either the player or the team, chances for that appear
infinitesimal.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, the 1995 AL Most Valuable Player who this past season
batted .337 (second to Williams) with 40 homers and 115 RBIs, told
Channel 4's Steve Burton Wednesday night outside his Easton, Mass.,
home, ``I'm not moving, I'm just going somewhere else to work. I
think it's just a situation where people didn't see eye to eye.
You've got to move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take our time and weigh it out and do the right thing
when the time comes. I don't know what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette now will leave the meetings here this morning, not to
return to Boston but to meet with prospective free agent signees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We owe it to our fans to present good players,'' Duquette
said, ``and there are a limited supply of good players.''
</P>
<P>
   In other business, the Red Sox made a minor deal with Arizona
for righthanded pitcher Bob Wolcott, who made a brief splash three
years ago when he was a surprise Game 1 starter for Seattle in the
1995 American League Championship Series against Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox also officially lost lefthanded reliever Greg Swindell,
who signed a three-year contract for $5.7 million with Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   As a Class A free agent, Swindell, will net the Sox an
additional first-round sandwich pick as well as a second-round
choice in compensation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
