<HEADLINE>
PENALTY SHOT SPARKS DEVILS OVER MONTREAL, 3-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ In a hockey rarity, the New Jersey
Devils wound up turning a two-man disadvantage into a score
Wednesday night that sparked New Jersey to a 3-0 victory over the
Montreal Canadiens at Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils were down two players when Scott Niedermayer broke
away down the middle of the ice and was tripped. He was awarded a
penalty shot that he converted with a crafty move from right to
left and back to right before a crowd of 14,017, and Montreal never
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Niedermayer's penalty shot was not the only highlight for the
Devils. Krzysztof Oliwa scored his first goal of the season and
third in 87 career games, and Sergei Brylin scored his first of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   With that kind of offensive success _ and with Martin Brodeur
playing brilliantly in goal _ the Devils emerged with a victory,
even though they played without the suspended Bobby Holik and the
injured Dave Andreychuk, two of their biggest and most physical
forwards.
</P>
<P>
   It was New Jersey's first shutout of the season at Continental
Arena. The victory was the fifth in the last six games for the
Devils. It improved their record to 8-5-0 and gave them a share of
the Eastern Conference lead with the Penguins, who visit the Devils
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Niedermayer was awarded the penalty shot after he broke away on
the left while the Canadiens had a two-man advantage and was
tripped by Patrice Brisebois, who dived at the Devils' skater with
his outstretched stick in a desperate attempt to thwart the speedy
Niedermayer just a few feet from the goal.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty shot, 64 seconds into the middle period, was the
first for the Devils since John MacLean, now with the Rangers, beat
Dominik Hasek of Buffalo in a 4-1 victory here Feb. 2, 1997. It was
the 13th penalty shot in the history of the team and the second for
Niedermayer, who failed on his first attempt, against Ken Wregget
of Pittsburgh, on Feb. 7, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Oliwa's goal in the opening period was a gift from Jose
Theodore, the Canadiens' goaltender, who left his crease to control
Lyle Odelein's dump pass behind his net. When Theodore missed the
puck, Oliwa gained control, went around the goal from right to left
and deposited the puck into the unguarded net with 7 minutes 48
seconds left in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   This was the fourth consecutive start for Theodore, who came
into the game with three consecutive victories in which he had
allowed only four goals. The Canadiens, meanwhile, scored 13 in
those victories.
</P>
<P>
   But the Canadiens had trouble finding the target against
Brodeur, who played all four games against the Canadiens last
season and registered a 1.72 goals-against average in three
victories and a loss. Brodeur looked sharp throughout the game, in
particular on shots by Shayne Corson midway through the second
period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
