</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-PANTHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS FALL EASILY TO PANTHERS, 4-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNRISE, Fla. _ After scoring 16 goals in their last two games,
the Rangers made people wonder if they were simply two-game wonders
or a juggernaut in the making. Wednesday night's evidence points
toward the former.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were handcuffed by a motivated Florida Panthers team
and fell limply, 4-1, at the National Car Rental Center.
</P>
<P>
   After watching the 22-year-old Dan Cloutier stop 26 shots in a
10-2 rout of Tampa Bay on Tuesday, Mike Richter returned to the
Ranger goal Wednesday night. That brought to the surface a flood of
bitter memories from the Panthers' management.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Bryan Murray was convinced he had secured
Richter as a free agent in the off-season, but Richter made a late
decision to stay with the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was assured when I made the offer that there was no right to
match as far as the Rangers were concerned,'' Murray said. ``But
the second I got off the phone, the first thing he did was run to
Neil Smith with my offer,'' he said, referring to the Rangers'
general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Murray clearly remains angry about Richter changing his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I told Mike afterward at the time, I didn't think he
showed very much character or honor by doing that,'' Murray said.
``Mike came to me with a proposal he liked, but all he did was use
it as a way to drive the price up for the Rangers. Mike had all the
leverage, and that's the way he decided to conduct his business.''
</P>
<P>
   On the ice, Richter, for the most part, showed why the Panthers
were so eager to part with $31 million over six years _ even facing
a Florida team playing as if Murray had promised extra cash for a
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Richter played steadily if somewhat unluckily through two
periods. He was victimized 21 seconds from second period's end by a
30-foot shot from defenseman Ed Jovanovski. The puck hit an
unidentified Ranger near the net and bounced over Richter's glove.
</P>
<P>
   Yet luck had nothing to do with a goal 3 minutes 23 seconds into
the third that gave the hosts a 3-1 bulge. Defenseman Robert Svehla
received a pass from center Dave Gagner on the right side and
rocketed a 10-footer by Richter and into the net's left corner.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did it have anything to do with Florida's fourth goal _ a
breakaway by wing Ray Whitney at 11:44 of the final period.
Whitney, heading in from the left, faked Richter into diving, held
the puck for an instant and then scored easily from an open right
angle.
</P>
<P>
   Just as coach John Muckler had feared after the rollicking
domination of Tampa Bay made scoring look so elementary, the
Rangers did not display the same early grit or aggressiveness.
</P>
<P>
   And that enabled the Panthers to seize early control.
</P>
<P>
   Only 2:57 into the game, Florida broke through on Richter. Johan
Garpenlov's shot was blocked, but the puck skidded back to fellow
wing Oleg Kvasha near the net. He slammed it between a scrambling
Richter's legs.
</P>
<P>
   Florida also built a 10-3 shot advantage in the period, before
the Rangers closed to 12-7 by the period's end. Defenseman Ulf
Samuelsson, who had two goals the night before, almost slipped a
25-footer by goalie Sean Burke at 15:42.
</P>
<P>
   The most conspicuous thing about the period was the absence of
penalties, considering the National Hockey League was using dual
referees: Kevin Maguire and Dan Marouelli. Previous Panthers home
games this season with two referees have averaged nearly 30
penalties.
</P>
<P>
   In fact the game's first penalty did not come until 7:06 of the
second period. It was against Ranger defenseman Jeff Beukeboom for
his tripping of Panthers wing Dave Nemirovsky.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers evened the game at the 16:14 mark of the second
period, thanks to Adam Graves' persistence around the net. Graves
jumped on defenseman Peter Popovic's deflected shot, which was set
up by a close-range, behind-the-net feed from Wayne Gretzky. It was
Graves' fifth goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was a case for the Rangers of not enough offensive
firepower. Center Marc Savard, who had totaled a goal and five
assists in his first two games since being called up, was among the
Rangers being shut out.
</P>
</TEXT>
